<HEADLINE>
SPRINT MAY ONE DAY BE THANKFUL FOR COLLAPSE OF WORLDCOM MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star The Justice Department may have done
Sprint and WorldCom a favor by derailing their proposed merger.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No doubt it's difficult for the heads of Sprint and WorldCom to
see a silver lining in the way things played out, but it may
transpire that there will be more opportunity in failure than
success.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible, of course, to know whether wonderful things
would have happened had the No. 2 and No. 3 long-distance carriers
been able to combine to challenge AT&AMP;T. The problem is, however,
that long-distance telephony as we know it is an industry whose
economics are undergoing drastic change.
</P>
<P>
   The changes hold much promise for consumers, but will make it
impossible for the enterprises involved to reap the lucrative
profits of the past.
</P>
<P>
   What it boils down to, many experts say, is the fact that the
cost of long-distance may someday fall to zero. For some ambitious
consumers, the price already has reached zero, because it's
included in the cost of their Internet connection or their cell
phone contract.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us who remain mired in a low-tech existence don't
appreciate such breakthroughs yet, but the pioneers have seen the
future and it is a wondrous world. To be sure, talking
long-distance by computer is still a clunky experience, but it's
merely a leading-edge example of what's ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The experts say the day is coming when the cost of using
long-distance won't be a per-call arrangement, but a matter of
buying access to the system in the same way Internet users
currently do.
</P>
<P>
   As the world of wireless telephony expands, connecting callers
across continents and oceans will be the same as connecting them
across town. As things stand, according to the experts, the cost of
a long-distance call is practically nothing compared with the cost
of system administration.
</P>
<P>
   Until this brave new world becomes a universal fact of life,
long-distance providers are depending on consumer inertia to keep
the lucrative per-call mind-set in place as long as possible. They
hope the transition will take at least as long as it did for
consumers to discover it was much more economical to own their
telephone instrument than lease it.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, it's impossible to fathom the rationality of the
Justice Department's effort to block the WorldCom-Sprint merger.
The trustbusters said AT&AMP;T's market share combined with
WorldCom-Sprint's would-be share left too much long-distance market
in too few hands.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but all that market share domination will vanish in the
future as the Bell regional companies get fully into long-distance,
as they inevitably will, and Internet carriers enhance and expand
their voice-exchange capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the relatively short period the WorldCom-Sprint
merger was on the table, the economics of the industry changed so
dramatically that the merged company would have had to reinvent
itself to meet future challenges.
</P>
<P>
   As a long-distance giant, the two may have been a good fit, but
traditional long-distance doesn't seem to be where it's at anymore.
Given Sprint's favorable technological position, perhaps a
different sort of partner will eventually generate an even better
deal for its shareholders.
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
