<HEADLINE>
MESSIER RETURNS AS CAPTAIN OF RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT6 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Messier stood on the podium at Madison Square
Garden on Thursday morning during his reintroduction to New York
and the Rangers, but he could not speak.
</P>
<P>
   The tears flowing down Messier's face spoke for him instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, I've embarrassed myself in front of millions of
people in America and Canada by crying,'' the always emotional
Messier finally blurted out, along with an attempt at a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   There may be no crying in other sports. But there is obviously
room for it in hockey, perhaps the toughest of them all. And on
Thursday, the tears shed by Messier were those of joy.
</P>
<P>
   The man with the shaven head, legendary stare and jutted jaw had
just donned his red-white-and-blue No. 11 sweater, with the
captain's ``C'' freshly stitched back on, for the first time in
more than three years. Not long before, Messier had signed a
two-year contract for a base total of $11 million to guarantee his
return.
</P>
<P>
   But there had to be tears of regret mixed in, too, for someone
who really needed no introduction to even the most casual of New
York sports fans. The Rangers have endured three seasons without a
playoff berth since Messier parted ways with the Rangers on July
28, 1997. Three long years of what-could-have-beens played out to
boos on Garden ice.
</P>
<P>
   At age 39 _ and after enduring three playoff-less seasons of his
own in Vancouver _ Messier now returns to the same Broadway stage
that he once owned like no other hockey player before or since.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it is for a long-anticipated second act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to retire,'' Messier defiantly vowed, once all
his emotions had been contained. ``I'm here to win, to play well,
to do all the things I have done in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Messier was brought back to New York for one purpose above all
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one conversation we had, Mark said to me he may not be able
to carry a team to the Stanley Cup, but he can certainly lead,''
said Glen Sather, the Rangers' new president and general manager.
``And leading is what I'm looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Messier's first acts as the Rangers' new captain was to
issue another of his guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee we're going to make the playoffs,'' he said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know where this franchise should be, where it's been
and where we're going to take it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Messier has made a career out of backing up his words. Game 6 of
the 1994 Eastern Conference finals immediately comes to mind, when
Messier not only promised a victory over the New Jersey Devils but
delivered it with a hat trick.
</P>
<P>
   Given how successful Messier's first act with the Rangers was,
someone questioned on Thursday the wisdom of his even attempting a
second one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a successful stint in New York for 54 years
before I got here,'' Messier shot back, referring to the Stanley
Cup he helped the Rangers win in 1994. ``Nobody knows what tomorrow
will bring. That's what we're here for.''
</P>
<P>
   One day earlier, Ron Low had been introduced as the Rangers' new
head coach. But this is clearly Messier's team. And town. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Checketts, the Garden president, indicated that he first
began to truly understand the significance Messier had in New York
on the day Wayne Gretzky retired, in April 1999. Almost two years
earlier, when Messier left for Vancouver, Checketts said something
in an interview that stung Rangers fans to their core.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long should we pay for that cup?'' Checketts said, words
he now regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all make mistakes,'' Checketts said on Thursday.
``But the past is the past and today is moving on. I've had very
few moments in 10 years at the Garden as special as what we just
experienced. I'm just glad he's back. It was probably a long time
overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers went so far as to import some genuine sod in a glass
tank, along with a pair of shovels, so that Messier and Checketts
could bury a hatchet, both literally and figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Messier has become synonymous with New York like few
other modern-day athletes with any city,'' Checketts said before
the burying began. ``He has arguably meant more to the Rangers'
sweater than anyone who has ever worn it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are concerns that Messier is past his prime. He had 17
goals and 37 assists in 66 games last season and will be 41 when
his contract is through. But Glen Sather, the Rangers' new
president and general manager who signed Messier to his first
National Hockey League contract in Edmonton, said he does not give
much credence to age.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mark started playing in Edmonton, he was 18 years old and
everybody said he was too young,'' Sather said. ``Now, I've had a
lot of people tell me he's too old. How old was Gordie Howe when he
retired? 52. Some people can do it. Some people can't. I've seen
guys at 29 who were through.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are gambling at least $11 million _ a $9 million
signing bonus plus a $1 million annual salary over the next two
years and assorted incentives _ that Messier is not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
