<SLUG> BC-FREDHARVEY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL FRED HARVEY MUSEUM WILL SHOWCASE A BIT OF U.S. AND KC
HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Once upon a time, there
was a Kansas City company like none other.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It created the first national chain of hotels and restaurants.
It transformed the lives of thousands of young women. It
constructed buildings that became National Historic Landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   The company changed _ perhaps forever _ the image of the
American Southwest. Its collection of Indian art and artifacts was
so renowned that William Randolph Hearst badgered the company to
sell him part of it to decorate his San Simeon castle in
California.
</P>
<P>
   This is no fairy tale. But much of the company's story has faded
from the scene _ even in Kansas City, where the company had its
headquarters in its glory years, from the late 1800s to 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Even at Union Station, where the company's offices were, the
Fred Harvey Co. gets little attention, except as the name for a
food court and restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   But the historical vacuum is near an end. Later this year the
National Fred Harvey Museum is expected to open in Leavenworth,
Kan., in the house where the company's founder, Fred Harvey, lived
and died.
</P>
<P>
   The museum _ near Seventh and Olive streets _ has been in the
works for two years. Harvey artifacts valued at $500,000 have been
donated. An archive will be established to store family and company
papers. If all goes as hoped, the museum will open no later than
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our heart and soul is here, and this museum belongs to
Leavenworth _ and Kansas City,'' said J. Stewart Harvey Jr., a
great-grandson of Fred Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Harvey was an English immigrant who headed for Leavenworth,
where a job as a railway ticket agent awaited him. But he found his
future when he saw the need for better food for railroad
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   He sold his idea to the Atchison, Topeka &AMP; Santa Fe Railway,
which let him operate restaurants along its routes.
</P>
<P>
   The first Harvey restaurant opened in Topeka in 1876. By 1916
the company's operations stretched west to Los Angeles and employed
2,100 people. The company slogan became ``3000 Miles of
Hospitality, From Cleveland to the Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   And all of it was overseen from the company's headquarters on
the second floor of Kansas City's Union Station. The town became
the home of most of the company's executives, who loved living in
what they considered the gateway to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the perfect place,'' said J. Stewart Harvey Jr., who
lived here as a boy. ``A better version of St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harvey Co.'s attention to detail was legendary. Menus had
color prints of works by such artists as Thomas Hart Benton. Tables
were covered with linen tablecloths. Coffee was frequently checked
by a thermometer to ensure the correct temperature. Hamburger was
made from prime beef.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt it set the standard,'' said Rod Anderson,
owner of the Hereford House restaurant in Kansas City. He also
operates two restaurants in the renovated Union Station, including
the Harvey House Grill.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey expected no less from its customers. In 1921 it appealed
a case to the Oklahoma Supreme Court so Harvey restaurants would
not have to serve male diners who did not wear suits.
</P>
<P>
   Burnishing the story further were the Harvey Girls, the
restaurants' battalion of waitresses. The subject of a movie that
starred Judy Garland, Harvey Girls are seriously credited with
helping civilize the West by inhabiting rough-edged towns, where
they worked at Harvey restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs proved a lifeline to countless women. Through the
years, thousands of prospective Harvey Girls visited the company's
personnel office in Union Station.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1926, Kathryn Massey was an 18-year-old orphan
picking cotton on an Arkansas farm when she found out that the
Harvey Co. was hiring.
</P>
<P>
   She jumped at the chance of $50 a month plus room and board, and
was sent to a Harvey restaurant at La Junta, Colo., the first stop
on a long career that included working at Harvey restaurants at
Grand Canyon National Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed the money, and I was grateful,'' she said. ``It
changed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Other details about the company are coming out that bring new
attention to its effect on popular culture, as well as its business
acumen. Even its practice of hiring mavericks is gaining admirers.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Mary Jane Colter, who became the Harvey Co.'s
architect in the early 1900s, working out of a studio in Union
Station. She went on to design buildings such as the La Posada
hotel in Winslow, Ariz., and Hopi House in Grand Canyon National
Park, which have become National Historic Landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the geniuses of the Fred Harvey company is they were
comfortable in hiring individuals and not feeling threatened,''
said Karen Bartlett, producer of a film about Colter that the
Public Broadcasting Service broadcast last year.
</P>
<P>
   When Kansas City's Union Station opened in 1914, the Harvey Co.
decided to challenge the conventional wisdom that travelers didn't
have time to shop.
</P>
<P>
   It opened ``minute'' shops that sold products ranging from
cigars to toys to books. They thrived. /{Publisher's Weekly/} was
soon writing about Harvey's revolutionary ``take along a book''
idea. In 1937 it could report that the Union Station book shop was
the largest in town.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's real legacy, scholars say, is the way it
weaved its business interest with the culture of the Southwest and
created the region's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1905 it had a museum featuring Indian crafts and artifacts
adjoining the company's Alvarado Hotel in Albuquerque, N.M. It
began to offer tours that visited Indians where they lived.
</P>
<P>
   The company also formed an Indian Department that bought
American Indian-made items such as silver bracelets to be resold in
the company's gift shops. It kept a collection of Indian artifacts
that became highly sought by museums.
</P>
<P>
   William Randolph Hearst had a 30-year business relationship with
the Harvey Co. Through the years he bought about 500 items and
often urged the company to sell him its best stuff. The company
sometimes refused even a Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buffalo hide shields, as I told you, we have always
refused to sell and would not sell one of them only to you,'' a
Harvey executive wrote in a letter to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1930s the company was noticing less interest in the
Indian items from tourists and collectors. An attempt at a
mail-order business selling the items flopped.
</P>
<P>
   There were deeper problems as well. The Santa Fe had begun to
serve meals on trains. Harvey had the dining car franchise, but
that meant many of its trackside restaurants had to close.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Depression had also weakened the company. Another blow
came with the death of the company's president, Frederick Harvey,
the founder's grandson. Another Harvey took over, but his offices
were in Chicago, where he ran the dining car operation. The
company's headquarters, and most of the Harvey family along with
it, moved to Chicago in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   After an upswing in business because of World War II, the
decline resumed as rail travel waned. The company tried to rally by
opening restaurants along the Illinois Tollway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never made a cent'' on the tollway restaurants, said J.
Stewart Harvey Jr., who was being groomed for a top job at the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was told that the company's days were numbered and that
he would be better off pursuing a career elsewhere. In 1968 the
remnants were sold to another company, and the Harvey House
restaurant in Union Station was closed.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City area lost its last connections to the Harvey
Co., though the Harvey name was resurrected when Union Station
reopened last year. J. Stewart Harvey Jr., who is now 68 and lives
in the Boston area, found another career. He is philosophical about
the company's demise, saying, ``Life moves on.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not too far. He recalls a visit to the Grand Canyon,
where two of the Harvey Co.'s premier hotels _ El Tovar and Bright
Angel Lodge _ still operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to go back to these places; it makes me
sad,'' he said. ``But now there's the museum in Leavenworth, and
that makes me feel good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
