<SLUG> BC-POLL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOW REPUBLICAN TALENT LEADING MISSOURI GOVERNOR'S RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Republican Jim Talent
has taken a slight lead over Democrat Bob Holden in what has been a
largely invisible campaign for Missouri governor, a new survey
indicates.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The poll, commissioned by The Kansas City Star, gave Talent a 41
percent to 36 percent lead over Holden statewide. The 5-point
margin was up from a 2-point lead in a similar poll taken in
February.
</P>
<P>
   The lead, however, was within the poll's margin of error, which
was plus or minus 4 percentage points for each candidate's rating.
And 23 percent of the respondents were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most significant finding was the relatively low name
recognition of both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Holden, the current state treasurer, ran successful statewide
campaigns for treasurer in 1992 and 1996. Yet more than one in four
of those surveyed said they did not recognize his name.
</P>
<P>
   Talent, of Chesterfield in St. Louis County, has represented
Missouri's 2nd Congressional District for the past eight years. But
nearly one of every five people surveyed said they did not
recognize his name.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Neuman, chairman of the political science department at the
University of Missouri-Kansas City, said the poll's numbers reflect
how the race for governor has been overshadowed by the campaigns
for president and the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate race matches two of Missouri's most successful
politicians. The Republican incumbent, Sen. John Ashcroft, has won
five statewide races and the Democratic challenger, Mel Carnahan,
has won four.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race is kind of lost right now,'' Neuman said of the
Talent-Holden matchup. ``These other races are on, and people know
those people. This race is really the tail being wagged by the rest
of the dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden, of Springfield, is the only candidate seeking the
Democratic nomination in the Aug. 8 primary. Talent faces only
token opposition from two challengers for the Republican
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Neuman said Talent's lead over Holden could stem simply from his
greater name recognition in the St. Louis area, which accounted for
three of every eight people surveyed. As a statewide elected
official, Holden has no geographical base of support comparable to
Talent's.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by Richard Martin, Holden's campaign
manager. Martin noted that Talent's 5-point lead was coupled with a
7-point advantage in name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Issues are not the reason (for Talent's lead),'' Martin said.
``It's people saying `We know him, so we're for him.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Scott, Talent's campaign manager, agreed that the campaign
has a long way to go. But he said the poll indicated that Talent's
message was finding a receptive audience, particularly in rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Talent has tried to break through the noise of the
higher-profile campaigns, Scott said, by emphasizing grass-roots
organizing. He said Talent volunteers marched in 36 Fourth of July
parades, which he said far outpaced Holden's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted by Mason-Dixon Polling &AMP; Research in
Washington, D.C., surveyed by phone 624 registered voters who said
they regularly vote in state elections. The calls were made from
July 6 to July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Phone numbers were chosen randomly within a cross-section of
telephone exchanges and weighted to reflect voter turnout in each
county. That means that 37 percent of the respondents were from the
St. Louis area. About 19 percent of those surveyed were from the
Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   J. Bradford Coker, Mason-Dixon's managing director, said the
poll shows that the race is wide open, because voters still don't
know the candidates. But the numbers indicate that Talent has been
more successful at getting his name known and at putting together a
campaign organization.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to Talent's 46 percent to 33 percent lead in the St.
Louis area.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a Republican to take a double-digit lead in a
traditionally Democratic area is a sign that he is building some
support,'' Coker said.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis area tally was notable because it came in the wake
of five weeks of television ads the Holden campaign ran there in
May and early June. Martin said the campaign had spent $350,000 to
introduce Holden to St. Louis voters. He said the poll was too late
to be affected by the ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that while you are on the air, you have great
influence,'' Martin said. ``But when you're not on TV, you're off
the radar.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll found Talent with slim leads in five of six regions of
the state. Holden's only advantage was the Kansas City area, where
he led 40 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Talent also held a decided edge among men, who favored him 44
percent to 33 percent. Among women, Holden led 39 percent to 38
percent. Both campaigns found something to crow about in the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said Talent's showing in Kansas City was good considering
he had not spent much time here. Talent's 4-point lead in northern
Missouri and his 1-point advantage in the central part of the state
were astounding, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boone County being the largest and most Democratic skews
everything in central Missouri. And for us to be up by 1 point
shows that rural Missouri is embracing our message,'' Scott said.
``I'm convinced it's because of our road plan. Jim Talent is the
only guy willing to fulfill the promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Talent has proposed a $10 billion bond program to build roads
promised in a 1992 plan that would have given a four-lane highway
to every town with a population of at least 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Martin predicted that the gender gap would close once the
campaign heats up and men begin to hear Holden's message. He said
he was encouraged by Holden's standing within 5 points of Talent in
heavily Republican southwest Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he didn't put much credence in the poll results,
especially from rural counties. The Holden campaign's polling never
showed Talent leading anywhere but St. Louis, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what this poll shows is that it's going to be a bumpy
ride to the finish,'' Martin said. ``These snapshots of the
campaign can sometimes be a little out of focus.'' ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
