<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROUGHT TALK DRIES UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Just weeks ago, amid
all that talk about drought, Gil Chappell saw an 80 percent chance
of trouble ahead for Kansas City area lawns.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We had a dry fall and a dry winter,'' said Chappell, owner of
Lawn Pro of Kansas City, a Lenexa, Kan.-based company that has
serviced lawns for more than two decades. ``The early spring was
dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came rain. Now the front yards of Lawn Pro customers in
Johnson and Jackson counties are doing pretty well. And Chappell
describes himself as ``sort of confounded.''
</P>
<P>
   All that talk about drought, you might say, has dried up _ at
least for now.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the latest edition of the U.S. Drought Monitor, a
government-sponsored survey, showed significant improvements in
Kansas and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Dry areas from central Nebraska and north-central Kansas to the
east have received at least an inch of rain in the last week, and
the drought eased in most of the central United States, the survey
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 1, Kansas City has received about 9.4 inches of rain,
nearly three inches more than normal, according to the National
Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a remarkable turnaround,'' said Mark Svoboda, a
climatologist with the National Drought Mitigation Center in
Lincoln, Neb. ``In some areas, there's too much rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather patterns didn't happen as expected, he said. Moisture
flowed up from the Gulf of Mexico, and cold fronts from the
northwest came through and triggered storms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main explanation,'' Svoboda said, ``is that Mother Nature
is the one who calls the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can predict that drought problems are gone for 2000.
Chappell pointed out, for example, that area lawns are beginning to
develop signs of heat stress.
</P>
<P>
   Out in western Kansas, farms remain dry, as they do in the
Missouri Bootheel.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, everybody from corn farmers to government
officials were sounding more encouraged than discouraged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel much better,'' said Kyle Vickers, deputy director of
the Missouri Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   Crops look good, as do farm ponds, he said. Although Milan, Mo.,
still has problems with the town water supply, most Missouri towns
aren't experiencing severe trouble, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But soil moisture levels aren't where they should be, Vickers
said, and the drought should not be declared over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question is what does the rest of the summer hold?''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, the Agriculture Department ponders the same question.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the temperature stays hot and it doesn't rain, the crops
could easily deteriorate rather quickly,'' said Eldon Thiessen,
state statistician for the department. ``But we haven't gone down
that road yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Some recent area rainstorms have been huge.
</P>
<P>
   In Springfield, Mo., 6 inches of rain hit the southern sections
of the city this week, and some residents had to use boats to leave
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In northeast Kansas, rains of as much as 5 inches near the
Delaware River eased a water shortage on the Kickapoo Indian
Reservation. Water conservation measures are no longer in place.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kansas does have trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bill Graves has issued a drought watch for the Upper
Republican and Solomon river basins in northwest and north-central
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure residents are prepared to take appropriate
actions if conditions get worse,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Holton, Kan., a town about 30 miles north of Topeka, Kan., is
continuing to call for water conservation.
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Brad Mears said lawn and garden watering has been
limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been pretty good,'' he said. ``Our water demand
has dropped by 11 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the United States, conditions are far worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Drought Monitor said Thursday that in the southeastern
United States, a drought of historic proportions continues to
affect many areas.
</P>
<P>
   Streams are flowing at precipitously low levels, and crop
conditions declined markedly, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer Pat Ross, who grows corn outside Lawrence, Kan., said
Thursday that it's best not to pay too much attention to forecasts.
The prognosticators, he said, have a hard enough time predicting
the weather for tomorrow and the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Ross heard the drought talk in the spring and then saw plenty of
rain fall on his farm. He now has an above-average crop growing in
his fields. It may turn into a bumper crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are shaping up,'' said Ross, who raises field corn and
sweet corn. ``Our crops look pretty good for the time of the year
we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   But a farmer never wants to be without rain very long. Ross said
Thursday his crops need moisture again soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready,'' he said. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
