u a BC-NY-COLLAPSE-NYT &LR;      07-14 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLAPSE DOOMS BUILDING AND ITS TREASURES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A wall and two floors collapsed on Thursday at an
architectural salvage shop in the East Village whose showrooms were
loaded with cast-iron fireplaces, Victorian bathtubs, original
porcelain New York street signs and Tiffany windows. The damage
left the building listing dangerously, forcing the evacuation of 51
apartments in three nearby buildings and leading the city to begin
an emergency demolition.
</P>
<P>
   The partial collapse shortly after 1 p.m. tore a three-story
hole in the south wall of the building at Second Avenue and Houston
Street in Manhattan. A construction crew was making alterations to
the first floor of the four-story shop, Irreplaceable Artifacts, in
defiance of an order to stop work, a spokesman for the city's
Buildings Department said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials ordered the building destroyed, along with
everything inside _ including several Tiffany windows valued at
$50,000 each and a walnut ceiling from William Randolph Hearst's
collection. Evan Blum, the owner of Irreplaceable Artifacts,
salvages fixtures from demolished buildings and refurbishes them.
The collection was worth millions of dollars, Blum said.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse came two days after a building exploded in
Brooklyn, killing three people. The explosion, on Tuesday, believed
to have been caused by a natural gas leak, destroyed two town
houses in the Boerum Hill section.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's collapse, nine men and two women suffered minor
injuries, the police said. One man was taken to the hospital, where
he was expected to be treated and released. .
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters estimated that more than 100 people were shut out
of their apartments. Virginia Mewborn of the Red Cross, which will
feed and house the evacuated residents, said some were so
frightened that the agency had called in mental health counselors.
``What their idea of a building collapse is right now is what
happened in Brooklyn,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Blum had been planning to capitalize on the trendy night life on
the Lower East Side by opening a restaurant that would face his
courtyard on Houston Street. This spring, workers had begun to
punch arched doorways into the brick wall without a permit, said
Richard C. Visconti, the acting commissioner of the Buildings
Department.
</P>
<P>
   On May 3, Visconti said, the department ordered a halt to
construction and issued a $2,500 fine, which he said had not been
paid. But this week, the department approved a proposal to alter
the building, Visconti said, though no permits had been issued. The
architect of record on the plans was the building's owner, Walter
Blum, who is Evan Blum's father, Visconti said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrzej Przytkla, a bricklayer who was working in the building,
said that before the collapse, he and other workers were replacing
bricks in a weak wall.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Blum said the workers were making minor repairs that did
not require a permit, and attributed the collapse to the building's
age. ``The building is 125 years old,'' he said. ``You get to 125,
how are you going to feel? You are going to collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Blum is known as a pioneer in the field of
architectural salvage, and he has provided antique fixtures for
many movies and shows, including ``Sophie's Choice'' and ``Sex in
the City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic,'' said Ralph Stevens, a cousin. ``Evan spends his
whole life saving items from buildings that were going to be
demolished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
