<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNOUNCEMENT OFFICIALLY ENDS SPRINT, WORLDCOM MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Complaining they got
a raw deal from regulators, Sprint Corp. and WorldCom Inc.
officially scuttled their long-troubled merger Thursday,
acknowledging that fighting the government in court would be
costly, protracted, distracting and hold an uncertain outcome.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The concession brought to a close one of the most controversial
and tumultuous chapters in Sprint's 100-year history, but left the
future of the Kansas City area's largest private employer as
uncertain as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Chief Executive William T. Esrey moved quickly to
reassure anxious employees that he hadn't abandoned one deal only
to become merger bait for a company such as Deutsche Telekom or
BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint is not for sale,'' Esrey insisted at a press conference
at the company's new Overland Park &QL;  Kan., campus. The statement
drew rousing applause from several hundred employees who gathered
in an outdoor amphitheater at the campus to hear him pronounce the
unpopular deal dead.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said the WorldCom deal had been a unique opportunity to
fill gaps in the respective companies' services. He said management
is still obligated to consider better merger alternatives if they
come along, but he finds that unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see such a thing on the horizon,'' Esrey said. ``We
are not talking to anybody, haven't talked to anybody, and aren't
looking to talk to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, the company would adopt a high-growth strategy
focused on wireless, data and Internet services, which he predicted
could generate annual revenue growth of 20 percent for the next
three years at least.
</P>
<P>
   The ``go it alone'' mantra is one that Esrey has been using for
the past five years, and repeated up to the day his company
announced its intention to merge with WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   And while the intention to resume that strategy may play well
with employees, analysts and industry observers remain skeptical
given the surfeit of companies who might take a run at the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably putting on a new dress and getting ready to
go back to the ball,'' said Bob Rosenberg, an analyst with Insight
Research. ``Once you've been out there, it's hard to go back
another way.''
</P>
<P>
   Most observers think Sprint is still a strong independent
competitor. Indeed, many customers prefer it stay that way, as the
company has a solid reputation for technical innovation, customer
service and aggressive pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in the absence of the Sprint//WorldCom merger, there
is still no single telephone company that can provide a complete
portfolio of voice and data services wherever customers need them.
So Sprint is not at an immediate disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to employees Thursday, however, Esrey said it was
clear that with the rapid pace of change and consolidation, ``we
can't be all things to all people. We will need to be energized in
the areas where we have a competitive advantage and where we can
define the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Esrey wouldn't specify areas that the company intends to
de-emphasize, but he did make it clear that pricing and profit
margins are under pressure in the company's flagship long-distance
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, the consumer long-distance business is dead,'' he
said, encapsulating the argument that WorldCom and Sprint tried
unsuccessfully to make with regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In Esrey's view, the company's future lies in providing packages
of communications services that bundle local, long-distance,
wireless, data and high-speed Internet services to high-value
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has many of the components it needs for that bundle, but
still has the same weaknesses and resource problems that led it to
consider a merger with WorldCom in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Most notable is the company's lack of international assets, a
hole that would have been filled nicely by WorldCom, and still
could be by a large international carrier like Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Providing high-end voice and data services to lucrative
multinational customers is one of the sweet spots in the
telecommunications industry, but one key is the ability to provide
end-to-end service across geographic boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint sold its European networks when it entered its Global One
international venture with Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom.
Since that troubled partnership was dissolved, however, Sprint has
been quietly expanding its Internet backbone in Western Europe,
Esrey said in an interview on Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, Sprint lacks local connections in markets around
the country to reach business and consumers without relying on the
regional Bell operating companies like Southwestern Bell, which
control the local loop.
</P>
<P>
   Again, that was one advantage of a merger with WorldCom, which
owns fiber networks in 100 of the largest metropolitan areas
nationwide. It's also the reason that some observers see merger
possibilities with BellSouth, whose local territory covers the
entire Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said the company plans to lease fiber rings in major
metropolitan areas around the country, and would install its own
equipment in Bell company offices that could reach 30 million
consumers by the end of the year, half of them with its high-speed
Sprint ION service.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's local strategy, Esrey said, relies heavily on ION, a
bundled service that combines high-speed data with local and
long-distance service. ION has been introduced for consumers in 10
cities, but has been plagued by delays, technical problems and
limited geographic availability.
</P>
<P>
   The holes in Sprint's services aren't necessarily fatal,
analysts say. The company doesn't have to build and own all the
facilities it uses to provide service.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take technology and the backbone they have and use lots of
other carriers to fill the gaps,'' said Jeanne Schaaf, an analyst
with Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``Sprint's brand and
Sprint's Web site will still be out in front of the customers, but
all the facilities don't have to be Sprint's.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger hurdle Esrey may face is the lingering expectation
that he will sell the company to bring a quick return to
shareholders, including himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as everyone expects you to be acquired, it's hard to
operate for the long term,'' said Steve Koppman at Dataquest Corp.,
a market research firm. ``Employees leave. Others make plans to
retire. Customers are reluctant to sign new contracts if they're
worried the company will be acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has already faced some turnover in its top management
ranks, and could face additional departures if Esrey and his top
lieutenant, Ronald T. LeMay, fail to overcome employee skepticism
regarding the company's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only issue is whether Esrey and LeMay have what it takes
to bring some enthusiasm back to the employees and get this thing
going forward,'' Schaaf said.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said he was disappointed in recent management departures,
and would be worried if the company ``lost a whole slew of
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the management team we have in place is as strong as
ever,'' he said. ``We're not hurting, wounded or nicked.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, Esrey and LeMay will begin traveling
around the Sprint system to meet with employees and start an
initiative called ``Mapping the Future.''
</P>
<P>
   He assured employees Thursday that he was with them ``for the
long haul,'' and wrote in his employee letter that ``my life, my
future is here.''
</P>
<P>
   One long-distance employee who listened to Esrey's speech at the
campus Thursday was still circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just see who comes along next,'' he said.
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 0028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
