r f BC-SPRINT-ESREY-KAN &LR;      07-14 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-ESREY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LETTER FROM WILLIAM T. ESREY TO SPRINT EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By   
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   Dear Associates:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today we announced the termination of our proposed merger with
WorldCom, effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   As I reflect on the past nine months, it is clear that a merged
Sprint and WorldCom was an exceptional opportunity to create a
broad-based international competitor. But no matter how much we may
disagree with the regulators or believe that we could eventually
prevail in court, it is time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Litigating these matters in court against the Justice Department
would be costly, protracted and distracting. And, even if we
prevail in court, the merger would still be contingent on getting
approvals from the FCC and the European Commission. Given the
time-consuming nature of the litigation, the extended regulatory
processes and the veil of continued uncertainty, pursuing that
option would not be in the best interests of our shareholders,
customers or any of you.
</P>
<P>
   I am confident in our decision. It is the right one because of
what our employees can accomplish going forward. No matter the
distractions, no matter what competitors threw at you or what
technological changes occurred, you have never lost sight of what
it takes to be successful. You are the Sprint brand. Through your
efforts we have delivered record results for 12 consecutive
quarters, and I firmly believe we will continue that success well
into the future.
</P>
<P>
   When we decided to pursue the merger, it was not because the
management team or the board of directors wanted to sell Sprint or
thought we were too small to compete. To say we are too small is
fundamentally wrong. We have successfully competed against much
larger companies and have been successful in growing faster than
the market. Rather, we chose to pursue the WorldCom merger because
it gave us an opportunity to do things we probably couldn't do as a
stand-alone company. It would have given us immediate scope and
geographic placement of facilities to be a more general competitor.
</P>
<P>
   However, we have an excellent array of assets, products and
services in the fastest-growing areas of telecommunications:
wireless personal communications services, the Internet, high-speed
data services, wireline and wireless broadband services, along with
packages and bundles of communications services aimed at high-end
consumers and small business.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weeks and months ahead, we will be mapping out
strategies that build upon our current success. It is clear,
however, given the rapid pace of change and consolidation that we
can't be all things to all people. We will need to be energized in
the areas where we have a competitive advantage and where we can
define the future.
</P>
<P>
   In my view, success lies with our ability to offer bundled
communications packages. It lies with placing more emphasis than
ever in implementing a ``One Sprint'' attitude in every employee.
It means a fast-moving, risk-taking environment that rewards action
and creativity. It means putting our capital resources in the areas
growing the fastest and building those initiatives and businesses
at even faster rates so that they form the basis of a very
high-growth strategy. We have a remarkable engine in place.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS is again expected to lead the industry in subscriber
growth in the second quarter, with growth being driven by extensive
consumer distribution channels (presence in more than 12,000 retail
outlets nationwide) and expanding penetration of the corporate
market.
</P>
<P>
   Data services in both the wireline and wireless businesses are
vibrant. Sprint PCS has several hundred thousand customers using
PCS wireless Web services, and new content providers are being
added almost daily. High-end data services in the company's long
distance operation grew 50 percent year over year in the first
quarter and have annualized revenues in excess of $3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In the area of broadband services, Sprint ION is now available
to large businesses nationwide and to small businesses and
consumers in 10 major markets. High-speed Internet access over
fixed-wireless (MMDS) is off to a highly promising start in Phoenix
and Tucson, and we continue to rapidly deploy DSL service in
Sprint's local territories.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of a separate business unit focused on Internet
services is already establishing momentum, growing at over 75
percent or roughly double the market rate of growth. Web hosting
centers have been added to the Sprint backbone network and we have
expanded into western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Our local division had its best quarter in its 100-year history.
We are holding our own in an increasingly competitive traditional
voice long distance market, where we continue to experience
double-digit volume growth.
</P>
<P>
   It is vitally important that you stay informed. During the
merger process we were committed to communicating with you frankly
and frequently. We will not sway from that commitment as we move
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   On Pinpoint we have replaced the merger site with a new site:
Sprint Strategic News _ Mapping The Future. Ron LeMay and I will be
traveling around the Sprint system meeting with as many of you as
possible to talk about the future, and we look forward to hearing
from you.
</P>
<P>
   My life, my future is here. Ron LeMay has assured me that the
same is true for him. We are both more enthused than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint brand has always stood for technological innovation,
excellent customer service and creative marketing. This is our
foundation. It is our strength. And with your commitment, together
we will continue to make Sprint the standard by which others are
measured and the most-admired company in our industry.
Sincerely, Bill Esrey Chairman and CEO
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
