<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP HONORS HOFFA; NBC RELYING ON CABLE; DEMOCRATS SETTLE LABOR
DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE CONVENTIONS
</P>
<P>
   GOP HONORS HOFFA
</P>
<P>
   Republicans plan to hold a reception honoring the Teamsters
president, James P. Hoffa, on July 31, the first night of their
party's convention in Philadelphia. The announcement Thursday by
Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee,
underlined the Republicans' desire to win Teamsters support, or at
least persuade the 1.4-million-member union not to endorse Vice
President Al Gore, who has worked hard behind the scenes to win the
union's backing. Thus far, Hoffa has bucked the AFL-CIO and not
endorsed Gore because the vice president supported the China trade
bill. In recent weeks, Hoffa has had kind words for Ralph Nader,
the Green Party candidate. Nicholson said this would be the first
time in at least 20 years that the Republicans have held a
reception for a union president at their convention.
</P>
<P>
   NBC RELYING ON CABLE
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the migration of political news to cable, NBC News
announced Thursday that its coverage of the party conventions on
one of its cable outlets, MSNBC, would form ``the centerpiece of
the NBC News effort.'' NBC will carry prime time reports from the
Republican and Democratic conventions for a total of only two and a
half hours on the final two nights of the four-day events, with the
Republicans in Philadelphia and the Democrats in Los Angeles. That
is less than the four hours over three nights that ABC News has
announced. But NBC News officials said the division's anchors and
correspondents will appear throughout the continuing coverage of
all four days of the gatherings on MSNBC. A total of 13
convention-related programs will be broadcast from the convention
cities by the network. The broadcast networks, which are much more
heavily watched than the cable channels, have been criticized by
media watchdog groups for cutting back their coverage this year.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS SETTLE LABOR DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   The last union without a contract for work at next month's
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles has resolved a labor
dispute, allaying fears that labor troubles might disrupt the
gathering. Local 501 of the International Union of Operating
Engineers accepted a contract offer on Tuesday to manage the
heating, cooling and electrical systems in the convention venue.
Meanwhile, in Philadelphia, site of this summer's Republican
National Convention, Local 58 of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers is questioning why some television networks are
not using union laborers for telecommunications work in that city's
convention hall. Mayor John Street is trying to resolve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   THE REFORM PARTY
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN CONSIDERS A LAWSUIT
</P>
<P>
   In the Reform Party's latest show of disarray, Pat Buchanan, who
is seeking its presidential nomination, has threatened to sue the
party if the names of 400,000 people who requested party primary
ballots through his campaign are made available to his rival, John
Hagelin. By a 7-2 vote on Wednesday night, the party's executive
committee voted to uphold rules that provide all candidates with
equal access to potential primary voters. The actual names are not
given to any campaign. But Buchanan has refused, and a spokesman
said his campaign would not discuss the matter. Not so for Hagelin,
who called Buchanan's position ``the latest assault on the
democratic process of the Reform Party.'' The Hagelin campaign has
agreed to make its list of 24,000 names available to Buchanan for
the distribution of campaign material. Michael Farris, chairman of
the presidential nomination committee, said he was trying to reach
an agreement with the Buchanan campaign to avoid a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Elizabeth, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ No public events
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
