<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-FON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS OFFER PREDICTION ON SPRINT STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The stock market was
initially unimpressed by the go-it-alone strategy broadcast by
Sprint Corp. Chairman William T. Esrey on Thursday after the merger
with WorldCom Inc. was officially called off.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sprint's FON stock closed at $48, up $1, on the New York Stock
Exchange. That price is a far cry from the $76 a share offered by
WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said Sprint shareholders may yet see the
stock hit $70 and up, but probably not soon. At least one believes
Sprint stock will languish unless it is prepared for a radical
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Sprint's PCS digital wireless business rose 61 cents
to $61.81 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even if another of the myriad of potential buyers makes a run at
Sprint, they probably couldn't find the level of cost savings that
Sprint and WorldCom could, some analysts said. As a result, they
would probably bid far less than WorldCom's $129 billion offer.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said Thursday he knew shareholders were disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had negotiated a very favorable deal for ourselves, and we
didn't get it done,'' Esrey said. ``It wasn't fair and they are
disappointed, I am sure. It was a lost opportunity, but I don't
think we are any worse off for having done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the sting of disappointment won't wear away soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say patience is the most important element at this
time,'' said Tom Burnett, president of Merger Insight, a research
firm for institutional investors. ``We think Sprint has a lot of
value. We also don't see the stock moving for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett conceded another buyer could emerge for Sprint. It does
have ``trophy properties,'' he said. Deutsche Telekom of Germany
and Atlanta-based BellSouth have been mentioned as possible buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know who the big players are, but they probably won't rush
out and make an offer,'' Burnett said. ``They will let the stock
trade down and quietly fade. We have no problem seeing a value
ultimately of $70, but when? We are of the view that it will trade
in the $40 to $42 range on the low end and $50 at the high end for
a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Klugman, of Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, agrees that
unless another buyer comes in _ and another might _ the stock will
remain depressed for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint has a lot going for it, but a lot of the performance of
Sprint right now will depend on when and if they find another
buyer,'' Klugman said.
</P>
<P>
   If Sprint remains independent, Klugman said the Westwood company
has operating holes to fill that will cost it money to buy or
build. ``It doesn't have much local, and it doesn't have anything
internationally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint had an international alliance with Deutsche Telekom and
France Telecom that gave it access to European infrastructure. But
that partnership dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   Local networks may be an even greater concern, Klugman said,
because Sprint can't get all of its other services to customers
cost effectively if it has to continue to go through someone else's
local lines.
</P>
<P>
   CIBC World Markets has downgraded Sprint's stock to a ``hold,''
but not because the WorldCom deal failed. CIBC no longer believes
the business model of being a vertically integrated
telecommunications company is valid.
</P>
<P>
   CIBC analyst Steve Kamman said his firm thinks
telecommunications is at the same place that personal computers
were in 1987 when the cost of providing more and more computer
power dropped dramatically. In telecommunications, the cost of
providing fiber optics and broadband services is beginning to fall
exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   CIBC sees companies dividing into wholesalers of
telecommunications and Internet services, and retailers with strong
marketing and customer attention. Kamman sees Sprint falling in the
second category.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 18 months, companies like Level 3 Communications and
Williams Communications have emerged as aggressive wholesalers of
services such as fiberoptic networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can maximize the value of your customers or you can
maximize the value of your assets, but you are going to have to
focus on one or the other,'' Kamman said.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom wanted Sprint primarily because of Sprint's PCS
wireless service. WorldCom has no wireless operations, considered
essential to have a complete consumer telecommunications division.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have suggested that if WorldCom didn't get
Sprint's wireless operations, WorldCom might get out of consumer
services entirely and concentrate just on business customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has changed in a year,'' Kamman said, ``and dusting off
last year's strategic plan is probably not going to get it.''
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
