<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HIP-INQUIRY-2TAKES     07-14 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HIP-INQUIRY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK HEALTH INSURANCE PLAN UNDER SCRUTINY FOR FREE-WHEELING
DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Fla., N.J.) 
By CHRISTOPHER DREW and MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Anthony Watson took command of the Health
Insurance Plan of Greater New York nearly a decade ago, he vowed to
turn the city's oldest and least expensive health maintenance
organization into a first-class operation.
</P>
<P>
   He had bold plans to keep caring for the nonprofit's traditional
New York clientele _ city workers and the poor _ while attracting
millions of wealthier corporate employees up and down the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, many of his ambitions have failed, burying HIP
in a deep financial hole. Expanding into other states has led to
big losses. And regulators in New York are investigating whether
Watson spent too freely in other ways, squandering millions of
dollars on lavish salaries, executive perquisites and contracts for
board members and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Both the state Insurance Department and the attorney general's
office are examining HIP's finances, looking into what former
executives describe as a clubby atmosphere that often seemed at
odds with HIP's special role in the city's health care system.
Mayor Fiorello La Guardia created the plan in the 1940s to provide
affordable coverage for city workers, and it insures many Medicare
and Medicaid patients.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several months, insurance regulators have
dispatched auditors to pore over HIP's books. They have also
subpoenaed documents and taken depositions from Watson and two
other executives.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Levin, the superintendent of insurance, said the scope of
the inquiry was broad.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the questions focus on Watson, 59, whose taste for fancy
cars and corporate apartments seems to have infuriated regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, HIP's financial reserves have dwindled below the
amount required by law.
</P>
<P>
   While Watson says he did nothing improper, the investigators are
exploring whether some of the expenditures were inappropriate for a
nonprofit corporation like HIP, which is exempt from most taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say HIP's troubles also reflect other problems. They
say Watson's expansions beyond HIP's New York customer base were
too risky in competitive health industry. And recent changes to
broaden the stable of doctors, stemming in part from a feud between
Watson and a New York medical group, have troubled health
regulators trying to minimize disruptions in care.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators and analysts said they do not expect HIP to collapse.
But they said it is also clear that the city's taxpayers will have
to underwrite part of the cost of reviving the plan.
</P>
<P>
   HIP's biggest losses have come outside New york. It lost $40
million when its operation in New Jersey collapsed last year. Its
operations in Florida have cost $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   But given its appeal to workers in the New York's clerical,
sanitation and teachers unions, the easiest place for HIP to raise
money is in New York, where it counts 200,000 city workers and
their relatives among its 796,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   On July 1, HIP raised its premiums by 9.9 percent, which will
add about $100 million to the city's health care costs. HIP
officials say they plan increases of 8 percent to 12 percent in
each of the next three years. Such increases are not inconsistent
with what other HMOs have been seeking, and HIP remains a popular
option because other plans charge premiums that are 10 percent to
20 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, a tall, gruff man known for his intimidating style,
conceded in an interview that he had made mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his $1 million annual pay package, he agreed that the
most visible symbols of extravagance were two Jaguars that HIP
leased for him _ one each in New York and Florida. HIP and its
Florida subsidiary also rented several apartments for executives,
including one for Watson near Miami that cost $7,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   HIP got rid of the cars and apartments last year after The Daily
News wrote about some of HIP's expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some critics caution that at HIP, there are echoes of the
kind of financial dangers that almost ruined Empire Blue Cross and
Blue Shield, another health provider, in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   HIP fell below the state requirement for financial reserves four
years ago. It is now $71 million below the $153 million required as
a cushion against unexpected claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really short,'' said Martin Weiss, chairman of Weiss
Ratings, which analyzes the strength of HMOs. ``They are not broke,
but they are heading that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson and other HIP executives dispute that, saying they
believe the worst days are past. They note that while HIP's
customer base fell to 727,000 members in 1998 from 906,000 members
in 1990, the company began to rebound in 1999, reflecting some
success in attracting new corporate clients. And last year, the New
York operation made its largest profit ever _ $25 million, though
most of it was sent to cover losses in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a much better company than we were,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   Complaint files at the state Department of Health suggest that
HIP's care has improved in some areas, but that its quality of care
has remained about the same over all, as at other large HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   HIP TAKES ON HEAVYWEIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   When Watson became HIP's chief executive in 1990, the giant
profit-making HMOs like Oxford Health Plans and U.S. Healthcare
were growing rapidly, and HIP's niche in New York no longer looked
secure.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that Watson's response _ competing with the
heavyweight HMOs _ started HIP on the free-spending ways that have
endangered it.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he had little choice. At the time, HIP had a
``terrible reputation.'' he said, ``It was accused of being a place
with foreign doctors, dirty clinics, and just not a place you
wanted to get medical care.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, who had worked in public health for 20 years, spent
millions of dollars to renovate HIP's medical centers. Members had
to go to these clinics for treatment, an approach that set HIP
apart from other HMOs with a greater choice of doctors. Watson also
decided to expand operations in New Jersey and Florida. HIP had
moved into Florida in the late 1980s to serve New York members who
retired there, and Watson wanted to compete for more business
there.
</P>
<P>
   To improve HIP's image, he moved headquarters from a building
with wire-caged windows to elegant offices on West 34th Street. He
also raised salaries to levels that were competitive with large,
for-profit companies. Before long, office meetings were accompanied
by catered meals, former executives say. Watson held management
retreats at the Montauk Yacht Club on Long Island and rewarded
sales representatives with trips to resorts.
</P>
<P>
   But his ambitions foundered in the mid-1990s. First, the
Giuliani administration, facing budget problems, forced HIP to
accept a three-year freeze in premiums. So in 1996, HIP tapped its
financial reserves to upgrade an antiquated computer system that
was letting claims go unpaid. With membership falling, it also
began making plans to create its own broad network of doctors to
appeal to more customers.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem, business analysts said, was that managed
care companies were undercutting one another on premiums, and HIP
was ill-equipped to compete. Expenses spiraled up, and as a
nonprofit corporation, HIP could not raise capital as easily as its
profit-making competitors to off-set losses.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators closed HIP's operations in New Jersey last year after
a troubled partner, PHP Healthcare Corp. of Reston, Va., raked off
most of HIP's cash.
</P>
<P>
   Now HIP's Florida affiliate is costing even more. Last year, HIP
sent $18 million _ all raised from premiums paid by New Yorkers _
to Florida. That brought the total of HIP's subsidies there to $80
million, more than enough to cover the current deficit in its
reserve in New York.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Records show that HIP has spent tens of millions of dollars in
Florida on marketing, including expensive sky box rentals at
professional sports events. Yet it still has fewer than half the
members of any one of the three largest HMOs there.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, federal prosecutors have been investigating whether
a Florida union leader did anything improper to help outside sales
brokers hired by HIP. The brokers helped HIP win a contract with
the Broward County School District, but Watson said he did not
believe anything improper occurred.
</P>
<P>
   PAYING FOR EXECUTIVE PERKS
</P>
<P>
   As Watson's ambitions for HIP rose, so did his insistence on
enjoying the rewards of running a larger company, former executives
say.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's salary and bonuses soared to $995,000 last year from
$395,000 in 1993. Contractually, he is entitled to a company car.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance regulators are reportedly looking at whether HIP
violated any laws that forbid nonprofit corporations to enrich
their officers or to spend in ways that do not further their public
mission.
</P>
<P>
   One set of questions involves the corporate apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Watson acknowledged that he personally selected the
$7,000-a-month waterfront apartment in Miami. Watson said he used
it once a month when he went to Florida on business.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Maiorana, the plan's spokesman, said HIP also had rented
two apartments in Manhattan in the late 1990s to save on hotel
bills for visiting executives. He said the most expensive one, on
East 65th Street, cost $4,500 a month.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are also scrutinizing some of HIP's contracts
with suppliers. In particular, they are looking at millions of
dollars in building leases and office-cleaning contracts to
determine whether HIP paid too much.
</P>
<P>
   One concern is that shortly before Watson was promoted to HIP's
top job in late 1990, HIP agreed to a new lease on a clinic that
real estate experts describe as unusually favorable to the owners.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are looking into whether those charges were
excessive _ and drained money from medical care. Documents show
that in 1998, the doctors solicited a proposal from another
cleaning contractor offering cheaper rates.
</P>
<P>
   THE QUESTION OF OVERSIGHT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To consumer advocates, one question is: Why didn't HIP's board
members _ or political leaders _ better monitor Watson?
</P>
<P>
   As a nonprofit organization, HIP depends on civic, union and
business leaders to oversee its executives. Critics say that at
HIP, one answer may be that influential board members had business
ties or other possible conflicts that compromised their
independence.
</P>
<P>
   When an investment adviser, Charles Johnston, left HIP's New
York board in 1994, shifting over to its boards in New Jersey and
Florida, Watson gave him a $250,000 contract to watch the New York
plan's investments.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1993, when the Rev. Carl Flemister, a Baptist minister,
suggested sending volunteers to comfort hospitalized HIP members,
Watson gave him a $125,000-a-year contract to start the program.
Flemister is now the chairman of an umbrella board that oversees
all of HIP's operations. He still runs the volunteer program and
was paid $183,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elson, a professor at Stetson University College of Law
in St. Petersburg, Fla., and an expert in corporate governance,
said such arrangements could cause board members to consider their
own interests over the company's.
</P>
<P>
   Flemister, Johnston and Watson all denied that the deals had
clouded their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be a fair question to anyone who doesn't know me,''
Flemister said. ``But I would not destroy my reputation of 50
years, having people gossip that Tony controls me. ''
</P>
<P>
   The regulators are also looking at whether HIP officials have
done anything improper in encouraging doctors to make political
donations.
</P>
<P>
   As a nonprofit organization, HIP cannot make campaign
contributions. So the medical groups that operate its clinics
created a political action committee in 1992. Records show that the
committee has donated $160,000 to more than four dozen political
groups and officials, including Gov. George E. Pataki and his
predecessor, Gov. Mario Cuomo, and Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and
former Mayor David N. Dinkins.
</P>
<P>
   But here, too, there are questions about whether Watson or his
aides have gone too far. Documents show that in June 1999, for
instance, Watson's chief of staff, Raymond Vacca, faxed the
committee a list of seven recommended donations totaling $8,750.
</P>
<P>
   HIP BANKING ON NEW MEMBERS
</P>
<P>
   New York regulators could force major changes in how HIP
operates. New Jersey is demanding $83 million to cover medical
bills left unpaid there. And while Watson thinks he can stop the
losses in Florida, he said he also could sell or close the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Watson expressed confidence that HIP's fortunes had
turned. He estimated that with the recent rate increase, the plan
would earn a $40 million profit in New York this year.
</P>
<P>
   And under state law HIP, can keep raising rates without
regulatory approval. This means that HIP could resuscitate its
finances through a series of rate increases, unless New York city
officials object. The city pays the premium for workers who choose
HIP, and it contributes the same amount for workers who select a
more expensive plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, HIP is also banking heavily on attracting more
members by expanding its network of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, state health regulators delayed HIP's plan to
transfer the patients cared for by the New York Medical Group to
organizations run by four hospitals. State health officials said
they were worried that care for some patients, especially pregnant
women and those with cancer, could be disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, regulators have agreed to changes only in the Bronx
and in Westchester County, where Montefiore Medical Center began
caring for patients on July 1. Contracts with hospitals in
Manhattan are either still being completed or are awaiting state
approval. And while HIP expects most of the same doctors to remain
at its clinics, many are now working under temporary arrangements,
and some have quit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
