<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-ANGST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY NEEDS TO CONTINUE COMMUNICATION WITH EMPLOYEES, EXPERTS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In the wake of a
failed megamerger, Sprint Corp. Chairman William T. Esrey and his
lieutenants face a monumental task in getting their 78,000
worldwide employees refocused, recommitted and re-energized,
consultants said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A corporate change consultant believes Esrey got off to a good
start with a long letter to employees, which was circulated
Thursday morning, hours before Esrey officially announced that the
$129 billion deal was definitely off.
</P>
<P>
   He addressed all the important issues in his letter _ why the
merger was agreed to in the first place, why it was being called
off, why he thinks Sprint can go it alone, and why Sprint has been
and will be successful. He also emphasized the role of employees in
building the Kansas City area's largest company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd give the letter an A _ he hit all the hot points,'' said
Don Blohowiak, a corporate change consultant based in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference Thursday morning, employees responded with
prolonged applause when Esrey said Sprint is not for sale. Yet for
the rest of the conference, many employees listened with crossed
arms and grim faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because there's still this realization that this really
isn't over,'' Blohowiak said. ``On an intuitive level, they all
know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Blohowiak expects recruiting vultures to circle
Sprint now more than ever, as wearied and drained employees who've
lived through nine months of angst, anxiety and uncertainty have to
decide if they would want to subject themselves to a repeat
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint employees are between a hard spot and their hearts,''
said Mary Lippitt, who specializes in organizational improvement
and leadership.
</P>
<P>
   To minimize the possibility of brain drain, Sprint officials
need to give employees a compelling reason to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what employees need now is candor and a focus on
Sprint's mission,'' said Connie Russell, a career development coach
who has several Sprint employees as clients. ``They need to restate
their core business and why each and every employee is valuable to
the future of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the letter to employees Thursday and in all
subsequent communications from the executive suite, employees will
be looking for the tea leaves that will reveal their future.
</P>
<P>
   And during the coming months there will be a lot of stress on
middle management in particular, who will be trying to interpret
signals from senior management to reassure those on the front
lines.
</P>
<P>
   But Randy Pennington, a business consultant who co-wrote On My
Honor, I Will, said it's his impression that Esrey and his team
have been forthright.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Blohowiak said it's his guess that everyone at Sprint _
from Esrey all the way down _ is shell-shocked by the bouncing ball
of it's on, it's off, it's dying, it's dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very tiring,'' Blohowiak said. ``There are a bunch of
very fatigued people at Sprint who should probably take a
vacation.''
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
