u p BC-BUSH-TEXAS-BUDGET-NYT     07-14 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TEXAS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BUSH, TEXAS DEFICIT BECOMES ISSUE IN PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For the past few years, Texas has enjoyed such a
booming economy that any news about the state budget has usually
been good. So when state lawmakers this week announced a $610
million shortfall, the bad news came as a surprise and prompted a
pregnant political question:
</P>
<P>
   How much of the blame belongs to Gov. George W. Bush? Needless
to say, Bush and his presidential rival, Vice President Al Gore,
offered very different answers on Thursday as they campaigned
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, where he appeared with former Sen. Bill Bradley of
New Jersey, Gore blamed the Texas governor for putting
``politically popular'' tax cuts ahead of paying for Medicaid and
other state services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Gore said, ``Governor Bush wants to do for American
what he's done for Texas: go to Washington and spend our surplus
and then more for budget-busting tax cuts _ and hope that somehow
it will all add up.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pennsylvania, with Gov. Tom Ridge at his side, Bush shot
back, pointing out that earlier state budget surpluses had made tax
cuts the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al Gore suggests a state with a surplus shouldn't cut
taxes,'' he asked, ``then how can the American people count on Al
Gore to cut taxes when our nation has a surplus?''
</P>
<P>
   There also was no agreement in Texas as to where any blame
should lie. Several Democratic lawmakers traced the shortfall to
the $1.6 billion in tax cuts pushed by Bush and his allies. But the
governor's supporters countered that such claims were cheap
politics, noting that many Democrats had voted for the budget
package.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate question in Texas is, what, if anything, the
deficit means for the state's fiscal future. In a bad economic
year, the news might have meant immediate budget cuts. But the
strong economy is expected to generate $1 billion in surplus tax
revenues, and key lawmakers said the money would more than cover
the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were predictions of future belt-tightening. On
Tuesday, Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, a Republican, agreed that the state
did not face any budget cuts, but he said expanding services as
part of the next budget package now seemed less likely.
</P>
<P>
   The basic explanation for the shortfall can be found in Texas'
two-year budget cycle. Lawmakers drafted the current budget, which
runs through Aug. 31, 2001, during last year's legislative session.
The $99 billion budget, which is divided about evenly between
federal matching funds and state general revenues, included a
$3,000 pay raise for teachers and $1.7 billion in tax cuts _ the
latter pushed aggressively by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But state Rep. Rob Junell, the influential Democratic chairman
of the House Appropriations Committee, said the shortfall occurred
because lawmakers had underestimated the cost of some services when
they drafted the current budget. In particular, he said, the rising
cost of prescription drugs had created Medicaid overruns of $439
million, while a shortage of prison space meant the state had to
spend $168 million to pay for local jail space. The remaining
overruns were divided between different state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do the best you can in forecasting these numbers, but
you're going to be wrong,'' said Junell, a legislative ally of the
governor's.
</P>
<P>
   He said such mid-cycle shortfalls requiring supplemental
appropriations were common in Texas. ``Had we not had a governor
running for president of the United States, there would be no
story, because we do this all the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for Bush, noted that shortfalls
also occurred in midstream during other budgets _ $182 million in
1997 and $104 million in 1999. In Pennsylvania, Bush said that
President Clinton was planning to sign on Thursday a $15 billion
supplemental appropriation for extra expenses in the current
federal budget year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But today my opponent attacked me because we're going to do
the same thing in Texas,'' he said. He added: ``That's why Vice
President Al Gore has got no credibility on an issue like this. On
one hand he wants to launch an attack. On the other hand President
Clinton is doing the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic Texas lawmakers were critical of Bush and the
emphasis he has placed on tax cuts. Garnet Coleman, a Democrat from
Texas, flew to Wisconsin to appear with Gore and brief reporters
about the budget shortfall. He said the size of this year's
shortfall was particularly worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   ``A supplemental appropriation is standard,'' said Coleman. ``A
supplemental appropriation between $610 million and $750 million is
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats say they worry that the deficit may reach $750
million. Coleman was particularly critical of the Medicaid
overruns, saying that Bush and lawmakers had known that fewer
federal dollars would be available for the program. He said
lawmakers intentionally underfunded Medicaid to free up money for
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that by spending this year's $1 billion surplus to
cover the shortfall, future budgets are short-changed. ``Once
you've spent that $1 billion, you've got to keep spending it
forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Gallego, a Democrat state representative expressed concern
that the state might return to the problems of the early 1990's,
when tough economic times prevented any expansion of services. But
he, like other Democrats, did vote in favor of the budget package.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of unfair to Monday morning quarterback, to say what
you did didn't work,'' he said. ``We had an opportunity to vote yay
or nay, and most of us voted yay. We're in the same boat as
Governor Bush on this issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
