<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN LAWMAKERS RELEASE DETAILS OF SUSPECT LOANS DURING BANK
CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Opposition lawmakers have disclosed the names of
about 3,300 wealthy debtors linked to questionable bank loans that
became part of a huge government bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies from the Party of the Democratic Revolution disclosed
the names at a press conference late Wednesday. Computer hackers
hired by the party cracked codes protecting the debtors' list on a
compact disc.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the loans ``a great fraud against the nation,'' Pablo
Gomez, head of the party's congressional delegation, assailed the
government and the bail-out agency, saying they pursued ``a policy
of absolute freedom for bankers.'' In the list of suspicious loans
is an album of top-echelon magnates who were close to the
government and fell into deep financial trouble after the currency
crash of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   It includes a loan to a brother of Rogelio Montemayor Seguy, the
current director of Petroleos Mexicanos, the state-owned oil
company, and another to a relative of a governing party senator.
</P>
<P>
   Also listed is a $5 million loan for a car race track belonging
to Jorge Hank Rhon, the son of a veteran governing party
politician.
</P>
<P>
   A $422,000 loan went directly to the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, in the state of Jalisco. The party
defaulted on the debt.
</P>
<P>
   The list was compiled by a Canadian auditor, Michael Mackey. The
congress hired him in 1998 to make a thorough audit of the bank
rescue. He drew up the list after sifting through tens of thousands
of loans in the bail-out agency's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   His list details loans totaling $7.8 billion that Mackey found
to be seriously irregular, either because they did not meet bank
credit standards or because they were made to people and companies
with direct business ties to the lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Mackey's list also includes loans to several prominent bankers
who are known to be facing criminal prosecution for huge frauds.
</P>
<P>
   Legal action has begun in hundreds of cases from the Mackey
list.
</P>
<P>
   The entire bank rescue so far has cost Mexican taxpayers $100
billion. The government jumped in to shore up the financial system
when it nearly collapsed in 1995, as interest rates skyrocketed and
millions of Mexicans defaulted on their debts. Finance officials
were obliged to act because all Mexican bank deposits at that time
were fully government insured.
</P>
<P>
   The officials argued that they did what they had to do to avert
catastrophe. Opposition lawmakers charge that that gave the banks
the opportunity to fob off billions of dollars in illegal loans
that are now being paid by the taxpayers. They say that the bailout
agency should not have agreed to pay for those loans.
</P>
<P>
   The records of the bail-out agency are confidential, protected
by bank secrecy laws, as was Mackey's auditing report. By agreement
with the parties in congress, Mackey put the list of potentially
illegal loans on one compact disc and provided separate secret
codes to each of the main parties, so that they could see the list
if they all agreed.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo and his party, the PRI, refused to
provide their code and blocked every opposition effort to release
information on the suspect loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Party of the Democratic Revolution, or PRD, was alone in
demanding disclosure until May. Then, in a flourish during a
televised debate among presidential candidates, Vicente Fox trumped
the PRD by handing over an envelope that he said contained his
party's secret codes to the disc. Fox, from the center-right
National Action Party, or PAN won the July 2 vote.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out those codes were not the right ones. Fauzi
Hamdan, a federal deputy who is PAN's point man on the bail-out,
admitted that he gave Fox mistaken codes.
</P>
<P>
   Hamdan has made it clear that he does not agree with the
opposition releasing bail-out information in violation of their
accord with Mackey. In the end he did turn over PAN's codes, but
the PRI did not offer its numbers.
</P>
<P>
   More than $200 million in loans went to three construction
companies that grew into giants during the years when the Mexican
government proffered a steady flow of contracts. A loan to Ignacio
Santos de Hoyo the PRI senator from the state of Nuevo Leon, was
for $6.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the bail-out agency said that criminal or civil
legal action has been brought in about 300 of the cases on the
Mackey list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
