<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILL GRUDZIELANEK HEADED FOR DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This is not the way the Los Angeles Dodgers wanted
to begin the second half. Not with second baseman Mark Grudzielanek
heading for the disabled list and not with catcher Todd Hundley
unable to throw a ball until the end of the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But such is life for the Dodgers, who received bad news on both
players before Thursday's interleague game with the Angels at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek was diagnosed with a viral infection. Team doctors
have told Grudzielanek to keep away from the ballpark, mainly
because they don't know what's causing it. He's expected to be put
on the 15-day disabled list today, retroactive to last Friday, and
utility player Mike Metcalfe is expected to be recalled from
Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek underwent tests at Centinela Hospital Medical
Center. Team officials said doctors are hopeful that test results
available today will give the club a better indication of what's
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all had the virus, the flu, but Grud's got real bad
headaches and some joint discomfort,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``The recommendation from the doctor is that we do
(put him on the DL).''
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Grudzielanek's loss mean a shift in the infield,
which could lead to shortstop Alex Cora playing second base again
but also throws another monkey wrench into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek has batted solely in the second spot in the order,
and is hitting .303 with five homers and 31 RBI. He's also turned
into a solid second baseman, making 10 errors but showing constant
improvement in his move from shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays showed Hundley has a nondisplaced fracture on the tip of
his right thumb, but he's hopeful of returning for the upcoming
Pittsburgh series. The fracture is under the thumbnail and he's
available to play when the pain allows him to. Hundley said he
could pinch-hit left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shooting for Sunday or Monday,'' Hundley said.
``Basically, it's getting all the swelling down so I can throw a
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Trade talk: The Dodgers are trying to acquire a starting
pitcher before the trading deadline, but they keep hearing the same
thing when it comes to a deal. Other teams want rookie right-hander
Eric Gagne, but the Dodgers front office remains unwilling to
include him in a deal.
</P>
<P>
   They've talked with Baltimore about right-hander Scott Erickson,
sources said. The Dodgers also talked to Philadelphia about Andy
Ashby before he was traded to Atlanta. The Dodgers also talked to
the Phillies about Curt Schilling, but Gagne would have to be
included in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Dodgers are prepared to do everything to keep
Gagne, and instead would like to package right-hander Darren
Dreifort, catching prospect Angel Pena, whom the organization has
soured on, and a minor- league pitcher for any deal they make,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Right-hander Gregg Olson pitched a perfect
inning in a rehab appearance for Triple-A Albuquerque against Iowa,
his sixth minor-league appearance. But the Dodgers are waiting for
Chad Kreuter's suspension to end after Saturday's game, and for
Hundley and Grudzielanek to get healthy before adding Olson to the
mix. . . . With lefty Carlos Perez slated to begin his five-game
suspension Sunday, right-hander Mike Judd is expected to be
recalled from Albuquerque.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1695 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-TRACK-LADN-(SLANG     07-14 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIALS BY FIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.2000 San Bernardino Sunn  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ No less than Michael Johnson calls this ``the
greatest track meet in the world,'' and who are we to argue with
the fastest long-sprint runner in world history?
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials begin today and conclude
July 23 at Sacramento State's Hornet Stadium and, indeed, a strong
case can be made that this is the premier meet on the planet _ both
for the caliber of its competition and the under-the-gun pressure
on its athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is one of the few countries that determines
its Olympic track team on the basis of one meet. A pulled hamstring
or a bad breakfast can ruin four years of training and render
``best in the world'' rankings irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly about pressure, because if you don't get in the
top three, you don't make the Olympic team,'' Johnson said
Thursday. ``It's the most pressure an athlete is in.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States remains the globe's preeminent track power. In
several events, particularly the sprints and hurdles, it is more
difficult to make the U.S. team than to medal at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Only the three top qualifiers go to the 2000 Summer Games in
Sydney. Johnson suggests the U.S. someday should keep open ``wild
cards'' for defending Olympic champions or world-record holders
``who get food- poisoning or whatever'' at the trials, but for now
it remains a do-or-die proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Multitalented Marion Jones comes to Sacramento with the most
ambitious schedule, hoping to qualify for three individual events
(long jump, 100 and 200) in her drive to become the first track and
field athlete to win five gold medals (including the two relays) in
one Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Jones runs in the 100-meter quarterfinals today and attempts to
qualify for Sunday's long jump finals. It shouldn't be difficult,
but getting past the U.S. trials is never a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts are, no matter what you did last week or last year,
no matter what you say, you've still got to go out and run the
races and make the team,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan O'Brien remains Exhibit A in the U.S. Trials nightmare
museum. He was the decathlon world-record holder and overwhelming
favorite to win gold in Barcelona in 1992, but he failed to clear a
height in the pole vault at the '92 trials and didn't get his
Olympic gold until 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people, if you get through our Olympic trials, you'll
do fine at the Olympics, because our trials are so tough,'' said
Antonio Pettigrew, a veteran 400-meter man.
</P>
<P>
   Pettigrew ought to know. He is a three-time world champion and
member of the fastest 400-meter relay team in world history, but he
has never gotten past the U.S. trials in three previous tries.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinters expect good times because of deep competition, a fast
track at Sacramento State and hot weather. Highs in the mid-90s are
forecast for the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to see a different level of women's
sprinting,'' said Inger Miller, world champion in the 200 and
Jones' top rival. ``I think this track can give us some good times.
And it's hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's top story lines: Jones attempting to move along in the
long jump and 100; Johnson going in the first round of the men's
400 (he holds the world record in the 200 and 400), and world's
fastest human Maurice Greene (9.79 in the 100) trying to show
recent weak performances were aberrations. (Greene on Thursday said
he can ``go under 10'' seconds ``anytime I want.'')
</P>
<P>
   Also today, Jackie Joyner-Kersee is expected to end her two-year
retirement and compete in the women's long jump.
</P>
<P>
   Other stories of potential interest as the trials continue
through Monday, and resume Thursday for a July 23 finish:
</P>
<P>
   __ Greene vs. Johnson in the 200 next weekend. They don't much
like each other, and Johnson seems intent on not allowing Greene to
usurp him in the event.
</P>
<P>
   __ Jones vs. Miller in the women's 100 and 200.
</P>
<P>
   __ Legally blind Marla Runyon attempting to qualify in the
women's 1,500 despite a recent injury.
</P>
<P>
   __ Johnny Gray, the 40-year-old half-miler, trying to make the
U.S. Olympic team for the fifth time.
</P>
<P>
   __ Decathlete O'Brien attempting to bounce back from knee
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gail Devers aiming for a Sydney berth in the women's 100
hurdles, giving her a chance to add to her two 100-meter sprint
golds.
</P>
<P>
   Capacity crowds of 21,000-plus are expected for the eight days
of competition at Sacramento State, which recently put down a $1.1
million track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track appears to be very fast,'' Johnson said. ``Most
important, there's a lot of seating for fans, and there doesn't
seem to be a bad seat in the stadium. Fans here seem to be very
enthusiastic and that's great for the competitors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
