<SLUG> BC-CITY-NATIONAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY NATIONAL CORP. BEATS PROJECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ City National Corp., parent of the
largest bank headquartered in Southern California, reported
Thursday a 28 percent increase in earnings for the second quarter,
due to high-interest income.
</P>
<P>
   The Beverly Hills-based owner of City National Bank exceeded
Wall Street estimates by a penny a share. The stock closed Thursday
at $35.56, down $3.06, or 7.9 percent, on heavy volume of 927,400
shares on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   City National earned $33.4 million, or 68 cents per share, for
the quarter ended June 30, compared with net income of $26.1
million, or 55 cents a share, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Total net interest and noninterest income, the banking
industry's equivalent to revenues, both showed increases due to the
result of strong loan and deposit growth and a higher prime rate.
</P>
<P>
   Net income rose 37 percent to $107.8 million, compared with
$78.7 million for the second quarter of 1999. Noninterest income
continued its strong growth, increasing 24 percent to $26.8 million
from $21.6 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a penny ahead of expectations because the company
benefited from rising interest rates,'' said Campbell Channey, an
analyst with Sutro &AMP; Co. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in interest income City National Bank has been
enjoying after a series of interest rate hikes by the Federal
Reserve should taper off by the end of the year, said Channey.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate loans rose 72 percent from $0.8 billion to $1.3
billion, while average deposits gained 38 percent during the second
quarter to $6.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   These results reflect, in part, the integration of The Pacific
Bank, acquired in February and American Pacific State Bank,
acquired in August 1999, into City National Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``City National's strong financial performance this quarter
demonstrates that our clients want to continue to invest in their
businesses, so we see our deposits and loans continuing to
expand,'' said Russell Goldsmith, chairman and chief executive
officer of City National Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith added, ``As people become even more aware of City
National Bank, especially in the (San Fernando) Valley, we will
continue to grow our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, City National said no shares were repurchased in the
second quarter. Since the current stock buyback program began on
July 29, the company has repurchased 731,100 shares for a cost of
$23.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The shares purchased under the buyback program have been
reissued for acquisitions, upon the exercise of stock options, and
for other general corporate purposes.
</P>
<P>
   City National bank has assets of $8.7 billion and 41 offices in
Southern California including Encino, Studio City, Sherman Oaks,
Sun Valley, Woodland Hills, North Hollywood, Van Nuys, Granada
Hills, Burbank, Northridge and Valencia.
</P>
</TEXT>
