<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RANGERS-D'BACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STUN DIAMONDBACKS IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Rangers' longest road trip of the season, one they
hope will push them back into the divisional race, is off to a
wildly thrilling and highly successful start.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, lifeless at the plate for most of the night,
overcame Arizona's 4-1 lead with five runs in the ninth and
defeated the Diamondbacks, 6-4, last night at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Alicea delivered the game-winning hit _ a bases-loaded,
two-out, two-run single off Diamondbacks closer Byung-Hyun Kim. The
victory left the Rangers within 71/2 games of the Seattle Mariners
in the American League West. The Mariners lost to San Diego, 2-1,
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer started the Rangers' winning rally by drawing a
walk. Kim struck out Ivan Rodriguez but then hit Rafael Palmeiro on
the leg with a 1-2 pitch. Frank Catalanotto followed with a
broken-bat single to right, scoring Greer and moving Palmeiro to
third.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Gabe Kapler, but manager Johnny Oates pinch hit
David Segui, the Rangers' designated hitter who didn't start
because of National League rules.
</P>
<P>
   Segui smacked a line drive to center and center fielder Steve
Finley tried for a sliding catch. He missed. The ball sailed under
his glove and all the way to the wall, scoring both runners and
sending Segui to third with a two-run triple to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   After Mike Lamb was walked intentionally, Kim struck out Royce
Clayton but walked Dave Martinez to load the bases. Alicea then
lined a single to right to put the Rangers ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks blew a chance to break the game open in the
eighth after they loaded the bases with one out against Rangers
reliever Francisco Cordero. Instead Mike Venafro and Jeff Zimmerman
bailed out Cordero with a huge assist from Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   With the infield in, Venafro got Tony Womack to hit a slow
grounder to Lamb, who charged hard and fielded the ball cleanly but
bounced his throw to the plate. Rodriguez saved him from disaster
by making a backhanded short-hop stop to get the force out.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell, who almost devastated the Rangers with two home runs
off Rangers starter Rick Helling, then hit a spinning grounder that
shortstop Royce Clayton couldn't get, an infield single that scored
one run. But Zimmerman ended the inning by getting Luis Gonzalez to
fly out to center, keeping the Rangers within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's terrible ninth followed eight brilliant innings by starter
Brian Anderson, who held the Rangers to one run on four hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers managed only three singles in the first seven
innings against Anderson, and none of the three base runners were
able to advance past first base. The Rangers also failed to get the
leadoff batter on base in any of those seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch hitter Scott Sheldon broke up Anderson's bid for a shutout
with a two-out home run in the eighth inning. Up to that point, the
night seemed to belong to the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks got a run off Helling in the third when Bell,
with two outs, jumped on a 1-0 pitch and smashed it high and deep
into the Diamondbacks' bullpen down the left-field line for a home
run. The Diamondbacks then mounted another rally in the fourth but
Helling pitched brilliantly to escape without allowing a run.
</P>
<P>
   He started the inning with a walk to Matt Williams, then gave up
a double to Steve Finley to put runners on second and third. That
brought up Erubiel Durazo, who fouled off three sliders, then took
a fastball for strike three.
</P>
<P>
   Helling walked Damian Miller on a 3-2 fastball just outside to
load the bases but caught Travis Lee looking on a 2-2 fastball for
another big strikeout. Anderson then ended the inning with a hard
grounder right at second base Luis Alicea.
</P>
<P>
   But Helling's reprieve didn't last long. Tony Womack lined a
single to left to start the fifth and then Bell lined a 1-1
fastball over the right-field fence for a two-run homer, giving the
Diamondbacks a 3-0 lead.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
