<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1701 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CAR-BESTDRIVERS-HNS &LR;      07-14 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BESTDRIVERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
WITH 2 CHARTS/LISTS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leader of the pack
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher makes strong case as best driver going
</P>
<P>
   By TERRY BLOUNT
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Judging who is the best marathon runner or who is the best
100-meter sprinter is a simple procedure _ just line them up and
see who gets to the finish first.
</P>
<P>
   Judging who is the best race-car driver is more difficult. Just
lining then up and having them battle for a certain distance will
determine the winner for that day, but it might not tell you who is
the best driver.
</P>
<P>
   The car the winner drove might be a lot faster than the car the
best driver was steering. The best driver on a starting grid cannot
win in the worst car, and the worst driver in the field can't win
in the best car.
</P>
<P>
   So trying to figure out who is the best driver in the world is
not an exact science. It really is just an educated guess based on
a number of factors _ record, car and team, and status among other
drivers who have raced against that particular driver.
</P>
<P>
   Using all those factors, the Chronicle has compiled a list of
the 10 best drivers in the world today, along with the 10 best who
no longer compete regularly.
</P>
<P>
   We also have lists for the 10 best _ active and inactive _ in
each type of racing, along with a top-10 list of future stars.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead. Beg to differ. Opinions vary and people disagree, even
within the racing community. There are no guaranteed answers, just
like there are no guaranteed winners each week.
</P>
<P>
   But the selections have been made and the consensus as to the
best racer in the world is Michael Schumacher in Formula One. The
31-year-old German has dominated the circuit this season and is
well on his way to giving Ferrari its first driver's championship
since Jody Scheckter in 1979. It will be the third F1 title for
Schumacher, who carried the Benetton team to its only championships
in 1994 and '95.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Schumacher won a championship, his talent was
apparent. In 1993, Tom Walkinshaw was the technical director for
the Benetton team. That year he became the first man to proclaim
Schumacher as the world's best driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who needs Ayrton Senna or Alain Prost?'' Walkinshaw said. ``We
have Michael Schumacher. He is the best driver I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would claim Benetton had the best mechanical package when
Schumacher won his first two titles. Some might argue Ferrari
finally has caught up with the McLaren team and Ferrari does have
the best car this season, but Schumacher has been so dominant that
it is clear he would be winning for either team.
</P>
<P>
   What makes him so good? His fellow F1 drivers list these key
components _ amazing reflexes and instincts at high speeds,
absolutely no fear on the track and total ruthlessness during a
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has an uncanny ability to get instant speed in any
situation,'' Ferrari director Jean Todt said. ``And he has that
competitive aggression that makes him the driver he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter characteristic won't win Schumacher any popularity
contests, but it has won him a lot of races.
</P>
<P>
   It also has cost him a few _ such as the 1997 F1 finale in Spain
where Schumacher and Jacques Villeneuve were battling for the
championship. Schumacher turned into Villeneuve on a curve and was
disqualified, ending Schumacher's chance at the title.
</P>
<P>
   That all-out attitude is a trait found in most of the top
drivers, including the No. 2 selection _ CART competitor Juan
Montoya. The Colombian is only 24, but his talent and ability are
undeniable after watching what he has accomplished the last two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He won the CART FedEx championship as a rookie last season. Some
people said anyone could have won driving for the dominant Chip
Ganassi Target team, but Montoya did more with the equipment he had
than anyone ever had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan may be the best driver we've ever seen in America,''
Ganassi said. ``I don't know how to rate him with drivers from
previous decades, but I know he's pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya won a rookie-record seven races and earned seven poles.
Perhaps the most amazing statistic was that he led in 15 of the 20
races on the circuit. Any doubts about his skills were erased in
May when he won the Indianapolis 500 in an IRL car, clearly
outclassing the field in his first race at the Brickyard.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely Montoya will move to Formula One next season and
drive for Frank Williams, which will be an opportunity to see how
he stacks up against Schumacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan has a natural ability that you can't teach,'' said CART
team owner Mo Nunn, who was Montoya's consultant and team engineer
last season. ``He has amazing raw talent and he is a very confident
young man.''
</P>
<P>
   The first American on the top 10 list is a man approaching half
a century on the planet _ Dale Earnhardt. At age 49, Earnhardt is
driving as aggressively as he did a decade ago when he was starting
a string of four Winston Cup championships in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite driving a Monte Carlo that has a clear aerodynamic
disadvantage to the Taurus and Grand Prix cars on superspeedways,
Earnhardt is No. 2 in the points standings and shooting for a
record eighth championship.
</P>
<P>
   The next two drivers on the list also are Winston Cup
competitors Jeff Gordon and Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 28, is going through a transition this season after
losing crew chief Ray Evernham, but Gordon still has won twice this
year on tracks that couldn't be more different _ the superspeedway
at Talladega and the road course at Sears Point.
</P>
<P>
   The win at Sonoma, Calif., was the sixth consecutive road-course
victory for Gordon, prompting more speculation about he would do in
Formula One.
</P>
<P>
   We might never know because Gordon is making so much money in
NASCAR that he has no incentive to prove himself in another series
the way top drivers did in the past. But his 51 victories and three
titles show he can win anywhere under any conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is the only driver without a championship on the top-10
list, but many times winning a title involves being in the right
place at the right time. That hasn't happened for Martin, but he
might be the most respected driver in NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the only flaw in Martin's game, something many people
see as an asset and an example of his character, is that he is just
too nice on the track. He doesn't have the killer instinct that
some of his opponents possess. He would rather finish second than
win in an unsportsmanlike fashion.
</P>
<P>
   A good gauge of Martin's driving skill is his four championships
in the IROC series, which pits 12 top drivers in identically
prepared Pontiac Firebirds. Martin won three consecutive IROC
titles from 1996-98.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth on the list is CART driver Michael Andretti, who won the
championship in 1991 and has been the series runner-up five times.
His father Mario has said several times that he believes Michael is
a better driver than he was, but the competition is tougher now.
Michael's 39 career victories are tops among active CART drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Formula One driver Mika Hakkinen, who won the last two F1
titles, makes the list, as does defending Winston Cup champion Dale
Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett has gotten better every year in a 20-year career where
he has paid his dues and learned how to run up front.
</P>
<P>
   The last two choices on the list might be the most controversial
_ Funny Car champion John Force and World of Outlaws racer Steve
Kinser.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful Force could drive a car that he had to turn left
or right at high speeds, but he is the master at stepping on the
throttle and going straight at more than 300 mph.
</P>
<P>
   He won nine NHRA championships in the 1990s and passed Bob
Glidden this season for the most career victories _ now 86 and
counting. Force is still going strong at 51 and will go down in the
books as the greatest drag racer of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Like Force in drag racing, Kinser is the undisputed king of
sprint-car racing on dirt. At age 44, he has won 15 World of
Outlaws championships and has more than 440 ``A'' feature victories
in his career. His 56 victories in 1987 stand as the national
short-track record.
</P>
<P>
   So there it is, the top 10 of 2000 _ subject to change, of
course, in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
