<SLUG> BC-drivers-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
from houston chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   with leader of the pack/schumacher
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Terry Blount
</P>
<P>
   TOP 10 DRIVERS ALL CIRCUITS
</P>
<P>
   ACTIVE &QC; 
1. Michael Schumacher _ At 31, he is well on his way to becoming
the all-time winningest driver in Formula One history. &QL; 
2. Juan Montoya _ Has proved he could be a champion in CART, a
winner in the Indy 500 and soon will win in Formula One. &QL; 
3. Dale Earnhardt _ Still going strong at 49 and has a realistic
shot at the historic eighth Winston Cup championship. &QL; 
4. Jeff Gordon _ Making a tough transition this season with a new
crew chief, but his driving skills rank near the top. &QL; 
5. Mark Martin _ Most Winston Cup drivers will tell you he has as
much skill as anyone in NASCAR. &QL; 
6. Michael Andretti _ Maybe not as aggressive as he was five years
ago, but a smart driver who knows how to stay in contention. &QL; 
7. Mika Hakkinen _ Having an off year in F1, but he has two
championships and probably will add some before he's through. &QL; 
8. Dale Jarrett _ Has spent 20 years learning his sport and is
becoming a crafty driver who knows how to get to the front. &QL; 
9. John Force _ Yes, he drives only in a straight line, but his
accomplishments in drag racing are unprecedented and deserve
recognition. &QL; 
10. Steve Kinser _ The king of the dirt. The World of Outlaws
driver can do things in a sprint car that no one else ever has
done.
</P>
<P>
   INACTIVE &QC; 
1. A.J. Foyt _ The first man to win the Indy 500 four times. His 67
Indy-car victories are 15 more than Mario Andretti, who is No. 2 on
the Indy-car list. But Foyt could race any type of car anywhere and
win. &QL; 
2. Richard Petty _ The King won 200 times in a stock car, including
seven championships. &QL; 
3. David Pearson _ With 105 victories, Pearson had a higher winning
percentage than Petty. His three championships came in a four-year
span, ending in 1969. &QL; 
4. Mario Andretti _ An amazingly versatile driver who proved he
could win in any type of race car. &QL; 
5. Aryton Senna _ Won 41 times over 11 seasons before being killed
in a crash at Imola, Italy, in 1994. &QL; 
6. Alain Prost _ His 51 victories are the most in F1 history. He
also won four championships. &QL; 
7. Al Unser Sr. _ Won 39 Indy-car races, including four Indy 500s. &QL; 
8. Bobby Allison _ His 84 victories tie him with Darrell Waltrip
for third on NASCAR's all-time list. &QL; 
9. Rick Mears _ Won Indy four times and had 29 victories overall. &QL; 
10. Cale Yarborough _ One behind Allison and Waltrip with 83
victories in a stock car.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE &QC; 
1. Dale Earnhardt Jr. _ Genetics at work. Junior has two victories
as a Winston Cup rookie and more are on the way. &QL; 
2. Casey Atwood _ Only 19, but the Busch driver is headed for
Winston Cup next year on the new Dodge team of Ray Evernham. &QL; 
3. Matt Kenseth _ Not as aggressive on the track as his best friend
_ Earnhardt Jr. _ but his patience and ability to consistently run
near the front might earn him Rookie of the Year honors in Winston
Cup. &QL; 
4. Kevin Harvick _ Busch series rookie who ranks No. 4 in the
points and will be driving in Winston Cup soon for Richard
Childress. &QL; 
5. Kurt Busch _ At age 20, he became the youngest driver ever to
win a NASCAR truck race two weeks ago at Milwaukee. He followed it
up by winning last weekend at New Hampshire. Team owner Jack Roush
has bigger plans for Busch soon. &QL; 
6. Greg Biffle _ Another Roush trainee who might win his first
truck title this year, but it could be his last year in that
series. &QL; 
7. Sarah Fisher _ 19-year-old IRL rookie has the talent to compete
with the top male drivers. &QL; 
8. Airton Dare _ Impressive IRL rookie from Brazil. &QL; 
9. Cristiano da Matta _ Second-year CART driver is gaining
confidence and ranks eighth in the standings. &QL; 
10. Oriol Servia _ CART rookie won the Indy Lights championship
last year and this season has shown promise of a bright future. &QL; 
$$$
</P>
