<P>
   TOP DRIVERS BY CIRCUIT
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup
</P>
<P>
   ACTIVE
</P>
<P>
   1. Dale Earnhardt _ Has proved this season he still can run with
the championship contenders. &QL; 
2. Jeff Gordon _ 51 victories and three championships at age 28. &QL; 
3. Mark Martin _ Might end his career as the best driver never to
win a championship. &QL; 
4. Dale Jarrett _ Within striking distance of a second consecutive
championship. &QL; 
5. Bobby Labonte _ Trying to win his first Winston Cup
championship. &QL; 
6. Jeff Burton _ Has all the tools to be a Winston Cup champion. &QL; 
7. Tony Stewart _ Former IRL champion who is following up a
remarkable rookie year with another solid season in Winston Cup. &QL; 
8. Rusty Wallace _ If only he could still race as well as he
qualifies. &QL; 
9. Jeremy Mayfield _ Has the ability to win, even when his team
doesn't cheat. &QL; 
10. Ward Burton _ Proving this season he can run with the big dogs.
</P>
<P>
   INACTIVE
</P>
<P>
   1. Richard Petty _ Won 27 races in 1967. &QL; 
2. David Pearson _ Won 11 of 18 races he entered in 1973. &QL; 
3. Cale Yarborough _ Three-time Winston Cup champion. &QL; 
4. Bobby Allison _ Won the Daytona 500 in 1988 when he was 50. &QL; 
5. Junior Johnson _ Won 50 of the 313 races in his career and was
instrumental in bringing NASCAR into prominence. &QL; 
6. Darrell Waltrip _ Technically, still active but just barely. He
won 12 races in 1981 en route to his first of three championships. &QL; 
7. Lee Petty _ A NASCAR pioneer who won three championships and 55
races. &QL; 
8. Ned Jarrett _ Dale has a ways to go before catching his dad, who
won 50 races and two championships. &QL; 
9. Herb Thomas _ Won 48 races and two of the first five NASCAR
championships. &QL; 
10. Davey Allison _ Was on his way to becoming one of the best
drivers in the sport when he died in a helicopter crash in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   CART/IRL bar
</P>
<P>
   ACTIVE
</P>
<P>
   1. Juan Montoya _ Won CART title as a rookie last year and will
move to Formula One next year. &QL; 
2. Michael Andretti _ A five-time CART runner-up and 1992 champion
whose 39 victories are the most in the series. &QL; 
3. Dario Franchitti _ Outstanding road racer who is getting offers
from F1. &QL; 
4. Kenny Brack _ A.J. Foyt protege and 1999 Indy 500 champ who is
headed for CART Rookie of the Year honors this season after winning
the IRL title in 1998. &QL; 
5. Eddie Cheever _ Has been an accomplished driver in F1, CART and
the IRL. He won the 1998 Indy 500. &QL; 
6. Gil de Ferran _ Has proved his worth this season with two
victories for a Penske team that had gone winless for three years. &QL; 
7. Roberto Moreno _ From supersub to superstar, Moreno has a chance
to shock everyone and win the CART FedEx title this year. &QL; 
8. Scott Sharp _ Has won in Trans-Am and Indy cars but appears to
be reaching his prime at age 32. &QL; 
9. Buddy Lazier _ One of the best drivers in traffic, the 1996 Indy
500 winner is seeking his first IRL title. &QL; 
10. Adrian Fernandez _ Maybe the most underrated driver in
open-wheel racing, Fernandez makes the most of the equipment he
has.
</P>
<P>
   INACTIVE
</P>
<P>
   1. A.J. Foyt _ No driver was more competitive and more driven to
succeed. &QL; 
2. Mario Andretti _ Won the Indy 500 in 1969, but bad luck kept him
out of Victory Lane several times at the Brickyard. &QL; 
3. Al Unser Sr. _ A 30-year career that included 321 starts and
5,812 laps led. &QL; 
4. Rick Mears _ His 14-year career included 40 poles. &QL; 
5. Johnny Rutherford _ Lone Star J.R. won 27 races, including three
Indy 500s. &QL; 
6. Bobby Unser _ A three-time Indy 500 winner who won 35 races in
his career. &QL; 
7. Bobby Rahal _ A three-time CART champion who won 24 races in his
career. &QL; 
8. Emerson Fittipaldi _ An accomplished driver in F1 and Indy cars,
he won 22 Indy-car events, including two Indy 500s. &QL; 
9. Arie Luyendyk _ Two-time Indy 500 winner and a consistent top-10
finisher in his career. &QL; 
10. Alex Zanardi _ Inactive for this year only but won two
championships in 15 races in three CART seasons.
</P>
<P>
   NHRA
</P>
<P>
   ACTIVE
</P>
<P>
   1. John Force _ Passed Bob Glidden this season for the most
career victories. Force has 86 and counting in his Castrol Mustang
Funny Car. &QL; 
2. Gary Scelzi _ In line for third Top Fuel title in four years. &QL; 
3. Warren Johnson _ Will pass Glidden soon for the most Pro Stock
victories in history. &QL; 
4. Joe Amato _ Only driver to win five Top Fuel championships. &QL; 
5. Kenny Bernstein _ A four-time Funny Car champ in the 1980s who
also won a Top Fuel title in 1996. &QL; 
6. Tony Schumacher _ Won his first Top Fuel title last year and is
in contention for a second this year. &QL; 
7. Tony Pedregon _ As Force's teammate, he doesn't get the
recognition he deserves as a talented drag racer. &QL; 
8. Jeg Coughlin Jr. _ Well on his way to winning his first Pro
Stock title this year. &QL; 
9. Jerry Toliver _ Has proved this season what he can do on a
well-funded team by leading Force in the points race. &QL; 
10. Larry Dixon _ In 1995, he was the first rookie in 23 years to
win a Top Fuel event but now is capable of winning a championship.
</P>
<P>
   INACTIVE
</P>
<P>
   1. Bob Glidden _ His 85 victories was the record for five years
until Force passed him this season. &QL; 
2. Don Prudhomme _ The Snake won 49 times, 34 in a Funny Car and 14
in Top Fuel. He won four NHRA Funny Car titles. &QL; 
3. Dan Garlits _ Big Daddy had 35 Top Fuel victories and three NHRA
championships. &QL; 
4. Shirley Muldowney _ The woman who hated to be called by her
nickname ``Cha Cha,'' was a pioneer for female drag racers, winning
three Top Fuel championships. &QL; 
5. Lee Shepherd _ The Arlington product won 26 Pro Stock events and
four championships. &QL; 
6. Gary Beck _ Won 19 Top Fuel events and two championships. &QL; 
7. Darrell Gwynn _ Was one of the best Top Fuel drivers in the
sport before a crash in 1990 left him paralyzed. &QL; 
8. Dick LaHaie _ A 15-time Top Fuel winner and 1987 champion who
has gone on to become one of the top tuners in the business. &QL; 
9. Eddie Hill _ Texas A&AMP;M product who finished in the top 10 in Top
Fuel nine times, won a championship in 1994, made the first
four-second pass and raced competitively until he was 63. &QL; 
10. Pat Austin _ His 66 wins in Alcohol Funny Car and 71 national
event victories deserve recognition.
</P>
<P>
   FORMULA ONE
</P>
<P>
   ACTIVE
</P>
<P>
   1. Michael Schumacher _ On the verge of giving Ferrari its first
driver's championship since 1979. &QL; 
2. Mika Hakkinen _ Coming off back-to-back championships for
McLaren. &QL; 
3. David Coulthard _ Outrunning teammate Hakkinen this season. &QL; 
4. Jacques Villeneuve _ His team is not a contender, but
Villeneuve's driving skills are among the best in the sport. &QL; 
5. Eddie Irvine _ Missed equaling Hakkinen by only two points last
year in a Ferrari before switching to Jaguar this season. &QL; 
6. Heinz-Harald Frentzen _ Will finish in the top 10 in points for
the fifth time in the last six seasons. &QL; 
7. Rubens Barrichello _ Got his big break this year by joining
Ferarri and has made the most of it, ranking fourth in the points. &QL; 
8. Ralf Schumacher _ Michael's younger brother is having his best
season, ranking sixth in the F1 standings. &QL; 
9. Giancarlo Fisichella _ After three consecutive top 10 seasons,
the 27-year-old Italian has made a move up, ranking fifth this
season and proving he has the ability to drive with the best. &QL; 
10. Jenson Button _ Talented rookie who has made a name for himself
this season.
</P>
<P>
   INACTIVE
</P>
<P>
   1. Ayrton Senna _ Won one of every four starts in his career and
had an amazing 65 poles in 161 starts. &QL; 
2. Alain Prost _ Along with his record 51 victories, the Frenchman
also finished second 35 times, third 20 times and had 33 poles. &QL; 
3. Juan Manuel Fangio _ The all-time leader with five F1
championships, but some say winning in the 1950s was much easier. &QL; 
4. Jackie Stewart _ Won 27 races and three championships in only 99
starts, and also finished second 11 times. &QL; 
5. Niki Lauda _ Won three championships and 25 races over his
12-year career. &QL; 
6. Jimmy Clark _ Won 25 races and two championships in 72 F1
starts. Also won the 1965 Indy 500 and finished second at Indy in
1966. &QL; 
7. Nelson Piquet _ Won 23 races and three championships. He also
finished second 20 times and third in 17 events. &QL; 
8. Nigel Mansell _ Won 31 events and the 1992 championship. He also
won the CART championship in 1993. &QL; 
9. Jack Brabham _ Won three championships over a seven-year span
(1959-66) but had only 14 victories. &QL; 
10. Damon Hill _ Won 22 races and the 1996 championship before
retiring after last season. &QL;
</P>
