<SLUG> BC-CHEMICAL-SAFETY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNAL FIGHTING HAMPERING NEW SAFETY AGENCY  &HT;     BY BERNADETTE TANSEY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Internal fighting and a muddled management
structure are hindering the work of a new federal safety agency
investigating the fatal 1999 Tosco refinery fire near Martinez and
other industrial accidents, federal investigators said this week.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. General Accounting Office review tracks closely with
the findings of a Chronicle investigation in April that found
management conflicts at the board have hampered probes into
workplace accidents across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The federal investigators said an independent oversight agency
should be appointed to monitor the U.S. Chemical Safety and Hazard
Investigation Board, where a majority of members are now pressing
the White House to expel the fledgling agency's former chairman
from his board seat.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the small agency 21/2 years ago was greeted with
great optimism by environmentalists, workers and industry groups as
a long-needed '`honest broker'' that would investigate major plant
accidents impartially, with an eye to preventing similar
catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tosco Corp. investigation and other probes suffered when
a feud erupted between founding chairman Paul Hill and the board's
three other members, who said Hill was monopolizing the board's
decision-making power.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress, dismayed by the delays in completing
investigations, sought a General Accounting Office review of the
chemical safety board's problems, and some threatened to wipe out
the agency's budget.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting office said the three-member board majority,
which took control of the agency after Hill relinquished the
chairmanship in January, has made progress toward getting the work
back on track. But it said the board should have revised its
procedures after former employees and others alleged that
investigations had been compromised by management interference or
bias.
</P>
<P>
   The federal report advised the board to develop methods to avoid
conflicts of interest in the assignment of investigators, permit
the airing and publication of dissenting opinions in accident
reports, and subject its reports to an outside peer review.
</P>
<P>
   Although the board majority has filled two of six vacant
positions for investigators, one of the four current staff
investigators is about to leave. Still, the board expects to
release two accident reports by the end of September, though the
Tosco review may not be finished until October.
</P>
<P>
   The federal investigators said the board should contract with
the inspector general's office of another federal agency, which
could initiate its own investigations of agency problems and
establish a hotline for employees to report their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continuing disagreements between three of the board members
and the former chairman raise questions concerning the board's
future productivity and efficiency,'' the report concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The three board members maintain the agency is still recovering
from mismanagement under Hill, whom they accused of malfeasance,
inefficiency and neglect of duty in their petition to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokeswoman Victoria Valentine said negotiations are
under way for Hill's departure from the agency. Hill could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The board majority supports the recommendation for an outside
inspector general and will consider the accounting office's other
proposals to ensure the objectivity of investigations, said board
member Irv Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We note that although we have not had written policies and
procedures on the items that the GAO identified, all three of the
CSB's (completed) investigation reports have been highly praised
for their objectivity and thoroughness,'' Rosenthal said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 0125EDT &QL; 
