<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1706 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     07-14 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ANYBODY GET HIT BY WEINERMOBILE?  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Who's zoomin' past whom?
</P>
<P>
   Let's have a contest: Who can get run over or close-called on
the streets of San Francisco by the most unusual or ironic vehicle?
</P>
<P>
   In the past week I've heard from pedestrians claiming to have
had near-death experiences with a school bus, a local TV news van
and (this one reported by Karen Green) a blood-bank truck.
</P>
<P>
   The blood truck incident gets my vote, unless someone checks in
with a story involving a hearse. Or maybe the Oscar Mayer
Weinermobile.
</P>
<P>
   GO AHEAD and build that schlocky San Francisco museum/theme
park, says Aaron Peskin. Just don't build it at Pier 45.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make it part of the airport expansion,'' says Peskin,
candidate for supervisor in the 3rd District.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists could fly into SFO, visit ``San Francisco,'' and fly
home without having to freeze on the Golden Gate Bridge, wait for
hours for the cable cars or get run over by a bloodmobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we still get their airport tax,'' Peskin notes.
</P>
<P>
   SAD NEWS for friends and admirers of Bill Kimpton, the
hotel-restaurant pioneer. He has checked into a Southwest
cancer-treatment center, friends say.
</P>
<P>
   Kimpton's life is an amazing story. He was born and raised in
Kansas City and because of dyslexia didn't read until high school.
His first job was as a flunky at the Clift Hotel in San Francisco,
where he literally started at the ground floor and worked his way
down, demoted almost immediately from the front desk to the wine
cellar.
</P>
<P>
   He became a business dynamo. After many successes, such as
taking KFC public, Kimpton started a hotel-restaurant empire based
on the concept of turning a marginal hotel into a luxury boutique
hotel, and installing a killer restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimpton Group had 28 hotels on the West Coast, 14 in San
Francisco, including the Sir Francis Drake and the Triton, before
selling recently to Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   DINING DIN is good, many trendy restaurant owners feel, because
it's a sign that the place is full of energy. Hip young diners
don't want to feel like they're eating in a library, unless of
course they're eating in a library.
</P>
<P>
   But when the restaurant is so noisy you have to converse via
charades, that can be a problem, especially if you're lousy at
charades.
</P>
<P>
   Dine, a hot new spot on Mission in SoMa, is the latest local
restaurant to down-sound. Dine hired The Finish Line, an acoustical
treatment firm that has also shushed XYZ, Farallon, Jardiniere and
MC2 (squared).
</P>
<P>
   The tab was a quiet $14,000, and now the din at Dine is fine and
benign. You still can't hear yourself think, but who's thinking?
</P>
<P>
   BIRD LOVERS, skip this item.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is the big annual Pigeon Roast in Union Square, where the
Bay Area Rotisserie Friends will roast up some rock dove, aka:
pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   It is absolutely legal, they say, to hunt, kill and eat pigeons.
But if you plan to partake, you must bring an invitation (go to
pigeons &LR; starchefs.com).
</P>
<P>
   The BARF people say the birds are yummy, especially the
cinnamon-honey grilled pigeon.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S GOOD to peep in on Los Angeles every now and then to make
sure things are still going smoothly down there.
</P>
<P>
   And they seem to be:
</P>
<P>
   -- Los Angeles is experiencing a shortage of lifeguards. You can
imagine how many men it must take to replace David Hasselhoff.
</P>
<P>
   -- A man convicted of stealing 55 Oscar statues was sentenced to
six months in jail. Like he's the first guy ever to steal an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   -- Inmates convicted of minor crimes in L.A. are allowed to
serve out their sentences at relatively pleasant suburban jails, if
they can get in. The suburban jails rent out cells, like hotel
rooms. Real Graybar Hotels. Bread and water and dessert cart.
</P>
<P>
   Because the jail rentals produce revenue, many of the little
jails now advertise. Do your time at the Hoosegow Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon: The slammer spa. And the community-service 18-hole
litter pick-up detail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
