r a BC-COUNCIL-SETTLEMENT-LA     07-14 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNCIL-SETTLEMENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. CITY COUNCIL BLOCKS PRATT DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Taking advantage of the absence of four
colleagues, four other Los Angeles City Council members blocked a
$4.5 million settlement with Elmer ``Geronimo'' Pratt because they
wanted to pay him as much as $10 million for his 27 years of false
imprisonment, the Daily News learned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Council members Rita Walters, Jackie Goldberg, Nate Holden and
Mark Ridley-Thomas successfully prevented the council from signing
off on the $4.5 million deal during a closed-session meeting
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, brokered by the City Attorney's Office and Pratt
attorney Johnny Cochran Jr., needed an OK from eight of the city's
15 council members. But with only 11 council members present, the
four dissenters had enough votes to block the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The council is scheduled to take up the matter at a closed
session during Friday's City Council meeting. At least one council
member who didn't attend Wednesday's meeting _ mayoral candidate
Joel Wachs of Studio City _ said he will vote for the deal Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way I'm going to agree to give more money,'' Wachs
said through a spokesman. ``We have so many basic city services
that I'd rather use this money for.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven members voting to support the settlement were Laura
Chick, Mike Feuer, Mike Hernandez, Cindy Miscikowski, Nick Pacheco,
Alex Padilla and Rudy Svorinich Jr. Absent were members Hal
Bernson, John Ferraro and Ruth Galanter, in addition to Wachs.
</P>
<P>
   Bernson and Ferraro had excused absences, according to records
in the City Clerk's Office. The same records show that Galanter and
Wachs attended earlier portions of the council meeting and do not
indicate a reason for their absence from the closed session.
</P>
<P>
   City officials who support the settlement say it will set an
important precedent for the lawsuits expected from the Rampart
Division corruption case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had a good deal that was approved by Pratt and
his attorney and the courts,'' said one official, who asked not to
be identified. ``And, we could say to the people in the Rampart
case, `Look, here we gave a guy $4.5 million for 27 years in prison
and you want more than that for 22 months?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if the council (pays Pratt more), they'll just open up
the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   But Walters on Thursday dismissed that argument, and said Pratt
was entitled to a larger payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The precedent on Rampart has already been set by the behavior
of the police,'' said Walters, who would not discuss specific
figures she thought Pratt ought to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should just say here's the key to the bank,
take what you will. But, they took so long to negotiate and the sum
came out so small compared to 27 years of a man's life. We stole 27
years of a man's life _ the prime years of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ought to be a penalty. We pay out some pretty handsome
sums for things that don't reach this level of significance,''
Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other notable settlements by the city in recent years,
Rodney King received $3.8 million for the infamous beating he
suffered at the hands of Los Angeles police officers in Lake View
Terrace in 1991. And Clarence Chance and Benjamin Powell were
awarded $9 million collectively in 1993 for being wrongly convicted
and spending 17 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt was freed from state prison in 1997 after a long legal
battle in which a judge said crucial information had been withheld
in the murder case against the former Black Panther leader.
</P>
<P>
   He had been convicted for the 1968 slaying of a woman on a Santa
Monica tennis court, even though he contended he was more than 400
miles away at the time. The chief witness against him had a
criminal record that officials failed to disclose.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed settlement, the city would be held liable for
about $3 million and the FBI would pay the remaining amount for its
role in helping convict Pratt.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to contact Pratt and Cochran on Thursday were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   An official who witnessed the debate said Ridley-Thomas
questioned how the settlement came about.
</P>
<P>
   ``He argued that the city paid $3 million for land-use cases and
wanted to know how it was decided to pay $4.5 million to Pratt,''
the official said. ``None of the people from the City Attorney's
Office could answer that, so he voted against the settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden and Goldberg also questioned the size of the settlement
and whether more should be paid out, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   USC law professor Erwin Chemerinsky said it would be unusual for
the council to override a settlement negotiated between the two
sides, and the rarity of it could be a sign of concern on the part
of council members.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do settle for more, it would reflect their belief of
the tremendous injustice done to (Pratt),'' Chemerinsky said,
adding he does not believe it would affect any cases coming out of
the Rampart Division.
</P>
<P>
   Since allegations surfaced last year that anti-gang officers
framed, beat and shot innocent people in the Rampart area, more
than 20 officers have been fired, suspended, relieved of duty or
have quit. Officials are reviewing hundreds of cases that the
officers were involved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the city attorney would like to use this as a
benchmark, but each case is settled on its own,'' Chemerinsky said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 0136EDT &QL; 
