A1712 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-AIDS-FUNDING-SFCHRON &LR;      07-14 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FUNDING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AIDS FIGHT GETS BOOST FROM HOUSE  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the world's attention focused on the
incredible devastation AIDS is wreaking on sub-Saharan Africa, a
bipartisan House majority Thursday approved a $42 million increase
in funding to combat the disease's march across the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, many of them stunned by news of the epidemic's toll
coming out of an international AIDS conference this week in South
Africa, amended a broader $13.3 billion foreign spending bill to
provide the added funding. It still requires Senate approval and
faces an uphill fight for President Clinton's signature.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators said the House's 261-to-156 endorsement of the
amendment, co-sponsored by Rep. Barbara Lee, D-Calif., showed
Congress is committed to helping Africa battle a disease that has
infected 24.5 million people and made orphans of millions of
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we saw today was a recognition of the tragedy and
the devastation of the HIV-AIDS pandemic and the willingness of
Congress to begin to at least do the right thing on this issue,''
said Lee, who recently returned from the 13th International AIDS
Conference in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would increase funding for international HIV/AIDS
treatment and prevention from $202 million to $244 million
annually, in line with a White House request. It would be offset by
reductions in military aid to poor U.S. allies.
</P>
<P>
   The issue sparked an emotional debate on the House floor that
saw conservative Republicans joining moderates and Democrats in
calling for decisive action and was all the more remarkable because
many influential lawmakers support the military spending that will
be sacrificed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a bipartisan vote, ... and it was very significant,''
Lee said. ``This was not a Republican or a Democratic issue. This
is a moral issue that requires a moral response. It's about human
beings and it's about life and death, and if you look at the vote
you will see that.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., who visited Africa
in December, told colleagues the AIDS epidemic there is ``the moral
imperative of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   International recognition of the scope of the human and economic
damage caused by HIV and AIDS in Africa has risen sharply during
the past year as statistics paint an increasingly shocking picture.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 34.3 million people in the world who have AIDS, 24.5
million are in sub-Saharan Africa, according to estimates from
UNAIDS, an umbrella group for the United Nations, the World Bank
and the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
   More than 12 million children in sub-Saharan Africa have lost
either their mother or both parents to the epidemic, and life
expectancy is expected to decline sharply. In Zimbabwe, for
example, life expectancy is estimated to drop from the current 61
years to 33 by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, there were 5.4 million new HIV infections worldwide,
with 4 million of them in Africa. Last year 2.8 million people died
of AIDS, 85 percent of them in Africa. The U.S. Census Bureau
projects that Africa will have 71 million fewer people in 2010 as a
result of AIDS, in part because of the death of women of
child-bearing age.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank and others contend that AIDS could stymie
economic growth in Africa for decades, much as the bubonic plague
left Europe struggling centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came back, I talked to members of Congress,'' Lee said.
``I believe people really realized that a vote on this amendment
sent the signal that we do intend to be on the right side of
history, both in a moral sense and in the sense that we are part of
the world community and have a responsibility to put this pandemic
in check.''
</P>
<P>
   The House measure must still be reconciled with a different
version of the foreign operations bill passed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   And although the House measure fulfills President Clinton's
request to increase AIDS spending, it still faces an uphill battle.
That's because the foreign spending bill it is part of falls short
of what the White House has proposed, and White House officials
pledged to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said UNAIDS estimates put the cost of fighting the worldwide
epidemic at $3 billion annually. Lee is sponsoring a bill called
the World Bank AIDS Marshall Plan to increase international AIDS
funding further.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
