<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-MILITARY (El Sando, Colombia) _ A three-day rampage of
torture, rape and killing by a paramilitary group took place in
this tiny village last February, with no effort by military and
police units just a few miles away to stop the slaughter. The
incident _ at the very moment when President Clinton was pushing an
aid package to step up antidrug efforts in Colombia _ strikes at
the heart of the debate over the growing American backing of the
Colombian military. For years the U.S. government and human rights
groups have had reservations about the Colombian military
leadership, its human rights record and its collaboration with
paramilitary units. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Thurmont, Md.) _ During President Clinton's
seven years in office, no world leader has journeyed more often to
the White House than Yasser Arafat. The Palestinian leader has met
Clinton there a dozen times, and his image in Washington has become
almost commonplace. In turn, Clinton made the risky gesture of
being the first American president to visit Arafat on his home turf
in Gaza. In the coming days, as the Camp David summit rolls towards
a climax, the White House will see whether that investment can be
made to pay in a peace settlement. Clinton believes that
personalities and relationships can fundamentally alter history,
and according to his aides, he is banking on his affinity with
Arafat, and with the Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel, to make a
critical difference at Camp David. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-WHITE-VAN-MAN (Leatherhead, England) _ In his hands he
has a wheel; in his ears, rings; on his arms, tattoos; and in his
heart, loathing for anyone he sees through his windshield. He is
known as White Van Man, and he is identified in motorist surveys as
the scourge of the stressed-out British road. That, at least, is
the popular caricature of the men who pilot the estimated 2.5
million commercial vans every day around Britain, a country with
the most congested roads in Europe and probably higher road rage
than any country on the Continent. A foreign journal by Warren
Hoge.
</P>
