Insurance Department and the attorney general's office are
examining the finances of the Health Insurance Plan of Greater New
York, looking into what former executives describe as a clubby
atmosphere that often seemed at odds with HIP's special role in the
city's health care system. Most of the questions focus on Anthony
L. Watson, a former Olympic long jumper whose taste for fancy cars
and corporate apartments has infuriated the regulators as some of
HIP's financial reserves have dwindled far below the amount
required by state law. By Christopher Drew and Melody Petersen.
</P>
