<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-METS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX SAVED IN NINTH BY DAUBACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a night of many happy returns for the Red Sox. Pedro
Martinez, healthy and haughty, was back for the first time in 18
days, and so, too, was the bottom-of-the-ninth comeback, not seen
in these parts since . . . well, it was so long ago that no one in
the Sox clubhouse could remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe not this year,'' said first baseman Brian Daubach, whose
two-out, two-strike, two-run double in the ninth off Mets closer
Armando Benitez lifted the Sox to a 4-3 win, made possible when
Mets shortstop Melvin Mora kicked away a certain double-play
grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with Daubach's memory, nor his timing. This was
the first time this season the Sox have come from behind in their
last at-bat, on a night in which Martinez left after seven innings
deadlocked, 2-2, having surrendered a tying home run to Jay Payton,
Nomar Garciaparra's Georgia Tech buddy who also doubled home the
Mets' first run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was huge,'' said Scott Hatteberg, who pinch hit in the
ninth and drew a walk that touched off the winning rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I can remember one homestand where we seemed to win
every game in dramatic fashion. Not only with big hits, but lots of
things. This is the first time this year I can remember this
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have closed it out and should have closed it out.
Maybe that's happened for us before, but we haven't capitalized.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had taken a 3-2 lead in the eighth when Carl Everett,
the Sox All-Star and former Met, misplayed Mike Piazza's base hit
into an error that allowed Edgardo Alfonzo to score from first. But
after Hatteberg drew a one-out walk in the ninth batting for Ed
Sprague, the best-fielding team in the National League made a rare
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Mora, playing shortstop in the absence of Rey Ordonez, the
all-world acrobat out for the season with a fractured elbow, muffed
Jose Offerman's ground ball just to the left of second base. Pinch
runner Manny Alexander, instead of being erased at second, wound up
at third when he advanced on Jeff Frye's liner to center, setting
up Daubach's duel with Benitez, who blew just his fourth save in 23
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we needed something like that,'' Frye said of the error
by the normally sure-handed Mora, who said he took his eye off the
ball as it glanced off his glove. ``We haven't had too many breaks
like that, but it wouldn't have meant anything if Dauber doesn't
come through there. I can't think of a much better way to start the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially with both the Yankees and Blue Jays losing their
interleague exercises against the Marlins and Phillies,
respectively, allowing the Sox to climb within 1 1/2 games of the
lead in the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of things happened,'' said Daubach, who lashed his
winning hit to the base of the right-field fence one pitch after
umpire Angel Hernandez decided not to ring him up on a 1-and-2
fastball from Benitez that had the sellout crowd of 33,894 audibly
relieved the game wasn't over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The error. The borderline call, my ball not bouncing out or a
fan not touching it. Maybe things are finally going our way,'' said
Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   Mets manager Bobby Valentine, who acknowledged he doesn't have
the best view of the strike zone from the third base dugout,
thought Daubach was done on the previous pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the crowd reacted, it looked like strike three,'' said
Valentine, whose starter, Bobby Jones, had shut out the Sox until
Everett singled and Morgan Burkhart homered in the sixth to give
the Sox a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he didn't call it . . . too bad. If that was strike three,
then we're off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach candidly admitted what would have happened had he
elected to take a hack at the 1-and-2 pitch, which was belt high
and hugging the outside corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' he said. ``I would have struck out.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he delivered some 10 o'clock drama that has been absent
most nights on the Fens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation, we start the second half, a game like this, one
strike away from the game going the other way, a great at-bat from
Daubach, that's really got to pick you up,'' said manager Jimy
Williams, who had Martinez on a pitch count and lifted his ace
after Martinez threw 104 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darn right,'' Williams said. ``I know it picks me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Daubach said, he was reminded of his defining moment from
last August, the bases-clearing double he hit off the Monster
against Oakland after narrowly missing a grand slam foul down the
right-field line the pitch before.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure,'' he said. ``The team got really hot after that.
Maybe this will get us going again.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled. ``But I also went in a slump after that hit. I don't
want that to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has now gone five weeks without a win. The last time he
pitched in four games without a win was nearly two years ago, in
September 1998. But after whiffing 10, walking one, and holding the
Mets to five hits, he pronounced himself satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take it any way we can,'' he said. ``I don't care how we
win it. As long as the `W' is in our clubhouse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
