<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODANG-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN IN 10TH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Anaheim Angels began their second half loose
and knowing they have a realistic shot at winning their division.
The Los Angeles Dodgers opened their post-All-Star schedule with a
team meeting in which manager Davey Johnson planned on stressing
the importance of picking up their recent lackluster play.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said one of the points of interest of the Dodgers'
closed- door meeting was to be a need to manufacture runs and not
rely solely on the long ball.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on the team's third attempt to push across the winning
run, Jim Leyritz delivered a two-out single to score Adrian Beltre
in the 10th inning and give the Dodgers a 4-3 win at Dodger Stadium
on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But before Leyritz's hit, Angels manager Mike Scioscia employed
some unique strategy. Beltre tripled off the right-field wall with
one out in the 10th. Scioscia then moved left fielder Darin Erstad
into the infield, and Kevin Elster grounded out to him. But Leyritz
singled off reliever Al Levine for the win.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had chances to end the game before it reached extra
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers catcher Paul LoDuca, recalled from the minors earlier in
the day, began the bottom of the ninth with a double to right
against reliever Mark Petkovsek, only to be stranded. Gary
Sheffield hit a one-hop linerto second, but LoDuca couldn't
advance. Shawn Green was intentionally walked and Eric Karros hit
into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   A potentially wonderful outing by Dodgers left-hander Carlos
Perez changed quickly to just solid in the seventh. Garret Anderson
led off the seventh with a single to right field, and Troy Glaus
hit Perez's next pitch over the left-field fence to give the Angels
a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing the Dodgers offense did was make Angels
starter Ken Hill work through six innings. Hill struck out eight,
and allowed just four hits, but he threw 123 pitches and was
replaced by Shigetoshi Hasegawa, who promptly got into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca's one-out hard grounder got through Mo Vaughn at first to
begin a seventh-inning rally. Sheffield, who hit his 28th homer
earlier, walked but the slumping Green came through. After striking
out in his first three at-bats, Green singled to center to score
LoDuca and tie it at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   One of the points Johnson wanted to make in the meeting was to
accomplish the little things within a game, and the Dodgers had a
chance to do that with Sheffield on third with one out. Karros
walked to load the bases, but needing a deep fly ball to give the
Dodgers the lead, Todd Hollandsworth struck out and Beltre grounded
out to third to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Before batting practice, Johnson spoke to Dodger all-stars Kevin
Brown and Gary Sheffield. He addressed the team as a whole after
batting practice in a closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to talk about where we're at, that we have to tighten the
belts and go get 'em,'' Johnson said. ``This is it. We have to make
it happen.Don't look over their shoulders for some help because
each of us has to pick up the slack.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of it has to do with executing in the finer points of game,
namely manufacturing runs and sacrificing at-bats for the
betterment of the team.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers were a season-high eight games over .500
(25-17) six weeks into the season, they were getting strong
starting pitching, but they also were doing the little things to
score runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the little things,'' Sheffield said. ``We got those
things earlyin the year. But the thing is, when things are going
good, it's easy todo those things, but in a 1-0 ballgame, to do
those things, that's when you know that your effort is like (a
championship team), to win a ballgame. Those are the things we have
to concentrate on doing in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone continues to work the
phones in hopes of making a trade that could bolster the starting
rotation, but many of the players believe the current roster of
players is talented enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the pieces are here,'' Karros said. ``Ideally, you would
like to get an all-star at every position and have five all-stars
on the (mound), but the reality is for us, our best pieces are
here. You're not going to go out and make changes and get that much
better. That's in reality. If you're playing rotisserie baseball,
you can go out and get whomever you want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
