<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-COACHES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACHING CAROUSEL SPINS WILDLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Check the calendar. Yep, it's July. Asphalt's melting,
thermometers are bubbling and the Rangers are looking for enough
arms to have a group hug.
</P>
<P>
   So what in the name of Naismith is going on with college
basketball? Summer isn't the time for coaching changes. But in the
last six weeks, the carousel has been spinning as fast as it
usually does in March. Illinois, Miami (Fla.), Tulsa, North
Carolina, Notre Dame and Tulane have all had to dust off their Help
Wanted signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very unusual off-season. And very difficult,'' Kansas
athletic director Bob Frederick said. And Frederick was lucky. For
about a week, he was ``tied up in knots'' as he waited to see if
Jayhawks coach Roy Williams would accept North Carolina's offer.
When Williams decided to stay in Lawrence, he made his boss very
happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dreading calling up athletic directors to ask permission
to talk to their coaches,'' said Frederick, who in June 1988 had to
do just that as he searched for a replacement for Larry Brown.
``Even though I knew they would understand, it's still something
that's very tough to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletic directors at this time of year are catching their
breath as one school year ends and another looms. Going over
end-of-the-year budgets is about the most demanding part of the
job. Usually when ADs have to hire a coach, they're ready for it
because they anticipate a coach's firing or departure. This
off-season has provided a series of surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA contributed to this wacky off-season. The Atlanta Hawks
hired Lon Kruger away from Illinois, and the Washington Wizards
hired Leonard Hamilton away from Miami (Fla.). North Carolina's
Bill Guthridge stirred the pot even more when he stepped down June
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little taken aback when the North Carolina situation
came up,'' Illinois athletic director Ron Guenther said. ``That's
late for a resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Guenther hired Tulsa's Bill Self to replace Kruger, while Tulsa
turned to Appalachian State's Buzz Peterson. North Carolina created
an opening at Notre Dame when it hired Matt Doherty as Guthridge's
replacement. The dominoes have been falling like new series on UPN.
</P>
<P>
   When basketball coaches start their on-campus player camps in
June, their mind-set starts to move toward the upcoming season. And
by July, when the summer recruiting//evaluation period starts,
coaches believe that the next season has started.
</P>
<P>
   ``By that time, the thoughts about change are over in their
minds,'' Frederick said. ``The time for hiring basketball coaches
is March 15 to June 1 with almost all of the hires done by April
15.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 10 times more difficult to try to hire a coach at this
time of year. It's a nightmare. I really feel badly for all these
people who are going through it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And Frederick is plenty happy he's not one of them.
\Nsubheds:Briefly The Sanford Independence Bowl, which has deals
with the Big 12 and Southeastern conferences, has not had a good
month. First, the Louisiana Legislature decided to stop providing
funds for the Sugar and Independence bowls. That cost the
Independence, based in Shreveport, about $250,000. And, the Dec. 31
game will be short on ticket sales because construction at
Independence Stadium has eliminated about 6,000 seats. Seating
capacity will now be around 44,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to one computer service, college football's 2000
season will end with Armageddon. The Cosgrove Computer Rankings
(no, it's not part of the Bowl Championship Series formula) are
projecting eight teams will be undefeated in the regular season _
TCU, Texas, Kansas State, Florida State, Wisconsin, Alabama,
Georgia and Utah. However, that list of undefeateds would be pared
to six because of the league championship games in the Big 12 and
Southeastern conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia and Wisconsin are close to finalizing a deal to play in
the 2001 Black Coaches Association Classic. The game would be
played in Madison, Wis. Next year will be the final season for the
preseason ``classic'' games.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0037 </DOCNO>
