<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S SUFFER POWER SHORTAGE WITHOUT THEIR BIG BATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ After Edgar Martinez singled with two out in the
10th inning Thursday, Mariners manager Lou Piniella looked to his
bench for a pinch-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that Martinez, the slowest Mariner, remained
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, also, that the Mariners didn't score and
wound up losing in the bottom of the inning. A two-out, bad-hop
grounder off shortstop Carlos Guillen gave the San Diego Padres a
2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's bench options, already limited, took a beating when
Rickey Henderson was hit on the left elbow in the third inning.
When you add the loss of the team's leadoff hitter to other
problems _ the right knee injury that has shortstop Alex Rodriguez
out and the absence of Martinez in the designated hitter-less
hinterlands of the National League _ it's clear that Seattle's
margin for error early in this second half of the season is
perilously small.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will make at least one move Friday, activating
catcher Dan Wilson from the disabled list, but they don't know if
Henderson will be able to play. They do know that Rodriguez won't
play for at least a few more days and that the NL isn't going to
implement the DH overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are going to have to suck it up. The first-place
team in the AL West will get no sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one cares about this,'' second baseman Mark McLemore said
in a matter-of-fact way. ``No one will take it easy on us because
of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get a mulligan in baseball. You've got to go out and
play. So we have more people out. So what? As long as you have nine
guys, you have to go out and play and not feel sorry for
yourselves. And we've got nine guys who can get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't Thursday. The Mariners got a craftsman-like start
from Freddy Garcia and reasonable relief work from the bullpen.
Garcia allowed just one run, which normally is enough to win. But
the Mariners' offense, without the punch that either Rodriguez or
Martinez would have provided, scored just one unearned run in 10
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle put multiple men on base just once, when Guillen singled
and Henderson was hit in the third inning. McLemore's subsequent
grounder was kicked by shortstop Kevin Nicholson, scoring Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   End of offense, such as it was.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres weren't much better, but San Diego scratched out a
run in the seventh inning, ultimately forcing extra innings. Then
Mariners reliever Brett Tomko made two crucial mistakes in the
10th. With two out, he walked Phil Nevin. Then he walked Bret
Boone, pushing Nevin to second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dealt myself that hand,'' Tomko said. ``It was my fault they
had the winning run at second base. All I could do then was get a
ground ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He did. But the grounder, off Wiki Gonzalez's bat, found a bit
of uneven turf. The ball jumped to about three times its expected
height, and Guillen wasn't able to keep it in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad hop I tried to keep in front of me,'' Guillen
said. ``As soon as it was by me, I knew we'd lost. I feel bad about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad feelings won't dissipate anytime soon if the offense
can't carry its share of the weight. Right now, it can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to play short again tomorrow,'' said assistant
general manager Lee Pelekoudas, suggesting no immediate help from
the minor league system can be expected. Given their current lack
of offensive weapons, the Mariners can expect more of this
low-scoring output in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   So the Mariners are going to struggle to be competitive,
something they didn't have to do in the first half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   True, Seattle could put Martinez in the lineup at first base any
time. But to do that, first baseman John Olerud either has to go to
the outfield _ where he hasn't played since 1990 _ or the bench.
Given the defensive differential, it's not a move Piniella is eager
to make.
</P>
<P>
   The manager seems stumped for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I may try to do is put in all my switch-hitters,''
Piniella said. ``That way I won't have to make any moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella was kidding _ sort of. He only has three switch-hitters
_ Guillen, McLemore and Stan Javier.
</P>
<P>
   What Piniella does have is a three-game lead in the AL West. He
also has the best pitching in the West.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have to maximize the latter to protect the former.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
