<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JUDO-STAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH 2004 AS GOAL, FORT WORTH GIRL DEVOTES LIFE TO JUDO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAWN REISS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Brigette Kubes turned down a potential track
scholarship at TCU to compete in judo. Her father tried to convince
her to stick with track, even offering to buy her a new car.
</P>
<P>
   She still wouldn't quit judo.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Kubes quit track. Gone were the workouts with TCU's
track coach. Forgotten was the strong performance in the 800 meters
during her sophomore year at Southwest High School.
</P>
<P>
   Her life became judo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I couldn't go to the Olympics in track, and there was a
much better chance of me going in judo,'' Kubes said. ``It was so
hard to do both and stay competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the 17-year-old Southwest graduate is the
third-ranked female judo athlete in the United States. She holds a
first-degree black belt and is ranked No. 1 at 70 kilos (154
pounds) in the 17- to 20-year-old junior division. She has even
trained in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of life because it's all I do,'' Kubes said. ``My
friends get tired because I can never go out, but I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her passion for judo has inspired an Olympic dream. Kubes
believes she can secure one of seven spots on the U.S. women's team
for the 2004 Summer Olympics. Kubes, who is 5-foot-10, trains six
days a week, running, lifting and practicing judo. She hasn't
consumed a soft drink in six years. In high school, she gave up
attending football games and dating to concentrate on judo and
maintaining an A average in school.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Kubes is scheduled to compete at the U.S. Judo
Association Nationals in Charlotte, N.C. After that, she and her
13-year-old sister, Nikki, head to the 15-country Maruchan Miami
Youth International competition, scheduled for July 22-23. Nikki, a
brown belt, has won junior nationals in her age category five
consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nikki has a lot of talent, and she can do things right away,
but it took Brigette longer to understand,'' said Koichiro
Toninura, a Japanese judo warrior and Dallas businessman who trains
with Kubes. ``She's gotten a lot better. It's very deceiving, just
by looking at her.''
</P>
<P>
   Brigette Kubes was not a model athlete when she started judo.
Kubes' father remembers that she could not do a push-up or climb a
rope, but gradually she grew stronger physically and mentally.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Kubes hoped to win the high school nationals for judo.
She placed second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so upset after the fight,'' Kubes said. ``The girl who
beat me is not near my level, but the next time we fight I'll get
her.''
</P>
<P>
   A month later, at the Judo Senior Nationals in Houston, she
fought back after losing in the first round. She won a bronze
medal, beating Kristi Springer, an alternate for the 1996 U.S.
Olympic Team and the top-ranked U.S. female judo athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so hard to fight your way back,'' Kubes said. ``I had
never won against her before. ... It boosted my confidence for all
of my tournaments coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   By placing third at the Senior Nationals, Kubes qualified for
the Gothenburg Youth International tournament in Sweden. Kubes
again placed third, almost assuring that she can compete in the
Junior Worlds this October in Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
   She also plans to compete in Hungary and Poland next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people respect you, they fight scared, and then it's
harder to fight a person,'' said Tommy Dyer, Kubes' coach. ``Now
she has earned that respect from her opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barring a major injury, I feel confident that she will be in
the Olympics. She's just that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubes' hard work attracted the attention of San Jose State,
which offered her a judo scholarship. The U.S. Olympic Training
Center also offered her residency in Colorado Springs, Colo. She
turned down both to continue training with Dyer at the nonprofit
Fort Worth Judo Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten me where I'm now, so why change that?'' Kubes
said. ``I also like home, and I want to help my sister come
along.''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters became interested in judo after their father, a
Tarrant County constable, wanted his daughters to learn
self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in law enforcement, I see the victims, I see the
statistics,'' Joe Kubes said. ``I knew 99 percent of fights are won
on the ground. I wanted them to be able to defend themselves in the
back seat of a car. My girls are not going to be overpowered.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the girls can throw boys in the ring, but there's a new
concern. Dyer and the Kubes family hope Nikki will be bigger than
Brigette so they won't have to fight each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics? They are both going to make it,'' their father
said. ``The only problem is getting them in two different weight
classes.''
</P>
<P>
   When Brigette returns from Europe, she plans to attend Tarrant
County College then transfer to TCU. And she's driving a lime-green
Volkswagen New Beetle, purchased by her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girl has been so good,'' Joe Kubes said. ``She has given
up so much to do this. My wife and I just told her, `This is a
reward, for good things happen to good people.' '' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
