<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY THE ATHLETES CAN RESCUE SHAMED OLYMPIC MOVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Woke up Thursday, opened my sports section and read a
nice story about Olympic discus thrower Aretha Hill _ a story that
made it impossible not to pose an urgent question:
</P>
<P>
   Can the athletes save the Olympics?
</P>
<P>
   It might be up to them.
</P>
<P>
   In this most cynical, big-business, everyone-can-be-bought world
of sports, this is no easy task. Athletes like Hill provide the
greatest hope for the strained, shamed Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, in the current climate, there's room for skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a former Australian discus thrower published a book
called ``Positive,'' claiming that swimmers and track athletes were
using illegal human growth hormones undetectable in conventional
testing methods.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest installment in a thorough indictment of the
state of chemically enhanced performance.
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, the hunt will be on for drug cheats, or so we are
told by International Olympic Committee officials sensing that
records and gold medals will be meaningless under a shroud of
suspicion about steroids and blood doping.
</P>
<P>
   The ring of skepticism will tighten closer around the athletes
upon whom this entire Olympic movement is built.
</P>
<P>
   There is truth to the notion that skepticism and cynicism are in
vogue, but no one wants the Olympics to die.
</P>
<P>
   An athlete like Hill makes you hold out faint hope that somehow
the IOC and all other layers of federations and governing bodies
will get their houses in order.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, a former University of Washington star, is training for
the U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials, which begin Friday in
Sacramento, Calif., and run through July 23.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked No. 4 in the country in the discus, Hill was an Olympian
in 1996. She was quoted regarding her desire to compete again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hardest thing to describe,'' Hill told the
Post-Intelligencer's Ted Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you walk in, 100,000 fans stand at their feet and
start yelling and screaming `USA! USA!' For the first time in my
life, I realized what it's like to be an American and represent
your country.''
</P>
<P>
   We all know the Olympics are rife with jingoism. The hype is
inordinate. But Hill, who has mortgaged her future to pay for
training, is banking that some part of the Olympic ``ideal'' still
holds true.
</P>
<P>
   She felt it. She wants to feel it again. She isn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who grew up glued to the television, witnessing the
wingspan of Mark Spitz or the joy of Olga Korbut, wants to feel it
again, too. So does Jackie Joyner-Kersee.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest athletes of all time, Joyner-Kersee
announced Thursday that she will compete in the U.S. Track Trials.
The queen of the heptathlon and long jump will seek to qualify for
the U.S. Olympic team in the latter event.
</P>
<P>
   Does the Olympic movement deserve Joyner-Kersee, whose comeback
from retirement will make for compelling action in the sand pits
this weekend in Sacramento?
</P>
<P>
   The scandal and corruption is widespread enough to warrant the
proposition that the Olympic movement is tarnished beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Hill earnestly working toward her dream, even with
Joyner-Kersee back on track, can we forget about Juan Antonio
Samaranch?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, after the IOC president's theater-of-the-absurd
appearance before a U.S. Senate panel last year investigating
high-stakes Olympic shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   Can we forget about the IOC members who received trips, health
care, gifts and jobs for relatives, leading to the ouster of 10 of
the shadiest freeloaders?
</P>
<P>
   Can we forget that Olympic organizing officials in Salt Lake
City and Australia bribed IOC members with less shame than Beltway
lobbyists?
</P>
<P>
   Can we forget that all of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee's
top officials had to be replaced as federal prosecutors uncovered
the widespread scandal?
</P>
<P>
   Down Under, IOC leader Michael Payne is warning Australian
leaders against ``ambush advertising.'' The message: Nothing like
that can happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Why? In downtown Atlanta during the summer of '96, the Olympics
were turned into a riot of commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta prostituted itself for the almighty dollar, with a
barrage of billboards, ticky-tack kiosks and chintzy shops that
overwhelmed almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's only saving grace was the flashes of brilliance from
Michael Johnson, Fatuma Roba's marathon victory and the triumph of
the gender-equity Olympics, thanks to the U.S. women's soccer,
basketball and softball teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic season is upon us once again. This time, with the
Sydney Games taking place so many time zones away, under a cloud of
shame and skepticism, it is time to wonder:
</P>
<P>
   Can the Olympics be saved?
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 0228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
