<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JUDO-PRIMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDO PRIMER 
WITH JUDO STAR PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
 subheds:JUDO: A PRIMER 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judo, which means ``the gentle way,'' was founded in 1882 in
Japan by Dr. Jigoro Kano, president of the School of Education,
Tokyo. Kano wanted to become physically and mentally fit through
discipline training. Judo for men became an Olympic sport in 1964,
was dropped in 1968, then returned in 1972 and has remained in the
Games since. Judo for women became an Olympic sport in 1992.
 &LR; subheds:Scoring In judo, points are awarded as follows:
</P>
<P>
   Ippon (full point): Throwing an opponent on his or her back with
force; or maintaining a pin for 25 seconds; or having an opponent
quit; or earning two waza-ari
</P>
<P>
   Waza-ari (1/2 point): A throw is almost successful, but is
either not with enough force or the opponent lands only partially
on the back; or maintaining a pin for 20 seconds
</P>
<P>
   Yuko (almost waza-ari): A throw is partially successful but is
sloppy with some part of the butt touching; or maintaining a pin
for 15 seconds
</P>
<P>
   Koka (almost yuko): A throw with some force but not on the back;
or maintaining a pin for 10 seconds
</P>
<P>
   Matches last four minutes, and the objective is to score one
point. Yukos and kokas are considered only if times runs out
without either contestant scoring a point. Then the victory is
awarded based on the next-highest score. For example, a waza-ari
beats any combination of yukos and kokas. If contestants are tied
in waza-ari, the leader in yukos wins, regardless of kokas. If
waza-aris and yukos are tied, the koka leader wins. If all scores
are tied, the match is decided by ``going to flags,'' and the three
referees vote, signalling their votes with flags.  &LR; name:_ Dawn
Reiss Sources: Fort Worth Judo Club president Tommy Dyer and
www.judoinfo.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 0231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
