<HEADLINE>
WEST HAS HAD ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 ... ADDS DETAILS, QUOTES (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK and DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jerry West, the heart and soul of the Los Angeles
Lakers franchise and its driving force as a player, coach and
executive over the last four decades, has decided to retire,
effective today, numerous sources told the Long Beach
Press-Telegram and Los Angeles Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to what I understand, (today) is his last day, and
then he's going fishing,'' a source close to West said Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   That vacation, team sources indicated, will be permanent. It
comes just 25 days after the Lakers won the NBA championship, the
seventh in the franchise's Los Angeles era, all with West as a
member of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his Bel Air home Thursday evening, West refused to
comment other than to say, ``I might go into the Laker office for a
few hours Friday morning for the final time. On Saturday, I'm
flying to Alaska for five days with my family to do a little
fishing. That's all I want to say for now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have not called a news conference, however, and are
declining comment on the story, which began with a FoxSports.com
report early Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not resigned yet,'' cautioned one member of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   West's departure might come as somewhat of a surprise to some
observers since he has three years left on a Lakers contract that
pays him $4 million annually, but those close to West long have
expected it. West in recent days has been negotiating a severance
package with Lakers attorneys, an indication that he planned to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement might not come for weeks. The Lakers are
negotiating with free agents but cannot sign players until Aug. 1;
West's retirement, observers say, might scare off potential
signees.
</P>
<P>
   West has persistently waved off rumors that he would resign as
the head of the Lakers' basketball operations _ a post he's held
since 1982, first as general manager and more recently as executive
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The notoriously stressed-out West has flirted with retirement
for the last several years, adding a dose of uncertainty to any
reports that he plans to quit. But many who know the 62-year-old
Hall of Famer say West has made up his mind. Two NBA general
managers confirmed that West considers this decision final.
</P>
<P>
   Health concerns, as well as the usual stresses of the job,
apparently prompted the decision. Apparently, West has had an
irregular heartbeat that doctors told him was caused by nervous
tension.
</P>
<P>
   He did not attend most of the playoffs and missed the NBA
title-clinching Game 6 triumph over the Indiana Pacers _ he was
driving around in his car while it was being played and a friend
informed him on the cell phone of its outcome. West was set to have
a defibrillation procedure on his heart at St. Joseph's Hospital in
Burbank a few days afterward. However, his heartbeat returned to
normal and the procedure was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he's sick, mentally and physically, because of what
this business does,'' said one person close to West.
</P>
<P>
   Although those around West are accustomed to his intense persona
and his roller-coaster of emotions, the feeling is that he has
reached a breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems like he's gotten more and more emotional,'' the
same source said. ``It's gone further and further each time.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, team insiders believe West will not accept any
consultant-type role to stay with the Lakers but rather will make a
complete break from the franchise. Working part-time, observers
say, would be impossible for West.
</P>
<P>
   There have been subtle but growing indications that West can no
longer endure the strain of an up-and-down NBA season _ he kept an
increasingly low profile during the season and did not attend most
of the Lakers playoff games. Even after the Lakers won the title,
ending a 12-year drought, West said the success had not eased his
personal pain.
</P>
<P>
   A day after they clinched the championship, when asked if it was
a gratifying conclusion to the work he did constructing the team,
West said ``Not for me. . . . This time of year is very difficult,
more difficult than I ever thought.''
</P>
<P>
   He also sounded an ominous tone regarding his future with the
team. Asked if he was still driven, West said, ``I don't know that.
I don't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet West will certainly be remembered for the drive that spurred
the Lakers to seven championships since 1972. He helped win the
first one as a prolific shooting guard dubbed ``Mr. Clutch'' for
his timely scoring.
</P>
<P>
   West was a consultant when the Lakers won titles in 1980 and '82
and was general manager of the ``Showtime'' teams that won
championships in 1985, '87 and '88.
</P>
<P>
   And his imprint is all over the 2000 squad, which returned the
Lakers to preeminence after several rough transition years that
followed the retirement of Magic Johnson and the end of the
``Showtime'' era.
</P>
<P>
   West cleared the roster and salary-cap room to sign center
Shaquille O'Neal in the summer of 1996, and at the same time
acquired high school star Kobe Bryant. Four years later, O'Neal and
Bryant form the best tandem in the league, and their talents
carried the Lakers to the championship.
</P>
<P>
   West also engineered the trades that brought key role players
such as Glen Rice and Robert Horry to the team.
</P>
<P>
   But new constraints on NBA executives' ability to make such
deals are also playing a role in West's frustration. The NBA's
salary cap has become increasingly stringent and complex, and the
league is bracing for a new so-called luxury tax that will penalize
teams that greatly exceed the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Lakers owner Jerry Buss has given strict orders to
contain and even reduce salaries, making it extremely difficult to
continually upgrade the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Still, people close to West find it difficult to believe he will
walk away. Knowing his mood swings and his passion for the job,
they say it won't be surprising at all if he decides to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's just talk, like he does every year,'' one Lakers
source said. ``But the circumstances (of the Lakers winning the
championship) make it more believable.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Lakers assistant coach Bill Bertka, who has known West
since his playing days, saw the opposite situation: that West will
stay because they won the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised (if he retired). It would be hard for me
to assume that he would walk away at this stage of his career,
especially with the kind of job that he has done,'' Bertka said.
``But I don't know. I'm not inside Jerry's head. . . . Only he
knows what his reasoning is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
