<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 03:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1752 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-NEWDODANG-LADN-(S     07-14 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NEWDODANG-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ... WRITETHROUGH 
DODGERS WIN IN 10TH
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers and Anaheim Angels are
roughly in the same spot. Five games behind in their respective
divisions. But they are also worlds apart and it has a lot to do
with a $34 million difference in payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels kicked off the second half of the season with a
loosey-goosey approach to the three-game I-5 series. The Dodgers
decided to have a closed-door team meeting before the game to
stress the importance of playing with enthusiasm and focus for long
periods.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Dodgers, after wasting a couple of late
chances, badly needed Jim Leyritz's two-out RBI single in the 10th
inning that propelled them to a 4-3 win Thursday night at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It came after the Dodgers had the bases loaded and one out in
the seventh and failed to get the go-ahead run in from third, and
after they wasted a leadoff double by Paul LoDuca in the ninth when
Gary Sheffield grounded out, Shawn Green was intentionally walked
and Eric Karros grounded into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it now is there is still a lot of games, but
there ain't enough games and we're going to start running out of
time if we don't start going now,'' said Dodgers right-hander Mike
Fetters, one of three Dodgers relievers to pitch a perfect inning
of relief. ``It's very important we go right now. The intensity was
a lot better tonight than it was in a while around here. It was big
for us to start off like this.''
</P>
<P>
   And even in the 10th, the Dodgers won it the hard way after
failing in the easier manner. Adrian Beltre tripled with one out
off Al Levine (1-1), but Angels manager Mike Scioscia brought left
fielder Darin Erstad in to make it a five-man infield.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Elster proceeded to ground out to Erstad, stationed on the
shortstop side near second base. ``We've done that a little too
often for my liking because you use it in dire situations,''
Scioscia said. ``This is one of the games out of the whole marathon
we've been talking about. It's a tough loss, but we have been good
at turning the page.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz bailed out the Dodgers with a single to right-center
field for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of going up there, and you're supposed to
fail, you're not supposed to succeed, so you go up with that
mindset and it takes the pressure off,'' Leyritz said. ``That kind
of game, if we lose that game, it's a big disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the points manager Davey Johnson wanted to make in the
team meeting was that little things need to be accomplished. Before
batting practice, Johnson spoke to Dodger All-Stars Kevin Brown and
Gary Sheffield. He addressed the team as a whole after batting
practice in a closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to talk about where we're at, that we have to tighten the
belts and go get 'em,'' Johnson said. ``This is it. We have to make
it happen. Don't look over their shoulders for some help because
each of us has to pick up the slack.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of it has to do with executing in the finer points of game,
namely manufacturing runs and sacrificing at-bats for the
betterment of the team.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers were a season-high eight games over .500
(25-17) six weeks into the season, they were getting strong
starting pitching, but they also were doing the little things to
score runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the little things,'' Sheffield said. ``We got those
things early in the year. But the thing is, when things are going
good, it's easy to do those things, but in a 1-0 ballgame, to do
those things, that's when you know that your effort is like (a
championship team), to win a ballgame. Those are the things we have
to concentrate on doing in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone continues to work the
phones in hopes of making a trade that could bolster the starting
rotation, but many of the players believe the current roster is
talented enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the pieces are here,'' Karros said. ``Ideally, you would
like to get an All-Star at every position and have five All-Stars
on the (mound), but the reality is for us, our best pieces are
here. You're not going to go out and make changes and get that much
better. That's in reality. If you're playing rotisserie baseball,
you can go out and get whomever you want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
