<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-SURVIVOR-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVING `SURVIVOR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, July 13, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fierce tri-headed god
</P>
<P>
   From whence is thy origin?
</P>
<P>
   Ahhh, ``Made in Taiwan''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Immunity Idol Haiku,'' one of more than 30 such poems about
``Survivor'' on an Internet web site.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the summer of 2000, we know Rudy is the crusty alum of
the Navy SEALs and Richard is the wickedly manipulative, openly gay
teddy bear and Colleen is the lust-inducing cute one who's lighting
up the Internet message boards and Gervase is the YMCA coach who
can't run or swim.
</P>
<P>
   But by the summer of 2001 we'll have forgotten all that. We
won't even be able to remember the names of the mouthy truck driver
(Susan!) or the doctor with the nipple ring (Sean!) or the nice and
relatively normal woman with the ukulele who was kicked off the
island in Episode 1.
</P>
<P>
   Whoops, forgot her name already.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, most of the contestants on the irresistibly cheesy
``Survivor'' are happily lapping up their notoriety like overheated
puppies unleashed on a gigantic bowl of cool spring water. Whether
it's the loser of the week gamely bantering with Bryant Gumble,
Sean telling Dan Rather he'd be thrilled to find the National
Enquirer going through his garbage, Rudy winning a fishing contest
or Ramona yukking it up with Dave Letterman, they're all having the
time of their lives, having nabbed the ultimate modern-day goal of
instant fame.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two months, these Gilligan-wannabes have no doubt
attained better name-and-face recognition than the justices of the
U.S. Supreme Court. You think I'm kidding? Go to any shopping mall
in America, armed with glossy photos of Justice Anthony M. Kennedy
and Pagong tribe member Gretchen, and you'll see who elicits the
most reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Jenna's on the cover of Time; Richard's all over the news wires;
Dr. Sean actually has professional headshots he's autographing for
fans. It's all good, as the kids say.
</P>
<P>
   But what these fresh faces don't seem to comprehend is that they
haven't won the lifetime lottery of fame _ they've nabbed a
temporary pass that gets them past the velvet rope for a short
while, but will soon morph into a ticket to obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   The entire world _ including various members of the ``Survivor''
gang in interviews I've seen _ likes to quote the Andy Warholism
about everyone being famous for 15 minutes, but nobody seems to
pick up on the unspoken conclusion to that thought, i.e., if you're
famous for 15 minutes, that means you're destined to be obscure for
about 39,420,000 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If the nearly decade-long run of the ``The Real World'' has
taught us anything, it's that these putative reality shows rarely
serve as launching pads to greater fame and fortune. They're
pseudo-celebrity sausage machines, grinding out dignity-impaired,
single-named exhibitionists (Judd! Julie!) who bare their
personalities and souls for our voyeuristic amusement, not
realizing that the fascination and adoration (and often the
derision) will soon give way to one gigantic national shrug of
apathy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Amaya needs bodyguards when she goes out in
public, OK?
</P>
<P>
   It was just last year when MTV viewers lived and died with the
soap-operatic struggles of Ruthie, the skinnydipping, sexually
ambiguous, alcoholic showboat from ``The Real World: Hawaii.''
These days Ruthie wouldn't attract much of a crowd if she were
hired to drop her top and serve margaritas at a gentlemen's club.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, a Puck or an Eric or a post-mortem Pedro might achieve a
level of fame that extends beyond the run of a show _ but even then
it's a fifth-tier kind of thing, putting them in the same category
as Court TV defendants, infomercial hucksters and televangelists.
(Consider Sarah from the ``Real World: Miami,'' now selling her
toys, clothes, you name it, on sarahscrap.com.)
</P>
<P>
   While it's true that reality television makes it easier for
average citizens to become instant celebrities, an extended stint
in the spotlight remains a nearly impossible feat unless one is
armed with genuine talent that sets one apart from the field. (Or
if you're a Kennedy).
</P>
<P>
   And even Fame Lite is more diluted now than it was back in the
Kato Kaelin Era of the mid-1990s. With the ``Real World'' alumni
club numbering close to 70, not to mention all those ``Road Rules''
players and ``Survivor'' castaways, we may be reaching the point of
reality-celeb saturation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rapidly-dwindling ratings of the fledgling ``Big
Brother,'' from 22.5 million viewers Wednesday to 6.5 million by
Saturday, could be the first sign that real people sitting at home
are getting tired of watching real people bickering on TV.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the ROEPER
COLUMN and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
