u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-DAUBACH-BO     07-14 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DAUBACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUBACH HANDLED THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Brian Daubach took the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Big Armando Benitez, the flame-throwing closer for the New York
Mets, was working with the lead and the count was in his favor (1
and 2). And he went with the heat again.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach watched it. Or at least watched it as much as anyone can
watch a 97-mile-per-hour fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Up, up, and away. Just a tad up and a tad away.
</P>
<P>
   Ball two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was up and away,'' said Pedro Martinez, who knows a little
about heat and strikes and watched this one over again from the Red
Sox clubhouse. ``Benitez made the pitch to get him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daubach held back, and Benitez had to throw another heater.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was just a little inside, and Daubach ripped the
pitch deep to right field. And when the ball landed at the base of
the wall, it didn't bounce into the stands, and no fan reached over
to interfere with it, the Red Sox had a couple of breaks on one
play. Manny Alexander scored from third and Jose Offerman _ who
would have gone back to third on a ground-rule double _ scored from
first and the Red Sox walked off with a win. They'll take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those must have been Red Sox fans in the front row; if they
were Mets fans they probably would have grabbed it,'' Daubach said.
``We didn't catch many breaks in the first half (of the season). We
got lucky a little bit in the ninth with the error and that ball
staying in play for us. Maybe that will get us going. It's a good
way to start the second half, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach didn't sound quite as sure as Martinez on the 1-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have been surprised if he called it,'' Daubach
said. ``But I would have been upset. It would have been a tough
pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a chance for redemption. In the fifth inning, with
one out and the bases loaded, he popped to first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not often you get a second chance,'' Daubach said.
</P>
<P>
   He got the ninth-inning at-bat. And he made the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was close,'' Daubach said of the reprieve on the 1-and-2
pitch. ``I knew I better swing after that. I wasn't taking anymore
close ones. When you face a closer, especially a guy like Benitez,
his best pitch is his fastball, and you know he's going to come
after you.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that Benitez had to think about Nomar Garciaparra
on deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good pitch to hit,'' Daubach said. ``He's got to come
after me, especially with Nomar on deck. Not too many teams want to
face Nomar with the bases loaded in the bottom of the ninth in a
one-run game. They had to come at me.''
</P>
<P>
   They did. This time they lost.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach leads the team with 26 RBIs from the seventh inning on.
In his last 11 games, he is hitting .405 (15 for 37) with 14 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach may have been further inspired by facing the Mets, the
team that drafted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially because it's my old team,'' Daubach said. ``They
gave up on me a long time ago. That makes it a little extra
special. It seems when I play against the Marlins and the Mets I
try to do a little too much. But it feels good. That's all I can
really say.''
</P>
<P>
   It felt good all around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Benitez, he's tough,'' said manager Jimy Williams. ``All
you have to do is look at his numbers, what people do against him.
No one really hits him.''
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers: Righthanders were batting .178 against Benitez;
lefthanders like Daubach had it even tougher at .125.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put up a tremendous at-bat,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   He took the heat. And won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
