<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1781 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-NEAGLE-BOS     07-14 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NEAGLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAGLE WAS NOT A PRIORITY FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Red Sox had higher priorities than pursuing Denny
Neagle, the newest Yankee, Boston general manager Dan Duquette said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Neagle, a lefthanded starter acquired Wednesday
in a trade with the Cincinnati Reds, has a 14-2 record since last
August. In Duquette's view, the Sox need hitting help more than
pitching, though several Boston players who have faced Neagle in
the National League described his acquisition as a potential boon
for the Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were aware Neagle was on the market,'' Duquette said before
Thursday's game with the Mets. ``But we're more focused on helping
our team with run production at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox players had no quarrel with Duquette's priorities. But
they shared little doubt about Neagle's potential impact on the
American League East race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who can help the Yankees a lot,'' said Manny
Alexander, who faced Neagle in his three seasons in the NL with the
Cubs and Mets. ``He will pitch seven or eight innings and keep his
team in the game. They're a tough team already, but now that
they've got another lefty, they could be even tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bernard Gilkey, who played in the NL for St. Louis, New
York, and Arizona, ``Neagle, when he is on, has the potential to
shut you down, so he is definitely an asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Sprague, another former National Leaguer, described Neagle as
a ``Jimmy Key type'' of finesse pitcher with certified big-league
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good pickup for them,'' Sprague said, ``although
anytime you can pick up a big-league starting pitcher these days
it's a good pickup.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in the Red Sox clubhouse was awed by the notion of
Neagle in pinstripes. ``I didn't care at all,'' injured right
fielder Trot Nixon said. ``They can get as many guys as they want.
You still have to go out and play the game. That's the bottom line.
Neagle's having a pretty good year, but it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Derek Lowe, Boston's All-Star closer, undone by the
deal. ``You can't worry about who's on another club,'' he said.
``You knew they were going to get somebody. It was good for them.
It adds consistency to their rotation. But you can't win around one
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Lowe said, ``If we can stay consistent in the
second half, we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite shaky outings before the All-Star break by Boston's two
lefthanded starters _ Jeff Fassero and Pete Schourek _ Duquette
said he hoped the return from the disabled list of Pedro Martinez
would provide ``a shot in the arm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pitching staff is still intact,'' Duquette said, though he
made clear that Paxton Crawford is poised to rejoin the team ``in
the event we need him.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, a rookie righthander, was sent back to Pawtucket
before the All-Star break after strong starts in his only two
appearances with the big club. But Duquette said the demotion was
meant only ``to keep him sharp during the break.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette's recipe for success hinges in part on the successful
return of his rehabbing pitchers, including two-time Cy Young Award
winner Bret Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, 36, who underwent major reconstructive surgery last
November on his right shoulder, continued his arduous recovery
regimen Thursday by pitching in his second simulated game in a
week. He threw 42 pitches over three innings and ``did very well,''
according to pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``It looks pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   If he continues on pace, Saberhagen will pitch Tuesday, almost
certainly in Lowell for the Spinners. Saberhagen, despite three
stints on the disabled list, won 10 games last year for the Sox,
more than any Boston pitcher except Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat alone in an empty clubhouse while his teammates took
batting practice, Saberhagen offered a restrained assessment of
Thursday's outing. ``Everything went well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Scott Hatteberg, who watched Saberhagen throw, said he
``looked really good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very encouraging,'' Hatteberg said. ``Hopefully, he'll
advance. It all depends on his shoulder, but I'd love to see him
get back. If he can do it and we can be in the run, he'll be huge
for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
