<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1782 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-PAYTON-BOS     07-14 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PAYTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA'S FRIENDSHIP FIRES PAYTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SMITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Something good must have rubbed off on Jay Payton when
he embraced his good friend Nomar Garciaparra before Thursday's
game at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Payton must have borrowed some of Garciaparra's .390 mojo,
because he didn't look at all like the player who finished the
first half in a 1-for-15 slump.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' rookie center fielder went 2 for 4 with an RBI double
and a solo homer in the Mets' 4-3 loss. But those weren't just any
two hits. Those were two hits against arguably the best pitcher in
baseball, Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever he's on the field I seem to do OK,'' Payton said of
Garciaparra, his roommate and teammate for three years at Georgia
Tech. ``Even when I played in the minor leagues, the short time
that he was there, when I played against him I seemed to do well.
Maybe he's a little bit of good luck for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty comfortable today. I finished (the first half of
the season) on kind of a sour note. I just wanted to come in today
and try to get off to a good start in the second half. I saw the
ball good, put some good swings on it, and fortunately, some good
things happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a lot of good things have happened to Payton during his
seven-year career. Drafted by New York in the first round of the
1994 free agent draft, he's been as much a regular on the disabled
list as he has in the starting lineup. Check out his medical
history:
</P>
<P>
   1995: Reconstructive surgery on the medial collateral ligament
in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   1996: Surgery to remove bone spurs from his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   1997: Missed the entire season after another surgery on the
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   1998: Arthroscopic surgery on his right shoulder. Oh yeah, and a
hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   1999: Left shoulder surgery and an oblique strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very blessed to be playing this game right now,'' said
Payton, who took over in center field when Darryl Hamilton went on
the disabled list after the sixth game of the season. ``So I just
go out and have fun, try not to do too much, and try not to put too
much pressure on myself. Just try to go out and have fun playing
the game and help the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly did his part Thursday night. In the second inning,
Martinez threw him a changeup low and inside, but Payton reached
and pulled it down the left-field line for a double that scored
Todd Zeile from second and give the Mets a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Payton struck out in the fifth, but in the seventh, with the
Mets trailing, 2-1, Payton sent a 2-2 pitch from Martinez over the
wall for his ninth home run of the season and 29th RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay's been playing well,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said.
``He's been a big-leaguer for us. Hopefully he's coming right into
his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra knew Payton had it in him all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he can play,'' said Garciaparra, who went 2 for 4 but
was robbed of a third hit and a couple of RBIs when Payton chased
down his deep drive to center to end the fifth inning with the
bases full of Red Sox. ``It doesn't surprise me that he got two
hits today. Anything he does doesn't shock me. He's always been
good, all you have to do is give him a chance, he'll show
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra should know. He and Payton led Tech to the College
World Series in 1994. That year Garciaparra batted .427. Payton
batted .434. But they've traveled different paths since then. While
Garciaparra has become a star in the big leagues, it's been a
struggle for Payton just to get there. Until this season, he'd only
played in 28 games with the Mets during brief call-ups in 1998 and
'99.
</P>
<P>
   But the two have stayed close. They keep in touch over the
phone, and Garciaparra took Payton with him when the Major League
All-Stars played an exhibition in Japan in the fall of '98. Seeing
Garciaparra flourish encourages Payton that he, too, can someday be
one of baseball's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy for him,'' Payton said. ``It kind of gave me some
confidence that, hey, if I can get back and get to playing, then I
got a good chance to play in the big leagues. To see him having
such success was kind of a confidence-builder for me, just to try
to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been through so much,'' Garciaparra said. ``And he's
overcome a lot. He's an inspiration. If I'm down I call him, or
he'll call me up. If he's down, I'm there for him. It's a great
friendship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
