<HEADER>
A1783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-ART-     07-14 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MARTINEZ'S RETURN ENCOURAGING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The cornerstone is back in place.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen days after Red Sox management dislodged him against his
will from the active roster, Pedro Martinez Thursday night returned
and did what he does as masterfully as anyone in baseball: pitched
into the late innings and left his team in position to win.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Martinez, claiming he is fully healed from a
strained oblique muscle, must continue to do if his teammates
harbor any hope of October glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not God,'' he said after Brian Daubach's two-out,
two-strike walkoff double in the ninth beat the Mets, 4-3. ``Only
God knows if I'm going to be healthy (for the rest of the season).
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel pretty good right now,'' he said. ``I feel
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Mets who were pained as Martinez shackled the first
five hitters in the New York order, including his nemesis, Mike
Piazza, for seven innings. The Mets catcher entered the game
hitting .412 against Martinez, with three home runs in 14 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   But Piazza and the other four Mets batting around him at the top
of the order went hitless against the Sox stopper.
</P>
<P>
   In seven innings, Martinez yielded two runs on five hits and a
walk. He struck out 10 for the eighth time this season, throwing at
92 miles per hour in the seventh, as he did in the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dominant anytime,'' said Mets ace Mike Hampton. ``I don't
care if he hasn't pitched in a year. Anytime he's in the game, he's
going to give you a chance to win. And coming off the injury, he
gave them a quality start, and that's all you can ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one Met _ an unexpected Pedro Killer at that _ robbed
Martinez of a scoreless performance. Of the five hits Martinez
scattered over seven innings, only two hurt him, and both were
struck by Jay Payton, the Mets center fielder who is playing in his
first full major league season.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, a buddy of Nomar Garciaparra and Jason Varitek from
their days at Georgia Tech, lined a run-producing double down the
left-field line in the second inning and hit a solo homer that just
cleared the wall in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra had given Martinez a scouting report on Payton
before the game, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never faced the guy before, and it's hard for me to really
know which pitch to make,'' Martinez said. ``I can't just follow
the scouting report. I have to go by my own adjustments and
instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   He tried to fool Payton with a changeup, which turned into the
double. And he later tried to blow a fastball by him, but Payton
deposited it in the screen above Lansdowne Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I should throw a fastball up and in,'' Martinez
said. ``I left it a little lower than I wanted to, but I thought I
made a good pitch. You have to give him credit. I tip my hat to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach said Martinez's return gave the Sox a lift, even if he
had to settle for his third no-decision in four starts. Rich Garces
got the win, as Martinez remained winless since June 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see Pedro out there,'' Daubach said. ``It was
too bad we couldn't get him a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez continued to insist that the Red Sox should have kept
him in the starting rotation last month, though the rest appeared
to help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel stronger, I feel rested, but I didn't agree with
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said Martinez ``came back really
fresh.''``He felt a little strange out there in the first inning or
two,'' Kerrigan said. ``But he settled down after 30 or 40 pitches.
Anybody who can take 18 days away from the battle and come back and
pitch like that is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams was equally impressed. ``A lot of people
expect more from him than other pitchers,'' Williams said. ``I
really don't. I look at him like a human being and enjoy the
moments when he pitches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
