<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA BACK BEHIND PLATE WITH CLEAR HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SMITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mike Piazza went 1 for 4 Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't hit a home run. He didn't have an RBI.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets lost, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   But he's back behind the plate. And that's just as beautiful a
sight for New Yorkers as one of his towering home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``(My) timing is off pretty bad,'' said Piazza, who came into
the game batting .348 with 24 homers and 72 RBIs. ``Just wasn't
taking good swings. I think that's to be expected. Four days off .
. . five actually. It's been a few days. I'm just trying to get
some timing back. Fortunately, I was able to eke out a hit in the
last at-bat. Unfortunately, it wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   For a brief moment Saturday night, Piazza had to be wondering
whether he'd be eking out anything anytime soon. The Yankees' Roger
Clemens hit Piazza on the helmet with a fastball, knocking the
All-Star catcher to the ground with a slight concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza missed Sunday's Subway Series finale at Shea Stadium and
had to sit out the All-Star Game Tuesday in Atlanta. Sunday he
accused Clemens of intentionally throwing at him and said that he
didn't ``have respect for him right now at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, a much cooler version of Piazza reflected on his
time back in the batter's box. ``It's good just to get back out
there,'' said Piazza, who will DH Friday night and will likely pay
another visit to a neurologist when the Mets return to New York
July 25. ``It feels good, and I'm pretty lucky. I feel lucky, just
that there wasn't any more severe effects from it, and obviously I
wasn't hit in the face or anything like that. So, as I said, it's
time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   He had to move on against, of all people, Pedro Martinez. On
June 5, 1998, Martinez hit Piazza on his left hand in his first,
and before Thursday, his only regular-season at-bat on Yawkey Way.
Piazza accused Martinez, his former teammate with the Los Angeles
Dodgers, of hitting him on purpose. Piazza missed the last two
games of the interleague series, but the two continued to exchange
insults.
</P>
<P>
   They got reacquainted in the second inning, when Piazza stepped
to the plate for the first time since the Clemens incident. He
grounded out harmlessly to Ed Sprague. ``Ironically, I think the
first pitch Pedro threw me was up and in a little bit,'' Piazza
said after the game. ``I wasn't . . . flinching.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth and sixth innings, Piazza flew out to Jeff Frye in
right. Martinez left after the seventh inning, meaning Piazza
didn't get a chance to add to his .304 average (7 for 23) against
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   But Piazza did end his evening at the plate on a positive note.
With two outs in the eighth against Rich Garces, he hit a soft
liner to center that Carl Everett misplayed. Edgardo Alfonzo scored
from first on the error, and Piazza wound up at second, though he
was not credited with an RBI for the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things,'' Piazza said of being beaned. He
was also hit in the head in 1991 while playing for Single A
Bakersfield. ``To do your job in this game, you have to have a
clear mind . . . You can't hit with one foot in the dugout and one
in the batter's box.''
</P>
</TEXT>
