<HEADER>
A1804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u c BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0715-CO     07-14 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Books for the novice woodturner
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two handsome paper-bound books, originally published
in England and offered here by Sterling, should be of considerable
interest to the novice woodturner looking for direction.
</P>
<P>
   They are ``Woodturning: a Fresh Approach'' by Robert Chapman and
``Bowl Turning Techniques Master Class'' by Tony Boase. Both list
for $17.95. Between them, these two books outline the basic
techniques used in just about every avenue of turning, from the
most basic bowl to stack-laminated work, reformed and painted
pieces and surface decoration.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman's book is the more detailed, and deals with the basic
concepts _ bowls, natural and formal-lipped; platters, boxes, and
closed or hollow vessels. Boase's book devotes one chapter to an
individual turner specializing in more advanced variations.
</P>
<P>
   Both these books are beautifully illustrated. As far as I could
make out the work displayed in Chapman's book is all his own, and
all the work in Boase's book as that of turners in the UK and
Ireland with the exception of the gallery in the back.
</P>
<P>
   I've been out of woodturning for a few years now, and I've never
heard of any of these people. Chapman, judging from the work shown
in his book, is an incredibly diverse and tasteful turner. The
artists in Boase's book are certainly first-rank, too.
</P>
<P>
   All the work on display here is outstanding, in stark contrast
to some of the turning books I've seen in the past.
</P>
<P>
   However, I would caution the beginner that wood turning, unlike
joinery, is not something that can be learned from a book. It is a
dynamic interaction between a piece of wood rotating at high speed,
a tool edge and the hands holding the tool.
</P>
<P>
   Videos, and there are good ones readily available, are more
useful for the beginner. Workshops and tutelage, of course, are
best.
</P>
<P>
   Once the beginner grasps the basics, it's a matter of practicing
until the mind no longer has to concentrate on the cutting action
itself, entrusting this to the hands while the consciousness goes
on to make decisions about form.
</P>
<P>
   These two books, while of interest to any turner, will be of
most use to the turner who has arrived at that happy state and is
beginning to move from technique to art.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
