<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; sci-z
u l BC-HUMAN-STEADICAM-DISCO     07-14 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMAN-STEADICAM-DISCOVER-$ADV05-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAINWORKS: YOUR STEADICAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Wed., July 5, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color art available.) 
 By ERIC HASELTINE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In the brain, as in life, success often lies in striking a
balance between too much and too little of a good thing.
 &HT;    For example, you may think that the ability to keep your eyes
fixed upon objects is good, and for the most part, you would be
right. Thus, when you shake your noggin during an argument, you can
still stare your opponent down. This is possible because of a
small, internal accelerometer called the vestibular sensory organ,
which is located in the inner ear and senses head movements. It
allows the eyes to move in equal and opposite directions from the
head. But a perfectly fixed gaze, as you will see, has its hazards.
 &HT;    
 EXPERIMENT 1  
 &HT;    Go to the mirror. Shake your head, but keep watching your eyes.
They will seem fixed, because the vestibular organ counteracts the
motion of the neck muscles. The net effect is a stabilized gaze _
more or less. The more-or-less part turns out to be very important.
Read on.
 &HT;    
 EXPERIMENT 2  
 &HT;    Close your left eye, and hold this page about one foot away. Fix
your right eye on the diamond below. The green dot should vanish.
(You may need to move the page closer or farther before the dot
disappears.)
 &HT;    The green dot falls on your blind spot, the area on your retina
punched through by nerve fibers on their way to the brain. This
region can't register images that appear in front of it, but you
don't normally perceive a hole in your vision, because one eye
covers for the other.
 &HT;    More important for this discussion, the visual cells straddling
the blind area don't register the huge gap between them because the
retinal dead zone is permanently fixed, and visual neurons quickly
damp their responses to unchanging stimuli.
 &HT;    
 EXPERIMENT 3  
 &HT;    Prove this by turning the lights out and pointing the beam of a
small flashlight up into one pupil. Twirl the beam around while
switching your gaze back and forth. You should catch glimpses of
what look like delicate branches. The gauzy branches are shadows of
the blood vessels that lie on top of your retina.
 &HT;    The vessels cast shadows as light streams into the eye, but
because these shadows never move, the brain ceases responding to
them. Moving the flashlight beam around shifts the shadows just
enough to make them momentarily visible.
 &HT;    But you can't cause images to fade just by staring at something
unmoving, because the visual system constantly jiggles the eye
muscles in a phenomenon called physiological nystagmus, which
prevents the perfect stabilization of images.
 &HT;    These muscle tremors are infinitesimal, but their effect is
huge. Without them, we would, in effect, go blind, tuning out what
we see shortly after fixating our gaze.
 &HT;    It's an interesting notion: Approximate perfection is more
perfect than perfect perfection.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Eric Haseltine is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 c.2000 Discover magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on DISCOVER
NEWS SERVICE and other features. &QL;
