<P>
   EPISCOPARY-WOMAN _ In November 1787, when Richard Allen stormed
out of the predominantly white St. George's Church in Philadelphia
and formed the African Free Society (later renamed the African
Methodist Episcopal Church), the thought of bringing a woman into
the hierarchy of his clan never entered his mind. But the prospect
of selecting a female to the lofty position of AME bishop could not
escape the minds of the 1,800 delegates who attended the order's
closely scrutinized General Conference at the Cincinnati Convention
Center this week. In a landmark, second-ballot vote, the Rev.
Vashti Murphy McKenzie, 53, of Baltimore, Md., was elected to the
Episcopary, becoming the first female in the 213-year history of
the church to assume that seat. (Dayton Daily News).
</P>
