u k BC-MINTER-COLUMN0715-COX     07-14 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From post to pillory
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I have been pleased to discover, in Jonesville, La.,
someone who shares my concern about e-mail, which has become all
too popular and a serious threat to intimate personal
communication, and to a unique way of recording history.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Womack writes a column for her Jonesville parish newspaper.
She sent a copy of one lamenting the decline of old-fashioned
letter-writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I received an antique form of correspondence last week,'' she
wrote. ``It was a real letter, handwritten, put in an envelope,
stamped and mailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The letter was from my Aunt Jessie Patterson, Mama's sister,
who lives in Yazoo City, Miss. Her letters are always fun to read,
filled with family news and witty comments. For instance:
'Something happens to grandsons when they get to be 13. Their heads
get hot, and the only place they can cool them off is in the
refrigerator. By the time they leave, the refrigerator and the
cupboards are as bare as Mother Hubbard's.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I derive a true satisfaction from receiving a personal letter.
Oh, I get letters all the time. 'Dear Alma Womack,' they say. 'You
are a valued customer. . .' or, 'We want you to run up $2,000 of
debt, for which we will happily charge you interest at Mafia
rates.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill and Hillary send letters asking for my help and money to
defeat the conservative forces bent on sending the Clintons into
oblivion. I get at least a letter a week advising me that I have
become a millionaire. These make good kindling.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter still sends me articles through the mail; things
she can't send on a computer, I mean e-mail. But friends I've
corresponded with since school days rarely write anymore. They all
want to e-mail me, which had been impossible until the last few
months, since I had nothing to e-mail to.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Alma, I held out on e-mail until I became an embarrassment
to my children and granddaughter. It was a mistake to give in. I
didn't know that with e-mail you can make a list of everybody you
know, or everybody in the phone book, and send them a copy of all
the e-mail you send or receive. Everybody else on e-mail can do the
same. E-mail works like an upside-down pyramid. It grows like
kudzu.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon I was getting about 8,000 e-mails a day. I didn't
have time to read them, but if you don't get rid of them your
computer will explode. I was spending 12 to 15 hours a day deleting
raunchy jokes, warnings about the end of the world, the Religious
Right, the Far Left, the Clintons, earth warming, earth cooling and
John Rocker. From strangers I'd never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   People who are otherwise respectable and have good taste wil
over, then put them back in a box for another day.
</P>
<P>
   ``With e-mail, we are losing not only our personal touches with
each other, but we also are depriving future generations of the
pleasure of finding a trunk filled with missives from another time.
E-mail may be fast and efficient, but like instant coffee and
instant grits, goodness has been sacrificed for speed.' '' Right,
Alma.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, on rainy afternoons, I sit in my depot hideaway and
reread letters written by my ancestors, all the way back to before
the Civil War. They tell me a lot about who they were, and who I
am. I don't think they'd be the same on a floppy disk.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
