u k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0715-C     07-14 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Research linking left-handedness, gays spurs humorous
observations
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ During the 71st All-Star Game in Atlanta I caught
myself paying more attention to the left-handed players.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that day, I read a news story in The Times of London
that said homosexuals are more likely to be left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   The story was based on a study by Canadian researchers involving
more than 23,000 men and women. The results, according to Nigel
Hawkes, the newspaper's science editor, is that the odds of being
left-handed are 39 percent higher in homosexuals than in
heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   While watching 6-foot-10-inch lefty fireballer Randy ``Big
Unit'' Johnson, the starting National League pitcher, bear down on
switch-hitter Roberto Alomar, I thought of gay power. I couldn't
help it.
</P>
<P>
   The study didn't say that left-handed people were homosexual, I
knew that. It simply said that left-handers are more likely to be
homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   So there was no reason to watch for nuances in the way big
first-baseman Jason Giambi, who batted cleanup, dug in at the plate
before taking his left-handed cut at the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the study said the left-handed effect is much stronger
in lesbian women than in gay men.
</P>
<P>
   ``While homosexual men are only 34 percent more likely to be
left-handed, homosexual women have nearly twice as many
left-handers as heterosexual women,'' said the news story about the
study that appears in this month's issue of Psychology Bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   NEW WAY TO VIEW GAME
</P>
<P>
   After Big Unit retired Giambi, David Wells took the mound for
the American League. Wells, nicknamed Boomer, was another
left-handed hurler. Research that shows homosexuals are more likely
to be left-handed sure offers baseball fans a new way to watch a
ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the Canadian study interested me is because I've
written about earlier studies that indicated homosexuality is a
genetic condition inherited at birth. Those discoveries caused
consternation among some religious fundamentalists who believe that
homosexuality is an unnatural lifestyle choice that deserves holy
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   If homosexuality is genetic, it means sexual orientation is a
product of nature, not nurture. And if a person's sexual
orientation is determined even before birth, then religious
fundamentalists would be forced to conclude that it is a God-given
characteristic.
</P>
<P>
   Religious fundamentalists find God-given attributes difficult to
condemn. It's a lot easier to blame homosexuality on an
individual's sinful choice rather than accept the fact that
homosexuality is naturally occurring in the same way that
male-pattern baldness or the ability to carry a tune is inherited.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the point, I've written that medical research
appears to show that homosexuality is an inherited trait in much
the same way as being born left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   I threw that comment into my discourse because it appears that
roughly 10 percent of the population is left-handed and about the
same percentage is homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   My observation did not go down well with religious
fundamentalists who condemn homosexuality as a sin against God.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, some homosexuals also don't like the idea that
their sexual orientation is something they can't control any more
than they can control the color of their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the consistent similarity between the numbers of
homosexuals and left-handers in society, I also compared the two
conditions because I am left-handed. I never dreamed that one day
medical researchers would overlap the two traits.
</P>
<P>
   At least, I've found an interesting new way to watch an All-Star
game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
