</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1869 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECHNOBUDDY0714-COX     07-14 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beware: Snoop software can record your every keystroke
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most of us live lives of quiet boredom. We don't steal
atomic secrets, plan hostile mergers, or plot to overthrow the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Worst case, you may say something mean-spirited in an e-mail,
brag about cheating the IRS out of a few bucks, or make a joke that
you wouldn't repeat to an assemblage of scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I don't know anyone who wants to make his life an open
book. Few of us would invite someone to sit down and read
everything in our computer, to browse all the e-mails stored there,
even to be able to read notes that were started and erased without
ever being saved.
</P>
<P>
   The computer has become _ over the years _ the most private of
personal secretaries. Until recently the information you stored
there was at least as safe from gossip as if you entrusted it to a
human secretary.
</P>
<P>
   There were ways _ of various sophistication _ of snooping. Even
years ago, there were programs _ distributed quietly on bulletin
boards and Web pages run by hackers _ called keyboard logging
programs. They hid in the shadows of your hard disk and were almost
impossible to detect by the user. They logged every keystroke on
that particular machine. Then, the hacker could sit down at the
machine at his leisure, enter a password and read a transcript that
showed every keystroke made.
</P>
<P>
   While that isn't exactly a great thing, the chances of being
snared by one of those programs were slim. Most ordinary people
didn't even know such programs existed, and some amount of computer
skill was required to locate and install the programs. There just
wasn't a big risk that you'd bump into something like that.
</P>
<P>
   But, within the past few months, the chances of someone _ a
spouse, a friend, a co-worker _ taking a private look at every word
you've written have jumped way up. That same type of spying
software is now available down at your favorite computer store.
There are now commercial programs _ selling in the $50 range _ that
are as easy to use as a word processor. Simply load one into a
computer and _ just like the old hacker programs _ you can read
every typed secret at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   Several of these programs exist including Spector, 007 Stealth
Activity Recorder, Cyber Snoop and eBlaster (we'll talk more about
this one later). The basic idea is that the program hides in the
computer and serves as a high tech peeping Tom.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are supposed to be able to make sure that kids aren't
hanging out on the wrong electronic blocks in cyberspace. Spouses
theoretically can use it to make sure a partner isn't engaged in
extracurricular sex _ either the real thing or the cyber version.
Even that rubs me wrong, but there would be those who disagree, so
I'll leave the question for those smarter than myself.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to be a genius to figure that some people are
going to use these programs in really twisted ways. Kids will snoop
on parents, boyfriends on girlfriends, and _ probably most likely _
a lot of folks will snoop just for the fun of it, turning your life
into a real-life soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   And, as if programs like Spector aren't frightening enough,
software such as eBlaster takes snooping to a higher level. That
program can be set up to send the details of what you type on your
computer by e-mail. Which means that the person who wants to spy on
your computer only needs access to it one time. After installing
the program, he can harvest the details of your life from the
safety of his home computer. And no trail of the e-mails remains on
the host computer.
</P>
<P>
   Finding these programs is easy at the store but difficult once
they're installed on the computer. After all, that's the whole
idea. They're made to hide and reside in hidden directories that
won't show up in a routine search. And since the person who
installs them can set the hidden command needed to view the log
files, you're unlikely to ever notice the program once it is
installed. Since the hidden logs files take up 50 megabytes or more
on the hard disk, one way to detect them would be to check hard
disk space. But in these days of 20 gigabyte hard drives, even that
isn't very practical.
</P>
<P>
   So the real secret _ when it comes to avoiding the risk that
someone might plant one of these sinister programs on your PC _ is
to know who your friends are. Which isn't such a bad thing, no
matter what your secrets are.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
