   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-LOTTERY (San Antonio) _ After nearly eight years, picking
six numbers between 1 and 50 for a ticket to millions of dollars
will end Saturday night for Lotto Texas players. Beginning Sunday,
tickets for the twice-weekly game will have players selecting from
a field of 54 numbers. By CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SEX (San Francisco) _ A San Francisco-based FBI team
that patrols children's chat rooms made its first arrest: a
39-year-old San Jose man who allegedly approached a 14-year-old
girl online and planned to meet her for the first time at the San
Francisco Zoo and then have sex with her. By DEMIAN BULWA.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-ALASKA (San Francisco) _ Lawsuits arising from the Jan. 31
crash of Alaska Airlines Flight 261 will be consolidated for
important pretrial proceedings in San Francisco, including the
discovery of evidence, judicial panel has decided. By SCOTT
WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-POT (San Francisco) _ Starting Friday, residents with a
doctor's note and $25 can obtain an identification card from the
San Francisco Department of Public Health that shows they are
legitimate pot smokers. City officials and medical marijuana
advocates say people who need the substance also need to be free of
police scrutiny. By DEMIAN BULWA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ What do you get when you
combine millions of dollars, heart-racing excitement, abject terror
and senseless carnage? You get the film ``Jaws,'' which is being
officially re-hyped with the release of its 25th anniversary video.
And anytime you speak of greed and carnage, you're talking the
language of the American workplace. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-ALERO (Undated) _ Oldsmobile finally has built an
affordable car that is every bit as good as one of those Japanese
sedans that consumers are so enamored with. Introduced just last
year as Oldsmobile's import-buster, mass-market compact sedan, the
Alero already has become the choice for many consumers who
otherwise would have bought a Honda Accord, Nissan Altima, Mazda
626, Mitsubishi Galant or other import brands in this market
segment. G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-BRIEFS (Undated) _ To help meet consumer demand, Honda has
increased availability of its new Insight gasoline-electric car to
6,500 units for calendar year 2000, up from the originally planned
4,000 cars. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
