   FILM-REVIEW-CHUCK-BUCK (Undated) _ Part case study, part
metaphor, all bidding for your own Kinsey-scale reading, Mike White
and Miguel Arteta's ``Chuck and Buck'' is a thumb-sucking entry in
the ``I don't wanna grow up'' sweepstakes. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BLOOD (Undated) _ Like a tale from the crypt penned
by James M. Cain, Joel and Ethan Coen's ``Blood Simple'' has
resurrected itself in taut, super-tense fashion, and is a somewhat
noticeable eight minutes lighter. (Wow, a director's cut that's
shorter than the original!) By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-ROCK-MOVIES (Pasadena, Calif.) _ The rock movie has been
around in theaters since the 1950s. Today, television has been
tapping that vein, most notably in the VH-1 documentary series. But
the network and others have branched out into excavating the drama
of rock, both in biopics and a couple of new fictional series
coming this fall. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-JAZZ (Pasadena, Calif.) _ First was ``Civil War.'' Then came
``Baseball.'' To complete his American trilogy, documentarian Ken
Burns says he's trading in the violins that marked those two works
for the saxophone: ``Jazz,'' a 10-part PBS series, which clocks in
a shade under 19 hours. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PBS-PREVIEW (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Pat Mitchell faced her first
mass interview as president and CEO of PBS in front of the nation's
TV critics. Historically, this is not a good thing. Almost every
year, the PBS chief gets slowly roasted over a spit-fire of
indignation and second-guessing, as critics try to speak for the
American taxpaying public. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Camping doesn't get any
stranger than this, and for many who have tried, it doesn't get any
better. At Lake Oroville, there are these strange, double-decker
floating camps, kind of like giant patio boats without motors,
along with floating bathrooms. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
