<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEARNING CAREER LESSONS FROM `JAWS' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What do you get when you combine millions of
dollars, heart-racing excitement, abject terror and senseless
carnage? All right, an Internet start-up. But besides that?
</P>
<P>
   You get ``Jaws,'' one of the greatest films ever made, which is
being officially re-hyped this week with the release of its 25th
anniversary video. And anytime you speak of greed and carnage,
you're talking the language of the American workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you thought it was safe to go back in the office, here
are four career lessons from ``Jaws'':
</P>
<P>
   _ Listen for the music.
</P>
<P>
   After a night of partying, a woman goes for a skinny-dip. After
a moment's peace, a great white shark rips her into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The swimmer had no idea what was about to happen, of course, but
the audience knew she had a future in the fast-food industry. For
what seemed like minutes before the attack, the theme from ``Jaws''
let you know that the shark was salivating.
</P>
<P>
   (I don't know that sharks really salivate. But lawyers do, so
I'm making a logical assumption.)
</P>
<P>
   Characters in a production are sometimes oblivious to clues that
outside observers can easily see. That's why your network should
always include people not only from outside your company, but from
related industries. They might be hearing the music while you're
naked and oblivious.
</P>
<P>
   _ Money will compromise your judgment.
</P>
<P>
   We all realize that, but it can still sneak up on you. You'll
make an emotional decision based on greed, then either rationalize
what you're doing or go into denial.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Jaws,'' town officials don't want to shut the island during
the busy tourist season because it would cost them tons of money,
so they try to explain away the first couple of attacks as
mysteries or boating accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Companies and workers run into this all the time, and not just
in obvious matters of professional ethics. People find themselves
in unsatisfactory careers, and the fear of the unknown locks them
into that weekly paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   As people earn more money, they classify a lot of life's goodies
as necessities when they're really luxuries. If you're unhappy and
afraid that quitting your job or cutting back will put a hardship
on your family, sit down and figure out what you'd really be giving
up. Are they luxuries or necessities?
</P>
<P>
   It could be that all these ``logical'' reasons you're giving for
not changing careers are merely rationalizations. You don't want to
admit that you're afraid of the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   _ You will need a bigger boat.
</P>
<P>
   By the time anybody sees the shark in ``Jaws,'' it's too late to
do anything about the size of the boat. The heroes are already
trapped in a life-or-death struggle with the shark.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been a bad networker and have been in denial about
problems at your company, you might not realize how much danger
you're in until it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   The more skills you have, the bigger your boat is. What can you
do better than your peers? Does your boss know that you're still
growing, or do you appear to be dead in the water? What have you
done lately without being asked?
</P>
<P>
   Even if you have the skills and the energy, the shark still
might destroy your boat. But you'll find another one.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eventually, the shark will lose.
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions, but people who come in and cause a lot of
carnage at a company don't usually stick around for the long haul.
They'll either go off in search of new prey, or the workers will
rebel so much that the ``shark'' will be forced out.
</P>
<P>
   Keep that in mind if you want a long future with the company.
Not only do you want to escape the giant shark, but you want to
stay away from the feeding frenzy, too.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever there's a shark around, it doesn't pay to get too
chummy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
