<SLUG> BC-BIG-TOP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GENERATION X RINGMASTER SHARES SECRETS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DANIEL J. VARGAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnathan Lee Iverson is the new kid under the Big Top.
</P>
<P>
   As the youngest and 31st ringmaster of the Ringling Bros. and
Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus, the 24-year-old is the darling of the
circus.
</P>
<P>
   This Manhattan native is a towering 6-foot-5-inches with the
voice of an operatic tenor. Just as impressive, he's the first
African-American to serve as ringmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be overlooked is Iverson's rich sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   So, we decided to forgo the standard interview and ask him a few
offbeat questions _ to find out what circus life has been like for
this Gen-X ringmaster during his first six months on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I imagine you won't be a ringmaster the rest of your life.
Have you thought about how this job is going to look on your
resume?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it will look pretty good. It's very unique. I've
started my career with a home-run hit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you ran away from the circus, where would you go and why?
</P>
<P>
   A: Brazil. The women. Everybody is gorgeous in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the strangest thing you've seen behind the tent flaps?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's a hard one. I think it was discovering that people
hate getting old. Some of the guys are like 17-year-olds stuck in
65-year-old bodies, and they hate every moment of it. They're big
flirts talking to the younger girls after the show. It's nothing
dirty or anything, just funny.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you were on the show Survivor and you had to vote off a
fellow circus colleague from the island, who would you vote off
first: a clown, a trapeze artist or an animal trainer?
</P>
<P>
   A: That is so hard. It's hard with the circus. I'm not trying to
cover my ass. Everyone here is so good at what they do. It wouldn't
be fair. The circus has figured out what the rest of the world
hasn't: It's learned how to work as a unit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Oh, come on now, you have to ditch one of them.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's so hard to say. Well, I guess if we were on a deserted
island, there would be a lot of trees so we would need a trapeze
artist.
</P>
<P>
   If a crazy animal comes at us, we'd need an animal trainer. I
guess we'd bounce off the clown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were you ever afraid of clowns? How about now?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, not at all. I have a great respect for clowns and
clowning.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But you just ousted the clown off the island.
</P>
<P>
   A: I wouldn't vote (clowns) off the circus.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you had your choice between cleaning up after the
elephants or feeding the tigers, which would you choose?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'd clean up after the elephants. No problem. I have a tough
nose. I'm from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're still young enough to be on MTV's The Real World. What
kind of roommate would you be?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'd be a cool roommate. I'll admit I like to get on people's
nerves to see how far I can go. But I'm a low-maintenance kind of
guy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Because you're a potential troublemaker do you think your
roommates would kick you out of the house?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not at all. I'm too interesting. I'd find a way to stay on
TV.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your least favorite circus animal?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's easy: horses. They're the most faithless animal on the
face of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the circus life first scared you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you sure? I don't believe you.
</P>
<P>
   A: Really.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you ever had to break up a circus fight?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. It was broken up by the time I got there. It was between
an acrobat and an animal trainer. Of course, it was over a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who won?
</P>
<P>
   A: They didn't have a chance to swing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So it really wasn't a fight?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, I guess not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do circus performers do for fun? That is, when they're
not shooting themselves out of canons or cramming themselves into
tiny cars.
</P>
<P>
   A: We have barbecues and go clubbing. There are other things,
too, but that will be in my uncensored book.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who in the circus would be your phone-a-friend lifeline on
Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Human Comet _ J.P. Theron. He knows so much useless info.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever met someone like that?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is that your final answer?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Laughing): Yeah, that's my final answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
