<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HONDA BOOSTS PRODUCTION OF HYBRID CAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To help meet consumer demand, Honda has increased availability
of its new Insight gasoline-electric car to 6,500 units for
calendar year 2000, up from the originally planned 4,000 cars, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   With an EPA rating of 70 miles per gallon, the Insight has the
highest fuel economy of any car in the world. Consumers across the
nation are on the waiting list for the cars, which went on sale in
February.
</P>
<P>
   The two-seat Insight is powered by a 1.0-liter, three-cylinder
gasoline engine and an electric motor, which kicks in when needed
to boost power. The electric motor receives its power from a bank
of nickel-metal-hydride batteries that are recharged while the
vehicle is driving on the gasoline engine; it does not have to be
connected to an external charger the way that all-electric cars
must be.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota is rolling out a four-passenger hybrid, the Prius, this
summer at its U.S. dealerships; that vehicle has been on sale in
Japan since December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS EARNS 4 STARS FOR SAFETY
</P>
<P>
   The new two-door Ford Focus subcompact garnered a four-star
rating (out of a possible five stars) for the driver, but just one
star for the rear-seat passenger in the latest crash tests posted
by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, the agency
said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   To check on crash ratings of the Focus and other 2000 models
that have already been tested and posted on the agency's Web site,
go to www.nhtsa.dot.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the crash tests of the all-new Chrysler PT Cruiser
still have not been posted, although at least one of the vehicles
has been tested.
</P>
<P>
   For both frontal and side impacts, the federal agency's New Car
Assessment Program reports crash test results in a range of one to
five stars, with five stars showing the best crash protection for
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Frontal tests should be compared only within the same weight
class.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you without Web access, a fact sheet containing
explanatory information and tables showing crash-test results for
model year 2000 vehicles is available by calling the NHTSA Office
of Public and Consumer Affairs, (202) 366-9550; the Auto Safety
Hotline, (888) 327-4236; or by writing to NHTSA Public Affairs,
Room 5232, 400 Seventh St. SW, Washington, D.C. 20590.
</P>
<P>
   The crash test information is available on the Web site by
clicking on ``Crash Tests'' under ``Popular Information'' in the
index on the left side of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
