<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-ALERO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NIMBLE ALERO IS NOTHING LIKE THE OLDS OF OLD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oldsmobile finally has built an affordable car that is every bit
as good as one of those Japanese sedans that consumers like so
much.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced just last year as Oldsmobile's import-buster,
mass-market compact sedan, the Alero already has become the choice
for many consumers who otherwise would have bought a Honda Accord,
Nissan Altima, Mazda 626, Mitsubishi Galant or other import brands
in this market segment.
</P>
<P>
   My weeklong test drive of the Alero GLS gave me a new
appreciation for American auto manufacturing, particularly at
General Motors, where compact and midsize sedans have taken a back
seat to the Japanese for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   What I found is that there really is no need to buy an Accord if
what you really want is a well-built American sedan in the same
price class. The Accord, for many reasons, has been the top choice
of compact/midsize buyers for the past several years, and it has
perennially battled with the Ford Taurus and Toyota Camry for the
honors of top-selling car in the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   But giving the Alero a try, especially not long after testing an
Accord and a Galant, made a believer out of me. If Olds can attract
baby boomers and Generation X-ers into its showrooms, I believe it
can sell them the Alero, instead of losing them to the Accord or
other imports.
</P>
<P>
   The Alero had a much more solid feel than the Accord, with road
handling that was surprisingly nimble and athletic. I almost
couldn't believe I was driving an American sedan, let alone an
Oldsmobile -- one of those GM brands known for decades for its big,
boatlike, wallowing sedans that appealed mostly to consumers beyond
retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile began re-inventing itself in the mid-90s with the
introduction of the Aurora premium sedan, which I have said before
is one of the best cars GM or any other automaker has ever
produced.
</P>
<P>
   While the Alero isn't in the same class as the $30,000-plus
Aurora, it is well above the class of some of its competitors in
the compact/midsize segment. Although technically classified by the
EPA as a compact because of its overall interior volume, the Alero
offers the roominess and interior comfort of midsize models such as
the Camry, Nissan Maxima and Volkswagen Passat.
</P>
<P>
   The Alero, which replaced the ho-hum Achieva sedan and is on the
same basic vehicle chassis as the Chevrolet Malibu and Pontiac
Grand Am, comes well-equipped to compete with just about any car in
the compact segment, including the Infiniti G20 and Volvo S40.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly a cut above the Ford Contour and Mercury
Mystique, the closest competitors in the Ford/Lincoln-Mercury
lineups.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy less-well-equipped Alero models that compete
head-to-head with the Contour, Mystique and Accord; the base engine
in the Alero GL and GX models is a 2.4-liter four-cylinder similar
to the base engines in the Contour, Accord and Altima.
</P>
<P>
   But the GLS1 model _ $22,095 including transportation _ comes
with a 170-horsepower, 3.4-liter V-6 engine and leather interior,
moving it up into the higher echelons to compete with the Maxima,
Camry, G20 and S40.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile says the Alero and other vehicles in its current
lineup, including the midsize Intrigue sedan, Silhouette minivan
and Bravada sport-utility, have helped lower the average age of
Olds buyers by six years. That trend is going to continue next
spring when Olds introduces its completely revised Bravada.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Alero buyers are primarily women, although I know of no
reason why this car should not appeal to men as well. And there is
solid evidence that this car is luring buyers away from the
imports.
</P>
<P>
   GM says up to 50 percent of Alero buyers have told their dealers
they would have bought an import if the Alero had not been
available. That's an important statistic for GM, because making
such ``conquest'' sales over imports is GM's primary marketing goal
for the Alero.
</P>
<P>
   What this car signifies most, perhaps, is that family-sedan
buyers don't have to compromise on anything to choose the Alero
over an import. This car is a smart buy for savvy consumers who
heretofore have believed that imports represent the best long-range
value.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is comfortable without being overly cushy, so there was
no feeling that I was driving one of those old-fashioned
Oldsmobiles. Those are gone, anyway; all current Olds products are
geared toward younger buyers and aren't anything like the Olds of
old.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't find much to dislike about the Alero. My only two
gripes had to do with the trunk. It's large enough to hold 14.7
cubic feet of stuff, but the opening is somewhat limited, which
restricts the size of objects you can put back there. This is not
unique to the Alero, however; it is a problem found in many cars in
this class.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the trunk on the Alero had a weird catch that would not
allow the trunk to latch without first pushing a button on the side
of the latch.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is some new kind of safety feature to prevent small
children from accidentally locking themselves in the trunk, but if
so, there is nothing in the Olds literature that mentions it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bit of a nuisance; if I tried to shut the trunk without
first pushing this button, the trunk lid just bounced back up.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of power with the V-6 engine, and the four-speed
automatic transmission shifts smoothly and seamlessly. Granted,
there are midsize sedans with more power, but this car has as much
zip as most people will ever need.
</P>
<P>
   I've driven the four-cylinder model, too, and also found it
adequate for most needs. The extra power offered by the V-6 engine
will help if you routinely carry a car full of people and stuff,
but for those of you who want a more affordable car, the
four-cylinder models should be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Alero isn't really a sporty car, Olds is offering a
five-speed, Getrag manual transmission for model year 2000 for
people who want more performance than convenience. But it is
available only with the four-cylinder engine, which does not come
in the GLS model.
</P>
<P>
   Standard GLS equipment includes traction control, manual
air-conditioning, six-way power driver's seat, premium
AM/FM/cassette/compact disc stereo, leather interior, automatic
on/off halogen headlights, four-wheel antilock disc brakes,
stainless-steel exhaust system, power windows/mirrors/door locks,
remote keyless entry, 16-inch polished-aluminum wheels, cruise
control, front bucket seats with console shifter, illuminated entry
system, and large (and readable) analog gauges.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings for the V-6 are 20 miles per gallon in
the city and 32 mpg on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
