<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TV LINEUP: ROCK IS ON A ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Who almost got it right more than a
quarter-century ago when they sang that rock was dead. It turns out
it's rock video that's flatlined.
</P>
<P>
   But the rock TV drama _ that's different. The live-fast-die
young-leave-a-good looking-corpse mentality of the 1960s and '70s
laid the foundation for numerous movie projects, not to mention
14,867 installments of ``VH1: Behind the Music.''
</P>
<P>
   The rock movie has been around in theaters since the 1950s;
today, television has been tapping that vein (so to speak), most
notably in the VH1 documentary series. But the network and others
have branched out into excavating the drama of rock, both in
biopics and a couple of new fictional series coming this fall.
</P>
<P>
   MTV, which used to play rock videos back in the day, has
branched out in many different directions (likewise, country cousin
TNN is also moving away from videos). One will be a new series
``Live Through This,'' in which a fictional seminal group from the
'70s, the Jackson Decker Band, reunite to go on tour with their
various children, ages 12 to 24. Hey, isn't that the MTV
demographic?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, VH1 will continue what it started last season by
rolling out more rock 'n' roll flicks. The slate includes: a biopic
on Meat Loaf subtitled ``To Hell and Back''; the comedy ``Out of
Sync,'' in which a gorgeous but off-key singer has her vocals
dubbed by the ugly duckling with the gorgeous voice (only in
television would Gail O'Grady, late of ``NYPD Blue,'' qualify as
ugly); and ``At Any Cost,'' the typical story in which rock 'n'
roll kills and soars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this fear that one of these years, I'm going to stand
up here and have nothing to say except, `We've run out of rock
history to strip-mine,''' VH1 executive vice president Jeff Gaspin
told reporters at the Television Critics Association Press Tour
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Even Showtime is getting involved: In ``The Chris Isaak Show,''
the rocker and his band play themselves in a mockumentary akin to
the late, great ``Larry Sanders Show.'' Isaak, who conducted one of
the funniest news conferences in recent memory at the press tour,
said the stories will be fiction based on his experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to have people that we can kill off every week,'' he
said. Don't put it past him.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a fly in the programming ointment: Most of the
rock-as-drama fare we've seen on television the past few years
stinks. Really stinks. You know I want to go further than that, but
I can't, so take what I'm saying and run with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I didn't do one,'' said rock legend David Crosby,
who was promoting ``Stand and Be Counted,'' a documentary
miniseries on the history of music as agent for social change (it
debuts next month on The Learning Channel).
</P>
<P>
   While Crosby's life, and much of what we see on ``Behind the
Music,'' is perfect dramatic fare, the Woodstock veteran wants no
part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them have been so trashy and so shallow that they're
really not worth watching,'' he said. ``I cite the Beach Boys one
(ABC's `An American Family') as an example. I've been asked to do
one for my autobiography (`Long Time Gone') over and over again,
but I'm not willing to have my life memorialized in a six-week
movie for TV. They don't do it well enough.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE REALITY ABOUT REALITY TV
</P>
<P>
   While networks are looking to get on the reality gravy train
following the success of ``Survivor,'' MTV is heading off in a
different direction.
</P>
<P>
   The home of ``Real World,'' the original ``Big Brother'' and
``Road Rules'' based much of its success on the novelty of those
shows. For a network whose money is made on being cutting-edge,
being part of the crowd is not where it wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to make a list of my Top 10 concerns for MTV,
(reality-show proliferation) is absolutely No. 1,'' said Brian
Graden, MTV's president of programming. ``Now we're no longer alone
in doing that, and so the question is: What is MTV's point of
distinction going to be going forward?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: ``While they're hanging their hats on reality _
which was important to us for the last five years _ we're probably
hanging our hat on (computer) interactivity.''
</P>
<P>
   A perfect point of transition is the new show ``DFX,'' in which
viewers will vote on line for what videos they want to see: Its
host, Teck Holmes, was one of the housemates on ``Real World
Hawaii.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   DIVERSE DIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Hispanic characters, let alone shows devoted to
them, remains an inexplicable blight on network television.
Showtime recently added the drama ``Resurrection Blvd.,'' which
chronicles a Hispanic family. Now Nickelodeon is going even
further, introducing three shows in which Hispanics are featured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brothers Garcia,'' a live-action comedy series following
the lives of a San Antonio family, premieres at 8:30 p.m. July 23.
It's narrated in flashback by John Leguizamo (``Summer of Sam''):
``I'm the Latin Daniel Stern,'' Leguizamo said, referring to the
narrator on the similarly constructed show ``The Wonder Years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Taina,'' a half-hour show about a teen-age Hispanic girl with
dreams of musical stardom, debuts on the cable network in October.
August brings ``Dora the Explorer,'' a preschool animated show
about a Hispanic girl who lives insides a computer.
</P>
<P>
   For additional diversity, the network will offer ``Pelswick,'' a
cartoon about a 13-year-old in a wheelchair, in October. Judging
from some preview clips, this series from nationally syndicated
cartoonist and author John Callahan (who is quadriplegic) could be
wickedly funny and irreverent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
