<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JAZZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW PBS PROJECT FOCUSES ON JAZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The subjects seem disparate, scattered: a
war, a sport, a musical genre. But documentarian Ken Burns saw the
thread, and knew how to weave it into the story of a country.
</P>
<P>
   First was ``Civil War.'' Then came ``Baseball.'' To complete his
American trilogy, Burns says he's trading in the violins that
marked those two works for the saxophone: ``Jazz,'' a 10-part PBS
series, clocks in a shade under 19 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the opening moments of our history of baseball,'' Burns
told television critics this week, ``the writer Gerald Early told
us that when they study our civilization 2,000 years from now,
Americans will be known for only three things: the Constitution,
baseball and jazz music.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his previous works, the miniseries uses the subject matter
as the locus for a number of issues, chief among them race.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Jan. 8, ``Jazz'' chronicles the lives and music of
greats ranging from Dave Brubeck to Louis Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said Armstrong ``is the most important person in music _ I
didn't say jazz: in music _ in the 20th century. He is to music
what Einstein is to physics, and what the Wright Brothers are to
travel.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   BUSY `NUREMBERG' AUTHOR
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Persico is busy on television. The small-screen
adaptation of his book ``Nuremberg: Infamy on Trial'' airs Sunday
and Monday (8 p.m. both nights on TNT). In October, PBS will air
the two-part series ``The Rockefellers,'' chronicling the dynastic
family.
</P>
<P>
   Persico, who worked on the television project, was chief
speechwriter for Nelson Rockefeller when he was governor of New
York and vice president under Gerald Ford, and wrote a biography of
the man.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   50 YEARS OF WINTERS
</P>
<P>
   If all you do is read the transcribed words of Jonathan Winters,
his humor can't be fully appreciated. It's all in the eyes and
mouth, the little ticks and twinkles that sell the joke.
</P>
<P>
   Winters _ the performer who once inspired a young comic named
Robin Williams _ will be featured in ``Jonathan Winters: On the
Loose,'' a PBS special airing in August. With nearly 50 years of
material to choose from, the documentary mines a wealth of
television clips, particularly from ``The Jack Paar Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The man known for a dizzying array of characters (most notably
the dizzy old lady Maude Frickert) also talks about his emotional
problems and nervous breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was classic manic-depressive, and now considered bipolar _
and I haven't been to either pole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
