<P>
   SCI-AIDS (Durban, South Africa) _ Developments as the 13th
International AIDS Conference concludes. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MISSILE-TEST (Undated) _ Experts say the recent failures in
the U.S. antimissile defense system are growing pains typical of
ambitious rocket projects and do not mean that it cannot be fixed
to meet the testing goals. Whether it will work as a real missile
defense is another question. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-DELAYS (Undated) _ Last summer was the worst on record
for airline delays, and this summer is shaping up to be even worse,
with delays in June up 16.5 percent over last year. By Laurence
Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DOTCOM-ENTREPRENEURS (Beijing) _ Hundreds of millions of
U.S. investment dollars have fattened the bank accounts of China's
young Internet entrepreneurs in the last nine months, making
dot-com companies the most vibrant part of the country's fledgling
private sector. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SOGO (Tokyo) _ Japan's finance minister said that the
bankruptcy of Sogo Corp., a department store operator, and its
aftermath will not derail the economy, but some central bank
officials suggest that they may decide against raising interest
rates at their policy board meeting on Monday. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   PLAYGROUNDS-DESIGN (Undated) _ Just as a society's ideas about
nature can be read in the character of its parks, and its beliefs
about education are often written in the look of its schools, the
attitudes of Americans toward children's play can be traced in the
changing face of public playgrounds. By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENTAL-IMPERIALISM (Undated) _ Portraying
environmentalists as latter-day missionaries of a new universal
truth, many anthropologists see Third World conservation as a form
of neocolonialism, the latest attempt by wealthy Westerners to move
into poor, tropical countries and tell the local residents what
they should and should not do with their land. By Alexander Stille.
</P>
<P>
   GUERNICA-DOCUMENTARY (Guernica, Spain) _ It's hard to imagine
the scene as it was here some 60 years ago, when one of the first
major atrocities of World War II took place. A new documentary
film, ``The Bombing of Guernica: The Mark of Men,'' produced by a
peace research center here, includes the voices of the people who
survived the Luftwaffe attack. By Herbert Mitgang.
</P>
