<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LOTTERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS REVAMPS LOTTO TO BOOST SAGGING SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CARMINA DANINI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ After nearly eight years, picking six numbers
between 1 and 50 for a ticket to millions of dollars will end
Saturday night for Lotto Texas players.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sunday, tickets for the twice-weekly game will have
players selecting from a field of 54 numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the jackpots will still start at $4 million, lottery
officials say accumulated jackpots will be higher than before.
</P>
<P>
   Because the odds of winning will be increased from 1 in 15.8
million to 1 in 25.8 million, there should be fewer winners. That
means jackpots should accumulate over a greater number of drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Lottery Commission members unanimously approved the
changes at their monthly meeting in May.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the changes could bring $166 million more in
annual sales and add $26 million more to the Foundation School
Fund, which provides money for education in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Old play slips will not operate in terminals after Saturday. New
play slips will be available Sunday for Wednesday's drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Players will see other changes in addition to having to select
from 54 numbers. Anyone matching five of six numbers will win
$2,500 instead of the current $1,500, while players matching four
of six will receive $105 instead of $100. Matching three of six
will increase to $5 from $3.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of four numbers is the first significant change to
Lotto Texas since it was introduced in November 1992 with starting
jackpots of $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials said the latest modifications were necessary
because of the decline in sales since 1997. Larger jackpots are
expected to increase ticket sales and attract players who yawn at
payoffs of less than $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   The average jackpot in 1999 was $11.39 million; average weekly
sales were $12.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think players will like this very much because the higher
the jackpot, the higher the interest,'' lottery spokeswoman Leticia
Vasquez said. ``There's a lot of excitement out there, and
aficionados are going to find that the game is better than it used
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Dawn Nettles, publisher of ``Lotto Report,''
available on the World Wide Web and at retailers in the Dallas-Fort
Worth area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to work,'' Nettles said Wednesday. ``Players
have already backed off and quit in disgust because they never win
anything. The other half that hasn't yet will, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Nettles, who urged the three-member lottery commission in May to
vote against the change to 54 balls, said she no longer plays Lotto
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to play $15 every drawing, but now I'll just play Cash
5 and Pick 3,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sanchez, who shared an $18.4 million in May 1995 with nine
coworkers, said he would continue to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like everything else, it's luck, so I'll still play,'' said
Sanchez, who retired from Alamo Iron Works in San Antonio four
years ago and spends $5 to $10 on Lotto Texas tickets per drawing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
