<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOP TURNS UP HEAT ON HILLARY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Attacks in the U.S. Senate campaign are
escalating as Democratic candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton finds
herself described as a ``polarizing and power-hungry'' politician
who ``isn't telling it straight'' about her opponent's health care
record.
</P>
<P>
   A television advertisement released Thursday by her rival,
Republican Rep. Rick Lazio, and a fund-raising letter from the
state Republican Committee turned up the heat in the campaign
against the first lady, who condemned the negativity and pledged to
focus on issues.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second advertisement from Lazio's campaign marked the
softer of the two attacks on Clinton. In it, a woman speaks to the
camera to defend Lazio's congressional voting record on health care
bills _ a focal point of Clinton's own campaign strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame, but Mrs. Clinton's campaign isn't telling it
straight about Rick Lazio and health care,'' the woman says in the
ad. ``... Rick voted for a Patients' Bill of Rights and Rick just
helped pass new legislation to help seniors afford their
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do I care so much about health care? I'm a registered
nurse. And how do I know so much about Rick Lazio? He's my
husband,'' says the woman, Patricia Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio voted against a bipartisan measure popularly known as the
Patients' Bill of Rights that aims to protect patients from
receiving substandard care from managed-care companies. Lazio voted
for a competing bill that basically aimed to provide health
coverage for uninsured workers _ which he says is a better
protection for New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   The assault by state GOP Chairman Bill Powers was more pointed.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising letter, sent to ``common-sense conservatives''
nationwide, calls Clinton ``abrasive and annoying, brash and
bitter, calculating and scheming, distant and deceitful, polarizing
and power hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers stood by the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole country knows the Clintons will do and say anything
to win and we also all know she's only using New York as a stepping
stone to the White House,'' Powers said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, campaigning in New York City, responded: ``I guess this
is going to be their strategy, to hurl insults instead of talk
about issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
