a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      07-14 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAY I ASK, IS THERE A GUN AT HOME? 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   An Indiana mother and doctor who
is worried about kids and guns proposed an intriguing idea on
National Public Radio. She thinks parents ought to ask their
friends and neighbors if they keep guns in the house.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her reasoning is sound. Parents have a general right to be nosy
where their kids are concerned, and usually they don't hold back.
We have no trouble asking if there is a fence around the swimming
pool where our child goes to play. Or if the dog's a biter and if
there's a parent at home after school. Parents make pretty good
sleuths. We can tell you which households allow diet sodas, Barbie
dolls and too much TV.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you ask about guns?
</P>
<P>
   How about: ``I was wondering if you keep a gun at your house. I
worry about kids and guns and just want to make sure there's no way
my little Evan can get his hands on one.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a horribly important and relevant question, one most
parents would understand. So, why does it make us squirm?
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns? I still don't know how to ask another mom if she
believes in video games,'' says the mother of a kindergartner.
</P>
<P>
   It's just too personal, she says. She could ask about guns at a
day care center, but she couldn't of a friend or neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Why are we shy about guns? We're only speculating about the
impact of video games and TV shows on children. But we know for
sure what happens when real guns and kids get together.
</P>
<P>
   If we knew the neighbor kept a pet python we wouldn't be afraid
to ask if it was in its cage when the kids were around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns are up there with politics and religion,'' says one
father. He doesn't own a gun but his sister, who works in law
enforcement, does. The two also part on the matter of toy guns for
their children. ``It's one of those subjects you don't bring up if
you know you're going to disagree,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   An open and neighborly discussion about guns and gun safety
would certainly advance the issue more than Congress or any
presidential candidate has. There really is no enemy. The motive is
not to out the gun owners of America, make them put little decals
on their front windows saying ``Gun in house.'' We just want to
keep kids from killing themselves and each other.
</P>
<P>
   Still, we balk because we have these prejudices. If you ask
someone about their swimming pool it's not a judgment thing. But if
you ask if they keep guns it feels accusatory.
</P>
<P>
   In communities where hunting and guns are commonplace, you could
probably bring up the subject naturally. It's different in
suburbia. You don't think about guns and suburbia. Yet, that's
where gun sales are up. Somebody's got to have them.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know who has a gun in your circle of friends? I don't.
</P>
<P>
   Another mother, who has a four-year-old, says, ``I know the
houses where my son goes to play. I assume his friends' parents are
like us. I feel we're aligned in our thinking. I don't have a gun
and so I naturally expect they don't either. But that may not be
true.''
</P>
<P>
   You also want to be able to trust another parent to keep your
child safe. And that's true whether or not they have a pistol in
the shoe box on the top shelf.
</P>
<P>
   This woman's son returned one day from visiting a neighbor's and
said he didn't want to go back because the other children were
playing ``Army,'' and as he told his mother, ``We don't do that in
our family.'' The mother's in a quandary because in explaining her
son's discomfort to the other family she doesn't want to sound like
she's insulting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to talk to them about it but I don't want to get into
a big NRA discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   The national debate over gun control has made everyone jumpy and
both sides have become so demonized by the other that it's hard to
get any serious discussion going. Yet, in between the adamant
anti-gun people and passionate pro-gun people are a lot of others
who must be capable of discussing guns without feeling personally
attacked.
</P>
<P>
   You'd like to think that if a gun owner were asked to assure
well-meaning parents that his weapons were safe from their child he
would. As well, you'd like to think that if a family found out
their well-meaning neighbor owned a gun, they wouldn't consider his
house a bad risk.
</P>
<P>
   As for parents not wanting to ask embarrassing questions on
behalf of their kids, get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
