<P>
   PROFESSOR-PAY _The pay of college professors in Southern schools
is falling further behind that of their national collegues, but
Georgia has been an exception, accoridng to a 10-year study by the
Southern Regional Education Board. Georgia professor salaries at
four-year schools were only $700 below the national average during
the 1998-99 school year, thanks to a four-year run of 6 percent pay
hikes during Gov. Zell Miller's final term. The SREB study says
faculty salaries have not grown as rapidly as those of other
workers with advanced degrees in the past 10 years. (Salzer,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MILLION-MARCH _ WASHINGTON _ Louis Farrakhan, leader of the
Nation of Islam, holds a news conference to discuss his call for
one million families to assemble on Oct. 16 on the National Mall to
observe the fifth anniversary of the Million Man march. (Dart, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS _ WASHINGTON Voters are more disengaged in the
presidential race this year than at any time in recent history,
according to a poll released Friday by the non-partisan Pew
Research Center. It could be an indication that turnout may be
lower than it was in 1996, when only 49 percent of eligible
citizens cast ballots, the first time in more than 70 years that
less than half of voters went to the polls. Yet despite voter
apathy, Americans say they are more satisified with their choice of
presidential candidates this year and they are less critical of the
way the campaigns are being conducted, the survey found. The poll
concluded that the race between Democrat Al Gore and Republican
George W. Bush remains wide open as each candidate heads to his
party's nominating conventions next month. (Holmes, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIANS _ Final arguments underway Friday morning in the
Branch Davidians' civil case. The ``advisory jury'' is expected to
begin deliberations this afternoon. Judge has determined the jury
decision will be issued as soon as deliberations are complete.
However, U.S. District Judge Walter Smith's ruling _ which is the
only one that matters _ will be not be issued until later in August
after he considers separately the issue of whether FBI agents shot
at the Davidians during the fire. (Witherspoon, Waco
Tribune-Herald)
</P>
