<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR WHOM THE BRIDGE TOLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Golden Gate Bridge's new FasTrak system got
off on the slow track Thursday morning. Guys were handing out
brochures explaining how to sign up for the electronic toll system,
which was nice, but it caused a bit of a traffic backup.
</P>
<P>
   I was taken aback by some of the fine print in the brochure,
which was harder to read than the average VCR manual.
</P>
<P>
   One clause stood out: ``You agree to . . . obey all traffic laws
and regulations. . . . You also agree to obey all posted speed
limits on all FasTrak toll facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Agree to obey the speed limits? This will be hard for some folks
who drive the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   That clause may be important. According to Mary Currie of the
Golden Gate Bridge District, FasTrak transponders have the
capability to record who is speeding on the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Hint: They're all driving SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   However, the transponders can't be used to nail speeders without
legislative approval, and that may be hard to get. You know how
fast legislators want to get to San Francisco from Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Another Big Brother question: Will transponder records be used
against people like cell phone records and e-mail? ``John Doe
claims he spent the whole weekend in Novato, but his transponder
says he went to San Francisco Saturday night.''
</P>
<P>
   John Doe should pay cash, or the bridge will toll for him.
</P>
<P>
   On a personal note, I hope all the Golden Gate Bridge toll
takers come through this OK. They are the greatest people in the
world, at least in three-second interactions. Transponders can't
smile and make your morning.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   In other sports news, golfers are upset because Stanford wants
to get rid of the first hole at the Stanford Golf Course to build
student and faculty housing. What is the controversy here? Is this
a university or a country club?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's both. But what's wrong with losing just one hole?
Golfers still will have 17 left. They shave strokes. They can shave
holes, too.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   All morning Thursday CNN was rerunning the video of a dozen
Philadelphia cops kicking and hitting a suspect. What a mess. The
cops were kicking and shoving each other in order to get at the
guy. No wonder he got away the first time the cops tried to pin him
down.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Philly cops kick and beat a guy who shot one of their
own, bit another and stole a police car? Yes, people are actually
asking that question.
</P>
<P>
   One city official said it wasn't anything like the Rodney King
case because black and white cops both piled on this guy. It was an
equal opportunity melee, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   The real question is how dumb these cops were to let a suspect
get away, steal a squad car and maybe a cop's gun _ and then go
berserk while a news helicopter was overhead.
</P>
<P>
   When you hear rotors, guys, smile and say cheese steak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
