<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1967 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-LEWIS-BOS &LR;      07-14 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THIS ERA, LEWIS IS RIGHT AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The man of war is at peace now.
</P>
<P>
   In less than 48 hours, Lennox Lewis will defend the undisputed
heavyweight title in his hometown, his first appearance in a London
boxing ring since he lost a portion of that title to one right hand
from a footnote in history named Oliver McCall.
</P>
<P>
   He will fight for the last time in front of a less-than-packed
house at the London Arena, a baffling situation considering it has
been more than 100 years since a son of England held the undisputed
title. Yet while his manager, Frank Maloney, vents, and his
promoter, Panos Eliades, frets over the way his fighter is viewed
in his own land, Lennox Lewis remains a sea of calm.
</P>
<P>
   Though arguably the greatest heavyweight in English history, his
popularity is dwarfed still by great British losers such as Henry
Cooper and Frank Bruno, men who fought with honor but without
anywhere near the ability, dominance or success of Lewis. Still,
English fight fans remain diffident toward Lewis, an odd contrast
to the mania in the streets just six months ago when Mike Tyson
first appeared in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   At 35, Lewis has little time left to make his point to his own
people and has apparently given up trying. He knows, it seems, what
few fighters ever realize. He knows his strength must come from
within . . . and so it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this era, Lennox Lewis reigns supreme,'' the World Boxing
Council, International Boxing Federation, and International Boxing
Association title holder said several days before Saturday's fight
with Frans Botha. ``In the past era, Muhammad Ali reigned supreme.
Joe Louis reigned supreme. Each era brings along a different boxer
who stands out. I believe I stand out in this era. (Evander)
Holyfield and Tyson stand out for different reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice the conqueror of Holyfield, although their first fight was
declared a controversial draw, Lewis believes Holyfield's place
comes from his skill, heart, and dominance of a big man's sport
despite having a small man's body. Tyson's place, he says, is
obvious, but it has less to do with his boxing skill than with the
public nightmare of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis's place, however, is with Dempsey and Louis and Ali,
because ``I'm a big heavyweight in an era of big heavyweights who
has done what I've done and made it look easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to elaborate where he ranks among today's heavyweights,
the champion hesitated not for a moment. ``Head and shoulders
above,'' he said. ``Definitely head and shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   While many still feel Lewis has never become the fighter his
trainer, Emanuel Steward, believes he could be, no one can deny
Lewis is a two-time heavyweight champion and the undisputed
title-holder, despite a World Boxing Association decision to take
its title from him for political and business reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In his last outing, he destroyed a vastly overrated Michael
Grant in two rounds only because there was a brave referee in the
ring who let the fight go that long. He has twice handled Holyfield
with relative ease, the smaller man's size being as much of a
factor as Lewis's skills.
</P>
<P>
   As Lewis is content to accept, he is what he is. And as John L.
Sullivan once boasted, Lewis believes he's a guy who can lick
anyone in the house (as Sullivan once announced in a Boston bar),
although Lewis would never mention that in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think like that because I know that,'' Lewis said.
``I'm a professional fighter. In the ring that's what I believe,
but I don't need to say it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my moment in time. There is nobody out there who can
match my skills. The proper matchup would have been with Riddick
Bowe, but he fell by the wayside.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowe had been Lewis's rival since the gold- medal fight at the
Seoul Olympics in 1988. Lewis dominated that day and believed he
would again after Bowe first won the heavyweight title from
Holyfield in the best fight of his life. But from that moment, Bowe
began to dissipate, mostly from his own mishandling of his training
and his approach to life.
</P>
<P>
   Bowe's career fell far short of the promise it once held for
both men, the promise of several titanic matchups between two huge
heavyweights of similar skills. That those fights never happened,
Lewis believes, robbed him of his place in history in the eyes of
his critics, but it also proved what he had always knew about
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said I'd be the last man standing,'' Lewis said.
``It's come to that. Once I would have said Holyfield would give me
a tough fight but he wasn't big enough. Look at all the big guys.
Grant wasn't tough enough. Tyson? I look at Tyson as a has-been
who's a few bricks shy of a load. He's plateaued off. His best days
are really gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing he's got to contend with is his name and his
power. The only way he could hurt me is if I stuck my chin out, and
he definitely could hit it and hurt me. But I'm a pugilist
specialist.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no such thing would happen with Tyson, and hence
the Big Man would beat down the little man and destroy him the way
George Foreman did to Joe Frazier when it was first Foreman's time.
</P>
<P>
   As for the mythical matchup with Bowe, who is believed to have
brain damage, Lewis looks at the tatters of a fallen champion and
sees what he says the world did not when the two were rivals. He
sees now what would have beaten Bowe even then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was mentally stronger,'' Lewis said. ``I knew I was
physically stronger as well. He may have been a better technical
boxer at the time because he grew up in New York and sparred with
pros when he was an amateur and he had a great trainer (Eddie
Futch), but I would have beaten him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel cheated I wasn't able to knock some of the stuffing
out of him. Riddick Bowe insulted me a couple times. I definitely
wanted him in the ring but every time he insulted me there were
1,000 people to stop us. Rock Newman (Bowe's manager) did a great
job keeping him away and blowing smoke signals saying I didn't want
to fight him.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, a contented man revealed for a brief moment a
light side which, if seen more often both here and abroad, might
well have made him a more popular champion. He was asked what he
had learned from Bowe's sad fall, and without hesitation replied,
``It's very important not to keep a frig in the (bed)room. I'm more
seriously inclined then he was. He was a big kid.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a reference to Bowe's horrible training habits, laziness,
and weight problems, which combined to bring him down before Lewis
had the chance to put him down. But unknowingly, it was also a
reference to the fact Lewis is the heavyweight champion of his era
because he has survived all challengers. He is, as he said, the
last man standing, a man with no real challenge ahead before his
era ends.
</P>
<P>
   And when it does, Steward believes, Lennox Lewis may not leave
as the people's champion even in his own country, but he will leave
as something more important than that. He will leave a contented
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox, you have to understand, has complete internal peace,''
Steward said. ``He has no demons. Lennox genuinely believes he
never dodged anybody who was willing to meet him. Only the guys who
threw away championship belts to avoid him (Bowe and Tyson) have
escaped, and that in itself is fulfilling because it showed him
their fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox will never place himself in a position of getting back
in the ring to take a terrible beating the way Joe Louis did
against Rocky Marciano, the way Ali did against Larry Holmes or
(Sugar) Ray (Leonard) did against Terry Norris and Hector Camacho.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he goes, he'll be gone and he'll remain gone. And history
will be kind in its judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as kind, if not more so, than the champion will be in his
own judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely in my place in history,'' Lewis said. ``I've
accomplished my goals and aspirations and I still have my
faculties. I may be a little scathed, but I'm unmarked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
