<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS ARE THE FORGOTTEN TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim McCarver readily admits he made a mistake. The Fox baseball
analyst ``somehow'' forgot to mention the Toronto Blue Jays when he
predicted at the beginning of the season that the American League
East would be a close race between the Yankees and Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meant to include the Blue Jays,'' he deadpanned. ``I knew
they would be good and they actually looked better last year. But
now they look like they will be a force to contend with in the AL
East.''
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight is always better. But McCarver is still sticking with
the Red Sox to make the AL East a two-way, err, a three-way race
with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Sox aren't going away,'' McCarver said. ``They didn't
age overnight. They still are potentially a better team than last
year. There's too much baseball left to play to rule out any of
those teams.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarver will call Saturday's Red Sox game against the New York
Mets. Though Ramon Martinez is pitching, McCarver's question is
about his brother. ``How's Pedro?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   McCarver said that Pedro ``fuels so many other elements of the
team's offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The big story is the return of Mike Piazza. McCarver said that
the Mets catcher will be able to shake off the cobwebs from a Roger
Clemens pitch that hit Piazza's head. McCarver was more concerned
by the effect all the hoopla will have on Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside pitching has been a sensitive issue for as long as I
can remember,'' McCarver said. ``All the great ones were accused _
Bob Gibson, Gaylord Perry, Don Drysdale. And the story wasn't blown
out of proportion. It deserved coverage because it was Clemens and
Piazza. But if I'm Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees pitching coach, I'd
tell Clemens to pitch inside right away. If Clemens doesn't come
right back in there, like he should and is his right, then he will
give hitters a tremendous advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarver said he didn't want to get into whether Clemens
intentionally hit Piazza. ``The bigger issue is whether Clemens can
get back up there and throw inside. He should not be deterred
because that side of the plate is as much his as it is the
hitters'. The problem has become incendiary because not enough
pitchers do it. You show me a pitcher who doesn't pitch inside and
I'll show you a loser.''
</P>
<P>
   Just for the record, Pedro Martinez has hit 11 batters this
season, Clemens six.
</P>
<P>
   McCarver said that he has seen Ramon Martinez pitch twice
against the Yankees and he has looked good each time. ``His arm
won't allow him to do the things that he did when he was with the
Dodgers,'' McCarver said. ``But he is intelligent enough to make
the changes. He has lowered his sights a little and is not throwing
the high riding fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarver said he doesn't believe in the Curse of the Bambino.
``The fact of the matter is that (the Red Sox) haven't won since
1918,'' McCarver said. ``I don't believe in all of that curse
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 1986 World Series loss to the Mets made him rethink his
reliance on facts. ``I was in the box with Nelson Doubleday, the
owner of the Mets, and was shaking his hand congratulating him on
the Series and telling him that maybe in a year or two the Mets
could win the whole thing and then Buckner flubs the ball,''
McCarver said. ``I just couldn't figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
McDonough retires
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will McDonough, the Boston Globe sports columnist and former NFL
analyst with CBS and NBC, has retired from the Globe. McDonough was
a member of management and subject to the company's policy of
mandatory retirement at age 65. It is expected that McDonough will
still write for the Globe from time to time. . . . ESPN's coverage
of the All-Star Game's Home Run Derby dropped 24 percent in
television ratings. Monday night's slugfest earned a 5.73 cable
rating, down from last year's 7.51 rating. The All-Star Game also
suffered from the lack of big-name players. Ratings dropped 16
percent to 10.1 and 18 share. The game still was the most-watched
prime time program. Boston viewers gave NBC an 11.8 rating and 21
share.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's Miller time
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When ABC hired Dennis Miller to be an analyst on ``Monday Night
Football'', no one expected HBO to receive as much free advertising
as it did. Everything from newspaper stories and the cover of
Sports Illustrated blared Miller's and HBO's name.
</P>
<P>
   It's now getting even better for HBO.
</P>
<P>
   HBO brass told reporters this week that Miller will be free to
plug his HBO show on the air at ABC.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-promotion was part of the deal between HBO and ABC.
HBO had exclusive TV dibs on Miller for HBO's ``The Dennis Miller
Show.'' Chris Albrecht, HBO's president of original programming,
said he received assurances from the ``highest levels'' that
Miller's HBO talker would be plugged. An ABC Sports spokesman said
that the plugging will be confined to identifying Miller as an HBO
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt this was a great opportunity for Dennis,'' Albrecht
said. ``When was the last time you saw Dennis on the cover of
Sports Illustrated?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
