<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S APPLET PICKING TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: A friend somehow entered a Web site that took
over his Internet Explorer 5, locking him into a revolving series
of pornographic sites. Closing one window opened another.
Additionally, the IE5 toolbar was hidden in all browser windows.
Opening another browser window simply loaded the original porno
site and began the chain of sites again. _ Vicious Cycle
</P>
<P>
   Dear Vicious: Gee, it's difficult to imagine that a smut peddler
would resort to such devious behavior just to sell dirty pictures.
Most of the pornographers I hang out with are really swell guys.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who's been snookered into visiting a porn site knows
what you're talking about. The sites take over the browser and
won't turn it loose: You have no choice but to look at all those
naked pictures of Rosie O'Donnell, again and again. Scary thought,
isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Small programs called ``applets'' can be included in the Web
page source code, where most people would never think to look for
them. Some can change your home page without asking, others call up
new browser windows when you attempt to close a page, and some can
remove all the toolbars, menus and buttons so you're left with
nothing but a full-screen ad that you have no way to get rid of.
</P>
<P>
   You can fight back, though. When I get one of those full-screen
dealies, I hit Control-Alt-Delete to display the list of running
programs, then knock the offending one off. You may have to do that
a dozen times before you get rid of all the crud, though. You can
also try closing the windows as quickly as you can: Sometimes you
can catch them before the applet kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   The only real defense is to shut off your browser's ability to
run these little hand grenades. In the Security tab of IE5's
Internet Options, you can customize the settings by disabling
``active scripting'' and ``Java applets.'' There are similar
click-boxes in Netscape's preferences. Look under ``Advanced.''
</P>
<P>
   You can also try a program like AdSubtract (www.adsubtract.com)
that can block not only those nasty little scripts, but also the
banner ads that clutter up almost every page you look at these
days.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, if you turn off scripting, gizmos on nonporn pages
aren't going to work either. It's a small price to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: About two months ago, my well-behaved computer
started putting blank boxes in my task bar. I assume they indicated
closed programs, but how can I get them to not appear after the
programs are closed? _ Annoyed
</P>
<P>
   Dear Annoyed: Sorry, there's still no answer to this one. A few
months back, something _ and nobody has figured out what _ affected
thousands of Windows 98 machines. Maybe it was a Windows update,
maybe a new virus signature file, maybe some upgrade to something
that a lot of people use.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was, it causes little phantom buttons to remain on
the task bar after a program ends. You can click on them to make
them go away, but that's not really a solution.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect it's just another plot to make us run out and buy the
replacement for Windows 98, irritatingly named Windows Me, if it
ever makes it past quality control. Oh boy! A whole new set of
bugs! At least it's job security for me.
</P>
<P>
   (If it wasn't for Microsoft, Dr. Emilio Bombay probably would
have returned to the food-service industry years ago. Instead, he
offers occasionally accurate answers about most things electronic.
In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial systems
manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.You can write to him at
drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: 390-7257. Want fries with
that answer? Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
