<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-LIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY SOLUTION TO TOYSMART PRIVACY ISSUE QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walt Disney Co., majority owner of Toysmart.com, seemed to
emerge as a savior this week when it offered to buy and then
``retire'' the bankrupt online retailer's customer data.
</P>
<P>
   But privacy advocates are skeptical of Disney's plans. Some say
they fear Disney will somehow use the information it has
``retired.'' Others say Toysmart.com's customer files should die
with the company. Permitting the sale at all, they argue, would
send the message that failed Internet retailers can auction off
confidential data they had promised to keep in-house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Disney has the right intentions,'' said Dave Steer, a
spokesman for TRUSTe, a San Jose, Calif., company that offers a
privacy-seal program. ``But it sets a bad precedent for a knight in
shining armor to come in and save the day.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Federal Trade Commission sued the Waltham, Mass.
toy retailer in US District Court in Boston, attempting to block
the company from selling consumer information it had promised to
keep under wraps. Toysmart.com had put the data up for sale to help
satisfy creditors in bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The case has also attracted the attention of several lawmakers,
including US Representative William D. Delahunt, a Democrat of
Massachusetts, who have proposed legislation to protect the privacy
of customers of online retailers that break privacy promises.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's lawsuit pits the interests of privacy advocates
against those of creditors, who hope to get repaid from the sale of
Toysmart.com's assets. Internet customer data can command a high
price if it contains a large number of repeat buyers and extensive
information about their preferences, online retailers said.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Toysmart.com's attorneys have been trying to
negotiate a settlement with federal regulators in which the company
can sell the data to a family-oriented Web site. Any buyer must be
approved by a US bankruptcy judge in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates hope the courts will block the sale,
forcing online retailers to stick to their promises to the very
end.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's proposal, they said, offers a quick solution but does
not address the issue of what happens to valuable customer data
once a dot-com fails _ a problem that is expected to grow as Web
businesses face stronger competition and more investor scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a message that these online privacy policies have no
teeth,'' said Andrew Shen, a policy analyst with the Electronic
Privacy Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   Chis Kelley, an analyst with Forrester Research, noted that
Disney did not define ``retire,'' raising questions over its future
use. ``That's troublesome to me, and I'm sure, troublesome to
consumers,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   A Disney spokeswoman said the database would not be used and
customer confidentiality would be assured. But she would not say
whether customer files would be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone takes a hard line against the sale of customer
data. Robert Ellis Smith, publisher of the monthly newsletter
Privacy Journal in Rhode Island, said he sees nothing wrong with
selling customer information under certain restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Courts, he said, can require companies to contact all customers
and offer them the option to have their information deleted from
files.
</P>
<P>
   Catalog companies, retail chains and marketers routinely swap
and purchase customer lists. But privacy advocates are more alarmed
by the gathering of customer data on the Internet, which allows for
more extensive collection on individuals' shoppping preferences,
hobbies, and even ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most rudimentary e-commerce sites gather and store
information such as customers' names, e-mail addresses, home
addresses and purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Like other online retailers, Toysmart.com had asked customers to
provide personal information such as their children's names and
birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   But though Toysmart.com had received high ratings from
consumers, it did not manage to please its investors. The Web site
closed in May after Disney, which had invested $20 million in the
firm, pulled its support. A month later, Toysmart.com filed for
protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the US Bankruptcy
Code.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet merchant's plans to sell personal information
emerged shortly after its collapse. In June, the company advertised
the sale of its customer list and other assets in the Wall Street
Journal. Around the same time, several local retailers said they
received solicitations from Toysmart.com representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Few companies have rallied in Toysmart.com's support. Even the
Direct Marketing Association, which represents thousands of catalog
companies, online retailers and marketers, has shied away from
supporting the retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corporate entity is Toysmart, and Toysmart said it would
not share its list of customers,'' said Stephen Altobelli, a
spokesman for the industry group. ``Therefore, it should not.''
</P>
<P>
   Both off-line and online, consumers should assume that
information about their information has migrated to new and
unexpected places, specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Jeffrey Steinberg, chief marketing officer for
MotherNature.com, was working for NetGrocer.com when a failed
Internet grocer asked him if he'd like to purchase customer data,
he said. He said he passed because he believed the price was too
high.
</P>
<P>
   Recent failures like Toysmart.com, Boo.com and CraftShop.com
have attracted more attention because they have tried to sell
consumer information despite promises that they would not do so.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other Web sites display pages and pages of privacy
statements that seem to stump even company officials. Shoppers at
Reel.com, for example, are told that the online seller of
videotapes has a new relationship with Buy.com. That means Buy.com
has access to information on new Reel.com customers.
</P>
<P>
   Things get more muddled when it comes to Reel.com's old customer
list. Hollywood Entertainment Corp., Reel.com's parent company,
recently folded the ailing Internet retailer into its own
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Entertainment, owner of the Hollywood Video chain,
promises not look at Reel.com's customer data, company spokesman
Sean Mahoney said. But it reserves the right to send promotional
information to Reel.com, which can pass it on to its consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is ridiculous,'' analyst Kelley said. ``Basically, these
companies seem to be looking at ways to use this data.''
</P>
<P>
   One organization is especially displeased with the liberties
online retailers have taken. It's TRUSTe, which allows its Web
members to display privacy seals if they adhere to certain
guidelines. The industry watchdog alerted federal regulators to
Toysmart.com's situation and is taking a closer look at its
customer list, which also includes Reel.com and Boo.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is now on Toysmart,'' said TRUSTe's Steer.
``Undoubtedly, others will emerge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
