<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1981 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-XMEN-BOS &LR;      07-14 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-XMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`X-MEN' WITHOUT SOULS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
X-MEN 
Directed by: Bryan Singer 
Screenplay by: David Hayter 
Starring: Hugh Jackman, Patrick Stewart, Ian McKellen, Famke
Janssen, James Marsden, Halle Berry, Anna Paquin, Tyler Mane, Ray
Park, Rebecca Romijn-Stamos, Bruce Davison 
Running time: 96 minutes 
Rated: R (sci-fi action violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As ``Blade Runner'' wannabes go, ``X-Men'' is OK, but not much
more. It lacks the tragic grandeur and psychic punch to go with its
stygian visuals. Expecting more may be asking too much. It may be
unfair to find fault with a comic-book movie that stays only
comic-book deep, tries to get most of the details right, but
settles for a screenful of good mutants/bad mutants stuff. Still,
``Blade Runner'' showed us that the alienation forced on its
androids could imbue them with a tragic nobility. The pain and
alienation forced on the mutants in ``X-Men'' by a frightened
humanity that wants to outlaw them, apart from being a barely
veiled comment on bigotry and racism, takes them only as far as
basic good guy/bad guy stuff, but with better toys.
</P>
<P>
   After playing a few villains recently, Patrick Stewart shifts
back into his Picard mode to play psychic Xavier, the wise old
headmaster of the good mutants who decide to take the high road and
not retaliate against the humans who fear the mutants'
extraordinary powers. The film does a scrupulous job of
transferring to the screen the laser vision of Cyclops (James
Marsden), the meteorological clout of Storm (Halle Berry), the
telekinetic telepath of Jean Gray (Famke Janssen) whose powers are
second only to Xavier's, and the energy-transferring talents of
Rogue (Anna Paquin). In a powerful prologue out of ``Schindler's
List,'' we can at least understand why the bad mutant, Ian
McKellen's Magneto, isn't too keen on humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The plot's mainspring is Magneto's
let's-get-them-before-they-get-us policy. This involves making war
on so-called normal people, starting with Bruce Davison's
reactionary senator, who wants to pass laws clamping down on the
mutants and rendering them second-class citizens. Magneto's posse
consists of the brawny Sabretooth (Tyler Mane), the
retractable-tongued Toad (Ray Park), and the shape-changing
Mystique (Rebecca Romijn-Stamos). They're pretty evenly matched,
and the tech wizards have outdone themselves in giving shape to the
respective underground lairs _ sleekly metallic and rational in
Xavier's case, stonily elemental in Magneto's.
</P>
<P>
   Of more interest to fans will be the news that the designers
have earned their money when it came to fashioning Wolverine's
retractable metal alloy claws, Toad's whiplash cable tongue, and
Mystique's morphing abilities. There is an attempt to portray the
conflicts eating at Wolverine and Rogue. I wish there had been more
of one and that the film explored character more deeply. Certainly
the potential is there, and without this resonance, ``X-Men''
recedes to a string of mere action exploits. These are proficiently
executed but, for all their visual authority, not much more than
routine.
</P>
<P>
   The real imagination in ``X-Men'' lies in the conception of the
characters, and one can't help wishing that the film had taken more
of a stab at locating their souls as well as their various bags of
tricks. ``X-Men'' could have been a lot worse. But neither is it
the film it could have been _ an issue of ongoing relevance since
``X-Men'' ends by setting up a sequel with everything but a release
date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     07-14 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A LONG HAUL TO FAME FOR NAVRATILOVA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ The name Agnes Semanska does not appear in
Martina Navratilova's seemingly endless resume of victories across
the globe. ``But it's important,'' says Martina. ``It was my first
big one.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody watched or cared but the two of them. ``I was 11,''
Navratilova said. ``Anna Semanska was my dear grandmother. She had
been a very good player as a young woman, and had a win over Vera
Sukova, who would be a Wimbledon finalist (1962). When I finally
beat her, after a lot of trying, I thought I was pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty good,'' of course, became great _ the greatest in this
view. Her life has been a long-running drama on an
adventurously-traveled road. It wound from that crimson dirt patch
and the village of Revnice outside of Prague through all the major
championships (nine Wimbledons), the celebrated duels with Chris
Evert, castigation and non-personhood in her native Czechoslovakia,
and arrives at the doorstep of the International Tennis Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Navratilova will be anointed Saturday on the lawn of Newport's
Casino in the company of Australian Mal Anderson and another
American, Judge Robert Kelleher.
</P>
<P>
   They called the slim 6-foot-1-inch Anderson ``Cowboy.'' He not
only looked the part but was the genuine article. Coming off a
40,000-acre Queensland ranch, Mal was more at home on a horse than
the homemade tennis court his family built from the grit of
knocked-over termite mounds. After dealing with angry bulls and
being thrown from saddles, tennis was pretty tame. But he went at
it like a raging mustang (though with Gary Cooperish demeanor),
galloping to the net and volleying fiercely.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's was the style of two other Queensland ruralists
who've preceded him into the Hall _ Rod Laver and Roy Emerson _ and
made him the first to win the US Championship unseeded in 1957. His
path went through the 2-3-1 seeds Dick Savitt, Sven Davidson, and
countryman Ashley Cooper. Three months later, he led Australia to
the Davis Cup over the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But his best years were spent in the obscurity of the pro tour,
roaming with the distinguished outlaws who were banned from the
established circuit until open tennis dawned in 1968. Five years
after that, at 38, he helped the Aussies win another Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kelleher, a federal judge in Los Angeles over the last 30
years, was instrumental in the monumental 1968 breakthrough that
unified the game under the banner of tennis open to pros as well as
amateurs, and sent it skyrocketing. As one of the few enlightened
and visionary presidents of the US Tennis Association, he pushed
for opens, along with the British, against much opposition at home
and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   He was determined to make the inaugural US Open splashy by
offering an unheard-of pot, $ 100,000 total for all events. ``I
didn't know where we'd get the money,'' he said with a laugh,
recalling how poor the USTA was then. ``But I figured attendance
would go up, and TV would want to join in.'' He took a chance and
was right. Today the USTA, wealthy because of the Open, offers
$800,000 each as male and female first prize, an award that was
$14,000 and $6,000, respectively, in '68.
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher, a New Yorker with a New England education (Williams
plus Harvard Law) has played numerous roles in the game, among them
captaincy of the victorious US Davis Cup team in 1963, and winner
of several US titles in senior (over 45) tourneys.
</P>
<P>
   But for titles, and soap operatic twists and turns blending with
competitive verve, few, if any, Hall of Famer measures up to
Martina. Her bold defection from a police state, announced at
Forest Hills just prior to the US Open men's final of 1975,
upstaged Manolo Orantes's huge upset of Jimmy Connors.
</P>
<P>
   For years she was condemned for becoming ``Americanized,''
regarded as nonexistent, her results unpublished in the Communist
land. Nevertheless, Martina went at tennis and life in a headfirst
rush, unafraid to be herself. ``I had to escape Czechoslovakia and
that control to fulfill myself as a player and person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As the ``great wide hope,'' she nearly ate herself out of
business _ then flip-flopped in the pursuit of super-fitness that
set the standard for the women on tour today. Her loves, tabloid
fodder, were never secret. She refused to hide her sexual nature, a
stance that was costly in lost commercial endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   But Martina, the lefty with racket and unconservative outlook,
keeps charging, serving-and-volleying excitingly. On and off the
court. As recently as last week, she was daringly holding her own
in a sweet, brief reprise at her beloved Wimbledon. Attaining the
quarterfinals in doubles, she represented, at 43, more years than
her foes combined: Venus (20) and Serena (18) Williams.
Nevertheless, Martina and Mariaan de Swardt prodded the champs in
their toughest match, taking the only set the Sisters lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something to be on the same court,'' said Venus of the
remarkable tableau. ``Martina still has faster hands than Serena or
me.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be more such cameos from Martina. ``I found I could
still handle myself out there, not be embarrassed _ and it was
marvelous fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In the matter of numbers, Navratilova's cover several pages,
detailing the most acquisitive of all professional careers, one
that began in 1973 and supposedly ended in '94. Unimaginable are
her record 167 singles titles (1,438 match wins), 162 doubles
titles (and 8 mixed). Overall this most consummate champ won 56
majors (18 singles, 31 doubles, 7 mixed).
</P>
<P>
   All right, was there one that meant the most?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first Wimbledon in 1978,'' she said. ``There's nothing
like the first. I was losing to Chrissie (Evert), down a set and
4-2, and she hit me in the head with a passing shot. I'd been
playing in a daze of my first Wimbledon final, but that seemed to
wake me up, and I won (2-6, 6-4, 7-5).''
</P>
<P>
   They paused, both laughing at the beanballing, but Evert
remembers, ``It went downhill for me after that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We played four more Wimbledon finals,'' says Martina. She won
them all, eye-catchers in the tapestry of the game's most
intriguing rivalry, 80 engagements, Martina finally ahead of her
good friend, 43-37.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martina was overweight but eager and gifted when we first met
in '73,'' recalls Evert, who entered the Hall in 1997. ``I was
beating her most of the time, but then she went on the fitness kick
and caught up. She forced me to do the same. We brought out the
best in each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her staggering success, Martina missed out on a Grand
Slam. She came closest in 1984, upset in the semis of the
Australian, last of the four majors that year. In a match of
curious connections, she fell to Helena Sukova, who had ballgirled
for her at tourneys in Prague. Helena is the daughter of a
Wimbledon finalist, Vera Sukova, a woman once beaten by Anna
Semanska, the grandmother who was Martina's ``first important
victim.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
