A2005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-     07-14 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ SET TO PITCH FOR MICKEY D'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Making the transition from pitcher to pitchman, Red Sox Pedro
Martinez is set to appear in new McDonald's TV ads that feature
99-cent double cheeseburgers, sight gags, and a new strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the ads to air in two versions, one with an
English voiceover, the other with a Spanish voiceover.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the ad is to introduce a ``new everyday value''
strategy to the eastern New England market, says Bill Connell, vice
president of the Boston office of ad agency Leo Burnett. The
office's client is Mac Inc. Co-op, a marketing cooperative of
McDonald's franchisees in eastern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Past ads from Mac Inc. have often talked up a number of
different short-term promotions, such as Happy Meals and Extra
Value Meals.
</P>
<P>
   With a single, long-term focus on the 99-cent double
cheeseburger, the new marketing strategy aims to be simple and
direct, says Sid Boorstein, the president of Mac Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show we have a definable everyday value proposition
for the consumer that is clear and consistent,'' says Boorstein,
who notes that the double-cheeseburger promotion could last six
months or more.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is the first for Mac Inc. from Leo Burnett. Previous ads
were created by Arnold Communications of Boston, and over the years
Mac Inc.'s ads have used such local sports stars as Larry Bird and
Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers often see two sets of ads for McDonald's. One
originates from McDonald's headquarters in Illinois and generally
focuses on branding. Then, in regional markets, franchisees often
band together to form cooperatives such as Mac Inc. that sponsor
separate ad campaigns. In many cases, ads from the cooperatives are
highly promotional.
</P>
<P>
   The Martinez ad uses McDonald's new national tagline, ``We love
to see you smile,'' which debuted last month and which replaces,
``Did somebody say McDonald's?''
</P>
<P>
   According to Connell, the local ad was carefully scripted so
Martinez wouldn't be forced to cross the picket line of the Screen
Actors Guild and the American Federation of Television and Radio
Artists, whose members are striking over pay.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Nomar Garciaparra of the Red Sox chose to honor the
strike and delay plans for taping an ad for Dunkin' Donuts, says a
spokesman for Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos of Boston, the ad
agency for the chain.
</P>
<P>
   In the new McDonald's spot starring Martinez, two young men are
attempting to watch the Red Sox game on TV, but the reception is
awful. One of the men gets up from the couch to adjust the TV's
rabbit-ears antenna. After trial and error, the antenna is twisted
into the shape of McDonald's signature Golden Arches, and suddenly
the reception is picture perfect, showing images of Martinez on the
mound, playing ball and smiling.
</P>
<P>
   All images of Martinez were stock footage taken from the
archives of Major League Baseball, Connell says; as a result,
Martinez never had to cross the actors' picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very sensitive to Pedro's position,'' Connell says.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the antenna seems to have become a popular prop in
local ads this summer.
</P>
<P>
   A recent TV ad for FleetBoston Financial has a girl trying to
tune in the ball game by using tin foil and a coat hanger to help
the antenna on her radio pull down the Red Sox signal. That ad was
created by Hill Holliday, and when the signal comes in, viewers
hear a radio announcer excitedly describing a homer just hit by
Garciaparra, who is never seen during the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Connell says he was unaware of the FleetBoston ad.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent TV ad from FleetBoston chronicles a Dominican boy
who idolizes Martinez. The only images of Martinez seen in the ad
are from newspaper clippings tacked up in the boy's room.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's franchisees presumably could use a boost that a
strong TV ad starring Martinez might give them. After many of them
invested heavily in new computerized equipment and vowed to upgrade
service, there was hope for big sales gains.
</P>
<P>
   But the marketplace has been intensely competitive. On the
fast-food side, rival Burger King has sought to take business away
from McDonald's with an aggressive Pokemon promotion, and with the
economy booming some consumers are opting to trade up from
fast-food fare to casual restaurants such as Chili's and the Olive
Garden, according to recently published reports.
</P>
<P>
   Boorstein remains confident that improvements at McDonald's
coupled with the new local ad campaign will pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited,'' he says of the new Martinez ad. ``And if the
Red Sox start winning, it will be even better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
