<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2007 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MEDIA-FAILURE-BOS &LR;      07-14 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-FAILURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE MAGAZINE TO CHRONICLE THOSE WHO DIDN'T MAKE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   As an idea, failure was sitting there like a hanging curve, too
sweet to ignore in this Age of Tremendousness, when life is gauged
in SUVs and stock options. Someone was bound to take a poke at it.
Jason Zasky turns out to be the guy.
</P>
<P>
   Zasky, a survivor of three defunct music magazines, was walking
in Manhattan a few years ago with his cousin, Fred Stesney, when
Stesney stopped and said: ``I have a great idea for a magazine _
failure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great idea,'' agreed Zasky.
</P>
<P>
   Cousins talk like that.
</P>
<P>
   Zasky ran with the concept all the way to Failure Magazine, an
online monthly publication that will surface next Monday at
Failuremag.com. As its editor and chief executive, he is convinced
he is on to something huge. Then again, so did the guy behind the
Edsel.
</P>
<P>
   But if, as the geek savants tell us, branding is key on the
Internet, then Failure just might have a chance. It is quirky
enough to survive a limited run on novelty alone. After that, it's
a crapshoot.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Failure is exquisitely against the grain. This is
critical to a new player that must rise above the fray to survive.
Also, failure is the key ingredient of schadenfreude, our reflexive
instinct to rejoice in the misfortune of others. Schadenfreude
makes the world go around.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Zasky and his partner, Kathleen Ervin, who runs the
marketing arm, have cheek and understand the big sell. Their
T-shirts reading ``Failure _ It's An Option'' could give the
ubiquitous Black Dog logo a run for its money at Starbucks. And
their press kits are swell.
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule, kits from companies trolling for stories land
on reporters' desks like flying fish _ sleek, shiny things that
come out of nowhere and are summarily thrown away. The one from
Failure consists of a black mesh wastebasket in the bottom of which
lies a crumpled piece of paper that happened to be its press
release. Smart.
</P>
<P>
   No one has a clue at this point who will read Failure. Ervin,
34, claims the core audience will be men and women, ages 20 to 40,
with an emphasis on men. Zasky, 30, thinks the gender split will be
even. Either way, there will be what Ervin calls ``the car-crash
people'' _ the group of failure addicts for whom the magazine will
be a little bit of heaven on earth. ``They're the ones who just
want to see the wreck when they drive by,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin and Zasky are quick to point out that interest in failure
transcends morbid curiosity. It is has similar DNA to risk _ a
hazard of life lionized at Outward Bound and Goldman Sachs for
character-building and reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about people who want to suck the marrow out of
life,'' Erwin said about her audience. ``If you're not failing then
you're not really trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true marketeer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are interested in failure because they're obsessed with
success,'' Zasky added from Failure headquarters, a three-story
house in a residential section of Scarsdale, N.Y. ``They don't want
to make the same mistakes other people have made. It's particularly
hot now with all of these Internet companies going under. Failure
is as inevitable as death and taxes. The subject always has and
always will fascinate us.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, how does he sustain a magazine on the same dark
theme? Are we really a society of car-crash people? Why won't
Failure end up as fodder for its own Web site?
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure is not just a a simple black-and-white issue,'' said
Zasky, who played guitar in Black Velvet Flag, named Best Unsigned
Band in Rolling Stone's 1995 critics poll. ``If we simply recount
failures, we'd get boring and old very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   What does that mean? It means that intriguing failure plays,
dumb failure doesn't. Nor will failure-on-the-road-to-success
stories that read like Fast Company magazine. Zasky must depend on
freelancers to find the right ideas and execute them well for $1 a
word. And he will need good editors.
</P>
<P>
   He claims to have most of the first three issues of Failure in
the can but will not divulge much now. One article he does trumpet
is a piece for the first issue about a bizarre old golfer who has
taken his lumps over the years. It is called ``Moe Norman: The
Greatest Golfer the World Has Never Known.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman, a 70-year-old former touring pro from Canada, is finally
gaining recognition late in life for his strange, deadly accurate
swing after failing on the circuit as a younger man. At one point,
he was so poor that he slept in his car. Today, he has a sponsor
and gives golf clinics. Norman blew it by conventional standards
for most of his life, writes Zasky, yet he has since succeeded in
other ways. Welcome to failure.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sweet story, but will anyone care? Zasky plans to run
four such pieces a month and four shorter ones each week. There
will also be an Editor's Column that may or may not run five days a
week and a daily staple called This Day In Failure documenting
disasters throughout history. Zasky packs wriggle room in his
descriptions of the product. Adverbs like ``ideally'' pop up a lot.
</P>
<P>
   He is pinning a lot on The Bomb Site, an interactive piece of
the magazine that will ask readers to rate movies before they've
seen them. It will appear every Monday and cover all films opening
later that week. The goal is 100,000 participants after the first
issue.
</P>
<P>
   How do you rate a movie sight unseen? No problema. People do it
all the time based on buzz and other ephemora. This data, it turns
out, is prized by Hollywood studios. Ervin says that some of them
have already contacted Failure about The Bomb Site and may
eventually pay for the information.
</P>
<P>
   Erwin calls Failure ``a lean-running unit.'' This means she and
Zasky are the only full-time staff _ the result of an early
decision on their part to steer clear of venture capital money. So
they are tight with the few hundred thousand dollars raised from
friends and family. Their cadre of design and technology folk,
spread from Arkansas to California, are all on contract.
</P>
<P>
   Zasky and Ervin may start in cyberspace but they hope to end up
in print. They want Failure eventually to be a real magazine. This
is a heady goal for a pair that haven't yet hit the dot-com
maelstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know within the first year if that will work,'' said
Ervin about their print dreams.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't, there is always FailureWear, their patented line
of clothing and paraphernalia. These will be available online from
the opening bell and could well be the last thing standing if
everything else at Failure goes down.
</P>
<P>
   Zasky is betting that students will become a big slice of
Failure readership and a gold mine for its branding. That's why he
will take his Rorschach logo on a road show in September to college
campuses for a second publicity blitz.
</P>
<P>
   He and Ervin have paid close attention to this part of the
business. They went through two designers to get the right logo,
which features the word ``failure'' with the bottoms of the letters
mysteriously obscured.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here? Is ``Failure'' rising or falling? Your
call, says Zasky. Ervin was equally opaque: ``It's incomplete. It's
a story that has yet to be told.''
</P>
<P>
   So true. For now, Zasky and Ervin live off of panic, adrenaline,
and optimism _ just as they should at this point. The plan is in
place. It all still makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you live for,'' Ervin said. ``It feels like we're
in the part of an Andy Rooney and Judy Garland movie when they say,
`Let's put on a play on in our back yard.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Failure is still a publication, not a situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
