<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG EARNINGS, FADING FEARS BOOST TECH STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Natural Microsystems Corp. plastered the financial world with
its report on the company's second-quarter performance early
Thursday morning, well before the stock market opened for trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Framingham, Mass. company, which makes software and hardware
components for communications equipment suppliers, reported profits
more than twice as high as analysts had forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Natural Microsystems stock took off like a rocket as soon as the
market opened and climbed even higher through the day, eventually
soaring $25.5625 to close at $129.50 per share.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of booming reaction has been taking place among a
handful of select technology stocks reporting quarterly profits
over the past few days, beginning with Yahoo Inc. early in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   As worries over climbing interest rates slowly recede, much
stronger than expected corporate earnings are proving to be a
powerful stock market catalyst, especially among technology stocks
still trading far below their highs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew things were going well in tech land, but some of the
numbers have just been spectacular,'' said Marc Klee, portfolio
manager of the John Hancock Technology fund. ``Rarely do you find
companies doing that in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: If a bellwether company in a particular industry
blew past business expectations for the second quarter, chances are
others in the same line of work did well, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba Inc., which sells products to help companies do business
with each other over the Internet, reported quarterly sales that
outstripped forecasts by more than 50 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba stock boomed, gaining $27.6875 to $131.1875, on the news.
</P>
<P>
   But Commerce One Inc., another high-profile business-to-business
Internet company, also gained nearly 16 percent in value Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Pent-up enthusiasm, though still narrowly channeled to stocks in
specific industries, follows a period of interest rate fears and,
more recently, the ``pre-announcement'' season when companies
typically try to soften the blow of disappointing quarterly results
with early warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The good news: We have just entered a corporate reporting period
that will stretch through next week and may well be a catalyst for
further technology stock advances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the early indications are that we're going to have a
couple of strong weeks for technology stocks,'' said Dale Dutile,
comanager of the MFS Emerging Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: A certain amount of investor sobriety regarding
technology stock valuations, acquired painfully in the spring,
appears to be in danger of going out of style again.
</P>
<P>
   Natural Microsystem's second-quarter operating profit of about
$4.2 million was terrific by all accounts. But the news added more
than $400 million to the company's stock market value, which
ballooned to $2.1 billion Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the current rally note that many of the stocks
benefitting the most at the moment were those damaged worst in the
spring. And those soaring by as much as 20 percent in a single day
are doing it with reports that prove their business is stronger
than anyone believed.
</P>
<P>
   Another plus: Few people expect much more bad news about
interest rates from Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan in the
months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speculative fires were never extinguished; they were just
dampened,'' said analyst Philip Fine, who follows small techology
stocks for Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really looking past August, and once we get through
maybe a (quarter percentage point) hike in August, I think the
Street would be astonished if Greenspan raised rates on the eve of
the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Broader technology stock indexes have moved ahead sharply this
week. The tech-heavy Nasdaq index, up 118 points to 4174.86 in the
last two days, was in the black for the year on Wednesday for the
first time since April 10.
</P>
<P>
   But Dutile and others note that not all technology stocks are
enjoying better times. Some companies focused on electronic
commerce, Internet infrastructure, telecommunications, and
semiconductors are moving up. Other companies, including mainframe
computer companies and service businesses focused on older, legacy
computer systems, aren't reaping any stock market rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Among those stocks that have suddenly regained their popularity,
the question of valuation remains. How much is enough?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell you tech stocks are cheap, but I think
they're OK,'' Klee said. ``The successful ones are better
(businesses) today than when they peaked, but they're more
reasonably priced, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
