<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2011 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-PIMP-BOS &LR;      07-14 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PIMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN PIMP' A SKIN-DEEP LOOK AT SEX TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
AMERICAN PIMP 
Documentary by: Allen and Albert Hughes 
Running time: 87 minutes 
Rating: Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last year we have seen, in descending order, ``American
Beauty,'' ``American Pie,'' ``American Movie,'' ``American
Psycho,'' and now, perhaps inevitably, ``American Pimp.'' The
latter doesn't make it to the big screen often, at least not in
documentary fashion. Several do here, but Allen and Albert Hughes
seem far more charmed than critical, which means their film amounts
to a mostly wasted opportunity. If not exactly a whitewash,
``American Pimp'' lets its subjects off easy, consisting of a few
softball questions and a lot of jive-talking, often charismatic,
usually evasive, although if you listen long enough the unvarnished
exploitativeness of the sex trade emerges clearly enough. As one
pimp puts it when asked how a woman could consent to such a
one-sided arrangement, he replies that his job is to ``steal a
bitch's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   That perhaps explains why a woman would place herself in such a
victimized state, especially since an experienced pimp is a shrewd
street psychologist, able to zero in on women susceptible to his
line. There's no violence, no drugs in the clips we see, never so
much as a bad hair day. Mostly just a string of fast-talking guys
grabbing face time to fill the screen with their self-justifying.
As one Versace-draped pimp named K-Red from Washington, D.C., puts
it: ``My mouth is an Uzi, and I'm armed and dangerous with a double
clip.'' It's more than glibness. Skilled pimps specialize in
telling prostitutes (and women the pimps want to recruit as
prostitutes) what they want and perhaps need to hear. Never do we
see drugs. Seldom do we see the other end of the equation _ the
mostly white guys who pay to not be seriously inconvenienced by the
mostly black pimps or their compliant subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   Given that glibness is their stock in trade, it's not surprising
that the pimps we see, with names like Fillmore Slim, Rosebudd with
two d's, and Bishop Magic Don Juan, are fast-talking charmers,
convivial, almost relieved to pick up on the Hughes brothers' lead
that they be regarded as just another variety of businessman, no
different than, say, a vendor of plumbing supplies. The prostitutes
aren't given nearly as much screen time. Of those who are, a few
seem stoned, or just plain dumb, content to live with the line that
the pimps have imprinted on them, the idea being that they support
the pimp lavishly, keeping little or no money for themselves and
are lucky to share him with several other women, harem-style. When
they aren't working, that is. Never do they wonder why they seem to
have such short shelf lives while the pimps seem to have such long
ones as ``American Pimp'' punctuates the interviews with clips from
exploitation films such as ``The Mack,'' from which most of the
pimps derived their self-image.
</P>
<P>
   A few have left the game, one, ironically, having exchanged
pimping for telemarketing. Another turns out to be a big momma's
boy, basking in his mother's approval since he found Jesus. The
Hughes brothers escape innocuousness by strongly implying that
black pimps are tolerated, and even allowed to live flamboyantly on
the fringe, because they provide a clandestine service to white men
with money. In Nevada, where prostitution is legal, a white man
owns the biggest brothel and he's no less glib. The highly
image-conscious black pimps are on their best behavior for the
camera. It's the white entrepreneur who provides the film's most
offensive moment when he asks one of his employees to pose facing
away from the camera on her knees, then pats her rump
proprietorially as she complies. That single gesture crystallizes
the commodification of women that should be the film's real
subject, but isn't.
</P>
<P>
   By playing to the pimps' ego thirst, the Hughes brothers may
have assumed they would get them to open up. ``American Pimp''
includes, without irony, footage of a pimps' convention in which
the pimps celebrate themselves, presumably because nobody else
will. Nobody until the Hughes brothers, that is. Probably there
wouldn't have been a film if the brothers had subjected their
subjects to anything like hard interrogation. Instead, the pimps
take over, and turn ``American Pimp'' from documentary into
performance art. The film creates the impression that the Hughes
brothers were willingly seduced, or at least fast-talked by the
pimps, who surely can't always have been as unfailingly
entertaining and jovial as they are here. ``American Pimp,'' if not
quite a self-serving orgy of self-justification, can hardly be
thought of as a searching look at the skin trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1411EDT &QL; 
