<HEADLINE>
`BUT I'M A CHEERLEADER' LACKS SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BUT I'M A CHEERLEADER 
Directed by: Jamie Babbit 
Screenplay by Brian Wayne Peterson 
Starring: Natasha Lyonne, Clea DuVall, RuPaul Charles, Cathy
Moriarty, Bud Cort, Mink Stole, Eddie Cibrian, Melanie Lynskey,
Katharine Towne 
Running time: 85 minutes 
Rated: R (strong language and sexual content involving teens) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Natasha Lyonne has it in her to be one of film's great young
skeptics. She wears a perpetually inquiring look on her face and
her throaty little Julie Kavner voice has a question mark built
into the end of every assertion. She wants answers. Not that she's
destined to get any from her new film, ``But I'm a Cheerleader.''
It shortchanges her on every count. It's a lame and painfully
overextended satire of homophobia. In it, Lyonne's cheerleader,
Megan, is sent to a sort of heterosexual boot camp for heavy duty
deprogramming after her parents, her cheerleading girlfriends, and
her boyfriend freak out over Megan's lesbian tendencies. Megan
doesn't seem to have noticed that she stares at girls, tapes girls'
swimsuit pinups inside her locker, and reflexively wipes her
boyfriend's kisses off with the back of her hand before they've had
a chance to dry.
</P>
<P>
   In the campy, cartoony world of the film, which cries out for
the touch of a John Waters, and in fact has one of his longtime
regulars, Mink Stole, in the role of Megan's horrified mother,
Megan is bundled off to a color-coded place called True Directions,
run by Cathy Moriarty as a sort of gauleiter of heterosexuality.
She already has emasculated her adolescent son named Rock (this is
the film's level of humor) and means to steamroll the campers, most
of whom cannot be described as happy. The boys wear blue, while the
girls are engulfed by pink. They not only wear pink, they sleep in
it. Their cabin contains pink padded headboards, pink quilts, pink
walls. Sleeping inside it is like sleeping inside a huge intestine.
</P>
<P>
   If Megan was undecided about her sexuality when she arrived, she
quickly enough edges into a relationship with Cleo DuVall's
smolderingly miserable but appealingly intense Graham. Their love
scene, when they do have it, seems to have been spliced in from
some other movie. Camp takes a holiday and their coupling is
realistic and tender. Otherwise, the film is so galumphingly
executed that its sweet plea for sexual openmindedness collapses
under a pileup of clunkiness so maladroit as to verge on the
amateurish before veering into a cement-handed ending out of ``The
Graduate.'' ``But I'm a Cheerleader'' leaves Lyonne, DuVall, and a
sympathetic RuPaul Charles, as a counselor who says he's an ex-gay
but shows little evidence of it, in the coveted
nowhere-to-go-but-up mode.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
