<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN DAY EMBRACES WARPED EQUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Punk-rock heroes Green Day are bashing back into view on this
year's Vans Warped Tour. The band won't release a new album until
October, but didn't want to wait that long to tour again. Given
Green Day's populist ethic, the Vans Warped Tour has been the ideal
place for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to stretch our necks out and get back in the
ring,'' says Green Day bassist Mike Dirnt. ``And we wanted to play
with all of these punk bands. Some people have called us the
headliners of the tour, but I think there are 38 headliners, if
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the number of bands on the multistage Vans Warped Tour,
traveling with the Mighty Mighty Bosstones, Papa Roach (whose
singer, Coby Dick, calls the tour a ``punk rock summer camp''),
Long Beach Dub Allstars, MxPx, Suicide Machines, and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never done it before, but it's such a great tour,''
says Dirnt. ``It has proven itself year after year.''
</P>
<P>
   Green Day even enjoys the daily coin toss that determines the
order of the bands, rather than giving the bigger-named acts the
first choice. Green Day has gone on everywhere from early afternoon
to the evening, though ``we're usually somewhere in between,'' says
Dirnt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the sense of equality on this tour,'' he adds. ``I
mean, great bands go on before us, and great bands go on after us.
It's a celebration of punk rock through the '90s into the year
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   It also comes complete with demonstrations of motorcycle
jumping, skateboarding, rock climbing, and a ``human cannonball''
named David Smith Jr., who gets shot out of a cannon every day.
``He's the real headliner,'' Dirnt says, laughing. ``Rumor has it
he comes out 2 inches shorter every time he does it.''
</P>
<P>
   The one-for-all spirit of punk is also illustrated by how some
of the bands chipped in when the drummer of NoFx got hurt in a
bicycling accident earlier in the tour. Green Day drummer Tre Cool
sat in as a replacement. And so did drummers from several other
acts, including the Suicide Machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the great thing about punk rock. People will help each
other out,'' says Dirnt.
</P>
<P>
   Each act plays for only 30 minutes, but that doesn't bother
Dirnt, either. ``It's awesome, really, because you get the best of
what everybody has to offer in a combined package, and everyone's
got a short attention span nowadays, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Green Day could have toured last year as opening act for the
Rolling Stones, but declined because it was working on its upcoming
album, ``Warning.'' Says Dirnt: ``I like the Stones. I love the
Stones. They are an amazing band, but do they listen to our
records? Probably not. But I'm not worried about it. Making our new
record was really important, and we didn't want to take a break
from where we were creatively.''
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Warning,'' Dirnt is reluctant to comment before the
release (and the band is not performing songs from it this tour),
but says the title track is about questioning authority (``A lot of
rules were meant to be broken, and a lot of laws were meant to be
disobeyed,'' he says), while noting that the sound of the record
has evolved somewhat. There are more acoustic guitars played by
Green Day's Billie Armstrong, but ``he's playing them like Pete
Townshend would play them. He's playing them like electric guitars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we feel stupid trying to sit here and describe the record
and sell it. It's like, `Look, it's a good record. If you don't
like it, if you're skeptical, then borrow the tape from somebody
first. We're happy with it. It's a Green Day record. It's bound to
have good songs on it. More than one, at least. You'll have a hell
of a time downloading all these good songs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Def Leppard returns: Is it cool again to like Def Leppard? The
Brit pop-metal band was huge in the '80s, selling 10 million copies
of ``Pyromania'' (1983) and 12 million of ``Hysteria'' (1987). Then
the bottom fell out in the '90s, when the grunge movement shoved
the more polished Leppard aside. ``It became a case of `If you like
this, then you couldn't like that,' '' recalls Leppard guitarist
Phil Collen. ``But things are changing. We've been handed loads of
compliments by many artists who you think would have hated us, like
Everclear, Hole, and Orgy. We did the `Edge Fest' in Minneapolis
last summer with Hole, and (singer) Courtney Love said some great
things about us from the stage.'' In addition, the Offspring
sampled the spoken intro to Def Leppard's ``Rock of Ages'' and put
it on the beginning of their hit, ``Pretty Fly (For a White Guy).''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a theory,'' says Collen. ``If you're popular one
decade, then you're not going to be popular the next decade, but
the decade after that, you're cool again. When the '80s came,
suddenly everything in the '60s was cool and retro. In the '90s,
the '70s were cool. And now in the year 2000, the '80s are all
right again.''
</P>
<P>
   Def Leppard floundered with its stripped-down ``Slang'' album in
1996, but rebounded last year with ``Euphoria,'' which evoked the
more classic '80s Leppard sound and reunited the band with producer
Mutt Lange (now Shania Twain's husband/producer), who also co-wrote
three songs. The album has gone gold (500,000 sold).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have songs that you can sing with conviction, then you
should keep going,'' says Collen. ``And we still feel that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
