<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LYNNE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE IS SHELBY LYNNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Shelby Lynne is ornery. You can see it from
across the hotel lobby. Bad attitude grips her like the leather
that covers every inch of her elfin body. Suspicion, sharp as her
boot tips, looms behind jet-black glasses that are never removed.
Lynne is not a fan of question-posers, career-chroniclers, or
smiling people with notebooks and pens. They have done her wrong _
big-time, as far as she's concerned. She's shaking hands, speaking
politely (for the most part), only because Lynne has this shiny
round disc that pretty much sums up everything she feels,
everything she believes is true, everything she hoped she would
become, and she very much wants people to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Lynne says about her new CD, ``is the real stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Her accent is thick with the off-road twang of rural Alabama,
where she grew up. She doesn't mince words. ``This is what I'm
about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I Am Shelby Lynne,'' released in January, is no less a
proclamation of self-discovery, of hard-won independence, than the
title suggests. At 31, after recording five albums of other
people's songs for three different record labels in Nashville,
Lynne has made the record she was never quite sure she had in her.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fetching, occasionally radiant juxtaposition of blue-eyed
soul, honky-tonk, slick rock, and torn-up torch produced by Bill
Botrell, who also works with Sheryl Crow. Despite critical raves,
``I Am Shelby Lynne'' has hardly made a dent on the charts. Lynne,
who opens for k.d. lang Aug. 31 at FleetBoston Pavilion, is nothing
if not a realist, and she's duly mystified by the vagaries of
commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to make that work,'' she says in an interview
at the South by Southwest Music Conference here in March. ``I think
about it all the time: how to do what I want to do. All I can do is
try to make some videos, play live, which is what I love. I think
the music has to find its way.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy. Lynne grew up in the tiny town of Franklin
in a musical family: Her father played guitar; mama, she says, sang
like a bird; and Shelby listened to records. ``Elvis, Bob Dylan,
country music. I never really did anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came a series of traumatic events: Her father shot and
killed her mother and then himself during an argument in 1986,
leaving then 16-year-old Lynne to raise her younger sister. Lynne
married and divorced soon after. At 18, she hit Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne was singled out almost immediately as an emerging country
star; her first performance on TNN's ``Nashville Now'' sparked a
major label bidding war, and George Jones asked her to record a
duet with him. Over the next five years Lynne recorded as many
albums, earning the respect, if not always the affection, of her
Nashville colleagues _ and the sort of reputation that often comes
to women who think for themselves on notoriously patriarchal Music
Row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I got the difficult label,'' Lynne announces. ``And
that's fine with me. I know I'm not difficult. I don't have any
difficulty in showing my opinion and I don't agree with everything.
If it's not all right with me, it's not doing anybody any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Things were compounded by Lynn's occasional brushes with
authorities _ one involving cocktails and loud singing onan
airplane, from which she was unceremoniously escorted, and another
having to do with driving someone else's car over county lines in
Texas. ``You know, I drink, smoke, have a terrible attitude
sometimes. I can't help it,'' Lynne says. ``But it's blown out of
proportion. It's not like any of it is a lie, it's just things look
like (expletive) in print. You give up a lot when you do press, and
you have to know that going in. And I do. What the hell am I going
to do about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Lynne just picked up and left Nashville, and returned
to Alabama. That was 1995. A romantic might call what came next
Lynne's lost years. From the outside it looked like a protracted
period of so-called downtime. Way down, by all accounts. Except
that Lynne started writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't all down,'' she says. ``That's another thing that
was fabricated. I just didn't know what was gonna happen. And when
you're a worrisome little wiry weirdo, you worry about things that
aren't right up in your face so you can see it happening. But songs
just started coming out. I was finally convinced that I could do
it, although at the time I didn't know if I'd be doing it in a
hotel lobby or on a record. But it didn't matter. I finally figured
out what I wanted to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the songs on ``I Am Shelby Lynn'' are about
love, and losing love, and just plain losing. They're
ripped-from-the-heart sad, and deeply bitter. It's raw, despite
Botrell's super-polished production, because Lynne sings songs like
``Your Lies'' and ``Life is Bad'' with the beautiful ache of
someone who's come out the other side and is still standing. It
doesn't seem a stretch to call this collection cathartic. But it's
a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's a bunch of (expletive),'' Lynne says. She may have
found peace of mind in Palm Springs, Calif., her new hometown, but
it hasn't exactly dulled her edge. ``Why does everything have to be
some realization? I know it's good. It's not therapy for me; it's
what I do. It's hard, I love it, I was born to do it. I'd kill
somebody to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
