<SLUG> BC-TV-KENNEDYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY DOCUMENTARY CURSED BY CYNICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
KENNEDYS: THE CURSE OF POWER 
Produced by: Patrick Bachmann and Linda Midgett 
Date: Saturday at 9 p.m. 
On: The History Channel 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Are the Kennedys cursed?'' asks the narrator of a new History
Channel presentation rooting through the lives of the fabled
political family from its arrival in the United States in 1849
until the present. The question sounds like a headline ripped from
the front page of a supermarket tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean that the two-hour ``Kennedys: The Curse of
Power'' is just more trashy exploitation of America's royal family?
How could it be, stocked as the production is with sympathetic
talking heads, largely family and friends, sympathetic journalists,
and political cronies?
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, ``The Curse of Power,'' airing Saturday night at 9,
is little more than a litany of tragic deaths, accidents, psychic
wounds, diseases, and broken biblical commandments. It rehearses
all of the violent and premature deaths, from the storied
assassinations to the mid-air explosion of Joseph, Jr.'s Navy plane
in 1944 to Michael Kennedy's fatal skiing accident and his brother
David's deadly drug overdose to the flight that a year ago took the
lives of John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife, and his sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders whether this documentary would even have been made
if not for JFK Jr.'s sudden death and the opportunity it affords
for an anniversary review of Kennedy misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
   The proof is in the production, which is scripted and edited
with transparent cynicism. For one example, consider the peculiarly
short segment on John F. Kennedy and his presidency. There is next
to nothing about his policies or politics, and the only positive
note, praising his comfort level with the Washington press corps,
is struck to make a negative point, that he was a shrewd accomplice
in manufacturing his own image. Otherwise, we hear only that, like
his notorious dad, he was a reckless womanizer, and that he died
violently in Dallas. So much for the 35th president.
</P>
<P>
   Brother Robert gets slightly fairer and longer treatment before
he's pictured dying in a pool of his own blood.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, any list of Kennedy calamities, self-inflicted and
otherwise, must include Edward Kennedy's plunge off of the
Chappaquiddick bridge and the ensuing death of Mary Jo Kopechne.
But is the loss of son Edward Jr.'s leg to bone cancer relevant in
the scheme of things? Apparently, yes. ``The Curse of Power'' also
implies that the 1973 air accident that took the life of Aristotle
Onassis's son Alexander was curse-by-association. At the time,
Aristotle was married to Jacqueline Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   It's entirely possible that the on-camera commentators _ among
them Ted Sorensen, Ben Bradlee, and the Boston Globe's Tom Oliphant
_ provided context and analysis when they were interviewed. But
thanks to manipulative, tendentious editing, what we have here,
dressed up as a serious historical documentary, is too-familiar
sleaze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2022 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-CHICKS-BOS &LR;      07-14 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CHICKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIXIE CHICKS HAVE SOMETHING TO CROW ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Country women have been on a roll. Think of Shania Twain. Think
of Faith Hill. And, most of all this summer, think of the Dixie
Chicks, who are on their first arena-level headlining tour. They
are selling out nationally with their special blend of energetic
country and irrepressible shtick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to be a female right now,'' says Emily Robison
of the Chicks. ``It's a good time for women in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicks are not only empowering other women to follow suit,
but are doing what few country acts have been able to do in recent
years. They are capturing young fans who might otherwise be at
shows by teen-pop acts such as Britney Spears and Christina
Aguilera.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based drummer Billy Beard, who is with opening act Patty
Griffin's band, says that touring with the Dixie Chicks this summer
is ``like opening for the Beatles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have some young fans with high-pitched screams,''
Robison admits gleefully. ``I've been surprised by how frenzied the
crowd has been. But we don't have a dance troupe. That separates us
from all the rest of those (teen-pop) acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Another difference is the Chicks' musical ability. Robison is
accomplished on many stringed instruments from banjo to dobro. Her
sister Chick (and blood sister, too), Martie Seidel, is a virtuoso
fiddler. Singer Natalie Maines has enough chutzpah and talent (she
went to Berklee College of Music) to put the whole thing over the
top.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicks have been a phenomenon, selling 9 million copies of
their ``Wide Open Spaces'' album, which put them on the map a few
years ago; and 5 million of their latest, ``Fly,'' which cemented
the bond with their fanatical crowd and showed the Chicks are more
than just a country act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've transcended country radio,'' says Robison. ``Even though
country stations are the only stations we've been played on, we
also get a lot of word-of-mouth popularity. That's how a lot of the
young girls and young boys hear about us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's uncharted territory for country,'' Robison says
of the Chicks' status. ``Country is always changing and, for
whatever reason, people decided they wanted something different.
And we are different.''
</P>
<P>
   They're different in that not only do they add an old-timey,
banjo/dobro/high-stepping flavor to some of their songs, but they
also perform tunes by Bonnie Raitt and Sheryl Crow. Their latest
album departs from the Chicks' upbeat, honky-tonk streak to even
include a song about spousal abuse, ``Goodbye Earl,'' which has
earned approval from the National Coalition Against Domestic
Violence. ``Women have thanked us for bringing the subject up
again,'' says Robison.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Chicks have more freedom to do what they want
because of their massive commercial success. They admit, for
instance, that ``Goodbye Earl'' might not have landed on their
previous album because the record company might have rejected it.
The same with the more provocative ``Sin Wagon,'' which has a line
about ``mattress dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we probably wouldn't have gotten that on there,
either,'' says Robison. ``But `mattress dancing' is like Mr. Rogers
compared to some of the stuff that gets on the radio today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicks are likewise using their newfound freedom and clout
to stage one of the more ambitious arena spectacles of the summer.
They hired Cirque du Soleil set designer Luc LaFortune, who worked
on Cirque's acclaimed ``O'' show in Las Vegas, to punch up the
lighting and other visuals, which include clips from CMT, only in
this case it's ``Chicks Music Television,'' not the Country Music
Television cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the Chicks' good-time image, they also have a
stage curtain shaped like a pair of trousers, with a zipper that
opens in the middle. It's a play on the album title, ``Fly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of my favorite parts of the show. It's so wrong and
so right at the same time,'' Robison says of the trouser motif.
``But we're not above some gags.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor are they above suggesting every meaning of the word ``Fly.''
They have a fly-shaped helium balloon (shades of Pink Floyd's pig)
that is hoisted above the crowd before the show and drops vouchers
for merchandise. ``We like to think of it as an incentive for
people to get there early,'' Robison says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having grown up as concertgoers of all sorts of music, we had
high expectations of ourselves for this tour. I wanted it to be as
cool as seeing Bon Jovi when I was in the seventh grade. We're a
band, and we're mainly going to be playing music, but there's also
an art to putting together an arena show.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicks have also kept their ticket prices reasonable, with a
top in the $40 range (a bargain by arena standards).
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope you'll want to see another Dixie Chicks show, so we
want you to be able to afford it,'' Robison says. ``We're laying
the groundwork for what we hope will be future tours for a long
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
