<HEADER>
A2026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BACH-BOS &LR;      07-14 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOLFF ILLUMINATES BACH'S WORLD WITH AUTHORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
JOHANN SEBASTIAN BACH 
The Learned Musician 
By Christoph Wolff 
Harvard University Press, 599 pp., illustrated, $39.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What there is to know about Bach, Christoph Wolff knows. (In
fact, even now, 250 years after the composer's death, Wolff has
added detail to the sum of knowledge on the subject.) And
everything Wolff knows about Bach's life, he has poured into this
new and magisterial biographical portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff also knows how much he doesn't know, and what no one can
know, and indicating dimensions of unavoidable ignorance is an
additional virtue of his book.
</P>
<P>
   Bach was a learned musician; within days of his death his
achievement in music was being compared to Sir Isaac Newton's
achievement in science. Wolff is learned, too; he teaches at
Harvard and serves as dean of the graduate school of arts and
sciences. Because of its subject, his book is necessarily learned,
but it is also user-friendly, helpful, and entertainingly
informative. Listeners in Boston who heard WHRB-FM's magnificent
Bach Orgy last winter will recall how direct and illuminating was
Wolff's commentary on Bach's major works, and on the major musical
issues that Bach confronted. The same manner is evident in his book
_ Wolff wants to share his awe and his enthusiasm, and to awaken
those qualities in the reader.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff uses technical language when he has to, but always
explains what he means; pages of musical examples are relegated to
an appendix, where they will prove helpful to the musical reader
but not intimidating to others. Much information is gathered into
tables where it can be studied at a glance. There are many
illustrations, and computer enhancement has altered many drawings
to make venues appear as they did in Bach's time.
</P>
<P>
   The knowable facts about Bach's life would fit onto a few pages,
and, indeed, Wolff provides a handy 10-page chronology in an
appendix. When Wolff must be speculative, which is often, he is
honestly so, and presents several alternative explanations of
things we do know.
</P>
<P>
   His main text surrounds the facts of Bach's life with an
invaluable sense of context _ additional facts about musical life,
courts, patronage, church doctrine, ecclesiastical and municipal
politics. The biography is also a portrait of what can be known
about Bach's world, and a summary of the practical obstacles and
opportunities he faced. There are also a few glimpses of domestic
life; of Bach's love of wine, food, and tobacco; of his second
wife's fondness for songbirds and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Of Bach's character, not a whole lot more is known, though he
was obviously industrious and knew how to concentrate. Wolff makes
much of how comprehensive Bach's plan always was. From our point of
view, he displayed complete mastery of every dimension of musical
composition that existed in his time _ harmony, counterpoint, form,
and style _ and he created some of those dimensions; his work is
our definition of what mastery is. From another point of view,
Bach's work represents a lifelong process of self-education and of
artistic development _ an attempt, in Wolff's words, to bring
``into congruence original thought, technical exactitude and
aesthetic beauty.'' Bach wrote his music not to demonstrate his
mastery but to achieve it. And of course, for him, writing music
was a spiritual act, a function of religious belief.
</P>
<P>
   Vast as his surviving output is, much of the music that Bach is
known to have written has vanished, including two whole cycles of
cantatas, more than 100 of them. And composition was only one
aspect of Bach's all-encompassing life in music _ he was a teacher,
a conductor, a keyboard virtuoso, a scholar, an expert in the
design and technology of musical instruments, a publisher, an
entrepreneur; music was the family business.
</P>
<P>
   Bach was evidently of genial disposition, but could turn
obstreperous when he felt ``threatened in his art.'' There are a
few lively anecdotes. Once he noisily chased a meddlesome church
official out of the choir loft. Another time an ill-timed display
of temper against a duke or high official cost him a month in jail.
Characteristically, Bach turned the time to good account. An early
commentator, who was perhaps in a position to know, said that Bach
wrote the preludes and fugues of Book I of the ``Well-Tempered
Clavier'' ``in a place where ennui, boredom, and the absence of any
kind of musical instrument forced him to resort to this pastime.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolff supplies an epilogue about ``Bach and the Idea of `Musical
Perfection,' '' but closes his biography with the famous anecdote
about Mozart's visit to Leipzig in 1789, where he heard a motet by
Bach, a composer then more known in hearsay than in performance.
Mozart is said to have exclaimed, ``Now there is something one can
learn from!''
</P>
<P>
   Mozart, like every composer who followed Bach, learned from him.
Wolff has provided every lover of Bach with a book to learn from.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
