<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCREEN WEEP HOLES TO KEEP WASPS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July   16, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My brick siding has small holes along every few courses of
brick. What purpose do they serve? Insects are getting into the
holes and may be making nests. How can I keep them out without
plugging the holes?
</P>
<P>
   MIKE PINHERO, Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, those are weep holes in the brick, allowing water that
gets behind the brick to flow out or evaporate. You can fill those
weep holes with a bit of screening without compromising their
drainage function. Roll screening into a tube and stuff it in. If
there are insects (probably wasps) there now, you can hit them with
a hornet and wasp bomb before putting in the screening. To hit
them, wait until the cool of the evening when they are less active.
Then hit them with the spray and run indoors. Repeat as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   You can avoid all this spraying by letting the wasps stay until
fall and winter, when the cold will kill them. They are beneficial
(they pollinate plants and eat other bugs).
</P>
<P>
   And, thanks for the idea of spraying perfume in your newspaper
delivery box to keep birds out. Great idea, and it goes straight
into the handyman's file of great advice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a 1932 brick Colonial (the bottom half is brick) with
paint washing from the second-floor, 15-year-old white aluminum
siding, down the face of the brickwork, staining it. How do I wash
away this stain? I am worried that power-washing may loosen the
mortar, and am curious if these now white bricks can be restored to
the original color.
</P>
<P>
   JOE COUGHLIN, Beverly, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The white stain is from rain washing off the powdering paint
on the aluminum siding. The older the siding gets, the more the
paint will powder. To prevent that, remove the siding and put up
wood siding and stain it. Or, paint the siding: Sand it to roughen
the finish, wash with a strong detergent and water, and apply two
thin coats of a latex solid stain or two thin coats of a latex
house paint.
</P>
<P>
   To clean the brick, power-wash it. The spray should not harm the
mortar if it is intact. If it starts to deteriorate, stop and scrub
the stain with a strong detergent solution.
</P>
<P>
   Finish with Drylock, or other masonry sealer; this will make it
easier to wash off any future stains.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you ever heard of vinyl shingles, instead of the
standard vinyl siding (horizontal clapboards)? Are they any good,
or better than the siding?
</P>
<P>
   BRIAN McMAHON, Dorchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, we have heard of them, and have seen them at home shows.
They are different from the standard siding, but they are still
vinyl and hollow, as are the clapboards, and in my opinion, not
worth putting on your house. If you can't opt for wood, consider
fiber-cement siding that comes in clapboards and shingles. While it
is an artificial siding, I think fiber-cement is the best of the
non-wood siding. It is made by James Hardie, Inc., of California.
Call 888-542-7343.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a caller recently asked how to keep his dogs in his yard
and to keep other dogs out of the yard, without a cumbersome,
expensive fence, the handyman suggested an invisible fence, an
electric system that zaps the dogs gently when they try to get out.
Once zapped, the dogs get the message and stay away from the
invisible fence.
</P>
<P>
   All well and good, said William Carpenter of Marshfield, Mass.,
who said the invisible fence only keeps the owner's dogs in the
yard, because they must wear a collar to make the fence work.
Outside dogs, other animals, and kids, too, can go into and out of
the yard with impunity, Carpenter said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the correction, William Carpenter. So it's back to
the drawing board, and the handyman suggests a fence high enough to
keep from jumping over. It could be a picket fence topped by
lattice, which is quite open and airy, and not intimidating. Such
fences are good neighbors' fences, as well, combining privacy and
good looks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our inside walls have dark paneling. One of our cats used a
wall as a litter box, staining the paneling with urine and in some
places turning it white. Is there a stain or finish that can reduce
or eliminate the stain?
</P>
<P>
   J.E.B, Belleview, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. Your best bet is to sand that stain to the bare wood, then
apply a penetrating oil stain to match the paneling. Minwax makes a
good stain for this purpose. If the patch job is dull and does not
match the gloss on the rest of the paneling, you might be able to
touch it up with satin polyurethane varnish. If the contrast is not
too great, don't bother with the varnish, especially if it is near
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   If the paneling is photographic hardboard (a layer of wood-look
vinyl over hardboard), you may have to touch it up with Polyshade
of the right color, another Minwax product that is essentially a
varnish stain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
