<HEADLINE>
SPANIARD WINS BASTILLE DAY STAGE OF TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRAGUIGNAN, France _ Francois Simon awoke Friday morning with a
song in his heart. So did Christophe Agnolutto, Didier Rous,
Stephane Heulot and nearly 30 other French riders in the Tour de
France. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That song was ``La Marseillaise,'' the French national anthem.
Friday was Bastille Day, the French national holiday. So victory by
a French rider of a stage on this day was special.
</P>
<P>
   But what was mostly remembered by the vast Tour entourage were
past indignities on the sacred day committed by foreigners.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outrage was generally expressed thus: Remember the time a few
years back when Djamolidine Abdoujaparov, an Uzbek, won a Bastille
Day stage? Remember last year, when Giuseppe Guerini, an Italian,
finished first? What next, many asked _ a Belgian? A Croatian? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, a Spaniard: Vicente Garcia-Acosta, 27, a humble worker for
his homeland's Banesto team. In his fifth year as a professional,
with two previous victories to his credit and a world ranking of
No. 309, Garcia-Acosta split from two traveling companions with 11
kilometers (7 miles) to go and rolled to victory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Garcia-Acosta was timed in 4 hours, 3 minutes and 2 seconds, a
rapid 45 kilometers an hour, for the 185.5-kilometer 13th stage
from Avignon east to Draguignan in the hills behind the Cote
d'Azur. Conducted in sunny and breezy weather, the race was watched
by enormous crowds, especially at the start, with thousands on
Avignon's ancient walls.
</P>
<P>
   The two riders the Spaniard left in his wake were Frenchmen.
Nicolas Jalabert of the ONCE team and Pascal Herve of Polti were
second and third, 25 and 27 seconds too late respectively to save
the day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was foreshadowed early despite banners encouraging
French riders. The first of the day's attacks was carried out by a
German and an Italian. After regrouping, it was the turn of
Lithuanians, Poles, Swiss, Spaniards, more Italians and Germans,
Danes and even an Australian as the French showed only tentative
initiative. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once a 12-man breakaway of low-ranked riders took form about 60
kilometers along, the pack was content to let the those riders go
ahead on narrow and zigzagging roads past perched villages and the
occasional vineyard. Including all the overall leaders, the main
pack arrived 10:06 behind the winner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The outcome changed basically nothing. Garcia-Acosta began the
day in 46th place, nearly 29 minutes behind. Nicolas Jalabert, the
younger brother of the star Laurent Jalabert, and Herve were
similarly in the cellar.
</P>
<P>
   So Lance Armstrong, the head of the U.S. Postal Service team,
remained secure in the overall leader's yellow jersey, nearly five
minutes ahead of Jan Ullrich, the German leader of Telekom and the
winner of the 1997 Tour. Joseba Beloki, a Spaniard with Festina,
was third, nearly six minutes behind in the 145-man field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the American's performances in the first two mountain
stages _ two second places and a daunting display of easy power _
none of his rivals appeared to be overly optimistic about the
coming three stages in the Alps. They begin Saturday and continue
Sunday and Tuesday, with Monday a day off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
