 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, July 15:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Camp David, Md.) _ Developments in the Mideast
peace talks at Camp David. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-AUSTRIA (Paris) _ Five months after the European Union
imposed sanctions on Austria to protest the inclusion of far right
ministers in the Austrian government, a panel of experts has been
named to study Austria's human rights record and the political
nature of its far-right Freedom Party. Once that is done, the
sanctions are to be reviewed, and, if the panel finds Austria does
not violate civil rights, presumably lifted. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MISSILE-TEST (Undated) _ Experts say the recent failures in
the U.S. antimissile defense system are growing pains typical of
ambitious rocket projects and do not mean that it cannot be fixed
to meet the testing goals. Whether it will work as a real missile
defense is another question. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move with an ``a'' category code.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-POLITICS (Frankfurt) _ In a remarkable political victory
for Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, the upper house of parliament on
Friday approved $24 billion in tax cuts. The keystone of the
five-year plan, the elimination of the 50 percent capital gains
tax, promises big changes in how German corporations operate. By
Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-HEAT (Adaparazi) _ Turkey is reeling under 120-degree
temperatures, as severe heat and drought strike several countries,
causing fires, wiping out crops and claiming at least 50 lives
across southeastern Europe and more than 20 in Turkey. By Douglas
Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS-MBEKI (Durban, South Africa) _ At the AIDS
conference here, former South African President Nelson Mandela
praised the current president, Thabo Mbeki, and urged an end to the
the controversy over Mbeki's questioning of whether HIV causes
AIDS. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-POLITICS (Rio de Janeiro) _ President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso is facing a political crisis as a corruption scandal grows.
By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TAX (Washington) _ The Republican-led U.S. Senate
Friday voted to abolish estate taxes and sent the legislation to
President Clinton, who has called it a tax benefit for the rich and
said he will veto it. The Senate voted 59-39 for the bill that
would phase out gift and estate taxes over 10 years, but the tally
is short of the two-thirds majority needed to override a veto.
(Summary from wires) By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   SUBSTITUTE-TEACHERS (Washington) _ Substitute teachers, those
transient workers who get so little respect they might choose
Rodney Dangerfield as a spokesman, are having their first national
conference, part of a scattershot effort to lobby for better pay,
benefits and working conditions that has led to unionization in a
handful of areas. The conference comes amid the most severe
shortage of substitute teachers in recent memory, as districts
scramble to fill classrooms in an era of record-low unemployment
and high teacher absenteeism. With most students seeing subs for
more than a year of their school lives, educators are beginning to
think about improving training and preparation, changing
substitutes from glorified babysitters to bona fide teachers. By
Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-LAB-SECURITY (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ It is one of the historic
relationships in science. The University of California, since the
very beginning, has run Los Alamos Nuclear Laboratory. Now with
security lapses the tight relationship between the Los Alamos
Nuclear Laboratory and the University of California is straining.
The Energy Department has taken security away from them. And Bill
Richardson, the energy secretary, is whacking away at them. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN-BISHOP (Cincinnati) _ On the Rev. Vashti Murphy McKenzie,
the first woman elected bishop of the African Methodist Episcopal
church. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   IND-BABY-ELEPHANT (Indianapolis) _ Indianapolis had a scientific
breakthrough in March with the birth of Amali, the first African
elephant in the world born after artificial insemination. And to
prove the pregnancy was not a fluke, another African elephant, also
impregnated artificially, is due to give birth next month. By Carl
H. Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Elizabeth, N.J.) _ As he has been doing frequently in
recent weeks, George W. Bush on Friday visited a community center
in the inner city. But this one didn't end the way he expected it
to, as one of the panelists challenged him about the execution of
Gary Graham and on his state's frequent use of the death penalty.
By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Saginaw, Mich.) _ At a town meeting Al Gore gets an earful
about Nader. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-DELAYS (Undated) _ Last summer was the worst on record
for airline delays, and this summer is shaping up to be even worse,
with delays in June up 16.5 percent over last year. No passengers
have suffered more than those flying United, the world's largest
airline. Less than 57 percent of United's flights arrived on time
in May, and the airline has had to cancel more than 7,000 flights
this year. United's problems are especially awkward now because it
is trying to acquire US Airways, a deal that would make it
responsible for carrying 25 percent of the country's passengers.
Many politicians and consumer advocates oppose the deal, and
United's operating performance is giving them added ammunition. By
Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DOTCOM-ENTREPRENEURS (Beijing) _ Hundreds of millions of
American investment dollars have fattened the bank accounts of
China's young Internet entrepreneurs in the last nine months,
making dot-com companies the most vibrant part of the country's
fledgling private sector. The torrent of cash into private hands,
unprecedented under Communist Party rule, is particularly
conspicuous given the enormous financing difficulties that many
budding Chinese entrepreneurs confront in a society that officially
discourages capitalism. If the money keeps coming, the impact could
be as big as the breakup of the country's Maoist communes 20 years
ago. A capital-backed private sector may be the economy's best hope
for survival as hundreds of millions of workers spill from sinking
state- owned enterprises and foreign competitors eagerly await
China's market opening after it joins the World Trade Organization.
By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   LEUCADIA-RELIANCE (Undated) _ Leucadia National calls off a
$1.03 billion deal for Reliance Group, a troubled insurer
controlled by Saul P. Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Robust consumer demand shows few signs
of weakening, while inflationary pressures remain tame, new
economic data show. Retail sales rose 0.5 percent in June, stronger
than expected and the sharpest gain since February. May retail
sales were also revised upward, to 0.3 percent. A separate report
showed that prices paid to producers, manufacturers and farmers,
excluding energy prices, fell 0.1 percent in June, the first
decline since January. The Producer Price Index rose 0.6 percent in
June, matching forecasts. Energy prices rose 5.1 percent _ the
sharpest increase since March. A third report shows that industrial
production rose a less-than-expected 0.2 percent last month. By
Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   RAIL-MERGERS (Undated) _ An appeals court rules that federal
regulators were justified when they imposed a 15-month moratorium
on rail mergers in March. The decision was a setback for Canadian
National Railway and Burlington Northern Santa Fe whose proposed
merger to create North American's largest rail network was halted
by the moratorium. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SOGO (Tokyo) _ Japan's finance minister said that the
bankruptcy of Sogo Corp., a department store operator, and its
aftermath will not derail the economy, but some central bank
officials suggest that they may decide against raising interest
rates at their policy board meeting on Monday. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
