<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2050 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-XMEN-HNS &LR;      07-14 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-XMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `X-MEN' RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way to ``X-Men's'' splashy climax,
Wolverine, a newbie mutant-superhero with major 'burns and an
attitude to match, ponders the skintight leather pantsuit he's been
required to don as a uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``You actually go outside in these things?'' he asks of his
similarly leathered colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would you prefer?'' bolts the reply. ``Yellow spandex?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good punch line _ a perfect one, in fact _ for the
venerable X-Men, who've been fighting crime in spandex (yellow and
otherwise) for nearly four decades. If there's a cardinal rule for
live-action adaptations of beloved superheroes, it's this: Never,
ever, not if your little life depends upon it, dress them in
tights. Comic-book heroes look good in tights; human beings do not.
Either their knees look knobby or their pectorals sag.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, fortunately, occurs in ``X-Men,'' a dead-serious,
dead-smart twist on the Marvel comics series that allows for just a
touch of self-reflective humor. Letting the bunch get quippy over
spandex is one such example.
</P>
<P>
   But while X-Men fanatics may pick nits over backstory
revisionism (making Wolvering a newcomer, for instance) and cropped
characterizations, this smooth, dark and consistently entertaining
``X-Men'' stays as true to the spirit of its source material as any
comic-book adaptation since the original ``Batman.'' As such, it
ought to placate hard-core followers while pressing enough
action-movie buttons to keep X-Men ignorami sufficiently amused.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, ``X-Men'' benefits from the sure hand of
Bryan Singer, the director who brought virtuosic cleverness to
``The Usual Suspects'' and near-virtuosic creepiness to ``Apt
Pupil.'' There's nothing virtuosic about ``X-Men,'' which follows
the exploits and existentialist crises of a band of mutant
superheroes, but it does bear the stylishness and economy of a
storyteller at ease with his material. It also bears the mark of a
screenwriter (David Hayter, a lifelong ``X'' fan) who can translate
heaps of pop arcana into a cogent tale.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, the X-Men's random genetic quirks give them
idiosyncratic superpowers: Storm (Halle Berry) can whip up
hurricanes, Cyclops (James Marsden) shoots laser-like blasts from
his eyes, Jean Grey (Famke Janssen) has telekinetic and telepathic
abilities. The hirsute Wolverine (Hugh Jackman), who's been
implanted with an ``adamantium'' alloy skeleton and 12-inch
retractable claws, boasts the ability to heal himself. This comes
in handy when Rogue (Anna Paquin), a pubescent mutant whose touch
can kill, grabs him in agony after he stabs her in the chest with
his claws. But we're getting ahead of ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the X-Men is the magnificently bald Professor Xavier
(played by the magnificently bald Patrick Stewart), whose
telepathic powers and worldly-wise demeanor make him the ideal
mentor. Xavier runs a school for gifted children that's actually a
haven for mutant kids, most of whom have been rejected by a society
that looks askance at preteens who can walk through walls and cook
up fireballs with their bare hands. (Mutants: the misunderstood
minority.) Amid such prejudice it's easy to get cynical, but the
revered Professor X maintains his idealism by vowing to protect the
very Homo sapiens who reject him. Lo, the Uncanny X-Men.
</P>
<P>
   Them's the good guys. The bad guys consist of Magneto (Ian
McKellen) and his entourage, which includes a large, fanged,
growling, hairy man named Sabretooth (the aptly monikered Tyler
Mane), a revolting, reptilian-tongued acrobat named Toad (Ray Park;
watch him hang from buildings by his tongue) and, the vilest of
all, a yellow-eyed, blue-skinned shape-shifter named Mystique
(Rebecca Romijn-Stamos). Magneto himself has telekinetic powers so
highly developed that he bends iron bars like overcooked linguini
and dangles metallic desk tchotchkes in thin air.
</P>
<P>
   But the beauty of Magneto, as any X-nut will tell you, is that
Magneto isn't entirely evil. He's _ there's that word again _
misunderstood. The film opens with a bit of personal history, as
the young Master M is split from his parents in a Nazi
concentration camp; in agony, he warps the iron fence that
separates them. This early trauma defines Magneto and makes him
triply suspicious of humanity's willingness to accept minorities. A
campaign by a xenophobic senator (played a perfectly giddy,
perfectly oily Bruce Davison) to smoke out American mutants only
fuels Magneto's paranoia. He resolves to fight humanity; Xavier
resolves to protect it.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the X-Men. Where the plot heads, exactly, won't be
revealed, though it's safe to say it involves lots of superhero
fisticuffs and fair bit of chest-heaving character development.
</P>
<P>
   Wolverine is by far the most interesting of the X-Men (fans of
the comics may mourn the absence of other X'ers), a charismatic
manimal who tosses off the best lines in the film with a Dirty
Harry rasp. Jackman even looks like a youthful Eastwood _ think
Clint with a biker-boy pompadour. Though Stewart and McKellen (who
played ``Apt Pupil's'' evil Nazi) are clearly the cast's thespian
heavyweights, Jackman commands the movie; when he's on screen, it
leaps to attention. Paquin is another standout _ in a much quieter
role _ while Romijn-Stamos, snake-like in scaly blue skin, makes
one heck of a slithering bad girl.
</P>
<P>
   Marsden, meanwhile, is monumentally dull as Cyclops, who's
always been a stuffed shirt but here comes across as too young and
too callow to save supermarket coupons, much less the world. Berry
certainly looks the part of Storm _ that white hair! that milky
glow in her eyes when she conjures a gale! _ but has only a couple
of eensy-weensy scenes and doesn't register much of an impression.
Janssen's Jean Grey (known in previous comic incarnations as Marvel
Girl and Phoenix) fares slightly better, striking a few sparks with
Wolverine that might get sexy in the next film.
</P>
<P>
   And there will be a next film. Don't even doubt it; the
filmmakers didn't, having crafted a deliberately open-ended coda.
Certainly the whoops and cheers that went up at the close of the
preview bode well for the box office and scream (as such things do,
these days) ``looming sequel.''
</P>
<P>
   As a well-hyped summer flick with plentiful action and a
fanciful plot, ``X-Men'' will make boodles of money. As a
well-crafted, entertaining film that never skids into camp, it
deserves to.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
