<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2052 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-BLOOD-HNS     07-14 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BLOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `BLOOD SIMPLE' IS BACK, TENSE AS EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a tale from the crypt penned by James M. Cain, Joel and
Ethan Coen's ``Blood Simple'' has resurrected itself in taut,
super-tense fashion, and is a somewhat noticeable eight minutes
lighter.
</P>
<P>
   The film elbows tastefulness until it leaves a bruise. Its
squinting, self-aware cockiness that was so bracing two decades ago
has had a cancerous effect on independent filmmaking. The
staggering truth of ``Blood Simple,'' however, is that the Coens
had the formal elan, stylistic arrogance and intellectual daring to
back up their prankishness. The brothers wanted to tell a
simple-but-corkscrewed story of a jealous bar owner who hires a
private eye to kill his wife and her lover. And they wound up
mistaking Texas for a confederacy of dunces and the sweaty bowels
of hell, forging their most organically terrifying experiment in
sideways storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   The whole dusty, humid landscape is satanically alive, as though
there were a road that leads from the open highway to the devil's
mouth, with poor, dim John Getz seemingly uncertain about from
where hysteria will next emerge. The camera work was by first-time
cinematographer (later turned director) Barry Sonnenfeld, and it's
God's own sight gag, rambunctiously oozing around corners, climbing
over some drunk passed out at the bar, colluding with the
low-budget production design to cast the perfect shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Plainly, ``Blood Simple'' is the nightmare that films noir like
``Detour'' were always allusively damming off. It's of the same sin
that wrought ``Chinatown'' (1975) and ``Reservoir Dogs'' (1992).
What begins as a crime thriller tops itself off as a supremely
inverted horror film curdled with a touch of evil.
</P>
<P>
   The film really takes off at the midway point or just about the
time that you realize the sound of a heart beating in a body bag is
an enervated ceiling fan. And from a sheer shock and suspense
standpoint, the final sequence is the tightest, most unrelenting of
its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hedaya, as the jealous husband, was laying the groundwork
for the grumbling goons he'd play over the next 16 years. And,
looking like a Kmart Jessica Lange, Frances McDormand exhibits a
Jamie Lee Curtis-like gift for hyperventilation. As the
batter-dipped detective, M. Emmet Walsh, potbellied and sweating
through a canary-yellow suit, is the undead (or the extremely hard
to kill). The fly that buzzes around has rightly pegged him for
carrion.
</P>
<P>
   Early reviews quibbled with ``Blood Simple's'' lack of
compassion and facetious bloodlessness, a charge that's stuck with
the Coen brothers, though it's only truly evident in ``The
Hudsucker Proxy.'' But in basic thrilling measure, it's the boys'
most immediately gratifying movie: The goods are delivered in a
hearse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1447EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2053 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-CHUCK-BUC     07-14 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CHUCK-BUCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHUCK AND BUCK'S AFTER-SCHOOL PSYCHODRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Part case study, part metaphor, all bidding for
your own Kinsey-scale reading, Mike White and Miguel Arteta's
``Chuck and Buck'' is a thumb-sucking entry in the ``I don't wanna
grow up'' sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   The film comes on like an ``After School Special'' psychodrama
that's been taken off its medication. Written by White, it gambols
along in the latent boyhood intimacy between friends that
evaporates in the ether of adulthood. Still skipping along in
pre-adolescence, 27-year-old Buck (White) is willfully mired in his
10-year-old self. He sucks on Blow Pops and displays an unsettling
affinity for ``Children's Television Workshop'' fashion, while
living in a time capsule of a bedroom in his childhood home with
his mother, who dies suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   Her funeral is an opportunity for Buck to reacquaint himself
with his profoundly estranged best-friend, Chuck (Chris Weitz,
producer of ``American Pie''), who, in the 17 years since they've
seen each other, prefers to be called Charlie. That look of
constipated woe Chuck wears suggests it's been 17 light-years.
</P>
<P>
   He arrives at the funeral accompanied by his fiancee, Carlyn
(Beth Colt), who treats the cumbersome resumption of the Chuck-Buck
relationship with bouts of suspicion, fascination and cluelessness.
She invites Buck to come visit them in Los Angeles, where Charlie
works as a music executive. Incapable of exercising a modicum of
self-control, Buck moves _ into the Little Prince motel, where he
transplants the kitsch museum that was his old room _ and commences
stalking Charlie.
</P>
<P>
   It's with a sneer that I disclose that White used to write for
``Dawson's Creek,'' and there's a sleepy-smirking quality about him
that makes him look like he's just climbed in through James Van Der
Beek's window. He looks like that kid who's always in search of a
rave _ or Legoland.
</P>
<P>
   He's a fey idiot who reaches out to '60s underground-movie star
Taylor Mead by way of sketch-comedy jester Chris Elliot. Arteta,
who also made the similarly bizarre but queasier ``Star Maps,'' has
fashioned neither a drama nor satire per se. The film, shot
pristinely on digital video, keeps an odd, but mercifully straight
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck and Buck'' teems with regrettable corniness but also
with droll wish-fulfillment in this dreamlike exorcism of White's
personal and Hollywood demons neatly arranged in its own
``Dawson's''-like format. Buck manages to mount the ballad of Chuck
and Buck called ``Hank and Frank'' at a community theater. It's a
play that the theater's production manager (Lupe Ontiveros, whose
rationale the film could have used more of) tags a ``homoerotic,
misogynistic love story.'' (Her analysis sails over his head.)
</P>
<P>
   Further, but brilliantly caught in the throes of his own
reflexivity, Buck carries on with the two actors playing Chuck as a
child and as an adult in his play (one of whom is played by Weitz's
older brother, Paul). He's not simply exploiting trauma, he's
trying, gingerly, to get into its pants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
