<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Saturday, July 15.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYGROUNDS-DESIGN (Undated) _ Just as a society's ideas about
nature can be read in the character of its parks, and its beliefs
about education are often written in the look of its schools, the
attitudes of Americans toward children's play can be traced in the
changing face of public playgrounds. By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENTAL-IMPERIALISM (Undated) _ Portraying
environmentalists as latter-day missionaries of a new universal
truth, many anthropologists see Third World conservation as a form
of neocolonialism, the latest attempt by wealthy Westerners to move
into poor, tropical countries and tell the local residents what
they should and should not do with their land. By Alexander Stille.
</P>
<P>
   UNREAD-BEST-SELLERS (Undated) _ The tale of the emperor's new
clothes has long been with us. But how about defining another
category of mass delusion, the emperor's new book _ the insanely
popular, often intellectually intimidating book that may sell
hundreds of thousands of copies (or sometimes even millions), but
that few of its purchasers actually read. By Bill Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CHILD-KILLING-REVIEW (Undated) _ On Showtime Sunday, ``Who
Killed Atlanta's Children.'' Reviewed by David DeWitt.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
