<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2086 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-POWWOW-CAMP-DAVID-ECO     07-14 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWWOW-CAMP-DAVID-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH STAKES, HIGHER OBSTACLES FACE CAMP DAVID SUMMITEERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 775-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Deadline after deadline has slipped by since Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, under
U.S. President Bill Clinton's benevolent eye, signed their
declaration of peace on the White House lawn in September 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But America's electoral calendar is compelling. Clinton is at
the tail end of his presidential authority. This, above all else,
has dictated the timing of the crucial summit between Clinton,
Arafat and Israel's current prime minister, Ehud Barak, at Camp
David, giving it sudden now-or-never urgency.
</P>
<P>
   Now or never also tripped off the tongue in 1978 when President
Jimmy Carter invited Egypt's Anwar Sadat and Israel's Menachem
Begin to the presidential hideaway. But the prospect of an
Israeli-Arab peace was then new and startling: the three leaders
were explorers in an unknown land.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians and Israelis, by contrast, have been tramping
the land for a decade, at the Madrid conference even before the
Oslo peace track revealed itself in 1993. They have surveyed every
inch of the territory.
</P>
<P>
   But since so many of their demands are incompatible, this
knowledge is not necessarily an advantage. Both Barak and Arafat
have to be able to leave Camp David declaring victory, or at least
seeing it in prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Barak needs a deal that enables Israelis to feel secure from
attack, their nation undiminished. Arafat needs a deal that offers
West Bankers and Gazans a respectable-seeming independent state
while not ignoring the concerns of the Palestinian diaspora and the
wider Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
   Neither leader can get away with less, for neither has the
domestic strength of his Camp David predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Begin had the huge advantage of coming from the right. Sadat had
a dictator's powers _ though he, like Israel's Rabin, was later
murdered by his own people for his belief in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has seen his coalition collapse in the face of a deal. It
put him in an awkward position, as he squeakily survived a vote of
no-confidence this week. But he may, in fact, be better off without
his departed partners: they were a mixed, narrow-minded lot,
endlessly squabbling and horse-trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government had reached the point when bargaining
with its own component parts often took precedence over negotiation
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has the personal strength to rise above his domestic
political bazaar. If he can make a fair deal and present it to his
people, including his Palestinian-born people, in a referendum, he
stands a good chance of success.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis have much more on their minds than the boring business
with the Palestinians, and most of them want to see an end to it.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has the opposite problem. Free of Barak's democratic
restraints, he should have little trouble pushing a deal through
his loyalist administration.
</P>
<P>
   His people are another matter. Palestinians outside the
territories have always opposed the Oslo peace track, mainly
because it touches only lightly on their overriding interest: the
right of their return to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Now West Bankers and Gazans, too, are skeptical of a process
that has brought few of them much freedom and has made most of them
much poorer.
</P>
<P>
   A central difficulty is that the Israelis believe that
concessions must start from the current situation, whereas the
Palestinians believe they have already made a vast concession by
accepting an embryo state amounting to little more than one-fifth
of mandated Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, they will have to concede a lot more. But if the end
result fails to win widespread West Bank and Gazan backing, the
initiative could pass to Palestinian rejectionists.
</P>
<P>
   The naysayers, with their violent Islamist elements, will never
be satisfied with anything Arafat can get. The hope is that the
rejectionists can be marginalized in the framework of general
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   The now-or-never label notwithstanding, the summit could end
inconclusively. The stumble towards peace could then continue. If,
at worst, failure cannot be disguised, the consequences will be
bad.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has promised to declare an independent state by Sept. 13.
He made a similar promise last year, only to retreat under
pressure. A second broken promise is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has threatened, in return, to annex the land on which
Jewish settlements have been built. No doubt, after a while, the
two sides would start talking once again. But it would be a
bloodily violent while.
</P>
<P>
   When things were at their nastiest at Camp David in 1978, with
the Egyptians packing their bags to go home, Carter intervened to
knock heads together. If he is to get a deal, Clinton too may have
to knock on more than wood. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
