<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-PEACE-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DIVISIONS AMONG IRISH PROTESTANTS REVEAL CRACKS IN PEACE PROCESS
</P>
<P>
   (700&AMP;ADDS)
</P>
<P>
   For Use Sun., July 16 And Thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   By BERT ROUGHTON JR. &QC;
</P>
<P>
   c.200 Cox News Service &QC;
</P>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland - On grassy patch along the Corcrain
Road in a ramshackle Protestant neighborhood here, the flames were
still burning Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   These were the remnants of Tuesday night's immense bonfire _
which was topped with an orange, green and white Irish flag and an
effigy of a Northern Irish policeman.
</P>
<P>
   The three-story blaze of scrap lumber, pallets and old furniture
_ there were even kitchen cabinets complete with metal sinks _
added a hellish light to the night's tumultuous edition of the
riots that have plagued this year's marching season.
</P>
<P>
   To repel an assault of the brick, beer-bottle and
gasoline-bomb-wielding mob _ composed in part of neighborhood
children _ police employed water cannons, batons and fired rubber
bullets. There were injuries on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was remarkable not only for its violence but because
it involved a largely Protestant mob attacking a largely Protestant
security force.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, it was the Catholic nationalists _ people aligned
with the Irish Republican Army's struggle to unite Northern Ireland
with the Republic of Ireland _ who warred with the police and army.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sign of the new frustrations bedeviling the fragile
peace process _ those of Protestants, who now believe they are
being trampled at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday morning, a lone man, who appeared to be in his mid
50s, walked past the scorched field, where there had been no
apparent effort at a clean-up. Tucked under his arm was an
oil-stained brown paper bag of fish and chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you look at the rubbish, then,'' said David Frew, who has
lived in the area for 38 years. ``But you must know that this is
all the fault of the government and the nationalists who have tried
to kill our culture. When the IRA does violence, they get what they
want. That's what the young boys have learnt from your peace
process.''
</P>
<P>
   While the peace seems to have again survived the marching
season, the uncommon nastiness of the 12-day period confirmed that
the province is a long way from resolving the blood feud that has
claimed 3,600 lives over the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   During the season, which climaxed on July 12 _ known universally
as The Twelfth _Protestants hold about 2,700 parades across
Northern Ireland to celebrate King William of Orange's 310-year-old
victory of over his rival Catholic King James II.
</P>
<P>
   The 1690 victory created the division in Ireland between the
north, which is still a British province, and the South, which
became the Republic of Ireland in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The catalogue of violence for this year's season, which began
July 1 and ended Thursday, provides chilling proof of how far the
province is from attaining a peace that U.S. President Bill Clinton
desperately wants to claim as part of his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the period, there were 329 attacks on security forces,
injuring 81 police officers and six soldiers, police said. There
were 305 incidents involving gasoline bombs. It could have been
worse: Police recovered 1,000 bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-five homes, 75 commercial or public premises and 404 cars
were damaged, and 105 vehicles were hijacked. Security forces fired
19 plastic bullets, 217 people were arrested and 87 have been
charged.
</P>
<P>
   While there were reports of a few stabbings, one man died after
being shot in the back of his head near a bonfire Tuesday night in
the port city of Larne. Local newspapers have reported that he may
have been killed for singing a song that may have offended some
Protestant militants.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Protestant leaders have been shocked by what they consider an
appropriation by hooligans of their respectable celebration. Some
fear that the organization's leaders have done too little to stop
the lawlessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see people blocking traffic with pints of beer in their
hands, that was not the organization I joined,'' said William
Brown, a longtime Orange Order leader. ``Good people have only to
do nothing to let bad men succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   While Irish and British leaders take heart that the recently
reinstated Northern Ireland Assembly _ the Protestant/Catholic
alliance created to assume governmental control _ survived, there
were signs that the broad public support for the 2-year-old peace
process was fraying.
</P>
<P>
   Support among Protestants for the 1998 Good Friday accord _
which established the peace process _ was waning, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My conversations with ordinary Unionists produced remarks such
as 'Peace - what peace?', 'I'm not a Paisley-ite (referring to the
radical Protestant leader Ian Paisley), but he speaks a lot of
truth', and most tellingly, 'If a referendum were held now, there
would be no majority in favor of the Good Friday Agreement,'''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rodgers, an Orange Order leader in Belfast, believes
Protestants are reacting to the inclusion of Sinn Fein _ the
political wing of the Irish Republican Army _ to the assembly
before the IRA surrendered its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA, which like unionist paramilitaries is observing a
cease-fire, says it has placed its weapons beyond use.
</P>
<P>
   Many Protestants believe the Good Friday Agreement has been
implemented in a way that has favored nationalist Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of frustration out there, and I have never
experienced anger like it,'' Rodgers said. ``I don't condone it,
but some Protestants see Sinn Fein in government after IRA violence
and they think if it worked for them, why not for us?''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Dudley Edwards, a Dublin-based author who has written about
the Orange Order, believes the organization is in danger of
``committing suicide'' over its internal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anti-agreement faction is determined to push out the
pro-agreement faction,'' she said. ``At the top there is a great
sense of drift and a concentration on negative politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The division was obvious Thursday, when national Orange Order
leaders asked for an end to a virulent protest over the
government's decision to ban them from marching through the
Catholic neighborhood in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Orange Order leaders in Portadown vowed to continue their
protest _ which has been cited as the spark that ignited the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Orange Order leader Robert Saulters said Friday that he was
worried that support for the organization was disintegrating
because of the protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have had enough,'' Saulters said. ``I think it's time
we sat back and reflected.''
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed deep frustration that his concerns were being
ignored by hard-liners. ``They are not playing the game with us at
all,'' he told the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.orangenet.org
</P>
<P>
   http://sinnfein.ie
</P>
<P>
   http://www.local.ie/content/11641.shtml
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
