u i BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-0715-COX     07-14 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ROW OVER RUSSIAN ARMY RESTRUCTURING ERUPTS AMONG GENERALS
 &HT;    (475&AMP;ADD).
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIZHNY TAGILL, Russia _ A squabble among Russia's top brass
about the future of the armed forces spilled over into the public
arena Friday as President Vladimir Putin and his generals attended
a major arms show aimed at spit-shining the military's image.
</P>
<P>
   Military and national security leaders have for months struggled
over ways to restructure the armed forces, and resuscitate the
country's military industrial complex as part of Putin's
overarching goal to overhaul the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, competing proposals came to light during a
closed-door meeting, when Chief of Staff Anatoly Kvashnin, a career
army man, recommended the elimination of the strategic nuclear
forces as a separate branch of the military and folding it under
one of the remaining three.
</P>
<P>
   He reportedly described the standing army as in a ``near
critical'' state and suggested savings from cuts in the nuclear
branch could be used to re-equip and better train conventional
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the plan erupted publicly Friday, when Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev, who made his career in the strategic
forces, said that a move like this would be a ``crime against
Russia and just plain madness,'' according to the Interfax news
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at the Urals Expo 2000 here Friday, Putin tried to
quell the row among the generals.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The discussion of restructuring) involves a major,
fundamental decision upon which the country's future depends. Such
a decision cannot be made behind closed doors, but nor can it be
opened up to nationwide debate,'' the president said, adding that
no decision was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   If Kvashnin's measure is adopted, it would disrupt the
international balance of nuclear forces and represent a 180-degree
about-face in the strategic policy of the country, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking from the history of parity with the United States
would be a major development,'' said military analyst Nicholai
Novichkov.
</P>
<P>
   The Nizhny Tagill arms show, held at a formerly secret military
base 900 miles from Moscow, was an apt illustration of problems
resulting from the last 10 years during which both the military and
military industrial complex were chronically underfunded.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's leading arms manufacturers paraded in front a deadly
arsenal of conventional weapons to about 100 international buyers,
few if any new technologies were exhibited or demonstrated.
Instead, the focus was on presenting modifications of time-honored,
reliable standbys, like the Kalashnikov rifle and the T-90 tank.
Soldiers and factory workers both complained of receiving late
wages, and companies said their future looked grim.
</P>
<P>
   While both generals, Putin and analysts agree that the military
needs to be restructured, just how to do this remains a thorny
problem, involving personal egos, varying ideas of how to protect
national security and a lack of money to pay for changes.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the 1.2 million-strong military is organized into
ground, air, naval and strategic forces, which oversee the nuclear
arsenal and are the cornerstone of the Soviet Union's military and
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Russian weapons makers exhibiting their wares at the arms expo
said their future relied on the government jump-starting weapons
procurement not on one-time sales to foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a problem if the government doesn't resume orders,''
said Vyscheslav Azingareev, the marketing director of the
Chelyabinsk Automatic Mechanical Enterprise, which makes artillery
shells. ``Russia has a saying that if a country doesn't feed its
own army, it will end up feeding another. It's a matter of pride
that we survive these times.''
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.militarynews.ru (The site is in Russian.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
