<HEADER>
A2133 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-GOP-BLACK-MAGIC-ECONO     07-14 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BLACK-MAGIC-ECONOMIST-550&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN BUSH BREAK BLACKS' FAUSTIAN PACT WITH DEMOCRATIC PARTY?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 2 trims, total 225; 1,175 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 950-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (NOTE: TWO OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 225 WORDS; TOTAL UNCUT IS
1,175.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ ``Most black people don't think alike. Most black
people just vote alike,'' says J.C. Watts, a black Republican
congressman from Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   That disjunction between the variety of black views and the
near-unanimity of support for Democrats sent George W. Bush, the
Republicans' presumptive presidential nominee, to Baltimore this
week, to address the annual meeting of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP), the largest black
political organization.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting heroes such as Jackie Robinson, the first black
professional baseball player, and W.E.B. Du Bois, one of the
NAACP's founders, he tried to lay the groundwork for a
reconciliation between his party and blacks by conceding that
racism still exists in America (which some Republicans have denied)
and by a nostra culpa: ``The party of Lincoln hasn't always carried
the mantle of Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush pointed to school reform in Texas, which has raised the
educational standards of minority students, and argued that
``compassionate conservatism'' offered a better alternative to poor
blacks than traditional big-government programs.
</P>
<P>
   The applause was diplomatic and the immediate response polite,
if skeptical. The Rev. Sidney Daniels, a civil-rights leader,
argued that ``in spite of all the promises he seems to be making,
he's still got the idea that private concerns can take over the
work of the government.'' But he gave Bush credit for showing up at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans consistently get a mere 10 percent of the black
vote, plus or minus 5 percent, says David Bositis, a senior
political analyst at the Joint Center for Political and Economic
Studies, a black think-tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole's showing among black voters in 1996, an anemic 13
percent, was still the best the GOP has managed since Dwight
Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just bad news for Governor Bush; it is bad news for
America's blacks. Although their long identification with the
Democratic Party has allowed some black leaders to emerge, it has
been, for the most part, a Faustian bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic candidates can make token promises to blacks which
can then be conveniently set aside as they dash to the middle for
swing votes, says the Rev Floyd Flake, a former Democratic
congressman from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republicans, reading the writing on the polls, never
bother to make any meaningful promises in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Republicans have much to recommend them to blacks,
who often describe themselves as more conservative than whites on a
wide range of issues.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1999 poll conducted by the Joint Center for Political and
Economic Studies, blacks were twice as likely as whites to cite
crime, violence and drugs as the most important problems facing the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks are significantly more likely than whites to support
school vouchers. Most blacks oppose abortion, says Watts (who would
say that). Three in four support school prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans might even trawl for black votes with pocketbook
issues. Since 1970, around 2 million black families have moved into
the middle class (i.e., earning more than $50,000 in 1997 dollars).
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to see why they should be any more enthusiastic about
Democratic poverty programs than their white suburban neighbors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 50 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 550) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Black Chamber of Commerce supports the repeal of the
inheritance tax. Watts even makes the slightly macabre suggestion
that blacks should favor private individual retirement accounts,
rather than the current system of state-guaranteed Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   They die younger than whites, he reasons. Unclaimed Social
Security benefits revert to the government; but private retirement
savings can be left to the family. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   So will Bush's appeal change minds? Not if the later reaction at
the Baltimore conference is any guide. An hour after he (and the
television crews) had left, Maxine Waters, a Democratic
congresswoman from Los Angeles, took the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we give people an opportunity to talk to us,'' she cried,
`` they should do more than quote our black heroes. When we give
you our platform, come prepared to talk business with us. We're
talking about police abuse, driving while black.'' The hall erupted
in cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Wendell Anthony, the president of the Detroit branch of
the NAACP (the largest in the country) was even ruder about Bush:
``An empty speech, an abdication of responsibility, he failed
miserably to address our concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans may indeed be the party of Abraham Lincoln, but
the Democrats became the party of Franklin Roosevelt. The New Deal
had much to offer poor blacks. Blacks and Republicans parted ways
more permanently three decades later.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican ``Southern strategy'' of the 1960s successfully
drew Southern whites into the party by opposing civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kristol, editor of the Weekly Standard, likes to claim that
every voter has a formative political experience: for many black
voters, it was the civil-rights era.
</P>
<P>
   Above all there is a basic lack of trust in the Republican
Party. ``If you don't trust,'' argues Bositis, ``issues really are
irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders compound their problems, he adds, with
``fool's errands'': defending the Confederate flag, visiting Bob
Jones University, holding up the appointments of black judges and
ambassadors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 175 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 875) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   However, at the local level, Republican hopes for some sort of
modest realignment look more realistic. As the Rev. Buster Soaries,
an adviser to (Republican) Governor Christine Todd Whitman in New
Jersey, puts it, ``There has been a lot of black political power
without a corresponding gain in welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican governors have done well with black voters. John
Engler earned 27 percent of the black vote in Michigan in 1998, the
same portion as Bush in Texas; Mrs. Whitman did similarly well in
New Jersey. Republican mayors, such as Bret Schundler in Jersey
City, have done even better.
</P>
<P>
   These state and local Republicans are more pragmatic than their
congressional colleagues. They are closer to the people and have
overcome black mistrust by letting their policies do the talking.
</P>
<P>
   They are also predominantly from the Northeast and Midwest,
where there is a kinder, gentler brand of Republicanism. ``They're
a different Republican Party,'' says Bositis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,175) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expects Bush to pick up 27 percent of the national black
vote in 2000. No candidate can reclaim goodwill lost over half a
century. But future elections might be a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to get elected to do those things,'' says Kristol,
who reckons that a compassionate George W. Bush, elected in 2000,
could double his vote among blacks in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, a political scholar at the Brookings Institution,
tells a story (probably apocryphal) about Brigham Young. The Mormon
visionary reached Utah with his followers and promptly decreed that
half of them would be Democrats and half Republicans: that way,
their votes would never be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   America would be a better place with more black Republicans.
That is not a bad place to start. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
