<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2136 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GENES-CANCER-HNS &LR;      07-14 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENES-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESEARCHERS PINPOINT PROTEIN LINKED TO CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Scientists say they have discovered how two
important genes work together in a healthy cell and why cancer can
form when these genes are defective.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Texas Health Science Center say
they have identified a protein that is activated by a gene known as
ATM, and now understand how ATM communicates with BRCA1, a gene
implicated in some inherited forms of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The study by Wen-Hwa Lee and his colleagues at the Institute of
Biotechnology was published Thursday in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   BRCA1, the so-called breast cancer gene, is a tumor suppressor
that activates when there is damage to DNA, the genetic blueprint
that resides in the nucleus of the cell. Estimates are that defects
in this gene account for 2 percent to 5 percent of breast cancers.
</P>
<P>
   ATM is considered a master switch that ``talks'' to other genes
in a cell, including the BRCA1 gene, and alerts them when there is
damage to DNA. These genes in turn carry out repairs. Without
repairs, the damaged cells can become cancerous.
</P>
<P>
   Defects in the ATM gene are known to cause a syndrome called
ataxia telangiectasia, or A-T, which is characterized by stunted
growth, immune disorders, neurological deficits and cancers like
leukemia and lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   A-T occurs once in every 40,000 births, when a child inherits
two copies of a defective ATM gene, one from each parent. These
children rarely survive into their 20s.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1 percent of the population has one defective copy
of ATM, Lee said, which leaves these individuals with impaired
responses to DNA damage.
</P>
<P>
   In normal cells, the researchers found, ATM activates a protein
called CtIP, which in turn causes the BRCA1 gene to produce another
protein, GADD 45, which is essential in cell repair.
</P>
<P>
   By learning how the ATM gene works, Lee said, scientists are
identifying potential targets for cancer drugs and other therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are still very, very far away,'' Lee said. ``We need
much more study.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said, the focus should be on prevention.
People who know they have ATM and BRCA1 mutations should limit
their exposure to DNA-damaging elements like radiation, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are ATM deficient, it is best not to go enjoy too much
sunshine or take too many X-rays,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's wife, Eva Y.P. Lee, also participated in the study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1525EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
