<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2158 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-AOL-MEXICO15-COX     07-14 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MEXICO15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW AOL MEXICO FEELS AUTHENTIC IN TONE AND CONTENT
 &HT;    Moving in (l) lifestyle and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America Online Inc.'s new Spanish-language service
is a virtual passport to an authentic online Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The largest U.S. Internet service provider launched AOL Mexico
this week in hopes of winning a large share of the country's
fast-growing market for online services.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, because AOL users in this country will have access
to the same Spanish-language content at no additional cost, ``it
will provide direct links between U.S. Hispanics and Mexicans,''
said Eduardo Escalante, president of AOL Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Escalante predicted the new service would be a big hit in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a service that is so easy to use and so convenient, we
think it is going to be very successful in this market, because
most people are going to be new users,'' Escalante said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the AOL Mexico's first users in Mexico City, Fernando
Moreno, 40, was impressed with the service's speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it is because the service is new, but I logged
on very quickly,'' Moreno said in a phone interview in Spanish. It
is typical to wait for several minutes to log on with other
Internet providers, Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked it,'' Moreno said. ``It is a very practical service.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL hired Mexican natives to design the new service, choose its
content and ensure its appeal to new subscribers, Escalante said.
</P>
<P>
   The screens in AOL Mexico are in generally the same style as the
American version, but the designers were obviously familiar with
Mexican taste.
</P>
<P>
   There are no pictures of Chihuahuas or other American-made
stereotypes. Where American users click on a dollar sign to link to
a financial page, Mexicans click on a piggy bank. Other links refer
to Mexican revolutionary heroes. Well-known Mexican lotto pictures
of a rooster, a heart and a ladder link to chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   As of content, there are areas for the latest political news on
Vicente Fox's election as the next Mexican president, soccer news
for sports fans, and chat rooms for the ``novelas,'' Mexico's
popular soap operas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took AOL 5.0 and adapted if for Mexico,'' Escalante said.
``It looks Mexican and feels Mexican.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many basic terms remain the same. Words like e-mail, chat
room, CD and home page are not translated. They are part of the
Spanish Internet language.
</P>
<P>
   The new service is available only in Mexico City, although
Escalante said it will soon expand to other cities. Many
cybercafes, a popular way to access the Internet in the capital,
have not yet installed the AOL software on their computers.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage more users, AOL Mexico is also teaming up with
Compaq Computers to bundle a PC and Internet service for about $55
a month.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is also offering Mexican users a three-month trial period,
compared to the one month offered in the United States, before they
begin paying a monthly fee equivalent to $22.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for now it can be hard to find Mexican users on line. A
recent visit to AOL Mexico _ made by clicking on the Mexican flag
on the main page of the American service _ turned up mostly U.S.
residents.
</P>
<P>
   AOL customer Mary Marrero, a Puerto Rican living in Florida,
found the new site and logged on to find out what Mexicans were up
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans are very humble people. When we chat I spend most of
the time explaining the Spanish terms used in Puerto Rico,''
Marrero said in a chat room conversation.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail address is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
