<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-HEAT-500&AMP;ADD-N     07-14 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-HEAT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEATWAVE CONTINUES FROM ROMANIA TO SOUTHERN TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADAPARAZI, Turkey _ For Sevgi Pinarci and her family, the
scorching temperatures that swept Turkey and southeastern Europe
over the past 10 days amount to heaping insult on top of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Since a devastating earthquake last August destroyed their home,
Pinarci, her husband and their two children have been living in a
tiny two-room makeshift shanty in a rubble-filled vacant lot. There
is no electricity, no running water and no relief from temperatures
inside the shack that have reached more than 120 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard for the children to sleep because even at
midnight it's like the hot sun at noon,'' said Pinarci, 38, as her
husband, Omer, 39, and two sons, Kaan, 13, and Bahadir, 9, looked
on.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the region eased somewhat Friday, but the
effects of the prolonged heat wave were still being felt from
Romania to southern Turkey. Crops, already suffering from a summer
drought, were damaged further. Water levels in reservoirs dipped,
threatening irrigation and hydroelectric plants. And firefighters
continued to battle wild fires on both sides of the Aegean Sea in
Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the heat, with temperatures topping 100
degrees, the authorities in Romania and Bulgaria ordered trains to
stop running because they feared that tracks would buckle from the
heat. The only nuclear plant in Romania was temporarily shut down
after the temperature inside reached 158 degrees and set off
sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Croatia were declared natural disaster areas as the
effects of the drought on crops was magnified by soaring
temperatures. Officials predicted crop production would be 40
percent to 70 percent lower than last year as a result of the
weather. Crops were also damaged in other countries, including
Bulgaria, Romania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   In Greece, high temperatures and strong winds helped to ignite
and spread more than 100 wildfires and led Prime Minister Costas
Simitis to order emergency services on maximum alert. ``Every
available force has been mobilized, and we hope we can bring the
situation under control,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fire temporarily threatened the ancient town of Corinth, 50
miles southwest of Athens, and other blazes cast a brownish pall
over the capital city.
</P>
<P>
   The scorching heat has claimed at least 50 lives across
southeastern Europe and more than 20 in Turkey and sent hundreds of
people to hospitals. In Istanbul, the heat topped 110 degrees and
broke a 60-year-old record. In other parts of the country,
temperatures reached 130 degrees and higher.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit of Turkey ordered government
offices closed Thursday and Friday to lessen the danger to workers
and ease the drain on the country's electricity resources. In this
politically contentious country, even the prime minister's largess
could not escape criticism. Mehmet Yildirim, chairman of the
Istanbul Chamber of Commerce, told a local newspaper, ``If this
government was in Saudi Arabia it would declare all 365 days of the
year a vacation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Highways were so softened by the heat in parched central Turkey
that the Ministry of Public Works banned truck traffic during
daylight hours for two days because the vehicles were digging deep
gouges into the asphalt. Istanbul police were issued sunblock
lotion and sandals and permitted to take showers during short
breaks at the hottest times of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But few showers were available for the tens of thousands of
Turks who have been living in prefabricated houses, tent cities and
shanty towns since the earthquake Aug. 17 that killed at least
17,000 people and left as many as 500,000 homeless. While the
government quickly rebuilt main highways, progress has been slow in
returning people to damaged homes or building new housing in
affected areas.
</P>
<P>
   A government spokesman said there are 35 official tent cities,
housing about 30,000 people, throughout the region damaged by the
earthquake. But the officials figures do not count all of the
people who are still homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Adaparazi, a city of about 180,000 some 100 miles
southeast of Istanbul, the Pinarcis are among seven or eight
families who have built ramshackle homes on a vacant lot not far
from their damaged homes. They bring in fresh water by bottle, cook
with propane tanks and wash their clothes in plastic tubs.
</P>
<P>
   Even as temperatures moderated and slipped below triple digits
Friday, the darkened bedroom of their two-room shanty was stifling,
and a hot wind blew a layer of dust across everything in the open
kitchen area. Sitting at a plastic table beneath an umbrella
outside the shack, Omer Pinarci complained that they had been
unable to join hundreds of other families in government-provided
prefabricated houses because local authorities said their house was
not damaged enough. But he said the house is unsafe and he refused
to allow his wife and children to live there.
</P>
<P>
   Winter was difficult, he said, but the last 10 days of heat were
even worse. ``The heat has been very bad, very bad,'' he said
mournfully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
