<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-JERUSALEM-071     07-14 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-JERUSALEM-0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE FOR JERUSALEM ARABS AND JEWS ALREADY DIVIDED
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ On the crowded stone streets of Jerusalem's Old
City, Jews and Arabs live in the shadows of their holy sites.
Distrust runs high and the thought of sharing power among the two
peoples seems impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would need a lot of guns and a lot of military,'' says
Gavriel Hubara, a Torah scribe who lives in the Jewish Quarter.
``They will try to push us out.''
</P>
<P>
   But, walk through the gates in the Old City walls and drive 15
minutes north. You're still in Jerusalem and it's still controlled
by Israel, but Jews and Arabs casually move in separate realms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should give all their territories to them,'' says Dima
Ribo, an 18-year-old Jewish student in the neighborhood of Pisgat
Ze'ev. He does not have any contact with the Arab neighborhood a
few hundred yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators at the Camp David peace talks this weekend will
reportedly discuss sharing or dividing the city among Palestinians
and Israelis. It may be the most difficult of all the issues on
their agenda. Palestinians want a piece of a city that Israelis say
is entirely theirs, forever _ their ``eternal, undivided,
capital.''
</P>
<P>
   But life in Jerusalem is already divided in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   As of 1998, according to the Jerusalem Institute for Israel
Studies, the city was populated by 433,600 Jews and 200,100 Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   They live in a mosaic of segregated neighborhoods. Their
children attend separate schools with different curriculum and
weekends. They speak different languages, celebrate different
holidays and rarely interact socially.
</P>
<P>
   Jews rarely go to most Arab areas. Arab areas get short shrift _
even by Israeli officials' estimates _ to city services like road
work and trash pick-up.
</P>
<P>
   When a crime occurs, Palestinians sometimes turn for help to
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's West Bank security services,
which already operate secretly in some areas of the city.
</P>
<P>
   In the primarily Arab Old City, the religious symbols and exotic
bazaars draw Israeli worshippers and shoppers by the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   But, in other areas, troops in flak jackets are about the only
regular Israeli visitors. They shout orders at the locals from
bullhorns on their jeeps.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the Camp David summit say the variation within the
city could lead to practical solutions for peace. The key is to
separate the emotional, symbolic issues from practical ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often, Jerusalem is presented in mystical terms that have
very little to do with reality,'' Daniel Seidemann, a peace
activist and expert on Jerusalem, says. ``Some of the political
arrangements that could be put into place do not require creating a
new reality but just recognizing the existing one.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls Israel's rule ``virtual sovereignty,'' because in many
Arab areas Israeli officials have little daily involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli peace activists say separate and joint political
arrangements could be set up in different areas of the city. They
would be placed depending on how important the areas are to Jews,
what the local Arabs want and how easy they are to separate.
</P>
<P>
   That angers Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert, who says the Camp David
talks should not allow any ``joint administration, joint
sovereignty or joint anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Olmert, who also opposed the historic Camp David agreement
between Israel and Egypt 22 years ago, says division in Jerusalem
would lead to confusion and fighting among adjacent authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leaders, meanwhile, seek to capitalize on the
divisions in daily life as justifications for getting Israel out of
the Arab neighborhoods, roughly in eastern parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those declarations by your leaders about Israeli
sovereignty in East Jerusalem are nonsense,'' Palestinian Cabinet
Minister Ziad Abu Zayyad told the Israeli newspaper Yedioth
Ahronoth.
</P>
<P>
   The city was split in 1948. When the British rule ended, Israel
was formed and Arab armies attacked to try to quash the birth of
the Jewish state. Israel held on to the western side. For almost 30
years, Jews lost access to their holy sites in the Old City. Then,
Israel captured the Old City and the east from Jordan in the 1967
war.
</P>
<P>
   But, most countries keep their embassies outside the city and do
not recognize Israel's claim to the captured areas.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking a final peace agreement, the hardest problem is the
Old City, with about 2,900 Jews and more than 22,000 Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   There, the Western Wall, sacred to Jews, forms a retaining
foundation for a campus that was once the site of ancient temples
central to Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the campus above the wall is home to the Dome of the Rock
and Al-Aqsa mosques, sacred to Muslims who believe it is land where
the Prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Even here, though, power is already shared. Israel rules but
gives day-to-day control over the mosques to Palestinians. Jews can
pray at the wall, but access for Israelis to the campus above is
tightly controlled.
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of the city, Arab and Jewish neighborhoods spread
out. Some are separated by rocky valleys, while others abut.
</P>
<P>
   If the lines were ever clear, they became especially confused
after 1967. An Israeli building program put 10 neighborhoods and
about 150,000 Jews on the east side to divide the Arab population
there.
</P>
<P>
   They live apart from their Arab neighbors in culture, politics
and most everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Most Arabs in Jerusalem are not Israeli citizens _ though at
times Israel has offered citizenship. They cannot vote in Israeli
national elections but were allowed to vote in Palestinian
Authority elections in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Zakarya Abu Sirrieh, 58, lives in one of three Arab homes at the
dead end of a street in Jewish Pisgat Ze'ev. He was here before the
Jewish community was built in the late 1980s and says his lingering
presence is a ``fork in their throat.''
</P>
<P>
   He only knows the names of two of his Jewish neighbors and
occasionally visits with one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our values are different from theirs,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   When he wanted to add on to his house, he borrowed money not
from an Israeli bank but from the Orient House, the office in
Jerusalem that acts as a branch of the PLO.
</P>
<P>
   But, if Israeli leaders might exaggerate their control over the
city, Palestinian leaders may overstate the desire of Jerusalem
Arabs to join the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jerusalem Palestinians say they enjoy Israeli health
insurance and fear paying higher taxes to Arafat's authority.
</P>
<P>
   Most feel mistreated by the Israelis, but wary of the incipient
and somewhat chaotic Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only solution in the Old City will be some kind of U.N.
control because neither side will give up their religious places,''
says Arab Mohammed Hamad, 42, who owns a grocery in the Old City's
Jewish Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, a Jewish boy in a skullcap entered to buy chocolate
milk and paused to write the amount on a tab his family keeps
there. Arab women in headscarves browsed the aisles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very, complicated,'' the grocer says. ``If you know
how to relate to people, you can make it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information about Jerusalem:
</P>
<P>
   www.jiis.org.il (Jerusalem Institute for Israel Studies)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
