<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2181 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-SHACKLETON-EXHIBIT-BO     07-14 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHACKLETON-EXHIBIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT RE-CREATES PART OF THE SHACKLETON EXPEDITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, Mass. _ Just when visitors may think they have wrung all
the drama out of the Endurance exhibition chronicling the legendary
Shackleton expedition to the Antarctic, they are challenged to
imagine its ultimate feat of heroic endeavor and nautical skill.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1914 the British expedition _ led by Ernest Shackleton
and including a team of sailors and scientists _ set off on the
ship Endurance in an attempt to cross the Antarctic continent by
foot.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton did not succeed in that, but at the moment of
failure, he accomplished the even greater feat that secured his
place in nautical history. He sailed a small lifeboat with a
five-man crew across 800 miles of storm-wracked southern ocean to
obtain rescue for the remaining expedition members, marooned on a
frozen and desolate island.
</P>
<P>
   The Endurance exhibition, which originated at the American
Museum of Natural History in New York, is now at the Peabody Essex
Museum here. In a darkened room sits a replica of the James Caird,
the 22-foot-6-inch decked lifeboat that Shackleton and his crew
sailed to the whaling station on tiny South Georgia Island in their
desperate rescue mission.
</P>
<P>
   To have missed that landfall would have doomed not only the men
in the James Caird, but also almost certainly the men left behind
on Elephant Island. Yet to find the island in the raging, trackless
ocean required navigational skill of the highest order, with no
Loran or GPS or other modern-day navigational aid, just a delicate
hand-held sextant, dependent on the navigator's ability to be held
steady in the rolling and pitching boat.
</P>
<P>
   So in that darkened room, behind the replica of the James Caird,
heaving ocean waves are projected, and the visitor is challenged to
imagine taking a noon sighting with sextants mounted on pedestals.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, says curator Daniel Finamore, ``to really capture the
experience, those pedestals would have to be bouncing up and down
and we'd be splashing cold salty water over you.''
</P>
<P>
   However realistic that might make the experience, adds
co-curator Caroline Alexander, it cannot convey the full nature of
the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The higher the class of experience you have,'' says Alexander,
``the greater the sense of awe and bafflement.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has spoken with ocean sailors, people who have
experienced the difficulty of navigating under storm conditions,
and, she says, ``they can't begin to explain how that navigation
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, a freelance writer who lives in New Hampshire,
developed an ``obsessive interest'' in the Shackleton expedition
after reading his own account, ``South.'' She organized this
exhibit for the natural history museum in New York and has served
as co-curator for its subsequent showings in Washington, D.C., and
here.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the exhibit _ setting the stage for the few moments
of imagined nautical heroics _ is the pictures taken by the
expedition's photographer, Frank Hurley.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander used Hurley's photographs to illustrate ``The
Endurance: Shackleton's Legendary Antarctic Expedition,'' her 1998
account of the expedition. While Shackleton is ``the star of the
bigger story,'' she says, ``Hurley is the star of the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley was an adventure-loving Australian photographer _
Alexander calls him ``gifted and gritty.'' Shackleton was banking
on his photographs to illustrate the books and lectures that would
repay the backers of the expedition.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Hurley was forced to abandon much of his work when
the Endurance, trapped in the ice, finally sank. Shackleton ordered
the glass negatives destroyed to prevent Hurley from trying to
salvage them.
</P>
<P>
   But what remains _ 150 are in the Peabody Essex show _
represents what Alexander calls ``one of the great feats of
photography.'' They are ``world-class images,'' she says, for ``a
world-class story.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley's still photographs have illustrated numerous accounts of
the expedition. Less well known is the fact that he also had a
movie camera. His footage of the men working on the ice with their
sled dogs after the ship was trapped gives a human dimension to the
story. And the footage of the ship's final days, augmented with
animation, is grim, even terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is prepared for that,'' says Alexander. ``Even if they
know about the loss of the Endurance, it is a real blow to see the
crushing by the ice as it unfolds.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the story leaves a ``sense of awe and of what is
wonderful _ awe of the landscape and awe of the human saga,'' she
says. ``It is a story you want to tell somebody. It is not a story
you want to sit with in silence. You want to discuss it. You want
to play it out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Endurance exhibit runs through Sept. 10. The Peabody Essex
Museum is located on East India Square in Salem, adjacent to both
the MBTA commuter rail station and municipal parking. It is open
Monday through Saturday from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., and Sunday, noon to
5 p.m. Admission is $10, $8 for seniors and students over 16, free
for children 16 and under. For information, call 978-745-9500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1606EDT &QL; 
