<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2183 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ESTATE-TAX15-COX     07-14 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-TAX15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE PASSES ESTATE TAX REPEAL, MOVES ON TO 'MARRIAGE PENALTY'
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Setting up a pair of politically charged
confrontations with President Clinton, the Senate approved a bill
Friday to phase out the federal estate tax and immediately began
work on erasing the ``marriage penalty'' tax.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has pledged to veto the estate tax bill. In a sharply
worded statement from Camp David on Friday, he called it a
``budget-busting ... irresponsible and regressive bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said half of the bill's benefits would go to about 3,000
families, ``while more than 10 million Americans are waiting for an
increase in the minimum wage and tens of millions of seniors lack
dependable prescription drug coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The 59-39 vote fell eight votes short of the two-thirds needed
to override a veto. Nine Democrats voted for the measure, while
four Republicans voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the bill last month by a margin large enough
to override a veto.
</P>
<P>
   A final Senate vote on eliminating the marriage penalty could
come early next week. The bill, which would cost the government
$248 billion over 10 years, would modifying a quirk in the income
tax law that results in about 25 million two-income married couples
paying higher taxes than they would if unmarried and filing
separately.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the marriage bill for a second time Wednesday
under rules designed to restrict Senate debate and amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also criticized this bill, but recently offered
Republicans a deal in which he would accept it if they accepted his
proposal for a prescription drug benefit under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hope to force Clinton into taking action on both
popular tax-cutting bills before their national convention begins
July 31 in Philadelphia. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
presumptive nominee, strongly supports both measures.
</P>
<P>
   Before the final vote on the estate tax bill, senators removed a
series of amendments added over the last two days that were
designed primarily as political ammunition for senators seeking
re-election this year.
</P>
<P>
   The dropped amendments would have:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ended the 3 percent telephone excise tax.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rolled back the amount of Social Security payments eligible
for taxation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Given research and development investments by businesses
permanent tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hailed passage of the estate tax bill as a major
accomplishment and called on Clinton to join them in eliminating
what they call the ``death tax.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When this morning is over, the death tax will be on its way to
the dustbin of history, where it belongs,'' Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott said shortly before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the estate tax and the marriage penalty, GOP Whip
Don Nickles said, ``these two taxes are the most unfair taxes we
have on the books. You shouldn't be penalized for death, and you
shouldn't be penalized for marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would raise the threshold for the maximum 55 percent
tax rate from $3 million to $3.675 million next year, while
gradually reducing the top rate to 40.5 percent by 2009. The tax
would be repealed in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argued that repealing the estate tax would allow
families the option of deciding when to liquidate a parent's assets
by shifting the time when a property was taxed from when it was
inherited to when it was sold. Assets left from one spouse to
another are exempt from taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, noted that among family businesses
which have existed for at least five years, 70 percent do not
survive to a second generation and 80 percent do not make it to a
third. He attributed that largely to the estate tax, which has a 55
percent top rate on assets over $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also eliminates over 10 years the federal tax on gifts
in excess of $10,000 and the generation-skipping tax, which taxes
certain assets left from a grandparent to a grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected to cost $105 billion during the first 10 years
and $750 billion during the next 10 years, when it would be fully
implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argued during the debate that the Republican plan was
geared primarily to the rich and would do little to aid small
businesses and family farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The estate tax affects about 2 percent of the households filing
income taxes. About half of those have assets in excess of $5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., suggested that because of the high
cost, Congress would back away from repealing the estate tax before
the bill was fully implemented, leaving lower rates for the
wealthiest without helping small businesses and family farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us agree we should essentially repeal the estate tax
for small businesses and family farmers ... but the Republicans
insist on repealing the estate tax for the wealthiest estates in
America,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats offered an alternative plan that would have raised the
individual exemption from $675,000 to $2 million by 2010. It would
have raised the exemption on a family-owned business or farm from
$2.6 million per couple to $8 million per couple by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic alternative, which would have cost the government
$64 billion in lost revenues over a decade, was rejected Thursday
by a vote of 46-53.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
