<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-VIDEO-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I SHOULD NOT BE A CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
 By BOB MORRIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Making a good home video of a party isn't for the thin-skinned.
I learned this the hard way last weekend in Vermont at a big
backyard party given by some friends turning 40. With a borrowed
camcorder, I intended to make a tape as a gift and went around
asking guests to share reflections.
</P>
<P>
   The witty brother of one of the celebrants refused flat out and
suggested I shoot his new car instead. A friend who isn't shy told
me to go away, and others turned their backs. Then someone stuck
his hand over the camera lens, Sean Penn-style, and I turned the
thing off and got a stiff drink. What was going on here?
</P>
<P>
   Robert Frost wrote, ``Something there is that doesn't love a
wall.'' The same, I guess, can be said about a camera. It's hard to
imagine it in this moment of pervasive reality TV and voyeuristic
talk shows, with people sharing and oversharing at the least
provocation. John De Mol, the creator of ``Big Brother,'' told
Newsweek that if he announced a show of 10 people on an airplane
with only nine parachutes, applicants would line up to risk death
as long as it was televised. So why did so many of my friends
resent being taped?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the distrust goes back to ``An American Family,'' the
1973 documentary on PBS that was so devastating to the Loud family.
Perhaps people don't know where the tape will end up. Who, for
instance, would know that those homey home videos of Elian Gonzalez
would be seen on TV screens across America?
</P>
<P>
   Was it Diane Arbus or Frederick Wiseman, with their cool, cruel
eyes, who fueled the distrust? ``When you stick your nose in the
faces of some people,'' a friend who made documentaries in film
school tolds me, ``they're going to want to bite it off. Not
everyone's going to react well to your stealing a piece of their
soul with your camera.''
</P>
<P>
   I know what she means. Recently, I was mortified to watch a
travel photographer treat a Saint's Day procession on Sardinia as
if it were a runway show. No wonder Susan Sontag has likened the
shooting of a camera to the shooting of a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe people thought I was being inauthentic _ that some
experiences should be enjoyed for what they are, not captured
through a lens. A friend who works at a public access TV station
didn't want a video of her own wedding. ``I prefer to remember it
as I experienced it,'' she said, ``not as a sequence of images
captured by a camera.'' OK, but what about eight-millimeter home
movies, those lovely, silent reminders of our radiant pasts? Are
they more meaningful because there's no sound?
</P>
<P>
   When I got home and reviewed my tape of the party, I was shocked
to find myself a noisy presence, prodding each person from behind
the camera. Carrying a tiki torch for lighting, I had invaded the
hot tub near the orchard, which did not go over well with the group
of women in it, although they did manage to say meaningful things,
even while wrapped in towels. One woman trying to reminisce about
our birthday boy's band at high school dances could hardly get a
word in for all my interrupting.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the tape is not about a lovely party, but about me
being an intrusive guest. The lesson is that you have to let your
subjects take you where they want to go. That's what real reality
TV would be. And that's how good documentarians (and polite people)
move about in the world.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder how Ricky, the video-obsessed neighbor in ``American
Beauty'' who captured that plastic bag dancing in the wind so
poetically, would have recorded this party. I wonder if I can have
my rude voice edited out before giving the tape to my friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're scripting every moment,'' one man told me as he looked
into the camera. ``You have a poetic urge to dominate.'' It's a
judgment that's all the more brutal because it's true. I'm not
sure, though, if it makes me want to work through my intense
control issues or simply work them. Maybe the only thing I've
realized, having played Big Brother for a night, is that what I
really want to do is what everybody else wants to do in this
I-am-a-camera-crazed culture: direct.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
