<HEADER>
A2189 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-WHITMAN-PHOTO-NEWHOUS     07-14 2051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITMAN-PHOTO-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW PLAYING COP CAME BACK TO HAUNT NEW JERSEY GOVERNOR
</HEADLINE>
   (Attention editors: For information about purchasing this article
as a separate-buy, contact Debra Weydert of the New York Times
Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail:
weyded(at)nytimes.com.)
 By KATHY BARRETT CARTER 
 And BRIAN DONOHUE 
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. -- Sporting a wide grin, the governor of New
Jersey is shown patting down a young black male on the streets of
Camden during a 1996 State Police drug sweep. The picture is grainy
and unfocused, like a home snapshot.
</P>
<P>
   But the reaction in the week since the photograph was published
has been anything but unfocused.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans say the image shows the governor to be
insensitive and proves she does not understand how deep racism runs
in the State Police. State troopers and their supporters say it
exposes the governor as a hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   This week Gov. Christie Whitman said she regretted the decision
to frisk the unarmed suspect, but stopped short of an apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mistake moving from just an observer to
participating,'' Whitman said at a news conference in Princeton.
``I shouldn't have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   The following account of how the photograph was taken and how it
came into public view is taken from more than a dozen interviews
with state troopers, lawyers and state officials, many of whom
insisted that they not be named. It is the story of an admittedly
naive governor whose anticrime zeal led her into a racially charged
situation that, four years later, has come back to haunt her at a
time of maximum political embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-May 1996, an elite unit of the New Jersey State Police
was in the midst of a five-month project designed to get drug
dealers off the streets of Camden, the state's poorest city.
Because it was raining that night and there was little action on
the streets, troopers had returned to their rally site, the
Bellmawr New Jersey State Police Barracks, just outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   Over pizza and beer, the several troopers talked about the big
news of the day: Whitman was coming to Camden the following night
to ride along with the State Police drug-busters.
</P>
<P>
   A trooper and a lawyer familiar with the gathering that night
say Capt. Edgar Hess, head of the operation, threw out a challenge:
Anyone who got a picture of the governor frisking a suspect in
Camden would get a week's vacation. (Hess has denied that he made
such an offer.)
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Whitman, like many governors in statehouses
around the country, was intent on being a law-and-order chief
executive. She was opening boot camps for juvenile offenders,
pushing tougher anti-drug laws through the Legislature and, in
recent days, had been focusing on the troubles in Camden.
</P>
<P>
   With the homicide rate spiraling out of control, then-Camden
Mayor Arnold Webster had personally pleaded with Whitman to send
the State Police in to help patrol the streets of the crime-ridden
city. Col. Carl Williams, superintendent of the New Jersey State
Police, had objected.
</P>
<P>
   He did not have the officers to spare, he said, and he feared it
might cause tension between local police and the state police.
Other cities might make similar requests, William said, and it
would be difficult to retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in comments about the photo, Williams said, ``It was
not my idea for the governor to do this. I was against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was overruled by the governor's office and state
troopers were dispatched to Camden. From January to late May 1996,
troopers from throughout South Jersey were selected from various
sections and units to work regular sweeps against local drug
dealers. The effort was called the Camden City Initiative, CCI for
short.
</P>
<P>
   The troopers combed the streets of Camden, frisking young men,
raiding drug dens and attempting to restore order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was basically report-free,'' said one trooper, explaining
that the unusual freedom the troopers were given made CCI a
sought-after assignment. Troopers just stopped people, and if they
found something illegal, they turned the person over to the Camden
Police, the trooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no paperwork. It was just a show of force,'' the
trooper said.
</P>
<P>
   When troopers learned Whitman would be coming, they were
encouraged, he said. They felt she was sanctioning their mission
and that they did not have to worry about getting any heat later
for anything that occurred in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was giving us more rope,'' said a trooper who works in the
Bellmawr barracks. Getting the Whitman photo was seen as a lark, a
sort of frat-house prank or game.
</P>
<P>
   During her two-day tour of the city, Whitman jumped in with both
feet. She wore a bulletproof vest, went into crack houses and stood
by as troopers conducted searches.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 p.m. on her second night in Camden, six troopers
accompanied by Whitman pulled up to the corner of Lansdowne Avenue
and Rose Street in two vans, one blue, one white. A group of young
black men had gathered around the stoop of a shuttered bar.
</P>
<P>
   Quayson Davis -- ``Q,'' to friends -- said he was one of the
young men at the scene that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were chillin'. We was drinking. We weren't bothering Mrs.
Whitman or nothing,'' said Davis, now 19. They were rounded up and
told to stand with their palms against the graffiti-riddled side of
the building as the State Police officers frisked each one.
</P>
<P>
   When troopers urged her to pose for a photograph while patting
down an African-American male stopped on a city street, Whitman
agreed, troopers say. But she had one condition. She wanted gloves,
one trooper at the scene says.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to get the prize photograph, troopers quickly supplied the
governor with a pair of black Kevlar gloves, special bulletproof
gloves used in police work.
</P>
<P>
   Donning her gloves, Whitman, dressed in a white jump suit, was
happy to respond to the photo request, troopers recall.
</P>
<P>
   Davis says the man Whitman patted down was last in line at the
wall. His name, Davis says, is Sherron ``Ron G'' Rolax, who was
just shy of his 17th birthday. Rolax's uncle, Anthony English,
confirmed that his nephew had told him about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Rolax was not arrested that night. He was found to have no drugs
in his possession. But, according to state records, he is now in
the Mountain View Youth Correctional Facility in Annandale on 1998
drug charges. Rolax, now 21, refused to comment for this article.
</P>
<P>
   When Whitman began patting down Rolax, Trooper Joseph Senatore
was ready with the camera, according to troopers familiar with the
operation. A classmate of Hess' who stands an imposing 6 feet 6
inches tall, Senatore, now 48, whipped out a Polaroid and began
snapping away. He handed a photo to Whitman but she declined,
troopers recall, allegedly saying, ``Keep it as a souvenir.''
</P>
<P>
   Senatore refused to comment on the photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Lt. Col. Robert Dunlop, who held the rank of major at
the time, had been assigned the role of setting up the Camden
program.
</P>
<P>
   He does not believe he was on duty that night in Camden, but
does not specifically remember. He does recall hearing that
Senatore took the
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I do know that,'' Dunlop said in an interview. He said
never saw the photo until it was printed in newspapers, but had
heard of it shortly after it was taken.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, he said, the photo was seen as an innocent
memento of the governor chumming around with the troopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was anything other than she was doing a
ride-along with the troopers. She had come to Camden to show
support to the troopers, the murder rate was up to 60 and it was
almost a lawless town,'' said Dunlop.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of Whitman's two-day visit, then-Attorney
General Deborah Poritz, who is now chief justice of the New Jersey
Supreme Court, tagged along, as did John Whitman, the governor's
husband. Ex-State Police head Williams Thursday said Poritz and
Peter Verniero, then-chief counsel and now a justice in the Poritz
court, were along for the ride the night the photo was taken.
Whitman, Poritz and Verniero all denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   After that night in Camden, Senatore held on to his photograph.
Other troopers say they saw it. ``It was passed around like a pack
of Marlboros,'' recalled one, but it eventually faded to the
background of troopers' memories.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in late 1998 and 1999, the force found itself embroiled in
charges of racial profiling and internal discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   As scrutiny of the State Police intensified, Senatore decided to
turn the photo over to an attorney for safekeeping, according to a
law enforcement source.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Moran, a Mount Holly lawyer who is suing the State
Police on behalf of dozens black state troopers, heard about the
photo earlier this year. Several weeks ago he began asking for a
copy of it from Attorney General John Farmer Jr., saying it was
relevant to his claims against the state.
</P>
<P>
   At first the Attorney General's Office told Moran that it was
not aware of any such photo. It added that Moran did not need to
file a subpoena, but could simply ask for it as part of the
discovery process.
</P>
<P>
   But, law enforcement sources said, the attorney general's
investigators began looking for the photo. They assumed that if
such a the one in Camden. But the State Police said their
photographers had taken no such photos.
</P>
<P>
   It was then, sources said, that several troopers remembered
Senatore and his photos.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:45 p.m. July 3, the day when the Attorney General's Office
was supposed to respond to Moran's request, Senatore was asked by
state officials to give up the photograph. He referred them to his
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next is not clear. But within days, the photograph
ended up in the hands of a national wire service reporter, John
McAlpin of the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman officials say privately that the release of the photo
makes it obvious that Whitman's enemies wanted it published at the
moment it would do the greatest damage to her just weeks before the
Republican National Convention was scheduled to kick off across the
river in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to the photo makes it clear that after two years of
attempting to reform the State Police, Whitman has few friends in
the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   One trooper said some troopers are so angry with Whitman they
would do anything to embarrass her. They had even discussed putting
the the caption: ``Arrive on vacation. Leave on probation.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't have a friend in the State Police on either
side,'' said the trooper. Many white troopers remain angry with the
governor, the trooper said.
</P>
<P>
   She angered them by admitting racial profiling, firing Williams,
and hiring Col. Carson Dunbar, the first African-American to serve
as State Police superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment of two white troopers charged with attempted
murder in connection with the April 1998 New Jersey Turnpike
shooting of three unarmed minority men further hurt her relations
with white troopers, a black trooper said.
</P>
<P>
   But some black troopers are not happy with Whitman's
administration either. They are irate that the state continues to
refuse to settle civil rights lawsuits brought by dozens of black
troopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are enjoying watching her twist in the wind,'' the
trooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an elite unit,'' the trooper said of the CCI unit on
duty in Camden that night. ``There were no black troopers in it.
The white troopers took the picture, held the picture and released
the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Steve Rogers, president of the New Jersey Community
Policing Association, said he feels no sympathy for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is getting what happened to Carl Williams,'' he said.
``For months she has been politicizing this issue by painting a bad
picture of the New Jersey State Police.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we see a bad picture of her on the front page of The
Star-Ledger'' of Newark, Rogers said. ``The governor will now know
how it feels to be falsely accused of being a racist.'' KC END
CARTER/DONOHUE (Kathy Barrett Carter and Brian Donohue are staff
writers for The Star-Ledger of Newark N.J. Staff writer David
Kinney contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
