<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CAMPING IN NORTHERN CALIFORNIA: TEEPEES, BOATS AND YURTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Camping doesn't get any stranger than this, and
for many who have tried, it doesn't get any better.
</P>
<P>
   At Lake Oroville, Calif., there are these strange, double-decker
floating camps, kind of like giant patio boats without motors,
along with floating bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out there are several camping options available for a
strange and usually wonderful experience across Northern
California, including teepees at two private campgrounds and a yurt
at a state park. Any can add new dimensions to a summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters for unusual camping opportunities is at Lake
Oroville, the giant reservoir in the foothills of the Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   The first time you see the double-decker floating camps, you
might think they are a weird-looking houseboat. Nope. It more
closely resembles a floating group camp. They sleep 15 people and
include picnic table, sink, food locker, life jackets, garbage can,
vault toilet, propane barbecue and water (not suitable for
drinking). It costs $85 a night during the week, $125 a night on
weekends and holidays, but get this, next year the cost will go
down to $42 a night, and it will be the best family camping deal in
the state. A comparative experience on an anchored houseboat at
Lake Shasta can cost $3,000 a week, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you need a boat to get there. But that provided, it
is ideal. You have all day to fish, ski, explore or just play in
the water, then return to your floating camp for meals, sleeping or
just to hang out.
</P>
<P>
   After all, you're on vacation, right? Oroville is an outstanding
lake for water sports, with warm water and plenty of room and also
has excellent bass fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Oroville has 10 floating camps. Reservations are available at
(800) 444-7275 or Web site: www.cal-parks.ca.gov. For information,
call the Lake Oroville Visitor Center at (530) 538-2219 or the Lake
Oroville State Recreation Area at (530) 538-2200.
</P>
<P>
   For boaters, Oroville also has a series of dispersed boat-in
camp sites around the lake. Of course, there are about 20 lakes
that offer boat-in camping in Northern California. The best
opportunities are at Bullards Bar Reservoir east of Marysville.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the few lakes in the Sierra Nevada to offer
boat-in camping at developed boat-in sites and to allow boaters to
create their own primitive sites anywhere along the lake's
shoreline. A chemical toilet is required gear for boat-in shoreline
camping. A developed boat-in site is also available. It is called
Garden Point, located on the western shore of the northern Yuba
River arm. For information, call Emerald Cove Resort and Marina,
(530) 692-3200.
</P>
<P>
   You say that's not strange enough for you?
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are also camps with teepees and another with a yurt.
</P>
<P>
   The two camps with teepees are privately operated: Yogi Bear
Beaver Creek RV Park (real name, seriously), located in the
foothills of Lake County south of Clear Lake, and at Stewart
Mineral Springs, located adjacent to the west flank of Mount
Shasta.
</P>
<P>
   Yogi Bear Camp has two teepees and four cabins to go with the
standard RV and tent sites common at drive-to camps, and this is
the closest location to the Bay Area where you can camp in a
teepee. This is a good camp to bring youngsters, with a pond with
canoes and kayaks available, a trout creek and trails for hiking
and birding. Horseback riding is also available nearby. But you say
you want strange? You can also arrange for a ride in a hot-air
balloon nearby.
</P>
<P>
   This camp is located near Highway 175 between Middletown and
Clear Lake near Cobb Mountain. The teepees cost $25 per night and
sleep up to five. For information, phone (707) 928-4322 or check
out their Web site at www.campyogi.com.
</P>
<P>
   Stewarts Spring is better known for its mineral spring baths,
and a following among the ``new-age people.'' It's almost like a
cult here, but the headquarters is a 100-year-old lodge with
cabins, apartments and, yep, teepees. The rite of passage is
getting boiled in a mineral bath, or sweating in a sauna, then
jumping in cold Parks Creek, which runs through the center of the
property.
</P>
<P>
   The park is located in forest in the foothills of Mount Eddy,
facing Mount Shasta. Views are nearby, though not available from
the park itself.
</P>
<P>
   For information, phone (530) 938-2222.
</P>
<P>
   But if only a yurt will do, then you must head to Patricks Point
State Park.
</P>
<P>
   What's a yurt? Actually, yurts are common in the Pacific
Northwest, where it rains so much, and that should tell you
everything you need to know. A yurt is a camping platform with a
roof to keep the rain and coastal moisture from fog off you while
you sleep. And you can get one at Patricks Point.
</P>
<P>
   Patricks Point is a beautiful place, filled with Sitka spruce
and offering an easy, beautiful hiking trail with coastal lookouts
and access to several private beaches. It's also a great place to
see passing whales.
</P>
<P>
   At the north end of the park, a short hike to see the bizarre
``Octopus Trees'' is one of the strangest walks around, with trees
that are growing atop downed logs, their root-system exposed like
octopus tentacles. A Native American village has been constructed
by the Yurok tribe here.
</P>
<P>
   Staying in the yurt here costs $40 per night, available by
reservation at (800) 444-7275. Starting Jan. 1, the fee will be cut
in half. For information, phone the park at (707) 677-3570.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2200 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-CO     07-14 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Anytime is a good time to make hay
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I was standing in front of the tire store where
my Cousin Bubba works, waiting on him to get off for lunch and
listening to a couple of fellows talking about haying.
</P>
<P>
   You might not think that hay means much to you, personally, and
maybe it doesn't. Maybe you're somebody who doesn't care much,
personally, about a good hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   Hay just happens to be the main ingredient, lower down the food
chain, for hamburgers, not to mention thick, juicy steaks.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you're going to have meat on the table, somewhere you
have to have beef on the hoof and hay on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   And wherever you have hay, you have problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even when it's been a good year for hay, that can be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   If you have more hay than you can use, you sell what you don't
need. Problem is, when there's a lot of hay, the price is low. You
can lose money on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   If it's been a bad year for hay, you won't have enough. Then
you'll have to buy extra. Problem is, when there's not much hay,
the price is high. It'll cost you dearly.
</P>
<P>
   Hereabouts, it's been a pretty good year. Well, so far, anyway.
That's as close as any farmer will ever admit to a good year.
</P>
<P>
   The county has enjoyed a better than normal rainfall. The ag
agent hasn't had very many calls about army worms. All and all, the
hay crop is sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Well, so far, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Last year started out good. Then it quit raining July 20, and
seemed like it was never going to start up again.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, we're in a two-week drought. The ground is drying out
and beginning to crack, young shade trees are showing stress, pond
levels are dropping.
</P>
<P>
   Make hay while the sun shines, they'll tell you. Better that you
made yours while we were still getting some rain.
</P>
<P>
   Countywide, we have about 6,000 acres in hay, out of 60,000
acres of forage production, out of a county that's 600,000 acres in
size.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, it's Bermuda grass and Bahia grass. Horses like Bermuda
better, with its higher protein value. Bahia is more drought
resistant, and cows can get along on it.
</P>
<P>
   Cows have four stomachs, you know, and horses just the one. It
takes four stomachs to stomach Bahia.
</P>
<P>
   You know Bahia when you see it, even if you don't know what it
is. Bahia has a forked seed stem that looks like a ``Y'' sticking
up.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad about invading lawns. You can mow it down one day, and
it'll be grown back three days later.
</P>
<P>
   A bale of hay, if you happen to be in the market, costs about
$2.50. Figuring by the pound, that seems cheap enough. A bale of
hay -- four-feet long, two-feet wide and two-feet thick _ weighs
60-65 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the old fashion bale. Nowadays, hay is baled in huge
rolls, taller than a tall man, and looking like giant pieces of
shredded wheat breakfast cereal.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for baling in rolls, like most anything else, is
economics.
</P>
<P>
   A roll weighs 1,000 to 1,500 pounds, and requires no more time
and effort for the hay fork operator to pick up than a regular
bale. You're saving a lot in labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   And that ain't hay.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. For lunch, instead of hamburgers, my Cousin Bubba and I had
a salad. That's because we're both trying to cut down the size of
our girth. Right now either of us look like we could get along on
Bahia grass, what with our four stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
