<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2202 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-VOTERS15-COX     07-14 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VOTERS SHOWING RECORD LEVEL OF APATHY
 &HT;    460&AMP;add. With VOTERS-DATA Moving in (w) Washington and (p)
politics categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Voters are more disengaged in the presidential race
this year than at any time in recent history, according to an
extensive survey of American attitudes towards politics released
Friday by a non-partisan research group.
</P>
<P>
   Good economic times and a sense that there is little difference
between Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush has lulled
voters into ``a rather pleasant sleep,'' said pollster Andrew
Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center for the People and the
Press.
</P>
<P>
   The flagging voter interest could be an indication that turnout
this fall may sink to a new low, Kohut said. In 1996, only 49
percent of eligible citizens cast ballots, the first time in more
than 70 years that less than half of voters went to the polls to
elect a president.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew poll found that fewer than half of registered voters _
46 percent _ said they have thought a lot about the election, a
decline from 55 percent in 1996 and 63 percent in the same period
in 1992. The drop-off in voter interest and familiarity with the
candidates is especially pronounced in young and middle-age adults.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good chance that turnout will drop below the 1996
level, and ``it seems virtually certain,'' Kohut said, that it will
be lower than the 55 percent of voters who came to the polls in
1992, when Bill Clinton defeated incumbent George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Yet paradoxically, Americans said they are more satisfied with
their choice of presidential candidates this year, and they are
less critical of the way the campaigns are being conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, 73 percent expressed satisfaction with the
candidates compared to 49 percent in 1996, when former Sen. Bob
Dole won the GOP nomination to challenge President Clinton.
Sixty-six percent of Democrats said they were satisfied this year,
compared to 56 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The poll concluded that the race between Bush and Gore remains
wide open as the candidates head to the nominating conventions next
month. The survey found that likely voters are split between Gore
and Bush _ 47 percent each, with 6 percent undecidrty candidates
Ralph Nader and Pat Buchanan will not have much impact on the race,
Kohut said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans increasingly believe that the election of the
president is not as important as it was a decade or two ago, the
poll found. Nearly half of Americans _ 49 percent _ believe things
will pretty much stay the same no matter who is elected.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew survey, conducted among 2,174 adults June 14-28 with a
margin of error of plus or minus 2.5 percentage points, mirrors
other recent polls which indicated that voters see little
differences in the two major candidates.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   This is despite their divergence on issues such as government
spending and social issues such as abortion and gun control and
whom each might pick to fill expected vacancies on the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is in play, but it would seem from our polling data
that American voters are dissatisfied, distracted or just don't
care,'' said Stephen Hess, a scholar on government and the media at
the Brookings Institution, a Washington policy center.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew survey found that fewer respondents are following news
about the campaign than did during the same period in 1996 and
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kohut also noted that the degree of voter interest could
change dramatically after the nominating conventions and if Gore
can energize Democratic and independent voters. He also said the
current voter disinterest could be due, in part, to the early
victories on Gore and Bush in the primaries that has created a lull
in media attention on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush enjoys an ``enthusiasm edge,'' with a greater proportion of
voters who described themselves as Republicans supporting him than
do Democrats who say they support Gore. Only 47 percent Democrats
said they strongly support Gore, compared with 56 percent of
Republicans who counted themselves as strong supporters of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, a slim majority of voters, no matter who they support,
said they believe Bush will win the election. Fifty-one percent
predicted that Bush will win, compared to 34 percent who said Gore
and 15 percent who said they do not know.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents ranked Bush higher on leadership abilities, while
giving Gore the edge on key issues important to voters, such as
education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of just how fluid voters attitudes can be, the Pew
survey, conducted over a two-week period, detected a significant
shift in support from Gore. Between June 14-21, Gore led Bush 42
percent to 41 percent, with 10 percent undecided. The following
week, amid news reports that a recommendation had been made for an
independent counsel to probe the vice president's 1996 campaign
finance activities, Gore fell to 35 percent compared to Bush's 42
percent, with 19 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   The Pew Research Center for the People and the Press:
www.people-press.org
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
