<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2204 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-PEACE-$ADV16-     07-14 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PEACE-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN MIDEAST PEACE TALKS, CLINTON, ONCE AGAIN, SEEKS TO RECONCILE
OLD CONFLICTS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 16 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ To the spiritual strains of ``The Battle Hymn of
the Republic,'' President Clinton took the stage on Thursday before
several thousand attendees at the annual convention of the NAACP in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   He'd journeyed there from Camp David, the presidential retreat
where he's trying to hammer out a peace accord between Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had to come to Baltimore,'' Clinton told the jubilant
NAACP crowd, on their feet, applauding, cheering and waving small
American flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``You embody the spirit of freedom and reconciliation we're
trying to capture there, that we need so badly at our talks,''
Clinton said. ``So I wanted to be here especially during these
peace talks to draw strength from you and take the spirit of the
NAACP back to Camp David.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long goodbye guiding his downhill glide from power,
Clinton has returned to the very themes of reconciliation and the
search for common ground among former foes that have formed the
heart of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he searches for a Middle East peace accord _ and
prepares to travel to Japan on Wednesday to begin raising money to
support an agreement, if one is reached, from U.S. partners in the
Group of Eight _ Clinton is reaching, again, to his core belief
that there is no conflict so ugly, no history so tortured, that it
must forever cloud the hopes and dreams of future generations.
</P>
<P>
   It's a belief Clinton turned to last month, in opening trade
with North Korea just days before he marked the 50th anniversary of
the outset of the Korean War, and again, on Thursday, when he
lifted trade sanctions against Vietnam, a quarter century after the
bitter U.S. conflict there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement is one more reminder that former adversaries
can come together to find common ground in a way that benefits all
their people, to let go of the past and embrace the future, to
forgive and to reconcile,'' Clinton said in remarks on the White
House lawn. ``From the bitter past, we plant the seeds of a better
future.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is precisely what Clinton is trying to do with
the Camp David talks that continue through the weekend at the
presidential retreat outside this railroad hamlet at the edge of
the Catoctin Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   There's no assurance that he'll succeed in brokering a treaty to
end a half-century of conflict between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The summit itself, though is the fruit of seven years of efforts
by Clinton to bring the two sides together around a table where
they can set their mutual animosities aside long enough to focus on
their common interests.
</P>
<P>
   That has been Clinton's favored approach to one problem after
another _ international as well as domestic _ since he took office
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The record of results has been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, Clinton has set a rhetorical tone of racial
inclusiveness and reconciliation, two constant refrains of his
presidency. He's made a studied attempt to reflect those goals in
his staffing decisions, his judicial nominations and his efforts to
pass federal hate crimes legislation and to win tax breaks for the
working poor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton has been criticized by some in the
African-American community for not doing more to combat racial
profiling among law-enforcement, or for going along with a
Republican-authored welfare reform plan that ended benefits for
thousands of struggling, low-income blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, Clinton's efforts to reach across history and
hatred have also met an uneven fate.
</P>
<P>
   There are places, like Northern Ireland, where Clinton's
attempts to shepherd foes into a common pasture remain very much a
work in progress, even as his time in office slips quickly away.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other spots, most notably Rwanda, where Clinton
has seen no clear way to effectively interject his philosophy, or
his country's resources, into difficult conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been places _ Haiti, Bosnia and Kosovo _ where
his approach simply hasn't worked, where Clinton opted instead to
deploy massive U.S. military force to try to impose some sort of an
end to conflicts that ruptured societies in ways that ultimately
affronted American values, if not threatened U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
   He's after something far different in the Middle East, where his
stated goal is an enduring and comprehensive peace that will
fundamentally change the region and the way ancient foes deal with
each other.
</P>
<P>
   In every application of his reconciliation drive, Clinton has
been inspired, he has said repeatedly, by lessons he learned
growing up in the segregated American South and reading the words
of the late civil rights leader, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``A full, fair and final peace . . . Dr. King reminded us, is
more than the absence of war,'' Clinton said before the NAACP,
''but the presence of justice and brotherhood and genuine
reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are more than just words to Clinton, who has had, at the
heart of his international agenda, the challenge of trying to
integrate into the family of U.S. partners former adversaries like
Russia, China, and, now, even Vietnam and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   He was on the road, earlier in his presidency, to strengthening
U.S. ties with Cuba, until Fidel Castro ordered his rusting air
force to shoot down a pair of civilian-operated Cessnas near
Havana, killing four Americans of Cuban descent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton inherited rather than initiated the global shifts
resulting from the end of the Cold War on the watch of President
George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It has fallen to Clinton, however, to fit together the brick and
mortar of the post Cold War world. In doing so, he's looked largely
to his own instincts for reconciliation, forged, he insists, in the
crucible of the Civil Rights era.
</P>
<P>
   When he traveled to Selma, Ala., last March to commemorate the
35th anniversary of the bloody crackdown by state and local police
on peaceful civil rights demonstrators after crossing the Edmund
Pettus Bridge, Clinton gazed again across the nation's racial
divide in a moment he referred to Thursday as one of the greatest
days of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a son of the South, the brave souls who marched across that
bridge 35 years ago set me free too,'' Clinton told the NAACP
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every movement for human rights in this country is about more
than gaining equal opportunity and equal rights and decent justice
for the oppressed,'' he said. ``It is also about forgiveness and
healing, about letting go and moving on, about giving our children
a better tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
