<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FBI ARRESTS MAN WHO SOLICITED `MINOR' ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DEMIAN BULWA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ FBI agents who monitor children's chat rooms
have arrested a 39-year-old San Jose man who allegedly approached a
teen-age girl over the Internet and planned to meet her for the
first time at the San Francisco Zoo and then have sex with her.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, 14, turned out to be a grown-up FBI agent pretending
to be a girl, one of a growing number of law officers nationally
who become expert on-line poseurs as they try to crack down on
pedophiles who use the Internet as a hunting ground.
</P>
<P>
   The agent, posing as ``Robin,'' corresponded for 2 1/2 months
with ``Roger'' before a meeting was set up, said FBI agent Andrew
Black, an agency spokesman. Then at 1 p.m. Thursday, the agent _
donning a green hat and backpack as promised in an Internet
correspondence _ arrested Roger Guerrero near the front entrance of
the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero, a business manager for Amdahl Corp. of Sunnyvale,
faces a felony count of enticing or coercing a minor to engage in
sex. He could get up to five years in prison if he is convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest, Black said, is typical of the work of the Internet
Child Protection Initiative, which was launched in March in San
Francisco and employs five undercover FBI agents. The project was a
response to a bevy of complaints from parents about pedophiles
lurking on the Internet, particularly on chat rooms designed for
kids.
</P>
<P>
   The agents patrol chat rooms mentioned in complaints, then set
up a profile of a minor, along with interests like soccer and
music, and wait to see if any adults take the bait, Black said. The
agents do not initiate the contact to steer clear of entrapment, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently pedophiles and sexual predators are using this as
another arena to stalk their victims,'' Black said. ``What we're
trying to do is prevent these types of crimes from occurring in the
future. We'd like people to know that if you are a predator of
children, the next person you talk to on line may be an undercover
police officer or agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Black said Guerrero first contacted ``Robin'' on April 27 and
then corresponded several times. Guerrero, Black said, told the
undercover agent he wanted to have sex with her, spoke in explicit
language and once said, ``I could face 20 years or more in prison
for statutory rape.''
</P>
<P>
   The agent eventually told Guerrero that she was also interested
in sex, and the two set up a meeting that would begin with a trip
to the zoo, Black said. Guerrero reportedly was arrested after he
walked up to the agent and asked, ``Are you Robin?''
</P>
</TEXT>
