<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-MARCH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FARRAKHAN CALLS FOR 'MILLION FAMILY MARCH'
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Louis Farrakhan, leader of the Nation of Islam,
called Friday for families of all races and religions to congregate
in the nation's capital on the fifth anniversary of the Million Man
March.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding more mellow than militant, Farrakhan said he envisions
a massive, peaceful parade where people seek common goals while
walking under their separate symbols: ``Muslims under the crescent.
Christians under the cross. Jews with the Star of David. I've
invited gangs in the cities to come in their colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Marching beneath their banners will be fraternal organizations,
he predicted: Elks, Shriners and a myriad of other subdivisions of
what he termed ``the human family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to construct a tent where everyone can find comfort
despite our differences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His message could have come from the pulpit of a fundamentalist
church.
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan quoted from the Bible as well as the Koran. He warned
of moral decline in a society plagued by ``a steady erosion of
family life and corrosion of family values.'' He blasted ``cultural
degeneracy'' on popular television programs and bemoaned the
decline of traditional families with two parents devoted to rearing
good children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there is no strong marriage and no strong family, there
is no strong community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan announced plans for the Million Family March at a
Washington press conference where reporters were frisked by his
followers _ clean-cut young African-American men wearing suits and
ties that matched the handkerchiefs in their breast pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The fiery, controversial Islamic leader, who has endorsed racial
separatism and once called Judaism a ``gutter religion,'' said he
was changed by his recent bout with prostate cancer. He expressed
gratitude that Christians and Jews joined with Muslims in praying
for his recovery.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would continue to focus his efforts on the
African-American community but would also heed the ``universal cry
of the human family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not fully recovered,'' he said of his illness. ``By the
grace of God, the cancer is out of my body,'' but he is still
battling ``the after-effects of a very high dose of radiation''
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The Million Family March is scheduled for Oct. 16, five years
after hundreds of thousands of black men gathered on the grassy
mall between the Capitol and Washington Monument in response to
Farrakhan's call for a day of atonement.
</P>
<P>
   There were tangible results to the Million Man March, including
a lower crime rate, he said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the marchers ``must reconstruct the family'' as
society's basic building block, Farrakhan said. ``It is our idea to
remarry a million men to their wives'' and to unite 10,000
unmarried couples into formal matrimony.
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan said the family gathering will have a more direct
policy agenda than did the Million Man March. It will take place
three weeks before the national elections, he noted, and _ ``if it
is the will of God'' _ a presidential candidate may be endorsed
from the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Government is more attuned to the ``greed of multinational
corporations'' than to ``the needs of the masses,'' he said. The
disillusion of Americans of all races is shown by the fact that
more than half of the populace doesn't vote, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The masses of the people are not satisfied,'' he said. ``They
are losing confidence in the democratic system.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that it would take $3 million to $5 million to
arrange the march, but said that most organizing would be on a
local level. The Million Man March cost about $2 million, he added.
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.millionfamilymarch.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
