<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERM LIMITS COLOR CONGRESSIONAL COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WASHINGTON _ Congress may have
escaped the noose of term limits when the Supreme Court struck down
state attempts to set congressional tenure in 1995, but term
restrictions are still influencing congressional competitiveness.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leaders of U.S. Term Limits say many of the hottest U.S. House
races this year are the direct result of limits, both self-imposed
by members of Congress or required of state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Stacie Rumenap, the advocacy group's deputy director, said seven
of 10 House members elected in 1992 and 1994 when term limits were
a top campaign issue are sticking to their pledges to leave,
setting up contests for open seats in Florida and South Carolina,
among other states.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, limits on state legislative service around the
country are driving those politicians into congressional races,
raising the caliber of competition in several contests. Lastly,
House committee chairmen whose time at the helm has been limited by
party rules are choosing to retire rather than return to the
rank-and-file. Five are quitting this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a start,'' said Rumenap, about the back-door impact of
term limits. Though Republicans gained control of the House
partially on the promise of term limits, legislative efforts to
restrict tenure stalled in the wake of the Supreme Court ruling.
Term limit supporters concede it is exceedingly difficult to get
lawmakers to relinquish power once they attain it.
</P>
<P>
   But at present, about 50 House members are serving under
self-imposed limits and U.S. Term Limits says about a dozen current
candidates have agreed to abide by such rules as well.
</P>
<P>
   And term limits can quickly become an issue when candidates who
initially embrace them later get cold feet. Rep. George Nethercutt,
the Washington Republican who became the poster boy for term limits
when he knocked off Democratic House Speaker Tom Foley in 1994, is
under intense criticism for reneging and running again this year.
</P>
<P>
   HE WOULD KNOW
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has been kicking the GOP-controlled
Congress as a ``do-nothing'' bunch, trying to evoke the winning
message that President Truman employed in his come-from-behind 1948
campaign. That didn't sit too well with Sen. Strom Thurmond,
R-S.C.. Not only is he a member of the current institution impugned
by Gore, but Thurmond actually opposed Truman in that historic
campaign as a third-party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gore, I knew Harry Truman,'' said Thurmond in a statement
that took a page from Lloyd Bentsen's famous jab at Dan Quayle in
their 1988 debate. ``I ran against Harry Truman. And Mr. Gore, you
are no Harry Truman.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is he a Strom Thurmond, who lost that battle with Truman
and went on to be elected in 1954 to the Senate, where he remains
to this day.
</P>
<P>
   A SCENT OF LEMON
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Sen. John Edwards wants the federal government to
be more proactive in confronting one of the consumer scams that
continues to ride the currents of the flooding from Hurricane
Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat is calling on the U.S. Department of Transportation
to conduct a study of the safety risks presented by vehicles
damaged by flooding, then cleaned up and resold to unsuspecting
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``While shoddily rebuilt vehicles can appear cosmetically
attractive, they are likely to be structurally unsound and may fail
to meet even the minimum federal motor vehicle safety standards,''
Edwards wrote to Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicles damaged by flooding along the Eastern Seaboard have
been turning up in North Carolina and other states with titles that
do not disclose their watery history.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL SEAMANSHIP
</P>
<P>
   Good news! The House of Representatives is firmly on record in
support of large bodies of water _ namely the world's oceans.
</P>
<P>
   A resolution adopted last Tuesday expressed the sense of the
House that a National Ocean Day should be established to
``recognize the significant role the ocean plays in the lives of
the nation's people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The oceans cover 71 percent of the earth's surface and are key
to the life support systems for all creatures on the planet,'' Rep.
Patsy Mink, D-Hawaii, informed her colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was adopted on a strong 403-28 vote, putting
those members of the anti-ocean caucus on the losing end of the
issue. Who says Congress is all wet?
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
