<HEADER>
A2232 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-PARIS-FASHIONS-$ADV16     07-14 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHIONS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUTURE DAYS: PERFECTION AT SAINT LAURENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It is, to begin with, a perverse world. Only 1,000,
maybe 1,500 women are rich enough, spoiled enough and otherwise
bored enough to buy haute couture clothes. And if they are very
rich, they don't even bother coming here at all. They send their
private planes to have the fitters from the big houses brought to
them. You can imagine what this adds to the price of a $50,000
dress trembling with illusion pearls.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a very specific world nonetheless, its influence and
entertainment value extending far beyond the thin women who sit
shank to shank along the gold-toned front row. There was Nan
Kempner on July 12 at the Yves Saint Laurent show, sitting a few
chairs away from Catherine Deneuve and Lauren Bacall, the sort of
classy dames who have been called ``broads'' and don't cry about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Kempner's chin was raised, she leaned forward like an egret in
tall grass. Now she saw something her brain told her she couldn't
live without _ yes, a coat of toffee-colored wool over a cloque
velvet dress _ and her lips formed a word that anyone could read,
if one looked: ``Fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was Tom Ford, the creative director of Gucci, who now
also presides over Saint Laurent ready-to-wear, scanning the
runway, his eyes sucking in every detail like a pair of giant
hoses. One can't help feeling that Ford, despite his own place in
fashion history, wants badly to have even a little of the
savoir-faire that Saint Laurent tosses about as lightly as coin.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Ford called the show, the penultimate of the fall
2000 couture collections, ``perfect.'' And it was, too, in every
way, from the loden and charcoal day suits that seemed right for a
slow walk in a cold abbey to the coy buttocks-revealing evening
dresses that were clearly Saint Laurent's way of saying to Ford
that he had the younger man beat by a mile in the deluxe sin
department.
</P>
<P>
   But ``perfect,'' it turns out, is not the most interesting thing
Ford had to say about the Saint Laurent show. Rather, it was, ``By
the 10th outfit, you're into his world.''
</P>
<P>
   That world is fading fast, to be sure, but on Wednesday, at 1:20
p.m., when the crowd rose for a genuine ovation, it was as if, said
Kal Ruttenstein, the fashion director of Bloomingdale's, ``Father
Time had woken up.''
</P>
<P>
   And none too soon, either. This has been a mixed bag of a
season. Karl Lagerfeld put on a smart, lively show on July 11, with
bouffant-teased models in electric tweeds gliding along a clear
plastic platform floated on a local public pool. Oscar de la
Renta's show for Balmain on the evening of July 10 had client
clothes galore, many of them good, especially a high-waisted black
taffeta skirt of the Balenciaga genre with an oddly seductive
childish white blouse.
</P>
<P>
   But Christian Lacroix's collection, which opened with mink and
motorcycle leather dyed in improbable Ho-Jo tones of orange and
turquoise and ended with the couture equivalent of the
everything-on-it bagel _ a gown dowsed with five different trims _
seemed an exuberant muddle. Yvan Mispelaere, a former Prada
designer, who showed his first collection for Louis Feraud on July
11, went astray with nursery prints and other naive gestures that
sophisticated couture clients rarely bother with.
</P>
<P>
   And though Viktor &AMP; Rolf's show on July 12 combined conceptual
brilliance with David Lean-style visuals _ models drifting through
a near-white mist as their clothes jiggled with masses of tiny
bells _ it, too, seemed lost.
</P>
<P>
   So the day belonged to Saint Laurent. There have been a lot of
Saint Laurent shows in recent years when nothing clicked and you
thought, `OK, this is as good as it's going to get.' But the thing
one realized the other day was how vast and deep are Saint
Laurent's reserves of creativity compared to those of other,
younger designers who blow themselves out early, and then spend the
next 10 or 15 years splashing around in the same puddle.
</P>
<P>
   Saint Laurent recalled for an over-stimulated audience how
fashion can suddenly look new just by giving it a sense of harmony
and proportion. He put classic knee-length coats in toffee or
petrol-blue tweed over slivers of cloque velvet cocktail dresses in
Cognac brown or midnight blue. Vestal robes, as pure as Grecian
drapes, came out in warm shades of brown, purple and blue, while an
evening jacket of slick, silvery-green feathers tapered over a
column of lacquered black velvet.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare when clothes work on an emotional level _ it makes you
see how very little of the effort that goes into making couture
seem new or shocking actually produces a tenth of the shock that
Saint Laurent gets by showing a well-cut jumpsuit, or finishing an
outfit with a pair of suede gloves. It's also rare for a designer
to be able to challenge a younger generation's frank sexual
references by slyly referring to his own.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if anyone but Saint Laurent had sent out a model
wearing nothing except some baroque pearls and a buttocks-revealing
skirt, he would have been dismissed as a flaming old codger. But
Ford, and his chic brothers and sisters, know better than to avert
their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from giving the season a sense of perspective, Saint
Laurent and Lagerfeld, who used to see a lot of each other in their
younger years, showed how to base a collection on a concept. This
sounds like a simple thing to do, but it's surprising how many
designers get so taken with an abstract idea that they can barely
express it in words, much less in clothes. (This may have snagged
Lacroix, who in his program notes wrote, ``Couture's history, never
quite the same nor quite something else, is part of history.'' The
clothes were no clearer.)
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld is the most consistently far-sighted designer in
Paris. He reads, he writes, he converses, he jokes, he remembers.
And all this flows in a clear train of thought into the clothes he
designs. This season for Chanel he moved away from some of the
volume of the past year or so, with narrower shapes, shorter
hemlines and sack-back jackets, although some of the perky suits,
including one in black wool that wraps ingeniously around the
waist, have flaring skirts.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of nubby tweeds (a trend this season) with wide
metallic leather belts that were sometimes inset low on the waist
of a coat dress or woven into the front of a tweed jacket flecked
with the same electric hues. The colors gave the clothes a kind of
hot-rod vivacity, especially with the black patent leather and
clear vinyl boots Lagerfeld showed on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   So the models walked on water. They had muffs of distressed
tulle on their shoulders and their hair was back-combed in the
perennial style of Deeda Blair, a longtime Chanel client, and the
1950s model Dovima. There were evening looks in pink and watery
blue paillettes. Lagerfeld also showed tailored tulle, notably a
severe, exceptional-looking dress with crisp pleats left to fringe
on the ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very Chanel,'' he said, ``but she would never have done a
dress like this. That's my job, no?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
