s l BC-PARIS-FASHIONS-$ADV16     07-14 0205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHIONS-$ADV16-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PARIS: job, no?''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   De la Renta brought to Balmain, and the more than 50 regular
clients in the front row alone, a lot more substance than last
season. Suits, some in salt-and-pepper tweeds and worn with chaste
white blouses or fur tippets, told the story for day. For evening,
de la Renta seemed to have plucked Lagerfeld's notion from spring
of pairing a short jacket with a full New Lookish skirt.
</P>
<P>
   On the way into the Viktor &AMP; Rolf show, someone wondered aloud
if it had been sponsored by Philip Morris. Suffice it to say, the
thick, water-based mist made for a lot of innocent groping. It
seemed an intriguing idea, encrusting ladylike couture clothes with
masses of tiny bells, and then inviting people to listen as the
models approached like sleighs through a blizzard. The disgruntled
bays of the photographers in another part of the room certainly
added an unexpected Chekhovian charm.
</P>
<P>
   But when the model Carmen Kass emerged, and Andre Leon Talley,
an editor at large for Vogue, leaned in and asked if her long
jingling vest was heavy, which is what everybody wanted to know,
Kass said in a weary voice, ``Yes, it's heavy.'' And that seemed to
say it all.
</P>
</TEXT>
