<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, July 16, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LARRY-DAVID-HBO (Los Angeles) _ ``To Jerry's credit, he never
censored anything,'' said Larry David, the co-creator and executive
producer of ``Seinfeld'' for seven years. ``But he vetoed this.''
``This'' is an incest-themed story line that never showed up on
``Seinfeld'' but that David was taping two weeks ago for his new
show, ``Curb Your Enthusiasm,'' starting on HBO in October. By Rick
Marin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-FASHIONS (Paris) _ It is, to begin with, a perverse world.
Only 1,000, maybe 1,500 women are rich enough, spoiled enough and
otherwise bored enough to buy haute couture clothes. And if they
are very rich, they don't even bother coming here at all. They send
their private planes to have the fitters from the big houses
brought to them. You can imagine what this adds to the price of a
$50,000 dress trembling with illusion pearls. But it is a very
specific world nonetheless, its influence and entertainment value
extending far beyond the thin women who sit shank to shank along
the gold-toned front row. By Cathy Horyn.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RAVE (St. Petersburg) _ From afar, lasers and strobe
lights could be seen bursting mutely from within the island fort,
as if it were being consumed by some mysterious battle,
transforming it into a radiant beacon amid the 3 a.m. twilight
covering the Gulf of Finland. But as the ferryboat loaded with
young people docked after its three-hour voyage, music pulsating
from the turreted fort broke the stillness. On the first weekend of
July, as many as 10,000 Russian youth laid siege to an abandoned
and crumbling Czarist structure some 30 miles off the coast of St.
Petersburg for dancing, performance art and general merriment
during the season of northern Russia's White Nights, when the sun
sets for only three hours. By John Varoli.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-CLIMBING (Undated) _ No one wants to be called a social
climber. It's not a pretty term. It suggests that you are grasping
and opportunistic, and a vulgarian to boot. Today's social climbers
are less conspicuous. By Richard Stengel.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-ELLEN-WRIGHT (New York) _ It took Martha Stewart a dozen
years, a slew of books and a lifetime of self-promotion to get the
kind of attention Ellen Wright has been showered with since her
first book hit the stores last month. Wright is a hostess in tony
media circles who has written ``Bridgehampton Weekends'' (William
Morrow &AMP; Co.), a coffee-table tome of recipes sprinkled with photos
of Long Island idylls. By Nancy Hass.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-VIDEO (Undated) _ Making a good home video of a party
isn't for the thin-skinned. By Bob Morris.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Hydrangea. And everything you ever
wanted to know about it. By Anne Raver.
