<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTTY-HUMOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUMMER'S MOVIE HUMOR IN A WORD: UGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Editor's Note: This story is rated PG-13 for mild references to
bathroom humor. Those who substitute more graphic references will
have their mouths washed out with soap.)
</P>
<P>
   Russell Crowe battles against all odds in ``Gladiator'' and
George Clooney and Mark Wahlberg take on Mother Nature in ``The
Perfect Storm,'' yet one of the more memorable moments on screen
this summer involves an intense discussion between a drug dealer
and a racist sociopath _ set in a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   If you saw ``Shaft,'' you know the scene. About halfway through
the movie, drug dealer Peoples Hernandez (Jeffrey Wright) and rich
racist Walter Wade (Christian Bale) are arguing. Hernandez, who is
sitting on the toilet, finishes the conversation with a bowel
movement. Discussion over.
</P>
<P>
   We got more potty humor when ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' opened: A
big dog relieves itself on the lawn of cowed cop Charlie
Baileygates (Jim Carrey), Baileygates returns the favor a few
scenes later. Then he sprays urine all over the bathroom after a
night of cavorting with Irene Waters (Renee Zellweger).
</P>
<P>
   Why is Hollywood resorting to gratuitous bathroom scenes the way
it uses sex, violence and language for shock value? Is this
entertainment? More importantly, is it really necessary for plot
development?
</P>
<P>
   During the past few years, watching _ and hearing _ people do
their private business on screen has become a staple of the Austin
Powers movies, TV's ``South Park,'' and shows such as ``The
Sopranos,'' ``NYPD Blue,'' ``Ally McBeal'' and more.
</P>
<P>
   Scenes set in bathrooms and/or featuring characters urinating or
defecating are not totally new _ recall the campfire flatulence in
``Blazing Saddles,'' Ewan McGregor diving into a toilet in
``Trainspotting,'' Jane Fonda on the potty in ``Fun With Dick and
Jane,'' John Travolta being gunned down by Bruce Willis in a ``Pulp
Fiction'' potty scene.
</P>
<P>
   And there isn't an episode of ``Ally McBeal'' that goes by
without a key scene taking place in the unisex bathroom.
Invariably, we listen to detectives on ``NYPD Blue'' discuss cases
or their personal lives while at the urinal.
</P>
<P>
   But judging by ``Shaft'' and ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' it looks as
if bathroom scenes are becoming more graphic and unnecessarily
realistic. For perhaps the ultimate gross-out effect, how about the
scene in last year's ``Austin Powers II'' where Austin drinks
liquefied poo?
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been primed for this _ it's been a long time
coming,'' says Texas Christian University sociologist Mike
Katovich. ``We've run out of lines to cross with sex, and we've
moved on to bodily functions _ it may be the last frontier. Sex and
violence and language have all had their day.''
</P>
<P>
   This belief is echoed by several in the film industry, all of
whom note that the convergence of cable TV, grittier network shows
such as ``Blues'' and the success of movies with bathroom humor,
such as ``Dumb and Dumber'' and ``There's Something About Mary,''
in the last several years has sent the message that toilet humor
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time someone takes a taboo and breaks it, it opens the
floodgates,'' says University of Texas at Arlington professor and
filmmaker Andy Anderson. ``It's, `Here's another device we can
use.' It's the idea that, `Now you can set dialogue here and set
scenes here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And target audiences have gotten younger and younger,'' he
adds, ``to the point that it's part of their daily routine of
humor. It's 13-year-old humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says that including urination in a movie can work for
more than a cheap laugh. In his movie ``Detention,'' which was
shown the first year of the Fort Worth Film Festival, several
students are caged by a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   He included a scene where one of the male students urinates
between the bars because he ``wanted the audience to feel the
uncomfortableness'' the captives were experiencing. ``What do you
do if you're a hostage? I had to deal with it _ it was a metaphor
for their complete lack of privacy,'' Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   The problem filmmakers often have, he says, is that they ``are
running out of ways to stage things and places for humor. Everybody
knows what a kitchen signifies, or a bedroom. And now you've
increased the type of room you can set things in. In `Shaft,' that
means that you can show a guy's dominance over another guy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current blockbuster-driven film landscape, where there is
so much attention focused on what a movie grosses in its first
weekend, the competition for the moviegoer's dollar has grown more
fierce. The boundaries of what is acceptable or tasteful are
expanding, with a ``can we top that'' mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you have Jeff Daniels taking a laxative and making all
those terrible noises in ``Dumb and Dumber,'' the next film has to
go past that,'' says Ryan Brennan, co-founder and co-director of
the Fort Worth Film Festival. ``It's like sex scenes in the '60s _
people see something, and pretty soon they get used to it. Toilet
humor has become an easy laugh, like slipping on a banana peel used
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And people DO laugh _ or groan or yell ``Gross!'' And they often
leave the theater happy, even if a particular scene was
distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because, Katovich says, they get ``an emotional attachment
to something that gets them to feel something. It stirs something
that makes you feel alive, which is what artists try to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Katovich calls this the Lenny Bruce Syndrome: People were
grossed out by the troubled '60s comedian, but they would say later
that they liked his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you don't like something, you get excited about it,''
he says. ``It gets your adrenaline pumping. It's like the shower
scene in ``Psycho'' _ I saw it when I was young and it scared me to
death, but I wanted to see other Hitchcock movies right away.''
</P>
<P>
   But, one could argue, there's a major difference between a
horrendously scary, perfectly executed scene such as the one in
``Psycho'' and watching Jim Carrey urinate in ``Me, Myself &AMP;
Irene.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, horror movies are meant to frighten, and profanity
and bathroom scenes can be used artfully for dramatic effect.
Watching people go to the bathroom for the fun of it, however, how
artistic is that?
</P>
<P>
   Not very, Anderson says. He says the large number of toilet
scenes recently are ``political incorrectness by proxy,'' the work
of lazy filmmakers dumbing their work down to pander to teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, toilet scenes may have already hit a wall, because
there's so little left to show, and because people may be getting
tired of them. ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' has not performed nearly as
well as its predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will go the way of profanity _ it'll become commonplace,''
says Brennan. ``There's only so far you can go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, meanwhile, figures there's still more ground to cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually a big star will do this and it'll becoming `daring
acting' and win an Academy Award,'' he says. ``It's easier than
being genuinely funny, but it will fade away.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
