<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-ELLEN-WRIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PARTY FOR HOSTESS ELLEN WRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 16)  
 By NANCY HASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took Martha Stewart a dozen years, a slew of books and a
lifetime of self-promotion to get the kind of attention Ellen
Wright has been showered with since her first book hit the stores
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Wright is a hostess in tony media circles who has written
``Bridgehampton Weekends'' (William Morrow &AMP; Co.), a coffee-table
tome of recipes sprinkled with photos of Long Island idylls. For a
book party last Saturday at Wright's home on Mitchell's Lane in _
where else? _ Bridgehampton, the list of co-hosts barely fit on the
invitation. It included Mort Zuckerman; Don Hewitt; Alan C.
Greenberg, known as Ace, chairman of Bear Stearns; and Pete
Peterson, of the Blackstone Group, and his wife, Joan Ganz Cooney.
It was the fourth such party in Wright's honor. Tom Brokaw gave one
at his apartment in Manhattan, Vernon Jordan was host of another in
Washington, and Lew Wasserman, former chairman of MCA, had his own
in Los Angeles. Her friends have also helped her score guest spots
on ``Good Morning America'' and ``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for someone who has spent so much of her life surrounded
by savvy media types, Wright, 60, seemed oddly ambivalent about
finding herself at the center of the fuss she helped create. As she
led a visitor on a tour of her 4,800-square-foot home, Wright
insisted it wasn't even her idea to line up her glittery friends as
co-hosts for the party. She said the publicist Peggy Siegal
convinced her that enlisting them would help generate buzz to sell
books. Blushing slightly, gray bob swinging gently, she conceded
that she had even been coaxed into hiring a hair-and-make-up person
for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't really my kind of thing,'' she said, as guests,
ferried from their cars in golf carts, poured in. ``I really don't
know a lot of these people.''
</P>
<P>
   As the party got going around the pool, there wasn't much mixing
among Wright's old-guard media friends like Hewitt, Zuckerman and
Alan Patricof and Siegal's coterie of socialites, including Tiffany
Dubin, Vera Wang and Beth Rudin DeWoody. Each group mingled
expertly with its own, and the evening took on a well-practiced
air, a movable cocktail party vibe.
</P>
<P>
   Wright looked vaguely uneasy. Her usual style of entertaining is
to have six or eight friends over for dinner in the kitchen. ``I
like things to be cozy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It is that lack of pretension that makes Wright a popular
hostess. A sculptor and interior decorator who also worked as an
assistant to James Beard, she has been giving dinner parties since
the 1960s, when she arrived in New York after college in
California. Among her oldest pals are Pia Lindstrom and the
director Mark Rydell. Almost 30 years ago, she met Tom Brokaw, who
has ``practically lived in my kitchen'' ever since, she said,
adding, ``I just like to cook for friends of mine who happen to be
famous.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, she married Mitch Rosenthal, the founder of
Phoenix House, the drug rehabilitation center. Her entertaining was
crucial to its fund raising, said Rosenthal, whom she divorced in
the early 1980s. One Passover her family Seder expanded at the last
minute to include James Beard, the actor Ben Gazzara and Bette
Midler.
</P>
<P>
   At the book party, the consensus was that Wright's finest
cocktail hour came last summer: a birthday hoedown, complete with
fried chicken and cornbread, for her present husband, Joe Wright, a
former Reagan administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Her friends also agreed easily as to who was the worst square
dancer. ``Mort, definitely,'' Susan Patricof said, referring to
Zuckerman. ``He had a left-right problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright responded gently, as always. ``It was lovely to see
people loosen up,'' she said. ``That's what really makes things
fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
