<SLUG> BC-AIR-ALASKA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWSUITS IN AIRLINE CRASH TO BE CONSOLIDATED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lawsuits arising from the Jan. 31 crash of
Alaska Airlines Flight 261 will be consolidated for pretrial
proceedings in San Francisco, a judicial panel in Washington, D.C.,
ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The case is likely to raise sweeping questions about U.S.
aviation safety, lawyers for families of the victims say.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling made public Wednesday, a panel of seven federal
judges in Washington chose San Francisco over Seattle, Los Angeles
and other cities. It assigned the case to U.S. District Judge
Charles Legge.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who took part in arguments before the panel May 19 said
the choice of San Francisco turned on the fact that allegedly
improper maintenance dating from 1997 was done on the doomed
aircraft at an Alaska hangar in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Operations at the hangar have been the subject of a criminal
investigation by a federal grand jury in San Francisco since 1998.
There have been no indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, aircraft disaster litigation normally is
consolidated when lawsuits arising from the same incident are filed
in two or more federal jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said civil wrongful-death proceedings could begin within
weeks, but a trial or series of separate trials was at least eight
months off, assuming there was no group settlement out of court,
which was considered improbable.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of millions of dollars in damages, including punitive
damages, are expected to be sought by hundreds of plaintiffs, the
families and estates of 88 passengers who died when the plane
crashed into the Pacific Ocean off Ventura County while flying from
Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Since Flight 261 was an international flight, the Warsaw
Convention of 1929 applies. The pact limits carriers' liability to
$75,000 unless willful misconduct by the airline can be proved.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, an accord between international carriers
greatly liberalized the legal situation for claimants. It said
airlines will not oppose claims up to $135,000 and there would be
no cap on damages shown to exceed that amount. The airlines,
however, may limit damages by showing they took ``all necessary
measures'' to avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is going to expose a lot of major safety flaws in
the airline industry that have not been reported publicly,'' said
Niall McCarthy, a lawyer who represents the family of former San
Francisco police Officer Karl Karlson, who went down with the
McDonnell Douglas-made MD-83. The attorney accuses Alaska of taking
shortcuts in maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   An Alaska spokesman said the legal development was mainly
procedural and had little or no bearing on the principal defendants
in the case, Alaska and Boeing, which acquired McDonnell Douglas
after the plane was delivered to Alaska in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska's attorney, Mark Dombroff of Washington, D.C., declined
to comment. Dombroff, former head of aviation litigation with the
Justice Department, has defended airlines in several prominent
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   At least 14 wrongful-death claims have been filed so far; six in
the San Francisco Bay Area, three in the Los Angeles area, three in
Chicago and one each in Spokane, Wash., and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said one lawsuit for each dead passenger could be filed
eventually, but they expected families of the five crew to settle
privately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
