<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2259 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GLENN-MATH15-COX     07-14 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-MATH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GLENN ASKS HIS TEACHING COMMISSION TO GET DOWN TO EARTH
 &HT;    370&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former astronaut John Glenn asked his national
commission Friday to come up with more down-to-earth suggestions on
how to improve the teaching of math and science in the public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want our report to be a dust-catcher like other
reports,'' Glenn said. The retired U.S. senator was appointed one
year ago by Education Secretary Richard Riley to chair the National
Commission on Mathematics and Science Teaching for the 21st
Century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a whole batch of specific suggestions,'' Glenn said at
the final public meeting of his 35-member blue-ribbon panel. ``List
the specific actions that parents, teachers, principals, school
boards can do, and that state school boards, higher education, the
state and federal governments should take.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke up after the members spent much of the morning
polishing the language of three major goals:
</P>
<P>
   _ Increase the supply, knowledge and skills of new math and
science teachers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Slow down the movement of math and science teachers into
better-paying professions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give career teachers more time for professional development
and create about 10 new regional ``Glenn academies'' in which some
8,000 math and science teachers annually would help create and
duplicate model programs for their fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real over-arching goal is that we establish a system of
math and science education for all children that will be
competitive with the best in the world,'' said Alice Gill,
associate director of the issues department of the American
Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn paced from room to room as subcommittees brainstormed on
how to meet his demand for specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say, 'School boards should do X,' `` he told one group.
Another was told, ``Tell state legislatures to do Y.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. James B. Hunt of North Carolina said he thought Glenn would
get what he wants before the commission issues its final report in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to find a way to stimulate the nation to take
bold action,'' Hunt said. ``Why don't we recommend a
man-on-the-moon type project _ except that we ought to do it in
three years, instead of a decade _ to get every math and science
teacher well-prepared to teach science and math?''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet agreement on specifics was difficult for the members, who
range from prize-winning classroom teachers and lab-bench
scientists to technology titans, university presidents, governors
and federal officials of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   One business leader suggested telling states to require that
within five years, all math classes in middle and high schools must
be taught by people who had majored in math. A mathematician
replied that it would take more than five years to train that many
math teachers.
</P>
<P>
   A teacher suggested increasing the mobility of math and science
teachers by having states recognize credentials from other states.
That won't be adopted by states that are afraid of having their
math and science teachers recruited by out-of-state school
districts, a governor quickly pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will all work out,'' Glenn said soothingly. ``It has
to.''
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil seemed very familiar to Bruce O. Boston, a
commission staff writer who worked for a similar commission in
1983. He recalled that its members chewed up and discarded eight
preliminary drafts of its report on ``A Nation at Risk'' before
agreeing on a final version, which warned that ``a rising tide of
mediocrity'' had engulfed American schools.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   National Commission on Mathematics Teaching for the 21st
Century, www.ed.gov/inits/Math/glenn/toc.html
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
