<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGFLATION-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS A HARDER LANDING IN THE WORKS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16.) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember stagflation? That's when the economy slows and
inflation rises _ the worst of both worlds. It was the curse of the
mid-1970s, as the economy fell into recession and the Consumer
Price Index rose 12.3 percent in a single year, 1974. And it
returned in 1980, when the CPI jumped 12.5 percent while the
economy ground to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation has come way down since then, and the economy is now
in the longest period of continuous growth on record. So who's
talking about stagflation? Not many people _ and that may be a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the few who are talking are not predicting anything like
the stagflation of yore. But they are saying that investors could
face a period of slowing economic growth, which they equate loosely
with stagnation, and of rising prices, which is inflation. They
warn that increases in unit labor costs associated with this more
benign stagflation will also cut into corporate earnings. But the
stock and bond markets have not yet factored this in; instead, Wall
Street forecasters still expect earnings to grow this year at the
quickest annual pace since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   At the worst, this small group of worried economists and
strategists adds, the Federal Reserve could raise short-term
interest rates higher than is now expected, in response to reports
of a climbing CPI. That extra tightening could push the the economy
into a recession.
</P>
<P>
   How could this happen, especially when many Wall Street
strategists think that the Fed is guiding the economy to a soft
landing, slowing it down to a manageable but still positive pace?
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, a slowdown in economic growth would set off a
decline in the growth rate of worker productivity, measured by the
value of output for each hour worked. In the last two quarters of
1999, productivity surged, rising an annual rate of 5 percent and
6.9 percent, respectively. Unit labor costs declined during those
quarters, by 0.3 percent and 2.9 percent. Corporate earnings,
meanwhile, surged 22.7 percent and 21.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But with economic growth slowing, productivity gains will
shrink, said Paul A. McCulley, a portfolio manager at the Pacific
Investment Management Co., a bond powerhouse in Newport Beach,
Calif. That would happen because companies do not shed workers
quickly as demand for products slackens. Indeed, with workers so
difficult to find these days, few employers would be willing to
consider layoffs at the first sign of a slowdown. So the same
number of workers would be producing fewer goods, and that works
out to lower productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller productivity gains mean that unit labor costs, which
equal total worker compensation minus productivity, would rise. In
the first quarter of this year, productivity gains slowed to 2.4
percent while unit labor costs rose 1.6 percent, according to the
Bureau of Labor Statistics. While corporate profits remained
strong, the CPI, not counting prices for food and energy, jumped at
a compound annual rate of 3.2 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with rising unit labor costs, companies have two choices.
They can pass them on to consumers in higher prices, which adds to
inflationary pressures, or they can absorb them _ because of
competitive fears _ and reduce their profits.
</P>
<P>
   It is also likely that workers will be pushing for wage
increases to compensate them for the high productivity gains of the
last few years. Pay raises are usually backward-looking, because
they are based on profits the company has already made.
</P>
<P>
   McCulley says the period _ or ``interregnum'' _ of rising prices
and slowing growth should not last long, provided that the Fed does
not raise interest rates too much and cause a recession. On the far
side, an economy with inflation again in check and the Fed on hold
will be good for stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``the equity market has not embraced an
interregnum of stagflation.'' Equities, he said, are already
overpriced for the shock of rising inflation and slowing growth; if
the Fed tightens too much in response to an inflationary spurt, he
sees stocks headed for disaster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
