<SLUG> BC-CAR-EARNHARDT-NYTR-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT DRIVES TOWARD AN EIGHTH WINSTON CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAT ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt is having a resurgent season. It's not now or
never for Chevy's top warrior, but if he doesn't win a record
eighth Winston Cup championship now, he moves one step closer to
never.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, 49, is crawling up the rear bumper of points leader
Bobby Labonte. With a sixth-place finish at New Hampshire,
Earnhardt's 15th top-10 in 18 races, he chopped Labonte's lead to
45 points.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the dominant force he was during his prime, but
Earnhardt is one of the most respected drivers in Winston Cup
competition. He doesn't run up front as much as he once did, but he
has won once in 2000. His strength is to take advantage of other
people's mistakes and his own experience to record quality finishes
week in and week out. That kind of consistency earns Winston Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got four years of racing left, at least,'' said
Earnhardt, whose contract with car owner Richard Childress runs
through 2003. ``Who knows? I might even drive another car with my
own team. I'm not ruling anything out.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt owns the two cars driven by his son, Dale Earnhardt
Jr., and Steve Park. Park has never had a breakthrough season and
suffers by comparison to the success young Earnhardt is having in
his rookie year. Park is signed through 2002 with an option year
after that, which coincides with the end of Earnhardt's contract
with Childress.
</P>
<P>
   Whether an Earnhardt in his mid-50s driving for his own team
would be a championship contender is problematic, which is why
Earnhardt is intent on taking advantage of the current situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a job and an opportunity to win that eighth
championship,'' Earnhardt said. ``That's what we're focusing on.
That's what we're driving for. That's what we're working for. We're
doing it with a more solid team than I've had in past years. I
think our whole program has come together from last year to this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Childress' decision to have Kevin Hamlin become Earnhardt's crew
chief in mid-1998, moving Larry McReynolds from Earnhardt's car to
Mike Skinner's, has been a plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin is more my type and style of crew chief,'' Earnhardt
said. ``He's constantly thinking. He never quits on making it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt said Hamlin reminds him of his former crew chief, Kirk
Shelmerdine. ``When I say something, he's already thinking it, and
that's the way Kirk was,'' Earnhardt said. ``We're thinking on the
same note. Our crew has been fine-tuned and moved around and
everybody really wants to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be with somebody who wants to win as badly as I want
to. I feel like that is the package we have this year,'' Earnhardt
said. ``We want to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
