</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-WESTBANK-ART-915&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER RIGHTS PLAY IMPORTANT ROLE IN MIDEAST TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARMEL, West Bank _ Rafat, a skinny 9-year-old too shy to supply
a surname, heads every summer morning to the only swimming hole in
this hardscrabble stretch of the Hebron hills. It is a stark stone
cistern, about 100 feet long and 50 feet across, built long ago to
store the rains that fall only in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Descending a rickety ladder, Rafat and his pals plunge happily
into stagnant water barely 3 feet deep, its surface an unbroken
carpet of brilliant green algae.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are our children,'' said Khalil Yunis, mayor of the
nearby town of Yatta, shaking his head at the sight of the small
boys diving under the undulating scum. ``And this is their water.''
</P>
<P>
   The algae-choked pool where Rafat swims is the centerpiece of
the village water system. The other daily water source for Karmel's
3,500 residents is a tiny spring-fed brook that wends its way
through a herd of goats into a newly covered concrete cistern.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers carry pails past a hand-lettered sign in English
and Arabic extolling this modest public-works project,
``implemented by Yatta municipality'' and financed by the U.S.
Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless America,'' Yunis said with a wry smile.
</P>
<P>
   Yunis tried to help Karmel further by linking the village to
Yatta's municipal water system, but the summer supply in Yatta is
so low that water now flows through the 3-inch pipe here ``just two
or three days a month,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the West Bank, Yatta gets its water from Israel's
state water company. Disputes over water resources have been a fact
of life here since the land was occupied by Israel 33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But with Israeli and Palestinian negotiators now trying to
resolve the issue of water rights, along with all their other
hypercharged disputes _ about refugees, borders, Jerusalem _ the
concern in this parched part of the West Bank is that Israel may
end up retaining its hold on the reserves beneath the bedrock here.
</P>
<P>
   About a mile down the dirt road, Yunis pointed out what is to
him a symbol of the conflict that he hopes the Camp David talks can
resolve: a pristine pumping terminal, protected by a chain-link and
barbed-wire cage, for a large water main supplying a Jewish
settlement town, Maon.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller pipe once channeled some of this water to Karmel, but
the link was severed by settlers, Yunis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water is right here, and we can't touch it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Within plain view of the fenced-in pumping station, outside
another small village, Azam Abugadiah lowered two yellow pails into
a 30-foot well dug a year ago in another local-government effort to
expand water resources.
</P>
<P>
   Four times a day he expertly tips the buckets into the few
remaining inches of standing water, his family's only supply of
drinking water. Next to the nearly dry well, a new storage tank
stands empty, an electric pump is idle and the year-old water meter
shows a long row of zeros.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank, water allocation is a zero-sum game, and
Palestinians consider local scarcity a direct and unjust
consequence of the resources given to Jewish communities.
</P>
<P>
   With their watered lawns and community pools, the 160,000 Jewish
settlers in the West Bank enjoy essentially the same suburban life
as Israelis elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the settlements, daily water consumption for households and
general urban use is about 774 gallons a person. That is not a lot
by American standards, but it is four times the Palestinian usage.
And during summer droughts, despite public-service calls to
conserve water, there is little real reduction in Israeli household
use. But among Palestinians, water supplies slow to a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis make all this fuss about a shortage of water to
wash their cars, and we do not have enough to wash our bodies,''
said Muhammad Amro, an official with the Palestinian local
government ministry in the Hebron region.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization says 26.5 gallons of potable water
per person is needed daily for minimal health and sanitation
standards.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank and Gaza, where Palestinians control local
government but Israel still controls most of the water resources,
the average consumption is 18.5 gallons daily. In the summer in
towns like Yatta, with water systems connected to Israel's national
network, the supply dwindles to half that or less.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated 215,000 Palestinians who live in villages with no
running water rely on trucked-in water bought in most cases from
Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Noam Lubell, a spokesman for Btselem, an Israeli human rights
group that brought European diplomats here for meetings with
officials of drought-stricken Palestinian towns, said the
settlements were just part of the problem. The drainage of aquifers
for Israeli industry and agriculture and the lack of serious
water-conservation efforts in Israel's affluent suburbs are the
real sources of the disparity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water issue is not one of the settlers vs. the
Palestinians, but of Israel vs. the Palestinians,'' said Lubell,
whose organization issued a study this month urging radical
cutbacks in Israel's use of underground fresh water reserves.
</P>
<P>
   In the inch-by-inch negotiating battle for territory here, the
lands that are bitterly disputed are precious and finite. But at
least they are not contracting. Subterranean water reserves, by
contrast, are steadily shrinking as the demands of two fast-growing
societies outpace natural replenishment by rivers and rainfall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As fresh water supplies diminish, brackish water from pools
deeper underground is drawn up into the depleted aquifers,
rendering the reserves undrinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Even Israeli officials who favor increased allotments to the
Palestinians have argued for continued Israeli control of shared
aquifers beneath the hills here. Israel's acknowledged expertise in
water management can benefit both sides, they contend, and
hydraulics and topography make it easier to tap the main reservoir
from within Israel's borders.
</P>
<P>
   But the Palestinians point to Israel's recent warnings that it
may unilaterally cut water supplies promised to Jordan under the
terms of its peace treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The one point of concurrence between Israeli and Palestinian
water experts is that the aquifers do not hold enough water to
supply both populations at present consumption rates for many more
years.
</P>
<P>
   While Palestinian villagers import Israeli water in tanker
trucks, Israel is seriously considering the emergency importation
of Turkish water in tanker ships, converted for the purpose from
the oil trade.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli experts deride that proposal as costly and
unsanitary, and say the farms that use most of the country's fresh
water should instead be irrigated with brackish and recycled waste
water.
</P>
<P>
   The only long-term solution, experts agree, is to create more
fresh water. Israel is seeking bids for gas-powered desalting
plants along the Mediterranean. The water-deprived Gaza Strip could
be the biggest beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   But in Karmel and other hamlets in the brown hills here, these
projects seem like a distant abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are discussing the problem of water for the next
generation,'' Amro said. ``But if we can't drink the water now,
there will be no next generation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2266 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CYRUS-MEHRI-PROFILE-$     07-14 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYRUS-MEHRI-PROFILE-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER IN COKE CASE SEEKS SWEEPING CHANGE IN CORPORATE AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16.) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Cyrus Mehri, challenging the status quo is second nature.
His Iranian mother was punished in her youth for criticizing the
shah. Asked to do a book report in the seventh grade, he chose one
written by Abbie Hoffman. He cut his political teeth with Ralph
Nader, organizing communities to rise up around issues like
telephone rates. Even his birthday, July 14, coincides with a
revolutionary milestone, at least for the French.
</P>
<P>
   So when he filed a federal lawsuit against the Coca-Cola Co. in
April 1999, representing four black employees who said they had
been denied raises, promotions and other advancement because of
their race, it was a fairly typical move for Mehri, who turned 39
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Coke mounted a vigorous defense, saying no discrimination had
occurred. But as the case continued into its second year,
investors, Wall Street analysts and others demanded that the
company resolve it quickly. After court-ordered mediation, the two
sides reached a tentative settlement last month, although no
details will be available until October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cyrus is an excellent lawyer in the sense that he has a very
good big-picture feel for the dynamics of the process,'' said
Hunter Hughes, the federal mediator who oversaw the settlement
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Mehri (pronounced ``merry'') parted company with
three of the plaintiffs, whose number had grown to eight earlier
this year. Along with a fourth plaintiff, they are now represented
by Willie E. Gary, a Florida personal-injury specialist who has
said that he can get more money for the employees than Mehri is
seeking. The split has created confusion among the estimated 2,000
current and former Coke employees who would be covered by the
settlement, and some have said they plan to opt out and file new
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In a minor victory for Mehri, Gary was ordered last week by the
judge, Richard W. Story of U.S. District Court in Atlanta, not to
solicit retainers or to invite the employees to meetings. ``I have
no problems with that,'' Gary said. ``We're not going to sign
anybody up until they have a chance to see this phantom
settlement.'' He has filed a discrimination lawsuit in Georgia
state court, asking for $1.5 billion in damages for four former
Coke employees.
</P>
<P>
   Mehri maintains that once the settlement terms are public,
plaintiffs and employees will be pleased. ``When the fog clears
this fall,'' he said, ``the narrow interests of a few will be
eclipsed by the movement of the many.''
</P>
<P>
   The case against Coke was the first for his law firm, Mehri,
Malkin &AMP; Ross, which he opened in September 1998. ``People thought
I was crazy to risk the future of my firm on this case,'' Mehri
said. But he was confident that his case was solid.
</P>
<P>
   About six months earlier, he received a telephone call from
Linda Ingram, an information systems analyst at Coke, who felt that
the company had treated her unfairly. Ingram had obtained his phone
number from Bari-Ellen Roberts, a former financial analyst at
Texaco whom Mehri represented when she sued the company in 1994,
contending racial discrimination. The two sides reached a $176
million settlement that year.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who is now a diversity consultant in Stamford, Conn.,
said that Mehri kept close tabs on everyone involved in the Texaco
lawsuit, and that he stays in touch with her to this day. ``He was
like a guardian to us,'' she said. ``We had weekly phone calls that
lasted well into the night. When he was on his honeymoon, he was in
contact the whole time, except when he and his wife climbed Mount
Kilimanjaro.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Coke lawsuit, Mehri, who says he believes that successful
class actions require a combination of hard work and lucky breaks,
received a mysterious package in the mail that turned out to be
Coke's human-resources database. Examining how black employees were
treated, he concluded that they were clustered in the lowest-paying
jobs; even in better jobs, they were often paid less than white
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Jones, who organized a boycott of Coke products this
spring, praised Mehri for his courage in bringing the lawsuit. ``I
was embarrassed that no black attorneys were willing to stand up
and take on this lawsuit,'' Jones said. But he also said Mehri had
underestimated the anger of black Coke employees.
</P>
<P>
   Losing some of the plaintiffs to Gary, who is black, took Mehri
by surprise, Roberts added. ``He saw that race plays a part in
everything, whether we admit it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehri, who lives in Washington with his wife, Robin Anne Floyd,
and their two young children, said every case was a learning
experience. ``We did Coke better than we handled Texaco,'' he said,
``and we'll do the next case better than we handled Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   There will always be another case. But Mehri's vision for
corporate America involves sweeping change, not the piecemeal kind.
He would like every company to file detailed pay-equity studies by
race and gender and what he calls a ``glass ceiling report card''
that would cover promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, no one is really going to look at their record, no
one is going to hold them accountable and no one is going to
enforce the law,'' he said. ``We can take the civil rights movement
to the next level, and level the playing field at the highest
reaches of these corporations. They let African-Americans in, but
they don't let them up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
