<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, July 15 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT (Miami) _ A Miami jury awarded $144.87 billion
in punitive damages Friday to plaintiffs in a landmark class action
lawsuit against the top five U.S. tobacco companies. (Summary from
wires) By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TAX (Washington) _ The Senate voted Friday to repeal
the federal estate tax, brushing aside a veto threat from President
Clinton and giving Republicans at least a symbolic victory on an
issue at the top of their election year agenda. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-TRIAL (Houston) _ A jury decided on Friday that the
government does not bear responsibility for the deaths of 80 Branch
Davidians during the cult's 1993 standoff with federal agents. A
federal judge will take the ruling into account before delivering
the verdict himself sometime later. The five jurors deliberated for
just 2{ hours in the $675 million wrongful-death lawsuit filed by
surviving Branch Davidians and relatives of those who were killed
in the standoff. (Summary from wires) By Ross E. Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-TAPE-BEATINGS (Undated) _ In the nine years since George
Holliday, a plumber standing on the balcony of his Los Angeles
apartment, videotaped the vicious beating of Rodney King by police,
tapes made by onlookers have become a potent legal and political
tool. This week, with two more beatings by police videotaped by
news helicopters in Philadelphia and Lawrenceville, Ga., the images
are as powerful as ever _ even though, like most bystander videos,
they do not present a full or clear picture of precisely what
happened. That is usually the main issue when cases involving
videotaped evidence come to trial: defense lawyers argue, as they
did successfully in the first prosecution growing out of the Rodney
King beatings, that because the video recorded only the tail end of
the interaction, it leaves out the behavior that led to the
beating. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-AUSTRIA (Paris) _ Five months after the European Union
imposed sanctions on Austria to protest the inclusion of members of
a far-right party in the Austrian government, machinery giving
everyone a face-saving way to end the diplomatic freeze is in
place. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
</TEXT>
