<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-HEAT-500&AMP;ADD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEATWAVE CONTINUES FROM ROMANIA TO SOUTHERN TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to correct spelling: ADAPAZARI, sted ADAPARAZI, is correct.
Name appears in dateline and 14th graf.) 
(EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADAPAZARI, Turkey _ For Sevgi Pinarci and her family, the
scorching temperatures that swept Turkey and southeastern Europe
over the past 10 days amount to heaping insult on top of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Since a devastating earthquake last August destroyed their home,
Pinarci, her husband and their two children have been living in a
tiny two-room makeshift shanty in a rubble-filled vacant lot. There
is no electricity, no running water and no relief from temperatures
inside the shack that have reached more than 120 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard for the children to sleep because even at
midnight it's like the hot sun at noon,'' said Pinarci, 38, as her
husband, Omer, 39, and two sons, Kaan, 13, and Bahadir, 9, looked
on.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the region eased somewhat Friday, but the
effects of the prolonged heat wave were still being felt from
Romania to southern Turkey. Crops, already suffering from a summer
drought, were damaged further. Water levels in reservoirs dipped,
threatening irrigation and hydroelectric plants. And firefighters
continued to battle wild fires on both sides of the Aegean Sea in
Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the heat, with temperatures topping 100
degrees, the authorities in Romania and Bulgaria ordered trains to
stop running because they feared that tracks would buckle from the
heat. The only nuclear plant in Romania was temporarily shut down
after the temperature inside reached 158 degrees and set off
sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Croatia were declared natural disaster areas as the
effects of the drought on crops was magnified by soaring
temperatures. Officials predicted crop production would be 40
percent to 70 percent lower than last year as a result of the
weather. Crops were also damaged in other countries, including
Bulgaria, Romania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   In Greece, high temperatures and strong winds helped to ignite
and spread more than 100 wildfires and led Prime Minister Costas
Simitis to order emergency services on maximum alert. ``Every
available force has been mobilized, and we hope we can bring the
situation under control,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fire temporarily threatened the ancient town of Corinth, 50
miles southwest of Athens, and other blazes cast a brownish pall
over the capital city.
</P>
<P>
   The scorching heat has claimed at least 50 lives across
southeastern Europe and more than 20 in Turkey and sent hundreds of
people to hospitals. In Istanbul, the heat topped 110 degrees and
broke a 60-year-old record. In other parts of the country,
temperatures reached 130 degrees and higher.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit of Turkey ordered government
offices closed Thursday and Friday to lessen the danger to workers
and ease the drain on the country's electricity resources. In this
politically contentious country, even the prime minister's largess
could not escape criticism. Mehmet Yildirim, chairman of the
Istanbul Chamber of Commerce, told a local newspaper, ``If this
government was in Saudi Arabia it would declare all 365 days of the
year a vacation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Highways were so softened by the heat in parched central Turkey
that the Ministry of Public Works banned truck traffic during
daylight hours for two days because the vehicles were digging deep
gouges into the asphalt. Istanbul police were issued sunblock
lotion and sandals and permitted to take showers during short
breaks at the hottest times of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But few showers were available for the tens of thousands of
Turks who have been living in prefabricated houses, tent cities and
shanty towns since the earthquake Aug. 17 that killed at least
17,000 people and left as many as 500,000 homeless. While the
government quickly rebuilt main highways, progress has been slow in
returning people to damaged homes or building new housing in
affected areas.
</P>
<P>
   A government spokesman said there are 35 official tent cities,
housing about 30,000 people, throughout the region damaged by the
earthquake. But the officials figures do not count all of the
people who are still homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Adapazari, a city of about 180,000 some 100 miles
southeast of Istanbul, the Pinarcis are among seven or eight
families who have built ramshackle homes on a vacant lot not far
from their damaged homes. They bring in fresh water by bottle, cook
with propane tanks and wash their clothes in plastic tubs.
</P>
<P>
   Even as temperatures moderated and slipped below triple digits
Friday, the darkened bedroom of their two-room shanty was stifling,
and a hot wind blew a layer of dust across everything in the open
kitchen area. Sitting at a plastic table beneath an umbrella
outside the shack, Omer Pinarci complained that they had been
unable to join hundreds of other families in government-provided
prefabricated houses because local authorities said their house was
not damaged enough. But he said the house is unsafe and he refused
to allow his wife and children to live there.
</P>
<P>
   Winter was difficult, he said, but the last 10 days of heat were
even worse. ``The heat has been very bad, very bad,'' he said
mournfully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-VOTERS-0715-1stLD-COX     07-14 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS-0715-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VOTERS SHOWING RECORD LEVEL OF APATHY
 &HT;    EDS: Resending to fix transmission garble
 &HT;    460&AMP;add.
 &HT;    With VOTERS-DATA Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Voters are more disengaged in the presidential race
this year than at any time in recent history, according to an
extensive survey of American attitudes towards politics released
Friday by a non-partisan research group.
</P>
<P>
   Good economic times and a sense that there is little difference
between Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush has lulled
voters into ``a rather pleasant sleep,'' said pollster Andrew
Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center for the People and the
Press.
</P>
<P>
   The flagging voter interest could be an indication that turnout
this fall may sink to a new low, Kohut said. In 1996, only 49
percent of eligible citizens cast ballots, the first time in more
than 70 years that less than half of voters went to the polls to
elect a president.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew poll found that fewer than half of registered voters _
46 percent _ said they have thought a lot about the election, a
decline from 55 percent in 1996 and 63 percent in the same period
in 1992. The drop-off in voter interest and familiarity with the
candidates is especially pronounced in young and middle-age adults.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good chance that turnout will drop below the 1996
level, and ``it seems virtually certain,'' Kohut said, that it will
be lower than the 55 percent of voters who came to the polls in
1992, when Bill Clinton defeated incumbent George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Yet paradoxically, Americans said they are more satisfied with
their choice of presidential candidates this year, and they are
less critical of the way the campaigns are being conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, 73 percent expressed satisfaction with the
candidates compared to 49 percent in 1996, when former Sen. Bob
Dole won the GOP nomination to challenge President Clinton.
Sixty-six percent of Democrats said they were satisfied this year,
compared to 56 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The poll concluded that the race between Bush and Gore remains
wide open as the candidates head to the nominating conventions next
month. The survey found that likely voters are split between Gore
and Bush _ 47 percent each, with 6 percent undecided. Third-party
candidates Ralph Nader and Pat Buchanan will not have much impact
on the race, Kohut said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans increasingly believe that the election of the
president is not as important as it was a decade or two ago, the
poll found. Nearly half of Americans _ 49 percent _ believe things
will pretty much stay the same no matter who is elected.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew survey, conducted among 2,174 adults June 14-28 with a
margin of error of plus or minus 2.5 percentage points, mirrors
other recent polls which indicated that voters see little
differences in the two major candidates.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   This is despite their divergence on issues such as government
spending and social issues such as abortion and gun control and
whom each might pick to fill expected vacancies on the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is in play, but it would seem from our polling data
that American voters are dissatisfied, distracted or just don't
care,'' said Stephen Hess, a scholar on government and the media at
the Brookings Institution, a Washington policy center.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew survey found that fewer respondents are following news
about the campaign than did during the same period in 1996 and
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kohut also noted that the degree of voter interest could
change dramatically after the nominating conventions and if Gore
can energize Democratic and independent voters. He also said the
current voter disinterest could be due, in part, to the early
victories on Gore and Bush in the primaries that has created a lull
in media attention on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush enjoys an ``enthusiasm edge,'' with a greater proportion of
voters who described themselves as Republicans supporting him than
do Democrats who say they support Gore. Only 47 percent Democrats
said they strongly support Gore, compared with 56 percent of
Republicans who counted themselves as strong supporters of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, a slim majority of voters, no matter who they support,
said they believe Bush will win the election. Fifty-one percent
predicted that Bush will win, compared to 34 percent who said Gore
and 15 percent who said they do not know.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents ranked Bush higher on leadership abilities, while
giving Gore the edge on key issues important to voters, such as
education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of just how fluid voters attitudes can be, the Pew
survey, conducted over a two-week period, detected a significant
shift in support from Gore. Between June 14-21, Gore led Bush 42
percent to 41 percent, with 10 percent undecided. The following
week, amid news reports that a recommendation had been made for an
independent counsel to probe the vice president's 1996 campaign
finance activities, Gore fell to 35 percent compared to Bush's 42
percent, with 19 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   The Pew Research Center for the People and the Press:
www.people-press.org
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
