<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2276 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-MEXICO-FOX-HNS &LR;      07-14 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANOTHER NEW TWIST IN MEXICAN POLITICS: JOB-SEEKERS MUST APPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 16)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Help Wanted: Men and women to form new Mexican
government. Requirements: Love of Mexico, sense of social
responsibility, honesty.
</P>
<P>
   Days after he became president-elect of Mexico, Vicente Fox
dispatched headhunters to search for candidates who will shape the
new Cabinet before he takes office on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The president-elect has shocked many traditional Mexicans with
his business-oriented method to government. But he has also
delighted others who would otherwise not have a shot to serve their
country.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's approach is not the way the business of government has
traditionally been conducted under the 71-year rule of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, which was
soundly defeated in the July 2 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Previous PRI governments consisted mostly of appointed friends
or relatives to those occupying the nation's highest posts,
sometimes without regard to qualification.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox, who ran under the banner of the pro-business,
conservative National Action Party, is not the run-of-the-mill
politician. The rancher who governed Guanajuato state was also
president of Coca-Cola in Mexico, and he is a whiz at successful
marketing in a country that slurps the soft drink like water.
</P>
<P>
   A believer of ``symbols,'' he marketed himself during the
campaign, wearing his cowboy boots, a huge belt buckle emblazoned
with ``Fox'' in silver, a blue shirt for his party's colors and a
trademark wave to supporters _ ``V'' for Vicente.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with PRI candidate Francisco Labastida, a reserved
economist and veteran public servant, Fox had a swaggering image
that stood out with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this country needs is a rancher with guts, not an
intellectual,'' said office worker Martin Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   The buzzwords Fox uses to describe his future government are
``quality'' and ``clients.'' Under the Fox dogma, clients are
Mexican citizens and his government will be a quality product.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Fox issued a lofty, five-point standard, published in
newspapers, that must be met by applicants to work in his
administration. They must have: ``Love of Mexico, high sense of
responsibility, proven honesty, recognized capabilities and be able
to obtain results.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he is looking for men and women from all backgrounds
and differing political affiliations. When he governed Guanajuato
state, the top financial post went to a longtime PRI member.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have commitments with no one, I don't appoint members of my
family. I don't bring teams I worked with on other projects,'' Fox
said this week in a late-night talk show on the TV Azteca network.
``The decisions I am going to make in the next two months will mark
the destiny of my six-year term.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he would have his new government in place within two
months.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, headhunters are combing Mexico and are even
searching for Mexicans living in the United States to fill vital
jobs. Fox himself will conduct interviews and do the hiring of the
tops Cabinet posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be assured that this Cabinet has two things:
experience, maturity, and, on the other hand, be like these yuppies
revolutionizing the world and making frog leaps to the process of
development,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in basic black, her shoulder-length hair pulled back,
Lucy Villamar, 35, might fit the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The public relations consultant, who has directed projects at
several museums, found out the name of one of the headhunters and
boldly gave him a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were surprised, but I was confident. I know there will be
a change because Fox said he would give opportunities to all
Mexicans,'' said Villamar, who wants to work with the Ministry of
Culture or a related post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a unique opportunity. I never would have had this chance
with the PRI because they put their friends in,'' added Villamar,
who said she voted for Fox. ``He said he would take into account
talent. Fox believes in women and the young. I see an opening.''
</P>
<P>
   While Villamar sees an opening, others are grumbling. This week,
the media had a field day, carping on Fox's headhunters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governing a nation is not the same as selling Coca-Cola,''
Reforma newspaper columnist Rafael Segovia wrote on Friday.
``Putting an ad in a newspaper to obtain ministerial candidates
tells us a lot about Fox's concept in the art of governing. Like it
or not, it is the activity of an elite.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fox, 58, has already broken the Mexican presidential mold in
several areas.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is he the first opposition leader since the PRI was
founded in 1929, he will also be the nation's first divorced
president and the father of four adopted children. And he has an
Irish surname and a mother who was born in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   In a Thursday meeting with international news agencies, Fox
revealed his plans to appoint seven close advisers _ ``czars who
will demand results.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be the czar of corruption, poverty, Indians, the
economy, education and social development, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly won't spend much time in the office. I'll leave
the work to them,'' if he has a good team, Fox said, adding he
wants to travel throughout Mexico finding out what people want and
how government can help.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would meet once a week with his Cabinet to plan the
next week's work.
</P>
<P>
   He envisions Mexico, a poor nation bordering a powerful United
States, as Spain was after the death of Gen. Francisco Franco in
1975: a flagging economy surrounded by European giants.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of August, plans to travel to Washington to meet with
President Clinton. Among Fox's long-term goals is to make the
tightly guarded U.S.-Mexico border as open as the one between the
U.S. and Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
