<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, July 16, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-HOLDINGS-REVIEW (Washington) _ It's the new risk for the
politician in this new economy: Lawmakers who actively invest are
discovering that their stock portfolios have become yet another
area of their personal lives that is vulnerable to attack. By Don
Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTES-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Where Have All the Footnotes
Gone?'' the historian Gertrude Himmelfarb asked in a 1991 essay. At
that point, footnotes lucky enough to survive at all had moved to
the backs of books and turned into less scrutinized end notes.
Annotation was out; breezy, uninterrupted prose was in. Indeed the
Web has not only revived the footnote, it has spawned a
cross-referencing craze that renders the formerly complete media
event into a reference-laden, link-dependent, list-spewing
wallflower waiting to be courted by the next available annotator.
By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITE-BOOK-REVIEWERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Book critics can be a
pompous, self-important lot. Many people gripe that they are out of
touch with the common reader and that their highfalutin academic
tastes have no relation to what the masses might enjoy. As with
every other aspect of modern life, the Internet _ specifically
Amazon.com _ has leveled the literary playing field. The Web site's
customers can review books and post their critiques, and thousands
of them have tapped out their thoughts and donated them to the
digital universe. By John D. Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   QUANTUM-PHYSICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Startling as life in the
subatomic realm can seem, with particles existing both here and
there or darting to and fro at the same time, people have been able
to take some small comfort in knowing that the ``real'' world
doesn't work that way. Though made of the very same stuff that
marches to the dictates of quantum theory _ the laws that explain
how particles behave _ solid objects obediently occupy one place at
a time and are never seen moving in two directions at once. But
when quantum rules are applied to the domain of creatures and
things, the result is nonsense. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX-REVIEW (Undated) _ The belief that anyone can grow
rich in America took root even before the colonies decided to
become a nation. This faith has outlasted innumerable depressions,
recessions, inflations and deflations, and today, with millionaires
now making up less than 4 percent of the population, it seems
stronger than ever. It's wise to keep this fiscal theology in mind
when trying to understand the push congressional Republicans are
making to repeal the estate tax _ and the unexpectedly wide support
they've garnered, both in Congress and among many Americans. By
Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-THESIS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Ah, the lessons learned in youth.
About love, faith, family and yes, the power of television to
define the modern presidency. This last issue weighed especially
heavily on at least one young person, Albert Gore Jr., as revealed
in the topic he chose for his senior thesis for the history
department at Harvard in 1969. Its title: ``The Impact of
Television on the Conduct of the Presidency, 1947-1969.'' The
84-page paper sheds light on an aspect of political life that would
preoccupy Gore in his own career in public office and into the
current presidential campaign. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-DEFENSE-REVIEW (Washington) _ There is a dirty little
secret in American arms control circles these days: No one really
knows where U.S. nuclear doctrine is headed. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-REFORM-FCC (Washington) _ In 1998, the Federal
Communications Commission announced that it was going to consider
setting up hundreds of low-power radio stations for non-profit
organizations across the country. In January of this year, William
Kennard, the commission's chairman, said he would proceed with the
plan and that the groups could begin applying for 1,000 licenses.
It was potentially the biggest change in the radio industry since
the growth of FM in the 1960s, analysts said, and it has become one
of the most controversial issues in Washington. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ News highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ULSTER-REVIEW (Jerusalem) _ It can be useful for
Israelis and Palestinians to look closely at Northern Ireland for
instructive parallels, warnings signs, and, more recently,
practical lessons in conflict resolution. Not all the lessons are
encouraging. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-REVIEW (Undated) _ They mislead each other, although they
are supposedly on the same side. They make decisions that shape the
economies of the world based on disturbingly imperfect information.
If they were a U.S. conglomerate, they would be market pariahs and
serious candidates for Chapter 11. The subject under discussion is
not a failing Eastern European car manufacturer, but the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, or OPEC, the
fractious group that controls the global supply of crude oil, the
commodity that runs the world. By Neela Bannerjee.
</P>
