<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2281 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-WORLD-BIZ-JAPAN-$ADV1     07-14 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BIZ-JAPAN-$ADV16-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JAPAN: OUTSOURCING WITHOUT A CAPITAL `O' 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ It's treated as a dirty little secret here, but Japan
Inc. is embracing, gingerly, one of America's most hard-knuckled
business tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by a need to streamline their balance sheets, cut costs
and drastically upgrade their information technology to regain
competitiveness, Japanese companies are farming out chunks of their
computer operations to companies like IBM Japan, Fujitsu and NTT
Data.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Inc. is often choosing, however, to forgo one of the most
lucrative side effects of such outsourcing _ the shrinking of the
corporate work force and the resulting cost savings.
</P>
<P>
   As American as outsourcing may be, in Japan it reflects a
business culture stubbornly resistant to practices that sacrifice
employee well-being for the sake of efficiency. Japan's version
suggests, more broadly, why technologies and management practices
that are propelling the American economic boom have had less impact
here.
</P>
<P>
   When IBM Japan and Daiwa Bank put themselves on the map in 1997
with what was billed as Japan's first real outsourcing deal, the
treatment of the people involved was a bigger issue than the
business and financial ramifications. ``Given the unique character
of the Japanese employment system, there was some initial
resistance at the bank and perhaps within society itself,'' said
Yoshinobu Ishigaki, general manager of IBM Japan's service business
development division. ``Even the government showed some concern
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Daiwa deal spawned business that more than tripled
IBM Japan's outsourcing revenue. This year alone, IBM Japan, a
wholly owned subsidiary of International Business Machines, has
scored contracts worth more than $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a turning point in 1997 _ and it was a sharp one,''
Ishigaki said. ``Japanese companies realized they needed to
demonstrate their ability to change, and maybe more importantly,
Japanese society began accepting outsourcing.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants like Fujitsu and NEC are also using outsourcing _ both as
providers and as clients _ to meet the new challenges of a global
business world that is increasingly reliant on computers and the
Internet. Many businesses, particularly those in financial
services, realize that they can no longer afford to invest in
sophisticated information technology themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks in Chiba, Ehime, Hokkaido and lots of other places are
looking to outsourcing as a way to survive,'' said Fumio Ohue, the
partner who until recently headed the outsourcing business of
Andersen Consulting and is now chief operating officer of the
Netyear Group, a Japanese company that is devoted to providing
strategic consulting services online. ``It's hard for them to try
to catch up with new products, networks and business management
services on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Outsourcing is a radical departure for most Japanese companies,
which have long taken pride in doing everything themselves, or at
least within their cluster of affiliated businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sort of all-by-ourselves-ism that developed,''
said Sachio Nishiyama, chief manager of the systems administration
division at the Mitsubishi Trust and Banking Corp. ``Now we're
casting off that attitude, because we understand that there are
areas where other companies can simply do it better.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year of discussions among senior executives, Mitsubishi
Trust handed over to IBM Japan the operation of its data centers
and the management of networks linking its sales offices; the deal
is worth more than $350 million over the next decade. The bank
expects to cut the cost of systems administration by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The costs would have fallen further if Mitsubishi Trust had sent
the 50 employees associated with those activities to IBM Japan. But
all were offered jobs elsewhere in the bank, according to Masahumi
Abe, manager of the systems administration division.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.S. and Europe, this is probably hard to understand,
since there, outsourcing is not just IBM Japan taking over the work
but also taking over the people,'' he said. ``But in Japan,
outsourcing hasn't reached such an extent.''
</P>
<P>
   Not nearly. In fact, only a few Japanese companies are
advertising their move toward outsourcing various aspects of their
business, including accounting and human resources. In this land of
lifetime employment, outsourcing conjures up an image of
job-cutting, which is still in many ways taboo. So most companies
would rather not talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, but why is The New York Times interested in our
outsourcing efforts?'' asked Fumiaki Ito, senior vice president of
the Meiji Seika Co., a candy, dairy and pharmaceuticals company
that hired IBM Japan in February to manage many of its computer
systems. ``We are not the only company adopting outsourcing, you
know. It's not such a big deal, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Katsuhiko Minami, director of Meiji Seika's information systems
department and manager of the 70 employees affected by the deal,
was quick to point out that only nine jobs were lost _ and that
those workers were given other posts or allowed to retire. ``There
are always new needs within the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Retaining workers would seem to defeat the purpose of
outsourcing. But Minami appeared happy with the 100 million yen, or
$943,000, that Meiji Seika would save each year for the five years
of its contract with IBM Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a lot on a percentage basis,'' he said, ``but it's a
lot of money saved nonetheless.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At some companies, however, such sensitivities are fading fast.
A recent television documentary about NEC's efforts to overhaul
itself showed four workers wrestling computers into shipping boxes,
tears streaming down their faces. They were part of a group of 300
white-collar employees, all formerly parked behind desks, who were
dispatched to a packaging and warehousing company affiliated with
NEC.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for NEC made no effort to explain away the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regard the case shown on TV as outsourcing,'' he said,
bluntly declining to use more euphemistic terms for the
longstanding practice of sending unnecessary workers to affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Others work harder to make outsourcing difficult to distinguish
from more traditional business practices here. Ohue classifies many
recently created joint ventures as outsourcing in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Toyo Information Systems, an affiliate of
Sanwa Bank, and Komatsu, the struggling general building
contractor. As part of a reorganization, Komatsu sold 65 percent of
its software subsidiary, Komatsu Soft, to Toyo. Komatsu can
continue to rely on its former subsidiary and, as a major
shareholder, still be treated as a special customer. Yet it shed
responsibility for some 700 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is win-win outsourcing done in a very Japanese way,''
Ohue said. ``I think we'll see more of that kind of outsourcing
because it allows everyone to save face and is not as harsh as
outsourcing U.S. style.''
</P>
<P>
   Outsourcing still faces opposition here, no matter how soft the
touch. NCR Japan has been one of the biggest outsourcers, moving
1,200 people off its payroll and fighting at least one bitter
battle with labor. In 1994, the company temporarily transferred 700
employees to a new, partly owned affiliate to handle maintenance
work. Four years later, when NCR tried to make those transfers
permanent, some union members took the company to court. The case
is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   That has not discouraged Isao Aoki, head of NCR Japan's human
resources operations. ``I introduced outsourcing to this company
because I believe it will strengthen the whole company,'' he said.
``It was the only effective way to restructure in Japan, where
simply cutting jobs is considered unjustifiable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
