<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0715-COX     07-14 2043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Faith, hope and federal money
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush proposed a $400 million increase in federal aid
for after-school programs today, and said religious institutions
should be permitted to qualify for both current funding and the new
money as well. ``We shouldn't fear faith and love,'' he said at a
Presbyterian community center in Elizabeth, N.J. Bush said he
favors ``combining compassion and love with federal money.'' Bush's
appearance was designed to underscore his campaign theme of
compassionate conservatism with the theme: no child left behind.
</P>
<P>
   WAIT, WHAT ABOUT THE METS?
</P>
<P>
   From New Jersey, George W. Bush crossed the Hudson River today
and mocked Hillary Clinton's bid to depict herself as a New Yorker
and said her rival for the Senate, Rick Lazio, ``doesn't have to
wear a Yankee cap to play like he's a Yankee fan.'' Bush and Lazio
spoke to the same Conservative Party luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S ALL IN THE TIMING _ BUT WHEN?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is strongly considering plans to announce his running
mate the day after the Republican convention ends early next month,
as a way of siphoning media attention from the Republican
candidate, George W. Bush, according to the New York Times. The
paper, quoting sources, said that Gore has not yet agreed. He may
want to allow some time to pass after the GOP convention ends to
gauge the public's response to the Republican ticket. And he may
also need extra time to determine whether he wants to counter the
Republican choice in terms of gender or geography.
</P>
<P>
   COULD IT BE GEPHARDT . . .
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is exploring the possibility of picking House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri as his running mate in a move that
would unite two of the most powerful figures in the Democratic
Party, according to several news organizations. Although talks are
at an early stage _ and could well go nowhere _ just the floating
of a Gephardt trial balloon has set off a sharp debate within the
Democratic establishment over the pluses and minuses of picking the
highest-ranking House Democrat. Gore held a secret meeting with
Gephardt last Saturday, and is not known to have had face-to-face
veepstakes discussions with anyone else under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   . . . OR COULD IT BE GRAHAM?
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham of Florida is going to Nashville on Saturday,
and it's not to be a backup singer on Faith Hill's next album. He's
vying to be Al Gore's backup. Speculation surrounding Graham as a
potential running-mate intensified this week when Gore asked
Graham, who also is a popular Florida ex-governor, to fill in for
him at a Tennessee fund-raising event. It will be the second time
in as many weeks that Graham has filled in for Gore, another clear
sign that Graham is on a shortlist of running mate choices.
</P>
<P>
   HAIL THE DEFEATED CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   John McCain will keep a schedule fit for a nominee at the
Republican convention, seeking the spotlight even as George W. Bush
claims the Arizona senator's delegates and the GOP presidential
nomination. McCain's tentative schedule includes one news
conference, three speeches, dozens of media interviews and a bus
trip. With an eye on a second presidential race, the Arizona
senator will promote himself and his reform agenda at the July
31-Aug. 3 convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   LOW PROFILE FOR LITTLE BROTHER
</P>
<P>
   Florida Gov. Jeb Bush says he has remained mostly out of sight
during the presidential campaign because he is worried that a
higher national profile could hurt brother George W.'s campaign.
``I've really been almost reclusive,'' said Jeb Bush in an
interview with the New York Times. ``I don't see how I help George
by having a high profile nationally. In fact, I see the opposite.''
Jeb has done relatively little campaigning for his brother outside
of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   GUESS WHO'S COMING TO DINNER
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters President James Hoffa not only will attend this
month's Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, he'll be
honored there at a party thrown by GOP chairman Jim Nicholson and
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge. This apparently will be the first time
in 20 years that a union president has been honored by the GOP
during one of its conventions. The Teamsters' endorsement in the
presidential race is eagerly being sought by both the parties. The
union, with its 1.5 million members, has not endorsed a candidate
yet.
</P>
<P>
   NEW BUSH TV ADS TO TRACK GORE'S
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party, which suspended its TV ad campaign three
weeks ago, is returning to the airwaves in force in an effort to
help their flag-bearer build momentum before his nominating
convention. An ad touting plans by George W. Bush and the party to
improve education will begin airing Tuesday in the 17 states
currently running Democratic National Committee ads on behalf of Al
Gore. In addition, Republican ads will air in California, Nevada
and New Hampshire. The new buy, about $6 million in the first week
alone, underscores Bush's intention to compete with Gore in
traditionally Democratic states.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T TRASH THEIR TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   Texans unhappy about their state being the target of political
broadsides by the Gore presidential campaign have formed an
organization to counter the attacks on health care, education and
other issues. The Proud of Texas Committee described itself in a
letter to Al Gore as a group of independents and Democrats who plan
to speak out against incorrect or misleading information about the
Lone Star state. Gore has criticized Texas' record under the George
W. Bush's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIT OK'D ON BUCHANAN'S LIST
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party leaders have cleared the way for Pat Buchanan's
opponents to force an audit of his massive list of supporters,
arguing that the list may taint the party's presidential selection
process. John Hagelin, the little-known physicist challenging
Buchanan for the Reform nomination, says he wants to know whether
the former Republican fattened his petition numbers with names from
his extensive list of Republican supporters. The auditor would be
required to keep the names on the list secret.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MANY, YOU CAN WAKE THEM WHEN IT'S OVER
</P>
<P>
   State polls show Al Gore ahead in California and New York, but
behind George W. Bush in Texas, Pennsylvania and Illinois, with
Ralph Nader taking support from Gore in several states. The race in
Florida was close after Bush led there in April, the poll
suggested. A national poll by the Pew Research Center for the
People &AMP; the Press (3 percentage point margin of error) suggested
less interest than in past presidential elections, with less than
half saying they thought a lot about the election, a drop from
two-thirds who were closely following the campaign in the summer of
1992.
</P>
<P>
   MORE MAKEUP NEEDED BEFORE THE CLOSE-UP
</P>
<P>
   It's not the spruced-up image this convention city was hoping
for. It was supposed to be American flags and a red, white and blue
skyline in honor of the Republican National Convention, not a
videotaped police beating of a black suspect after a stolen car
chase and shootout. The incident is a reminder of Philadelphia's
unpleasant past, marked by police brutality, corruption, racism and
a deadly fire-bombing. Police Commissioner John Timoney says a
single incident, however the investigation turns out, should not
taint the country's image of the city. But the videotape will have
an impact.
</P>
<P>
   THE CITY OF BROTHERLY PROTESTS
</P>
<P>
   From T-shirts and fliers with the convicted man's face to a day
dubbed the ``Executioner's Ball,'' supporters of death row inmate
Mumia Abu-Jamal are expected to be particularly visible in the sea
of activists during the Republican convention. So visible that
other demonstrators worry about over-saturation, though some of
Abu-Jamal supporters say there can't be too much attention.
Abu-Jamal, 45, is the ex-radio journalist and Black Panther who was
sentenced to death in the 1981 killing of white Philadelphia police
officer Daniel Faulkner. Abu-Jamal's supporters say he was framed
by racist police.
</P>
<P>
   LIKE THE SUPER BOWL SIDESHOWS
</P>
<P>
   For political junkies, there will be a home away from the
Republican convention: PoliticalFest, a multimedia show, that will
try to capture some of the history and hoopla of the nation's
political conventions. PoliticalFest is set for the cavernous
Pennsylvania Convention Center from July 26-Aug. 3. Visitors will
be able to deliver a whistle-stop speech, tour replicas of the Oval
Office and Air Force One, explore items on loan from 10
presidential libraries, and otherwise immerse themselves in
American political history. The event was dreamed up a few years
ago as a way to distinguish Philadelphia from other convention
hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   MIRROR IMAGE OF 1988
</P>
<P>
   He's a popular governor, has no foreign policy experience, is
running against a sitting vice president and enjoys a comfortable
midsummer lead against his opponent. Who is he? If this question
were posed on ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire,'' the most obvious
answer would be George W. Bush. But the description also fits
Michael Dukakis, the 1988 Democratic nominee against another George
Bush. The similarities are eerie: a strong economy as the campaign
backdrop; an administration marred by major scandal; a vice
president struggling to move out of the shadow of a star-quality
president; a Democratic candidate criticized for not connecting
with the voters. And a man named Bush.
</P>
<P>
   FACING HIMSELF IN THE MIRROR
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dukakis, today a college professor, has had plenty of
time to reflect on a campaign that started with high expectations
but went down to dismal defeat. ``The first thing you ought to
learn from 1988 is that the horse race numbers are meaningless,''
he said, pointing to the polls in the summer of 1988. ``Those
numbers were never real, and they never are.'' In mid-June of that
year, Dukakis led Vice President George Bush by a 14-point margin.
The day after the Democratic convention ended in Atlanta, Dukakis
was ahead by 17 points. He ultimately lost the election 53 percent
to 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S OFFICIAL _ NBC BACKING AWAY
</P>
<P>
   NBC News released coverage plans for the conventions that could
push President Clinton's speech at the Democratic event off the NBC
broadcast network and instead relegate it to the less widely
available cable channel MSNBC. MSNBC will extensively cover each
four-day convention, but the NBC network _ making official what it
earlier hinted at _ said it will limit live coverage to just one
hour on the Wednesday of each convention and 90 minutes on the two
Thursdays, when nominee acceptance speeches are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN A KISS IS A HANDSHAKE
</P>
<P>
   On a campaign swing through Queens, Hillary Clinton offered her
most detailed explanation yet about why she kissed Suha Arafat,
wife of Yasser Arafat, after Arafat made scathing remarks about
Israel during a joint appearance in November. Responding to a
woman's question at the Bell Park Jewish Center: ``I don't know if
any of you have been to the Middle East. But if you have, you know
that a kiss is a handshake. ... I did what I was expected to do.''
She added that she had ``responded appropriately as the first lady
of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   WHO ARE THESE GUYS, ANYWAY?
</P>
<P>
   Republican Jim Talent has taken a 41-36 lead over Democrat Bob
Holden in what has been a largely invisible campaign for Missouri
governor. Perhaps the most significant finding in the poll
commissioned by the Kansas City Star was the relatively low name
recognition for both. Holden, the state treasurer, ran successful
statewide campaigns in 1992 and 1996, yet more than one in four of
those surveyed said they did not recognize his name. Talent has
been a congressman from St. Louis County for eight years, but
nearly one of every five people surveyed said they didn't recognize
his name.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
