<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2299 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KITTINGER0715-COX     07-14 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITTINGER0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Balloon team holds 40-year reunion
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Neil Armstrong stepped onto the moon in 1969 and
called it ``one small step for a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Kittinger stepped into thin air on Aug. 16, 1960, and nobody
could call it small.
</P>
<P>
   Kittinger's step set a world record that still stands for the
world's highest parachute jump _102,800 feet. He had floated to the
edge of space in a helium-filled balloon as part of the Air Force's
early high-altitude flight experiments, before America sent its
first astronauts into space.
</P>
<P>
   Kittinger relived those pioneering years Thursday with about 20
other members of the balloon research team at the Air Force Museum,
where the recently restored gondola from his record-setting flight
is on display.
</P>
<P>
   The reunion marked the 40th anniversary of the flight, which was
known as Excelsior III.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the first time we've all gotten together,''
Kittinger said.
</P>
<P>
   The team decided to mark the anniversary this weekend because
Kittinger was in town to attend the National Aviation Hall of
Fame's weekend enshrinement ceremonies. Kittinger was inducted into
the hall of fame in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Although the balloon flights were made from Holloman Air Force
Base, N.M., the research projects were managed at Wright-Patterson
Air Force Base, where Kittinger was stationed as an Air Force
officer from 1958 to 1963. Kittinger now lives in Orlando, Fla.,
but he said most of the people he worked with still live in the
Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   The gondola, parachute and other equipment designed specifically
for the flight were made on the base, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything for that project, except for the balloon, was done
right here in the shops at Wright Field,'' Kittinger said. ``The
Air Force had a tremendous capability, and it gave engineers a lot
of hands-on experience. We kept the civilian contractors honest
because we had the capability of doing it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kittinger called it ``sad'' that the Air Force has closed its
shops at Wright-Pat and turned most of its research over to
contractors, but the tone of Thursday's reunion was upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Kittinger recalled how Mad magazine once poked fun at his leap
by speculating on the fate of the photographer who snapped a famous
photo of Kittinger, clad in pressure suit and parachute pack,
leaping away from the gondola.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a civilian, and we didn't have a pressure suit for
him,'' Kittinger joked.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the camera that snapped the photo was set up by Tom
Arnold of Springfield, who was in charge of the cameras that
documented the flight and recorded data.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold recalled trying to make sure the cameras could work in
the extreme cold of the upper atmosphere, where temperatures fall
to minus 100 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have enough power (in the gondola) for heaters, so
we used hot water bottles,'' he said. Arnold warmed small plastic
water bottles in his car before the flight, then taped them to the
cameras before liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
