<SLUG> BC-FREE-LEXUS0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Settlement reached in Lexus suit
 &HT;    By Jeff Ostrowski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Five people will receive free three-year leases
on luxury cars, the result of the Florida Attorney General's suit
prompted by a West Palm Beach Lexus dealer's questionable ads.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Attorney General in February sued Lexus of Palm
Beach, which is owned by Bob Cuillo. The state said the Okeechobee
Boulevard dealership lured customers with deceptive ads.
</P>
<P>
   The dealership and its Boca Raton ad agency, McGee &AMP; Starr, say
there was nothing wrong with the ads. Attorneys for both companies
said they settled to avoid a costly court battle.
</P>
<P>
   McGee &AMP; Starr agreed to pay for the free leases as part of an
out-of-court settlement approved by Broward County Circuit Judge
Charles Greene.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to stand by their product,'' said Scott Richman,
an attorney for McGee &AMP; Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The agency created full-page ads that were published in The Palm
Beach Post in June 1999. In the ads, Lexus of Palm Beach offered
free cars if it couldn't match or lower customers' monthly
payments.
</P>
<P>
   One ad promised: ``No matter what you're trading in, no matter
what you're paying now, we will meet or beat your current monthly
payment or we'll give you the Lexus FOR FREE!''
</P>
<P>
   The dealership contended that the ads' disclaimers in small
print excused it from giving away cars.
</P>
<P>
   Two customers, Barbara Sherry of Boynton Beach and Mindy
Felinton, an attorney from Boynton Beach, were enticed by the ad.
In separate visits to Lexus of Palm Beach in June 1999, they tried
to trade their luxury cars for Lexus RX300s, a sports utility
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   When the dealership didn't meet the terms of the ad, Sherry and
Felinton complained to the Attorney General's Office. The state
investigated and found two other car shoppers from Palm Beach
County and one from Broward County who also were lured by the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry and Felinton didn't return calls. Assistant Attorney
General Bob Buchner said the five customers signed confidentiality
agreements as part of the settlement. Those agreements prevent them
from discussing the payment.
</P>
<P>
   Buchner said the free three-year leases are worth about $15,000
each.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
