<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robert Spano's Brooklyn hot list
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 16.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We asked Robert Spano, the new music director of the Atlanta
Symphony Orchestra and the conductor of the Brooklyn Philharmonic
since 1996, his favorite things to do in the borough. Though Spano
maintains a home in Brooklyn Heights, his schedule doesn't permit
him to spend much time there _ hence his fondness for takeout. His
list:
</P>
<P>
   1. The Promenade. This 2/3-mile walkway overlooking the East
River offers a knockout view of Gotham and the Brooklyn Bridge and,
on clear days, a glimpse of the Statue of Liberty. Brooklyn
Heights, between Cranberry and Remsen streets.
</P>
<P>
   2. Junior's cheesecake. Junior's is a quintessential New York
deli. New York magazine has called its cheesecake ``the world's
finest.'' 386 Flatbush Ave., downtown. 718-852-5257. To order
cheesecake: 1-800-958-6467.
</P>
<P>
   3. Nanatori Japanese Restaurant. A fashionable sushi place that
offers takeout. 162 Montague St., Brooklyn Heights. 718-522-5555.
</P>
<P>
   4. Heights Chateau Wines. Laura Park, the Philharmonic's
concertmaster and Spano's roommate, jokingly reminded the conductor
that ``the booze shop on Atlantic Avenue'' is one of his favorite
spots, because _ you guessed it _ it delivers. 131 Atlantic Ave.
718-330-0963.
</P>
<P>
   _Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
