<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2304 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-BROOKLYN16-COX     07-14 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Brooklyn state of mind: Manhattan's neighbor borough more than
holds its own, a beautiful bridge to America's melting-pot heritage
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 16.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, N.Y. _ Imagine spending your honeymoon here.
</P>
<P>
   My parents did, in 1947. But all my mom ever talked about was
the time she got her high heel caught in an escalator, and my dad
never could get over the tunnel guard who took one look at the
slowpokes with the Georgia license plate and yelled: ``Damn it, go
ahead!''
</P>
<P>
   How those Yankees laughed at their expense. My folks never made
it back, but they clung to their Brooklyn stories.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a lifetime of studiously avoiding the place in favor
of the Big Apple _ the mother of all boroughs and one of the most
intensely cosmopolitan cities on Earth _ I've gotten jazzed about
Brooklyn myself.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs Manhattan glam when you've got BAM (the Brooklyn
Academy of Music and home of such trendsetting artists as Mark
Morris, Laurie Anderson and Robert Spano, the newly appointed music
director of the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra)? Who needs Dorothy
Parker and The New Yorker's vicious circle when you can wander
among houses where Walt Whitman, Arthur Miller, Truman Capote,
Carson McCullers and Thomas Wolfe once wrote? Who needs a skinny
island cramped with skyscrapers when you've got Brooklyn's 3 1/2
centuries of history, architecture and that fabulous bridge? And
who needs Carnegie Deli or Katz's when you've got Junior's, an
orange-vinyl, downtown monstrosity that dishes out 59 kinds of
sandwiches and arguably the world's best cheesecake?
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Brooklyn-born comic Henny Youngman, take Manhattan
_ please. It's Brooklyn, birthplace of the hot dog and the Dodgers,
George Gershwin and Woody Allen, Mae West and Barbra Streisand,
that gets my vote as a truly great American place.
</P>
<P>
   Walking around one misty Sunday morning, crossing the scroll of
history that's the Brookyn Bridge, seeing Gotham through its Gothic
arches and watching the ferries cross the East River, I got an
altogether different view of this urban landscape. The towers and
steeples of lower Manhattan (Chemical Bank, Trinity Church, the
World Trade Center) were lined up like upended lipstick tubes
shrouded in murky blue ether. As joggers in Nikes and Yankees caps
slushed across the 117-year-old bridge, historical markers reminded
me that I was standing on a monumental feat of engineering, where
cable cars, electric trolleys, elevated trains _ even stagecoaches
_ have left the etchings of Time and Invention. Stagecoaches? Whoa.
</P>
<P>
   Down under the bridge, I stuck my head into the River Cafe,
where urns of pussy willow and banks of potted azaleas, hydrangeas
and daffodils announced a scene that is one of the most romantic in
the city. This restaurant is so in demand as a setting for marriage
proposals that the pastry chef has fashioned a chocolate
ring-holder. As I stood swooning, a man who looked like he was late
for work scooted through the parking lot and mocked the sound of
the blaring foghorn: ``Booooooonk! Boooooonk!'' Street scat.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing my morning constitutional, I strolled through one of
the oldest parts of Brooklyn, the Fulton Ferry Historic District,
so named for the steam ferries that began regular service to and
from Manhattan in 1814. By the mid-19th century, tens of thousands
of commuters made the trip daily. And Brooklyn _ or Breukelen, as
the original Dutch settlers of 1635 called it _ became New York's
first suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The view of city, water and sky from this vantage point was a
gas, and it was particularly moving to see that lines from Walt
Whitman's ``Crossing Brooklyn Ferry'' had been scripted into the
metal railings of the esplanade. (Nearby, at 170 Fulton St.,
Whitman, editor of the Brooklyn Eagle in 1846-47, set the type for
``Leaves of Grass,'' published in 1856.) ``Stand up, tall masts of
Manhattan! Stand up, beautiful Hills of Brooklyn! Throb, baffled
and curious brain!'' read the Whitman lines, making me feel at one
with the past and my present state of mind. Which meant it could
only be time for one thing: Junior's.
</P>
<P>
   Over this recent long weekend, I had hoofed my way around
Brooklyn's trendiest neighborhoods, from Brooklyn Heights to Park
Slope. I had hopped from BAM to BMA (Brooklyn Museum of Art) to the
BBG (Brooklyn Botanic Garden). But it wasn't until I got to
Junior's that I began to understand the melting-pot beauty of this
borough, where Hassids and homeboys all come together to say
yous-guys. While a James Dean type in a white T-shirt drank a glass
of milk, an African-American family noshed on cheesecake. And I
ordered matzoh ball soup and salmon croquettes.
</P>
<P>
   For Brooklyn is nothing if not the accumulated wealth of its
Italian, Jewish, African-American, West Indian, Asian and Latino
populations. It is home to 2.3 million people, representing 150
racial, ethnic and religious groups, according to its tourism
council. And _ here's where I drop my matzoh ball _ one in seven
Americans has roots in Brooklyn. This explains why my parents came
here on their first big trip out of the South _ to visit my Uncle
Gus and Aunt Pauline.
</P>
<P>
   After a fashion, Brooklyn is the Northeastern equivalent of New
Orleans _ a polyglot culture where anything can happen. And usually
does.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask my mom about her honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2305 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-BROOKLYNTOUR16-COX     07-14 2018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYNTOUR16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boroughing through Brooklyn: The highlights
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 16.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, N.Y. _ Next to glitzy Manhattan, Brooklyn has often
seemed stuck in the shadows _ like an old aunt's frowzy walk-up or
those leftovers that keep getting pushed to the back of the fridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of Brooklyn, I think of my grandparents'
apartment with plastic on the furniture and the smell of pasta
sauce lingering in the hall,'' says Stacey Colosa Lucas, the
Georgia Shakespeare Festival's marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, that's pretty much been everybody else's notion,
too. Though Brooklyn Heights has long been one of Manhattan's most
desirable burbs, look beyond its ``Moonstruck'' view and you'll
find yourself deep in the gritty heart of East Coast America. From
one subway stop to the next, the moods of Brooklyn can careen from
Spike Lee's Bedford-Stuyvesant to Neil Simon's Brighton Beach, aka
Little Odessa. If Manhattan is a platinum-blond starlet, Brooklyn's
a babushka.
</P>
<P>
   But that's been changing of late.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to 30 years of adventurous programming, BAM _ the moniker
of the Brooklyn Academy of Music, America's oldest performing arts
center, which opened in 1861 _ has become a cultural flashpoint in
the heart of the city. As evidence, the Daily News recently
reported that more than 25 Manhattan dance and theater companies,
smelling cheaper rents, were moving to the borough. At the same
time, The New York Times inked mammoth spreads on the flourishing
club and restaurant scene that's sweeping Fort Greene, Smith
Street, Park Slope and even bombed-out-looking Williamsburg.
Suddenly, it seems that Brooklyn's the hippest across-the-river
bohemian hangout since the Left Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Brooklyn's transformation to the ground zero of cool
has been so sudden that guest accommodations can't keep up with
demand. The downtown Marriott, which in 1998 became the first hotel
to open in 60 years, is already planning to expand. To fill the
void, Brooklyn Tourism Council spokeswoman JoAnne Meyers says there
are nearly a dozen bed-and-breakfasts and a service called Homestay
New York (information: 718-434-2071) that places visitors with
families that share similar interests.
</P>
<P>
   Over a recent long weekend, I had no trouble finding a place to
stay, checking in first at Park Slope's cozy but expensive Bed &AMP;
Breakfast on the Park, a 20-minute walk from the Brooklyn Museum of
Art and the Brooklyn Botanic Garden _ two warhorse institutions
that are worth a trip on their own. For a more urban experience, I
later moved to the Marriott, just a couple of blocks from the
Brooklyn Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, I found Brooklyn to be an ideal place for a weekend's
sight-seeing. Another option, of course, is to stay in Manhattan
and take a day trip to the Second City, only 30 minutes away by
subway. Just take your walking shoes, and don't plan on hurrying
back after dark.
</P>
<P>
   Some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brooklyn Academy of Music. Robert Spano, the Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra's new music director, remains very much a part of the
Brooklyn Philharmonic and its adventurous programming. The ensemble
sounds terrific, especially in the acoustically splendid BAM opera
house _ a gilded musical cage stacked with balconies, boxes and an
oval, coffered ceiling. Spano's next program, Nov. 17-18, includes
works by Schoenberg and Martin. Check the Web site
(www.brooklynphil.com) for the complete season.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs at the opera house is the BAMcafe, a hip destination
for good food and performance art Thursdays through Saturdays. Here
you can find spoken-word performances, Cuban dance parties, swing
nights and the likes of Duncan Sheik, Chocolate Genius or
``Spanglish salsa'' lord Coati Mundi and his RhumbaPhonic Band. The
monumental, vaulted room has the air of a European train station,
and the full-service cafe is a lovely place to have a schmear of
hummus and tapenade with a glass of vino before (or during!) a
concert. On the same level, BAM Rose Cinemas is a first-rate
art-film house. 30 Lafayette Ave. 718-636-4100, www.bam.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brooklyn Museum of Art. As the first museum in America to show
African objects as art (in 1923), this facility's African and
Egyptian collections are extraordinary. Yet I was most taken by
American works such as Georgia O'Keeffe's ``Brooklyn Bridge,''
Augustus Saint-Gaudens' bronze ``Head From the Adams Monument'' and
Abbott Thayer's luminescent portraits of his family. If there was a
pre-Raphaelite period in American art, Thayer and Saint-Gaudens
defined it.
</P>
<P>
   It was also fun to peek into the museum's period rooms _
oversize dollhouses furbished with mint-condition colonial
antiques. The gift shop was a little fusty, but I found some
wonderful, offbeat bargains _ like the leftover Nicholas and
Alexandra postcards, marked down to $1 for a triple pack of about
30, and an ultravivid red and yellow velvet-flocked pillow cover
that I'll probably never find a home for.
</P>
<P>
   While the scandalous ``Sensation'' show remains a footnote in
the museum's history, a Maxfield Parrish exhibit runs through Aug.
6 and a William Merritt Chase show through Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture garden in back is a nice place to lunch in the sun
and meander among the architectural fragments waiting for
restoration. 200 Eastern Parkway. 718-638-5000,
www.brooklynart.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brooklyn Botanic Garden. After Central Park, this garden is
the most significant green space in New York. Not only has the
80-year-old Japanese garden been recently refurbished, but the
bonsai collection of this living, breathing museum is boffo. Also,
I saw Amazon-size lily pads, roses named for Barbara Bush and the
Eiffel Tower and learned that the grounds are a hot spot for
shooting pop-music videos and Vogue covers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to learn about Brooklyn's cultural
contribution is to stroll through the celebrity path, which has
pavers for the likes of Lauren Bacall, Lena Horne, Susan Hayward,
Jacob Lawrence, Norman Mailer, Marianne Moore, Barbra Streisand,
Barbara Stanwyck _ and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   In the Shakespeare Garden, you can see everything from wormwood
and tongue of dog (``Macbeth'') to pomegranate (``All's Well That
Ends Well'') and rosemary (``Hamlet''). But not every fragrance
wafting here is from the garden _ that caraway you smell may be
from the spice factory two blocks away. 1000 Washington Ave.
718-623-7200, www.bbg.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brooklyn Heights. This is one of the most beautiful urban
spaces in America, a cornucopia of 19th-century architecture
dripping with gargoyles, stained glass and other whimsies.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Whitman onced lived on Cranberry Street, and Truman Capote
wrote ``In Cold Blood'' in the basement of 70 Willow St. With its
spas, cafes and coffee shops, the neighborhood around Montague
Street seems as spiffy as Soho and Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   It's absolutely essential to visit the Promenade, where you
linger in the shadow of some of the city's best-situated real
estate while taking in the gorgeous Gotham view across the East
River. This walk is ideal for jogging at daybreak _ and making out
after sunset. Go west on any street between Cranberry and Remsen
and you'll run into the Promenade.
</P>
<P>
   Dining out
</P>
<P>
   For Middle Eastern food, hit Atlantic Avenue. For Italian, it's
Bensonhurst. Want Polish? Go to Greenpoint. And so it goes in this
ethnically vibrant town. Park Slope (particularly Fifth Avenue) and
Smith Street are the new culinary hot spots _ with food that can be
as ambitious as you'll find in Manhattan, though the vibe and the
prices are often more relaxed. Here are some neighborhood favorites
(for more recommendations, check out www.tasteofbrooklyn.com):
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Al Di La. With his corkscrew hair and narrow designer frames,
owner Emiliano Coppa is a funny guy who resembles Italian actor
Roberto Begnini _ no matter what you say, he bursts out laughing.
</P>
<P>
   His neighborhood gem is getting more and more press all the
time, and I see why. The lamb shank is burnished with root
vegetables and tender to the bone. Malfatti _ little balls of
Parmigiani-Reggiano cheese mixed with herbs and served with brown
butter and sage _ is very good and very rich.
</P>
<P>
   After I'd worked my way through a hefty three-course meal, Coppa
dropped by to offer me a glass of grappa on the house. ``Only for
those who really enjoy themselves,'' he said, making me feel very
special indeed. 248 Fifth Ave. 718-783-4565.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diner. In what looks like a funky old trailer, practically
underneath the Williamsburg Bridge, is an old-fashioned diner
that's been rethought by former bartenders from Balthazar and
Odeon.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday brunch, a friend and I sucked down a couple of Bloody
Marys and plowed our way through big platters of poached eggs,
slices of juicy-tender fresh pork and a hearty helping of beans.
Cowboy Eggs, they called it. At other hours, we hear the
traditional bistro food _ like skirt steak, fries and a martini _
really rocks. 85 Broadway. 718-486-3077.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cambodian Cuisine. The word is out about this hole-in-the-wall
across from the Brooklyn Academy of Music. My $12 lunch included a
little dish of sweet pickled veggies and an enormous bowl of noodle
soup in spiky lemon grass-chili broth with shrimp and fishballs.
Very yummy and very cheap. 87 South Elliott Place. 718-858-3262.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Junior's. This is one of those '50s time-capsule spots where
you can get everything from cold borscht and potato pancakes to
beef tongue sandwiches and barbecue. Plus, you can't find a better
place for soaking up local color.
</P>
<P>
   The matzoh ball soup was a bowl of seductive little dumplings
floating in schmaltzy broth like manna from heaven. Next came an
appetizer portion of salmon cakes with Dijon hollandaise. And as it
was raining outside and I was waiting to check into my hotel, I
decided to go for broke with the open-face beef brisket sandwich.
Then I got depressed because I didn't have room for that
world-famous cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
   But next time it's raining and I'm feeling sentimental for
Brooklyn, it's good to know Junior's will ship the cheescake
anywhere in the States (1-800-958-6467). 386 Flatbush Ave.
718-852-5257.
</P>
<P>
   And sleeping in
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bed &AMP; Breakfast on the Park. Overlooking Prospect Park and on
the edge of the vibrant shopping and dining neighborhood of Park
Slope, this is a quiet place to spend a night or two and get a
really good breakfast. I loved the glittering, chandeliered dining
room, painted a bright orange-red and chockablock with the owner's
collection of paintings and silver.
</P>
<P>
   You will pay about the same price as the Marriott (about $250 a
night), but you're liable to make new friends over breakfast. And
the staff, though a bit persnickety over details (arrival time,
payment method, forgotten keys), seems willing to go the extra
mile. They even offered breakfast to an old friend of mine who
dropped by to say hello. Take a virtual tour at www.bbnyc.com. 113
Prospect Park West. 718-499-6115.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New York Marriott Brooklyn. Convenient to downtown, Brooklyn
Heights and the Brooklyn Bridge, this is where you stay if you are
working and need a quiet place to unwind. The rooms are tasteful
and commodious. There's an indoor pool, and subway service to
Manhattan is just outside the door. And as a New York Times writer
once noted, the sewing kit _ with six pre-threaded needles _ is
``the best ever.'' I'm hooked. 333 Adams St. 1-888-436-3759 or
www.marriott.com
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: New York's LaGuardia airport is closest to the
center of Brooklyn, but if you can find a cheaper fare to JFK or
Newark, it may be worth the five extra miles in a cab. Several
airlines, prodded by an AirTran sale, currently offer a
14-day-advance fare of $168 round trip.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Brooklyn Tourism Council, 718-855-7882 or
www.brooklynx.org.
</P>
<P>
   Another good Web guide: www.brooklyn.about.com
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
