<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2306 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-VANGOGH16-COX     07-14 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANGOGH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Boston, `Face to Face' with van Gogh's genius as portraitist
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 16.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The woman behind us on the subway was having a grand
time. She tried her best to muffle her appreciative laughter while
eavesdropping on every word my then 10-year-old son, Daniel, was
saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the big deal with Monet?'' Daniel wanted to know. He
was a painter going blind, he said. Impressionism wasn't anything
more than being unable to see clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel spelled out his preference for Rene Magritte, David
Hockney and Degas (not the ballerinas, he insisted, it's the bronze
horses). But it was really his assessment of Vincent van Gogh that
sent the woman into gleeful delirium.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with the sturdiness of Roger Ebert's thumb, Daniel
unleashed a two-word review of one of the most celebrated painters
in art history: ``Too brushy.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is with some parental trepidation that I have escorted
Daniel here, six years after his subway lecture, to see the
all-portrait ``Van Gogh: Face to Face'' at Boston's Museum of Fine
Arts. It's a monumental mounting of 80 of the 19th-century Dutch
artist's paintings and drawings. Running through Sept. 24, the show
not only features eight self-portraits but 17 paintings of postman
Joseph Roulin and his family, favorite van Gogh subjects in late
1888 and early 1889 in Arles before the painter entered the asylum
in St.-Remy in southern France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face to Face'' may not hold the wonder of seeing a premier
artist's most celebrated work. Van Gogh's ``The Starry Night,''
loaned out by the Museum of Modern Art only a dozen times in the
past century, and two other important works will be displayed at
Atlanta's High Museum of Art from Sept. 2 to Nov. 5. And, sadly,
``The Potato Eaters,'' the large study of expressive peasants, is
not here, either. But at its, forgive me, brushiest, these 80 works
combine to illustrate provocatively an artist searching for the
elusive connection to the human soul.
</P>
<P>
   Portraiture ``moves me to the depths, and it makes me feel
closer to infinity than anything else,'' van Gogh wrote in 1888.
</P>
<P>
   It's a remarkable statement from a man so greatly inept at
maintaining personal relationships. Maybe he couldn't communicate
very well with most humans, but as a largely self-taught artist, he
could paint the hell out of them.
</P>
<P>
   The show is divided into five major segments, starting with his
pencil drawings of aging pensioners in the early 1880s in The Hague
and proceeding through his time in Nuenen, where he produced the
dark character studies of peasants; in Paris, where, influenced by
avant-garde painters like Georges Seurat, he began using brighter,
clearer colors; in Arles, where the influence of Paul Gauguin
appears to have reached full bloom in his paintings of the Roulin
family and others; and in St.-Remy and Auvers, where, in between
seizures, his brush indeed seemed to sweep the broadest of his
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect illustrations for a bleak Dickens novel, van Gogh's
pensioner drawings are intensely dark, often deep-lined depictions.
In ``Orphan Man With Top Hat'' (1882), he physically rubbed the
black lithographic crayon he used to draw the old man's coat until
it hinted at the white underneath.
</P>
<P>
   My son will have none of it. He's immediately off to other
rooms, searching for more arresting work.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when all art seemed to astound Daniel. That was
years ago. He'd run ahead of me at Washington's National Gallery of
Art into the middle of a gallery of Dutch masterpieces, twirl 180
degrees, thrust his hands in the air and happily exclaim,
``Rembrandt!''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 16, like many teenagers, he sometimes speaks only when
he has to _ unless the subject has landed on pro wrestling or Kevin
Smith flicks.
</P>
<P>
   I can only wonder what Daniel thought of ``Head of a Peasant''
(1885), the unnerving portrait of a young man in dark cap and worn
coat with bold, questioning eyes.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, ``Face to Face'' reveals a perceived progression in
van Gogh's approach, from exact re-creations and a yearning to
reach inside a melancholy subject through his or her eyes to using
bold color to intimate mood and, in his own self-portraits,
dressing up in different outfits to perhaps see how physical change
affected his own tortured psyche.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is most dramatic in a grouping of six self-portraits,
all painted from 1886 to 1888. Van Gogh hardly looks the same, his
eyes peering from different locations in their sockets, his head
sporting a gray felt or straw hat, his chin a little more pointed
here, his cheeks a little more full there. Each of the paintings
reads remarkably well from across the room, and one, the
extraordinary 1887 ``Self-Portrait'' with swirling dots of orange
and blue about the head, seemingly pushes itself forward.
</P>
<P>
   As you turn the corner from this series, the most dramatic
painting _ ``Skull'' (1887-88) _ stops the show. With a background
of yellow and white, the detailed skull is etched in red and black.
A thick-but-lean, agitated slash of white paint appears to throb
from the left forehead with the force of a migraine.
</P>
<P>
   The next room, the largest in the show, holds the bulk of the
Gauguin-influenced works, including the rare grouping of 17
paintings of the Roulin family. The latter includes six pieces,
three provocative paintings each of Joseph and his wife, Augustine.
Viewed as triptychs, they echo the self-portraits, experimenting
with floral backgrounds, skin tone and body shapes to evoke
different emotions, creating a greater whole.
</P>
<P>
   It's a while before Daniel surfaces. And after persistent
prodding, he reveals the painting that interests him the most. It
is ``Skull.''
</P>
<P>
   Much later, with a single word he states what the work said to
him. ``Dread.''
</P>
<P>
   All of van Gogh's soul-searching _ and there it is in one
syllable. He was a man haunted by misery, a man whose brushstrokes
often screamed. One who likely heard voices and could never stop
the ringing in his head. Not even, as this show illustrates, after
he took a knife to his ear.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Art exhibit: ``Van Gogh: Face to Face.'' Through Sept. 24 at
Boston's Museum of Fine Arts, 465 Huntingdon Ave. 9 a.m.-4 p.m.
Saturdays-Tuesdays; 9 a.m.-8 p.m. Wednesdays-Fridays. $18-$20
adults; $16-$18 seniors and students; $6 ages 6-17; free ages 5 and
under. 617-542-4632 or www.mfa.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: A current fare sale offers nonstop flights to
Boston for $79 one way on AirTran or Delta with a 14-day advance
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accommodations: About 20 hotels have packages involving ``Van
Gogh: Face to Face''; some include meals inspired by the artist and
passes to the exhibit. Rates range from $199 to $650 per night.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Boston Back Bay Hilton, 40 Dalton St.
(617-236-1100), is within walking distance of the museum. Starting
at $239 (taxes and gratuities not included), accommodations for two
include an overnight stay (deluxe executive rooms with views of the
city are available), breakfast and exhibit passes. Detailed hotel
information can be found at www.boston.com
</P>
<P>
   /mfa.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Greater Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau,
1-888-733-2678 or www.bostonusa.com.
</P>
