<HEADER>
A2308 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GRAHAM0715-COX     07-14 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gaga for Graham: Many believe senator ideal Gore running mate
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Suddenly Bob Graham is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, shadowed by a pack of Florida journalists, he is
going to the home state of Al Gore to fill in for the vice
president as guest speaker at a dinner for Tennessee Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he is going to New York to tour Ellis Island with
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He's in the current issue of Time, is a frequent guest on the
news talk shows and is getting lots of ink in the nation's
newspapers as the press rushes to handicap the Veep chase.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Florida's senior senator is all the buzz, a red hot
pick to become Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   How likely is that? Increasingly so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole game is kind of like the stock market,'' said
Jennifer Duffy, a political analyst for the independent Cook
Political Report in Washington. ``Graham was very high for a while
a few months ago and then he dropped. Now, he's back up and the
trading is heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham is being mentioned along with Massachusetts Sen. John
Kerry as a finalist for the job. Some Democrats believe that in
that matchup, the nod would go to Graham. House Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt of Missouri is also being mentioned, but he seems
less likely than Graham or Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a former Tennessee senator, and Graham have known each
other for years. Both are policy wonks with similar records on the
issues. Both were contenders in 1992 to be President Clinton's
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Graham is unaffected by the attention. Privately,
Graham, 63, who has done nothing to squelch the speculation, is
said to be more than willing to accept if he gets the call from
Gore. And if the media speculation and the guesses of party
insiders are accurate, Graham has a much better shot at the No. 2
job this year than he had eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Graham would make a great vice president,'' said Attorney
General Bob Butterworth, Gore's Florida campaign chairman. ``This
state is competitive now, without Bob Graham. We're going to be a
lot more competitive with Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a ``celebrity death match'' in Florida, with Graham
taking on both Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Florida Gov. Jeb Bush,
said a Democrat close to Graham who believes that it would be a
very close race with no certain winner.
</P>
<P>
   With a new round of commercials playing in Florida and frequent
trips by Gore and Clinton, Democrats have made it clear that they
intend to challenge the Bush clan and its well-organized Florida
political machine.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists say Florida is a win even if they lose as
long as they can keep the race close and force the Republicans to
spend a lot of money here.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is far more important to Bush than it is to Gore.
Current thinking is that Gore has a lock on two of the four largest
states _ California and New York. Bush has a lock on Texas. That
leaves Florida and its critical 25 electoral votes. It takes 270
votes to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who was governor from 1979 to 1987, is extremely popular
with Florida Democrats. He also has been successful winning votes
from Republicans and independents. In 1998, he won reelection with
62 percent of the vote. In 1992, he won with 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that Bob Graham would make the race a lot
more interesting,'' said Randy Enwright, a GOP political consultant
working with Bush. ``I still think we would win the state, but
Graham would make it a closer race.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that could hurt Graham is Democratic Party concern
that if a Gore-Graham ticket won, Republican Gov. Jeb Bush would be
able to appoint Graham's replacement in the Senate. Bush would be
certain to pick a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be a factor,'' said Duffy. ``I don't think
Democrats have a realistic chance of winning control of the Senate,
but if they win two or three seats now, they could pick up two or
three more in 2002 and go over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duffy thinks winning the White House is more important to
Democrats than just holding on to Graham's seat. ``I think the next
few weeks are going to be very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
