<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Locally heavy rainfalls exceeding 2 inches will douse parts of
the Northeast this weekend as an unusually strong low-pressure
system at 18,000 feet, which marks the center of a large pool of
cold air aloft, moves sluggishly southeast from the Great Lakes.
The focus of the heaviest rains will likely be in eastern
Pennsylvania, southeast New York and the high ground of southern
New England, where a strengthening flow of moist air from the
Atlantic is forced to rise over the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms, some with hail and damaging winds, will
erupt Saturday over parts of the Middle Atlantic states as very
warm and humid air rises into cold air aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, potent thunderstorms will flare across parts of the
northern Plains as a cold front vigorously lifts very warm and
moderately humid air.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: STORMY WEEKEND
</P>
<P>
   Low-level warmth and moisture, which meteorologists refer to as
``thermodynamics'', are typically high during the sultry days of
July. On the other hand, the amount of lift imparted to warm, moist
air by upper-level disturbances, which meteorologists refer to as
``dynamics'', is often limited in July because winds aloft are
weak. This weekend, however, dynamic lifting by an active upper-air
disturbance dropping south from Canada will be unseasonably strong,
likely setting the stage for some exceptionally wet and stormy
weather across parts of the Northeast and Middle Atlantic states. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
