<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIDDONS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Atlanta novelist Anne Rivers Siddons' `Nora, Nora'
recalls life in fictional Georgia town where similarities to her
childhood abound
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 16
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been more than two years since Anne Rivers Siddons packed
up and moved to Charleston, S.C., but the novelist clearly still
has Georgia on her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Siddons makes frequent trips back to Atlanta to visit friends,
and her new novel, ``Nora, Nora'' (HarperCollins, $25), is a
nostalgic coming-of-age tale set in Lytton, Ga., a fictional
version of her hometown of Fairburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hadn't realized how much you miss your context,''
Siddons says. ``In Atlanta, I knew where every road went and knew
where everybody was. It's taken me a while to learn that about
Charleston. I do miss that feeling of just seamlessly belonging to
a place. I'll never miss the traffic and what the city has turned
into lately. Still, when I think of Atlanta, I think of my time of
being young there, in the '60s and '70s.''
</P>
<P>
   The 64-year-old author has written about those years before, in
``Downtown,'' ``Peachtree Road'' and other best-selling novels. And
it's the same era that is the backdrop for ``Nora, Nora.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1961, the novel is the story of 12-year-old Peyton
McKenzie, a frail, nervous, motherless girl who considers herself a
loser. But Peyton's life changes dramatically when her beautiful,
eccentric cousin Nora rolls into town in her Thunderbird coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Siddons acknowledges there is an autobiographical thread that
runs through the new novel. From her summer home in Maine, Siddons
talked about the parallels between Peyton's life and her own
small-town childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It seems like the 1960s are your favorite time? Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: I do keep going back to that time like a homing pigeon. It's
an interesting time, especially for those who were raised in small
towns in the South. It was a big leap from my hometown of Fairburn
to Atlanta, but I loved the journey. It was such an exciting time
of change. I feel sorry for kids now who don't have something they
can establish an allegiance with, like we did with the civil rights
movement or the Vietnam War. There's a hole in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How autobiographical is ``Nora, Nora''?
</P>
<P>
   A: I felt a little like Peyton when I was growing up in
Fairburn, Ga. I knew that I would have to leave my insular little
world and live in a bigger world. I was a little afraid. Everything
was so gentle then. You knew you couldn't stay there, and you don't
know what's ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the inspiration for this book?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wanted to go back and look at that time in my life _ the
seventh grade and the enormous sense that everything was about to
change. And I realized how vulnerable young women were at that time
and how easy it was to fall back into the life they knew. Unless
you had a Nora in your life, nobody in your town was going to teach
you about the wider world.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you have a Nora?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, and I wish I had. Nora is a creation of my deepest
wishes. I was an only child, and I always wanted an older sister.
Then I realized what I always wanted was a Nora, someone who would
help me not be afraid.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How difficult was it to recapture the mood of 1961?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was surprisingly easy. I had to go back and see what the
songs of that year were. But the ter three books I still want to
write. I'd like to do a novel about suburban Atlanta if I can keep
from turning it into a caricature.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you feel about e-books and publishing on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it's fine if people want to do it that way. I do not
want to sit at a screen and read it. I don't think I want to write
a serialized book online, like Stephen King is doing. I think I
would feel extremely constrained.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rivers Siddons will sign and discuss her novel at 7 p.m.
Tuesday at the Margaret Mitchell House &AMP; Museum (999 Peachtree
St.). Refreshments will be served. Admission is free, but call
770-578-3502 for reservations. Other signings this week: 7 p.m.
Wednesday at Chapter 11 book
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
