<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2313 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-EPISCOPARY-WOMAN0715-     07-14 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISCOPARY-WOMAN0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AME elects first woman bishop
 &HT;    By Khalid Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In November 1787, when Richard Allen stormed out
of the predominantly white St. George's Church in Philadelphia and
formed the African Free Society (later renamed the African
Methodist Episcopal Church), the thought of bringing a woman into
the hierarchy of his clan never entered his mind.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of selecting a female to the lofty position of
AME bishop could not escape the minds of the 1,800 delegates who
attended the order's closely scrutinized General Conference at the
Cincinnati Convention Center this week.
</P>
<P>
   In a landmark, second-ballot vote, the Rev. Vashti Murphy
McKenzie, 53, of Baltimore, Md., was elected to the Episcopary,
becoming the first female in the 213-year history of the church to
assume that seat.
</P>
<P>
   Although the selection of McKenzie wasn't a total surprise, it
nevertheless rolled back two centuries of inertia and sent a clear
message to religious orders that continue to exclude women from
church leadership.
</P>
<P>
   From all reports, the Democratic and Republican presidential
conventions will be hard pressed to match the drama, intrigue and
unfeigned elation of the AME general conference in Cincinnati. The
meeting had all the trappings of a political convention. Frantic
delegates waved banners, passed out fliers and campaigned hard for
their candidates. Because AME bylaws require a simple majority vote
to elect a bishop, the first ballot failed to produce a clear
winner.
</P>
<P>
   A second vote was taken. Kathleen Henderson, a member of
Dayton's Wayman AME Church, was on the floor of the Convention
Center when the groundbreaking tally came in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was phenomenal and exciting,'' she gushed. ``I'm so proud,
certainly of Bishop McKenzie, but I'm also proud of the electoral
body that brought her forward on her own merits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The body spoke very loudly and said, 'It's time.' It was a
fantastic feeling to be there and witness her acceptance speech. I
feel really, really proud.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie, who delivered the keynote speech at Wayman's 160th
anniversary in 1995, has extensive Miami Valley ties. She earned
her doctor of ministry degree from Dayton's United Theological
Seminary and has been a trustee at Wilberforce University since
1998. Wilberforce director of university relations, Gwendolyn
Brown, remembers McKenzie as a ``wonderfully spirited and dynamic
individual with keen business instincts and a profound spiritual
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   As pastor of the Payne AME church in Baltimore, McKenzie has
tripled its membership in six years to more than 1,700 members
while remaining a champion of programs to cure urban ills. As
freshly minted AME bishop, she will have to relinquish her duties
as pastor of Payne as a prelude to her new post as head of the 18th
Episcopal District in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came into the ministry my goal was not to become an AME
bishop.'' McKenzie told Associated Press. ``My goal was to take
care of the needs of people, spiritual and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time went on, I began to realize that God's intention for
my life was beyond the local congregation. Things were moving to a
ministry that is much broader.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie's election comes on the heels of the recent vote by the
Southern Baptist Convention, which effectively banned women from
the ministry. And as the debate on the role of women in church
leadership drags on, McKenzie let it be known in her acceptance
speech that she is mindful of the struggle it toos, to transform
themselves from cooks or maids to entrepreneurs. In short, Madam
C.J. Walker spawned the entire African-American hair and beauty
industry as we know it. And she became very wealthy in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Black Rose'' is a compelling, fictionalized account of
Walker's long and tedious journey from poverty-choked sharecropper
to philanthropic businesswoman. Walker was born Sarah Breedlove to
former slaves on a Louisiana plantation in 1867. In 1874, both her
parents died of yellow fever, leaving Sarah and her older sister to
fend for themselves as sharecroppers and later as washerwomen.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah gains and loses a husband (to racial violence), learns to
read and raises a bright and headstrong daughter before, at nearly
age 40, she develops the formula for ``Wonderful Hair Grower'' and
becomes the affluent and cultured Madam C.J. Walker (a name she
acquires through her second marriage). Novelist Tananarive Due
spends as much time on the hungry years as she does on the wonder
years that follow _ years in which Walker builds a factory, a
training school and a mansion.
</P>
<P>
   With the patience of a born storyteller, Due slowly allows
Walker's stirring story to unfold. She portrays Walker as an
intelligent, determined visionary who was destined to succeed. At
the same time, she doesn't soft-pedal Walker's flaws: Most notably,
she was a workaholic, before the condition had a name, and the
tough standards she held for herself and others eventually strained
her relationship with her daughter, talented socialite A'Lelia, and
ultimately killed her, as Due tells it. Yet, even while the
novelist gives us this well-balanced view of Walker, she never
veers from her optimistic narrative.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of triumphant, historical fiction is a departure for
Due, author of two previous novels, ``The Between'' and ``My Soul
to Keep,'' both of which featured elements of magic realism and
even leaned toward science fiction. (The only such element in this
novel is Walker's claim that her secret hair formula was revealed
to her in a dream.) Yet Due seems perfectly at home with the
material _ an impressive achievement given that she inherited it
from Alex Haley.
</P>
<P>
   When he died in 1992, the acclaimed author of ``Roots'' was
working on a novel about Walker; his estate selected Due to
complete the book, using the thousands of pages of research Haley
had amassed. Due was an inspired choice: As a thirtysomething black
woman, she brings a contemporary sense to Walker's story that even
Haley would have been hard-pressed to provide. And, because the
book is fiction, she is able to explore Walker's interior life with
much more freedom than a biography would have allowed.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to a slight discomfort: Readers are left wondering
how much of the story is true and how much Due has invented. The
seamless narrative makes it hard to tell _ which, of course, was
the author's goal. Still, reading this historical fiction might
make you crave a straightforward biography. Luckily, you won't have
to wait long. Early next year, Scribner will publish a biography of
Walker by her great-great-granddaughter, journalist A'Lelia
Bundles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Due's page-turner should go a long way toward helping
Madam C.J. Walker, the Oprah of her era, gain a following among
21st-century readers.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Boyd, an editor at The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, is
working on a biography of Zora Neale Hurston.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   The Black Rose. By Tananarive Due. One World/Ballantine. $25.95.
375 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An inspiring page-turner.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Boyd writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
