<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2314 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS16-COX     07-14 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An ex-Atlantan has the `Blues' in the best way
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Michael Skube
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Leavin' Trunk Blues. By Ace Atkins. St. Martin's. $22.95. 256
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The late John D. MacDonald began with blue and finished with
silver. When he died in 1986, he was just about at rainbow's end.
``The Lonely Silver Rain'' was the last in MacDonald's Travis McGee
series, 20 detective mysteries with a color in the title and a
laconic Florida boat bum at their center.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been ``Free Fall in Crimson,'' ``The Turquoise
Lament'' or ``Nightmare in Pink,'' but there was a sense in which
MacDonald was writing the same story from one novel to the next. He
was giving us the enigmatic McGee, with his lone-wolf suspicions
about love, his doubts about progress, his sidelong glances at a
past never fully revealed to us.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery novel depends on its contrivances of character and
setting, and more often than not is the better for it. A familiar
world doesn't have to be a believable world. It's enough that a
reader return, suspending reality and living in a world he knows
intimately.
</P>
<P>
   In only two novels, Ace Atkins has learned how to use the
devices so adeptly you hardly notice them. At the same time, he has
created a character, Nick Travers, we want to know better.
``Crossroad Blues'' involved the murder of blues guitarist Robert
Johnson in 1938. Crackling in incident, it was an impressive debut,
but it was clearly enough a first novel. ``Leavin' Trunk Blues'' is
a more textured, more accomplished piece of fiction. Travers is
back, and so is the music. The noir world of New Orleans' French
Quarter returns only as backdrop. Travers, the gone-to-seed blues
historian, is on Chicago's South Side on Christmas Eve. Seventy
miles away, in a prison cell, sits Ruby Walker, convicted of
killing a man named Billy Lyons in September 1959. She'd been one
of Chicago's great blues singers once, and Lyons was both her
producer and her lover.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, Travers comes upon some letters and asks to
interview her. Walker agrees on condition that he investigate facts
she says will uncover the truth of Lyons' death. Up from New
Orleans drives Nick Travers, unaware there are people on the South
Side who want to keep that truth buried. One of them is the
fearsome Stagger Lee, his name an echo of black folklore going back
to the days of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Crossroad Blues,'' Atkins' love of the blues infuses his
story, and it now and then threatens to overload his narrative. But
he instinctively knows where his story needs to go next. In this
respect, he already is a more disciplined writer than MacDonald,
who would interrupt his story to let McGee muse on urban sprawl,
the anonymity of a credit-card culture or the loneliness of women
married to rich men. Travers is not yet so sharply defined as
McGee. But he has become a more complicated figure in this second
novel and so, too, has the milieu in which the story takes place:
</P>
<P>
   ``On Forty-third Street, aka Muddy Waters Avenue, Nick watched a
group of teenagers staring at their reflection in a cracked mirror
propped against an abandoned warehouse. Next door, a wino sat on a
bucket looking at his rotted shoes as a bunch of kids played
hopscotch by a liquor store. The kids smiled and giggled, oblivious
to the poverty around them.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is Travers who must carry the story, and Atkins gives
readers enough without giving too much. There are details about
Travers' past that you don't know, but you discern his character by
his actions.
</P>
<P>
   That Atkins, at 29, should pick it up so quickly is a side
story. It wasn't many years ago that he was attending junior high
school in Marietta, and then Dunwoody High School (his mother,
Doris Atkins, still lives in Dunwoody). In his sophomore year, the
Atkinses moved to Auburn, Ala., where his late father, Billy Atkins
Sr., had been a football star on Auburn's 1957 national
championship team. The younger Atkins would later play for Auburn's
unbeaten 1993 team, an undersize defensive end whose fourth-quarter
sack of Florida quarterback Danny Wuerffel made the cover of Sports
Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   But he was an unusual kind of college football player. Lunkhead
coaches resented his refusal to gorge himself at the training table
so he could bulk up to 270 pounds. He told them he was quicker and
healthier at 213. And they noticed he was always reading or
scribbling stories in a spiral notebook, and smirked. The Poet,
they called him.
</P>
<P>
   The Poet wasn't at Auburn to find out how high he'd go in the
NFL's cattle-call. He took serious courses, earned a degree and for
the past several years has been a crime reporter for the Tampa
Tribune. He's written about cops, carnies and con men, and once
walked into a biker bar in Ohio to learn something of a killer
who'd been a regular.
</P>
<P>
   A novelist must have a nose for human motive, and novelists of a
certain kind must have an ear for the language of people with no
way out. Atkins has honed both to a high degree. When he was at
Auburn, he told someone he would rather meet John D. MacDonald than
Joe Montana. It was something else his coaches wouldn't have
understood.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
