<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-AIDS-810&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA CLOSES AIDS CONFERENCE WITH CALL TO MOVE BEYOND
CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ Closing the 13th International Aids
Conference Friday, Nelson Mandela urged scientists to move beyond
their concerns about South Africa's president and to focus on
combating the epidemic that is raging across the African continent.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech punctuated by repeated applause, Mandela said the
world could not afford to be distracted by the furor surrounding
President Thabo Mbeki, his successor, who has questioned whether
HIV causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela did not clarify Mbeki's views on the subject, but told
his audience that Mbeki was committed to fighting the sickness in
South Africa, the country with the largest number of people
infected with the AIDS virus, 4.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much unnecessary attention around this conference had been
directed toward a dispute that is unintentionally distracting from
the real life-and-death issues we are confronted with as a country,
a region, a continent and a world,'' said Mandela, who handed over
the reigns of power to Mbeki one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the face of the grave threat posed by HIV/AIDS, we have to
rise above our differences and combine our efforts to save our
people,'' he said. ``History will judge us harshly if we fail to do
so, and right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech marked the end of the first international AIDS
conference to be held in a developing country. About 34 million
people, most of them in Africa, are infected with HIV. And this
week, scientists debated the best ways to battle the scourge,
finding hope in studies that suggest circumcision reduces the risk
of infection and disappointment in a report that questions the
long-term benefit of a drug intended to protect newborns from the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   But the many scientific developments announced here were almost
overshadowed by the controversy surrounding Mbeki. He addressed the
conference only once, in the opening speech on Sunday, when he
singled out extreme poverty, rather than AIDS, as the biggest
killer in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But in the corridors and conference halls at the convention
center here, the president dominated conversations nearly as much
as the talk about future vaccines. Last week, the scientific
magazine Nature published a declaration signed by 5,000 scientists
from around the world who described the link between HIV and AIDS
as ``clear-cut, exhaustive and unambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   And this week, in panel after panel, scientists and activists
criticized Mbeki, who stirred the debate by consulting with two
U.S. researchers who argue that poverty and malnutrition, not HIV,
cause AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes the link between poverty and AIDS, which is well
established. And government officials here emphasize that Mbeki has
never said that HIV did not cause AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers fear that Mbeki's heavy emphasis on poverty and
his talks with AIDS dissidents may fuel confusion among ordinary
people who may assume they can engage in risky sexual behavior
because the president has raised questions about HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed, to put it bluntly,'' Roy Anderson, a
prominent AIDS researcher, said this week of Mbeki's speech. ``In
South Africa, it's really such an acute problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The government quickly lashed back. Health Minister Manto
Tshabalala-Msimang dismissed the criticism and accused the media of
distorting Mbeki's message. She insisted that the president was
committed to fighting the disease by encouraging safe sex and by
sponsoring research on drug therapies and a possible vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should he deny something he has not said?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Mandela also defended Mbeki. He called him ``a man of
great intellect'' and emphasized that he ``continues to place this
issue on the top of the national and continental agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela acknowledged that the government, under his leadership
and Mbeki's, had fallen short in its efforts to fight the disease.
Scientists and AIDS activists have repeatedly accused South African
leaders of a lack of leadership in combating the epidemic. In 1993,
HIV infected 4 percent of South Africa's adult population. Now the
figure is 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will, with me, be the first to concede that much more
remains to be done,'' Mandela said. ``I do not doubt for one moment
that he will proceed to tackle this task with the resolve and
dedication he is known for.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela did differ with Mbeki on some points. For instance, he
emphasized his reluctance to engage in the scientific debate,
saying he lacked adequate knowledge to contribute seriously.
Several scientists and commentators have criticized Mbeki for
delving so deeply into an issue in which he lacks expertise.
</P>
<P>
   And while Mbeki has questioned the safety of AIDS drugs, Mandela
stressed the urgency of using them to reduce the transmission of
the virus from mothers to newborns, saying such measures ``have
been proven to be essential.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mandela, who walked slowly and stiffly to the microphone,
leavened his speech with humor and populism, reminding his audience
not to forget the ordinary people who live with the disease. And
several delegates said they were cheered by his message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if he had anticipated a feeling in the audience,
that this was becoming a hindrance to our making progress,'' said
Benon Biryahwaho, a virologist from Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   His colleague, Remie Rwankote, an immunologist in Britain,
nodded in agreement, saying the speech left him with hope for South
Africa. ``We think they are ready to act,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
