<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2320 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-AIDS-MANDELA-HNS &LR;      07-14 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MANDELA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
(Editors: In 17th graf, Tuesday refers to July 18.) 
 
By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ Even in the face of staggeringly grim
statistics and estimates that one-half of this country's young
people could eventually die of AIDS, the 13th International AIDS
Conference _ the first ever held in a developing nation _ ended
Friday on a euphoric note.
</P>
<P>
   A delegate from Switzerland predicted that this conference,
attended by more than 12,000 scientists, doctors, nurses and
activists, would go down in history ``as the one that turned the
tide.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the high points: Recruitment of volunteers for the first
human trial of an AIDS vaccine for Africa was announced. Many said
the meeting prompted an unprecedented response from governments and
pharmaceutical companies. (Merck &AMP; Co. Inc. announced a $50 million
collaboration with the Bill &AMP; Melinda Gates Foundation in Botswana,
for example.) New data gave irrefutable evidence that a $4 course
of an anti-HIV drug could prevent thousands of new infections in
babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will be able to stop the process that started here,''
said Stefano Vella, president of the 10,000-member International
AIDS Society, which organizes world conferences on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   All week, on the fringes of the scientific presentations, a
debate raged over the South African government's reaction to the
epidemic. South Africa has the highest number of HIV-infected
people in the world, and its leaders have been accused of
exhibiting ``irresponsibility that borders on criminality,'' as a
deputy president of the World Bank put it.
</P>
<P>
   Sophia Mukasa Monico, a lawyer in Uganda who works with AIDS
support organizations, said, ``We know what works. AIDS is now a
crisis in governance.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a closing speech, former South African president Nelson
Mandela, a beloved figure described by the conference chairman as
``an icon of the century . . . the center of gravity of this
country,'' brushed all that aside as a distraction from ``the real
life-and-death issues.'' His grandfatherly admonition, in effect,
reduced the dispute to a squabble among overly bright children.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``The ordinary people of the continent and the world _
particularly the poor who on our continent will again carry a
disproportionate burden of this scourge _ would, if anybody cared
to ask their opinions, wish that the dispute about . . . politics
or science be put on the back burner and that we proceed to address
the needs and concerns of those suffering and dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela called the conference ``the one event where every word
uttered, every gesture made, had to be measured against the effect
it can and will have on the lives of millions of concrete, real
human beings all over this continent and planet.''
</P>
<P>
   In previous months, South African President Thabo Mbeki
dismissed the anti-HIV drug AZT as toxic. He has been harshly
criticized for refusing to implement a national program to
distribute anti-retrovirals to rape victims and pregnant women.
This spring, he invited dissident scientists who argue that HIV
does not cause AIDS to join an influential advisory panel,
prompting some researchers to call for a boycott of the $10 million
international AIDS conference.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate escalated, and demands for better access to
medication intensified, some drug companies decided to send fewer
representatives to the conference, or to not attend at all, out of
concerns for security. Delegates housed in distant locations were
able to move into vacant hotel rooms closer to the conference
center. Organizers worried they would not break even on costs.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the meeting drew 4,000 people from Africa, 3,000
from the United States, 3,000 from Europe, with the remainder
coming from other countries. (The 2002 conference is taking place
in Spain.)
</P>
<P>
   In his opening address to the conference, Mbeki disappointed
many delegates by not pronouncing HIV the cause of AIDS and by
focusing instead on poverty's ravaging impact on health. In
response to criticism, South African government officials
repeatedly emphasized that Mbeki never said that HIV does not cause
AIDS. They pointed to numerous examples of the country's efforts to
fight the disease. For example, prior to Mandela's election in
1994, annual condom distribution was 5 million. Today, it is over
190 million.
</P>
<P>
   Health Minister Manto Tshabalala-Msimang reminded guests at a
gala dinner that many of the country's current leaders had fought
to the death during apartheid for better quality of life. ``Why
would we be prepared to do that, and yet not be prepared to do
everything in our power to save the very lives of the people that
we led to freedom?''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Salim Karim, scientific chair of the conference, reconciled
Mbeki's emphasis on poverty with what is known about AIDS. Living
on a meager income is associated with many common diseases, Karim
said. Even before HIV, South Africa had one of the highest
tuberculosis rates. Each year, there are thousands of measles cases
and last year there was a malaria epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's migrant labor system, an artifact of apartheid
that forces men and women to leave home for long periods to work in
the cities, ``is one of the main reasons this country is
experiencing an explosive epidemic,'' he said. ``Poverty is part of
that profile.''
</P>
<P>
   In Africa, as elsewhere, elders rarely talk frankly about sex
with youngsters. But Mandela, who turns 82 on Tuesday, broke free
of tradition, calling for safe sex promotion, use of condoms and
early treatment of curable, sexually transmitted diseases. He said
voluntary HIV testing and counseling are ``essential in the fight
against AIDS.'' He drew applause for his plea for ``large-scale
actions'' to prevent mother-to-child transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hoosen Coovadia, a University of Natal HIV specialist who
chaired the Conference, told Mandela afterward, ``You cannot
imagine how your speech is music to our ears. It has answered so
many spoken and unspoken questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Malegapuru Makgoba, president of the South African Medical
Research Council, the country's largest research body, said the
conference had set a new standard: ``Maybe things will never be the
same. I feel proud to be associated with that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
