A2322 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-LOUD-COMICS0715-COX     07-14 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUD-COMICS0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Comic artist bets on ethnic heroes for super success
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Brace yourself. You're about to meet the
world's first multi-racial, all-female, half-human half-alien
superhero team.
</P>
<P>
   Raven's the leader. She's black, has the mind of a strategist,
and has super-vision. Rampage, a Hispanic woman, has mechanically
augmented super-strength. Bombshell can explosively disintegrate _
and reassemble _ herself. (She's white.)
</P>
<P>
   And the Asian, Silhouette . . . well, we're not sure what she
can do yet.
</P>
<P>
   They're the first characters to debut in a new comic book called
``The Crusaders.'' The book is the first offering from Loud Comics,
a West Palm Beach-based comics company. It's operated out of
36-year-old publisher Tim Mitchell's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Crusaders'' marks the realization of a dream Mitchell has
had for a few years now: To work in the comics business. Mitchell,
who gives private music lessons, has read comics since he was a
boy. He'd always done doodles and sketches, too. But in 1997, he
decided that wasn't enough and began submitting his portfolio to
large publishers like Marvel Comics.
</P>
<P>
   When the big boys wouldn't bite, Mitchell became discouraged.
But on a 1998 plane flight home from a Chicago comic convention,
something happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met a salesman on the plane,'' Mitchell says. ``He looked at
my stuff and said, `Why don't you just start your own company'. So
by the time I got back to Florida, I had that voice in my head. I
decided, `Let's do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So he did. In 1999, Mitchell created Loud Comics and the
characters in his ``Loud Universe,'' the imaginary Earth where
superheroes are reality. The guy has big dreams for ``The
Crusaders'' and the other comic titles he's planning. He wants his
characters to eventually become American icons like Spider-Man and
Superman.
</P>
<P>
   The key is to make decisions fueled by creativity and business
savvy. For instance, the decision to have a multi-racial cast in
``The Crusaders'' was deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   ``An all-white group isn't what's happening in America,''
Mitchell explains. ``If you live here in Florida you see people
from all walks of life. Hispanic, Middle Eastern, they're all here.
And if you're going to do superheroes _ who are hopefully going to
be read by people all over the planet _ then you need to have
something they can identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart thinking, and ``Crusaders'' (which Mitchell pencils) is
just the beginning for the upstart company. In the fall, Mitchell
hopes to release ``Scream Theatre,'' a 100-page quarterly comic
that'll feature vampires, morticians and rock 'n' roll. (That rock
'n' roll part, Mitchell knows a lot about: In the '80s, he was a
guitarist for the local heavy metal band Crazy Agnes.)
</P>
<P>
   After ``Scream Theatre'' debuts, Loud Comics will release ``Man:
Zero,'' a man-turned-cosmic entity story. It should debut sometime
next year. And ``Crusaders 2'' is already in the works.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be a hard journey for Mitchell and his wife, Rebecca, who
writes ``Crusaders.'' The financing for Loud Comics is coming from
the money Mitchell earns giving music lessons. The first issue of
``Crusaders'' is being sold exclusively on the World Wide Web,
while Mitchell looks for a mainstream distributor. And his
employees _ young unknowns in the comics industry, from around the
country _ aren't getting paid much.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone involved believes in the dream, Mitchell says.
That's what matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories will be strong enough that when you sit down to
read it, you'll say, `You know, there's a lot to this team','' he
says. ``I want people to become fans because they like what we do.
Spider-Man isn't a fad. He's here to stay. I hope our characters
become the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
