u i BC-TEENAIDS-HNS &LR;      07-14 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULTIMEDIA EFFORT TAKES ON SEX TABOO IN S. AFRICA 

</HEADLINE>
 AIDS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The billboard next to the freeway
is startling, impossible to miss. It features a stark quote from a
14-year-old child:
</P>
<P>
   ``I had sex. Will I die?``
</P>
<P>
   It's a pressing question in this country, where an estimated 4
million people are infected with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say young South Africans are particularly at risk: In
the past year, the infection rate among adolescents age 15 to 20
increased by 65 percent. Yet straight talk about the subject is
rare and misinformation is rampant, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   An ambitious, multimedia initiative called loveLife is
attempting to break through taboos and encourage frank discussion
about sex and gender relations. It features hip, in-your-face
advertisements (such as the billboard), radio programs, train cars
with slogans splashed on their sides and the country's first-ever
television talk show for young people about sex.
</P>
<P>
   In one TV episode, a 15-year-old boy put the problem eloquently:
``We cannot speak to our parents about love. They don't want us to
fall in love. So how can we talk to them about sex? If we can't
talk to them about sex, how do we talk to them about HIV and AIDS
and condoms?''
</P>
<P>
   LoveLife, sponsored by the U.S.-based Henry J. Kaiser Family
Foundation, is the country's largest HIV prevention program for
adolescents. Its aim is to halve the incidence of HIV among 15- to
20-year-olds over the next three to five years. The Bill &AMP; Melinda
Gates Foundation announced a $7 million donation to the program
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 13th International AIDS Conference in Durban, where
the train was stationed for four days, national director Shirley
Ngwenya has been swamped with phone calls, e-mails and requests for
youth centers and services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The faxes, I can't cope!'' she said. ``It's from grass roots
to corporate sector. It's a demand.''
</P>
<P>
   A new toll-free sexual health hot line receives between 70,000
and 123,000 calls a month, depending on where the phone number is
marketed, said loveLife media director Judi Nwokedi. LoveLife has
not yet advertised the number on radio, the most far-reaching
medium, because ``we don't believe we have the capacity to cope
with the calls,'' Nwokedi said. ``Which shows the need loveLife
tapped into. It was desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the program, visit the Web site at
www.lovelife.org.za.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
