<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2324 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MINIVANS-$ADV16-ART-3     07-14 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIVANS-$ADV16-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRYSLER PLAYS IT SAFE IN MINIVAN REDESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Since the early 1980s, Chrysler has
cultivated a reputation for daring, innovative designs, beating
bigger rivals by creating the minivan market and by revitalizing
the full-size pickup truck market with the burly Dodge Ram. Just
this year, its new PT Cruiser, an eccentric combination of a 1930s
gangster car and a minivan, has been such a hot seller that dealers
across the country have months-long waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   So four years ago, when Chrysler formed a team to start
designing the next generation of minivans for introduction late
this summer, the pressure was fierce to come up with another big
step forward. After all, Chrysler invented the traditional minivan
in 1983, producing a vehicle that Ford Motor and General Motors had
studied for years but never had the courage to build. Chrysler has
dominated the minivan market ever since with breakthroughs like the
introduction of driver's-side sliding doors in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But a few months before the minivan team was formed in February
1996, Chrysler executives were shocked by the public's hostile
reaction to Ford's radical restyling of its Taurus sedan and wagon.
Customers deserted the Taurus in droves, allowing the Honda Accord
and Toyota Camry to seize the lead in the midsize car market. So as
work began on the new minivans, Chrysler officials struggled to
understand what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   The results of their deliberations are in, and the new minivans
will go on sale in late August. After much market research, which
found that many buyers liked their minivans pretty much the way
they were, Chrysler, now part of DaimlerChrysler AG, decided to
play it cautious. It made many small changes in its minivans _ the
Dodge Caravan, Chrysler Voyager and Chrysler Town &AMP; Country _
offering, among other things, more powerful engines and an
optional, powered rear liftgate that goes up and down at the push
of a button. But it did not alter the fundamental design.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's experience with the Taurus ``set the fear in,'' said
David C. McKinnon, Chrysler's director of vehicle exterior design.
``You don't want to depart too much from your script if you have a
successful product.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporations capture headlines when they make big changes in
products with household names. Sometimes those changes prove
disastrous, as when Coca-Cola introduced a new Coke. But far more
common are the modest changes that companies make periodically,
even in best-selling products, to keep them from seeming out of
date.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler executives say their decisions reflected a careful
balancing of risks. The managers worried about the dangers of not
going far enough, which could result in losing less-loyal customers
to rival minivans like the Honda Odyssey, Toyota Sienna, Ford
Windstar and Pontiac Montana. They fretted about the popularity of
sport utility vehicles, which now outsell minivans by more than
2-1, and made some adjustments to give the minivans a slightly more
``aggressive'' appearance.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, they punted. They stuck with a basic design that
has led the market since 1983 and was last restyled in the
mid-1990s. Yet its market share has eroded to 42 percent, and other
automakers now make models that look similar, score better on
government crash tests and offer conveniences like third rows of
seats that fold into the floor of the cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically came to the conclusion that the formula was the
thing to preserve,'' said Gordon L. Rinschler, the engineer and
DaimlerChrysler vice president who oversaw the minivan redesign
project.
</P>
<P>
   Rival automakers, which have long struggled to catch Chrysler in
the minivan market, contend that Chrysler has decided to milk the
profits from selling to repeat buyers, instead of spending the
money to attract new ones. ``We're raising the bar, whereas
Chrysler decided to invest its money elsewhere,'' said Jim
Townsend, the marketing manager for the recently updated Ford
Windstar, the nation's second-best selling minivan after the Dodge
Caravan.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler executives reject that interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   But marketing experts say DaimlerChrysler's decision to make
incremental changes is fairly typical of big companies these days,
as so many are loath to experiment with proven success.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when companies come up with an innovative idea, they
tend to choose new names and create separate brands, despite the
formidable advertising expenses involved. With an attitude of ``if
it ain't broke, don't fix it,'' companies limit their real
money-spinners to cosmetic changes.
</P>
<P>
   A percentage point of market share is now worth more in many
industries than it was 10 or 20 years ago, because the markets for
so many consumer goods have become so fragmented as the country has
become more culturally diverse, said C.B. Bhattacharya, an
associate professor of marketing at Boston University. Global
competition from many different brands has intensified, too. ``If
you want to protect your share, then that calls for caution,''
Bhattacharya said.
</P>
<P>
   At DaimlerChrysler, wariness of big changes in its minivans is
particularly noteworthy, because the company, though the minivan
leader, is the third-largest player overall in the American auto
market, after GM and Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, said Jag Sheth, a marketing professor at Emory
University in Atlanta, companies that are not No. 1 or No. 2 in
their markets tend to be the most innovative, because they have
less to lose. In fact, Chrysler's overall record is one of the best
illustrations of that axiom, Sheth said.
</P>
<P>
   But these are prosperous times, and automakers, like companies
in many consumer industries, tend to be most cautious when sales
are strong. As the current economic expansion gets older, ``there
is a natural conservatism,'' said James R. Gregory, the chief
executive of Corporate Branding, a brand strategy company in
Stamford, Conn. ``People want to hold on to the gains.'' It takes a
recession or heavy financial losses to drive many companies to take
risks with successful products.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both the ground-breaking Taurus sedans and the minivan that
Chrysler introduced in late 1995 were designed during the 1991
recession. Chastened by public reaction to that Taurus, Ford
redesigned it for the 2000 model year to make it one of the
blandest, most nondescript midsize cars _ its plain, rectangular
windows replacing the ovals that made the previous version so
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Chrysler has more to lose if it miscalculates. Financial
analysts calculate that minivans contribute as much as one-third of
the profits of the Chrysler group, even though they account for
less than one-fifth of the vehicles it sells. And minivans are
particularly important to the company now, as high gasoline prices
could threaten its other big source of profits, Jeep and Dodge
Durango sport utility vehicles. While Chrysler expects gasoline
prices to fall later this summer, the relatively fuel-efficient
minivans could gain in sales at the expense of sport utilities if
prices stay high, said James P. Holden, Chrysler's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler acquired Chrysler in 1998, after the design of the new
minivans, but the merger produced one windfall for Chrysler:
Daimler's Mercedes division had been planning to introduce a luxury
minivan closely modeled on the Town &AMP; Country, but canceled the
project after the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite lavishly financed assaults over the years by practically
every other large automaker, Chrysler remains king in minivans,
with its 42 percent market share. Though that is less than half its
peak of 90.5 percent in 1988, Chrysler's dominance in the category
still surpasses that of any rival in any other major segment of the
American auto market.
</P>
<P>
   That success has been based on customers like Conrad and Dede
Weil, who have bought a new Chrysler minivan every two or three
years since 1983 and plan to buy another Town &AMP; Country as soon as
the latest design goes on sale next month. ``I put my order in for
the next one a year or two ago, before I even knew what it would
look like,'' said Weil, a real estate developer in Houston who
trusted Chrysler not to make radical changes.
</P>
<P>
   Until the new minivans go on sale, the best place to see one is
in the windowless, tightly guarded design dome at Chrysler's
headquarters here. Its circular floor, covered in dark gray
carpeting, is wide enough to hold a dozen automobiles for
executives' review. Its white, hemispherical ceiling has soft,
diffuse lighting that minimizes glare.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, a new, white, long-wheelbase Town &AMP;
Country was the only vehicle in the room. McKinnon walked around
it, pointing out subtle changes from the previous model. He
occasionally crouched, holding out his hands to triangulate, like
an artist before a large painting.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at the front of the vehicle, he gestured toward the
hood, an inch higher than on previous models, and the headlights,
twice as big and 80 percent brighter. ``It gives it a flush,
aggressive look,'' he said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to the driver's side, he pointed to the lower edge of the
rear side windows, which now tilt upward at a slight angle, instead
of being nearly flat. ``It gives it a little more aggressive
tilt,'' he said. The wheel wells are also flared out slightly, as
on many sport utilities. And the engines on the new minivans have
180 to 230 horsepower, up from 140 to 180.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked whether Chrysler was trying to imitate the
aggressive appearance of sport utilities, McKinnon grew defensive.
``It was nothing intentional,'' he said, quickly deciding that
``dynamic'' might be a better word than ``aggressive'' to describe
the new features.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors is trying to make some of its minivans,
particularly the Pontiac Montana, look more like sport utilities,
and the reasons are clear. Minivan sales have doubled since 1990,
but sport utility vehicle sales have nearly quadrupled. Pontiac
enjoyed immediate success in 1997 by marketing a Montana version of
its Trans Sport minivan with television ads showing cowboys riding
alongside in scenes similar to those in sport utility ads. Soon,
Pontiac eliminated the Trans Sport name and now sells all its
minivans as Montanas, trying to elude the ``soccer mom'' image of
minivans.
</P>
<P>
   On the bottom foot or so of the sides of the Montana, Pontiac
offers taupe- or charcoal-colored plastic cladding _ a feature
commonly used on $40,000 sport utilities to make them seem
utilitarian, even if they are seldom driven off-road. But while
Chrysler minivans have long had scuff-resistant plastic cladding,
too, it will stay the same color as the rest of the vehicle, making
it virtually invisible to anyone not looking for it.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Chrysler's market researchers concluded that
minivans and sport utilities were really two separate markets.
Holden said the soccer-mom image had been inescapably associated
with the minivan ever since the first advertising campaign in 1983,
which presented the vehicle as an alternative to the station wagon
for families with children. ``We pitched it like that, fairy dust
and kids, in the first ads touting it as a `magic wagon,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While buyers of sport utility vehicles are mainly concerned with
a vehicle's image, minivan buyers do not even put the exterior
styling in the top 10 reasons for their purchase, said David
Bostwick, Chrysler's director of market research. By an
overwhelming margin, he said, minivan buyers focus instead on how
functional and flexible the vehicle's interior will be for hauling
people and their belongings.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon, circling the Town &AMP; Country in the design dome,
bridled when told of Bostwick's comment. The market researchers do
not ask the right questions to determine the importance of exterior
styling, he said, contending that minivan buyers' overall image of
their vehicles is shaped by first impressions _ formed before they
ever step inside.
</P>
<P>
   Walking around the back of the Town &AMP; Country, he cheerfully
demonstrated the vehicle's most distinctive new feature: a powered
rear liftgate. It opens when he pushes the button on a remote
control key fob, beeping as it rises to warn anyone nearby. Then
McKinnon stands warily below the liftgate and pushes the button
again; the liftgate begins to close automatically but stops
instantly when it touches the top of his head and rises again. ``It
worked,'' he says, jokingly pretending to be relieved.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But inside the rear liftgate is one of the most important
features that Chrysler left little changed: the third row of seats.
The 110-pound row is still designed to be rolled out the back of
the vehicle when not needed and stored in the owner's garage. An
option this year is for the seat to come in two rollable 55-pound
pieces. But it does not fold down flat into a compartment in the
vehicle, like the fold-away third row in the Honda Odyssey, which
ranks a distant third in sales but is gaining on Chrysler faster
than any other brand.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon wrestles with the Town &AMP; Country's third row in an
unsuccessful effort to remove it; such features commonly do not
work in early prototypes. (The seats are designed to roll out,
although the task usually requires two people, as in Chrysler's
current minivans.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the prototype's difficulty, Chrysler's minivans are the
only such vehicles produced by Detroit automakers to be recommended
by Consumer Reports magazine, which harshly judges the reliability
of most American-made vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas G. Elliott, the executive vice president for auto
operations in Honda's North American unit, said Odyssey buyers gave
higher marks to the fold-away seat than any other feature. GM's
Chevrolet Venture, Oldsmobile Silhouette and Pontiac Montana will
offer fold-away seats beginning this fall. And Townsend said Ford
was working to develop a fold-away seat for the Windstar as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph A. Sarotte, the general manager of Chrysler's minivan
operations, said the company had rejected fold-away seats after
finding that the space for folding them down could function as a
hollow drum, amplifying road noise and making it difficult for
passengers to hear one another. The new Chrysler minivans are much
quieter inside than competitors' models because they have
traditional rear seats, Sarotte said.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors question this compromise between noise and
convenience. ``I was floored with the '01 Chrysler, that they
didn't touch those seats,'' said Fred J. Schaafsma, a top GM
vehicle development executive who oversaw minivans until early this
summer. ``That was a horrible trade-off.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the design dome, McKinnon moved to the passenger side of
the Town &AMP; Country and pointed to the front overhang, the distance
from the wheels to the front of the bumper. The larger headlights
make this overhang look short, he said, but it is actually an inch
longer now.
</P>
<P>
   The ratio of a vehicle's front overhang length to its weight is
the main consideration in determining a vehicle's performance in
the federal government's crash tests, which involve hurling a
vehicle at 35 mph into a concrete wall. Lightweight vehicles with
very long hoods tend to do best in the tests, while heavy vehicles
with short hoods often allow severe damage to the dummies inside.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler officials concede that even with the extra inch, the
fairly short overhang on their minivans will likely mean that they
receive four stars for frontal crash safety in the government
tests, compared with the top rating of five earned by the Windstar,
Sienna and Odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   But Chrysler could not increase the front overhang without
lengthening the vehicle, which would have made it harder to park,
or moving the front tires back in the vehicle, which likely would
have reduced the interior room. Either step would have involved an
expensive redesign of the vehicle's underbody, which remains little
changed from the previous generation. Either would also have
required the replacement of considerable factory equipment, which
would have caused a costly delay before the first production of the
new models.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler chose a modest increase in the front overhang. ``To
improve that rating, you have to put more body in front of the
wheels,'' Rinschler said. ``You make the vehicle longer, heavier
and, to my eyes, less attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Rinschler and other executives contend that government crash
tests are an imperfect measure of how vehicles actually perform in
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Chrysler's current minivans, which also have four-star
ratings, have slightly below-average death rates for their drivers
compared with other minivans, and minivans as a group have a lower
death rate for their drivers than any other type of vehicle,
according to insurance industry data. But when the Insurance
Institute for Highway Safety, an insurance industry trade group,
did its own crash test of the current minivans, it gave them an
overall rating of ``marginal'' and found that they permitted ``the
likelihood of significant injury to both legs,'' a problem for
vehicles with short front overhangs.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has heavily advertised the Windstar's five-star rating.
Bostwick questioned whether the difference between four and five
stars would influence customers; regulators acknowledge that the
difference is sometimes small. A four-star rating indicates an 11
percent to 20 percent chance of a life-threatening injury in a
crash at 35 mph with a similar vehicle or a fixed object, while a
five-star rating means a chance of 10 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an overwhelming issue _ they're all safe vehicles,''
Bostwick said. ``Between the four and the five, it's something to
talk about, but it's not going to change someone's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   At the design dome, McKinnon added up the changes and declared
that Chrysler had done what it set out to do: to freshen but not
overhaul a vehicle that continues to sell very well. But throughout
the process, he said, the company's designers remembered one lesson
learned over the years from rivals: ``Competitors would try
something to be different, and when they went too far, the
customers would walk on them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
