<P>
   BABYMOSES _ Since state lawmakers created safe havens such as
hospitals for mothers to abandon their babies without fear of
prosecution, seven states have followed in Texas' footsteps. More
than 18 others are considering laws modelled after ours. Even
Germany has come calling. The only trouble is, since it was enacted
last September, no babies have been left at safe havens. Part of
the problem might be that there was no money appropriated for a
public awareness campaign. A nonprofit called the Baby Moses
Project seeks to promote the law. Today it unveils a PSA to a
select few, including the Fort Worth doctor who proposed the law,
its sponsor Rep. Geanie Morrison and the ubiquitous David Dewhurst.
(Bahadur, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   KITTINGER _ WRIGHT-PATTERSON AIR FORCE BASE _ Neil Armstrong
stepped onto the moon in 1969 and called it ``one small step for a
man.'' Joe Kittinger stepped into thin air on Aug. 16, 1960, and
nobody could call it small. Kittinger's step set a world record
that still stands for the world's highest parachute jump _102,800
feet. He had floated to the edge of space in a helium-filled
balloon as part of the Air Force's early high-altitude flight
experiments, before America sent its first astronauts into space.
(Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate is expected to vote Friday
to phase out the Federal estate tax. President Clinton has pledged
a veto. (Lipman, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   FREE- LEXUS _ Five people will receive free three-year leases on
luxury cars, the result of the Florida Attorney General's suit
prompted by a West Palm Beach Lexus dealer's questionable ads. The
Florida Attorney General in February sued Lexus of Palm Beach,
which is owned by Bob Cuillo. The state said the Okeechobee
Boulevard dealership lured custohools were only $700 below the
national average during the 1998-99 school year, thanks to a
four-year run of 6 percent pay hikes during Gov. Zell Miller's
final term. The SREB study says faculty salaries have not grown as
rapidly as those of other workers with advanced degrees in the past
10 years. (Salzer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MILLION-MARCH _ WASHINGTON _ Louis Farrakhan, leader of the
Nation of Islam, holds a news conference to discuss his call for
one million families to assemble on Oct. 16 on the National Mall to
observe the fifth anniversary of the Million Man march. (Dart, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS _ WASHINGTON Voters are more disengaged in the
presidential race this year than at any time in recent history,
according to a poll released Friday by the non-partisan Pew
Research Center. It could be an indication that turnout may be
lower than it was in 1996, when only 49 percent of eligible
citizens cast ballots, the first time in more than 70 years that
less than half of voters went to the polls. Yet despite voter
apathy, Americans say they are more satisfied with their choice of
presidential candidates this year and they are less critical of the
way the campaigns are being conducted, the survey found. The poll
concluded that the race between Democrat Al Gore and Republican
George W. Bush remains wide open as each candidate heads to his
party's nominating conventions next month. (Holmes, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIANS _ A jury decided Friday that the government does not
bear responsibility for the deaths of 80 Branch Davidians during
the cult's 1993 standoff with federal agents. A federal judge will
take the ruling into account before delivering the verdict himself
sometime later. (Witherspoon, Waco Tribune-Herald) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
