   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ WACO, Texas _ During the 71st
All-Star Game in Atlanta I caught myself paying more attention to
the left-handed players. Earlier that day, I read a news story in
The Times of London that said homosexuals are more likely to be
left-handed. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ ATLANTA _ I have been
pleased to discover, in Jonesville, La., someone who shares my
concern about e-mail, which has become all too popular and a
serious threat to intimate personal communication, and to a unique
way of recording history. Alma Womack writes a column for her
Jonesville parish newspaper. She sent a copy of one lamenting the
decline of old-fashioned letter-writing. (Jim Minter is a former
editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ This is not a time for
pettiness, but I can't help feeling peeved that, until last fall, I
appear to have been the only person in town who didn't know Joe
Belle. If he was Mr. UD (University of Dayton), Mr. Personality and
all that, don't you think he could have taken the trouble to call
me up? (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I was standing in front of
the tire store where my Cousin Bubba works, waiting on him to get
off for lunch and listening to a couple of fellows talking about
haying. You might not think that hay means much to you, personally,
and maybe it doesn't. Maybe you're somebody who doesn't care much,
personally, about a good hamburger. Hay just happens to be the main
ingredient, lower down the food chain, for hamburgers, not to
mention thick, juicy steaks. So, if you're going to have meat on
the table, somewhere you have to have beef on the hoof and hay on
the ground. (Joe Murray, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-NET _ Microsoft's new vision of technology - whether
or not the antitrust ruling is overturned - is that computing is
moving to the Net. In fact, it's Microsoft.Net will allow users to
use applications such as word processors and spreadsheets directly
from the Internet. Steve Ballmer, Microsoft president, is in town
Friday to explain and push for Microsoft's new vision for the the
future. We'll also ask about the antitrust ruling, of course.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   JARGON _ The Atlantic Steel bridge made it into the RTP and TIP
because it's a CMAQ, part of Project XL and favored by the EPD,
EPA, GRTA AND ARC. With all that alphabetical firepower behind it,
the bridge will get built PDQ. A generation ago his country used to
turn out solid acronyms, like radar and scuba. (McCosh, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ SBC Communications Inc. and BellSouth Corporation
today announced that Stephen Carter has been named president and
chief executive officer of the joint-venture company that will be
created with the merger of the two companies' U.S. wireless
operations. The HQ will be in Atlanta. In April, BellSouth and SBC
announced plans to merge their domestic wireless operations to
create the nation's second-largest wireless company, a powerful
single entity jointly controlled by both companies, poised to
compete nationwide in the exploding wireless voice and data
businesses. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: NORTH CAROLINA PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   BBT _ BB&AMP;T, a North Carolina-based regional bank, is taking over
45 Premier Bancshares branches in north metro Atlanta on July 17.
This is pursuant to a buyout announced last year. Talking to CEO
John Addison about the takeover and BB&AMP;T's larger strategy in the
metro Atlanta market. Will try to work it into an overview on the
second-tier bank competition in metro Atlanta. (Grantham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
