<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Two handsome paper-bound books,
originally published in England and offered here by Sterling,
should be of considerable interest to the novice woodturner looking
for direction. They are ``Woodturning: a Fresh Approach'' by Robert
Chapman and ``Bowl Turning Techniques Master C lass'' by Tony
Boase. Both list for $17.95. Between them, these two books outline
the basic techniques used in just about every avenue of turning,
from the most basic bowl to stack-laminated work, reformed and
painted pieces and surface decoration. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EPISCOPARY-WOMAN _ In November 1787, when Richard Allen stormed
out of the predominantly white St. George's Church in Philadelphia
and formed the African Free Society (later renamed the African
Methodist Episcopal Church), the thought of bringing a woman into
the hierarchy of his clan never entered his mind. But the prospect
of selecting a female to the lofty position of AME bishop could not
escape the minds of the 1,800 delegates who attended the order's
closely scrutinized General Conference at the Cincinnati Convention
Center this week. In a landmark, second-ballot vote, the Rev.
Vashti Murphy McKenzie, 53, of Baltimore, Md., was elected to the
Episcopary, becoming the first female in the 213-year history of
the church to assume that seat. (Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER _ Hot. That's what parents and youngsters have to say
about the summer, now that the first weeks of the season are a
memory. With still six weeks or so remaining before kids return to
school, we offer some thoughts on things to do for the rest of
summer, including volunteer opportunities, retreat centers, movies,
music and books. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
