<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BABY-MOSES0715-COX     07-14 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-MOSES0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finding a safe place for babies
 &HT;    By Gaiutra Bahadur
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With a little-known law passed last year,
lawmakers placed Texas at the forefront of a national movement to
allow mothers to abandon their babies in ``safe havens'' such as
hospitals and fire stations without fear of prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Now state officials want to step up the public's knowledge of
the law and let desperate mothers know they have alternatives to
leaving their children in Dumpsters or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Since Texas passed the so-called Baby Moses law, 11 states have
followed in its footsteps. Another 24 are interested. And
television crews from as far away as Germany and Australia have
come calling.
</P>
<P>
   The only trouble is, since the law took effect last September,
no babies have been left with emergency medical personnel at
hospitals or fire departments, the protected spheres created by the
law.
</P>
<P>
   The problem _ says Rep. Geanie Morrison, R-Victoria, sponsor of
the legislation _ is that no money was appropriated in the budget
for a media campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Land Commissioner David Dewhurst, who has provided
hundreds of thousands of dollars from his own pocket to create and
air a public service announcement to spread the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all believe the best place for a baby is with the mother,''
Dewhurst said at the unveiling of the TV spot Thursday at Austin
Fire Department Headquarters. ``But if a young, scared mother can't
do the best thing for a baby, for heaven's sake, do the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second ad opens with a shot of a trash bin, the vista for
a teen-age girl who says in a quivering voice: ``I was desperate. I
mean, I knew I couldn't keep it. I didn't have anywhere to go. . .
. I didn't want to do it. It was all I could think of.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, a female narrator offers the grim statistics: 800 babies
are abandoned every year in Texas, 50 are left to die in Dumpsters.
She explains the safe haven law. one life is saved, it would be an
investment in which we can all take pride,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, Dewhurst has also provided some of the
greenbacks to elevate the Baby Moses Project, an informal crusader
for the law outside Texas run by a Morrison aide, into a nonprofit
foundation to educate pregnant women about the alternatives to
infant abandonment. He is the honorary chairman. Morrison is
president.
</P>
<P>
   But one critic of the law adopted in Texas, a California-based
nonprofit called Project Cuddle whose members have tread the same
talk-show circuit as supporters of the Baby Moses Project, said
that publicity is not the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's government,'' said Debbe Magnusen, the founder and
director of Project Cuddle. ``The girls we work with are scared of
government. They're afraid of officials. . . . They deny a lot of
stuff. They haven't told their families. They haven't told their
best friends. Why would they go to a facility with a camera?''
</P>
<P>
   Promotions of the Texas law have included billboards in Houston
and appearances by the law's supporters on ``The Montel Williams
Show,'' ``The Oprah Winfrey Show,'' CNN's ``Crossfire'' and NBC's
``Dateline'' over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Magnusen said that the defensive mindset of pregnant teen-agers,
rather than their ignorance of the law, explains why no one has
taken advantage of the Baby Moses protections.
</P>
<P>
   There are two known cases of mothers who almost did.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a baby girl was left swaddled in a pink towel on
the floor next to a toilet at a Houston hospital. And in May, a
baby boy was abandoned at a covered bus stop on the edge of a Plano
hospital's parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as close as she felt she could go,'' Magnusen said.
</P>
<P>
   She also pointed to a loophole in the law.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Texas County and District Attorneys
Association, the law doesn't prevent district attorneys from
pursuing abandonment cases. It gives a mother ``an affirmative
defense'' _ which means that if she can prove she gave her baby to
an emergency services provider, she will not be found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every case turns on its own facts,'' said the association's
general counsel, Rob Kepple. ``You don't have prosecutors running
around and promising they won't prosecute. (But) the very terms of
the law make it unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the other states that have passed laws, most have gone a
little further than Texas, according to the National Conference of
State Legislators.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey appropriated $500,000 to promote its law.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana's law broaches the issue of mothers who change their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's and South Carolina's versions address fathers'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   And Florida goes as far as discussing genetic testing to
establish paternity.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said that, by helping other states craft their laws,
the Baby Moses Project has become aware of ways to refine and
improve the Texas law and that all of them are under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
