<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-1035     07-14 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-1035(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN PARLIAMENT APPROVES TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Bowing to the competitive pressures
sweeping across Europe, Germany's left-of-center parliament passed
a radical tax program Friday that will slash rates and should also
unleash a wave of restructuring in ``Germany Inc.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was a remarkable and unexpected victory for Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder, the Social Democratic leader who began his
career as a long-haired student protester but whose tax plan made
him a hero of the corporate elite.
</P>
<P>
   In a role-reversal worthy of Lewis Carroll, Schroeder received
extensive lobbying support from German corporations, as well as
from U.S. businesses here, and overwhelmed the usually pro-business
party, the Christian Democratic Union. It fought the bill for
political reasons, and criticized it as too limited.
</P>
<P>
   By 2005, the law will reduce crushing tax rates for individuals
and corporations by a total of 50 billion marks, or $24 billion a
year. The top tax rates for individuals will drop, to 42 percent,
from 51 percent, and the overall corporate burden is expected to
decline to 40 percent, from 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking change, however, is a provision that will let
corporations sell subsidiaries or shares in other companies without
paying any tax on their profits. That change is expected to
revolutionize the structure of German business, because it clears
the way for the big banks and insurance companies to sell over $100
billion in shares of industrial companies like DaimlerChrysler and
Siemens.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old structure of ``Germany Inc.,'' those crossholdings
created a web of mutual support that helped finance Germany's
spectacular economic recovery after World War II. But now, with
companies dependent on satisfying the performance demands set by
investors on Wall Street or in London, banks and manufacturers
argue that the tangled ownership has become an obstacle to
restructuring and a drag on profits.
</P>
<P>
   Yet selling the stakes was almost impossible under current law,
because selling companies would be charged a 50 percent tax on tens
of billions of dollars of profit from shares that they might have
held for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and corporate executives say the combined effect of
the changes will be to transform Germany, which is Europe's biggest
economy but one that has been growing slowly. Some of the changes
will take effect next year, and Elga Bartsch, economist at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, estimated that the law would increase German
growth then to 3.1 percent, from 2.6 percent. Norbert Walter, chief
economist for Deutsche Bank, predicts that growth will exceed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very important signal to investors, because here you
have a government of Social Democrats and Greens that has passed a
very business-oriented tax reform,'' Walter said Friday. The
pro-business political trend is apparent across Europe, he added,
even where left-of-center parties control the biggest countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The euro is the catalyst,'' Walter said, referring to the
single currency that has now been adopted by 12 countries. ``It is
the catalytic effect of a truly internal market that has now pushed
the laggards toward the more advanced countries in terms of
modernization.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder came into office two years ago dependent politically
on the left-wing leader of his party, Oskar Lafontaine. But since
the two men had a falling out a year ago, Schroeder has steered his
party in a more pro-business direction. As recently as Wednesday,
most experts were convinced that Schroeder would be blocked in the
upper house of parliament, the Bundesrat, by the Christian
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder steamrolled over Christian Democrats on the right
and disgruntled left-wing traditionalists in his own party, showing
a self-assurance and readiness for conflict that were missing when
he first came to power in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats argued that the tax plan failed to
provide enough relief to small and medium-sized companies, but
their primary goal seemed to be to stymie Schroeder, whose Social
Democrats blocked a Christian Democrat tax plan three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder lashed back by promising over $1 billion in sweeteners
to small companies as well as to states where political leaders
were wavering.
</P>
<P>
   He persuaded the Christian Democratic leader of Berlin to defect
to his side, by promising 75 million marks for more police officers
and 25 million marks to renovate the city's Museum Island. And he
got leaders from the impoverished eastern state Mecklenburg-West
Pomerania to go along, by cutting a deal with state's neocommunist
Party of Democratic Socialism.
</P>
<P>
   That party, successor to the old East German Communist Party, is
a minority partner of the state's governing coalition and normally
no friend of corporate Germany. But Schroeder received its support
after he promised to support construction of a highly subsidized
power plant in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents protested fruitlessly that Schroeder was using
government money to buy votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not experienced this sort of abuse of a constitutional
branch of government in 30 years,'' thundered Hans Jochen Vogel,
the Christian Democratic governor of Thuringia. But Angela Merkel,
chairman of the Christian Democratic Union, seemed cowed by the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came to the process, Schroeder was clearly the
winner,'' she said glumly at a news conference Friday.
``Maintaining unity proved to be much thornier and more difficult
than many people had thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, grinning broadly after the vote, brushed aside the
criticism as ``hypocrisy'' and said the plan would be good for
business as well as for individuals by leaving them more money in
their pockets. ``This is truly a good day for Germany,'' Schroeder
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors generally agreed. The DAX index of blue-chip German
stocks jumped 2 percent after the vote and financial institutions
ended considerably higher. Shares of Allianz AG, the insurance
conglomerate that is perhaps at the center of German
cross-holdings, jumped 7 percent to 395.65 euros. Shares of
Dresdner Bank jumped 5.6 percent and Deutsche Bank rose 3.36
percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But economists also said that the law's effects could reach well
beyond Germany. Foreign investors, including many corporate buyout
funds from the United States, are scouring Germany for companies to
buy, spruce up and sell for a profit years later.
</P>
<P>
   Merger-and-acquisition activity, already torrid, is expected to
soar as the tax provision on selling corporate holdings takes
effect in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group, which has been an adviser in many of
Germany's biggest mergers, is hiring hundreds of new executives and
leasing eleven new floors in one of Frankfurt's biggest
skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies were unusually active in lobbying for passage of
the bill. Representatives of the American Chamber of Commerce in
Germany, based in Frankfurt, visited officials from several German
states that were wavering in their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is the signal we get from Germany,''
said Norbert Quinkert, executive vice president of the Chamber and
chairman of Motorola Deutschland. ``It wasn't important whether the
top tax rate was 42 percent or 43 percent. The issue was whether a
tax reform could be passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartsch, of Morgan Stanley, argued that the German tax package
would put pressure on countries like France and Italy to cut their
taxes. ``This is a very big country with very high corporate tax
rates, which has allowed neighboring countries to hide behind a
shield,'' said Bartsch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
