<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2339 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-BUSH-SHANTYTOWNS-$ADV     07-14 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SHANTYTOWNS-$ADV16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEMOCRATS MAKE ISSUE OF SQUALID VILLAGES IN BUSH'S BACK YARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 16)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY MARTIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats are making impoverished shantytowns in
South Texas an issue in the presidential race, challenging Gov.
George W. Bush's ``compassionate conservative'' mantle and accusing
him of neglecting issues that affect Hispanics and the poor in his
own state.
</P>
<P>
   The squalor of the border shantytowns that dot the U.S. side of
the Rio Grande is vividly shown in a videotape produced by
Democrats to underscore their criticisms of Bush's record on
education, health care and minority issues in Texas. These
``colonias,'' the Spanish name for villages, are illegal
subdivisions that often lack running water, sewage systems and
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Bush's negligence and inaction, schoolchildren in
the colonias live in perpetual poverty,'' said Rep. Loretta Sanchez
of California, a co-chair of the Democratic National Committee
(DNC).
</P>
<P>
   Republicans counter that the DNC is serving as a surrogate on
the issue for Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential
hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore and the national Democrats have an active campaign to
trash the state of Texas,'' said Ray Sullivan, a Bush campaign
spokesman in Austin. ``In doing so, they not only insult Democratic
and Republican leaders in our state, but also the citizens of our
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say the criticism is related to Democratic
efforts to protect their base and blunt Bush's push for votes among
Hispanics and minorities, who do not traditionally support
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush is ``attempting to spin out a record'' of helping the
poor, the Gore campaign and the Democrats are trying to saddle the
Texas governor with all the blame for the conditions in the
colonias, said Garth Jowett, University of Houston Communications
Department director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perception is better than reality,'' Jowett said of the
tactics being used by both parties.
</P>
<P>
   It's a timeworn practice in presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Vice President George Bush _ the Texas governor's
father _ used Boston Harbor pollution and the prison furlough of
convicted killer Willie Horton to paint Michael Dukakis, the
Massachusetts governor and Democratic presidential hopeful, as an
ineffective leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly tarnished his image as governor,'' said William
G. Mayer, a political scientist at Northeastern University in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer said the campaign strategy was to raise questions about
Dukakis' effectiveness ``and blunt any challenges he might raise
about the environmental record of the Reagan-Bush administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The Horton issue and others were raised, Mayer said, ``to very
specifically focus on Dukakis' attempt to portray himself as a
moderate and to suggest that he was a liberal who had adopted these
traditional liberal policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has launched an aggressive effort to portray himself as a
moderate and to reach out to minorities. He has delivered speeches
to the NAACP, the National Council of La Raza and the League of
United Latin American Citizens (LULAC).
</P>
<P>
   The governor's message has been to welcome blacks and Hispanics
into a ``big-tent'' Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's venture into Hispanic territory has received a warm
reception.
</P>
<P>
   He received applause last month when he told the LULAC national
convention that education initiatives in Texas were breaking down
the racial bigotry of low expectations and helping minority
students receive a better public school education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The analysis says we are making great progress. Our state has
set high standards,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   His critics assert that his message is poll-driven.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan Battleground 2000 poll conducted for Voter.com
found that while Bush had the support of a majority of whites,
blacks overwhelmingly support Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also held a double-digit lead over Bush among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Celinda Lake, a Democrat, predicted Gore would
``steadily gain'' support from Hispanics as the election nears. But
even Democrats concede Bush has made surprising inroads in that
demographic group.
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Ed Goeas said Bush's support from Hispanics
is the highest a GOP presidential candidate has polled since Ronald
Reagan in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing Bush solidifying his base on the right, the
governor is using the weeks before the Republican National
Convention to target new voters who have traditionally remained in
the Democratic column. His message of compassionate conservatism
speaks of improving education, health care and economic
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say the colonias show that reality doesn't match the
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charge that during his six years in the Governor's
Mansion, Bush has never visited a colonia.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan did not deny the claim, but said the governor has
visited ``barrios'' and poor communities in the state, unlike some
of his predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has spent a great deal of time in the border
region, effectively addressing border-related issues,'' Sullivan
said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Washington last month, state Sen. Mario
Gallegos of Houston blasted Bush for vetoing a bill to streamline
procedures for state agencies and help improve conditions in the
colonias, which house roughly 400,000 Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush responded that he signed a measure designed to remove
barriers that impeded state and local efforts to improve conditions
in the colonias, including a lifting of regulatory language to
expedite individual water and sewer connections.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bush signed a bill to provide $5.6 million in
low-interest loans to help colonia residents improve their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot speak out of both ends of your mouth,'' Gallegos
said. ``The truth needs to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   The DNC videotape shows residents living in Third World
conditions, dilapidated shacks and unpaved streets. The five-minute
tape shows ramshackle homes made of plywood and tin, an outhouse
and refuse strewn about unpaved roads.
</P>
<P>
   It details the lack of electricity, running water and sewage
systems in a colonia outside the city of San Juan in the lower Rio
Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of the tape have been made available to public
television. It was broadcast nationally on CNN's ``Inside
Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A DNC news release quotes a 1998 study by former Texas
Comptroller John Sharp that shows the 43-county Texas border area
as the poorest region in the country, and another report that ranks
Texas 49th among states for children without health insurance, 1.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Texas also ranked 49th for children living in poverty, the news
release said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't talk about compassion and turn your back on the
colonias,'' said Jenny Backus, a DNC spokeswoman. ``He's saying
he's a different kind of Republican who will work to reduce
poverty. His record doesn't add up.''
</P>
<P>
   Responded Sullivan: ``This attack is another symptom of what's
wrong with Washington and Al Gore's Washington-style politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles A. Gonzalez, D-Texas, said the Bush campaign is
trying to sidestep a legitimate debate that affects the rural
reaches of South Texas, as well as its urban centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush labels everything as negative campaigning if someone has
a different opinion,'' Gonzalez said. ``Once we get past that
smokescreen, then we have the right to question whether the emperor
has no clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all Texans and we are proud of our state. But we are
realists, and we realize we fall short for the poorest people of
our state.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gary Martin can be reached by e-mail at
gmartin(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
