<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ABORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID INTIMIDATION, ABORTIONS DWINDLE IN CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ A campaign of violence and intimidation
against doctors who perform abortions has succeeded in shutting
down Canadian abortion clinics and frightening physicians so
effectively that the procedure is becoming extremely difficult to
obtain in many parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Police in British Columbia this week warned doctors providing
abortions to go on ``high alert'' after Dr. Garson Romalis, a
63-year-old gynecologist, was stabbed outside his Vancouver clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, which police say was almost certainly the act of an
antiabortion extremist, marked the second attempt on Romalis's life
_ in 1994, he was ambushed and seriously wounded by the notorious
``abortion sniper,'' a rifleman from Vermont whom the FBI and Royal
Canadian Mounted Police are seeking in connection with five
shootings on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Also this week, threats were made against the life of Dr. Ellen
Wiebe, the physician leading Canadian tests of the French abortion
pill RU-486. ``All of us abortion providers in North America must
live with fear,'' Wiebe said.
</P>
<P>
   Even high-profile abortion advocates concede that fear among
doctors has become so pervasive that the procedure is becoming
almost unobtainable in Canada outside major urban centers in
Ontario, Quebec, British Columbia, and Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors in smaller places have succumbed to the pressure,''
said Dr. Henry Morgantaler, a Toronto gynecologist who is Canada's
best-known abortion rights activist. ``They don't want to become
the target of some crazy person.''
</P>
<P>
   Laws restricting abortion were overthrown by the Canadian
Supreme Court in 1988, mainly as the result of challenges brought
by Morgantaler.
</P>
<P>
   Although the issue rarely triggers the sort of raw public
emotion in Canada that it does in the United States, this country
is loathed by abortion foes because it places no legal constraints
on when a pregnancy may be terminated _ in theory, a woman can get
an abortion up to the moment of birth. Canadian courts have ruled
that a fetus at any stage of development has no rights.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, US antiabortion groups are increasingly
engaging in direct antiabortion crusades north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   The protests and threats have been aimed largely at Canadian
physicians and medical students. As one result, abortion advocates
say, the numbers of doctors willing to terminate preganancies has
declined dramatically in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number is going down, fewer and fewer young doctors are
willing to provide abortion services, and fear is a big part of the
reason,'' said Cyndy Recker, spokeswoman for the Ottawa-based
Canadian Abortion Rights Action League. ``Antiabortion groups,
including very extremist elements from the US, are contacting
students in Canadian medical schools, saying, `If you do abortions,
you are going to be in danger.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the most withering effect on Canadian physicians has been
the series of highly-publicized sniper attacks on abortion doctors
_ beginning with the shooting of Romalis six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Romalis, then 57, was waiting for bread to pop from the toaster
in the kitchen of his suburban Vancouver home when two high-powered
7.62mm rifle slugs smashed through the window. One tore into his
thigh, shattering the bone and severing an artery. Even with a
makeshift tourniquet fashioned from his bathrobe belt, he nearly
bled to death on the linoleum floor.
</P>
<P>
   Four more rifle attacks in Canada and the United States,
including the 1998 assassination of an upstate New York doctor who
performed abortions, Barnett Slepian, are believed by the FBI and
Canadian police to be the work of James Charles Kopp, a 45-year-old
abortion foe whose last known address was in northern Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   The stabbing of Romalis on Tuesday is thought to be directly
linked to his abortion practice but not to the earlier shooting.
The physician remained listed in good condition Friday in a
Vancouver hospital under heavy police guard. His attacker,
described as a white man in his 20s, remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion specialists say that most doctors still providing
abortion in Canada are older practitioners, like Romalis, nearing
retirement age _ and only a handful of younger doctors are taking
their place.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in some parts of Canada have become so reluctant to
provide the procedure _ or even make referrals _ that abortion is
becoming almost unobtainable except to women willing to travel
hundreds of miles to big cities or the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Edward Island forbids provincial hospitals from providing
abortion, and access to the procedure is extremely limited in Nova
Scotia, New Brunswick, Manitoba, and Saskatchewan. The number of
private clinics specializing in abortions has fallen to 30 across
Canada, almost all concentrated in Toronto, Montreal, Vancouver,
and two or three other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, fear among gynecologists is so high that many ask
colleagues and professional associations not to give out their
names even as professional referrals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a strange way, it's come back to the days when abortion was
a black market job, done in back rooms on the hush-hush'' said a
Quebec doctor, asking that her name not be used. ``If you have a
pregnant teenager or some other woman who feels she needs an
abortion, you kind of call around, saying, `Pssst, do you know
anyone?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
