<HEADLINE>
BURNS' 10-PART `JAZZ' GOES WELL BEYOND THE MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Ken Burns is back.
</P>
<P>
   The one-man history channel brings his 10-part,
18-and-a-half-hour film ``Jazz'' to PBS in January, completing a
trilogy of American life that started with ``The Civil War'' and
continued with ``Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   As only Burns can do in his erudite populist style that defies
contradiction, he declared: ``Jazz is ... a glimpse into the inner
workings of the democratic ideal and the redemptive future
possibilities of this extraordinary but by no means perfect
republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, it's also toe-tappingly enjoyable music. But will
America sit still for 18-plus hours of ``Jazz?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are enough people out there that will be moved
and, I think, quite satisfied by what we've done and probably be
hungry for a lot more,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   Because jazz was invented by African Americans, the documentary
holds a mirror to America's race relations throughout the 20th
century. So Burns hopes that, while the series encourages Americans
to discover or rediscover an art form, it also encourages some
serious reflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complicated dynamic,'' he said, ``and one of the
things we are most proud of in this series is that it has not
chosen to accept the simplest, most superficial aspects of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Novick, Burns' co-producer, added: ``I think there will be,
in a way, a kind of redemption in allowing Americans to have a
dialogue about such an important subject that we so often don't
want to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the power of music.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were none.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Wiest will join the 11th season of ``Law &AMP; Order'' this
fall as the new district attorney, replacing Steven Hill, the last
remaining member of the show's original cast.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, producer Dick Wolf said: ``Having a female
actor of this caliber is unprecedented on series television. Dianne
has ... established herself as one of the finest actors of her
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiest, 52, has received two best supporting actress Oscars, for
``Bullets Over Broadway'' and ``Hannah and Her Sisters,'' an Emmy
as guest actress in ``Road to Avonlea'' and numerous other awards.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, 78, has played the crusty Adam Schiff since the first
season of ``Law &AMP; Order'' in 1990. His character reportedly will
depart after losing a bid for re-election as district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said Hill's gemlike performances ``will be forever etched
in the minds of television viewers.'' A Seattle native, Hill was
the original Mr. Briggs on the first season of ``Mission:
Impossible'' in 1966.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
