<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-NET _ Microsoft's new vision of technology - whether
or not the antitrust ruling is overturned - is that computing is
moving to the Net. In fact, it's Microsoft.Net will allow users to
use applications such as word processors and spreadsheets directly
from the Internet. Steve Ballmer, Microsoft president, is in town
Friday to explain and push for Microsoft's new vision for the the
future. We'll also ask about the antitrust ruling, of course.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   JARGON _ The Atlantic Steel bridge made it into the RTP and TIP
because it's a CMAQ, part of Project XL and favored by the EPD,
EPA, GRTA AND ARC. With all that alphabetical firepower behind it,
the bridge will get built PDQ. A generation ago his country used to
turn out solid acronyms, like radar and scuba. (McCosh, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ SBC Communications Inc. and BellSouth Corporation
today announced that Stephen Carter has been named president and
chief executive officer of the joint-venture company that will be
created with the merger of the two companies' U.S. wireless
operations. The HQ will be in Atlanta. In April, BellSouth and SBC
announced plans to merge their domestic wireless operations to
create the nation's second-largest wireless company, a powerful
single entity jointly controlled by both companies, poised to
compete nationwide in the exploding wireless voice and data
businesses. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: NORTH CAROLINA PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   BBT _ BB&AMP;T, a North Carolina-based regional bank, is taking over
45 Premier Bancshares branches in north metro Atlanta on July 17.
This is pursuant to a buyout announced last year. Talking to CEO
John Addison about the takeover and BB&AMP;T's larger strategy in the
metro Atlanta market. Will try to work it into an overview on the
second-tier bank competition in metro Atlanta. (Grantham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: NORTH CAROLINA PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   COKE-SUIT _ Coca-Cola is seeking to move a $1.5 billion
discrimination lawsuit prepared by attorneys Willie Gary and
Johnnie Cochran from state court to federal court, where a
class-action bias suit has been playing out. The move could put the
case before U.S. District Judge Richard Story, who has been
presiding over the class-action case. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COX-NEWSPAPERS _ Cox Newspapers will buy two dailies in Ohio and
10 specialty publications. Gannett had planned to buy the papers as
part of a larger deal with Thomson but Cox had a right of first
refusal, and exercised it, for the papers its buying. (Bowman,
Dayton Daily News). 12.
</P>
<P>
   DEPOT-SCHOOLCOLORS _ University of Tennessee fans soon will be
able to find their true colors at Home Depot in what is being
billed as the first mass marketing of collegiate-coordinated paint.
Four Home Depot stores in Knoxville will start selling specially
licensed and formulated Tennessee Orange paint. If it goes over big
with fans, Carolina Blue, Notre Dame Gold, Ohio State Red and
Alabama Crimson may follow, Home Depot said. We'll ask when the
Georgia red will be on the market. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
