<HEADER>
A2357 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BOX-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      07-14 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN BRINGS PRO-MILITARY MESSAGE TO ARMS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIZHNY TAGIL, Russia _ When the going gets tough, Vladimir Putin
gets martial.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's president is already renowned for flying a fighter jet
to visit troops fighting rebels in Chechnya and performing judo on
national television to boost his election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   So it came as no surprise Friday that Putin, struggling through
a welter of political crises that have clouded his young
presidency, was out at a firing range, letting off some steam by
unleashing a round from a 122mm howitzer.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was Ural Arms 2000, an exhibit of Russian military
hardware that Moscow hopes will help stimulate growth in the
country's massive arms industry and boost the economy. But the
event was also a chance for Putin to repeat one of his favorite
messages: All is well in the land when all is well with the
military.
</P>
<P>
   After firing the howitzer (and receiving the used casing as a
souvenir) Putin watched a series of displays of modern Russian
armor and missiles. The big hit was a T-90s main battle tank _
known here as ``the flying tank'' _ negotiate an obstacle course
like a rally car. At speeds of up to 45 miles per hour, the tank
climbed over walls, swam through a river, and popped a wheely off a
jump, landing with a thud a few yards away and firing its cannon.
Bullseye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all I liked everything,'' a beaming Putin enthused
after congratulating the tank crew and revealing that he has long
been a 122mm howitzer buff. ``They shoot accurately, they move
quickly, they make tanks jump like bicycles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Russian military hardware is the best in the world,'' crowed a
Russian television commentator, adding that none of the tanks had
been specially prepared for the show. ``Today, every shot was a
bullseye.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, in real life the targets are tougher to hit, and misses
common. Putin, waging battles to rein in oligarchic business
leaders and curb the powers of Russia's regional governors,
received an unpleasant reminder of that Friday from a conflict in
which his generals have often declared victory.
</P>
<P>
   With a defiant interview on Russian television, rebel commander
Shamil Basayev unscored that after months of fighting in Chechnya,
the Russian military has been unable to crush several thousand
separatist guerillas.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, an embarassingly public spat between Russia's two
top military commanders over the fate of Russia's nuclear forces
came to a head. Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev called `'psychotic''
a plan pushed by the chief of the general staff, General Anatoly
Kvashnin, to strip down Russia's strategic arsenal. Sergeyev,
travelling with the president, threatened to quit if the scheme was
implemented, but he backed off after Putin intervened, saying it
was merely a discussion of options.
</P>
<P>
   The war in rebellious Chechnya has revealed the poor state of
Russia's conventional military, and a recent army-funded study made
the same finding. While an estimated $4 billion worth of weapons on
display Friday will be sold abroad to virtually anyone who can pay
the price, the Russian Defense Ministry rarely has the money to
order the latest technology for its own troops, said Alexander
Kobin, deputy head of the state arms sales agency.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Eduard Rossel, one of the outspoken opponents of
Putin's plan to limit regional leaders' powers, said this week that
arms manufacturers could sell more if the Kremlin let them deal
with buyers directly, like American defense factories do, rather
than through a state agency.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia's defense industry has little experience in
marketing, sales, and financing. In the Soviet era, that was all
taken care of by the state, which neglected consumer goods but
lavished funding on developing weapons, including building up a
huge defense industry in this region. Some local arms makers
clearly long for those days, but it is not about to happen.
</P>
<P>
   When the director of one of Nizhny Tagil's largest factories,
which produces armor for tanks, suggested that the government put
more money in the metal industry and less into ``the production of
Tampax,'' Putin brushed the remark off with a smile and a
wisecrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what you produce cannot replace those products you are
referring to,'' Putin said. ``And the people need them daily.''
</P>
<P>
   People need a lot of things in Nizhny Tagil _ an upgrade of the
roads last repaired by German prisoners after World War II might be
nice, as would regular running water.
</P>
<P>
   But the news was not all bad at the exhibition. Russian and
foreign dignitaries got their first look at the Iskander-E tactical
rocket launcher, said by Russian analysts to have the highest
accuracy and longest range in its class.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Gushchin, the director of KBM, the firm that makes
Iskander-E, said he expects to increase exports from $20 million to
$100 million this year. The company also makes Arena, a tank
protection system that uses radar to identify and knock out
incoming anti-tank projectiles (like the tank-killing hand-held
grenade launchers Chechen rebels prefer, which KBM also makes).
</P>
<P>
   Turkey recently required that companies wishing to sell it tanks
install Arena. That prompted General Dynamics, maker of the US M-1
Abrams main battle tank, to rush to Moscow for talks with KBM.
</P>
<P>
   The T-90 tanks also seem popular _ India recently placed a
multimillion-dollar order for a shipment _ and people were
expecting Putin to don fatigues and take a test drive.
</P>
<P>
   But the president turned down the invitation. War games are well
and good, but he has a country to run.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe researcher Anastasia Saschikhina contributed to this story
from Moscow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
