<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG REPEATS HIS PROWESS IN TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRAGUIGNAN, France _ The Tour de France is just more than half
over, and already the scene at the end of each stage has become
repetitious.
</P>
<P>
   The pack of cyclists rides into town, Lance Armstrong hops up
onto the podium to put a fresh yellow jersey over the one he's
already wearing, and gets a bouquet of flowers, a small stuffed
lion, and kisses on the cheeks from two women as he is again
declared overall leader of the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   That was the scene again after the 13th stage Friday, as no
other rider could put a dent in Armstrong's lead.
</P>
<P>
   Six French riders finished in the top 10. It no doubt would have
been all the more reason to celebrate Bastille Day if a countryman
had taken home the stage's top prize. But Spaniard Jose Vicente
Garcia-Acosta ruined the party when he broke away from the pack
with fewer than 30 miles to go. Frenchmen Nicolas Jalabert and
Pascal Herve joined him, but Garcia-Acosta shook off their
challenges. He crossed the finish line in 4 hours 3 minutes 2
seconds, which was 25 seconds ahead of Jalabert and 10 minutes
ahead of the main pack.
</P>
<P>
   But Garcia-Acosta is in 29th place overall, so his win had
little effect on Armstrong, who finished 27th but has a 4:55 lead
over German Jan Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that it was a very pretty course, but we didn't have
much time to look,'' Garcia-Acosta said after his win.
</P>
<P>
   And he didn't mind crashing the French holiday. ``Well, it's the
end of the festival in Pamplona, so it's season for celebration
there, too,'' said the 27-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   The roads on the 115-mile course weren't nearly as mountainous
as the roads from the day before or the ones will be Saturday _ a
155-mile climb from Draguignan to Briancon _ but Armstrong said he
was surprised at the twisting and turning the cyclists had to
navigate as they made their way from Avignon to Draguignan in the
south of France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty surprised at the hardnesss of the course,''
Armstrong said through spokesman Luc Vershueren. ``There were a lot
of very small roads, and I thought I'd get more of a rest between
the two mountain stages.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether it's small roads or giant mountains, Armstrong has
shown he doesn't discrimiate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Hamilton, who was riding next to his US Postal Service
teammate almost the entire mountainous stage Thursday, likened it
to being a rabbit in a track race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to set a hard pace to wear the other riders out,
and I did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said that by riding just in front of Armstrong's wheel
and allowing him to draft, Armstrong expends about 25 percent less
energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if you get him to the most (finishes) as fresh as possible,
then you've done your job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong finished second in the 12th stage, behind Marco
Pantani.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even though all signs point to Armstrong wearing the yellow
jersey into Paris next Sunday, US Postal Service team director Mark
Gorski warns against getting too optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to be focused and feel like you're not way
ahead, because when you start getting complacent, flat tires,
crashes, things can happen. That's part of cycling, and you can't
discount those things too much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
