<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2359 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      07-14 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS MAY NEED WALKING SHOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The man who once took step-aside money rather than
force a court-ordered fight with Mike Tyson now wants his employer,
HBO, to do the stepping aside at a huge financial cost so he can
finally have that fight.
</P>
<P>
   Failing that, Lennox Lewis wants Tyson to force his employer,
Showtime, to do the same for the third time for Lewis's benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Failing either of those things, Lewis told the London Daily Mail
Friday, he will retire.
</P>
<P>
   Well, order the cake.
</P>
<P>
   HBO and Showtime are no more going to allow their heavyweights
to meet so the other can reap an expected $100 million pay-per-view
windfall than Bill Parcells is going to come back to New England to
save the Patriots from Bobby Grier.
</P>
<P>
   As Showtime executive Jay Larkin recently put it, ``Pork chops
will grow on the trees in Tel Aviv before we let Tyson go across
the street.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for that is they don't believe he'll come back in one
piece. And so there will be no Lennox Lewis-Tyson fight this year.
Or next year. Or any year.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no fight because Tyson owes Showtime millions.
Until it gets all of it back, he's going nowhere but on their
channel against safe opponents. HBO is not going to give away the
biggest heavyweight title fight since Evander Holyfield-Tyson I
because it doesn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis's threat to retire after his scheduled November title
fight against No. 1 challenger David Tua (if his next bout isn't
against Tyson) is an idle one for the simplest of reasons: He gets
paid more than he's worth to the cable network every time he fights
as it is already. He is not the engine pulling HBO's TV train. That
is Oscar De La Hoya, Naseem Hamed, Felix Trinidad, Shane Mosley,
and Fernando Vargas. On that train, the heavyweight champion is the
financial (and ratings) caboose.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night against Frans Botha, for example, Lewis (36-1)
returns to his hometown of London to fight for the first time in
six years. He will be 35 in September and has said he will not
fight here again. Combined with the fact he is the first British
undisputed heavyweight champion in more than 100 years, he should
be a draw of some magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   But not only has Lewis been unable to fill a 12,000-seat arena
(scaled back from 18,000), he wasn't able to attract much of a
crowd to a free outdoor weigh-in Thursday in Covent Gardens on what
passes for a summer day in this refrigerator of a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, when Tyson first appeared in London, madness
ensued everywhere he went. Well past his prime and by now a pariah
in his own country, Tyson drove Englishmen mad. They followed him
everywhere, stormed his hotel, and generally made a nuisance of
themselves whenever he appeared in public. Then they bought more
than 21,000 tickets to his fiasco against Julius Francis in one day
knowing what was going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, on the other hand, stands half naked on a weight scale
for free in one of London's biggest parks and fewer than 1,000
people show up. Worse, more than half were heard to say as they
passed, ``Why are those two men standing up there on the piazza in
their knickers?''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly the fight with Botha (42-2-1) is far from compelling
considering that he has been knocked stiff in the only two
significant fights of his life _ a fifth-round KO by Tyson and a
12th-round stoppage against then-champion Michael Moorer. Still,
Lewis's appearance at home needed to inspire a lot more interest
for his retirement threat to hold any weight with HBO.
</P>
<P>
   As for Showtime, what does it care? It would much rather feed
Tyson batting-practice opponents like Francis and Lou Savarese and
watch him act like a maniac to attract attention and viewers than
put him at risk. One more drubbing like the two Holyfield put on
him and the one Buster Douglas gave him and there'll be no more
selling the Godzilla of Brooklyn for $49.95. He'll be like clothes
on the streets of Brooklyn: discounted.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis can rightfully say, ``Tyson is the last big fight of my
era. But if they're going to prevent us from getting it on, there's
no point me carrying on.'' But he also knows he's making more than
$5 million for this bout and probably $7 million for a showdown
with Tua. It is easy money he can continue to pick up until he
retires in the next year or two.
</P>
<P>
   If Holyfield defeats John Ruiz Aug. 12 to claim the WBA title,
he could probably get $10 million or more for a third fight _
boring as it would be _ because it would again be to unify the
belts and all that nonsense. What's far more likely is that it will
be the Holyfield-Ruiz winner who fights Tyson for the $20
million-$30 million Lewis figures to get for such a match.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Not because the public doesn't want to see a Lewis-Tyson
fight, but because the networks don't need it. Holyfield-Lewis
served a purpose for both networks, even though Showtime had to let
the fights go to HBO. Showtime executives believed Holyfield had a
strong chance of winning. If he did, he would return to Showtime to
continue his contract as the undisputed champion.
</P>
<P>
   Since it also already had Tyson, one can only imagine what a
third fight would have done for business in this day of sicko TV
shows. The same holds true today.
</P>
<P>
   HBO was betting Lewis would win and enhance his reputation, but
also knowing it could get out of a contract that has not served it
particularly well because of Lewis's lack of popularity if he lost.
</P>
<P>
   This time the stakes are different. Showtime has nothing to gain
and a big investment to lose if Tyson fights Lewis on HBO and is
destroyed, especially when there's a good chance it can get him a
last title shot with the Holyfield-Ruiz winner and hype it for a
pay-per-view date worth considerable to them.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Finkel, who handles Tyson as best one can, knows this as
well. That is why he and Tyson keep saying he's not ready for Lewis
even though Finkel knows Mike Tyson, at 34, is a shadow of what he
once was and fading daily, both mentally and physically.
</P>
<P>
   So if Lewis truly believes it when he said, ``I'm close to the
point where it's Tyson or nothing. I'm ready to walk away,'' let me
give him a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a comfortable pair of walking shoes first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
