<P>
   FIRST-TUESDAY (Mexico City) _ Around the world, young
entrepreneurs and venture capitalists gather once a month to search
for prospects, ideas and dates. What's on their minds in London,
Moscow, Madrid, Prague, Singapore, Mexico City and New York. By
Andrew Ross Sorkin. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   CYRUS-MEHRI-PROFILE (Undated) _ For Cyrus Mehri, challenging the
status quo is second nature. His Iranian mother was punished as a
university student for criticizing the shah. He cut his political
teeth with Ralph Nader, organizing communities to rise up around
issues like telephone rates, and even his birthday, July 14,
coincides with a revolutionary milestone, at least for the French.
So when he filed a federal lawsuit against the Coca-Cola Co.,
representing four current and former black employees who said they
had been denied raises, promotions and other advancement because of
their race, it was a fairly typical move for Mehri. By Constance L.
Hays.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BIZ-JAPAN (Tokyo) _ Japanese companies outsource, but
without getting rid of the employees who were doing the outsourced
tasks. So former senior executives push boxes in the warehouse,
tears streaming down their faces. A tale of Japan's halting
attempts to modernize and realize economies already taken for
granted in United States. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEK IN REVIEW (Will move in `a' or `i' categories, as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTES-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Where Have All the Footnotes
Gone?'' the historian Gertrude Himmelfarb asked in a 1991 essay. At
that point, footnotes lucky enough to survive at all had moved to
the backs of books and turned into less scrutinized end notes. Now,
the Web has not only revived the footnote, it has spawned a
cross-referencing craze that renders the formerly complete media
event into a reference-laden, link-dependent, list-spewing
wallflower waiting to be courted by the next available annotator.
By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-DEFENSE-REVIEW (Washington) _ There is a dirty little
secret in U.S. arms control circles these days: No one really knows
where U.S. nuclear doctrine is headed. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-THESIS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Ah, the lessons learned in youth.
About love, faith, family and yes, the power of television to
define the modern presidency. This last issue weighed especially
heavily on at least one young person, Albert Gore Jr., as revealed
in the topic he chose for his senior thesis for the history
department at Harvard in 1969. Its title: ``The Impact of
Television on the Conduct of the Presidency, 1947-1969.'' By Peter
Marks.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ULSTER-REVIEW (Jerusalem) _ It can be useful for
Israelis and Palestinians to look closely at Northern Ireland for
instructive parallels, warnings signs and, more recently, practical
lessons in conflict resolution. Not all the lessons are
encouraging. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
