<P>
   GERGIEV-BALLET (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ Every year, around the
summer solstice, crowds gather on the banks of the Neva River, even
shabby hotels fill up with tourists and at the venerable Maryinsky
(formerly Kirov) Theater, the seats at the ``Stars of the White
Nights'' festival are taken up by rich patrons from all over the
world. This is also the one time when Valeri Gergiev, one of the
world's most sought after conductors, brings his star quality home
to this gritty city with a pretty face. By Celestine Bohlen. (With
photos)
</P>
<P>
   BOLSHOI-BALLET (New York) _ Power and passion: The Bolshoi
Ballet's dancing has been synonymous with these qualities, making
it a company unlike any other. Virtually sold out for its
appearances at Lincoln Center Festival 2000 this week, as was its
recent five-city U.S. tour, the fabled company from Moscow returns
to New York for the first time in 10 years, and with its potent
mystique intact. By Anna Kisselgoff. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   COMMIE-COMEDY-FILM (Undated) _ The phrase ``Communist musical
comedy'' may sound like an oxymoron, but even the officially
achieved utopia of no-longer-extant East Germany required a few
measures of utopian song-and-dance. ``Hot Summer,'' the teen-age
musical that was the DDR's second-highest-grossing film in 1968, is
not quite socialism a-go-go but it's an entertaining artifact
nonetheless. By J. Hoberman.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUBERT-MUSIC (Undated) _ Christopher Gibbs begins his brief
new book on Schubert (``The Life of Schubert,'' Cambridge
University Press) by avoiding any claim to the ``true'' man and
composer. He will, in his words, ``recount what can be reliably
documented and examine some of the persistent images.'' By Bernard
Holland.
</P>
<P>
   PULITZER-PHOTOGRAPHY (New York) _ Now for the bad news: Good
news is on vacation. Permanently. In the news media, anyway. That
goes double for news photography: The news photographs you remember
are likely to compose a litany of grief and terror, from the murder
of Lee Harvey Oswald to the execution of a Vietcong prisoner on the
streets of Saigon to the dragging of a dead American soldier's body
through the streets of Somalia. A show called ``The Pulitzer Prize
Photographs: Capture the Moment,'' at the Newseum/NY through Sept.
23, reinforces the widespread impression that news tends to be
violent and morbid. By Vicki Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CHINA (Beijing) _ A new Beijing museum displays superb
pieces recently acquired. By Eric Eckholm.
</P>
