<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS HE'LL VETO GOP-BACKED ESTATE TAX REPEAL 

</HEADLINE>
 TAX-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Friday vowed to veto
Republican-backed legislation to repeal the federal estate tax over
the next decade, an act that could give both parties rallying
issues at their national conventions this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the GOP-led Senate's final passage of the
proposed repeal, Clinton issued a blistering denunciation of what
he called a ``budget-busting bill that provides a huge tax cut for
the most-well-off Americans at the expense of working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators defended the legislation now headed to the
president's desk, calling the estate tax inherently unfair because
it allows the federal government essentially to tax people after
they die. The GOP-dominated House passed the measure last month,
279-136, with 65 Democrats breaking party ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The estate tax affects about 2 percent of U.S. taxpayers. Almost
half of the revenue is paid from a small number of estates worth $5
million and up. Only a tiny fraction of farms and small businesses
pay the tax because of exemptions _ $675,000 this year for
individuals and $1.3 million for farms and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive GOP presidential
nominee, also weighed in against the tax and challenged his likely
Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, to tell Clinton to
sign the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the Gore campaign ridiculed the governor's support
for the GOP measure as ``another example of Bush deciding to stand
up only when it benefits the few and well-connected.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's 59-39 vote in favor of the bill fell short of the
67 affirmative votes that would be needed to override a
presidential veto. Nine Democrats broke party ranks in voting for
the repeal, while four Republicans split from the GOP in opposing
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   With the party's nominating conventions looming, the partisan
fighting over taxes will only increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Monday is expected to pass legislation, already
approved by the House, that would repeal tax code provisions that
cause dual-income married couples to pay higher income taxes than
they would if they were single. Clinton has said he would veto that
Republican-backed measure as well because it is not tied to his
proposal to provide $250 billion in federal prescription drug
coverage for seniors during the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the two GOP-backed measures to the Democratic president
before the Republican convention could make the proposed tax breaks
major issues at the July 31-Aug. 3 event in Philadelphia. At the
meeting, Republicans are expected to formally nominate Bush to be
their party's presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, will hold their national convention Aug.
14-17 in Los Angeles, where they are expected to pick Gore as their
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pending conventions, Democratic and Republican
senators stayed clear of directly invoking the presidential
showdown into their often heated debate on the proposed estate-tax
repeal. However, the coming November election was clearly on the
minds of several lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (Democrats) want to write a law rather than create a
political issue,'' said Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, countered that the GOP's objection to
the estate tax was based on principle, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think death ought to be a taxable event,'' Gramm
said. ``We believe that when you build up a family farm or a family
business it ought to be yours for keeps'' and not subject to tax
after death, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's Texas colleague, Republican Kay Bailey Hutchison, also
voted for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate debate on the estate tax repeal also provided a
potential preview of the party conventions. Democrats accused the
GOP of being consumed with protecting the wealthy, and Republicans
countered that Democrats are too fond of taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we doing moving forward on repealing the tax . . .
instead of using some of this money to make sure that families in
our country can afford good child care for their children,'' said
Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. ``Why aren't we talking about a
commitment to education?''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Wellstone, Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., said the tax
applies largely to the few Americans with estates worth $5 million
or more but generates revenue needed to help pay for education and
other programs that help the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority's priorities are not those of working-class
people,'' Feingold said of the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans were just as vitriolic in attacking the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to control people even after they're dead,'' said
Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn., adding that the estate tax is
``anti-American, anti-family, unfair, unjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Grams, rebutting the accusation that Republicans seek to help
the wealthy, said the estate tax also applies to middle-class
farmers and small-business owners with equipment and other assets
worth $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death taxes hurt hard-working Americans the most,'' he said.
``We're not talking about tax relief for the wealthy. They're going
to take care of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., assailed the ``insatiable appetite
in Washington, D.C., to get hold of everybody's assets.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would get rid of the federal estate tax, which
includes gift and generation-skipping transfer taxes, by 2010 and
use $105 billion from the projected budget surplus to make up the
difference. Generation-skipping taxes are those paid when
grandchildren inherit from their grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Before passing the GOP-backed legislation, the Senate rejected
53-46 a Democratic substitute that would have raised the exemptions
without repealing the tax.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also rebuffed on a 59-40 vote a proposal by Sen.
Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., to suspend for 150 days the
18.3-cent-per-gallon federal gasoline tax in an effort to bring
down the high price at the pump. Opponents said the tax suspension
would reduce revenue needed for highway improvements.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the estate tax accounted for $20 billion of the $1.6
trillion in revenue paid to the federal government, according to
The Center for the Study of Taxation, which opposes the tax.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
