<SLUG> BC-STATES-FEC-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;   &QL;  &UR; Santorum Trounces Klink In the Money War &QL;   &UR; By Laura J.
Winter &QL;  &QC;  C. 2000 States News Service &QL;  &QC;  WASHINGTON (July 14) - Not
much has changed from the general primary season. Democratic Rep.
Ron Klink's war chest looks like a piggy bank compared to his
Republican rival Sen. Rick Santorum's bankroll.
</P>
<P>
   This is deja-vous for Klink. The Democrat from Murrysville
successfully faced down Democrats state Sen. Allyson Schwartz and
former state Labor Secretary Tom Foley in the April primary. While
Klink earned the right face off with Santorum, Klink's fundraising
booty came in a distant third behind the other two top Democratic
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign finance reports submitted to the Federal Election
Commission cover the second quarter period - March 31 through June
30. The Santorum 2000 campaign reported it raised $1.44 million
retaining $4.34 million in the bank. During the same period
$779,500 trickled into the Klink for U.S. Senate campaign coffers,
leaving it with $564,500 in cash on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The question is will Klink, a fourth-term House-member, pull off
a repeat performance unseating Santorum and ascending to the Senate
in the November General Election. Six years ago Santorum was a
rookie, squeezing into his seat with 49 percent of the vote. Klink
was reelected to his house seat in 1998, garnering 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With Klink's election track record, his campaign manager Mary
Murphy Kiernan would rather look at Klink funding situation as
pockets half full - not half empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right on track to have the money we will need to
communicate our message to the voters of Pennsylvania,'' Kiernan
said in a statement. ``Neither poll nor fundraising numbers in July
offer any historical guidance to the outcome of this election. We
will win this race in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Klink more than trebbled his cash on hand in the past three
months from the $119,162 he had at the start of this quarter's
reporting period. Klink's campaign received a total of $1.15
million in contribution since January 1.
</P>
<P>
   Still the incumbent's campaign spokesman Rob Traynham enjoys
having the larger of the two war chests, calling it a sign Santorum
will keep his seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers reflect the broad base of support that Sen.
Santorum has developed within every county in Pennsylvania,''
Traynham said in a statement. ``They (Pennsylvanians) are willing
to voice their confidence in him by submitting a check.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum's campaign did not reveal how much he had raised since
the beginning of the year. His campaign's press release did say
9,766 separate contributions were received in the three-month
period. At the same time the candidate spent $817,000.
</P>
<P>
   Klink's campaign received 1,009 separate contributions in the
second period. He spent just over a third of that spent by his
opponent - $339,626.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
