<HEADLINE>
ELECTRON BEAMS FROM THE SUN TO GENERATE WEEKEND AURORAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The weather in space will be stormy this weekend. That could be
bad news if you run a satellite or an electric power grid, but it's
good news for anyone interested in seeing one of the most
spectacular events that can ever grace the skies: a really
energetic display of aurora, or northern lights.
</P>
<P>
   An unusually powerful blast of particles ejected from the sun
over the last two days was heading straight for Earth, leading
forecasters to predict a strong likelihood of bright auroral
displays Saturday night. The sun is currently right in the middle
of the period of maximum activity in its 11-year cycle, a period
when such outbursts are relatively common.
</P>
<P>
   But the blast this week, a combination of an intense solar flare
and a phenomenon called a coronal mass ejection, or CME, is one of
the strongest recorded so far during this ``solar max'' period. The
resulting solar magnetic storm is the most powerful seen since the
last solar maximum in 1989, according to the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The storm could cause ``strong'' to ``severe'' magnetic storm
conditions above the Earth and could present problems for
satellites and electric power transmission lines, as well as radio
communications and electronic navigation systems, according to
warnings issued by NOAA.
</P>
<P>
   But astronomers warn that even though this weekend's onslaught
of particles from the sun is intense, any auroras that develop will
be masked by the bright moon, which will be full Sunday. Ordinary
northern lights might be completely washed out by the moon's light,
but an unusually bright display could shine through the moonlight.
And only those away from cities and their sky glow will have any
real chance of seeing the display
</P>
<P>
   In northern locations such as Alaska and northern Canada,
auroras are visible almost every night during the solar maximum.
Only the most intense displays extend southward into the
continental United States. This weekend, though, NOAA is predicting
auroral displays that could be visible over ``much of the US.''
</P>
<P>
   In March of 1989, one unusually bright display was seen as far
south as Florida and Arizona, which is extremely rare. At that
time, fire departments in Florida were swamped with calls from
people who thought the reddish glow on the horizon, something they
had never seen before, must have been caused by brush fires.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Further details available on the Internet at: www.spaceweather.com
</P>
</TEXT>
