<SLUG> BC-BUSHAIDE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush adviser refutes 'glass ceiling' concept
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A top policy adviser to Gov. George W. Bush
resists the concept of a ``glass ceiling'' that limits women's
career advancement, and equates day care to leaving children ``in
the care of rented strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Willett, who recently went to London to share Bush's ideas
with British conservative leaders, also said in an internal 1998
memo that efforts to improve working conditions for women are
nothing more than ``more government.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, spokeswoman for the Governor's Office, sought to
distance Bush from the memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one person privately expressing his personal opinion
to a colleague,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Willett formerly served as Bush's director of
research and special projects in the Governor's Office. Willett is
now a domestic policy and special projects adviser for the Bush
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He offered his thoughts about working women's issues in a memo
aimed at torpedoing a gubernatorial proclamation honoring the Texas
Federation of Business and Professional Women. The proclamation
declaring ``Business Women's Week'' in Texas, was issued, but only
after it was rewritten to reflect Willett's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   A request for a draft of the proclamation was sent to the
governor's general counsel for review.
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed similar proclamations for the group in 1997 and
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the wording of the 1998 proclamation were first
raised by Vance McMahan, Bush's director of policy. Willett
responded to McMahan with a memo saying ``I share the discomfort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I resist the proclamation's talk of `glass ceilings,' pay
equity (an allegation that some studies debunk), the need to place
kids in the care of rented strangers, sexual
discrimination/harassment and the need generally for better
`working conditions' for women (read: more government),'' Willett
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to list his political objections to the Federation of
Business and Professional Women, which has a long history of
backing Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McMahan responded to Willett's concerns by handwriting a none to
Shirley Green, Bush's director of correspondence, that said ``Do we
have to do this proc?''
</P>
<P>
   The final version of the proclamation included a statement that
said, ``Many working women still face resistance in attaining
certain managerial positions, and some still earn less than what
men are paid for the same job.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Federal of Business and Professional Women,
in Philadelphia for their national convention, were not available
for comment on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Edwards said the governor ``absolutely
recognizes and greatly appreciates the vital contributions of women
in the work force.'' ``Many of his most key advisers are women, and
he believes women should be afforded unlimited opportunities in the
workplace,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards added that Bush ``is very supportive of efforts to
expand and enhance opportunities for working parents to place their
children in quality child care.''
</P>
<P>
   Willett is a leading advocate of Bush's effort to use government
money and assistance to help faith-based organizations provide
social services, including drug treatment. Bush campaign spokesman
Scott McClellan said Willett was unavailable for comment on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Willett accompanied Bush adviser Marvin Olasky to
London for a meeting with William Hague, leader of the British
conservative party. The trip was paid for by a British public
policy foundation.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
