<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-L.A.-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL VIDEO CAN COST MORE THAN FILM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Miguel Arteta first put himself on the map in Hollywood
with ``Star Maps,'' a stylish little film about a Latino teen who
hawks guides to celebrity homes. Now he's back with the smartly
creepy ``Chuck &AMP; Buck,'' and this time, he ditched the richly toned
film of ``Star Maps'' for digital video.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't do it to save money, the reason many independent
and documentary filmmakers go digital these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually shot `Star Maps' for less money,'' Arteta said.
``In 'Star Maps,' we literally used the short ends of (unused) film
from people. We begged, borrowed and stealed to make that film.''
</P>
<P>
   Arteta's choice of digital video (he used the stalwart Sony DCR
VX-1000 camera) ``was definitely an artistic decision. I saw
(Thomas Vinterberg's 1998 DV film) 'The Celebration' and hadn't
seen where the technology was until then. The new (digital video)
transfers to film have this new finish to them, a silkiness, that
feels very intimate and immediate. I thought, 'This is fantastic.'
''
</P>
<P>
   That immediacy fed directly into the overall feel of ``Chuck &AMP;
Buck,'' which plays with our notions of, and screenwriting
conventions about, obsessive relationships. Because the video feels
more ``real,'' more like life than a Hollywood fantasy, it feeds
into our growing dread as the movie progresses.
</P>
<P>
   Using DV also contributed to the film's acting performances,
Arteta said, because he could use smaller crews, longer shoot times
and two cameras at once. That said, technology isn't the only thing
that makes a film work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of feel like technology is very important to
filmmaking, but it gets too much of an emphasis,'' Arteta said.
``What I go to a theater for is to get to an emotional place. It's
all about how fresh the characters are, how fresh the performances
are. Ultimately, does the audience care that 'Clerks' was shot in
16mm (film), '(The) Blair Witch (Project)' in DV or 'Taxi Driver'
in Super 35mm (film)? If you can access the emotional space, it
doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ---Devil of a good time &QL; 
The wait is finally over for fans of Diablo, the beautifully
wrought role- playing adventure from Irvine-based Blizzard
Entertainment that was such a hit several years ago. The game's
long-awaited sequel, Diablo II, finally hit store shelves about two
weeks ago, but didn't stay on them for long: More than 127,000
copies of the game were sold the first day.
</P>
<P>
   The fervor is understandable. It's a terrific game, at least to
my feeble first efforts to slog through, pushing the original's
great graphics and involving gameplay forward in lots of ways. Put
simply, this game looks great and plays great.
</P>
<P>
   Blizzard has replaced the original five-player types with five
others and has adds lots of little tweaks that make things like
going inside buildings easier and more intuitive. And of course,
there's Battle.net, Blizzard's excellent online gaming service,
where you can play other humans.
</P>
<P>
   My only knocks so far aren't really knocks, even. One is that
getting hooked on this game is devilishly easy. Two is that, once
hooked, it guarantees my right index finger shall be worn to a nub.
That's because you keep the left-click button depressed much of the
time as you intuitively guide your character through the game's
caves, castles and killer moors. I'll be suffering from some sort
of carpal tippal syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   And again, for you digital moviemakers, the game's opening
cinematic sequence is worth noting for its remarkably lifelike
computer-generated ``performers.'' It is in such games that we are
seeing some of the most interesting advances in graphics, advances
that aren't far, if at all, from big-screen quality.
</P>
<P>
   Blizzard also has good news for Macintosh users, who won't have
to wait much longer to get the good stuff. Diablo II for the Mac
has ``gone gold,'' which means it soon should be flying off store
shelves as well. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
