<SLUG> BC-NY-BRATTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRATTON MULLING TRY FOR N.Y.C. MAYOR'S OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William J. Bratton, the former top cop here, is
considering a return to public life, this time as the mayor of New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seriously looking at it,'' he said in a phone interview
Friday. ``Over the last several months, I've had meetings with a
lot of people to get their opinions on my chances.''
</P>
<P>
   A former Democrat and now a registered independent, Bratton also
confirmed a report _ which first appeared in Friday's New York Post
_ that he might run for the office as a Republican, to avoid what
is bound to be a crowded Democratic primary. The mayoral election
will be held in November 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody born outside of New York has ever been elected mayor
here. However, Edward I. Koch, the city's most overtly New
Yorker-ish mayor in recent times, does not see that as an obstacle
for Bratton. ``He has a record here,'' Koch said. ``I consider him
a son of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Koch, who was one of the people Bratton sought out for
advice, added that he did not give him much encouragement: ``I told
him that I thought he'd be best-served by accepting _ as I'm sure
he will be offered _ the position of police commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was first-rate at that job,'' Koch continued, ``but then he
left public service. The other four likely candidates have never
done anything but public service.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic consultant, who has not met with
Bratton, agreed: ``He's thinking Giuliani came into this as US
attorney, so he can come into it as former police commissioner. The
difference is, there was a lot of crime back then. There isn't
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sheinkopf added, ``He's got as good a shot as any of the
other four. He'd do well in the outer boroughs and he'd cut into
the black community.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratton made a splash when he moved here from Boston in 1990 _
as crime in the subways was nearly wiped out when he was Mayor
David N. Dinkins's transit police chief, and crime in the streets
was slashed when he was Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's first-term
police commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani pushed him out of the job in 1996 in a clash of egos
over who deserved more credit for the crime reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton briefly thought about running against Giuliani in the
following year's election, but gave up the idea, realizing that his
boss-turned-nemesis _ then at the peak of his popularity _ was
unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely different set of equations now,'' Bratton
said.
</P>
<P>
   First, due to term-limit laws, Giuliani cannot run again.
</P>
<P>
   Second, no clear front-runner has emerged among the four
Democrats who plan to run _ and there are no Republicans in the
wings.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Bratton thinks he can make headway amid the anxiety over
crime spurts and racial tensions marking the final months of the
Giuliani era.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are growing concerns about crime, with Giuliani leaving
and his close association with that issue,'' Bratton said. ``That's
an area where I have a strong reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   With the recent spate of police shootings and shakedowns in
black neighborhoods, he added, ``crime, race, and police brutality
are all related now.'' He would make a campaign issue of boosting
Boston-style ``community policing'' _ an idea that Bratton began to
push in his final days as commissioner but which Giuliani rejected.
</P>
<P>
   As for other subjects, Bratton allowed, ``Nobody knows where I
stand on a lot of issues,'' but he sees this as an advantage: ``I
have flexibility. I can use a campaign to help shape an image,
establish positions on issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratton, 52, is currently a consultant on law-enforcement
issues. He travels around the world. He is working on a TV pilot,
based on his own career. ``It's a cross between `West Wing' and
`Law and Order,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he added, ``I'm having a pretty good life right now,
and the money is great.'' But, ``The public sector, making change _
I like that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The declared candidates include City Council speaker Peter
Vallone, Comptroller Alan Hevesi, Public Advocate Mark Green, and
Bronx borough President Fernando Ferrer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
