<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2376 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-RARE-BIRD-HNS     07-14 2705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RARE-BIRD-HNS </SLUG>
 
 Purported Sighting of Rare Woodpecker Sparks All-Out Search 
 (Attention editors: For information about purchasing this article
as a separate-buy, contact Debra Weydert of the New York Times
Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail:
weyded(at)nytimes.com.)
 By SAM HODGES 
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEARL RIVER, La. -- All David Kulivan wanted to do was kill his
first wild turkey.
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, 1999, at age 21 and on spring break from Louisiana
State University, he managed to call one from its roost.
</P>
<P>
   But the turkey landed behind him and skittered away before he
could shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made a fool out of me,'' Kulivan said.
</P>
<P>
   So early the next morning he returned to the Pearl River
Wildlife Management Area, a bayou-threaded woodlands 45 minutes
northeast of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in camouflage, cradling a 12-gauge shotgun, he waited
for another chance to show a gobbler who's boss.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he says, two large, vivid woodpeckers flew into view
and landed on a water oak about 25 yards from him.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes they flew to another oak, only 10 yards
away.
</P>
<P>
   Kulivan was familiar with all the common woodpeckers, including
the big one, the pileated.
</P>
<P>
   But these were the biggest woodpeckers he'd ever seen. They had
more white in the wings than he remembered from pileateds. One had
a red crest, the other a black crest. Each had a creamy white beak.
</P>
<P>
   At LSU, Kulivan had briefly studied the ivory-billed woodpecker.
</P>
<P>
   He learned that most ornithologists considered it extinct, but
some believed it might be hiding out in remote forests of Cuba and
the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   When the birds hit the first tree, Kulivan wondered if he might
be seeing ivory-bills.
</P>
<P>
   When they landed on the second, he quit wondering. ``There was
no doubt in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes the woodpeckers flew away.
</P>
<P>
   Kulivan strode after them. He heard them do a toy-trumpetlike
call for a while, but never got another look.
</P>
<P>
   Kulivan drove to the New Orleans suburb where his parents live.
He felt both privileged and burdened.
</P>
<P>
   He'd had a camera in his bag but had failed to get a photograph.
</P>
<P>
   And he'd seen the birds on April 1 -- April Fool's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting, because I saw something that a lot of other
people think is extinct,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other emotion, I guess, was maybe a little trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   Like, `What's going to happen when I say it?' I knew I had to
say it.
</P>
<P>
   I knew it was the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   But I wondered, `Are people going to assassinate my
character?'''
</P>
<P>
   The following Monday spring break was over and he was back at
LSU, attending Vernon Wright's course on the natural history of
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   After the lecture, he went up to the professor, whose
encyclopedic knowledge of the state's flora and fauna had deeply
impressed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to talk to you, quickly,'' Kulivan said.
</P>
<P>
   They did talk, and Kulivan told him everything, and the life of
the young man who only meant to kill a wild turkey hasn't been
quite the same since.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, the ivory-billed woodpecker existed throughout
the
</P>
<P>
   mountain forests of Cuba and swamp forests of the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   At 20 inches long, it was -- or is -- the second-largest
woodpecker in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Early naturalists remarked on the ivory-bill's majestic beauty
and
</P>
<P>
   frantic energy.
</P>
<P>
   Country people, impressed by its 3-inch beak and ability
</P>
<P>
   to shred long strips of bark, dubbed the bird ``Log Cock'' and
``Lord God.''
</P>
<P>
   Less adaptable than the smaller, similar-looking pileated
woodpecker, the ivory-bill depended on recently dead trees in
mature forest for nesting sites and wood-boring beetle larvae, its
main food.
</P>
<P>
   As the virgin stands fell, the bird's range narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-19th century, ornithologists were remarking on the
ivory-bill's decline.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1920s, some believed it extinct.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1932, a few ivory-bills were found in east Louisiana, in
Tensas River bottomland woods owned by the Singer Sewing Machine
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later ornithologists from Cornell University, in
Ithaca, N.Y., went to the Singer Tract and made a recording of
ivory-bills calling.
</P>
<P>
   From 1937 to 1939, James Tanner, part of the Cornell team, did
an intensive study of six ivory-bills he found in the Singer Tract.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner also visited other swamps in hopes of finding additional
remnant populations.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner found none, but based on reliable reports he estimated
there were 22 ivory-bills in the United States in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Despite protests, logging of the bird's habitat continued,
including at the Singer Tract.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the early 1950s in the United States, and the 1980s in
Cuba, have there been widely accepted ivory-bill sightings.
</P>
<P>
   Most ornithologists have given up hope of seeing one alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to believe, of course, but I'd say two-thirds of
them think it's impossible,'' said Van Remsen, curator of birds at
LSU's Museum of Natural Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the other third would say `highly unlikely.''' Remsen
puts himself in the optimistic ``no opinion'' category.
</P>
<P>
   He does so partly because of his encounter with David Kulivan,
turkey hunter.
</P>
<P>
   X X X Vernon Wright, the LSU wildlife biology professor,
listened to Kulivan's story.
</P>
<P>
   Wright had him type up a description of the sighting, then sign
it.
</P>
<P>
   Wright was proceeding like Scotland Yard, but he was inclined to
believe his student.
</P>
<P>
   Kulivan had a reputation for both scholarship and good character
within the LSU School of Forestry, Wildlife &AMP; Fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the hot-dog type,'' Wright said of Kulivan, a
practicing Catholic and political conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Wright sent Kulivan's statement to Remsen at the Museum of
Natural Science.
</P>
<P>
   Remsen gathered LSU's best bird people -- professors and
graduate students -- and summoned Kulivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grilled him pretty hard,'' Remsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to call it an inquisition, but I deal with a
couple of ivory-billed woodpecker reports every year, and I've
never been interested in any before, because they were obviously
pileated or even red-headed woodpeckers.
</P>
<P>
   But his description was amazingly good.'' Most impressive to
Remsen, Kulivan mentioned details about the bird that weren't in
field guides, such as its call, way of shredding bark, and loud but
echolike ``double tap'' when pounding a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Kulivan freely conceded the April 1 date and his failure to get
a to him that Kulivan's account had the weirdness of truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remsen was convinced and stated it was the most credible
sighting reported to LSU in 20 years,'' said Steve Shively, a
zoologist with the Louisiana Wildlife and Fisheries Department.
</P>
<P>
   X X X The state of Louisiana quietly put a moratorium on timber
harvesting at the Pearl River Wildlife Management Area, a
35,000-acre fishing and hunting tract.
</P>
<P>
   And, with Kulivan leading the way, about 15 ornithologists and
birders spent a late April Saturday walking the area.
</P>
<P>
   They hiked to the spot where Kulivan had his sighting, then
played the recording of ivory-bills that the Cornell team had made
in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   No response.
</P>
<P>
   They broke into groups and spread out.
</P>
<P>
   Some people thought the habitat was good enough to support
ivory-bills.
</P>
<P>
   Some didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought they heard a double tap.
</P>
<P>
   Others figured that was the sound of tires on a nearby
interstate overpass.
</P>
<P>
   One searcher was Laurence Binford, a well-known, LSU-trained
ornithologist who believes he heard an ivory-bill calling near the
Tensas River in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, almost 40 years later, he was among those who heard a
double tap, a sound he has heard many times in Mexico while
studying the pale-billed woodpecker, which is in the same genus as
the ivory-bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people claimed it was road noise, which I didn't believe,
because I heard that noise hundreds of times during the morning,''
Binford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This didn't sound anything like that.'' But neither he nor
anyone else saw ivory-bills.
</P>
<P>
   There would be more group searches in the next weeks, but the
optimal period had passed, due to foliage (which helps birds hide),
bugs, snakes, heat and humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agreed to make a push the following winter, and to keep
the sighting quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Kulivan went back to LSU, finished his exams, then drove to
northern Virginia where he would spend the summer working at the
National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   X X X Serious birdwatchers call themselves ``birders.'' Birders
aren't content to enjoy whatever flies past the breakfast nook.
</P>
<P>
   Birders go looking for birds, and keep a ``Life List'' of
species they've seen.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS) When explaining how much they would
like to see an ivory-billed woodpecker, birders don't have to grope
for a metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   The metaphor is right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told people I could die after I see the ivory-bill,''
said Guy Luneau, a chemical engineer and hard-charging birder from
Kilgore, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the holy grail.'' (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS) Ivory-bill
fever broke out among birders in late January of this year when The
Clarion-Ledger, the daily newspaper in Jackson, Miss., published
the first story about Kulivan's sighting.
</P>
<P>
   Now back at LSU pursuing a master's degree in wildlife, Kulivan
began to hear from scores of birders and ornithologists who wanted
a blow-by-blow account.
</P>
<P>
   Birders created Web sites for discussion about the ivory-bill's
status.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana Ornithological Society began advertising ``I Want
to Believe'' T-shirts with drawings of a male and female
ivory-bill.
</P>
<P>
   The main development was the arrival in southeast Louisiana of
dozens of birders, from all over the country, determined to find
Kulivan's birds.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Luneau and his brother, David, came from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Scott came from Maryland and Jim Williams from Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Russell arrived from New Jersey, taking vacation from his
job as a wildlife biologist for the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Fish &AMP; Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS) Out in Sacramento, Calif., John
Trochet heard about Kulivan's sighting.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, sensing his excitement, gave him a vacation to
Louisiana as a birthday present.
</P>
<P>
   He spent a week in the Pearl River Wildlife Management Area,
devoting hours to rigorous searching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a wonderful time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't see ivory-bills.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS) The birders saw promisingly large
woodpecker holes, and trees with shredded bark.
</P>
<P>
   Some people had intriguing glimpses of flying birds, and Mary
Scott is pretty sure she saw an unusually large woodpecker with
lots of white in the wings, though she didn't manage to take a Most
of those who looked are being cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard or saw anything during my four days in February
that in any way, shape or form would I say was an ivory-bill,'' Guy
Luneau said.
</P>
<P>
   But he stressed that he and the other birders had searched only
a fraction of the Pearl River Wildlife Management Area.
</P>
<P>
   He intends to return next January, when deer hunting season has
ended and the leaves have dropped.
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS) When he could, David Kulivan went
with the birders.
</P>
<P>
   He was impressed with their commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Some wore camouflage, the way a turkey hunter would do.
</P>
<P>
   Others covered themselves with bug spray and lugged into the
woods binoculars, spotting scopes, cameras and boom boxes, on which
to play the Cornell recording of the bird.
</P>
<P>
   One group carried a cell phone to maintain long-distance contact
with an animal communicator, a sort of woodpecker whisperer who
gave advice on search techniques.
</P>
<P>
   This did not impress Kulivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a psychic is going to help us find the birds,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS) X X X Van Remsen warned Kulivan that
some people would lump him in with those who say they've seen
Bigfoot or Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been quite that bad, but there are skeptics willing to
speak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the deal is but I know what the deal isn't,
and it isn't two live ivory-bills,'' said Wes Biggs, a top Florida
birder who tried and failed to find ivory-bills reported in South
Carolina in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs thinks it's been too long since the last unchallenged
sighting for there to be any real hope.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that birdwatching's popularity has grown in recent
years, along with the desperation of top birders to see new
species.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe a bird of that size, with that loud of a
voice, could be any place in North America where it's not going to
be found,'' Biggs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, nothing would please me more than to be proved
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   I'd give up every bird on my Life List if I could add the
ivory-bill.'' Bob Russell, one of the searchers for Kulivan's
birds, thinks Biggs will be proved wrong.
</P>
<P>
   True, there are lots of birders, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   But they haven't been aggressive enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty much wimps compared to the naturalists of the
19th century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to go to the swamp for a month without going home.
</P>
<P>
   We hardly ever get into the parts of the swamp where the birds
might be.'' Russell and other believers also point to the frequent
number of ivory-bill reports through the years, some of them from
knowledgeable sources.
</P>
<P>
   John V.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, author of articles and books about birds, says he saw an
ivory-billed woodpecker in the Big Thicket area of east Texas in
1966.
</P>
<P>
   James Tanner, the Cornell-trained expert, came to check it out,
didn't see the bird, didn't like the habitat, and left dismissing
the report.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, now 80 and living in Princess Anne, Md., remains bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who doesn't have a doctor's degree or graduated from
Cornell or something, they think this guy's just seen a pileated
woodpecker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics counter that none of the recent reports of ivory-bills
-- including Dennis' -- has been documented by photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has any been verified by birders who came along afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody comes up with anything concrete,'' said Paul Sykes.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes, a biologist and birding legend (he has a longer Life List
than almost any other member of the American Birding Association),
joined Tanner in checking out Dennis' report.
</P>
<P>
   He said they concluded, after thorough investigation, that
Dennis almost certainly got it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Sykes has chased other hot ivory-bill
reports, none of which panned out.
</P>
<P>
   In February, he went to the Pearl River Wildlife Management
Area.
</P>
<P>
   He liked the habitat, and he thinks a turkey hunter like Kulivan
would be a good bet to see any surviving ivory-bills.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't see or hear anything that gave him much hope the
birds exist there.
</P>
<P>
   ``His story seems impeccable,'' Sykes said of Kulivan, ``but
I've been through this before.'' There are agnostics in the debate,
and they include Steve Shively, the zoologist with the Louisiana
Department of Wildlife and Fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent many hours looking for Kulivan's birds, and many
more listening to the back and forth about whether ivory-bills are
still around.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his gut feeling on the matter, Shively thought for a
second, then laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling,'' he said, ``is I don't know.'' X X X Maybe
someday delayed stress syndrome will take hold, and David Kulivan
will awake screaming from nightmares in which ivory-billed
woodpeckers double tap on his head.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he insists he's feeling pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   He appreciates those ornithologists and birders who support him.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't blame the doubters.
</P>
<P>
   He's glad there was rigorous searching this winter and spring,
and looks forward to more next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short of finding the bird, I'm pleased with what we've
accomplished,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it just seems so difficult to ever find it out there.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of birds, thousands of acres.
</P>
<P>
   But if we can concentrate on certain kinds of habitat, in
certain areas we think they might be visiting, we can increase our
odds.'' (FOURTH OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS) One measure of Kulivan's
poise is that he sometimes returns alone to the Pearl River
Wildlife Management Area.
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, 2000, a day short of the anniversary of his
sighting, he saw two wild turkeys there.
</P>
<P>
   He shot one, his first ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so proud.'' t
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
