<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2379 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH0715-COX     07-14 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth-SBC venture to be based in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth and SBC Communications have unveiled the
first details of their planned wireless venture: The chief
executive comes from one partner and the headquarters will be in
the home city of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Carter, who now heads SBC's wireless unit, will be chief
executive of the new company, which will start life this fall as
the nation's second-largest wireless company and will be based in
Atlanta. A specific location for the headquarters has not yet been
chosen.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have said since announcing the alliance this
spring that SBC _ as the largest partner _ will own the majority
stake, but the two will share management 50-50. The four-member
board of directors will include two men from each company.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Feidler, who now heads BellSouth's wireless phone unit,
will be chief operating officer of the new company, and Rick
Lindner, now senior vice president and chief operating officer for
SBC Wireless, will be chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Chairman Duane Ackerman has made a public commitment
to put as many employees as possible near mass transit routes
within Atlanta city limits. However, neither Feidler nor Carter
would predict that the new headquarters would meet that criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't speculate on that,'' Carter said. ``Suffice it
to say that we are looking at all the options.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of recent telecom projects, including Alltel and GTE
Wireless _ now Verizon _ have been sited in Alpharetta, Ga. A
consolidation of WorldCom employees may also be headed there.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has about 2,300 employees working for its wireless
unit, which is headquartered across from BellSouth Corp.
headquarters. It is too early to say how many would move, and how
many jobs would shift from the base of SBC's wireless unit in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   At least one will: Carter, who lives in the Dallas suburb of
Plano, will move to Atlanta, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Job reductions to save money in combining two units are
possible, but are unlikely to be dramatic, Feidler said. ``Wireless
is such a rapidly growing business the pact is generally going to
be very, very modest.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for creating a company that will immediately have
more than 17.4 million customers and reach areas in 34 states where
175 million people live. Included in that turf will be 42 of the
nation's top 50 markets. Only Verizon, which combined the wireless
units of GTE, AirTouch and Bell Atlantic, will be bigger. By
comparison, AT&AMP;T and affiliates have 12.9 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   But several key markets _ most especially New York City _ will
not be covered by SBC-BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Until those gaps are filled, the new company will lack the reach
of national providers AT&AMP;T, Sprint and Nextel. But the new company
will either bid for licenses or buy smaller companies. Both SBC and
BellSouth have also thus far managed to do well in wireless with
only regional presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really feeling very good about our ability to
compete,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements seemed to offer hefty evidence that neither
BellSouth nor SBC is going to bid for Sprint, whose merger with
WorldCom was officially scotched this week. Some speculation had
BellSouth buying Sprint after selling its wireless unit to SBC.
</P>
<P>
   The SBC-BellSouth venture could conceivably suffer from using
two different technologies. One, called CDMA, is used in most of
the properties. But BellSouth in the Carolinas and SBC in Nevada
and California also use a technology called GSM.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, a traveler using a phone made for one technology
cannot ``roam'' onto the other kind of network. But SBC and
BellSouth have been pushing manufacturers to make phones that can
easily move between both, and those phones should be available next
year, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the CDMA technology has been behind GSM in
carrying data transmissions in addition to voice. The newer phones
will let the new companies catch up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports had the companies committed to placing
headquarters in a neutral city and selecting a top executive from
outside both companies. That was apparently a misunderstanding. The
companies hired a search firm to seek executives, and also
considered headquarters elsewhere. But in the end it was home-grown
management and an Atlanta home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be tough to find a city better than Atlanta or Dallas
to put a company like this,'' Feidler said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
