<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-REUNITE0715-COX     07-14 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUNITE0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soldiers meet `baby' they saved in WWII
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOTHAN, Ala. _ Ben Byrd searched for enemy soldiers in the small
stucco house of an Old World German village. He found a crying
baby.
</P>
<P>
   That was 1945, on a cold February afternoon in Baldringen _ 12
miles from Trier, Germany's oldest city, where ruins of the Roman
Empire remain. The end of World War II still was months away.
Byrd's battalion was helping secure the town.
</P>
<P>
   Private first class Byrd and buddies Harry Biggs and Rene
Binette drew their rifles and entered the house in the middle of
town. Near the kitchen, a 7-month-old cried. The baby was
well-wrapped in a blanket, placed with a bottle of milk in a wicker
carriage.
</P>
<P>
   They pushed the buggy outside and headed to the church two
blocks away, where civilians had taken shelter. There was a stir as
they approached. The baby's mother shoved through the crowd. She
cried. She thanked Byrd, Biggs and Binette in German and took the
child.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers never got a name, never knew whether they had saved
a boy or a girl. They returned to the house and spent the night.
The battalion marched away the next morning. Before they left,
enemy artillery shook the house.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, shrapnel from a German shell struck Byrd in the
right shoulder. He recovered in Bristol, England, before returning
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old left the army later that year and registered for
pre-med classes at Auburn University. Byrd became a general
surgeon, working in Louisville and Richmond before settling into
practice near his hometown of Ozark, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, he wondered about the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd thought about him a thousand times,'' said Byrd, 74.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight over barbecue and beer, the soldiers _ and the refound
baby _ will celebrate their reunion 55 years later at a party with
family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Using old war notes, a German native in Dothan as translator,
encouragement from his wife and daughter and letters to
Baldringen's burgermeister, Byrd found the baby again: 55-year-old
Josef Koltes, a retired locksmith who still lives in the village.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three _ my saviors,'' Koltes said in Byrd's living room
with the help of a translator.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Koltes and his wife, Elke, arrived at Atlanta's
Hartsfield International Airport. It's their first visit to the
United States. Byrd, his wife, Sue, and German native Ilse Cantey
waited at the gate with a handmade sign that welcomed Koltes in
German: Willkommen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have known them even without the sign,'' Koltes said.
</P>
<P>
   They talked nonstop on the four-hour drive to Dothan. On Sunday,
they'll drive to a beach rental in Panama City.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures and maps were scattered across Byrd's long dining
table. Three German-English dictionaries bought from
Books-A-Million were shared eagerly. In the living room, Sue Byrd
served Koltes a bottle of Samuel Adams beer. With insistant
Southern hospitality, she later poured him a glass of Miller High
Life from a shimmering gold can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nein, nein,'' Koltes politely declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him not to argue with his mother,'' Sue Byrd said to
Cantey, the translator.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a German railroad worker, Koltes is the youngest of
five children. During the war, his father was a soldier, captured
by the Russian army.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard this story of my rescue many times when I was growing
up,'' Koltes said. ``But after my parents died, we didn't talk
about it much. When you're really, really busy, you don't think
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother died in 1985, his father in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother told me that my life depended on those soldiers,''
Koltes said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Byrd, Biggs and Binette, Koltes wondered what had happened
after the Americans left.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I did not know where to start, how to find them,'' Koltes
said. ``The soldiers knew it happened in Baldringen, but I didn't
have any idea where the soldiers were.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, after Byrd tracked him down, people in the
village have taken to calling Koltes the ``Wunderbaby of
Baldringen.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd recounted his war story in a letter to Baldringen Mayor
Willi Emser. Cantey translated. Emser asked around and found
Susanne Thinnes, an 87-year-old village resident. Now the eldest
person in town, she told Emser she was at the church the day
Koltes' mother took the carriage from Byrd and Biggs.
</P>
<P>
   Information flowed through e-mails, letters and telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never did I expect a letter from America, and now I send my
letter to you,'' Thinnes wrote to Byrd on June 2, her neat
penmanship producing blue cursive strokes of German words. ``I can
remember a lot from that time. It was the 27th of February when the
American soldiers came to Baldringen. The inhabitants waited
tensely for what was going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, all the people had to get out of their houses and meet
in front of the church. So did Frau Koltes and her family. She was
not allowed to go back into the house to get her child, and had to
go with her heavy heart to the assembly point. I remember very well
that she was very upset because she had to leave the baby back all
by itself. . . . The little Josef Koltes survived all his events
and grew into a man. Four times he became a father, and now he is a
grandfather.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Byrd invited Koltes to Dothan for an improbable
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be Herr Koltes,'' Byrd said, ``but he's the baby to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
