<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors, managing editors, wire editors:
</P>
<P>
   For six weeks, The New York Times has been publishing a series
of articles, ``How Race Is Lived in America.'' The series is the
outcome of a yearlong effort by a team of Times reporters to
capture some of the voices of ordinary people and some of the
troubling issues that Americans continue to face.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has filed the 14 articles in the
series that appeared in the daily paper.
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times Magazine for July 16 will have three additional
articles that are a part of the series, but not a part of the News
Service package. They are for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's CENTERPIECE news service, or as separate buys for
others.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's centerpiece is RACE-BIRACIAL-FAMILY-CENTERPIECE,
``Getting Under My Skin,'' a revealing memoir of growing up
biracial, by Don Terry, a national correspondent for The Times. The
other two are:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-FORUM-CENTERPIECE, Highlights of a forum moderated by Sam
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-ENNUI-ESSAY-CENTERPIECE, by Margo Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Please contact one of these sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 1-732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   _Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   _Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
<P>
   For more detail, look on the wire for the
CENTERPIECE-ADVISORY-NYTSF.
</P>
<P>
   These are the 14 stories in the series that moved to News
Service clients and are available for repeats:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-HOUSTON (Houston) _ In Houston, the fourth-largest city in
the U.S., blacks, Anglos and Hispanics each make up roughly a third
of the population. So the election in 1998 of Lee P. Brown as the
city's first black mayor was more than a celebration of victory for
blacks. It was also a testament to how racial and ethnic groups in
Houston had put aside their suspicions and rivalries and come
together largely out of self-interest to achieve power. By Mireya
Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT150-156 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-COPS-DRUGS (New York) _ On Friday, Feb. 25, at 5 p.m.,
there wasn't a single narcotics officer on the streets of Harlem.
Everyone was being held inside on standby in case of a race riot.
The Amadou Diallo verdict was about to come down. The whites _
officers like Sgt. Maria Brogli and Detectives Lee Macklowe and
John Montes _ hoped the four Diallo officers would be found not
guilty. The blacks _ detectives like Johnny Gonzalez and the
undercovers Derrick and Rob _ felt they should be found guilty on
at least some counts. No case in recent years has hit the police
closer to home. The 1998 killing of a black man by four panicky
white policemen touched every narcotics officer _ black and white _
to the core. By Michael Winerip.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT140-149 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-HIP-HOP (Undated) _ Billy Wimsatt, 27, was born as rap
music was being invented by blacks and Latinos in the South Bronx.
What began as party music became their cry of ghetto pain and their
great hope for a way out. And as hip-hop blossomed into the center
of youth culture, Wimsatt and lots of other white kids found in it
a way to flee their own orderly world by discovering a sexier, more
provocative one. He regarded hip-hop as a bold modern hope to ease
some of the abrasiveness between the races. Elliott Wilson, a young
black man, had never met Wimsatt, but their lives had traced
similar trajectories across the hip-hop landscape. By N.R.
Kleinfield.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT130-134 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-SPORTS (Baton Rouge, La.) _ In July 1996, Southern
University, a powerhouse among black colleges, desperately needed a
quarterback, and a white player, Marcus Jacoby, badly needed a
place to play quarterback. Southern's head coach, Pete Richardson,
recruited Jacoby. The decision made headlines. So began an odyssey
of triumph and defeat on and off the football field. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT120-125 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-PAPER (Akron, Ohio) _ Carl Chancellor and Bob Dyer were
part of a team of reporters for The Akron Beacon Journal that had
explored the racial attitudes of this city. Their series earned the
paper the Pulitzer Prize. The Beacon Journal also tried to lead by
example, and shortly after the series ended, it introduced a lineup
of columnists reflecting ``the perfect demographic,'' as Dyer put
it. They included a black woman and a white woman as well as
Chancellor, who is black, and Dyer, who is white. The paper, it
seemed, had become a proud model of racial enlightenment. Which
made it all the more startling when just a year later, the
jubilation began to fade. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT110-116 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-POLITICS (Bainbridge Island, Wash.) _ Many voters here say
that by putting a Chinese immigrant's son and two descendants of
slaves atop the governing pyramid of the state, Washington state
has transcended race. But if the old racial order has eroded, a
more complex one has replaced it, and now the system rewards
nonwhites who know how to make the largely white electorate see in
them what the voters see in themselves. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT701-706 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-CHURCH (Decatur, Ga.) _ Nearly 50 years after the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. scolded Christians for making 11 a.m Sunday
the most segregated hour of the week, the Assembly of God
Tabernacle here is the rarest of religious institutions: a truly
integrated church in the heart of the South. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT101-106 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-IMMIGRANTS (Miami) _ Before they left Cuba for America in
1994 Joel Ruiz, who is black, and Achmed Valdes, who is white, were
the best of friends. Today, in Miami, the two men live only 4 miles
apart, not even 15 minutes by car. Yet they are separated by a far
greater distance, one they say they never envisioned back in Cuba.
By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT201-207 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MILITARY (Fort Knox, Ky.) _ On a chill December morning,
two soldiers _ one black, one white, both part of an institution
portrayed as a model of race relations _ stood only yards apart in
the middle of this sprawling base, each believing himself the
victim of racism; one because of an award, the other because of a
transfer. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT301-307 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-TV-DRAMA (Baltimore) _ Who Gets to Tell a Black Story: When
David Simon proposed to HBO a television series based on his book,
``The Corner,'' about black inner-city drug addicts, he was not
thinking much about the fact that he was white, but as the project
began to take shape, the issues of race loomed ever larger. By
Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT401-407 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-WEB-ENTREPRENEUR (Atlanta) _ Timothy Fitzgerald Stevenson
Cobb Jr. and his partner, Jeff Levy, had built an Internet research
company in Atlanta and by May 1999 each man's net worth had swelled
by about $25 million. It conferred an uncommon distinction on Cobb:
He became one of the country's few black Internet millionaires. The
racial backdrop to Cobb's accomplishments went largely unmentioned
by the people he did business with, but he seemed never to forget
it. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT501-506 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MEAT-PLANT (Tar Heel, N.C.) _ The first thing you learn at
the Smithfield hog plant here is the value of a sharp knife. The
second thing you learn is that not everyone has to work with a
knife. Whites, blacks, American Indians and Mexicans, they all have
their separate stations, but it is blacks and Mexicans that are
left to battle over the dirty jobs, one of the only places in this
muddy corner of North Carolina where a person might make more than
$8 an hour. By Charlie LeDuff.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT601-606 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-PLANTATION (Natchitoches, La.) _ At the south edge of the
old plantation, eight simple cabins stood in a field of clover.
Generations of whitewash were peeling in ugly patches from the
mud-brick walls. All but one front porch had rotted away, and there
were gaping holes where doors and windows used to be. Obscured by
rows of live oaks, the cabins had been forgotten by many and
ignored by most. There was almost nothing left _ except the stories
of the slaves who once lived in them. Will re-enactments of slave
life at a former plantation, now a national park, help to heal
racial wounds _ or open them? By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT901-908.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-KIDS (Maplewood, N.J.) _ Friendships ebb and end. It
happens everywhere, but what is striking is that it happens even
here, where the school district is extraordinarily mixed. But as if
pulled by internal magnets, black and white children begin to
separate at sixth grade. These are children who walked to school
together, learned to read together, slept over at each other's
houses. But race becomes as much a fault line in their world as in
the world their parents hoped to move beyond. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT801-NYT806 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
