</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-CHEMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS CHEMOTHERAPY IMPAIRS WOMEN'S THINKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some breast cancer patients score lower on mental tests during
and after chemotherapy, apparently confirming that the problem of
fuzzy thinking that patients call ``chemo-brain'' is real, a new
Canadian study has found.
</P>
<P>
   The level of impairment suggested by the study means that
doctors and patients should take it into account when making
treatment decisions, said the researchers from Princess Margaret
Hospital in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are seeing real effects here,'' said Dr. Ian F.
Tannock, an oncologist at Princess Margaret, Canada's largest
cancer center.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added emphatically, ``I worry that this will be
misinterpreted by groups of women with breast cancer as a reason
for not taking chemotherapy. That is the last thing we would want,
he said. Such a decision is ``always one of balancing risks and
benefits,'' Tannock said.
</P>
<P>
   Other oncologists agreed, and said that the problem of
post-treatment mental impairment should only be a consideration for
women who were considering chemotherapy to slightly improve an
already-good prognosis.
</P>
<P>
   Tannock and his colleagues found that, compared to normal
healthy volunteers, the women who were receiving chemo or had
undergone it a year or more previously did significantly worse on
cognitive tests, particularly those involving verbal performance
and memory.
</P>
<P>
   The effects were more pronounced in women undergoing chemo at
the time than in those who were a year or more out from the
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The study, reported in the current issue of the Journal of
Clinical Oncology, involved 107 women: 31 breast cancer patients
currently getting chemo, 40 patients who had completed chemo
therapy an average of two years previously, and 36 healthy women
who served as controls. The chemo patients were receiving standard
doses of the drugs rather than the high-dose chemotherapy that has
already been linked to impaired thinking and memory.
</P>
<P>
   Each person was asked to perform tasks requiring memory,
concentration, planning verbal and motor skills. They also took
tests of their mood to exclude the possibility that the patients
were depressed, which could reduce their performance.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on their test scores, the women were rated as normal
or borderline, mildly, moderately or severely impaired.
</P>
<P>
   The results showed that 12 of the 31 current chemo patients had
severe impairment and 3 had moderate impairment. Of the 40
previous-chemo patients, 9 showed severe impairment and 11 had
moderate. Of the 36 healthy control volunteers, four rated severely
impaired and the remainder were either normal or showed mild
impairment.
</P>
<P>
   The new study is one of only a few that have looked at the
problem. Tannock said his interested was piqued several years ago
when a patient told him, ``In our support group, we're all talking
about how this chemo stuff addles our brains.''
</P>
<P>
   Tannock said he has launched a much larger study of the problem
and hopes to pin down exactly which part of the treatment is to
blame. Patients typically are given a combination of chemo drugs
and may also be taking hormone treatments and drugs designed to
reduce nausea and vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eric Winer, a breast cancer specialist at the Dana-Farber
Cancer Institute in Boston, said that some of his patients complain
of poorer memory, but added that he's not yet convinced by any of
the studies that chemotherapy is to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are occasional patients who say it's really bothersome
to them, but you wonder whether it is related to the chemo or to
something going on in their lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Winer said, ``there have been enough reports of
this that I think we need to look at this issue more. It's not
something we can ignore.''
</P>
<P>
   At North Shore Cancer Center in Peabody, Mass., Dr. Joel
Schwartz said that neither he nor his colleagues recalled breast
cancer patients complaining of mental problems.
</P>
<P>
   But, like Winer, he said he believed the issue should be studied
``because it's something we need to tell our patients about before
chemotherapy'' if it is found to be a significant risk.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd way, Schwartz said, the debate is a sign of progress
in the fight against breast cancer. He noted that 20 years ago the
issue was ``whether we could cure the disease. Now that we are
beginning to cure patients, we have the luxury of saying, what are
we doing to their quality of life?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
