<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2386 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-SUIT0715-COX     07-14 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SUIT0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke moves bias suit to federal court
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola took its first step Friday to defend itself
in a $1.5 billion discrimination suit by notifying plaintiffs'
attorneys Willie Gary and Johnnie Cochran that it moved the case
from state court to federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The removal to federal court places the recently filed suit by
four black women in the same venue as a class-action bias suit that
has been playing out for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The claims made in this lawsuit are primarily federal claims
and, therefore, should be heard and ruled on in federal court,''
said Coca-Cola spokesman Ben Deutsch. ``This removal is a very
routine and common procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gary's law firm said it will oppose the change. ``We will
file the appropriate legal documentation in federal court to
attempt to have the case remanded back to state court,'' said
Tricia C. K. Hoffler, an attorney in Gary's office.
</P>
<P>
   No hearing or judicial ruling was required before Coke removed
the case to federal court, Hoffler explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a judicial ruling will be necessary to determine whether
removal of the case was proper, once we file our pleadings,'' she
said. ``The issues presented in this case are ripe for state court,
and the state claims predominate the federal claims. Either way,
whether in state or federal court, we will seek justice on behalf
of our clients.''
</P>
<P>
   If the case stays in federal court, it could be handled by U.S.
District Judge Richard Story, who has been presiding over the
class-action suit. Earlier this week, Story placed restrictions on
Gary's Florida law firm, prohibiting it from soliciting or entering
into any fee agreements stemming from the class-action case until
terms of a final settlement are announced in late October.
Individual class members can ``opt out'' of the settlement, which
is being negotiated by another group of plaintiffs' attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Gary and Cochran filed the state suit on behalf of
the four former employees, who allege a total of nine claims
against the company. The claims include creating a hostile and
discriminatory work environment, engaging in intentional infliction
of emotional harm, and negligent supervision, hiring and retention.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed on June 14 _ the same day Coke and the other
group of plaintiffs' attorneys announced an agreement in principle
to settle the class-action federal suit on behalf of 2,000
African-American employees. That suit alleged that the company
discriminated against current and former workers in pay, promotions
and performance evaluations. Coca-Cola denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's highest-ranking black executive questioned the
timing of the second suit when it was filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to view it as anything but blatant and disruptive
legal maneuvering, seeking to forestall the progress made in the
other lawsuit,'' Carl Ware, the company's executive vice president
for global public affairs, said last month.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffler dismissed Ware's statement as ``false and
self-serving.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
