<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-FILM-860&AMP;ADD-NY     07-14 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-FILM-860&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIZE-WINNING CHINESE FILM ATTACKED BY CENSORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ When Jiang Wen's powerful wartime film, ``Devils on
the Doorstep,'' won the Grand Prize in Cannes _ second only to the
festival's Palme d'Or _ in May, the word was that he faced trouble
with China's film censors.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, that seems an understatement. His film
languishes unscreened, officially condemned for political reasons
that seem drastically out of kilter with China's increasingly
buoyant and sophisticated society.
</P>
<P>
   He has also fought with his investors over their demands, on
commercial grounds, to shorten the two-hour 40-minute movie.
</P>
<P>
   And now Jiang, one of China's most acclaimed actors as well as a
second-time director _ he starred in Zhang Yimou's classic ``Red
Sorghum'' in 1987 and the recent hit television series ``Beijingers
in New York'' _ sounds utterly despondent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all too much like a Hitchcock thriller,'' Jiang, 37, said
in an interview. ``There's terror all around me, but I can't see
what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, Jiang said, he has never been officially notified of
the long list of demands made by the notoriously conservative Film
Bureau. The bureau vets all scripts of films made in China and then
must approve the finished product for release, often nit-picking
scripts and nixing topics that can be broached in newspapers,
magazines and books.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang said that the film's producers, Asia Union Film and
Entertainment Co. of Hong Kong and China Film Co-Production Co., a
required government-run partner that ushers foreign companies
through the bureaucratic maze, had been instructed not to show him
the Film Bureau's document.
</P>
<P>
   More ominous, Jiang and his friends have heard repeated rumors
that the Film Bureau plans to bar him from making or acting in
films for many years. He said he has tried to meet with the
authorities to discuss the matter, but has been repeatedly
rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   An official of the bureau's Film Censorship Committee, Zhou
Jiandong, said Friday: ``The film hasn't been banned; it just
hasn't passed the inspection process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This film has lots of problems,'' Zhou said in a telephone
interview. ``It was shown at a film festival abroad without prior
approval, which is a clear violation. This film is at odds with a
number of regulations concerning film content and distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the rumors that Jiang might be barred from making
new films, the official would only say: ``We're still dealing with
the matter. I can't say how they will resolve these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Devils on the Doorstep,'' which features Jiang as an actor as
well as director, tells the story of a wounded Japanese soldier
held prisoner by Chinese villagers in the last winter of World War
II, as the Japanese invasion is crumbling. In a story replete with
ironies and cultural misunderstandings, most of the villagers treat
the man well for a time, before they decide to trade him back to
the Japanese for grain.
</P>
<P>
   The rapacious Japanese occupation of China is a deeply sensitive
historical topic here, a source of persistent personal bitterness
and of frosty exchanges between the Chinese and Japanese
governments. This has led to contradictory attacks on Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the film was completed, government censors, not
known for their appreciation of irony, began demanding that he
change the title, apparently worried that characterizing the
Japanese as ``devils'' might cause a furor. His producers urged him
to find a new title, too, worried about alienating potential
Japanese viewers as well as about Beijing's approval. But Jiang
would not budge.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all the points raised by the censors in their review
of the finished movie involve its failure to paint every character
in politically correct colors. Copies of the April 21 appraisal
have been faxed around Beijing and it has even appeared on the
Internet. It reads almost like a parody of censorship from the
heyday of Mao's Cultural Revolution of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese military anthem is played many times throughout
the film,'' the multipage letter says. ``This signifies the
strength of the Japanese military and severely hurts the feelings
of the Chinese people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese are called `chink pigs' by the Japanese many times
throughout the film,'' it says. ``This severely damages the image
of China.''
</P>
<P>
   More generally, this ``Official Opinion from the Film Censorship
Committee of the State Administration of Radio, Film and
Television'' complains that too many Chinese in the film behave in
a friendly manner toward the Japanese, ``creating the impression
that Chinese civilians neither hated nor resisted the Japanese
invaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Jiang is berated for changing previously approved scenes and for
failing to make previously demanded changes in the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a shot of a naked female,'' the letter says. ``In
general, the style of the film is too vulgar.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's producers are invited to resubmit the film after
complying with a long list of demands for cuts and changes, and so
far the matter remains at an impasse. But given the sweeping
condemnation, it is hard to see how Jiang could make the film
acceptable, even if he tried.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I feel pulled in all directions and my will has been
completely exhausted,'' Jiang said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a filmmaker,'' he said. ``I wanted to show how people
react under extreme danger, how Chinese and Japanese responded and
how, in the middle of a war, people can lose all humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I never expected it would become so tangled up and
politicized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's plight is hardly unique. Since the mid-1990s, the Film
Bureau has if anything tightened its grip on filmmaking, causing
anguish and humiliating choices for many directors, sending some
abroad and influencing others to stick with innocuous topics.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds of convention, prudery and ideological correctness
imposed on domestically made movies seem all the more outdated
considering some of the Hollywood films that are approved for
showing _ and which are clobbering domestic films at the box
office.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the up to 10 foreign films allowed in each year are the
likes of ``Gladiator'' and ``Titanic,'' adventures and romances.
But one of this spring's biggest hits in China was ``The General's
Daughter,'' which features a woman's corpse, naked and
spread-eagled on the grass, and discussions of kinky sex that would
never be allowed in a Chinese film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all right to portray Americans as decadent,'' explained
one movie fan here with a laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
