<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2391 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-HEADHUNTERS-$A     07-14 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-HEADHUNTERS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEADHUNTERS TURN A FEW ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
 By REED ABELSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors have been bidding up more than dot-coms into the
stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In a labor market squeezed tightly by the demands of a robust
economy and the Internet, stocks of executive search firms have
been spectacular performers of late. The stock of Korn/Ferry
International has more than doubled since the company went public
in February of last year, while Heidrick &AMP; Struggles International,
which made its debut two months later, has nearly quadrupled. TMP
Worldwide, which went public in 1996, has since increased more than
fivefold, more than doubling in the last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition for talent is incredible,'' said Mitchell
Rubin, a portfolio manager for Baron Capital, which owns these
stocks. He credits the strong economy and a fundamental shift
toward information-based businesses. ``Right now is nirvana,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By combining traditional search businesses with the promise of
the Internet through online recruiting ventures, these companies
appear to be making good on the promise of ``bricks into clicks,''
said Mary Lisanti, the chief investment officer for equities at
Pilgrim Advisors, which owns both Korn/Ferry and Heidrick.
</P>
<P>
   But while these firms are benefiting tremendously from boom
times, and their close but not too-close proximity to the
technology sector, some analysts and investors worry about the
impact when the economy slows down. These companies have been in an
``upward spiral,'' said Kenneth Broad, a portfolio manager for
Franklin Templeton Investments, who has passed on these stocks.
``If and when they trip, there's a downward spiral,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The climb has surpassed expectations and shows no sign of ending
anytime soon. Revenue of the 25 largest firms nearly doubled since
1996, to about $1.3 billion at the end of 1999, according to
Hunt-Scanlon Advisors, a Stamford, Conn., firm that tracks the
recruiting industry. Hunt-Scanlon predicts that industry revenue
will grow at least 15 to 20 percent in 2000 and that online
recruiting will become an $8 billion industry by 2005, up from only
$250 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, the world's largest
executive recruiter, said it expected to report in early August a
gain of more than 40 percent in quarterly revenue _ as well as
higher-than-expected earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The search business, already expanding overseas, could see
explosive global growth as the Internet catches on. Recruiting in
Latin America, Europe and Asia ``is going to be the next big
phenomenon,'' said Brian P. Lee, chief marketing strategist at
Hunt-Scanlon. As if to underscore the point, last week Vicente Fox
Quesada, the Mexican president-elect, hired Korn/Ferry to help him
fill key government positions.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have already been impressed with the online efforts of
some companies. Heidrick offers LeadersOnline.com, which combines
traditional search techniques with online tools; Korn/Ferry's
Futurestep.com is aimed at middle managers.
</P>
<P>
   TMP Worldwide's claim to fame online is its popular Monster.com
job board, for anyone seeking a job. The company has teamed with
America Online to offer help-wanted ads and provides an inexpensive
way to recruit, said Ann Miletti, an associate portfolio manager at
Strong Capital, which owns TMP shares. ``As a firm, we use the
Monster board, too,'' Miletti said. The site says it has 15.2
million unique visits a month.
</P>
<P>
   While some investors feel that the search companies' stocks are
not yet priced to an extreme, the market has certainly been kind.
Heidrick now trades at $68.46875, nearly 46 times its estimated
earnings per share for this year. Korn/Ferry closed at $34, for a
comparable multiple of 31. TMP, which represents more of a bet on
its ability to remain the dominant Web site, trades at $77.0625, or
a comparable multiple of 87.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is convinced that search firms make for good
public companies. Competitors like Spencer Stuart and Russell
Reynolds Associates have chosen to remain private _ at least for
now. ``The market is very fickle,'' said Joseph Griesedieck, the
chief executive of Spencer Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   While the current business environment puts a high value on
these companies' services, investors have not always been so
generous. If the search business slows, they could be quick to
punish the stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, search firms have had trouble navigating public waters
when times were not so good. Korn/Ferry, for example, was a public
company briefly in the early 1970s before choosing to go private
again. LAI Worldwide, formerly Lamalie Associates, which was the
only public search firm for a time, was a dismal stock market
performer that was bought last year by TMP.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also make huge demands of public companies. ``As a
public firm, there is a tremendous amount of pressure to grow your
revenues,'' said Lee. By contrast, the private firms ``can be a lot
more selective in the assignments they take on,'' he said. Russell
Reynolds and Spencer Stuart, for example, boast higher revenues per
consultant than the public companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue for the search industry is the general prohibition
against raiding one client company to find an executive for
another. That makes it difficult to become too large a player,
because too many places are off-limits, Broad said. ``It's a
natural catch-22 for growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what happens if the Internet frenzy or the overall economy
comes to a screeching halt? While few people predict a major
slowdown anytime soon, these companies would be affected if fewer
people were hopping from job to job. The level of vulnerability,
however, is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are cyclical stocks in the sense that the labor market is
tight,'' said Miletti of Strong Capital. But she and the other
proponents of these stocks argue that these companies would prove
fairly resilient in any downturn, especially given their online
activities. ``The costs are so much less, it's compelling,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Broad of Franklin Templeton is not sure. Some companies,
like Korn/Ferry and Heidrick, are sometimes paid in stock warrants
by start-up clients. While that has benefited them as many stocks
have soared, a downturn could act ``like a magnifying glass on the
stocks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All of which might make for a pretty hard landing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
