<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2392 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-FRIEDMAN-MUTUA     07-14 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-FRIEDMAN-MUTUAL-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH: ROBERT FRIEDMAN OF MUTUAL EUROPEAN FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years in the wilderness, value investing is staging a
comeback, and Robert Friedman, who runs the $926.7 million Mutual
European fund, is basking in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good days for value investors,'' Friedman said from
his office in Short Hills, N.J. ``Europeans are running good
companies with solid, often global businesses at a time when boards
of directors are willing to restructure companies that need it. The
confluence makes this better than any other time in European
business history.''
</P>
<P>
   His investors are having good days, too. The fund returned 21.6
percent a year, on average, for the three years through June 30,
compared with 14.9 percent for all Europe stock funds, according to
Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, 41, takes a bottom-up approach to picking stocks,
seeking good but out-of-favor companies that are selling at cheap
prices. Ideally, he wants to buy shares at less than 60 percent of
what he thinks they are worth today.
</P>
<P>
   He looks for evidence of a catalyst that will push up a stock
price toward a company's intrinsic worth, like aggressive new
management or good prospects for merger, consolidation or a major
revamping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe is in its infancy in the reorganization of companies,''
Friedman said. ``Capital markets are opening up, and governments
are more willing to let companies restructure. Even Western
European countries with strong histories of socialism now recognize
the need for corporate access to capital markets and the importance
of company shares being properly valued.''
</P>
<P>
   While the fund has no geographic mandates, most of the companies
it holds are in Western Europe. About a quarter of the portfolio is
in British stocks, 20 percent in Scandinavia and 15 percent in
France; there are smaller concentrations elsewhere. The fund is
always at least 80 percent hedged against currency fluctuations, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By Friedman's reckoning, large-capitalization stocks are
becoming overvalued in Europe, though less so than in the United
States. So he is now focusing on companies with market caps of $400
million to $40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In evaluating a company's finances, Friedman is less concerned
about revenue growth than profitability. ``If a company has good
margin improvement on stagnant sales growth,'' he said,
``management is doing serious cost-cutting or restructuring.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman brings an American-style activist approach, a hallmark
of the Mutual Series funds, to the fund's relationship with
companies in the portfolio. ``Shareholder activism will be very
important in European markets going forward, because of the growing
awareness on the part of institutional investors that management
works for shareholders,'' he said, adding that Continental Europe
was lagging behind Britain in adapting to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   He sells stocks when discounts begin to shrink. When shares
reach 60 to 90 percent of what he believes they are worth, ``it's
time to take money off the table,'' he said. And when they reach
their full value, ``we are largely gone.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friedman sees bargains among European financial and engineering
companies.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, he says, is Irish Life and Permanent, an insurer
with a small presence in the United States. ``Ireland has been the
tiger economy of Western Europe because of low tax rates,
business-friendly government, economic growth in the upper single
digits and inflation of less than 3 percent,'' he said, adding that
demand for insurance is growing. For this company, he said, the
catalyst is a potential rebound of the country's financial services
sector, which was hurt earlier this year by rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman bought Irish Life, which trades in London, at prices
between 4.70 pounds and 5.70 pounds and figures its true worth at
about 10 pounds; it closed on Friday at 5.36 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is Powell Duffryn, a British conglomerate with
specialty engineering and port services businesses. Friedman said
it ought to be worth more than 7 pounds a share; it now trades at
4.68 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   He took a small initial position at 6 pounds in early 1999, but
rising interest rates depressed port revenue early this year, and
the stock price slumped, letting Friedman scoop up more shares at
prices of 3.50 pounds to 4 pounds. He forecasts earnings growth of
12 to 15 percent a year, he said, because ``management has really
restructured the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman also likes Internatio-Muller N.V., a Dutch engineering
company specializing in plant design and construction that has
agreed to merge with a local rival, Stork N.V., and sell off much
of its business. Friedman opposes the timing of the merger; he
wants Internatio-Muller to divest its assets first, pay a dividend
to shareholders with the proceeds and then complete the merger.
Dutch law provides little recourse to block the merger, he said, so
he is trying to win over company management to his approach
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, he said, the fund will profit. ``There's
too much hidden value not to make money here,'' he said, ``but not
as much as if they postpone the merger until after the sale.'' He
got in at about 20 euros a share in May, and puts the company's
intrinsic worth at 18 to 25 euros before the sale and at 30 euros
after. It closed on Friday at 18.4 euros.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
