<SLUG> BC-RAIL-MERGERS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER COURT'S RULING, RAILROAD MERGER WILL PROBABLY NOT HAPPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating for all needing)  
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. and Canadian railroads that were planning to combine
resources to create a rail system spanning North America lost a
court appeal Friday and will probably end up scuttling their
proposed $6 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court in Washington upheld a temporary ban on railroad
consolidations that was imposed in March by the Surface
Transportation Board of the United States. The board had frozen
action on all mergers after the Burlington Northern Santa Fe Corp.
and the Canadian National Railway Co. announced plans to put
together a vast freight network that would crisscross the United
States and Canada and offer service into Mexico, too. Their merger
would have been the largest in railroad history.
</P>
<P>
   The railroads argued that the board lacked the authority to
impose such a ban and could only approve or reject merger
applications. But the District of Columbia U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, in a 2-1 decision released Friday morning, ruled that the
board had not exceeded its statutory authority.
</P>
<P>
   The decision effectively upheld the ban that began on March 17 _
the day the board originally imposed the moratorium _ and runs
until June 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement released Friday, the two railroads
expressed disappointment over the court's decision but did not
signal their next move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither BNSF nor CN will speculate about its options,'' the
statement said. ``The managements of CN and BNSF will discuss the
ruling's implications for their proposed business combination, and
each will consult its respective board of directors.''
</P>
<P>
   Both companies already have quarterly board meetings scheduled
for this month. The BNSF board is to meet on July 20, and the CN
board on July 24. Spokesmen for both railroads refused to discuss
whether the future of the proposed merger or any further legal
action, including a request for a rehearing or a filing with the
Supreme Court, would be discussed at those meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts are almost certain that the deal will be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is dead for the foreseeable future,'' said James M.
Higgins, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. He said that
the Burlington Northern board in particular was impatient and
unwilling to be held up for more than a year, during which anything
could happen.
</P>
<P>
   In public comments shortly after the ban was imposed and the
railroads had filed their appeal, Robert D. Krebs, the chairman of
Burlington Northern, expressed doubts that the deal would go
forward if the moratorium was not overturned. In answer to a
question at a luncheon in Washington on March 24, Krebs said that
the economic climate in the industry would change so much during
the postponement that the proposed merger would probably no longer
make sense.
</P>
<P>
   At that same luncheon, Krebs also expressed concerns about the
Surface Transportation Board's announced plans to consider new
rules and regulations governing mergers that would be different
from those under which the venture had been planned by the two
railroads. And he said that the uncertainty generated by such a
long delay would hurt investors and further depress the rail lines'
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The board itself acknowledged that financial markets would react
negatively to a moratorium, but it found that danger would be
outweighed by the potential consequences of moving forward
``without appropriate rules in place at the beginning.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since the plans were disclosed in December, railroad stock
prices have gyrated wildly in reaction to predictions about what
federal regulators in Washington would do. Overall, Burlington
Northern shares have fallen more than 5 percent this year, while
Canadian National declined a bit over 1 percent. Both were up
slightly Friday as investors responded positively to the court's
action because they believed that some of the uncertainty that has
dogged the rail lines since the merger was proposed had been
lifted. Shares of Burlington Northern rose 68.75 cents, to
$26.9375, while Canadian National also jumped 68.75, to $30.75.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the plans of the two large carriers to
create a coast-to-coast, cross-border rail network have been both
praised and condemned. The new system would include 50,000 miles of
track and combined annual revenue of $12.5 billion. Analysts liked
the fact that despite their huge dimensions, the two systems
overlapped in few places. Railroad executives promised that few
jobs or miles of parallel track would be lost.
</P>
<P>
   But the vision of a transcontinental railroad came just as
shippers and manufacturers that use the rails were adjusting to a
previous round of mergers that had greatly disrupted service and
left a large number of rail clients unhappy. Many feared that the
Burlington-Canadian National combination would bring on even more
mergers and leave North America with just two very large national
railroads, which would decrease competition and lower the
responsiveness of the railroads to client needs.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators in Washington believe that more consolidation
is likely in the rail industry. They say they imposed the
moratorium to review regulations and make sure the industry
develops in an orderly way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
