<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2400 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS &LR;      07-14 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS PAUSE FOR RELIGIOUS OBSERVANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ The scene sounds a little like summer camp:
Delegates drive to and fro on golf carts. Staff members go bowling
during their free time. On sunny days, officials sometimes hold
meetings on the back porch.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is essential to the Camp David experience, and the
reason President Clinton chose to hold this week's Middle East
peace talks here. Nestled in a wooded retreat in the Catoctin
Mountains, sometime-enemies are not only hidden from the eyes of
the world. They are also, officials said, relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   That atmosphere will become especially critical Saturday, as the
Israeli delegation takes a break from the official talks to observe
the Jewish Sabbath, a 24-hour period during which they are not
permitted to do work. Under normal circumstances, that means
abandoning all rituals of the modern office, such as fax machines
and paperwork. But at Camp David, officials said the setting will
allow Israeli negotiators to observe the Sabbath and also carry on
with their main task: having informal conversations with Americans
and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We speak the whole Sabbath,'' said Rabbi Michael Melchior, a
member of the Israeli cabinet who serves as minister of disapora
affairs. ``What better (discussion) to have than one that brings
more peace?''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday marks the the fifth day of the summit, which has been
conducted in total secrecy as Israelis and Palestinians try to
settle their half-century conflict over a variety of issues,
including the status of Jerusalem, the fate of Palestinian
refugees, and control of Israeli-occupied territory on the West
Bank and Gaza Strip. One US official said Friday that ``at times,
discussions are tense.'' But few details of the negotiations have
thus far been divulged.
</P>
<P>
   According to an anonymous source quoted by Reuters news service,
Arafat threatened to walk out of the talks on Thursday night, after
US envoy Dennis Ross presented him with a verbal proposal on the
future of a Palestinian state, control over Jerusalem, and
refugees. Arafat reportedly only agreed to remain in the
negotiations after Clinton intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a crisis during the talks (Thursday) and Arafat
ordered his delegation to pack their bags to leave Camp David in
anger at American proposals which were identical to the Israeli
position,'' Reuters quoted the source as saying. ``President
Clinton calmed Arafat down and the Palestinian leader agreed to
stay only after the Americans withdrew their proposals. They are
expected to submit new proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, obeying their self-imposed news blackout,
refused to discuss what had taken place. But White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart denied reports originating with Palestinian officials
about Arafat's threat to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't witnessed any deterioration,'' Lockhart said. ``I
didn't see any luggage today.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart did, however, report one curious detail: That two
negotiators had gotten into a minor accident in their golf carts
Thursday night. He declined to say who they were, but he did say
they were from the same country.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton returned Thursday from a day of meetings
outside the compound to hold a back-porch meeting with Shlomo Ben
Ami, the Israeli minister of internal security. Clinton then walked
to dinner at a nearby cabin, where he dined at 8:30 p.m. with 30 or
so members of both delegations, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent all day Friday in bilateral talks, meeting
separately with both Arafat and Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the talks were ``very, very difficult.'' And they
cannot continue indefinitely; the Palestinian leader has promised
to declare an independent Palestinian state on September 13 if no
agreement is reached. And Clinton has an even earlier deadline: He
is planning to leave for Japan on Wednesday. Although Israeli
officials have suggested they might carry on negotiating without
him, US officials have indicated that possibility is remote.
</P>
<P>
   Those limitations have given the talks this weekend a greater
sense of urgency, making it difficult for the eight-member Israeli
delegation not to participate Saturday at all.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unlikely they will hold any formal conversations, or
even plan meetings, several diplomatic experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak will not negotiate on Saturday,'' said Alon Ben-Meir,
project director for the Middle East at the World Policy Institute.
``If it ever leaked that he did, it would probably end his tenure
as prime minister. That's all the Israelis need is one more excuse
to bring his tenure down by learning he violated the Sabbath.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Ben-Meir said, ``The advisors in both camps, they'll be
sitting together, eating in the same dining room, walking around
the paths. And they're going to be talking to each other. But
they're not going to sit down in a formal setting. There's a big
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Aronson, director of the Foundation for Middle East
Peace, agreed. ``I don't think Barak himself has any personal
qualms about sitting down and talking to people on the Sabbath, but
Israeli sensibilities are such that they cannot be seen to be
negotiating officially on Saturday. But who knows what they may
talk about when they shut the door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
