<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2401 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DEPOT-SCHOOLCOLORS071     07-14 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPOT-SCHOOLCOLORS0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols to be test market for Home Depot's college-color paint line
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's been a meeting of the orange-minded in
Knoxville. Four Home Depot stores in University of Tennessee
territory are testing a new line of paint licensed with the
school's signature color. ``Tennessee Orange'' will brighten up
dens, dorm rooms and ``just about anything,'' said Kim Taylor,
assistant manager at the Home Depot on Centerline Drive in
Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is `Big Orange' country here. We take our football quite
seriously,'' said Taylor, who's considering turning her garage into
a glowing orange hub for watching football on her big screen TV
this fall. ``We've got a local radio station offering to paint an
entire house orange if somebody will let them,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Orange costs about $25 a gallon, the going rate for
designer-brand paint. If it's a hit, Home Depot may consider
licensed colors such as Georgia red, Alabama crimson and others.
Home Depot's announcement said part of the proceeds from paint
sales will benefit the universities, but financial terms weren't
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta designer Karen Castles Gray, president of Castles Sport
Apparel, came up with the idea for the liquid loyalty. Two years
ago, she started marketing a line of college-licensed apparel for
women, which is sold in department stores such as Dillard's and
Parisian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have been asking for collegiate-logoed home decor
products, so I created designs for ``alumni rooms,'' said Castles
Gray, an East Carolina graduate who plans to turn 12 rooms at her
Buckhead residence into a ``designer showroom'' of school colors.
``I'm going to have a Georgia room, a Tennessee room and so on,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The orange-blooded Volunteers were an obvious choice for the
Home Depot launch, Castles Gray said. ``Last fall, we did over a
million dollars in (collegiate apparel) sales just in Knoxville,''
she said. ``I was given one shot to be successful with Home Depot,
and I couldn't think of a school that had more rabid fans than
Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
