<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0715-C     07-14 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SABBATH BRINGS WELCOME BREAK AT SUMMIT AS TENSION GROWS
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-JERUSALEM-0715
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Negotiators at the Camp David peace summit
hosted by President Clinton paused at sundown Friday for a meal
marking the Jewish sabbath, after a tense day of talks between
Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hunkered down at the presidential retreat, however, for
negotiations expected to heat up again late Saturday and Sunday
between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   As rumors circulated Friday that Arafat was poised to walk out
of the talks, Clinton sent U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright to a nearby town for an emergency meeting with Palestinian
politicians, and the White House warned that negotiations were
``bound to get harder,'' in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Albright met for an hour with the group, six Palestinian
opposition politicians who flew here on their own to urge Arafat to
take a tough stand in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   In the hour-long meeting at a federal training facility in
Emmitsburg, Md., Albright sought to tamp down Palestinian
expectations, warning the political figures that Arafat won't get
everything he wants in talks centered on security, territory and
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   And, said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart, Albright told the
group to brace for increasing difficulty in the days ahead, saying
that ``as they work through these issues, this process is bound to
get harder as they move along.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat have set a Sept. 13 deadline for resolving a
comprehensive set of issues aimed at settling once and for all the
two sides' 52-year-old dispute. Clinton has cleared his schedule to
remain here until Wednesday, when he is slated to fly to Japan for
the annual summit of leaders from the Group of Eight _ the seven
wealthiest democratic countries and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   As Albright sought to calm the worst fears of Palestinians,
negotiators for both sides split into groups in an effort to work
their way issue-by-issue through the contentious slate of divisions
at the root of the 52-year-old Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues include the question of Palestinian statehood,
borders of a Palestinian state, the future of Jerusalem, the
security of Israel and the ability of Palestinian refugees to
return to their homes in lands now under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart declined to confirm reports that U.S. diplomats had
begun to propose suggestions aimed at bridging the gaps between
Israelis and Palestinians, but he made clear that such proposals
are an expected part of the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly would not eliminate any diplomatic initiative, or
effort, that might move the process forward,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, held separate meetings with Barak and
Arafat. The White House released a photo showing Clinton, in blue
jeans and an Arkansas Razorbacks sweatshirt, smiling and listening
to an animated Arafat, wearing his trademark khaki military uniform
and black and white checked kafiyeh, the traditional Arab
headdress.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end Friday, Arafat and Barak had met with each other
just once in four days, with one other meeting among Barak, Arafat
and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The three had also had several meals together, though they were
not seated next to each other, said Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has thrown a strict news blackout over the
summit, declining to comment in any way on the substance of the
talks and providing scant detail even about atmospherics inside
Camp David. Some 200 media correspondents covering the event are
spending time at a temporary press center set up at the Thurmont
Elementary School, in this town of 4,400 five miles from Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's meeting was not subject to the blackout, however, and
it provided a rare glimpse at the dicey nature of the ongoing
talks.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton to send his top diplomat away from the talks to try
to console Arafat's opponents was, in itself, a signal of the level
of tensions within the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that there is public support for what Chairman
Arafat is doing,'' Lockhart said. Arafat is the chairman of the
Palestine Liberation Organization, or PLO.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just as important,'' Lockhart said, ``for Prime Minister
Barak to have public support.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian sources widely reported Friday that Arafat had
threatened to pack his bags in the face of mounting pressure to
accept painful compromises in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The reports could not be confirmed, but Lockhart told reporters
at a press briefing that no one should be surprised to hear of
negotiators' nerves on needles and pins.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tensions everyday when you're trying to work through
these difficult issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was expected to be a day of informal discussions among
negotiators, said Lockhart, with talks expected to turn serious
again Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
