<HEADLINE>
POLAROID SAYS DIGITAL PRODUCTS BEING SNAPPED UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teenagers who ``listen'' to their camera and insurance agents
who snap a digital picture and press a button for an instant
photograph are the target audiences for a gaggle of new Polaroid
products that the company expects will push sales growth up by at
least 10 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision I have is the same as Dr. Land for taking really
complicated technology and making it simple and easy to use,'' said
Gary DiCamillo, Polaroid chief exectuive, referring to Edwin Land,
Polaroid's founder.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the company's filmless digital cameras, primarily sold
in Wal-Mart, Kmart and Target stores since December, have already
surpassed the 400,000 units sold in all of 1999. The Cambridge,
Mass. instant-photography leader said five of the 10 best-selling
digital cameras are from Polaroid. And while digital products will
account for 10 percent of Polaroid's revenue over the next three to
four years, it will outpace the growth of instant film products.
</P>
<P>
   Investors remain skeptical of the company that dominates instant
photography _ a technology that is being rapidly replaced by
digital imaging. But while Polaroid commands a large share of the
corporate market for digital identification systems such as state
drivers' licenses, they face stiff competition in marketing digital
products to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Though Polaroid successfully rebounded from recent woes last
year, Wall Street has questioned the company's ability to sustain
growth for the long haul. the company's stock price _ $17.50, up 25
cents Friday _ has been sliding since its September 1999 high of
$30.0625.
</P>
<P>
   The big push into digital photography comes after last year's
successful launch of I-Zone, a low-cost pocket-sized camera and
postage stamp-sized film that appeals to the youth market. Together
with larger cameras, called JoyCam and PopShots, and new instant
films, the combination boosted sales by 7.2 percent to $1.98
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Now Polaroid wants to go the next step and leverage its core
instant picture technology platform with digital imaging for
consumers _ particularly in the mobile and wireless marketplace.
That includes developing new kinds of devices, many of them aimed
at the youth market _ and competing against Eastman Kodak Co. and a
cadre of established Japanese digital camera makers such as
Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   By year-end Polaroid expects to begin selling a digital camera
combined with an MP3 player that can store and playback music off
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, digital cameras require a desktop computer printer to
provide paper-based images. Polaroid plans to market a $250
handheld device that uses its film packs to print 2- by 3-inch
images from removable standard memory cards found in most digital
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   And while most of its digital cameras are priced between $99 and
$399, a new $800 digital camera with a built-in instant picture
film packs can immediately print out a digital image as well as
store scores of images on digital memory cards. The hybrid system _
first discussed by DiCamillo two years ago _ is aimed at businesses
such as insurance companies and real estate agents. However,
Polaroid is increasing its sales projections based on conversations
with customers and test marketing the unnamed camera system with
high-end consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Friday DiCamillo also hinted at a new low-cost instant picture
technology for taking digital images and converting them into
paper-based photographs. It would significantly reduce the
company's bread-and-butter $1-per-print instant film, possibly down
to 25 cents for a paper-based image. Company officials said it
probably will show up next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polaroid has done a good job with I-Zone and its other camera
lines, but the problem is we are seeing a slowdown in Japan, with
concerns that some products are fads,'' said Jonathan Rosenzweig,
managing director at Salomon Smith Barney. ``We have not seen the
company's ability to translate its success into extraordinary
top-line growth.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that Polaroid has endured some foreign currency
issues and had to divested nearly a dozen small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``DiCamillo is moving in the right direction, but he has a lot
of competitive hurdles ahead,'' Rosenzweig said. ``Execution _
being able to deliver consistent growth quarter by quarter _ is the
key to everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
