<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-NET0715-COX     07-14 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-NET0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft chief exec opens Window on new Web world
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The chief executive of America's most important _ and
controversial _ high tech company came to Atlanta on Friday with a
hole in his shoe, a malfunctioning computer and a sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Ballmer, CEO of Microsoft, was the draw for the first-ever
sellout crowd at a Technology Alliance of Georgia event. He told
the audience of 1,400 that Microsoft was placing its bets for the
future on the Internet and on a business called Microsoft.Net.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to transfer many of the functions of the PC to the
Internet, including programs that now require software (which
Microsoft makes) on the PC.
</P>
<P>
   Known in the industry as a supersalesman, Ballmer sometimes
abandoned the podium and paced the floor like a tent revival
preacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I saying that the PC is dead?'' he asked the crowd.
``Noooooooooo. I come from Microsoft and wear the PC tattooed on my
head.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, part of the strategy for Microsoft is that future
versions of Microsoft Windows will incorporate features designed to
add functionality to Microsoft.Net.
</P>
<P>
   The plain-spoken Ballmer said: ``Some people are saying that we
are basing it on Windows. Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said Microsoft.Net will also support numerous other
platforms and devices ranging from interactive TV to wireless
palm-size computers.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a stool toward the end of his speech, Ballmer
unwittingly displayed a hole the size of a quarter in the sole of
his shoe. While not in the same league with the world's richest
man, Microsoft founder Bill Gates, he can afford to replace the
brown loafers. Ballmer is America's 11th richest man with a net
worth as of mid-June of $15.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Undetered and a little amused by a malfunctioning laptop
computer used to display slides illustrating his speech, Ballmer
said America's move to the Internet had been slow and not so
obvious in the beginning, at least not at Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at Microsoft for 14 years before anyone took the
Internet seriously,'' Ballmer said.
</P>
<P>
   That's far from the case today. While Ballmer believes the
antitrust ruling that ordered the company's breakup will be
overturned, the move toward Microsoft.Net represents a path for the
company that does not rely so heavily on the dominance of its
Windows software.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer believes the Internet now is in the second phase of its
existence. But _ lurking just around the next cyber corner _ is
what he calls Internet Version 3.
</P>
<P>
   As he began to explain Version 3, Ballmer's laptop shut down
again, blacking out the slides that had been projected on the large
screens that flanked him. Minions rushed to the stage and began to
work on the laptop as Ballmer happily narrated the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are in power save mode,'' he reported. ``Now it's
rebooting. I like the way that thing shut down so nicely, I'm very
impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, without missing a beat, Ballmer shifted back to his text
event as technicians messed with the computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Version 3 there will be an Internet environment in which
the customers are in control,'' he said. ``Today Web producers are
in control. I want to see my view on the Internet ... my financial
accounts, my files, a world in which the individual is in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the power Microsoft.Net will presumably bring
to the individual, Ballmer said he would be able to create a Web
site and publish it instantly _ without any particular computer
skill. The speed and ease would mean Web sites could be created for
specific purposes, used and then discarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say I'm going on vacation,'' he said. ``So I have
Myvacation.com. I tell it to book my flight, to put my arrival time
on my sister's calender, and to notify her if my plane is going to
be more than 30 minutes late.''
</P>
<P>
   On his sister's side of the world, her own Web site could filter
the information and if appropriate page her to let her know that
Ballmer's flight would be late.
</P>
<P>
   These interlinking Web sites would become electronic servants
and create what he calls ``a world of cooperating Web sites'' with
the user in control.
</P>
<P>
   As was true last year, Ballmer was in Atlanta to take part in
the Microsoft Fusion event. The event is held by Microsoft each
year in cities _ including Atlanta and San Francisco _ to meet with
companies that are its customers and business partners. Ballmer
also spoke to the TAG group last year.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the TAG crowd, Ballmer said too much money is
being invested in Internet ventures that have little potential for
making money.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are overinvesting in dot-com startups,''
Ballmer said. ``There has been a hysteria. There is too much money
chasing Internet ideas in the short run.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer declined to talk about Microsoft's quarter that ended
last month or the outlook for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the U.S. economic outlook, he pointed out that
computer maker Gateway Inc., which Friday reported a 36 percent
gain in earnings from higher-profit businesses, had declining sales
to businesses. Gateway said sales to businesses declined 10
percent, reflecting a shift in focus to smaller companies, schools
and government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
