<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CAT-STEVENS-NYTR &LR;      07-14 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAT-STEVENS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FORMER CAT STEVENS TELLS HIS SIDE OF THE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL DeYOUNG   
 Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back home in London, Yusuf Islam on Friday reflected on his
detainment and expulsion from Israel this week, because of what
officials at Tel Aviv's Ben Gurion airport would only tell him was
a matter of ``national security.''
</P>
<P>
   Islam, who gained fame in the 1970s as pop star Cat Stevens,
said it was only after he arrived in England that he read he had
been barred from the country for allegedly delivering money to the
radical Palestinian group Hamas during a visit in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Islam's name appeared on a list of people banned from Israel,
the Israeli daily Maariv reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knowingly gave any terrorist group money,'' Islam
said. ``I've given to poor people and hospitals. I've helped to buy
ambulances in the Holy Land. Obviously quite clear and supportable
aims.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no affiliation with any organization such as Hamas,''
he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Islam's charitable organization, Mountain of Light, has donated
money and supplies to Israel, Bosnia and Macedonia. He has visited
children and other war victims.
</P>
<P>
   Islam, 51, said he had planned to visit Jerusalem with a crew
from the VH1 program ``Behind the Music,'' which is producing an
episode chonicling his pop career and subsequent conversion to the
Islamic faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were literally just going there for this filming,'' he
said. ``I thought everything was quite clear and understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to visit the Dome of the Rock, the beautiful
mosque in the center of Jerusalem, which was the first mosque I
ever walked into, as part of the story. I was going to be narrating
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, ``I was immediately separated from the crew
and questioned. Then I was told that I was going to be sent back to
Frankfurt on the next flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was led away to a very small cell with four other detainees.
Three were from Gaza, and another was an American who was coming
for a wedding. In a little room with no handle on it; it was a
locked door. With no water or other facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials denied mistreating the former singer, saying
he had been detained in the departure lounge.
</P>
<P>
   His 1988 visit, Islam said, was strictly a humanitarian mission.
``I had no intention, ever, to support terrorist groups, only to
look after the poor and needy who obviously need support in
difficult times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Money designated for Hamas-backed charities, the Israelis say,
often is diverted to the group's guerrilla wing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Islam was refused admission to Israel when he arrived
to attend a festival with his 5-year-old son. ``It was very sad
that my son had to bear that kind of experience,'' Islam said.
</P>
<P>
   Born Steve Deimitri Georgiou in West London, Islam changed his
name to Cat Stevens at the age of 17, and had sold millions of
records by 25. His best-known songs include ``Moonshadow,''
``Morning Has Broken,'' ``Peace Train'' and ``Wild World.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of spiritual journeys that turned into dead-ends, he
became a Muslim in 1977 and abandoned his music career. All of his
instruments and gold albums were auctioned for Islamic charities.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, he founded the Islamic Schools Trust, and today
he operates the Islamia primary and secondary schools in London. He
recently released a children's album featuring a recitation and
explanation of the Islamic alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   Islam has been at the forefront of efforts by conservative
Muslims in Britain to pressure the government to fund separate
Islamic schools. He was thrust back into the international
headlines in 1989 when, during a speech at a British college he was
asked what he thought about Iran's death sentence against author
Salman Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
   Islam's answer _ merely that the Koran supported capital
punishment for blasphemy, but that such action was unwise and
illegal in the modern world _ became a sensationalistic headline
around the world: Kill Rushdie, says Cat Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   He insists he was misinterpreted and was never asked to set the
record straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That issue was something people tried to connect me with, and
it had nothing to do with me,'' he said. ``But because I was a
famous name, I was being asked to comment on all sorts of crises
affecting the Muslim world. Which is not really fair, because I'm
not a scholar, and I shouldn't really be asked those kinds of
complex legal questions.''
</P>
<P>
   He fears this week's event will become yet another public
relations debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``With repeated attempts at maligning my integrity, and my good
intentions,'' he said, ``there's an objective to cast a dark shadow
_ more than a moonshadow _ on my life.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
