<SLUG> BC-LEUCADIA-RELIANCE-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKEOVER OF RELIANCE FALLS THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A planned takeover of Saul Steinberg's Reliance Group Holdings
collapsed Friday amid worries that Reliance might be unable to pay
debts that come due next month.
</P>
<P>
   Leucadia National, which had agreed in May to buy Reliance for
$295 million in stock, said it was unwilling to proceed with the
transaction, but left open the possibility that it might reach
another deal with the struggling insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   The Leucadia deal had valued Reliance shares at $2.55 each, but
the stock has fallen well below that price as Reliance's financial
condition has continued to deteriorate. On Friday the shares fell
6.25 cents, to 50 cents. Reliance bonds that are due to mature in
November were quoted at 30 cents on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Reliance was the centerpiece of Steinberg's empire, which he
took over in a daring corporate raid in 1968 when he was 29 years
old. He used it in a failed attempt to take over Chemical Bank, a
New York giant, the next year, and in 1984 he made $60 million in a
failed effort to buy Walt Disney.
</P>
<P>
   As an insurance company, Reliance was moderately successful, but
it suffered major losses in workers compensation insurance in
recent years and began to decline.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, as insurance rating agencies cut Reliance's
rating to very low levels, Reliance has had to sell some
subsidiaries whose products, like insurance for corporate directors
and officers, can be sold only by companies with relatively high
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is in a fire sale right now,'' said Matthew Coyle,
a director of insurance ratings for Standard &AMP; Poor's. ``It has to
sell key businesses or lose them.''
</P>
<P>
   While the remaining insurance subsidiaries do not appear to be
in financial distress, most of the company's debt is at the
holding-company level, including nearly $240 million of bank debt
that matures in August and $290 million of bonds maturing in
November.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P cited ``increasing concerns that Reliance will fail in its
efforts to refinance'' those debts as it lowered its rating of the
company's bonds to CCC, the lowest rating the agency has for bonds
that are not in default. It also lowered its rating of the
insurance company's ability to pay to B, a weak level.
</P>
<P>
   Leucadia, whose shares rose 31.25 cents to $24.50 on Friday,
said it was continuing to talk to Reliance and would not say what
had led it to back away from the previously agreed transaction.
Along with property and casualty insurance, Leucadia has a wide
range of businesses and is known for snapping up undervalued
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg owned 29 million shares of Reliance at last report,
but most of them were pledged to secure debts from three financial
institutions, which are not fully covered at the stock's current
price. Some other shares have been sold to meet margin calls.
Reliance shares peaked at $19.8125 in the summer of 1998 and traded
above $6 as recently as February.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg has also sold other assets, including shares in other
companies and his Park Avenue apartment, which fetched over $30
million, and his antiques collection, which brought $12.5 million
in a Sotheby's auction in May.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Steinberg got his start in 1961, when he was 22 and just out of
the University of Pennsylvania. He identified opportunities in
computer leasing, a business that was in its infancy. IBM, which
made the computers, was not interested in long-term leases, but
there was a demand for them. He started Leasco, which grew rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The company went public in 1965 and quickly became a hot stock,
as reported profits grew rapidly. There was criticism that the
profit growth reflected aggressive accounting, but the criticism
was largely ignored, and Leasco stock provided Steinberg with the
currency to take over Reliance, an old-line company that had assets
worth more than Wall Street realized.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Steinberg became known for a lavish lifestyle
and for an ability to sniff out value. The companies he raided were
often undervalued, but he generally was unable to make significant
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as an operating executive, he was less successful. He
took Reliance private in 1982, when stocks were cheap, and sold
shares in it to the public again in 1986. Those shares were issued
at $10 each, or about 20 times their current market price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
