<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-MAHUAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PRESIDENT OF ECUADOR WORKING AT KENNEDY SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN AND JONATHAN FRANKLIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Ecuadorean Supreme Court has issued warrants for
the arrest of Jamil Mahuad, who was deposed at the country's
president in January and has been teaching and working at Harvard
University's Kennedy School of Government since April.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad could not be reached Friday about charges that he
committed unconstitutional and corrupt acts during Ecuador's 1999
banking crisis. That crisis, and his decisions, were part of the
subject matter of a study group for undergraduates that Mahuad led
while a fellow at the school's Institute of Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Phillips, coordinator of the fellows program, said
Mahuad, who has a master's degree in public administration from the
Kennedy school, taught during April under a special program ``for
distinguished politicians and professionals who can only come for a
short period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrangements were then made for him to stay on at the school
through the summer working on projects of his own.
</P>
<P>
   In the study group, Mahuad ``talked about his experiences as
president of Ecuador,'' including his decisions to freeze thousands
of bank accounts and bail out 18 failed banks, said Phillips, who
attended some of the sessions. ``One of the great things about
having him here as a fellow was his willingness to talk about these
decisions and their repercussions. He is reflective and takes good
challenging questions.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ordering Mahuad's arrest, Galo Pico Mantilla,
head of Ecuador's supreme court, ordered electoral and
anti-corruption officials to provide details of contributions to
Mahuad's 1998 presidential campaign. According to El Comercio,
Ecuador's leading newspaper, the focus of interest is a $3 million
contribution from Fernando Aspiazu Seminario, former president of
Banco del Progresso.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts expect Pico to seek to have Mahuad extradited,
they said the effort is unlikely to succeed because of
international concerns about the inadequacy of procedural
guarantees in Ecuadorean law. Former vice president Alberto Dahik,
who is sought on corruption charges, has been granted political
asylum in Costa Rica, and former minister and presidential aspirant
Cesar Verduga received asylum in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad was president of Ecuador from August 1998 until he was
forced from office by the military.
</P>
<P>
   Former vice president Eduardo Pena Trivino, in a statement
Friday, said the arrest order was counterproductive because, he
said, Mahuad would never return while facing a jail sentence. If he
did not face arrest, the vice president said, Mahuad might have
returned to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of this being a triumph of justice, (the arrest order)
may well impede the truth from being found out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Radin reported from Boston; Franklin from Santiago, Chile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
