</P>
<P>
   CYRUS-MEHRI-PROFILE (Undated) _ For Cyrus Mehri, challenging the
status quo is second nature. His Iranian mother was punished as a
university student for criticizing the shah. Asked to do a book
report in the seventh grade, he chose one of Abbie Hoffman's. He
cut his political teeth with Ralph Nader, organizing communities to
rise up around issues like the Superfund cleanups and telephone
rates, and even his birthday, July 14, coincides with a
revolutionary milestone, at least for the French. So when he filed
a federal lawsuit against the Coca-Cola Co., representing four
current and former black employees who said they had been denied
raises, promotions and other advancement because of their race, it
was a fairly typical move for Mehri. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BIZ-JAPAN (Tokyo) _ Japanese companies outsource, but
without getting rid of the employees who were doing the outsourced
tasks. So former senior executives push boxes in the warehouse,
tears streaming down their faces. A tale of Japan's halting
attempts to modernize and realize economies already taken for
granted in United States. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   HEADHUNTERS (Undated) _ Headhunting firms _ options on the
economic expansion and the tight labor market _ are on a tear. By
Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-AGENTS (Undated) _ Agents and agent-like intermediaries are
cropping up &QL; 
in many walks of life where they were unheard of until recently.
But &QL; 
watch out: their loyalties may not be where you think they are. By
Elaine Silver.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-SYMBOL (Undated) _ The appearance of ``ISO 9000'' on labels
is just one way that arcane international standards for product
