<HEADLINE>
RED DOT, MEET GREEN: IF IT'S TUESDAY, NETWORK! 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, July 16) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is July 4 in London, around 7 p.m., and Helen Sinclair,
director of a British venture capital fund called Matrix Private
Equity, is surveying the buzzing bar from a corner of the room
where, at least for the moment, she can relax. ``As a red dot, I
get swamped,'' Sinclair says, looking somewhat exhausted. ``I meet
green dots for only three minutes each and can usually get in
around 40 green dots in an evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair is referring to a surreal new social order that springs
up in more than 80 cities around the world on the first Tuesday of
every month. In fashionable watering holes, entrepreneurs
identified by the green dots on their name tags seek out investors,
identified by red dots, while a third subculture, identified by
yellow dots, simply hobnobs, in case its members ever want to
become red or green dots.
</P>
<P>
   What began as an informal networking party on Oct. 2, 1998, at
the Alphabet bar in London's Soho for 80 people working in the new
economy has grown into something of a worldwide phenomenon. A bevy
of imitators have sprung up, too. And those who created the first
gathering in London have incorporated as a start-up business called
First Tuesday, which a company founder, Julie Meyer, acknowledges
is a bit of a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're an accidental company,'' she said. ``It was totally the
right place at the right time.'' Nonetheless, she is intent on
expanding the concept around the globe to ``democratize the process
of getting venture capital.''
</P>
<P>
   With one small catch. Eyeing the more than $100 million its
gatherings have helped entrepreneurs raise, First Tuesday plans to
make money by taking a cut of the deals that emerge from its
events.
</P>
<P>
   As dot-com mania expands far beyond its Silicon Valley origins,
entrepreneurs and investors worldwide face many issues _ some
global and some distinctly domestic. Money &AMP; Business sent
reporters to First Tuesday gatherings in seven cities this month to
see what was on the minds and the lips of members of the dot-com
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City: An Election Victory Is Good for Business
</P>
<P>
   Mexican society has been buzzing with excitement since Vicente
Fox Quesada, the former Coca-Cola executive, booted the world's
longest-ruling political party out of office on July 2, and nowhere
was that feeling more pronounced than at the euphoric First Tuesday
gathering in Mexico City. Members of the dot-com generation here,
which is largely responsible for sweeping Fox into power, could
barely contain their excitement about the new economy's newfound
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the next president of Mexico worked for
Coca-Cola means he really understands business,'' said Francisco de
Dios, chief executive of iBest Mexico, an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   And in the opinion of many of the dot-com players that crowded
into the Hacienda de los Morales, a lavish 17th-century farmhouse
that is now a restaurant, Fox is exactly what the new economy
needs.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just Fox's victory that is inspiring them. They
see the Mexican market as a field of opportunity anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico has enormous growth potential, even more so now that
democracy has arrived,'' de Dios said. ``We're still in diapers in
this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many people here say legal reforms are essential for that
potential to be realized. For example, although the Mexican
Congress took an important step forward two months ago by
recognizing the validity of electronic documents, some grumbled
over legislators' decision to stop short of legitimizing electronic
signatures. Another legal constraint, according to Tony Rayo, chief
executive of Grey Interactive Mexico, an affiliate of the big
advertising company, is that Mexican law requires companies to be
profitable for several years before they can file for initial
public offerings, forcing start-up companies to look for financing
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Rosengaus, chief executive of NCubo, which offers
investment capital and technical expertise for Internet start-ups,
said that more flexible regulations are needed to open the stock
market to start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican start-ups, Rosengaus added, suffer from the lack of a
venture-capital mentality here. ``If we get better access to
capital, there will be a greater development of concepts in the
country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _DAN FINEREN
</P>
<P>
   London: Where Options Are No Advantage
</P>
<P>
   Talking about money has always been considered crass in Britain.
So three floors full of 500 people not only talking about money,
but asking for it, pleading for it and in at least one case begging
for it, might normally be considered downright gauche.
</P>
<P>
   But not tonight. ``If you put all these people in a pub, they
would never talk to each other,'' said Mike Boston, head of
executive search at Citadel, a British recruitment company, who
came armed with a box of business cards. ``This event breaks down
that British reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston asserted that Britain was going through a fundamental
shift in culture, driven by the new economy. In London, American
business values and a combination of cultures from around the world
have steadily infiltrated the traditionally staid British mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Stratford, a 24-year-old entrepreneur, is prowling for
start-up financing. He needs about $750,000 for what he will
describe only as a transport business. ``You could easily bum the
idea,'' he said. His name tag, which identified him as being from a
company called Equido.com, bore an Internet address he had not even
bought yet. He does not have a business plan, either.
</P>
<P>
   While green dots clearly outnumbered the red dots, the money
still seems to be pouring in here. Andrea Marshall, an American
working in London as a consultant for Roland Berger &AMP; Partners,
said she used to believe that Britain's new economy lagged behind
that of the United States by two years. But she recently revised
her opinion. ``The stereotype that the Europeans are less
entrepreneurial is no longer true,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One factor that continues to annoy people in the high-technology
industry is Britain's tax treatment of employee stock options. In
contrast to practice in the United States, employees must pay
capital gains tax on stock options in Britain, making the incentive
less attractive than a substantial salary. That puts pressure on
companies to find loopholes and other ways to compensate employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so bloody complicated that you spend hundreds of
thousands of pounds and lots of management time trying to find
work-arounds,'' said Azzeem Azhar, chief executive of Esouk, an
incubator company.
</P>
<P>
   _ANDREW ROSS SORKIN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
