<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spiritual diversions: Here's a list of ways to keep your cool
and keep the faith this summer
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hot and dry. It's been that kind of summer.
</P>
<P>
   And now, for many families in metro Atlanta, those long-awaited
vacations have been taken and cabin fever is setting in as everyone
waits for the first days of school and, a bit later, the first
cooling breezes of early fall.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much that can be done about the weather, but we've
been talking among ourselves and with metro Atlantans and have
devised a battle plan _ a spiritual battle plan _ to handle the
last few weeks of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a list of things to do _ books to read, music to listen
to, movies to watch, retreat centers to attend _ that might make
the coming weeks more enjoyable and meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN CONTEMPORARY
</P>
<P>
   ``Fearless''
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Lewis
</P>
<P>
   Pastor's tiny daughter with the big voice combines R&AMP;B stylings
from the '70s with pulsating electronic rhythms for another
standout album.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lay It Down''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Knapp
</P>
<P>
   Singer/songwriter mixes acoustic rock arrangements and string
arrangements for a strong sophomore effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nicole C. Mullen''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole C. Mullen
</P>
<P>
   Mullen's debut album melds folk, rock, blues and funk into a
style she calls ``funkabilly'' and makes work.
</P>
<P>
   CONTEMPORARY GOSPEL
</P>
<P>
   ``Mountain High . . . Valley Low''
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Adams
</P>
<P>
   Veteran gospel singer earned a 1999 Grammy Award for best
contemporary soul gospel album for this album, which is currently
the No. 1 gospel album in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shout Hallelujah''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Clarence McClendon
</P>
<P>
   McClendon and his Harvest Fire Mega Mass Choir live up to their
name with a fiery album.
</P>
<P>
   ``Purpose By Design''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hammond
</P>
<P>
   Gospel music's most innovative artist unleashes a gospel gem
that's more traditional than previous efforts.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   ``The End of the Affair''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Neil Jordan
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Ralph Fiennes and Julianne Moore
</P>
<P>
   Mesmerizing and sensual adaptation of Graham Greene's novel,
which explores love both physical and spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Third Miracle''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Agnieszka Holland
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Ed Harris and Anne Heche
</P>
<P>
   Provocative portrait of a Catholic priest struggling with his
own beliefs. Film manages to convey a powerful affirmation of faith
without being preachy or sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Paul Thomas Anderson
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Tom Cruise
</P>
<P>
   Weaves intricate story about shattered families, love and
forgiveness in a riveting drama of biblical intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Kahuna''
</P>
<P>
   Director: John Swanbeck
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Kevin Spacey and Danny DeVito
</P>
<P>
   Born again-Christian meets up with two world-weary salesmen.
Movie explores faith when it collides with the mundane reality of a
sales convention where everyone is trying to land the big contract.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   Among the most overtly ``religious'' material these days are two
series of novels with very different tones and messages, but with
equally enthusiastic audiences: the apocalyptic fiction of Jerry B.
Jenkins and Tim LaHaye in the ``Left Behind'' books, and the
everyday adventures of the inhabitants of the mountain village of
Mitford in the works of North Carolina novelist Jan Karon.
</P>
<P>
   For the theologically inclined, there are biblical explorations
such as ``Stories Between the Testaments'' by Atlanta author
Marjorie Kimbrough (March 2000, Abingdon Press, $12, 176 pages), a
study of the people of the books called the Apocrypha by
Protestants and the Deuterocanon by Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers who wander into metro Atlanta bookstores are likely to
get some of the following recommendations _ some out for a few
years, some brand-new, some obviously religious, some more subtly
spiritual:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of Happiness: A Handbook for Living''
</P>
<P>
   By the Dalai Lama with Howard C. Cutler
</P>
<P>
   (November 1998, Riverhead Books, $23.95, 322 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Advice from the spiritual leader of Tibetan Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Isaiah Effect: Decoding Our Future through the Lost
Science of Prophecy, Time, and Miracles''
</P>
<P>
   By Gregg Braden
</P>
<P>
   (March 2000, Harmony Books, $23, 276 pages)
</P>
<P>
   An examination of one of the best-known of the Dead Sea Scrolls
looks at the link between the spiritual and the physical worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Tent''
</P>
<P>
   By Anita Diamant
</P>
<P>
   (November 1998, Picador USA, $14, 321 pages)
</P>
<P>
   A biblical novel told through the voice of Dinah, the daughter
of Hebrew patriarch Jacob.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traveling Mercies: Some Thoughts on Faith''
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Lamott
</P>
<P>
   (February 2000, Anchor Books, $13, 275 pages)
</P>
<P>
   A novelist's memoir about a devout but quirky walk of faith
through a troubled past that, according to People magazine, ``has
you guffawing on one page and bawling on the next.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's So Amazing About Grace?''
</P>
<P>
   By Philip Yancey
</P>
<P>
   (September 1997, Zondervan, $19.99, 304 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Best-selling Christian author Yancey's search for grace in a
cruel world full of troubling moral issues.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
