 UNDATED: Ross Sorkin.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moscow: Plenty of Scientists, But Few Managers
</P>
<P>
   In the dimly lit Planet Hollywood in central Moscow,
entrepreneurs are fishing for financing. Some carry business plans
scrawled on single sheets of paper; others speak of offices in
Siberia. A banker chatted under a fake palm tree with the head of
Russia's biggest Internet portal, Port.ru.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's online market is tiny. In a population of 147 million,
only about two million people use the Internet. Advertising last
year barely topped $2 million, but that seemed to indicate all the
more potential for a country dominated by scientists and engineers.
``This place is a gold mine of sophisticated ideas,'' said Igor
Kocmanek, president of iXcelerator.com, whose assets include a
software company.
</P>
<P>
   When First Tuesdays began here last October, a group of about 40
curious industry insiders took part. That number has swelled to
more than 300, and investors sometimes outnumber project
developers. ``It's pure business,'' said Kocmanek, a Czech citizen
who formerly worked at an investment bank here. ``When we started
in October, there was no money in the Russian Internet. Then in the
winter, it all started.''
</P>
<P>
   Over all, there has been about $15 million in commerce involving
what locals call RuNet _ the Russian Internet _ according to Ron
Lewin, chairman of the Internet technology committee at the
American Chamber of Commerce here.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem in Russia is finding good managers. The
Soviet Union produced generations of talented scientists and
engineers, people in the business community say, but it crushed
entrepreneurial instincts. People with ideas lack marketing skills.
Business plans are rough road maps, hastily drawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good CFO's are few and far between,'' said Brian Wardrop, who
helps manage an $80 million high-technology fund in central Europe.
``A lot of times, we'll pass on a deal because we don't believe the
company will actually produce monthly reports. Responsiveness is a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet niches abound in Russia's nascent market _ and the design of
programs for export is one of them. Russian companies exported an
estimated $1.5 million in programs last year, dwarfed by, say,
India's $6.5 billion. Russians have a reputation as superb
programmers, but the country's main business hurdle is selling the
goods.
</P>
<P>
   Some projects defy the imagination. As Igor Vasiliades, a first
vice president at Sibintek, an Internet subsidiary of Yukos Oil,
Russia's second-biggest oil company, tells it, his company is
trying to exploit that niche. So Sibintek retrained 1,100
unemployed oil-town workers in four Russian cities and put them to
work in computer programming labs. Eventually, Sibintek plans to
have 2,000 retrained employees writing programs for foreign
clients. ``We want big factories that can fill any order quickly
and cheaply,'' Vasiliades said. ``Labor in the regions is a fifth
of what it costs in Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   Other projects bring the market to Internet users. Brian
Flygare, sales director at a small marketing service provider,
Direct Star, said his site had struck a note with small businesses
that lack the time or the money to develop online sales. Flygare
sends troops of college students out to retailers, like the shops
in the famed GUM department store on Red Square, to persuade them
to post coupons on the site offering discounts to customers. Direct
Star gets a small fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of retailers out there who are terrified _
they hear `Internet' and they don't understand it,'' Flygare said.
``This is a way to wet their feet.''
</P>
<P>
   _SABRINA TAVERNISE
</P>
<P>
   Madrid: How to Play a Game Of Internet Catch-Up
</P>
<P>
   Standing beneath a glass case holding an elaborate black mask
from the movie ``Zorro,'' Bruno Mazzilli is checking out the action
in Planet Hollywood. But it is not the svelte young women
circulating around the oblong bar that interest him _ unless they
are wearing green dots.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzilli works for Unin Fenosa, a Spanish utility that has
bought big stakes in telecommunications operators and is now
looking to do the same in Internet start-ups. It is the old economy
seeking opportunities in the new.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already invested in two Internet companies and want to
invest in more because it's definitely the future, but things
aren't moving as fast here in the sector as they were six months
ago,'' complained Mazzilli, 28, a corporate development executive.
Behind the slowdown is nervousness from the sharp downturn in
American technology stocks States during the spring.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet sector in Spain still lags behind other
countries, he added. According to industry analysts, just over 11
percent of Spaniards use the Internet regularly, much lower than
the percentages in the United States or some other European
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Others who gathered here expressed similar concerns: timidity
among potential investors and Spain's need to catch up with the
remainder of the wired world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there's less euphoria,'' said Jaime Ventura, 24, managing
director of Universidadweb.com, a Web site aimed at Spanish
university students. ``But there is still incredible potential for
growth in Spain, because the Internet is so underdeveloped in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   People here, ranging from older executives in business suits to
those barely out of their teens and in sandals and T-shirts, said
Spaniards would gladly surf the Web for information, but were
reluctant to use it to buy goods, mainly because they are not
comfortable sending their credit card numbers over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is afraid of fraud,'' explained Cesar Canas, 28, who
is trying to drum up business for Construdia, a company that he and
two partners started last year to provide business-to-business
services for small to midsize construction companies.
</P>
<P>
   But there is some confidence that people will get used to the
Internet. ``The government is taking an active role in the sector
and telling everyone that the new technology and the Internet are
the future,'' Caas said. ``I hope it comes soon, because our
company is operating now for seven months and we're still looking
for customers.''
</P>
<P>
   _BENJAMIN JONES
</P>
