 UNDATED: for customers.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prague: Bells Are Ringing For `M-Commerce'
</P>
<P>
   In a polo shirt and jeans, Richard Seewald, a lawyer, stands on
the terrace of the Fromin discotheque overlooking the church spires
of Prague, scouting for places to invest $50 million for his
Internet venture capital fund, Redstars.com.
</P>
<P>
   He sees potential pots of gold here. The Czech economy has begun
to stabilize after two years of recession, and prospects look good
for Internet business, particularly in ``m-commerce,'' the new tag
for buying and selling over the mobile telephones that are
ubiquitous in Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet here has taken off in the past six to eight
months, so there is a need for what we do,'' Seewald said. ``The
buzz up to now has been ex-pat companies; now we are getting more
and more local business plans'' _ not just those of Americans with
an idea that was too late for Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wireless is totally the buzz,'' agreed Adam Healey, a 25-year
old New Yorker, as the constant ringing of mobile phones filled the
room. Healey's Samba Digital Media, an Internet services company
based in Prague, just pulled in $2.5 million of venture capital.
Healey had just finished briefing 200-odd entrepreneurs who filled
the disco. ``Ask yourself which investor you can hang out and have
a beer with,'' he said. ``You're going to be spending a lot of time
with them, so you'd better like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Healey's company produces Web pages and e-commerce solutions for
companies around the world. Like many local ventures, he combined
the entrepreneurial skills of the young Americans who have flocked
to Prague with the technical knowledge of Czech software engineers.
Now he is moving a step further _ to m-commerce _ and he has come
to First Tuesday to spread the gospel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Czechs have one of the highest penetrations of mobile
phones in the world,'' he said. ``It's a lot easier for someone to
buy a mobile than a PC.'' And because of the lack of credit card
use and consumer credit, the firms that operate digital mobile
phone networks take the credit risk. With only about 6 percent of
Czechs having regular Internet access at their homes or offices,
m-commerce is likely to outstrip the PC-based internet for most
consumer use.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Krasnan, 21, a student at the prestigious Prague School of
Economics, also has big plans. He doesn't have a business card yet;
his nameplate has just an e-mail address. With fellow students, he
is perfecting a secret mobile phone application as part of a
national student contest to join an Internet incubator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideas I have, but I am keeping them for myself,'' Krasnan
said. ``Of course we want to be rich, but we really want to create
something that isn't here. We want to change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Vedej will settle for changing the way that Czechs think
about the Internet. ``Companies here are still investing in
traditional marketing tools such as printed stuff,'' complained
Vedej, 25, managing director of Frontline Management, another
e-solution provider for the Czech market. ``They don't appreciate
the potential of the Internet. They are just waiting.'' The first
time Vedej came to a First Tuesday, earlier this year, he didn't
even know what venture capital was. Now he has a business plan and
is looking for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Karel Kosman, another red-dot wearer, fears that Prague's
Internet boom may have gathered speed too quickly. ``The situation
is a little like the Wild West here. People are snapping up any
deals at all. It's not healthy. People are going to lose money.''
</P>
<P>
   _PETER GREEN
</P>
<P>
   Singapore: A Caution Signal In Venture Capital
</P>
<P>
   The spring rout on the Nasdaq caught Southeast Asia's dot-com
industry in an awkward adolescent stage, somewhere between finding
venture capital and a public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Bar, a minimalist hang-out where 20- and 30-somethings
come after work, business cards are flying like chips in a casino.
But consultants outnumber venture capitalists, who in turn
outnumber the people with the ideas worth financing.
</P>
<P>
   Caution is the watchword, and one good indication is Chia Tek
Yew's appointment book. Chia, chief executive of
PricewaterhouseCoopers' Venture Accelerator, specializes in
investing in high-technology start-ups. But these days, he said,
venture capitalists are hiring his group to scrutinize the business
plans of companies in which they want to invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want someone to rubber-stamp them,'' said Chia, as he
described how early hopes for easy riches had given way to
questions about which businesses would prosper and which would die.
``The idea of spending someone else's money is gone,'' he said,
adding that his own firm now insists on being a co-signer of its
start-ups' checks.
</P>
<P>
   That, in a way, brings the region full circle. At this time last
year, aspiring entrepreneurs were rare and venture capitalists
willing to finance them even rarer. But government incentives and
success stories from the United States changed all that, giving
rise to what some say has been a gold rush of dot-com financing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Southeast Asia presents its own disadvantages to potential
investors. Political instability and civil strife around the region
have scared off foreign investors to larger markets with more
obvious Internet plays. So despite efforts to set up Southeast
Asian versions of Nasdaq with easier listing requirements for
high-tech start-ups, the prospects for a wildly received initial
public offering are dimmer than before.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Southeast Asia as a market for online services is
looking less lucrative. Only a tiny minority of the region's
residents use the Internet so far, and they are spread across vast
regions separated by language, culture and regulatory barriers. ``I
won't look at a plan that says the company is looking at only one
country or just Southeast Asia,'' Chia said.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh on many minds here are the travails of a local start-up
called Catcha.com. Designed as a Yahoo-style search engine tailored
for Southeast Asian Web surfers, the company is cutting staff after
postponing plans to raise 55 million Singapore dollars ($31.5
million) in an initial public offering in May. Its 25-year-old
founder has offered to work for free.
</P>
<P>
   _WAYNE ARNOLD
</P>
<P>
   New York: A Little Optimism At the Fashion Show
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers love a party they can't get invited to. Or so you
would guess watching the long line outside Ohm, a discotheque on
West 22nd Street in Manhattan. There, 600 fashionable men and
women, whittled from a list of 1,400 who wanted to attend, sipped
flavored martinis and angled for face time before a roving news
camera.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the technology stock meltdown in April, new-economy
soirees still attract a lot of media. There were so many reporters
there it was nearly impossible to miss them, or the legions of
entrepreneurs trying to woo them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad time for a lot of people,'' said Michael
Petersohn, the vice president for sales at Clickfinger.com, a
yet-to-be launched Web site that helps users bookmark their
favorite sites. ``But things are getting better.'' Clickfinger
started developing its site three months before the technology
plunge and has had trouble attracting money. But in recent days,
potential investors have been more willing to listen to
Clickfinger's pitch, though the commitments are slow in coming.
``Individuals are saying, `we didn't lose our Hamptons house,' so
they are more open,'' he said. ``But it's still hard.''
</P>
<P>
   And not just for Web builders. Near the front bar, Etyan
Bar-Chama, 30, a partner at Carpediem Technology Ventures, said
investors have balked on the millions of dollars they first
promised, leaving the five-month-old fund with only $5 million.
``They are taking down their investments,'' he said. ``We see more
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors, he said, are becoming more selective about what
venture capitalists they want to give money to. One way his firm is
addressing that is by bringing in other, more established venture
capitalists to lead a deal. The fledgling fund has been trying to
forge strategic alliances with established corporations that have a
history of acquiring venture-backed concerns.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear, as the First Tuesday festivities drew to a close,
that the Internet party that attracted khaki-clad Jeff Bezos clones
and sleek women in Manola Blahnik heels was, in a larger sense,
past its prime.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Price, vice president of business development for the Web
site USLaw.com, said he used to go to ``three or four parties a
night and walk away with martini glasses and stuff like that.'' But
those days are gone. ``Now you have the concept of profitability
and people are looking at the cost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That did not dampen the spirits of Walter Joyce, vice president
for strategic planning at Inculab, a Manhattan-based incubator for
Internet ideas. ``I came to try and gauge the pulse,'' he said.
``I'm still optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   -LAURA M. HOLSON
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
