<SLUG> BC-TV-CHILD-KILLING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHO KILLED ATLANTA'S CHILDREN?': HAMPERED BY A PLODDING, SKETCHY
SCREENPLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By DAVID DeWITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One at a time they cascade across the screen, face after face,
lives cut short and deaths not explained.
</P>
<P>
   Set against a dark background and accompanied by haunting gospel
music, the opening moments of ``Who Killed Atlanta's Children?''
suggest a film that will have a focused appeal and a subtle
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's good intentions, however, are undercut by the bulk
of this fact-based drama, which compresses a painful, complex tale
into a plodding, sketchy screenplay that, sadly, is not enlivened
by either direction or performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Killed Atlanta's Children?'' _ on Showtime Sunday at 8
p.m. _ is based on a 1986 investigation by Spin magazine, which
reported on the doubts that remained in the wake of a frightening
series of murders in Atlanta between 1979 and 1981. Known as ``the
Atlanta child murders,'' the case was declared closed after the
1982 conviction of Wayne Williams, who was a suspect in the
murders, for killing two of the victims, who at 21 and 27 were
adult men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Killed Atlanta's Children?'' covers explosive territory.
The case prompted fear in the Georgia capital and across the
nation, because of the victims' youth, because of their numbers
(the official total was 29) and because of their race: All were
black.
</P>
<P>
   As depicted in the film, mothers of some slain children remain
unconvinced that Williams, who is black, was responsible for all
the deaths. Ron Larson (Gregory Hines) and Pat Laughlin (James
Belushi) are the journalists who step in to help their cause. They
find evidence of a confused investigation and desperate
investigators. An insider source (played with crusty authenticity
by Sean McCann) points the reporters to suspects allied to racist
groups. Worse, the source offers documentation of an inquiry into
those suspects, one not made public because, the film suggests, the
authorities were more concerned about smoothing racial tensions
than about solving crimes.
</P>
<P>
   That secret investigation and its disturbing context were the
crux of Spin's report. The film, written and directed by Charles
Robert Carner, has an even broader reach. One short but evocative
scene is dominated by a portrait of President Reagan, with a man in
the foreground giving telephone assurance to an unidentified
someone that the authorities had settled the Atlanta child murders.
</P>
<P>
   Such conspiracy material, coupled with the families' grief and
desire for closure, offers plenty to occupy ``Who Killed Atlanta's
Children?'' So it is disappointing that the film wastes most of its
energy on the journalists' professional issues and domestic
worries. Imagine ``All the President's Men''; make the
investigative focus more somber and grisly; now envision Woodward
and Bernstein talking about their childhoods, or swapping advice on
balancing family and work. The mix makes an unwieldy whole.
</P>
<P>
   Hines gives Larson a nicely reticent dignity, but he can't lift
dialogue that locks his character, an editor, into obvious
professional conflicts with the freewheeling writer played by
Belushi.
</P>
<P>
   Also conventional is the revelation that Larson feels distant
from his lower-income relatives as well as from his less
sophisticated Southern sources. (The film's portrait of Atlanta is
visually and socially unappealing.)
</P>
<P>
   Belushi as Laughlin is saddled with even more generic material.
``Everyone wants to blame others for their own failures,'' Laughlin
says of the Atlanta murders, a provocative attitude that is diluted
because it is used to reveal the reporter's boyhood more than it is
to enrich his current situation. Belushi's few muted moments add
more to the film than his typical bluster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Killed Atlanta's Children?'' does not try to answer its
titular question. The movie does not exonerate Williams (given a
creepy edge by Cle Bennett). And it makes no declaration of blame,
though it examines possibilities of several killers tied to several
motives: urban prostitution, political hypocrisy and organized
racism.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the movie calls attention to a set of killings that
were never given as fair and thorough a hearing as they deserved.
The streamlined tale of ``Who Killed Atlanta's Children?'' proves
no more satisfying a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WHO KILLED ATLANTA'S CHILDREN?'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Charles Robert Carner; produced by Rudy
Langlais; Michael Grais and Mark Victor, executive producers;
Michael Goi, director of photography. A Showtime presentation.
</P>
<P>
   With: James Belushi (Pat Laughlin), Gregory Hines (Ron Larson),
Sean McCann (Melton), Aidan Devine (Jack Johnson), Shawn Doyle
(Royal McCullough), Cle Bennett (Wayne Williams) and Kenneth Welsh
(Wayne Williams' lawyer).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
