<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SPENDING DATA SHOWS LITTLE LETUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States' shoppers kept spending through the spring
despite an uninspiring stock market and increases in interest rates
and gasoline prices, according to government reports issued Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, analysts said, a superheated U.S. economy may not
be cooling to the satisfaction of the Federal Reserve Board , which
over the last year has raised the cost of borrowing money on six
occasions as it seeks to keep prices in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got an economy that's slowing but that may not be
slowing enough,'' said Diane Swonk, chief economist for Bank One
Corp. in Chicago. She said the risks were still high that the
Federal Reserve would decide it needed to raise interest rates
again.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market's reaction to Friday's economic data was swift:
Prices fell, raising yields, as traders and investors decided that
a bigger-than-expected rise in retail sales last month _ on top of
a hefty upward revision for May _ outweighed a relatively
market-friendly report on June producer prices.
</P>
<P>
   A third survey, on industrial output for June, showed the
smallest increase in nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales, according to the Commerce Department's initial
estimate, climbed 0.5 percent last month, to $269.3 billion, with
about 70 percent of the gain spent at automotive dealers and about
half the rest at gasoline stations.
</P>
<P>
   While the increase was not much more than had been expected,
analysts said, it was from a base in May that was considerably
higher than first reported, as the department's statisticians,
using more complete data, transformed what had been a decline of
0.3 percent in retail sales into a gain of 0.3 percent. Retail
sales, which account for about half of consumer spending and
one-third of all economic activity, are widely watched for clues to
current conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department's report on prices paid to producers, which
excludes both services and imported goods, showed a 0.6 percent
advance for finished goods; the rise was largely driven by oil and
natural gas. While this matched expectations, economists said they
were surprised that the so-called core rate, which excludes energy
and food, edged down 0.1 percent after rising 0.2 percent in May,
the first drop since January.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Glassman, an economist and a managing director of Chase
Securities, went so far as to call it ``stunning'' that the long
run-up in energy prices has spilled over so little into other
sectors. ``Underlying inflation remains well behaved,'' he said,
adding that an enormous, continuing corporate appetite for
high-technology equipment implies further anti-inflation pressure
by rising productivity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Goods at the intermediate stage of production, like a sack of
flour, climbed 0.9 percent last month, while raw materials jumped
5.8 percent, in both cases reflecting the surge in energy costs.
Recently, Swonk said, gasoline prices have dropped sharply in the
Midwest, where they had risen the most.
</P>
<P>
   The industrial production report, compiled by the Federal
Reserve, showed that the nation's factories, mines and utilities
raised output 0.2 percent last month, a little less than expected,
compared with a 0.5 percent rise in May.
</P>
<P>
   Automobiles, semiconductors and business equipment were the main
contributors to the gain, with output slackening for appliances,
clothing, steel and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The next scheduled meeting of Federal Reserve policy-makers, who
last month found signs of economic slowdown ``still tentative and
preliminary,'' is on Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   In another development Friday, the National Association for
Business Economics published a survey that found that one-third of
businesses were able to offset higher costs by raising prices
during the second quarter, the highest proportion since the first
quarter of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pricing power has improved,'' said Swonk, who is currently the
association's president. ``It makes the Fed awfully cautious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
