<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN WORCESTER FIRE RELEASED TO CUSTODY OF MAINE COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRAMINGHAM, Mass. _ ``Hi!'' yelled Julie Barnes into a celluar
phone with a cheerful voice as she motored off to a new life in
Maine in the backseat of Debb and Tim King's car.
</P>
<P>
   She had no possessions. But she was out of prison, heading
north, hundreds of miles from the scene of the fire that devastated
a community just seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, now 20, and her one-time boyfriend, Thomas Levesque, 37,
were arrested last December in the wake of the Worcester warehouse
fire. Six firefighters died battling the blaze, and Barnes and
Levesque were each charged with involuntary manslaughter in the
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the pair, who had been squatting in the
warehouse, set the fire accidentally and left the building without
telling anyone. Barnes was taken to the state women's prison in
Framingham. Her bail was set at $1 million at first, then lowered
to $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   Things seemed bleaker than ever for the 19-year-old, three
months pregnant at the time. By friends' accounts, the young woman
who had drifted for years between her parent's homes and the
streets was also mentally disabled.
</P>
<P>
   But her prospects changed when the Kings saw Barnes' picture in
a newspaper, a few weeks after the fire. She bore an uncanny
resemblance to their adopted daughter, Jennifer, who had mental
disabilities but had thrived in their care. They quickly discovered
that Julie and Jennifer were sisters, separated by the state
Department of Social Services 16 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings grew determined to raise the money to bail Julie out
of prison, hoping they could bring her to Maine and give her some
of the social supports she lacked throughout her life. On Thursday
they had a breakthrough: a Worcester Superior Court judge reduced
Barnes' bail from $75,000 to $25,000, and said she could be
released into their care.
</P>
<P>
   So Friday morning the Kings came from Maine, handed prison
officials $25,000 in cash, and prepared to meet Julie at the prison
door.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tumultuous day for Julie, Debb King said. She didn't
realize she was leaving prison until officers came to her cell and
told her to pack her bags. She seemed shocked to see the Kings at
the door, and was crying. But she also gave them big hugs.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a tumult of activity, King said: a drive to a
probation office, where Barnes signed papers agreeing to the
conditions of her bail; a press conference at her lawyers' office,
where the cameras intimidated her.
</P>
<P>
   But by mid-afternoon, she was in the Kings' car, calm and
cheery. Tim King was showing her how the gadgets on the dashboard
worked. They stopped at a gas station, and Barnes spotted a dog.
``Hey, look at the doggie!'' she cried out, and went over to pet
it.
</P>
<P>
   Into the cellphone, Barnes yelled that she felt ``good right
now. At least I'm out of Framingham.''
</P>
<P>
   And Debb King said she, too, felt relived that the months-long
campaign was over. Now, she said, she wants to ``try to go home and
find a normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a long road to their destination, Ellsworth, Maine, where
Debb King runs a travel agency and Tim King is city manager. Once
there, the first order of business will be shopping, Debb King
said; Barnes has no clothes except for the sweatshirt and jeans she
was given in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But soon, there will be serious work to do: connecting Barnes to
social service programs that will teach her life skills. Some of
the training might help her care for Joshua, the baby boy she
delivered in prison last month.
</P>
<P>
   The baby is now in foster care, and the Kings say they will work
with the state Department of Social Services to determine what's
best for his future.
</P>
<P>
   And a most important task will come a week from Saturday, Debb
King said. Jennifer King is away from home _ for the first time
ever _ working as a counselor's aide in a summer camp. She doesn't
realize her sister is coming to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   So her parents plan to surprise her. When they drive to camp to
pick her up, they said, they will bring Julie along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
