<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-DIONGLOVER0715-CO     07-14 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DIONGLOVER0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glover out to prove himself
 &HT;    By Monique Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two years ago, magazine covers touted Dion Glover as
the next superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as quickly as his departure from Georgia Tech, everyone
turned the page.
</P>
<P>
   Glover was left behind to recover from tearing the anterior
cruciate and medial collateral ligaments in his left knee at the
beginning of his sophomore season at Tech. Even though he did not
play one minute of basketball that year, Glover was picked 20th
overall by the Hawks in the 1999 draft.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 guard has been surviving on potential to this
point. Granted, he was one of Tech's leading scorers while he was
there and was 1997's Mr. Georgia Basketball at Cedar Grove High.
</P>
<P>
   But now he wants to receive accolades in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to prove to myself I belong here,'' Glover said. ``I
never want to feel complacent. I have to prove to me and to
everyone else this is where I belong.''
</P>
<P>
   Going from being one of Tech's leading scorers in the 1997-98
season (18.4 points 5 rebounds a game) to averaging 6.5 points a
game his rookie season with the Hawks was something Glover had
never been through before.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time in his career that he wasn't a
starter,'' said Karl McCray, one of Glover's AAU coaches during his
high school days. ``Everybody knew he had extraordinary talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone just wanted to see how he would respond to his knee
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover recovered from the injury with little trouble, but said
he had to adjust to playing against quicker, bigger and smarter
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Against the New York Knicks in March, Glover said he could only
watch as he was faked out and left ``picking my face up off the
ground,'' by a quick move to the basket. He had nine points
(3-for-6) in that game, which the Hawks lost. But it was a part of
his learning experience to become quicker and stronger, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It would be an experience he would have to learn primarily from
the bench. Glover played in 30 games, averaging 4.9 minutes last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Glover has started both games in the Hawks Summer Shootout and
has been the Hawks' leading scorer, averaging 20.5 points.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie guard Scoonie Penn said it has been an experience helping
Glover create opportunities on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dion Glover is a great penetrator and he likes to get into
position where he can create and get to the basket. That's how he's
effective,'' Penn said.
</P>
<P>
   Glover said he hopes that effectiveness lasts into the regular
season. It is an attitude first-year coach Lon Kruger said he hopes
extends to the entire team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should all feel that way and that's the nature of
being a better basketball player,'' Kruger said. ``Dion has worked
hard this summer and he's making progress. As Dion says, he just
has to keep working hard at it, and that's a good attitude to have
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of having the world handed to him, Glover said he is
working to return to his old form.
</P>
<P>
   ``My knee is 100 percent right now,'' Glover said. ``It feels
great, and I'm feeling more comfortable. I just need to get the
confidence mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be ready. I'm always ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
