<SLUG> BC-PROFESSOR-PAY0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia bests rest of South in professor pay
 &HT;    By James Salzer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The salary gap between college faculty in the South
and the rest of the country has continued to widen over the past
decade, but Georgia has bucked the trend, according to a new report
by the Southern Regional Education Board.
</P>
<P>
   The average faculty salary at a four-year Georgia university in
1998-99 was $56,251, less than $700 below the $56,916 national
average, the SREB report said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, University System of Georgia Chancellor Stephen
Portch said there are signs Georgia is slipping in its ability to
recruit top faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a crisis mode,'' Portch said, but added, ``It's
something we're going to have to pay attention to.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's ranking among SREB's 16 states _ running from Delaware
south and west to Texas _ rose from 7th to 5th in university
faculty salaries and climbed from 96 percent of the national
average to 99 percent in the past 10 years, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   At $42,141, faculty salaries at two-year schools in Georgia also
rose from 7th to 5th among SREB states, and from 93 percent to 94
percent of the national average.
</P>
<P>
   The university averages include professors, associate
professors, assistant professors and instructors.
</P>
<P>
   As a region, the report said, salaries at four-year schools fell
from 94 percent of the national average in 1988-89 to 93 percent in
1998-99, and from 92 percent to 87 percent of the national average
at two-year schools during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Marks, author of the report, said the regional trend is a
reflection of what's been happening nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing that's been going on is nationwide, faculty
salaries have been playing catch-up,'' he said. ``The reason the
region has not been faring as well is we are chasing a moving
target.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1970s and 1980s, he said, faculty salaries did
not keep pace with inflation, so schools have been making up for
lost time in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said, college enrollment increases in the South meant
states have had to put more money into providing education and
services. Other areas of the country where enrollment has remained
stagnant or declined may have had more money available to fund pay
hikes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When adjusted for inflation, faculty in some states, such as
Texas, Tennessee and Florida, have lost ground in the past 10
years, the report suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is one of the few SREB states that have gained on the
national average at both four-year and two-year schools. Much of
the state's success can be attributed to 6 percent annual pay hikes
pushed through the General Assembly by former Gov. Zell Miller
during his final term, from 1995 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   His successor, Gov. Roy Barnes, has won approval for more modest
pay raises of 4 percent and 3 percent during his first two
legislative sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly have significantly improved (over 10 years), but
we have slid a little bit,'' Portch said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia faculty salaries had climbed to 2nd in the SREB _ behind
Virginia _ a few years ago. But the chancellor said when the SREB
added high-paying Delaware, Georgia fell behind North Carolina and
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Portch said the market for top faculty is becoming increasingly
competitive. He met with system presidents this week and said they
told him stories of having computer science hires ask for more
money between the time they accepted a job and started work because
they'd gotten more job offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we ask (presidents) is a very honest question: How's your
recruiting been going and how's your retention of top faculty?''
Portch said. ``We're beginning to feel some slippage. Two years
ago, when I asked that question of presidents, they said they got
their first choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
