<HEADER>
A2521 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-WACO-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      07-14 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY VERDICT LAYS BLAME FOR WACO SIEGE ON BRANCH DAVIDIANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The Branch Davidians brought death upon
themselves, a federal court jury said Friday in a nonbinding
verdict that vindicated the U.S. government of wrongdoing in the
1993 siege at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing a month of testimony, the five-member advisory
panel spent 2 1/2 hours behind closed doors before concluding that
federal agents acted reasonably in the initial raid and didn't
cause the fatal fire that ended the 51-day standoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this shows is that the responsibility for the tragedy
that happened at Waco is with David Koresh and the Branch
Davidians,'' said U.S. Attorney Michael Bradford of Beaumont, who
is leading the government's defense in a $675 million wrongful
death lawsuit brought by surviving members of the religious sect
and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to put this to rest and move on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The jury said agents of the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms did not use excessive force or fire indiscriminately when
they raided the sect's rural headquarters on Feb. 28, 1993 to serve
search and arrest warrants &UR;  &LR; for weapons charges &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jurors also said the Federal Bureau of Investigation was within
its authority to use tanks to plow into the compound and insert
tear gas in the final hours of the siege on April 19, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The panel concluded that the FBI was not negligent for failing
to position firefighters near the complex when it erupted in
flames. A plan to call on nearby communities in case of fire was
sufficient, the jurors determined.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter Smith said he will take the
``advisory'' jury's verdict into account as he continues
deliberating allegations of government negligence and other issues
raised by the Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   The jury verdict answered five questions posed by Smith. After
they delivered the verdict form, the jurors quickly left the
courthouse. The judge said they did not want to answer reporters'
questions. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Although Smith said he can use the verdict ``in any manner I
see fit,'' lawyers for the Davidians said the findings probably
won't be discarded by the judge, whom they had fought to keep from
trying the case because he presided when five sect members were
convicted on weapons charges in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a practical matter, when you get a verdict, it's over, at
least with Judge Smith,'' said Davidians' lawyer Michael Caddell of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no judgment against the government issued by
Judge Smith. I wouldn't be foolish enough to suggest otherwise,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell also said that for most people, the verdict will end a
seven-year debate about alleged government misconduct at Mount
Carmel. Caddell said the nearly 300 guns found at Mount Carmel
probably swayed the jury more than any other evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having that quantity of weaponry this close to Waco is just
too much for them,'' Caddell speculated.
</P>
<P>
   Special Counsel John Danforth, appointed by Attorney General
Janet Reno to oversee an independent investigation into the
standoff and fire, declined comment. It is unclear when his probe
will be finished.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he hopes to resume the trial on Aug. 2 to take up a
question that wasn't put to the five-member jury: whether federal
agents fired on the compound when it was engulfed in flames.
</P>
<P>
   That debate was postponed because a court-appointed expert was
unavailable to analyze infrared videos taken during the fire that
could show whether there was FBI gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   The government maintains that no shots were fired by its agents
on the final day of the siege. And a May 19 simulation of the event
by a British firm seemed to support their account. Vector Data
Systems said it believed the flecks of light on the infrared tape
were caused by sunlight glinting off of debris, not government
gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments, Bradford called the siege a ``terrible
tragedy,'' in part because four ATF agents were killed on the first
day. But he said the deaths of the Davidians were their own fault
because they could have surrendered at any time and weren't
prevented from leaving the compound when fuel-fed fires broke out
at three locations.
</P>
<P>
   The government lawyer said Davidian plaintiffs were ``trying to
distance themselves from David Koresh, and who could blame them?''
Bradford painted Koresh as a ``psychopath'' who claimed to be Jesus
Christ and so dominated his followers that they ``had to get
permission to kill themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing the inventory of weapons, including dozens of fully
automatic rifles, grenades and armor-piercing ammunition, Bradford
said Koresh had been preparing for ``a war'' for a long time.
``That's what they wanted that day when the ATF showed up at Mount
Carmel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government disputed the Davidians' contention that the
decision to penetrate the structure with tanks, ostensibly to open
exit paths for Davidians as well as inject tear gas, was a
departure from the plans approved by Reno.
</P>
<P>
   She approved of subjecting the Davidians to up to 48 hours of
tear gassing before reassessing the situation. The Reno-approved
plan provided for any emergency response to fire to come from
Bellmeade and Waco, but neither fire department had units nearby
when the blaze consumed the compound.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bradford told jurors that ``Davidians were still firing
their weapons out of the compound while the fire was going on,'' so
even if firefighters were there, they wouldn't have been allowed
inside.
</P>
<P>
   But plaintiffs' lawyer Ramsey Clark, a former U.S. attorney
general, insisted the Davidians ``didn't want to burn themselves
down. What they did was endure six hours of unbelievable government
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the large stockpile of weapons, Clark said the guns were
bought and sold legally for profit and we not part of a ``war
theory. That's absolutely absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark told jurors that unless they ruled against the government,
``no one will be free from the violence of our government. It has
to be stopped,'' he pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   And after the verdict was rendered, survivor Clive Doyle reacted
bitterly, saying, ``The American people need to be praying they're
not next on the (government's) list. You better hope you're not on
the receiving end of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell had portrayed the Davidians as unusual but nonviolent,
except for Koresh and a few devoted followers known as Mighty Men.
He said most Davidians were overcome with panic at the end of the
siege but were not bent on mass suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said no ``emergency'' forced the FBI to act, and he
chastised the agency for departing from a plan to pump tear gas
into the compound for two days. ``They should have let them sit in
it for 48 hours. They (FBI) wanted it (surrender) now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the ensuing fire a ``holocaust,'' Caddell said Davidians
``couldn't get out. By the time they realized the fire had begun,
it was too late.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said Davidians who huddled in a concrete bunker were
``trapped'' and were compelled to kill their children and commit
suicide. If he saw a trapped child's skin peeling off from heat,
Caddell said, ``I would take that child's life and I would take
mine as quickly as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidian lawyers agreed that some of the government agents acted
properly, even bravely. Caddell singled out the heroics of FBI
agent James McGee, who entered the burning structure to extract
Davidian Ruth Ottoman Riddle, carrying her to safety even after she
refused to tell McGee where the children were hiding _ in a
concrete bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saddest thing about this case,'' Caddell said, ``is that
there will be another David Koresh.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
