<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2528 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-INFECTION16-COX     07-14 2759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFECTION16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diseases conference to target complacency
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An international corps of scientists who will gather in Atlanta
this evening has a long list of enemies to talk about: HIV,
malaria, tuberculosis, influenza, and exotic emerging infections
such as West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   But the chief opponent being targeted by the second
International Conference on Emerging Infectious Diseases is
complacency _ the widely held, and completely inaccurate, belief
that infections pose no threat to the industrialized world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Infectious diseases are just not thought of as a major issue
in developed countries,'' said Dr. James Hughes, director of the
National Center for Infectious Diseases at the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention. ``People forget that infectious diseases
are the leading cause of death worldwide and the third-leading
cause of death in this country. Legionnaires' disease, AIDS and the
re-emergence of TB have reminded us repeatedly that we do not have
infectious diseases under control.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference, co-sponsored by CDC, the American Society for
Microbiology and the World Health Organization, brings 2,500
researchers and public health specialists to the Marriott Marquis
to examine successes and failures.
</P>
<P>
   Major topics on the agenda include foodborne diseases, such as
the E.coli O157:H7 that sickened hundreds in Ontario in May and
June; insect-borne diseases, such as resurgent malaria and the
tick-borne erlichiosis that recently surfaced in Atlanta; and
animal diseases that unexpectedly cross to humans, such as West
Nile virus, which was never seen in this hemisphere before last
summer. On Wednesday afternoon, there will be a special session on
West Nile, which scientists fear will spread from New York, where
it was first identified, via migrating birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lot of information presented at this
conference that people will not have heard before,'' Hughes said.
``Much of it has not yet been published. It will be very current.''
</P>
<P>
   Other topics under discussion are the ongoing trend toward
antibiotic resistance among disease organisms; the effects of
climate change, and movements of large groups due to war or
economic change, on the development of disease; and the potential
use of pathogens as weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The conference opens on the heels of a major international
dispute over infectious disease. Throughout the International AIDS
Conference, held last week in Durban, South Africa, South African
President Thabo Mbeki has maintained that HIV may not be the cause
of AIDS and that AZT, a primary drug in AIDS treatment, may not be
as useful against the virus as believed.
</P>
<P>
   In response, 5,000 scientists and physicians signed a protest
letter, now known as the ``Durban declaration,'' that was published
in the scientific journal Nature. Bruce Levin, an evolutionary
biologist at Emory University, was one of the signers of the
declaration. He will speak at the Atlanta conference this week,
presenting research into the twin influences of ecology and
evolution on the emergence of HIV/AIDS as a human disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pragmatic understanding of when and how new i Three thousand
miles away, Niko's 29-year-old brother, Pano Karatassos Jr., takes
a boning knife to a pig's head in the name of gastronomy. He cuts
away the plates of the skull, rolls and ties the remainder in
cheesecloth, and proceeds to prepare a rarefied pig pate called
``tete de cochon.''
</P>
<P>
   As a chef de partie at the French Laundry _ the Napa Valley,
Calif., restaurant called the nation's ``most exciting'' by The New
York Times _ Pano Jr. manages the meat station. For a lunch shift,
he wakes up at 4 a.m. to ready a dozen astonishing dishes _ from
sweetbread-stuffed rabbit shoulder with caramelized salsify, to
veal heart confit with brussels sprout leaves, to a comparatively
straightforward pan-roasted squab with baby turnips, prunes and
foie gras. His muscular 5-foot, 8-inch frame clad in chef's whites
and a blue apron, he anchors a team of identically dressed cooks in
an expansivnature. ``Pano's the most like my dad. He can be anal.''
</P>
<P>
   During the summers, family vacations became eating expeditions,
used as research for new restaurants. ``Whenever we'd go on a trip
it was, `When are we going to eat?' and then, `When are we going to
eat again?''' recalls Pano Jr. ``Sitting down at a restaurant was
playing fill-in-the-blanks because everyone had to order something
different. My brother and I used to race each other to order
first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We always over-ordered,'' Pano Sr. recalls. ``I had this table
full of little kids eating escargot and sweetbreads.''
</P>
<P>
   The kids also spent summers working in their father's
restaurants, which were numbering a half-dozen by the end of the
1980s. Niko and Pano Jr. began as prep cooks. One summer, Niko
joined his dad on the floor of Pano's and Paul's as an assistant
waiter.
</P>
<P>
   Pano Jr. quickly graduated from prep cook to pantry cook,
plating salads and desserts. The summer after 10th grade, he got
his first job on the line at the Fish Market at Lenox (the
precursor to the Atlanta Fish Market), preparing hot entrees. By
the summer after 12th grade, he graduated to the saute station _
the hardest one on the line.
</P>
<P>
   On one trip to New York, the family ate at Le Bernardin, a
French seafood restaurant that had taken America by storm. Young
Pano was ushered into the kitchen to meet the great chef Gilbert Le
Coze, now deceased. He saw the expanses of stainless steel, the
cadre of cooks and the immaculate seafood. And he knew that cooking
would be more than a summer job.
</P>
<P>
   GROWING UP
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT
</P>
<P>
   Pano Sr. says the successful restaurateur must live by his work
ethic and never forget he is a servant to his customers. So,
naturally, he did everything he could to dissuade his kids from the
restaurant business. He wanted better for them.
</P>
<P>
   Karatassos grew up in the back of his father's deli in Savannah,
a small grocery store with a short-order restaurant. The shelves
were perfectly stacked at all times, each can in its precise place.
The air was pungent with the competing odors of dried beans and
salt cod. Never comfortable in their adopted home, the parents
didn't allow their children out into the city, so young Pano and
his siblings stayed close to the store at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Karatassos could never please his severe father, also named
Pano. Even if he swept the sidewalk in front of the door he would
be upbraided for doing a poor job.
</P>
<P>
   The shop would one day belong to the son, as his father
constantly reminded him. Pulling his son by the ear, the father
would bring him to the counter and show him the key to the door.
``This key is waiting for you,'' he gravely reminded him in Greek.
The son nodded _ and at 17 left home to join the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   A gig as ship's cook persuaded him to pursue a career at the
Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, N.Y. For the next few
years, he cooked in resorts in the United States and Europe.
Although his career in food service was shaping up, his father gave
him no encouragement. When he returned to Savannah, the father
looked at his new clothes in contempt and huffed that he still had
a perfectly good suit that was 25 years old.
</P>
<P>
   In his early days, before he made the jump from the kitchen to
the dining room, Karatassos worked for Klaus Fritsch, who later
founded the Morton's of Chicago restaurant chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to be perfect with Pano,'' Fritsch recalls. ``He didn't
do anything halfway. There was no gray. It was black or white. Dead
or alive. Right or wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Albrecht, his former partner, agrees that Karatassos ``had a
European work ethic. He was very strict. He never let his guard
down for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Not one to delegate, Karatassos was involved in every decision
in the early days of the company. If he saw a waiter doing
something slightly wrong, Albrecht recalls, ``he'd correct it right
on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Karatassos' stature grew in the Atlanta restaurant community as
he opened one smash success after another. As the company expanded
throughout the 1980s, it moved away from the Continental
fine-dining model of Pano's and Paul's, 103 West and Capriccio (the
formal precursor to Pricci) and into the more casual terrain of the
Buckhead Diner and Atlanta Fish Market, the latter accompanied by a
65-foot sculpture of a leaping salmon that some equated to the size
of his ego.
</P>
<P>
   While Karatassos' detractors point out that his restaurants are
not original (wasn't the chrome fantasy of Buckhead Diner a clever
reworking of San Francisco's Fog City Diner?), he freely admits
that he shops for concepts and sits on them until he thinks Atlanta
is ready. ``I've always had a feeling how far you could take the
Atlanta market,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Karatassos has taken Atlanta further than anyone might
have imagined. Along the way he became active in charitable giving,
and under his leadership, Atlanta's chapter of Share Our Strength
raises more money to fight hunger than any in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   At some point during the company's growth, Karatassos learned to
better control his legendary temper and to delegate more. ``My
father's had to change his managerial style,'' says Niko. ``His `my
way or the highway' approach didn't get the best results. He had to
learn to listen to people and support them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Karatassos has never relaxed enough to sit down to a
meal at Pano's and Paul's. ``I couldn't do it. I'd keep thinking,
`What would my father say if he saw me sitting down with a napkin
tucked in my shirt?''' Though his father has been dead for more
than a decade, his ghost still hovers.
</P>
<P>
   And he has solidified a reputation in some quarters as a
ruthless competitor. Some former business associates refused to
discuss the dissolution of their dealings with him, or would do so
only off the record. Albrecht admits that their partnership
eventually went sour. ``When the business grew, I think things got
a little lopsided. The way we left it was a little rough. Attorneys
got involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But Albrecht and everyone else agree on one thing: Karatassos
has always been a great father.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Pano Karatassos couldn't dissuade any of his kids
from going into the restaurant business. All three graduated from
the School of Hospitality Management at Florida International
University, and at their father's insistence, went to work at a
Fort Lauderdale branch of Houston's to learn the value of
consistency. Anne was the hostess, Niko the bartender and Pano a
line cook.
</P>
<P>
   And then they joined the family company.
</P>
<P>
   THE LINE CONTINUES
</P>
<P>
   Anne went to work in the payroll department at Buckhead Life.
She married Peter Symbas, a physician, and earlier this month gave
birth to the family's first grandchild, a girl. Her name was
decided by family fiat. Several months before the baby's birth,
Niko said, ``We're going to name her Georgia, after my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Niko had plenty of back-of-the-house experience in the kitchen,
but his obvious aptness was in customer relations. So he worked
through the front of the house, landing as an assistant floor
manager at Pricci. At this glam-packed Italian restaurant, he
served the cream of Atlanta society and industry. Twice he rescued
choking customers with the Heimlich maneuver. One woman was
beginning to lose color when he spotted her. ``We had her food
replaced and she was eating again in five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   When Buckhead Life opened BluePointe, its most ambitious and
expensive contemporary restaurant to date, Niko was named general
manager. This may be his test: From the beginning he has been
besieged with complaints of overbooking and late seatings due to
the restaurant's enormous popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he is not the kind of manager to correct service on the
spot. When he heard a waiter telling a customer, ``You look like a
merlot drinker,'' he made a mental note. The next day he brought up
the issue at the daily service meeting, not to embarrass the waiter
but to encourage input. Together, the staff decided that servers
shouldn't stereotype customers.
</P>
<P>
   Pano Jr. spent a year in Atlanta after college cutting fish at
the Fish Market during the day and working on the line at 103 West
in the evening. But he wanted a grounding in classical French
stocks and sauces, and so he set off to the Culinary Institute of
America.
</P>
<P>
   Before Pano Jr. graduated, his father, who was on the board of
the institute, flew up to join his son in a cooking demonstration.
It didn't go 100 percent well. Pano Jr. drove his father crazy with
his compulsive lining up of dish towels and utensils. Pano Sr.,
with his showman's personality, tried to take over. The event may
not have been a bonding time for father and son, but Pano Sr. left
thinking, ``I knew he had arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   After school, Pano Jr. married Angela King, the daughter of
Atlanta real estate developer and former Georgia Tech football hero
Kim King. Instead of returning to Atlanta, he set out to get the
best culinary education that money, ambition, determination and
intellectual curiosity could buy. He first returned to the place of
his epiphany, Le Bernardin, and spent a year and a half in this
``extremely intense'' four-star kitchen, working under chef Eric
Ripert. He worked every station in the kitchen. ``I learned how
seafood should be handled and produced. If Le Bernardin taught me
one thing, it was simplicity.''
</P>
<P>
   After that he moved to another four-star New York restaurant,
Jean-Georges. Chef Jean-Georges Vongerichten created spontaneous
menus each morning, devising brilliant combinations of spice that
he expected the cooks to master with scant training for the lunch
service. ``It was a challenge working for him, trying to understand
his food,'' says Pano. ``We'd see him drinking his coffee and
writing his menu, and we just wanted to rip it out of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jean-Georges always said he wanted his food `sexy.' His
cooking is about glamour.''
</P>
<P>
   Simplicity. Glamour. What could be next?
</P>
<P>
   THE RIGHT FIT
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Pano Jr. flew to California to work for chef Thomas
Keller of the French Laundry. ``His philosophy and his kitchen was
exactly what I was after. There's a huge intermingling between the
cooks, and a communication in the kitchen built on organization and
doing things right. There's a huge desire to be the best. Every day
we ask how can we better ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French Laundry is all about finesse.''
</P>
<P>
   Pano Jr. talks candidly about his ``perfectionist'' nature.
Every day he puts out his clothes for the next. He keeps his car
perfect. He cannot bear the stress of rushing or looking for
things. Admittedly, he drives his wife crazy.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also his philosophy of cooking and life. ``There's no
need to rush something you want to be good, whether in the
restaurant or my career. There's one right way to do everything. I
get it from my grandfather. But Dad, he's like that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   After the French Laundry, Pano Jr. is considering a move to
France to work in a Michelin three-star establishment, and his
father will wait and see. ``Sometimes I get concerned that Pano
will be in this bubble _ the Thomas Kellers, the Jean-Georgeses.
But when he's ready to have his restaurant, we're going to talk
through it. He wants to do his own thing and certainly will get the
support from me. And Niko will be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pano Jr. and Niko look forward to the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta's my home,'' says Pano Jr. ``And I plan to be there
when this whole thing comes full circle.''
</P>
<P>
   PANO
</P>
<P>
   KARATASSOS JR.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Age: 29
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: Graduate of Florida International University School
of Hospitality Management and the Culinary Institute of America.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Experience: Worked as a cook through high school at Buckhead
Life Restaurants; recently cooked at Le Bernardin and Jean-Georges
in New York City (both four-star restaurants); currently at the
French Laundry in Yountville, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Personal: Married to the former Angela King, daughter of
Atlanta developer Kim King.
</P>
<P>
   NICHOLAS
</P>
<P>
   `NIKO'
</P>
<P>
   KARATASSOS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Age: 28
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: Graduate of Florida International University School
of Hospitality Management.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Experience: Worked as cook and waiter through high school at
Buckhead Life Restaurants; recently assistant manager at Pricci;
currently general manager at BluePointe.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Personal: Single.
</P>
