<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2546 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FALCONS0713-COX     07-14 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS0713-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eyes on Anderson
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Dallas Neil got plowed under by the ``Hit of
the day'' at Friday's first day of Falcons' camp. But it's Jamal
Anderson everybody wants to know about.
</P>
<P>
   The former All-Pro running back, out 14 games last season with a
torn anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee, was slightly
limited while in pads for the first time since suffering the injury
Sept. 20 in a game at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a little bit of soreness,'' he said, ``but it's not the
tendinitis situation (that bothered him last month). So far, so
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson didn't get popped nearly as hard as Neil, the undrafted
rookie punter/tight end from Montana.
</P>
<P>
   But he made a mental note of the blast from linebacker Keith
Brooking that knocked him off his feet near the end of the
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Up to then, Anderson had taken a few harmless knocks.
</P>
<P>
   After bouncing outside left on a running play in non-tackling
drills, he lowered his head and butted cornerback Ashley Ambrose
helmet-to-helmet.
</P>
<P>
   He barely had time to see Brooking coming.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage to Brooking.
</P>
<P>
   The third-year pro from Georgia Tech dropped his shoulders and
hit Anderson's right torso, sending the runner heels _ and knees _
over head.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson went skidding out of bounds on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you I was going to have a problem with Keith Brooking
and look what the guy did to me,'' Anderson said, smiling. ``But it
was fun to get back out here and get the pads cracking.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooking said, ``He was giving his fair share of hits so I
figured I should get him back. Maybe he needed that little hit to
give him some confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson wants more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keith caught me from on the side, which is cool because those
hits you don't see until the last second . . . are the ones that
will prepare your knee,'' he said. ``You don't know, will it buckle
or will it hold up? Today it held up.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Dan Reeves, who has vowed this would be a more physical
training camp than last, was smiling. Really.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day was extremely good,'' he said. ``Jamal looked
good and I think that made all of us feel a lot better. I saw him
take some licks and he was cutting. The fact he was able to do it
without any pain is a huge improvement over a few weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hit the blocking sled just once and didn't participate
in fumble drills or conditioning. He'll participate in one of
today's two practices.
</P>
<P>
   Neil will be available for both. For a few seconds Friday, that
was in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   After catching a pass, he turned toward the left sideline and
headed upfield. He never saw reserve safety Gerald McBurrows coming
full speed.
</P>
<P>
   Neil _ who months ago sent a self-promotional package to teams
with a mannequin's leg and a note saying, ``I'd give my left leg to
play for you'' _ nearly lost a couple limbs. ``I guess that was my
wake-up call to the NFL,'' Neil said. ``You got to get up; you
can't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   After the play, the undrafted rookie jogged to the huddle and
patted McBurrows on the rear, ``to let `em know I'm coming back,''
he said. One problem: It was defensive end Emil Ekiyor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
