<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH PENALTY LIVES ON AS THORN IN BUSH'S SIDE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETH, N.J. _ The execution of Gary Graham haunted
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush Friday, as
anti-death penalty hecklers interrupted one of his speeches and a
guest at a community center event accused him of acting politically
instead of morally.
</P>
<P>
   While anti-death penalty pressure on the Texas governor faded
rapidly two years ago after the execution of pickax murderer Karla
Faye Tucker, the protests over Graham's execution last month have
marred several of Bush's events this week.
</P>
<P>
   Four protesters were removed from Bush's speech to the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People convention on
Monday. Two more were ejected Friday as Bush spoke to a
Conservative Party fund-raiser in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop the racist death penalty!'' the pair shouted, waving
posters bearing Graham's picture before being forcibly ejected from
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about America is a man gets to express his
opinion,'' Bush told the crowd after the protesters were thrown
out. ``I don't have to take polls or focus groups to determine my
job should be to uphold the laws of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, as Bush promoted faith-based social services
at the Elizabethport Presbyterian Center, the Rev. Joseph Garlic
lectured Bush on the fairness of the justice system for blacks.
Garlic said Bush should have stopped Graham's execution last month
because of doubts about Graham's guilt in a 1981 Houston murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talked this morning about love and giving people an
opportunity, and I think the doubt that surrounded the case of Gary
Graham gave you an opportunity to show some compassion and love in
a way that had not been shown,'' Garlic said.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic, who is black, said Bush tried to show earlier this week
that he was a different kind of Republican by talking to the NAACP.
But he said Bush also should have been aware that justice sometimes
is unequal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read somewhere where you said you trusted the criminal
justice system. At the same time, I think you are aware,
particularly as it relates to black people, justice has not always
been fair,'' Garlic said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended his actions in the Graham case, saying he believes
the death penalty saves lives through deterrence and that it is his
job to carry out the laws of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the death penalty,'' Bush said. ``It's not an easy
decision to make . . . This is not a political decision for me,
reverend. If it costs me votes, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Garlic responded that Bush had acted politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a political decision, because there are other ways to
punish criminals other than the death penalty,'' Garlic said.
``While you say it was not a political decision, it definitely was
not a moral decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush cut Garlic off by saying the pair simply disagree.
</P>
<P>
   While at the Elizabethport center, Bush proposed a program to
give $400 million in vouchers to help low-income parents defray the
cost of putting their children into after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's home state, the Texas Education Agency awarded $10.6
million to 71 school districts last November for programs designed
to keep middle-school children out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In January, it awarded another $85 million to be divided among
234 school districts for programs aimed at preventing freshmen from
dropping out of high school. Although districts were not required
to use that money for after-school programs, some did.
</P>
<P>
   Most after-school programs are funded at the local level, said
TEA spokeswoman Debbie Graves Ratcliffe.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bush had breakfast with New York Gov. George
Pataki at the airport Hilton in Newark, N.J. Aides confirmed the
two discussed Pataki's chances of becoming Bush's running mate.
They have been friends since attending Yale University together in
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compassionate conservative politics are going to work for
America when Governor Bush becomes president,'' Pataki later told
the New York Conservative Party while introducing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush praised Pataki as a friend but never hinted to the crowd
that he might be under consideration as a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also praised U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio, the New York GOP nominee
for U.S. Senate. Bush poked fun at Lazio's Democratic opponent,
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, for not being a native New
Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   (Kathy Walt in the Chronicle Austin Bureau contributed to this
story.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
