u r BC-TOUR0715-COX     07-14 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBy Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRAGUIGNAN, France _ A quick Tour de France trivia question:
When was the last time that the rider who wore the overall leader's
yellow jersey failed to pick up a single stage victory on his way
to the finish line in Paris? American Greg LeMond is the last
champion to own that distinction of no stage wins. He never stood
on the stage winner's podium back in 1990, yet he beat Italy's
Claudio Chiapucci by 2 minutes, 16 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   If Austin's Lance Armstrong maintains his ways this year, he'll
join LeMond.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has four second-place finishes through 13 stages of
this year's Tour, yet he also owns a dominating 4 minute and 55
second lead over German Jan Ullrich, the only rider who holds any
hope of catching the American.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, most of the yellow jersey contenders were content to
allow the French riders, some of whom sported blue, white and red
wheels and spokes, to take the spotlight on Bastille Day, France's
national day of liberation.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong finished in the peloton, the main group of riders, as
the cyclists cut through Provence and toward the Alps. He was 27th,
10:06 behind stage victor Vicente Garcia-Acosta. Ullrich, the 1997
Tour champion, finished with the same time as Armstrong, but was
22nd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance is not out to win stages right now,'' said Chris
Carmichael, Armstrong's long-time private coach. ``He rode today to
stay out of trouble. He really just needed to be safe. He's not
focused on the daily battles, he's focused on winning the entire
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong described Friday's stage as very stressful.
</P>
<P>
   ''These stages in between the mountains are really hard,''
Armstrong said. ''They're difficult. They're not really flat like
the first week. They're rolling and everybody is moving at a faster
speed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look, this thing is far from over. Tomorrow (today) is the
largest and longest stage. We'll see where we are Sunday night. The
next two days are critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was closely guarded by his U.S. Postal Service
teammates, who formed a shield in front of him for much of the
afternoon. U.S. Postal was one of only five teams still with a full
contingent of nine riders. To celebrate Bastille Day, Cedric
Vasseur, the lone Frenchmen on the American team, was the first
Postal rider to cross the finish line. He was 23rd.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia-Acosta, a Spaniard riding for Team Banesto, spoiled the
French riders' collective attempts at glory on this national
holiday by riding alone for the final seven miles of the stage.
Like all other stage winners, he pumped his fist in the air and
waved to the throngs who lined the route.
</P>
<P>
   Frenchmen Nicolas Jalabert was second, 25 seconds behind. Like
his more famous brother, Laurent, he rides for the Spanish team
ONCE. Pascal Herve, another Frenchman, was third.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong will be one of the favorites to take today's long
stage, which winds from Draguignan to Briancon. The 154.7-mile trek
features three high mountain climbs and will favor riders such as
Armstrong and Marco Pantani, the Italian who won Thursday's stage.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani, the 1998 Tour champion, still was 13th in the overall
standings, 10:26 behind Armstrong. But his victory Thursday made
him an even more popular figure with the Italian media, who swarmed
him before Friday's stage. With today's route coming so close to
Italy, Pantani likely will have more of a home-country advantage
than the French riders.
</P>
<P>
   After today, the riders must endure another mountain stage, with
Sunday's ending at the 6,000-foot summit in Courchevel. Monday is
the Tour's last off day, with the remaining stages gradually
returning to flatter routes before the race concludes in Paris on
July 23.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael said he was ``absolutely'' confident that Armstrong
would maintain his lead through the weekend. But he still remained
cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race is not over _ a lot of things can keep Lance
Armstrong from winning the Tour de France, but I'm not saying he
won't win it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
