<HEADLINE>
SUMMIT CONFEREES TACKLE `INTRACTABLE' MIDEAST ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: In 11th graf, ``today'' refers to Saturday.) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Israeli and Palestinian negotiators slogged
through their fourth day of talks in secret Friday, wrestling with
what U.S. officials characterize as ``intractable issues'' in the
search for Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   While negotiations continued at Camp David, officials hustled to
keep dissidents away from journalists and to keep a lid on details
of what is happening at the mountain retreat.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart dismissed reports that the
Palestinian delegation, led by Yasser Arafat, had threatened to
leave the summit when a proposal by the United States appeared to
favor Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any luggage,'' Lockhart said, acknowledging that
the talks are tense and will only get harder as they continue. At
the same time, he said, he has not seen any deterioration in the
two sides' willingness to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tensions every day when you try to work through
these issues,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with his senior advisers Friday morning after a
late-night round of one-on-one talks with Israel's top negotiator,
Shlomo Ben-Ami, and later with Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, sessions that lasted until 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   About midday, the Israeli, Palestinian and U.S. teams of
negotiators broke into small groups to focus on specific issues
that go to the heart of settling the 52-year Israeli-Palestinian
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   On the table are the status of Jerusalem, the nature and borders
of a Palestinian state, the future of Jewish settlers in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, and whether more than 2 million Palestinian
refugees will be allowed to return to their homes in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Whether either side was showing signs of yielding was not
evident during Lockhart's two briefings for a large group of
international journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are intractable issues,'' he said, ``These are issues
that go to the vital interests of both of the parties. So this is
very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Formal negotiations came to a halt at sundown Friday in
observance of the Jewish Sabbath. Still, Lockhart said, some
informal meetings were likely today but full-scale negotiations are
not expected to resume until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright left the
presidential compound temporarily to meet with a group of
Palestinian leftists in nearby Emmitsburg, Md. The seven were
demanding an audience with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which wants Arafat and Barak to focus on
settling their differences without distractions, did not rule out
the possibility that Arafat could meet the delegation at some
future time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the spirit of the ground rules we've put down, we
indicated that we would prefer that that meeting not happen up at
Camp David,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the seven Palestinians, Tayseer Khaled, refused to meet
with Albright and accused the Americans of interfering in
Palestinian affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refused to go to the meeting with Albright in protest of the
American behavior. This is meddling in Palestinian internal affairs
and the U.S. has no right to do that,'' said Khaled, a member of
the radical Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   American hosts barred Israeli or Palestinian delegation members
from visiting with reporters, and in the second such incident this
week an Israeli official was ushered out of an elementary school
being used as a press room about six miles from Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Limor Livnat, a spokeswoman for Israel's opposition Likud Party,
was asked to leave by State Department officials, then was escorted
from the press facility as she was outlining objections to Barak's
willingness to yield somewhat to Palestinian demands on Jerusalem
and the Jordan Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Before the summit, Barak indicated that he was prepared to allow
the Palestinians a foothold in Jerusalem, where Arafat wants to
locate a Palestinian capital. Barak also signaled that the
strategic Jordan Valley could be turned over to the Palestinians if
they agree to allow Israel to establish early warning facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready for compromises,'' said Livnat, a member of
Israel's Knisset. But Barak, she said, is the nation's first prime
minister who has agreed to discuss ``giving up Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
