<HEADER>
A2594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LOW-BIRTHWEIGHT-ART-N     07-14 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOW-BIRTHWEIGHT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT LINKS FERTILITY AIDS TO SMALL SIZE IN NEWBORNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The proportion of low-birthweight babies, those born weighing
less than 5.5 pounds, has been growing steadily since 1984, a
federal report released Thursday says. Most of the rise can be
attributed to the rapid increase in the number of multiple births,
especially to older white mothers using assisted-reproduction
techniques like in vitro fertilization and drugs that increase
ovulation.
</P>
<P>
   Such techniques often produce twins, triplets or quadruplets,
who are far more likely than single babies to be born prematurely,
and tiny. The number of twin births rose more than 50 percent from
1980 to 1997, while the number of triplets quadrupled _ with white
women older than 45 having the highest rate of multiple births.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multiple births and assisted-reproductive technologies account
for the bulk of the increase in low-birthweight babies,'' said Dr.
Duane Alexander, director of the National Institute of Child Health
and Human Development. ``It's become a substantial concern among
OB-GYNs, who are beginning to step back a little, I think.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, if they get seven healthy fertilized embryos in
an in vitro attempt, they might put two or three back in, not all
seven. The problem is with the older mother, who may have only one
shot at pregnancy and wants them all. And then you get into whose
embryos are these, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks traditionally have had a higher rate of multiple births
than whites. But with more whites turning to assisted reproduction,
that gap has narrowed substantially; white mothers are now more
than twice as likely as blacks or Hispanics to have triplets.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the age of women giving birth has been creeping up;
Massachusetts has become the first state where women older than 30
now make up the majority of new mothers. And older women, overall,
run a higher risk of delivering a low-birthweight baby.
</P>
<P>
   The growing number of low-birthweight babies is intensely
troubling to health policy makers, who have devoted enormous
resources in the last three decades to new programs intended to
offer easy access to prenatal care, in hopes of solving the
low-birthweight problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting back in the 1960s, there were all these programs to
provide care to low-income women earlier in pregnancy, and we
thought it would really make a difference,'' said Alexander. ``The
low-birthweight rate did go down in the '70s, but since the middle
of the 1980s, it's been going up. You have no idea how frustrating
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the latest year for which statistics are available,
low-birthweight babies made up 7.6 percent of the nation's births,
according to the report, ``America's Children: Key National
Indicators of Well Being 2000,'' which was released on Thursday.
While the current rate is not quite as high as the 7.9 percent rate
in 1970, it has climbed substantially since the low of 6.7 percent
reached in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of all logic and expectations, and everything we'd
like to see as policy makers, it's been very difficult to show that
prenatal care can reduce low birthweight,'' said Dalton Conley, a
sociologist at New York University who studies low-birthweight
babies. ``We still assume it makes a difference, but the research
doesn't show the effects.``
</P>
<P>
   Low-birthweight babies are a serious health concern, because
such infants are far more likely to have vision and hearing
impairments, cerebral palsy or impaired intellectual ability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
