<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.C. UNITED NO LONGER AN MLS BULLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Nearly everywhere D.C. United plays a soccer game
these days, coach Thomas Rongen faces the same questions:
</P>
<P>
   What in the world happened?
</P>
<P>
   How did the arrogant Goliath of Major League Soccer turn into a
puppy dog overnight?
</P>
<P>
   Since the league was born in 1996, United has played in the MLS
Cup annually, winning three titles, becoming the envy and target of
every franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But since the Galaxy opened United's season with a 4-0 beating
against the defending champions at RFK Stadium in March, United
hasn't recovered. Each day, week and month since has been a
humbling and humiliating experience for United, which has the
league's worst record.
</P>
<P>
   What little life is left in United will be on display tonight at
the Rose Bowl as the Galaxy attempts to sweep its four-game season
series against the long-time MLS bullies without six starters
because of national team duty.
</P>
<P>
   United's fall from glory is baffling ,if not impossible to
understand. This is basically the same team minus striker Roy
Lassiter that beat the Galaxy 2-0 last October to capture its third
title.
</P>
<P>
   But after Wednesday's 2-2 draw with Tampa Bay, United dropped to
4-13-6 with 18 points. United is 1-4-5 in its last 10 matches and
two of its last three games were 3-0 beatings.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's practice at the Rose Bowl, Rongen shook his head,
stared at the turf and offered a simple explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have under-performed,'' said Rongen. ``You can use the
analogy from the movie `A Perfect Storm': A lot of things at the
same time went haywire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started with under-performing, then there were injuries,
national team and Olympic team duty and then not getting the luck
that good teams normally get.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything collided at one time and we're still trying to
recover from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman nodded his head yes when asked
if he enjoyed United's fall to the worst record in MLS nine points
behind Dallas (8-11-3, 27 points), which holds the eighth and final
playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to wish something bad on anybody, but I think a
lot of people have adverse feelings about how D.C. handles
themselves around the league,'' said Hartman. ``There has been some
ring-waving going on, so yeah, it's hard to feel for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy defender Paul Caligiuri echoed Hartman's feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think deep down inside most of the players in this league
are happy about what's happened to them because they pretty much
stole the show since the league began,'' said Caligiuri. ``I really
can't answer what didn't motivate them to come out and play the way
they have in prior seasons because most of their roster is still
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Rongen admits his team is getting no sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've made 11 coaches and 11 general managers very
happy,'' he said. ``There is no one shedding tears over what has
happened to us, but we expected that. We built a dynasty here, so
regardless of our record, we're the game everyone points to.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustration is mounting.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent loss, midfielder Richie Williams and Rongen were
nose to nose, screaming at each other after Williams was taken out
of a game.
</P>
<P>
   Marco Etcheverry, a two-time MLS MVP and the league's best
playmaker, has lost his cool on occasions. He was ejected the last
time D.C. visited L.A. after taking a nasty swipe at Mauricio
Cienfuegos.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see all the small things start to happen to them and now
it's added up,'' said Hartman. ``Sometimes you see players fighting
with a coach, or this or that. I think they can sense (the season)
starting to get away from them.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean United isn't taking this last stretch of games
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Etcheverry and Jaime Moreno are in town instead of with Bolivia
for a national team game. Even so, United is missing Ben Olsen and
Jeff Agoos because of injuries, along with Raul Diaz Arce (El
Salvador) and Eddie Pope (U.S.), who are with their national teams.
</P>
<P>
   With only nine matches left, Rongen admits United needs to win
nearly all of them to reach the postseason and defend its title.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our last game a lot of guys played with a lot of energy and
a lot of heart,'' said Rongen. ``We've got a huge task ahead of us.
Every game is a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to be in this situation but this is the hole we
have dug for ourselves. We'll just have to find out if we can dig
ourselves out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
