u p BC-GORE-VEEP-NYT     07-14 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE IS MAKING OVERTURES, BUT GEPHARDT IS RESISTING
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Mo., N.Y., Fla., Mass., Maine, Ill., Ind., N.J.) By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Dick Gephardt has emerged high on Al Gore's
list of possible running mates, people close to Gore say. But
there's a big problem: Gephardt's advisers insist that he wants his
name scratched.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the advisers said a Gephardt emissary on Friday
telephoned Warren Christopher, who is leading Gore's search, to
tell him that Gephardt, the House Democratic leader, would not fill
out a detailed questionnaire about his voting record and would not
hand over any financial and personal information because he does
not want to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   The advisers to Gephardt said he had breakfast with Gore last
Saturday at the vice president's residence here _ at Gephardt's
request _ to tell him personally the reasons why Gore should not
pick him.
</P>
<P>
   The main argument was that it would greatly complicate the
Democrats' drive to retake the House. Gephardt also argued that if
Gore became president, he could be more helpful to him in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not in any way trying to be cute,'' said a Gephardt
confidant. ``He would be very happy if they picked someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be, of course, that Gephardt is being cute. His
advisers refuse to declare flatly that he would never take the job
under any circumstances. And Jack Kemp, who was Bob Dole's running
mate four years ago, recalled that he had repeatedly told Dole he
did not want to be picked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Would you be interested in being my running mate?'
'' Kemp said in an interview. ``I said, `Well, I'm flattered but I
don't know that I'm the best running mate. You need an attack dog
and I'm not known as an attack dog.'''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, it seems clear that Gore is seriously interested in
Gephardt. But Gephardt's resistance underscores the difficulty he
may be facing in settling on an appealing choice.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats agree that there seems to be a dearth of options
with sizzle. For all his appeal as a seasoned, respected politician
from the hotly contested state of Missouri, many Democrats said
Gephardt was far from electrifying. And his advisers said he would
rather stay where he is, poised to become speaker if the Democrats
win back the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good people around, but I don't think the
Democratic Party has done a particularly good job of showcasing
them, and we're paying a price for it,'' said Robert Strauss, a
former Democratic national chairman and wise man in the party.
</P>
<P>
   Among others under consideration, according to prominent
Democrats and people close to the process, are Sen. John Kerry of
Massachusetts, Sen. Bob Graham of Florida, former Sen. George
Mitchell of Maine, Sen. Richard Durbin of Illinois and Sen. Evan
Bayh of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Gephardt, it could be, as often happens in
presidential politics, that the Gore campaign is floating his name
as a trial balloon. Who really knows the vice president's
intentions? Probably only Gore and his wife, Tipper, Christopher,
and, maybe, William Daley, the campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Warning of the dangers of all the uninformed speculation,
Michael Whouley, one of Gore's top strategists, said, ``None of the
sirens of conventional wisdom have actually had a conversation with
Apollo.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncertainty, Gore's overtures to Gephardt are being
taken seriously enough that they have set off maneuvering among
House Democrats over who would fill Gephardt's job as the House
Democratic leader and speaker-in-waiting) if he left.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, the No. 2 Democrat, telephoned
reporters Friday to assure them that prospects for House Democrats
would not be jeopardized if he was to serve as the acting leader in
place of Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the leadership in the caucus would rally behind me as
acting leader,'' he said in an interview, ``and we would have a
very close coordinated relationship with the Gore-Gephardt ticket
if that's where all this moves to.''
</P>
<P>
   He would not say what he thought Gephardt should do. In an
interview earlier this summer, Bonior cited Rep. Robert Menendez of
New Jersey and Bill Richardson, the energy secretary, among others
as good possibilities. Asked why he did not mention Gephardt as one
of his favorites, Bonior replied, ``I didn't think it was a real
possibility then.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to Gephardt said he had thought hard about Gore's
entreaties but that they posed a serious quandary for him: would he
be more valuable on the national ticket or helping his party try to
win control of the House? And what about his own ambitions?
</P>
<P>
   Although he has long had designs on the White House, Gephardt,
who is 59, decided not to take on Gore for the nomination this year
so he could devote his efforts to picking up enough House seats to
assure himself of becoming speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's associates said that he would rather be speaker than
vice president but that he recognized either perch could be a
jumping off point for a later bid for president. (But while several
vice presidents have moved up, no speaker has ever advanced
directly to the White House.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Both races are, in my view, a tossup,'' said one person who
has discussed the predicament with Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's interest is understandable. Gephardt has a deep command
of the issues, is popular with many constituency groups like labor,
where Gore still has to do some fence mending. He could also assure
Gore that the ticket would be more competitive in Missouri.
Gephardt is also a seasoned campaigner who would effectively make a
case for the Democrats, and tear down Bush.
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, Gephardt is hardly a fresh face. And he
would contribute to the feel that the ticket is composed of two
longtime Washington insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Already Friday, CNN was broadcasting excerpts of tense moments
between Gore and Gephardt in a debate in 1988. In fact, the two
long had an icy relationship dating back to when they battled each
other that year for the Democratic nomination _ and both lost to
Michael S. Dukakis. But in the last two years, their relationship
has warmed appreciably.
</P>
<P>
   And nominees have never hesitated to turn to foes as running
mates. Dole and Kemp had never been pals. When John Kennedy picked
Lyndon Johnson, their relationship had long been bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rare and wondrous event when something happens such as
a Kennedy picking Johnson and Johnson taking the job, which he
regretted for years,'' said Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
``Oh God, what a torment that was for him!''
</P>
<P>
   Yet no one ever disputed the outcome: Johnson was crucial in
assuring that the Democrats won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
