<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBT0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BB&AMP;T to put its name on 45 Atlanta banks
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Signs of change will be showing up over 45
Atlanta-area banks Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Winston-Salem, N.C.-based BB&AMP;T Corp. will change the signs and
operating systems of the Atlanta-area branches of First Citizens
Corp. and Premier Bancshares, both acquired over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   And while most folks may see the new signs as just another name
on their bank statements, the folks who run or invest in many of
Atlanta's smaller banks may see opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: BB&AMP;T Corp. says it wants to buy or build more banks
totaling at least $2 billion in assets in Georgia, which it sees as
its next logical growth market.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year-and-a-half, BB&AMP;T has acquired five Georgia
banks with $5 billion in assets, including Newnan, Ga.-based First
Citizens in July and Atlanta-based Premier Bancshares in January.
</P>
<P>
   That puts BB&AMP;T in the No. 8 spot both in Georgia and the Atlanta
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be in the top five in the markets we serve,''
said John Allison, BB&AMP;T's chief executive officer. ``We need about
$2 billion in additional assets in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the bank prefers to get there with acquisitions. During
the past 10 years, BB&AMP;T has acquired 45 community banking
companies, bringing itself to $55 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   BB&AMP;T was rumored last week to be interested in Birmingham-based
SouthTrust, which has almost $44 billion in assets and operations
in eight states, including Georgia and the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   But Allison said BB&AMP;T is not interested in a merger of
equal-sized banks or the Alabama market, at least now.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long term, yes. Right now, we're focused on our
footprint,'' he said, referring to growth within its seven-state
territory stretching from Washington, D.C., to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   SouthTrust officials dismissed speculation last week that it is
in talks with BB&AMP;T, according to published reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is the timing is not correct for either company,''
said Christopher Marinac, a Robinson-Humphrey analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Inman, chief executive officer of Tucker Federal Bank, said
he's noticed commercial lending activity has picked up since BB&AMP;T's
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker Federal is part of Tucker-based Eagle Bancshares, which
has $1.2 billion in assets and 14 branches in suburban Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they have been actively recruiting commercial loan
officers,'' said Inman.
</P>
<P>
   He added that a newcomer like BB&AMP;T can probably capture 10
percent of the Atlanta market by concentrating on commercial
customers too small to be targeted by Atlanta's four largest banks,
Bank of America, Wachovia Corp., SunTrust Banks and First Union
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
