<SLUG> BC-OPED-MANNERS-PYLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE MANNERS STILL MATTER
</HEADLINE>
  (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, July 15, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By GEORGE B. PYLE    
 c.2000 New York Times   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALINA, Kan. _ From complaints about impolite cell-phone users
to gripes over bad service at restaurants, it seems that everyone's
gotten a bit prickly over everyone else's manners _ or lack
thereof. This perception that civility is on the decline has taken
hold not only in places often associated with rudeness, like busy
Eastern cities, but also in the supposedly more mannerly cultures
of the South and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   I can't comment on conditions elsewhere, but I would argue that
this so-called rash of incivility has not pervaded the country
completely. Civility in Kansas and the rest of the heartland, for
example, remains intact. It has endured because it comes not so
much from any strict code of etiquette but from a comfortable lack
thereof.
</P>
<P>
   In my 43 years living in the heartland, I can think of only two
instances in which I was the victim of what I consider overt
rudeness. Both were perpetrated by people who were trying to
enforce their own brand of etiquette. Both ran against the relaxed,
live-and-let-live attitude that to me has always seemed the gentle
core of Plains culture.
</P>
<P>
   Both involved my hat.
</P>
<P>
   In third grade, in my hometown of McCook, Neb., I wore my Cub
Scout uniform, cap and all, to school. I was pretty proud of it.
But the principal had only one thing to say: ``Do Cub Scouts wear
their hats in the house?''
</P>
<P>
   It was the only sentence I remember her speaking to me in the
five years I attended that school. I took the hat off, stifling the
urge to tell her we were not in a house.
</P>
<P>
   The second time was in 1984. I was having an early dinner in a
bookstore-coffee shop in the artsy Westport neighborhood of Kansas
City, Mo. It was a warm day, and I was wearing a white Panama hat.
I thought it looked quite jaunty.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of older women rose to leave from a nearby table. As they
passed me, one leaned over and said: ``I must say, I remember a day
when a gentleman would never wear his hat inside a building.''
</P>
<P>
   I left it on, stifling the urge to tell her she was no lady for
insulting a perfect stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Heartland men like John Wayne (from Winterset, Iowa) and Henry
Fonda (from Omaha) would be more likely to have said something
like, ``Well, you do as you please _ just don't get in my way,''
than tell someone that what he or she was doing was impolite _ even
if they generally took their hats off to say it.
</P>
<P>
   Out here in the Plains, we don't get in each other's way much.
As long as that standard is met, friction stays at a minimum. Road
rage is not the rage here _ we don't have to fight for parking
spaces and spend as much time on crowded freeways as other
Americans do.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the Kansas solution to those who are worried about a
decline in civility: Don't worry so much. It only makes you cranky.
</P>
<P>
   (George B. Pyle is the editorial page editor of the Salina
Journal.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
