<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND PATAKI DISCUSS VICE PRESIDENCY, BUT DOUBTS ARE PLENTIFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas met privately
Friday morning with Gov. George Pataki of New York to talk about
the vice presidency, and Republican officials with ties to Pataki's
office said that the hourlong discussion coincided with other signs
that Pataki is being looked at for a spot on the Republican ticket.
</P>
<P>
   None of these officials claimed that Pataki had emerged as the
front-runner in a selection process that has been shrouded in the
utmost secrecy, and others expressed skepticism that Bush would
choose him.
</P>
<P>
   But several Republicans said that aides to Pataki had spent much
of the last week reviewing his record and his past to assist with
the kind of intensive background check that prospective vice
presidential candidates typically undergo.
</P>
<P>
   They also said that Pataki's breakfast meeting with Bush, in a
hotel suite in Newark, N.J., where Bush was campaigning, came after
Pataki had received one of the questionnaires that the Bush
campaign distributed to possible running mates and after the New
York governor had spoken on the telephone several weeks ago with
Richard Cheney, the former defense secretary, who is supervising
the selection process for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Later Friday, after both Bush and Pataki had addressed the New
York Conservative Party in Manhattan, they ate lunch together in a
hotel suite there, Republican officials said. These officials said
they did not know if the second meeting was private, or if it
concerned the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely been a kick-up of activity there,'' said
one Republican official, referring to communications between the
Bush campaign and Pataki's office.
</P>
<P>
   But other prominent Republican officials, some of them close to
Pataki, said that his chances would be hurt by his support for
abortion rights and his recently aggressive advocacy for gun
control. Those positions are not only at odds with the Texas
governor's but also inevitable points of contention with
conservatives in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   They also said there was no evidence that Pataki could help Bush
carry New York state, which is considered nearly a sure winner for
Vice President Al Gore. They said that Bush's meeting with Pataki
on Friday morning, which the Bush campaign made no effort to hide,
could simply have been a gesture intended to flatter Pataki and to
project the image that Bush was openminded about sharing the ticket
with a more moderate Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that it was done as theater,'' said one Republican
official who is close to Pataki. ``Nobody in Austin is talking
about Pataki. And they're not going to take the risk of picking a
pro-choice governor and having the convention become all about
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, confirmed that
Bush and Pataki talked about the vice presidency Friday morning,
but did not provide details. Until now, Pataki's name had been
mostly absent from Republican officials' speculation. Other names
that have been mentioned frequently include Gov. Frank Keating of
Oklahoma, Sens. Fred Thompson and Bill Frist of Tennessee, Sen.
Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, Elizabeth Dole and, more recently, Gov.
James S. Gilmore III of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also campaigned frequently and spoken privately with
Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, a close friend. But many Republican
officials and political analysts say that Ridge and Pataki will
ultimately be passed over because of their support for abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But a Republican official with close ties to Pataki's office
said that the party was so solidly behind Bush that he might be
able to afford the choice of Ridge or Pataki, and that Pataki was
the less controversial of the two. Unlike Ridge, the official
noted, Pataki had not been drawn into bitter disputes with the
Catholic leaders in his state.
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, a senior adviser to Pataki, said Friday that ``the
governor has not and will not talk about any private conversations
he may or may not have had with Governor Bush.'' And Bush and
Pataki, in their remarks to the Conservative Party, simply made
clear that they shared a friendship and a mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the world of George Pataki,'' said Bush, who attended
Yale University at the same time as Pataki and became governor of
Texas the same year that Pataki became governor of New York. ``He's
a really good man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' Bush added, ``the second-best thing that happened
in 1994, in November of 1994, was watching the New York returns
come in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
