<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 BUSH DEFENDS DEATH PENALTY TO RELIGIOUS AUDIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of George W. Bush's campaign events unexpectedly turned into
a debate over the death penalty on Friday, when a black minister
raised questions about the governor's compassion and told him that
a recent execution in Texas was ``not a moral decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprise exchange, in what is usually a highly scripted
campaign, took place at a Presbyterian meeting hall in Elizabeth,
N.J., where Bush had gone to highlight his belief in using
religious institutions to provide social services.
</P>
<P>
   The presumed Republican presidential nominee sat with a mostly
black and Hispanic panel of church leaders, community organizers
and local officials, who had been assembled by his campaign to
discuss how churches provide services. But halfway through the
event, the Rev. Joseph H. Garlic, seated immediately to Bush's
right, changed the subject.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had to ask a sensitive question. ``It is one I could
not live with myself if I did not ask or bring up,'' he said, ``and
that's about Gary Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who had been convicted for the 1981 murder of a man
outside a Houston supermarket, was executed in Texas last month,
with Bush proclaiming that ``justice is being done.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the questions that swirled around the case,
including the competence of Graham's lawyer and the fact that only
one witness testified against Graham, Garlic said the case had
given Bush ``an opportunity to show some compassion and love in a
way that had not been shown before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that when you chose protocol and not setting a
precedent over a decision about a man's life,'' Garlic said, ``you
missed an opportunity to show some of this compassion, and to show
some of this new Republican spirit that you talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You and I must differ on the death penalty,'' a surprised Bush
replied, speaking softly. ``I support it because I think it saves
lives when it's administered fairly and justly and surely.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``My job is to uphold the laws of my state. That's
what I was sworn in to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said of his refusal to intervene in the execution, ``It's
not an easy decision to make, as I'm sure you can understand.'' He
added, ``But it isn't a political decision for me, Reverend.'' He
said he would continue to ``uphold the law'' and ``if it costs me
votes, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dissatisfied, Garlic persisted. ``With all due respect, sir,
that is not an answer,'' he said. ``That is not a good enough
answer for me.'' He said the issue was whether Graham was guilty.
``And while you say to me that it was not a political decision, it
definitely was not a moral decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just disagree on that case,'' Bush said, and the group
returned to talking about services for children and to a proposal
by him for a $400 million program to help lower-income parents pay
for after-school activities.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made a concerted effort throughout his campaign to
prove he is a ``different kind of Republican,'' by appearing in
minority neighborhoods. He began his week at the convention of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People. And he
told the small crowd of guests on Friday that he hoped his
appearance before the civil rights organization would cause black
voters to think, ``Hey, there might be a little different cut to
this man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many Republican presidential candidates have
come to this neighborhood before,'' he said. ``I hope it tells
people I care.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By the end of the event he had the crowd laughing, when he
raised the question of whether he would remember his visit. ``I
think it's safe to say I might,'' Bush said with a smile. Then the
governor turned to Garlic, former director of the the Elizabethport
Presbyterian Center, where Bush spoke, and shook his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Though Garlic said afterward that he ``was absolutely not''
satisfied by Bush's response, he said Bush ``handled himself very
well in the total situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Several others in the audience said the governor had left them
more comfortable with the idea of a Bush presidency and even
willing to consider voting for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little bit more down to earth than I thought,'' said
William Ward, a member of the center's board. ``He's more
impressive than I thought. Now I've got to listen to the other
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a sense of humor,'' said Vera Atkinson, an assistant
director of an organization that builds low-income housing in the
neighborhood. ``I thought he was uncomfortable but answered the
best he could.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Bush traveled to more traditional Republican
turf _ a reception of New York's Conservative Party in a New York
City hotel ballroom. But the Gary Graham issue followed him, as two
protesters rose in the back of the room and began chanting. They
were quickly evicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
