<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TOBACCO0715-COX     07-14 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury delivers record setting verdict in tobacco trial
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The ``day of reckoning'' sought for years by cancer- and
emphysema-ravaged Florida smokers arrived Friday in a packed
courtroom as a jury slammed the tobacco industry with a
record-shattering $145 billion punitive damages verdict.
</P>
<P>
   But tobacco lawyers vowed to put years of appeals and legal
roadblocks between Friday's verdict and any payday for sick
smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors deliberated less than five hours before arriving at the
largest civil verdict in U.S. history. The trial lasted nearly two
years and was the nation's first smokers' class-action trial to
come before a jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a day of reckoning,'' proclaimed Stanley Rosenblatt,
the attorney for an estimated 300,000 to 700,000 Floridians with
smoking-related illnesses. Rosenblatt urged a multibillion-dollar
penalty to punish tobacco companies for decades of misleading the
public about the health risks of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco lawyers blasted the award as excessive and the trial as
legally flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably not a country in the world that can withstand
a verdict of this size and pay it at one time,'' said Dan Webb, the
attorney for industry leader Philip Morris, which was socked with a
$73.96 billion penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict is roughly seven times larger than the previous U.S.
record, a $22 billion award by a Hawaiian jury in 1996 against the
estate of former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos. That award
was later overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Robert Kaye can reduce Friday's verdict if he finds it
excessive. Florida law forbids a punitive damages award that would
bankrupt a business.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye, when he was first handed the verdict, appeared stunned by
its scale. He slowly leafed through the thick packet of pages
detailing the award, then placed his left hand over his mouth and
exhaled. Ten seconds passed and the hushed crowd in the courtroom
watched as Kaye fumbled with the papers.
</P>
<P>
   After the wait, Kaye muttered, ``I will publish this verdict.''
But he stopped short, raised his right index finger to the jury,
smiled, and said: ``Wait. Before I do that, let me think on this
for just a second.''
</P>
<P>
   Furrowing his brow, Kaye waited five more seconds before his
deliberate reading of the damages.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the verdict, Kaye said, ``A lot of zeros.''
</P>
<P>
   The five tobacco companies that were sued in the case claimed a
combined net worth of $15.2 billion and said they could not afford
to pay more than $381 million in damages _ less than 1 percent of
the amount jurors awarded.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco lawyers noted Friday that about two dozen other state
and federal courts have rejected similar class-action suits,
generally saying the smokers' histories and awareness of risk were
too varied to be tried in a single case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been heard of in American history to do anything
like this . . . This should not happen in an American courtroom,''
Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every court in this country has ruled that these
types of cases . . . should not be litigated as one huge,
consolidated case,'' said Lorillard general counsel Ron Milstein,
who vowed to appeal the $16.25 billion penalty against his company.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds lawyer Jim Johnson, whose company was ordered to
pay $36.28 billion in damages, blasted the proceeding as a ``show
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Friday's verdict is upheld, tobacco lawyers said they
don't expect to part with damages money in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe that day will come for decades,'' said Webb,
who maintains that the hundreds of thousands of smokers in the
class must go through separate trials before collecting damages.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt called that argument ``an absurdity'' and the
industry's complaints in general as ``sour grapes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally they got tagged. Finally they got hit. The day of
reckoning was delayed in coming and they should just take it,''
Rosenblatt said. ``I don't think two years of hard work by a
dedicated judge and a dedicated jury will be thrown down the drain
by some technicality.''
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's verdict, Philip Morris share prices closed at
$24.69, down 31 cents on the day, while shares of RJ Reynolds
closed at $26.19, down 94 cents. British American Tobacco
Industries, parent of Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco, closed at $12.50,
down 25 cents. Loews Corp., parent of Lorillard Tobacco, closed at
$63.06, down 44 cents. Vector, parent of Liggett Group, Inc.,
closed at $14.44, down 44 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed in 1994 and went to trial in 1998. The same
jurors who returned Friday's verdict decided last year that the
tobacco industry conspired to conceal the deadliness and
addictiveness of cigarettes. In the trial's second phase, the
jurors in April awarded $12.7 million in compensatory damages to
two smokers with cancer and the widower of a third.
</P>
<P>
   One of the compensatory damages recipients, Orlando clockmaker
Frank Amodeo, hugged Rosenblatt after Kaye read the jury's numbers
to a hushed courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only about money. It's about justice,'' said Amodeo,
whose throat cancer forces him to eat and drink through a tube in
his stomach. ``There's no amount of money in the world that's going
to change the way I eat or drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Farnan, who also was awarded compensatory damages in April,
tearfully said jurors ``should be commended by this whole country''
for Friday's verdict.
</P>
<P>
   After their verdict was read, Kaye encouraged jurors not to
publicly discuss the reasoning behind their verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you've done here is your own private business. Nobody can
question it. Nobody should,'' said Kaye, who arranged for the
jurors to be whisked from the courthouse before reporters could
question them.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt, who asked for $154 billion in damages and said any
substantial reduction would be ``a crushing blow to public
health,'' praised jurors for their verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six thoughtful, courageous Americans listened quietly and
carefully to testimony for close to two years,'' Rosenblatt said.
``And, dammit, they did the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce called the decision ``an obscene
symptom of a court system that is out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trial lawyers have subverted the legal system for their own
financial gain,'' said Bruce Josten, Chamber executive vice
president. ``Legitimate, but politically out-of-favor businesses
have been attacked by attorneys driven by the prospect of absurd
punitive damage awards.''
</P>
<P>
   But anti-smoking advocates also heralded Friday's verdict. Even
if the punitive damages are reduced, Northeastern University law
professor Richard Daynard said the verdict will shake the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly a tremendous landmark,'' said Daynard, who chairs
the Tobacco Products Liability Project. ``There's no question, this
is going to force the tobacco companies one way or another to
change the way they do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
