<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-GAMBLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAKE JEB BUSH LETTER USED IN FIGHTING BILL TO CURB WEB GAMBLING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Conn., Texas)  By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Florida authorities are investigating a letter
purportedly from Gov. Jeb Bush to a Florida member of Congress that
the governor's office says is a forgery.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which claims to detail Bush's position on
legislation now before Congress to ban gambling on the Internet,
was addressed to Rep. Cliff Stearns, R-Fla., and dated June 23.
</P>
<P>
   The letter says Bush is opposed to the bill on the grounds that
it would prevent the state from selling lottery tickets online and
would infringe on states' rights. The document has been circulating
on Capitol Hill for the past several days and has been used by
opponents of the measure as an argument for its defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But the letter is a forgery, Bush's office said Friday. ``We
don't know where it came from,'' said Justin Sayfie, Bush's
communications director. ``It is not his position. It is not the
governor's signature. It is not his letter. It is not authorized.
And it is troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayfie said that Bush had taken no position on the bill. Neither
has Gov. George W. Bush of Texas taken no position on the bill, an
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   The genesis of the letter became clear late Friday, although its
authorship remained a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   An official of Shandwick Washington, the Washington subsidiary
of Shandwick International, a major public relations firm based in
London, contacted Bush's office last month to request a letter
stating Bush's position on the gambling legislation, said Mark Day,
a Shandwick spokesman. Shandwick requested that the letter be
addressed to a member of Congress, Day said.
</P>
<P>
   Shandwick represents eLottery Inc., a Connecticut company that
provides computerized services for state lotteries and would profit
from online sales of lottery tickets. The Internet gambling
legislation would prohibit sales of lottery ticket on the Internet;
it is opposed by eLottery and several other lottery vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Shandwick said it had hoped to get a letter from Bush stating
his opposition to the bill _ as they had from several other
governors _ because it would inhibit electronic sales of lottery
tickets and infringe on states' rights. Day said that Shandwick
received the letter in late June and immediately began circulating
it on Capitol Hill, hoping to generate opposition to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We requested of Governor Bush's office and received a copy of
a letter to members of Congress, which we had every reason to
believe originated in the governor's office,'' Day said. ``It
appeared to be on official stationery and contained what appeared
to be an official signature. We later learned that the governor's
office did not authorize the letter and disavowed it. We
immediately stopped using the letter and urged others to do the
same. If there's a problem with the letter we believe absolutely we
should get to the bottom of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles A. Degliomini, senior vice president of sales and
marketing at eLottery, referred questions about the matter to John
M. Haddow, partner in the Washington lobbying firm Symms &AMP; Haddow
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Haddow said that he and eLottery officials were angry about the
letter and ``furiously trying to find out the source of this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously not a valid letter,'' Haddow said. ``I can't
tell you how much this annoys me and my partner.'' Haddow's partner
is Steven Symms, a former Republican senator from Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is expected to come before the House for a vote next
week. The measure seeks to curb the growth of wagering on the
Internet, particularly on casino-style games and sports. Many
governors oppose the bill because it would deny them the option of
selling lottery ticket online. It is supported by state attorneys
general, major professional and collegiate sports leagues, family
organizations and the Nevada gambling industry.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns said in a statement that he never saw the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I and my staff do not recall receiving a letter addressed to
me dated June 23, 2000, from the governor of Florida, Jeb Bush,
expressing his opposition'' to the Internet gambling bill, Stearns
said. ``If such a letter had been received, it certainly would have
been brought to my attention. However, at this time only the
governor's office can comment on the authenticity of this letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayfie said that the Florida Department of Law Enforcement was
investigating the letter. ``Hopefully, we'll get to the bottom of
this,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
