<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2678 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COX-NEWSPAPERS0715-CO     07-14 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-NEWSPAPERS0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox acquires area papers
 &HT;    By Jim Bohman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Cox Newspapers, publisher of the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution and the Dayton Daily News, expanded its reach
across southwestern Ohio Friday by acquiring daily newspapers in
Middletown and Hamilton and several non-dailies, including papers
in Miamisburg, Germantown and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Cox acquired the Middletown Journal and the Journal-News in
Hamilton, plus 10 weeklies, from Thomson Newspapers, a unit of
Toronto-based Thomson Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The non-daily newspapers include the Miamisburg News and West
Carrollton News, the Germantown Press and the Lebanon Western Star,
plus the Oxford Press, Fairfield Echo, Franklin Chronicle,
Springboro Star Press, Today's Express in Morrow and the Monroe
Times.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction also included several niche publications and a
printing plant in Butler County.
</P>
<P>
   The various publications have 350 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase follows the announcement last month that Thomson
had sold these publications and certain others across the U.S. to
the Gannett Co. Inc., Arlington, Va., for $1.12 billion.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cox held a right of first refusal in future Thomson
transactions when it negotiated a newspaper swap in 1996 that gave
Cox two newspapers in North Carolina and Thomson two Cox newspapers
in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett is proceeding with the purchase of 19 Thomson dailies
and 23 non-dailies in central Ohio, Louisiana, Maryland, Wisconsin
and Utah for approximately $1.035 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers, a subsidiary of Atlanta-based Cox Enterprises,
did not disclose the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   However, based on what the publicly traded Gannett Co.
acknowledges paying for the other Thomson publications, the price
is approximately $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pending regulatory approvals, Cox expects the deal to close in
the third quarter, according to J. Bradford Tillson, president and
chief executive of Cox Ohio Publishing and publisher of the Dayton
Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Tillson noted that the acquisitions are Cox's second major
investment in Cox Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently spent $90 million on the Dayton Daily News
Print Technology Center.
</P>
<P>
   The investments represent a powerful vote of confidence in the
future of newspapers in southwest Ohio, and in the strength of the
Cox Ohio team of employees, Tillson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to working with Carl Esposito, the Thomson
executive in charge of southwest Ohio properties, to ensure an
orderly transition of the properties and their employees from
Thomson to Cox,'' Tillson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to achieve the highest level of service to our
customers during and after this transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite TV's importance and the growing use of the Internet,
newspapers remain a major force for delivering news and
information, Tillson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspapers are still the biggest mass media in the country in
terms of reach and advertising dollars,'' Tillson said. ``Cox
believes they will continue to be strong in the future. That's not
to say that the Internet is not going to come in and grow, but Cox
believes in newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tillson said there is no plan to combine any Cox newspapers or
their sections with the Thomson publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought them because we think they are good properties,
period. Once the deal is closed, we're going to go in and learn a
lot more about the Thomson operation and the Thomson newspapers.
Working with them, we'll look for ways down the line that we can
grow our revenues and market share. But we don't have any plans to
combine anything at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of serving advertisers, bigger is better to some
extent, Tillson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have under the Cox Ohio group daily newspapers with
circulation of close to 300,000. Obviously, for some advertisers,
that will be very attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
