<SLUG> BC-NY-CAMPS-VIRUS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPING IN, AND LEAVING THE BUGS OUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELISSA GOOTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was the perfect end to a day of swimming, relay
races and folk singing at summer day camp in the Rockland County
woods, north of New York City: a Hawaiian luau with hamburgers,
pineapple slices and inflatable palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   And that was just the beginning. The campers were looking
forward to campfires and s'mores for the one night that they were
to spend without their moms, dads, brothers and sisters, or teddy
bears too big to squeeze into knapsacks.
</P>
<P>
   So the 140 children, ages 7 to 10, piled into five buses with
their sleeping bags _ and rode into Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the camp experience in the age of the mosquito.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in at least a decade when the skies were
clear, Manhattan's 92nd Street Y camp's fabled overnight under the
stars would take place indoors in Manhattan instead of at the Henry
Kaufmann campground in Pearl River, N.Y. Instead of a campfire,
there would be a circle of flashlights. The s'mores would be made
with marshmallow fluff.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Y said that out of concern for the safety of
the children and parents' fears about the West Nile virus, they did
not want campers exposed to mosquitoes during the active feeding
hours between dusk and dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, at a time when danger lurks in the form of disease-bearing
pests and litigious parents, camp operators are becoming more
cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're dealing with the outdoors, we're dealing with ticks
and we're dealing with mosquitoes and we're dealing with bats,''
said Peg Smith, the executive director American Camping
Association, based in Indianapolis. ``I think everybody's more
conscious today. Clearly everybody is living in that world that
tends to be concerned about lawsuits. But what we're most concerned
about is the safety of children going to camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she did not know of any other camps in the country
that had eliminated outdoor camping. The fears over West Nile are a
local phenomenon, and so far this year, no one in the New York
region is known to have become infected.
</P>
<P>
   For the children at Camp Yomi, the only day camp sponsored by
the 92nd Street Y that features an overnight camp out in Rockland
County, safety meant sleeping indoors in the Y building on
Lexington Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The campers found themselves sitting atop hardwood floors in a
dance studio, smearing marshmallow fluff on graham crackers. When
it was time for the nighttime story, they assembled into a rough
circle, around a campfire fashioned from small blue flashlights.
</P>
<P>
   And at night, they padded down the hall to the bathroom and back
to the classrooms where the carpeting was covered by a wall-to-wall
patchwork of sleeping bags. After a few tears were wiped away and
several campers had phoned home for a reassuring good night,
post-lights-out giggles reverberated from plaster walls instead of
disappearing into the stars and shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Marissa Katz, 10, was not impressed with the alternate
arrangements. ``I live in the city, and it's just all the stars you
see'' at the camp in the woods, she said. The Yomi campout last
year ``was much more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people brought junk food,'' she said wistfully. ``It
was just that we liked the stories they told and everything _ it
was just a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   Marissa had her own solution to the mosquito problem. ``I'm
trying my best to catch them and kill them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to the West Nile virus, the Camp Yomi kids'
awareness spanned from blissfully in the dark to surprisingly
plugged in. Some are anxious, others fearless.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Gilbert, 8, did not claim to be fearless, but nor did she
reserve her antipathy for the carriers of the ``Western disease,''
as she called it. ``I'm scared of all bugs,'' Molly announced,
twisting a red and purple lanyard.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Saltz, the director of the 92nd Street Y's many camp
programs, said he wanted the campers to have the experience of
dealing with their fears in the woods. He recalled his own
childhood summers sleeping on tarps beneath the open sky at the
same Henry Kaufmann campground, no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole trend in parenting that I've seen in my 10
years here, that I'd call micromanaging,'' he said, adding, ``It's
hard to imagine my folks getting worried about these kinds of
things. I just think the world has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saltz ultimately decided to err on the side of caution after
consulting with the Rockland County health department. Six of the
10 crows infected by the West Nile virus in the New York region
this year were discovered in the county. He said the fear of
lawsuits did not figure into his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Kristine A. Smith, a spokeswoman for the State Department of
Health, said the 92nd Street Y's move was a ``prudent precaution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not telling any overnight camps that they shouldn't be
in business,'' Smith said. ``We're telling them what the risks are
and what the personal prevention measures are that could be
taken.''
</P>
<P>
   One parent said she was glad Saltz took the initiative. Juggling
the responsibilities, concerns and errands of child rearing, she
said she forgot even to worry about West Nile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling bad that I really haven't thought about it,'' said
Diana Rodriguez, who arrived at the Y just before the buses left
for Henry Kaufmann to drop off the in-line skates that her son
Joshua Flores, 9, left behind. ``You hear about it, but I don't
have any connection with anyone who's had it,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
