<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MISSILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS PLAY DOWN ABM TEST FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES GLANZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second straight failure of a test for the proposed national
missile shield has set off a barrage of criticism. But such
breakdowns are routine in ambitious rocketry programs, even ones
that eventually succeed, several military and industry experts
outside the Pentagon say.
</P>
<P>
   The comments suggest that in the long run, a much larger
challenge to the program will come from critics who say that no
matter how well the shield eventually performs in the tightly
controlled tests, it will be all but worthless in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly the case that they'll be able to make this system
work against a simple, laboratory-designed threat,'' said Dr.
Michael O'Hanlon, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution who
specializes in military policy. ``These failures someday will end.
However, it doesn't mean it can defeat a real-world threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Many doubts about the shield are based on the contention that
decoys could always confuse an interceptor to let a warhead slip
through. For their part, officials in the antimissile program
maintain that the system can sift through the decoys.
</P>
<P>
   But among technically knowledgeable observers on all sides of
the debate, there is a remarkable range of agreement that the
shield's fattest target for criticism at the moment _ the generally
low-tech breakdowns that have caused the test failures _ say little
about whether the program will eventually succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every program has gone through failures,'' said Louis Deeter
of Quantum Research International in Huntsville, Ala., a retired
colonel who for three years was government program manager of the
Army's theater high-altitude area defense, or THAAD, antimissile
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything, today, that says the system
won't work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the test last week, a modified Minuteman rocket topped by a
so-called kill vehicle was launched into space from Kwajalein Atoll
in the Pacific Ocean. With the help of radar and satellite data and
its own sensors, the kill vehicle was supposed to fire its
thrusters and guide itself into a collision with a mock warhead,
pulverizing it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the final stage of the two-stage rocket began tumbling,
and then the simple mechanism that was supposed to release the kill
vehicle from the booster did not function properly, said Lt. Col.
Rick Lehner, a spokesman for the Ballistic Missile Defense
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not new technology,'' Lehner said. ``There has never
been a problem with that particular technology.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Pentagon analysts were examining second-by-second
telemetry data from the flight to determine exactly what went
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous test, last January, the kill vehicle separated
properly from the booster. But the vehicle missed the target
because a cooling line clogged, shutting down its heat-seeking
sensors.
</P>
<P>
   And in October, the Pentagon described the system's first
intercept test a complete success, but later was forced to concede
that the kill vehicle had drifted off course and locked onto a
decoy balloon. It turned out that the kill vehicle's navigation
system had been loaded with an incorrect star chart, and that the
guidance system suffered from a drift.
</P>
<P>
   Those failures were similar to the basic mechanical breakdowns,
electrical shorts and software flaws that led to a spate of recent
failures in launchings of commercial booster rockets for lifting
satellites into space and in the test program for THAAD, which is a
less ambitious antimissile system that is meant to protect troops.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in April, during a string of six failed launchings
in nine months, a protective shroud covering a payload failed to
detach from a Lockheed Martin Athena 2 rocket, dragging an
earth-imaging satellite back into the atmosphere, much as the
Minuteman did with the kill vehicle last week.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, one of six consecutive misses by THAAD was
apparently caused by particulate contamination of its seeker eye, a
problem similar to the one that derailed the national missile
defense test in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The launch business is absolutely unforgiving,'' said John
Willacker, vice president for space launching operations at the
Aerospace Corp. in El Segundo, Calif., who was involved in several
critical reviews of the booster program.
</P>
<P>
   But after what Willacker called a ``return to fundamentals''
involving management changes and redoubled quality-control
procedures, the booster program returned to flawless launchings.
</P>
<P>
   The THAAD program followed its heavily criticized failures with
two hits last year after a reorganization of the testing program
and extensive analysis of the problems. Earlier missile and
antimissile programs, with names like Sprint, Patriot and Polaris,
had similar histories of repeated failure followed by success, at
least in controlled tests.
</P>
<P>
   David Mosher, a policy analyst at the Rand Corp. who specializes
in nuclear weapons and missile defense, said the national missile
shield would ``need a couple more good failures'' before the crisis
atmosphere that surrounded the THAAD misses could be expected to
set in. But he added, ``This is a hard thing to do, and you should
expect failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehner said that pending the Pentagon's investigation of the
miss last week, the system's next test is expected to take place in
October or November.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts cautioned that whatever the technical relevance of
the problems, another miss would exact a steep price in political
criticism of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall program has not tested successfully,'' said Janne
Nolan, director of International Programs of the Century
Foundation, who sits on the Defense Policy Board, which advises the
Pentagon. Until it does, she warned, ``there's no there there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
