r a BC-WACO-TEX     07-14 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVISORY JURY FINDS GOVERNMENT NOT RESPONSIBLE FOR DAVIDIANS DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 (Fixes time element in lede) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JENNIFER AUTREY 
And BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A five-member advisory jury on Friday cleared
federal agents of any wrongdoing in the fiery deaths of some 80
Branch Davidians near Waco, a decision that government attorneys
said should end a 7-year-old controversy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter Smith Jr. is expected to issue the
final verdict next month in the $675 million wrongful death
lawsuit, but the lead attorney for the Davidians indicated that he
may be finished with the case.
</P>
<P>
   Still to be resolved is whether FBI agents fired into the sect
headquarters on April 19, 1993, the day the 51-day standoff ended
in a fatal fire. Smith has tentatively set Aug. 2 to hear
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The jury deliberated for 2 1/2 hours on Friday before issuing
its finding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is vindication for the law-enforcement officers
who were out at Mount Carmel doing their jobs under very difficult
circumstances, very dangerous circumstances,'' said U.S. Attorney
Michael Bradford, who represented the government in the month-long
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said the decision proves that sect leader David Koresh
and the Davidians were responsible for the April 19, 1993, tragedy
at Mount Carmel, the name of the sect's complex about 10 miles
outside of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Caddell, lead attorney for the Davidians and their
families, said he has spent more than a million dollars on the case
and may drop the allegation against the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in pursuing lost causes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reactions from survivors and relatives of the Davidians killed
at Mount Carmel included disappointment, bitterness and sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it wasn't a fair trial. I said that before it
started,'' said Clive Doyle, 59, an Australian-born Davidian who
escaped from the fire, with burns. His 18-year-old daughter was
among those who died.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle described his reaction to the decision as ``ho-hum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been surprised if the jury and the judge had
ruled in our favor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his efforts to make new evidence against the government
public, Caddell said he fears that the focus will be solely on the
jury's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the vast majority of the American people will take
this as the final word,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell predicted that the jury's decision might influence
former Sen. John Danforth's independent investigation of the events
at Waco.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Danforth, who was appointed in September by
Attorney General Janet Reno, told The Associated Press that he
would not comment on the jury's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys James Brannon of Houston and former Attorney General
Ramsey Clark joined Caddell in trying to prove that 75 agents from
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms fired indiscriminately
in a gun battle that broke out when they tried to serve a search
warrant at Mount Carmel on Feb. 28, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Brannon and Clark left without comment.
</P>
<P>
   The raid left four ATF agents and six Davidians dead.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, during closing arguments, pointed to testimony from some
of the ATF agents, saying they fired at windows from where they
believed the shots were coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't see anybody; they just shot,'' Clark said. ``If
that's not indiscriminate, what is indiscriminate?''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the plaintiffs' closing argument appealed to the jurors'
emotions. Clark described sect members as peaceful church people;
Brannon showed photographs of three babies killed in the fire; and
Caddell read aloud part of the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury found that ATF did not act inappropriately and that
the FBI, which took over after the botched raid, was not negligent
April 19. Smith asked the jury to determine whether the FBI was
negligent in any of three ways: by using tanks to destroy part of
the sect's building; by starting or contributing to a fire that
raced through it; and by failing to have a firefighting plan.
</P>
<P>
   The charred remains of about 80 Branch Davidians were found
after the fire was doused, although the actual number remains in
dispute. Autopsies, some of which were performed by Tarrant County
Medical Examiner Nizam Peerwani, show that the majority died by
smoke inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen died of gunshot wounds consistent with suicide and a
few suffocated or died of blunt trauma, the reports show.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said the government never presented testimony to counter
the Davidians' fire investigation expert, Pat Kennedy, who said the
government helped at least spread the fire by using tanks to insert
tear gas directly into the sect's living quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you destroy a building, you make kindling,'' Caddell
said.
</P>
<P>
   The government presented secretly-recorded tapes from April 19
that voice engineers said captured Davidians discussing their
efforts to spread fuel and then light a fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, David Koresh and the Branch Davidians were responsible
for that tragedy, as well,'' Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvelyn Cooney, 48, whose sister Jaydean Wendel was fatally
shot during the initial raid as she combed her child's hair,
praised the jury and the Davidians' attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the verdict could have been different, but I admire
everyone who tried to bring justice,'' Cooney said from Spokane,
Wash., where she cares for her sister's four children.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said the jurors, whose names were not made public, did
not want to be interviewed by attorneys or news agencies. They left
the courthouse before the verdict was read.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he couldn't say why the jury wasn't persuaded. He
said jurors may have been unsettled by the Davidians' firepower,
which included automatic weapons, grenades, grenade launchers and
hundreds of rounds of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, ``for some people, it is difficult, if not
impossible, to believe that anyone with law enforcement would not
be completely truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell also said that the judge's instructions to the jury
omitted key information, such as what responsibility the government
bore in foreseeing the tragedy and what duty it had to avert the
suicide of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would eat my shoe,'' Smith responded, if the instructions
didn't reflect the issues in the case.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2713 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT-1STL     07-14 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-580(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY SAYS TOBACCO INDUSTRY MUST PAY $144.8 BILLION IN CLASS-ACTION
SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS penultimate graf to 1st take with figures from previous
settlement; ADDS 12th graf to 2nd take with value of companies)  
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In the largest damage award in U.S. history, a jury in
Miami-Dade County on Friday ordered the tobacco industry to pay
$144.8 billion in punitive damages to some 500,000 sick Florida
smokers.
</P>
<P>
   But even as some of the sick smokers and the widows and widowers
of others celebrated the verdict as a sweeping victory over the
industry, tobacco executives called the award ridiculous, and one
that would push the companies into bankruptcy, if it is ever paid
at all.
</P>
<P>
   The companies vowed to appeal, a process that could take years.
While those appeals are underway, their financial exposure could be
relatively minimal. Under a law passed last year with this case in
mind, cigarette makers could be required to post an initial bond of
no more than $100 million per company. A judge may decide as soon
as Monday whether that law applies in this case, since the suit was
filed before the law was passed. In addition, Florida law prohibits
a damage award that would force a company into bankruptcy. Experts
on both sides debated whether such a massive judgment would put the
companies out of business. ``There is no industry in America,
there's probably not a country in the world, that could withstand a
verdict of this size,'' said Dan Webb, a lawyer for Philip Morris,
the country's largest cigarette maker.
</P>
<P>
   The six-member jury, which has weighed the different phases of
this case for two years now, deliberated only five hours before
reaching its decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of zeroes,'' said Judge Robert Kaye, as he read the
amount of the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Guillermo Saa, who has had his vocal cords and much of his
throat removed because of smoking-related cancer, became so
emotional after the verdict was read that he had difficulty
breathing, and had to leave the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine how happy I am,'' said Saa, one of the
plaintiffs, speaking through an electronic voice box. ``My heart is
happy, because this is a lesson for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs said the massive verdict was an
appropriate punishment for an industry that makes a product that
kills 430,000 Americans every year and for misleading the public
about the dangers even after medical research showed that smoking
causes cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye can reduce the amount, but lawyers for the industry are
likely to appeal any award approaching the billions the jury voted
for.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the five companies had said in closing arguments
that such a verdict would be a ``death warrant'' for the industry.
But after the jury's decision, the companies' lawyers said instead
that the judgment would have no immediate impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased, because there is no practical impact on Philip
Morris,'' said Webb.
</P>
<P>
   He called the verdict ``an unfair procedure, unheard of in
American history,'' but one that would not stand up under an
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a verdict in favor of no one,'' said Webb.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris was ordered to pay $73.96 billion, R.J. Reynolds
$36.28 billion, Brown &AMP; Williamson $17.59 billion, Lorillard
Tobacco $16.25 billion, and Liggett Group Inc. $790 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire industry could not even pay that amount,'' said Dan
Donahue, senior vice president at R.J. Reynolds, of the judgment
against his company. ``It's a ridiculous amount.''
</P>
<P>
   The punitive damages would come on top of the $246 billion the
industry agreed in 1998 to pay the states over 25 years in a
concession that ended its record of successful resistance to claims
of damages.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the $144.8 billion judgment was to be paid by
the Council for Tobacco Research and the Tobacco Institute, which
had provided false data that refuted medical research of the
dangers of smoking.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sick smokers, some of whom have followed the case every day from
the courtroom pews, were optimistic about the outcome. The same
jury had found in July 1999 that the tobacco industry manufactured
a deadly product, and that it had deceived the public for years. In
April, the panel ordered cigarette makers to pay $12.7 million in
compensatory damages.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the jury heard 157 witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In the punitive stage of the trial, sick smokers first asked for
$196 billion in damages. But the lead lawyer for the plaintiffs,
Stanley Rosenblatt, would eventually suggest an award of $154
billion to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a day of reckoning,'' said Rosenblatt. ``This was never
about money. This was about showing these companies up for what
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt said the jury, which was made up of a postal worker,
a bank teller, a welder, a telephone technician, an assistant
principal and another school employee, ``did the right thing. They
said to those companies, `Cut it out. Tell us the truth.' They were
stoic, unemotional.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter in the case from now on, said Frank Amodeo, one of
three sick smokers who legally represents the 500,000 others in the
class-action lawsuit, the jury's verdict is the most significant
victory so far in a fight to make the companies acknowledge their
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Amodeo contracted throat cancer about 10 years ago, cannot
swallow and must be fed through a tube. ``There is no amount of
money in the world that will change the way I eat.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was history making in other ways. Top executives for
the companies, who rarely testify under oath, took the stand to say
that their companies had changed, that they were spending millions
to discourage underage smoking and were repentant of the way
business was done in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the companies had said the cigarette makers could
afford to pay between $150 million to $375 million, but would be
put out of business if the jury granted anything approaching the
requested award.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either destroy them or you don't,'' said Gordon Smith, a
lawyer for Brown &AMP; Williamson, in his closing argument. ``Your
verdict must reflect current ability to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   But the amount of punitive judgment the industry said it could
afford to pay represents a fraction of its audited net worth, and
could be recouped in just a few days of wholesale cigarette sales,
said critics of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Brown &AMP; Williamson, a unit of British American Tobacco, is
valued at $13.6 billion; Liggett, a unit of the Vector Group, is
valued at $317 million; Lorillard Tobacco, a unit of the Loews
Corp., $6.2 billion; Philip Morris, $56 billion, and R.J. Reynolds,
$2.7 billion.
 &UR;  &LR; ``We ask you to speak for all those silent, anonymous victims of
tobacco grieved by their loved ones but unknown to a callous and
deceitful industry,'' Rosenblatt said in his closing argument.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling eclipsed the punitive damage award of $5 billion
against Exxon Mobil for the Exxon Valdez oil spill in Alaska, and a
$4.8 billion award against General Motors in a car fire in
California _ a judge later reduced that award to $1.09 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in fact, the largest award of any kind, much more than
the $22 billion awarded in Hawaii in 1996 to a treasure hunter who
sued former President Ferdinand Marcos of the Philippines for an
alleged theft of gold bullion. That verdict was later overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Turner, a former Wall Street executive who formed Smokefree
Educational Services, had testified for the plaintiffs on the
industry's ability to pay in the event of such a judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Turner does not believe the plaintiffs will ever see any money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country, the guilty people don't always have to pay,''
he said. ``They were found guilty of lying, killing, causing
diseases. But the tobacco cartel has friends in high places. They
own Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The award, he said, ``will never amount to a hill of beans.''
</P>
<P>
   But the message, he said, will.
</P>
<P>
   ``These six ordinary people,'' he said, ``have decided this
industry is guilty of the biggest fraud, deceit, maiming, killing,
destroying and lying in the history of mankind. Nothing will ever
change that fact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
