<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN CREW MODULE CLIMBS TOWARD RENDEZVOUS WITH SPACE STATION
SEGMENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recently launched Russian-built crew module for the
international space station began its climb Friday toward a linkup
with the other components of the orbital outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Two successful maneuvers placed the 43-foot module, which is
designed to serve as the living quarters for the slowly developing
station's first resident astronauts, in an elliptical orbit with
high and low points of 224 miles and 167 miles, the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration said.
</P>
<P>
   The unpiloted crew module was launched from Central Asia by the
Russians late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The spacecraft is scheduled to rendezvous and dock with two
previously launched and joined segments of the U.S.-led station
late July 25. They are circling the Earth at an altitude of about
240 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Guidance and propulsion systems aboard the station's first
segments are designed to rendezvous automatically once the crew
module completes its climb through a gradual series of maneuvers.
The operation is being closely monitored by the Russian mission
control facility in suburban Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   If the modules are successfully mated, the first resident crew
of cosmonauts and astronauts will be launched to the station for a
three-to four-month stay in late October.
</P>
<P>
   The crew module's many electronic and mechanical systems have
been undergoing a component-by-component check.
</P>
<P>
   The only component that has not passed muster so far is a backup
docking target, said Kyle Herring, a NASA spokesman in Moscow. The
fixture may actually be correctly positioned, though a sensor is
indicating otherwise to ground control teams, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The target would be used only if the automated rendezvous is
unsuccessful. In that event, the Russians plan to launch a pair of
cosmonauts to the crew module in a Soyuz capsule.
</P>
<P>
   Once aboard, the cosmonauts would attempt to bring the modules
together using a backup system that relies on television cameras
for guidance. The target is one of the guidance cues the cosmonauts
would use for the linkup.
</P>
<P>
   The crew module represents only the third large component of the
orbital outpost launched since assembly began in late 1998. Russian
financial difficulties delayed its lift off by 27 months.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia are part of a 16-nation partnership
involved in the assembly of a new space station whose laboratories
will be used for a range of physics, biology and medical
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
