<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACESUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA SAYS HAZARD COULD CAUSE SPACESUITS TO CATCH FIRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bulky white garments that U.S. astronauts have worn for two
decades on spacewalks outside the shuttle have accumulated an oily
contaminant in their emergency oxygen supplies that could ignite,
NASA said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The finding comes as the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration is preparing for a steep increase in its number of
spacewalks, raising the concern. The space agency estimates that
its astronauts will conduct at least 165 of the six-hour excursions
over the next five years as it assembles the U.S.-led international
space station.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has ordered the dirty dispensing mechanisms in the garments
cleaned. New filters to prevent further contamination will be
installed in the ground oxygen supply systems for the suits' air
tanks before its astronauts walk in space again, said Greg
Harbaugh, who manages the agency's spacewalk planning office. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The concern, Harbaugh said, is that the oily droplets in the
regulators of the all-oxygen environment could ignite in the
high-pressure emergency system of the suits.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency apparatus is designed to force out a half-hour of
air for a spacewalking astronaut, even if the suit is punctured by
a small meteorite. The lower pressure primary system that normally
furnishes seven to eight hours of oxygen could be rapidly depleted
if the protective garment were breached. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; NASA's 84 previous spacewalks, including one during the most
recent shuttle flight in May, were conducted without the need for
an astronaut to turn to the backup air supply.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the space agency does not intend to press its luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``(This) is something that has the potential to create a fire if
the right conditions are present,'' Harbaugh said. ``It is my
judgment that it's an unacceptable risk to take.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA maintains 12 of the $10 million spacesuits, which were
developed before shuttle flights began in 1981. Though not every
mission includes plans for a spacewalk, at least two astronauts on
each trip aloft are trained and equipped to make an excursion to
deal with a range of emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Harbaugh said the spacesuit issue was brought to NASA's
attention in mid-June by the companies that developed the garments
and the vendor for the contaminated regulators, prompting a quick
response.
</P>
<P>
   Those activities were first disclosed by an Internet news
service on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A small quantity of an oily contaminant was found in the
regulators of the backup oxygen supply of all 12 suits. The
mechanisms had not been examined since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Experts are still trying to track down the source, but the
leading suspect is the supply tank used by NASA's shuttle
contractors to prepare the spacesuits for flight. Shuttle engineers
believe the grime has been accumulating for years, Harbaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason the contractors have been instructed by NASA to
install new low-temperature filters in their supply lines to trap
contaminants before they enter the suits, Harbaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   The spacesuits are constructed of a puffy fabric suit pant, a
rigid structure that fits over the upper torso of the astronaut, a
helmet and a large backpack. The backpack contains the suit's life
support apparatus, including the primary and backup air supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery also prompted an assessment of the primary oxygen
regulators in the suits, an analysis that will not be complete
before NASA's next scheduled shuttle flight in early September.
That mission includes a single spacewalk. Four excursions are
planned during another flight to the space station in October.
</P>
<P>
   So far, NASA has not found a contamination problem with the
primary air supplies of its spacesuits. Nonetheless, its engineers
have conducted a series of tests designed to reveal whether high
quantities of grime could ignite in a suit if it could not be
cleaned before a flight.
</P>
<P>
   The primary regulators were dirtied with twice the level of
contamination found on the emergency mechanisms for the trials.
Engineers were unable to detect signs of ignition in the primary
regulators, though they were cycled dozens of times.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the findings, Harbaugh said he believes it will be
safe for NASA to continue with its shuttle missions as long as the
spacesuits they carry have only emergency air supply mechanisms
that have been thoroughly cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
