<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A JURY IN FLORIDA AWARDS $144.8 BILLION TO SMOKERS
</P>
<P>
   A jury in Florida ordered the tobacco industry to pay $144.8
billion in punitive damages to 500,000 smokers in the largest
damage award in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   But even as some of the sick smokers and the widows and widowers
of others celebrated the verdict as a victory over the industry,
tobacco executives called the award ridiculous and said it would
push the companies into bankruptcy if it is paid. They vowed to
appeal the verdict, which could take years.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE REPEALS FEDERAL ESTATE TAX
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted to repeal the federal estate tax, brushing
aside a veto threat from President Clinton and giving Republicans a
symbolic victory on an issue at the top of their election-year
agenda. The vote was 59-39. Although Democrats have long said
repeal of the tax would be a hugely expensive giveaway to the rich,
nine of 45 Democrats voted for the legislation. Four Republicans
voted against.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ'S HIGHEST CLOSE IN THREE MONTHS
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq market finished with its highest close in three
months as strong earnings and a tame inflation report bolstered
hopes that the Federal Reserve Board would not raise interest rates
again this year. The Nasdaq composite index jumped 71.32 points, or
1.7 percent, to 4,246.18. The Dow Jones industrial average climbed
24.04 points, or 0.2 percent, to 10,812.75. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index rose 14.14 points, or 0.9 percent, to 1,509.98.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER SPENDING STAYS STRONG
</P>
<P>
   U.S. shoppers kept spending through the spring despite an
increase in interest rates and gasoline prices, according to
government reports. Retail sales climbed 0.5 percent last month, to
$269.3 billion. The Labor Department's report on prices paid to
producers, which excludes both services and imported goods, showed
a 0.6 percent advance for finished goods.
</P>
<P>
   NEW PRESENCE IN THE BOSS'S OFFICE
</P>
<P>
   A federal agency's ruling this week that nonunion workers
summoned into a boss's office can take along a fellow employee as a
witness has won derision from managers and praise from labor
activists. But both sides say the decision is unlikely to alter the
dynamics of the workplace anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   CBS CHECKS PAST OF A CAST MEMBER
</P>
<P>
   CBS said it was ``looking into'' a report that one of the
participants in its new reality series, ``Big Brother,'' was an
associate of the militant anti-Semitic black leader Khalid
Muhammad, but the network said it saw no reason to remove the man
from the program.
</P>
<P>
   IMPRESARIO SETTLES SUIT WITH KPMG
</P>
<P>
   The Broadway impresario Garth Drabinsky, a Canadian citizen
wanted on criminal charges in the United States related to the
collapse of his Livent production company, said he had settled his
suit against his former accountants KPMG and KPMG Investigation and
Security Inc. KPMG acknowledged that it had breached its fiduciary
duty by allowing KPMG Investigation and Security to conduct an
inquiry into Livent's financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN RECOVERY SAID TO BE ON TRACK
</P>
<P>
   Japan's finance minister said the failure of the giant retail
chain Sogo would not undercut the country's economic recovery, and
Standard &AMP; Poor's called the Sogo bankruptcy necessary medicine for
the Japanese banking system. A bailout of Sogo collapsed after
Shinsei Bank, a big Sogo creditor that was recently bought by
foreign investors, balked at forgiving any Sogo debts.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSICO HAS 21 PERCENT GAIN IN EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   PepsiCo reported a 21 percent rise in second-quarter earnings
this week, soundly beating estimates. The performance was driven by
double-digit gains at its salty snack and juice businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
