u a BC-MAID-ENSLAVEMENT-NYT &LR;      07-14 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAID-ENSLAVEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT REACHED IN MAID'S SUIT AGAINST DIPLOMAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A rare federal lawsuit in which a domestic worker accused her
employer, a diplomat from Bahrain, of keeping her in virtual
peonage has been settled out of court, the woman's lawyer said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is investigating the case, a prerequisite to any
criminal charges, the lawyer said. Until that investigation is
completed, she added, the maid, Shamela Begum, will remain in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in December in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan, accused Mohammed Saleh, the second secretary at the
Bahraini Mission to the United Nations, and his wife, Khatun, of
flagrant labor law violations and indentured servitude, a violation
of the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the defendants had not addressed any of the suit's
allegations, but instead claimed diplomatic immunity. Under the
Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations, diplomatic envoys cannot
be prosecuted by a host country, although according to State
Department rules, they are to abide by local laws, including wage
and hour provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement prohibits the parties from discussing its terms
publicly. On Friday, Begum said only that she was glad to have
taken her case to court and was satisfied by its outcome. ``I
thought it was more or less fine,'' she said in a brief telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   In an especially strange twist, the Clinton administration,
which has been pushing for greater vigilance against what the
attorney general has called ``modern-day slavery,'' sided with the
defense, warning that a failure to honor the defendants' immunity
could lead to retaliation against American diplomats abroad. The
judge, Richard M. Berman, did not throw out the case, but urged the
parties to pursue out-of-court talks.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement agreement was reached last month, said Begum's
lawyer, Chaumtoli Huq of the Asian-American Legal Defense and
Education Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Begum, an illiterate mother of three from Bangladesh, has said
her ordeal began nearly two years ago, when an employment broker in
her hometown, Dhaka, arranged for her to work as a maid in Bahrain.
She was persuaded to be brought to work for the Salehs in December
1998 and was kept a virtual prisoner in the family's high-rise
apartment on Manhattan's East Side. They took away her passport the
day she arrived, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For the next nine months, she said, she was forced to work seven
days a week and was forbidden to leave the apartment alone. Her
wages _ $100 a month, she said _ were sent to her husband in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
   Begum, who speaks only Bengali, escaped from the household last
summer with the help of a Bengali-speaking fruit vendor who worked
nearby and a South Asian workers' rights group called Andolan _
struggle, in Bengali. She has worked as a maid in other households
since then.
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 800 migrant domestic workers with special visas
allowing them to work for U.N. officials in New York, State
Department officials said. In recent years, several of these
workers have sued for back wages and over other labor law
violations. A few cases have been settled out of court, like
Begum's. Others have been dismissed on the grounds of diplomatic
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Huq said she hoped Begum's case would prompt other women to come
forward if they had been mistreated. Moreover, she said she hoped
the FBI would urge federal prosecutors to file criminal charges if
there was sufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Margolin, an FBI spokesman, said he could not confirm his
agency's involvement in this or any other case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT &LR;      07-14 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMP DAVID TALKS IN LULL BEFORE EXPECTED WHIRL OF DECISION-MAKING 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Whizzing around Camp David in golf carts and on
bicycles, as if they were resort guests and not confined like
prisoners of diplomacy in a pressure-cooker peace summit, Israeli
and Palestinian leaders spent their fourth day in secluded
negotiations Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They divided into groups to tackle issues separately, and a
senior Palestinian official who is not inside Camp David said the
Americans had begun to offer proposals to bridge the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   With the information lid still tightly secured on the
presidential retreat in Maryland, it was unknown how far the
parties had progressed toward an actual agreement or whether, as
some American officials believe, they had not progressed much at
all.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they have averted a crisis, a storm-out, a showy packing
of the bags or a deliberate leak to the news media. But Reuters
cited unnamed Palestinian officials as saying they had come close,
and claiming that Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, was ready
to storm out in anger after seeing the American bridging proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Officials on all sides expect that the serious decision-making
will begin only this weekend, despite a slowdown for the Jewish
Sabbath on Saturday, and will build toward some kind of peak early
next week before an unofficial deadline of Wednesday, when
President Clinton is scheduled to depart for a Group of 8 meeting
in Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   The informal atmosphere _ including one fender bender between
negotiators' golf carts _ belies the seriousness of the mood, said
Joe Lockhart, Clinton's spokesman. ``These are intractable
issues,'' he said. ``These are issues that go to the vital
interests of both of the parties, so this is very serious. You
know, at times discussions are tense, but that should come as no
surprise to you.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Israeli official said that Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
spirits remained as high as they were on the plane ride to the
United States. At that time, the official said, Barak believed that
both sides were primed to compromise because they saw ahead only
negative alternatives _ renewed violence and unilateral steps that
would complicate each party's carefully nurtured international
standing.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and American officials are stressing to the Palestinians
that Barak, whom the Palestinians had soured on long before the
summit talks, represented their best hope for a conciliatory peace
partner.
</P>
<P>
   This is the picture they are painting: Despite the fragility of
his new minority government, Barak, as a former general committed
to forging an agreement, has the authority to sell serious
concessions to an Israeli public hungry for an end to the conflict.
If no agreement is reached and the relationship disintegrates into
violence, Barak could end up forging a unity government with the
rightist Likud Party. Or he could go to new elections, in which
case either a rightist leader or a centrist with less clout as a
security expert than Barak would be elected.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, some Cabinet ministers have been priming Israelis for
possible concessions by publicly discussing some of the compromises
that may be on the table at Camp David. Some Israeli-Arab lawmakers
have been leaking ideas, too. None are new thoughts, but they are
being aired in what seems to be an effort to ease them into the
realm of the possible.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Yossi Beilin, the justice minister, whose draft
agreement in 1995 with Abu Mazen, the secretary-general of the
Palestine Liberation Organization, is providing a template, said on
Thursday that Israel would consider swapping land with the
Palestinians. That is, in order to retain some of the West Bank and
annex the Jewish settlement abutting Jerusalem, it might be willing
to turn over land adjacent to Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   And Avraham Burg, the Parliament speaker, who has served as an
unofficial Israeli spokesman in Washington and New York this week,
hinted that land swaps might work in Jerusalem too. Jerusalem could
``expand and shrink,'' he suggested. That is, it could gain some
neighborhoods _ the Jewish ones outside its limits _ and lose
others, the Arab ones within. It is an idea that would provoke
volatile emotions in Israel but could help broker a solution to the
thorniest issue, Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Further, an Israeli-Arab legislator, Ahmed Tibi, who used to
advise Arafat, said he had learned that both sides had agreed that
Israel would relinquish the few remaining settlements in the Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   The periphery of Camp David drew both Israeli and Palestinian
opposition leaders on Friday. Limor Livnat, a lawmaker from the
Likud party, showed up at the Thurmont Elementary School to give a
piece of her mind to the hundreds of reporters awaiting any
information. She opposes the peace summit. But she was ushered out
by American officials, into the parking lot, where a ragtag
collection of protesters gather every day.
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Amr, a Palestinian Cabinet minister, was similarly exiled
earlier in the week. American officials are trying to keep the
parts of the Camp David area that they control a propaganda-free
zone in order, as one said, ``to give peace a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the outskirts of the summit zone, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright met with Palestinian opposition leaders who were
barred from entering Camp David to consult with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke with them in Emittsburg, Md., where side conferences
on issues like the environment and the regulation of the
electromagnetic space shared by the two sides are supposed to be
discussed. They are not being allowed to see Arafat inside the
retreat because it is restricted to official delegates, American
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the spirit of the ground rules we've put down, we
indicated that we would prefer that that meeting not happen up at
Camp David,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
