<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-TOBACCO-LAWYER-NY     07-14 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TOBACCO-LAWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-FLYING LAWYER AGAIN INFLICTS DAMAGES ON TOBACCO INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
  (With FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT, FLA-TOBACCO-ASSESS)  
 By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley M. Rosenblatt, the lawyer who won the biggest
class-action lawsuit award in history Friday, is part of a
husband-and-wife legal team that operates as lone eagles in the
tobacco wars. They are not among the big-name plaintiffs' lawyers
who sued the industry on behalf of the states and amassed hundreds
of millions of dollars and great political power.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not the first time that Rosenblatt has scored big
against the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be out of my mind if I was doing this for the money,''
Rosenblatt said in 1996, when his class-action lawsuits against
tobacco companies were just beginning to seem dangerous to the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   That was before he was awarded $49 million in fees in the
tobacco industry's 1997 settlement with flight attendants, who
claimed they were damaged by secondhand smoke. And that also was
before Wednesday, when he won what one tobacco attorney called a
``death warrant'' for the industry: a $144.8 billion damage award
in a lawsuit brought by Florida smokers who blamed their illnesses
on smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt's fee is yet to be determined by the court. He will
submit his expenses, and ask the judge for a percentage of the
award.
</P>
<P>
   The small _ some say aloof _ firm run by Rosenblatt and his
wife, Susan, an appellate lawyer, has made its reputation by
succeeding where polished celebrity lawyers have failed, and by
being paid handsomely for it.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-tobacco activists criticized his fee in the flight
attendant's lawsuit, particularly because the plaintiffs received
nothing. Four of the largest tobacco companies agreed to spend $300
million researching smoking-related illnesses. But the plaintiffs
retained the right to sue for individual damages.
</P>
<P>
   After a federal appeals panel dismissed what would have been the
largest class-action suit in history, brought against the tobacco
industry by a consortium of some 60 lawyers in 1996, attention
shifted to Rosenblatt's two suits, the flight attendant suit and
the suit representing some 500,000 Florida smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's up to Ma and Pa Kettle,'' Rosenblatt said at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   They have won several multimillion-dollar malpractice judgments
in Florida, including a $6 million verdict on behalf of a motel
guest who became a quadriplegic after diving off a pier and $3.8
million for the parents of a teen-ager who was killed when his
motorcycle was hit by a car.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt first encountered the effects of cigarettes in 1988,
when he successfully defended a St. Petersburg, Fla., doctor who
was accused of murder after he wrote about helping his wife die.
The doctor's wife had been suffering from lung cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-BAKALY-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      07-14 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKALY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR SPOKESMAN DEPICTED AS EAGERLY LEAKING DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department closed its criminal contempt
of court case against Charles G. Bakaly III Friday by portraying
the former spokesman for the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, as
eagerly leaking confidential information to make the counsel's
office look important.
</P>
<P>
   Two FBI agents quoted Bakaly as telling them that he had seized
on an opportunity presented by questions from The New York Times
about the future of the office, but then felt the story had not
hidden his role as a source. ``I played a risky game, and I got
burned,'' an agent, Thomas F. Lewis, quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly is charged with making false statements to government
officials when he denied providing sensitive information to The
Times for a Jan. 31, 1999, article that portrayed Starr as having
decided he could indict a sitting president.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said Bakaly told him that ``reporters need to be fed
information,'' and that the questions from The Times offered an
opportunity to tell the public that even if the Senate acquitted
President Clinton, ``the independent counsel's office was not going
to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Another agent, Russell P. Robinson, said Bakaly told him the
message he wanted to send from the Office of the Independent
Counsel was ``in the event there was an acquittal in the Senate
case, the OIC could move forward with its indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Bakaly argued for a directed verdict of acquittal,
saying the prosecution had not even made a minimal case that he had
lied in denying discussing secret information. Bakaly's lawyers
have portrayed him throughout as earnestly seeking to deflect the
article away from the details of what was going on in the
prosecutor's office and toward a historical approach.
</P>
<P>
   Michele A. Roberts, a defense lawyer, said the government had a
``burden to prove to the court that these matters were nonpublic
matters'' and could have tried to do so by showing that none of the
information had been published before, or by getting Starr to
testify that the issues Bakaly discussed with The Times were
secrets. By doing neither, she said, the government forfeited its
case.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Norma Holloway Johnson of U.S. District Court here said
she would rule on the motion on Monday. But she told the defense to
be ready to proceed with its case. She is hearing the case without
a jury, which is permissible under the law of criminal contempt
because the Justice Department had promised not to seek a prison
sentence of more than six months.
</P>
<P>
   The article appeared in the midst of Clinton's Senate trial, and
it produced angry complaints from his lawyers and from Johnson.
Both charged that the story revealed secret information from the
grand jury. But last fall a federal court of appeals said
information about the prosecutor's strategy was not protected grand
jury material.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that by making false or misleading statements _
in particular the denial of discussing ``nonpublic matters'' _
Bakaly delayed the investigation of the leak and wasted the court's
time. Johnson ruled that such delays would constitute contempt; the
defense has said it will appeal the ruling if Bakaly is convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Friday's argument dealt with how much of a secret it was
that Starr was considering four options _ to indict Clinton
quickly, to indict him but keep the indictment under seal until he
left office, to wait until he left office to indict, or not to
indict. Several government witnesses have conceded under
cross-examination that those choices are always available and did
not constitute any secret.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 27, 1999, all of the Starr office lawyers debated the
options in a lengthy meeting, and on Jan. 28, according to FBI
agent Michael Erbach, the Times reporter, Don Van Natta, brought
them up with Bakaly.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson testified that two independent counsel lawyers, whom he
did not name, sent a memo around the office the day after The Times
article ran, saying that from its detail, ``it appeared as though
Van Natta was at the all-attorney's meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis revealed another detail about that meeting. He said Bakaly
told them that Starr's deputy, Jackie Bennett, told him the lawyers
present had taken a straw vote on whether Clinton should be
indicted. But he did not give the result of the vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
