<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FLA-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CIGARETTE MAKERS UNDER SIEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 15:
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry may be forever changed by a Florida jury's
stunning award of $145 billion in punitive damages in a
class-action lawsuit brought on behalf of injured smokers in
Florida. The process of appeals on every aspect of this case will
likely continue for years, making it hard to predict how much of
the award will ultimately stand. But there is no doubt that this
case poses a serious threat to the survival of the cigarette
business.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer size of the award is an important symbol. The
industry, which for so long had been able to escape liability for
individual deaths and illnesses, is now facing a sea change in
public attitudes _ and the attitudes of future juries _ about its
responsibility for selling products that cause death and disease.
</P>
<P>
   Under Florida law, a punitive damages award cannot drive a
defendant into bankruptcy. The industry is challenging the
appropriateness of allowing a plaintiff class that could cover more
than 500,000 Florida residents. Other questions are also
unresolved. For example, the punitive damages are awarded to the
entire class, but it is unclear how such an award would be divided
among the unidentified class members, who would each still have to
show that his or her particular injuries came from cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the individual class members have yet to prove
their cases and many procedural issues will be reviewed by higher
courts, the six-member Florida jury has now found that the industry
committed fraud on the public, conspired to conceal the dangers of
smoking and placed on the market a product that was ``defective and
unreasonably dangerous.'' This spring, in the second phase of the
trial, the jury awarded nearly $13 million in compensatory damages
to three plaintiffs who had contracted lung or throat cancer as a
result of smoking. Now it has found that the industry must be
punished and deterred from further wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   For years, tobacco firms were able to beat such lawsuits by
blaming the smoker for not quitting. But that strategy did not work
with this jury when it was confronted with thousands of internal
industry documents showing that the companies had known for decades
that smoking causes disease and is addictive, and yet mounted
public campaigns to cast doubt on the scientific evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco firms tried to argue that punitive damages were
unnecessary because the industry changed its conduct when it made a
$246 billion settlement with the states. The jury, reaching its
decision in only five hours, was not convinced. A California jury
also rejected that argument when it awarded a smoker with terminal
cancer $20 million in punitive damages in March. In the end, these
juries simply refused to let the industry get away with decades of
lying about a product that causes more than 400,000 deaths in
America a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
