<P>
   (NYT4) WALTHAM, Mass. -- July 14, 2000 --
TECH-DIVERSITY-COX-2 -- Highly technical professions have a
disproportionately small number of women, blacks and Hispanics in
high-paying positions. The trickling pipeline of science and math
majors from American colleges and universities suggests that the
situation will not improve, leaving the specter of a growing wage
gap. Greg Bogin, 20, a college junior, is doing research this summer
for Verizon Laboratories in Waltham, Mass., in a program jointly
sponsored by the United Negro College Fund.  Bogin, working on new
data encyrption software for the Palm Pilot handheld device that
would improve e-mail security. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WALTHAM, Mass. -- July 14, 2000 --
TECH-DIVERSITY-COX-1 -- A recent study by the American Association of
University Women found that female students are avoiding high-tech
careers not because of a math and science phobia, but because they
consider computer-related jobs to be boring and lonely. Raegan
Higgins, 20, a student working for Verizon Laboratories near Boston
in a program jointly sponsored by the United Negro College Fund
agrees. A math major from Baton Rouge, La., her summer experience in
the lab confirmed her belief that she would not enjoy a job working
exclusively with computers. She would like to earn a doctorate and
then become a university professor. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SANGPO VILLAGE, China -- July 14, 2000 -- ADV. FOR
MONDAY, JULY 17 -- CHINA-IVILLAGE-COX-1 -- Once a "poor, backwards,
uneducated" speck in Henan province of China, in the words of one
local official, Sangpo Village is now a wired outpost. Its 4,800
residents boast private cars, cellular phones, about 100 personal
computers and a bustling Internet cafe. Fourth-graders at Sangpo's
elementary school in Sangpo Village, China, learn computer basics.
All fourth- and fifth-graders get two computers classes a week.
(Julie Chao/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SANGPO VILLAGE, China -- July 14, 2000 -- ADV. FOR
MONDAY, JULY 17 -- CHINA-IVILLAGE-COX-1 -- Sangpo Village didn't get
rich growing wheat and corn, which is how most of surrounding
Mengzhou County makes a living. Having very little land, village
leaders realized long ago the road to wealth lay in private
enterprise, not agriculture. So it decided to capitalize on a
traditional handicraft of its Muslim population -- sheepskin
processing. In 20 years, the village has grown these backyard
businesses into a multi-million dollar niche market. It now processes
5 million sheepskins a year. Sangpo proudly calls itself China's "Fur
City." Ding Yufeng, 23, left, and his father Ding Cunzheng, 50, stand
in their factory's warehouse surrounded by unprocessed sheepskins.
(Julie Chao/Cox News Service)
</P>
