<P>
   (NYT9) DOTHAN, Ala. -- July 14, 2000 -- REUNITE-COX -- It was
1945, on a cold February afternoon in Baldringen, Germany and the end
of World War II still was months away when  Private first class Ben
Byrd and buddies Harry Biggs and Rene Binette discovered a baby,
Josef Koltes, well-wrapped in a blanket in a wicker carriage. The
soldiers never got a name, never knew whether they had saved a boy or
a girl. The battalion marched away the next morning. Using old war
notes, a German native in Dothan as translator, encouragement from
his wife and daughter and letters to Baldringen's burgermeister, Byrd
found the baby again: 55-year-old Josef Koltes, a retired locksmith
who still lives in the village. From left to right: Harry Biggs, Ben
Byrd, Josef Koltes, 55, and Rene Binette, reunited for the first time
since 1945. (Marlon Manuel/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) KARMEL, West Bank -- July 14, 2000 -- MIDEAST-WESTBANK
-- The stone cistern that is the centerpiece of Karmel's water system
in the West Bank is filled only three feet deep with stagnant,
algae-covered water. But lacking any better swimming hole in the
vicinity, young boys make use of it. "These are our children," said
the mayor of a nearby town. "And this is their water." In the West
Bank, water allocation is a zero-sum game, and Palestinians consider
local scarcity a direct and unjust consequence of the resources given
to Jewish communities. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
