<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2763 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-TOBACCO-ASSESS-NY     07-14 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TOBACCO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: INDUSTRY CROSSES TROUBLING LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT, FLA-TOBACCO-LAWYER) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For tobacco companies, getting the $145 billion punitive damage
award handed down Friday by a Miami jury reduced, and even possibly
thrown out, may be the easy part.
</P>
<P>
   But fighting this one case may be the least of the industry's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago the idea that an individual smoker could
legally triumph against a tobacco producer was unthinkable. Now
even though the industry scores most wins, that has changed. And
the Miami panel's decision Friday in the first class-action case to
go to a jury has taken producers across an ever deeper and more
troubling legal Rubicon.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the moment, this is the realization of the industry's
50-year nightmare,'' said Robert Rabin, a law professor at Stanford
University. ``And that nightmare was that when the dam burst, it
would burst catastrophically.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one thing when cities and states started to line up to
sue the industry. It is another if the millions of Americans who
believe they became ill from smoking can start lining up to file
claims. And many experts believe that Friday's verdict is likely to
encourage more lawyers to bring similar claims in other states. And
the size of the verdict may also cause jurors in other smoking
cases to become more liberal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that it will tend to ratchet juror verdicts
upward,'' said Peter Schuck, a Yale law professor who has served as
a legal consultant to a cigarette company.
</P>
<P>
   Both cigarette company executives and tobacco industry analysts
shrugged off the Florida verdict. Offering a first glimpse at what
is likely to be a protracted appeals process, they said the
two-year state trial had been riddled with procedural errors and
would be thrown out on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, tobacco industry lawyers have long argued that a
class-action case involving all Florida smokers should never have
been allowed to go forward, because members of the group had all
decided to smoke for different reasons and at different times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are any financial ramifications to this
decision,'' said David J. Adelman, an analyst with Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter. ``The scale of the verdict speaks to the absurdity of
the process.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is little question that tobacco producers saw Friday's
verdict coming. In May, as the Miami case progressed, a strange
consortium of industry lobbyists, Florida officials and plaintiffs'
lawyers involved in recent state tobacco lawsuits successfully
pushed a bill through the Florida Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   That bill limited to $100 million the amount that a defendant in
a Florida lawsuit had to post to appeal a verdict. Under the
previous rule, a defendant had to post the entire verdict to
appeal, an amount that, given the size of Friday's award, might
have driven producers into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Robert Kaye of Miami-Dade Circuit Court, who is presiding
over the case, may decide as soon as Monday whether to enforce the
bond limit. And presuming that he does and that Stanley Rosenblatt,
the plaintiffs' lawyer in the Miami case, cannot get the new
Florida appeal measure declared unconstitutional, the tobacco
industry will have plenty of financial breathing room while its
appeals proceed.
</P>
<P>
   But how far they may want to pay the string out is another
issue. On Wall Street, the huge award will likely hang over the
value of the companies' stock. And while industry lawyers said they
were confident that a higher Florida court would dissolve the
class-action cases on procedural grounds, other experts are not
sure.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin, the Stanford professor, said that while the Florida State
Supreme Court previously deferred ruling on the appropriateness of
a class action by smokers, their lack of action might not be
welcomed by producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have let the ball keep rolling so long and the case has
become so protracted that it seems unlikely they will turn around
now and say this case should not have happened in the first
instance,'' Rabin said.
</P>
<P>
   Others disagree. But now both producers and Rosenblatt, the
plaintiffs' lawyer, find themselves in a box with tremendous stakes
and with risks that could drive both closer to settlement talks,
something they have previously resisted, said Stephen Sugarman, a
law professor at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt, despite his victories to date, could see them
quickly wiped out by an appeals court. For their part, tobacco
producers could roll their appeals' dice and lose. A settlement
could also wipe out much of Friday's award. But settling the case
might bring on more class-action lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Sugarman said he had no idea how the Florida case would
eventually play out. But one lawyer who has worked with the tobacco
industry said that whatever happened in Miami case, its meaning was
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may get the Florida verdict reversed to zero,'' that
lawyer said. ``But this corroborates that the industry cannot win
the litigation battle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-14 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HOMECOMING FOR A HERO? NOT REALLY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  LONDON _ Pete Sampras and the Williams sisters have come to
Wimbledon and are now gone. Tiger Woods is not yet in St. Andrews
for the British Open. So Saturday night Britain presumably belongs
to the heavyweight champion Lennox Lewis. Or does it?
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Business or pleasure?'' the man at Heathrow's passport counter
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business,'' the U.S. visitor replied. ``I'm here to cover the
fight Saturday night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What fight?'' the passport man asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lennox Lewis fight,'' he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know,'' the passport man said.
</P>
<P>
   In the taxi into Londontown, the driver had to be reminded that
Lewis was defending the WBC and the IBF titles against Frans Botha
of South Africa in the new London Arena next to the glassy office
buildings of the Docklands area.
</P>
<P>
   ``For another multimillion pounds,'' he snorted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't Lewis a hero here?'' the American said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the boxing world he's known,'' the driver said, ``but it's
not like you have a pinup of him in your front room.''
</P>
<P>
   Or any other room.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fight is billed as ``The Homecoming'' for Lewis, he
is not accepted here as a homeboy, even though he is the first
British-born heavyweight champion since Bob Fitzsimmons lost the
title to James J. Jeffries in 1899, and he parties here when he is
not in training. He also had most of his early pro fights in
England.
</P>
<P>
   But his parents are Jamaican and he grew up in Kitchener,
Ontario. He won the 1988 Olympic heavyweight gold medal for Canada
with a second-round knockout of Riddick Bowe at Seoul, South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   He seldom trains here anymore, but you would think that he would
have trained here this time, if only to help promote his first
fight in London since his second-round knockout by Oliver McCall at
Wembley in 1994 _ the only stain on his 36-1-1 record with 28
knockouts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lewis trained, as he often has, at Caesars Brookdale
resort in Scotrun, Pa., in the Poconos.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have mingled with the people, then the fight would
have been sold out the first night,'' Botha said, alluding to the
expected assembly of only 10,000 in the 12,000-seat arena. ``If I
was from London, I would have been training right here so I could
have all the fans around me. It was a big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   In the cable television era, boxers don't have to sell tickets
to the arena. Their money is usually guaranteed. Lewis will collect
an estimated $5.5 million and Botha $1.5 million for Saturday
night's delayed HBO telecast.
</P>
<P>
   The referee, incidentally, will be the respected Larry
O'Connell, the judge who judge scored Lewis' debatable draw with
Evander Holyfield at Madison Square Garden early last year as just
that: a 12-round draw.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing is different here. Thursday's outdoor weigh-in at Covent
Garden should have been a promoter's dream. Attract the lunch-hour
crowd to the charming old market area that is now mostly cafes and
boutiques. See the boxers step on the scale in front of St. Paul's
Church, which opened in 1633 and was later a theater. Stir
interest. Sell tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But the London bobbies ordered the promoter Panos Eliades not to
publicize the site or the time of the weigh-in. The bobbies didn't
want the Covent Garden area more crowded than it usually is at
lunchtime. The bobbies got their wish. As Lewis weighed 250 pounds
and Botha 236, what turned out to be a nonevent was crowded but not
overcrowded.
</P>
<P>
   As for the fight itself, Lewis is a 14-to-1 favorite in the
legal betting shops over Botha, whose only losses in his 40-2-1
record were knockouts by Mike Tyson and Michael Moorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to put a lot of pressure on Botha,'' said Lewis'
trainer, Emanuel Steward. ``He'll be a real cutie-pie if you let
him. He'll turn, twist, grab you. If you give him room, it can be a
very awkward fight. You've got to stay busy. He's very durable,
too. Lennox can't sit around and wait. He can't fight a technical
fight. He's got to stay busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Botha's new trainer, Abel Sanchez, has the bulky South African
in better shape, with more strength and more stamina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that Frans punches harder than Oliver McCall did,''
Sanchez said. ``He could knock out Lewis in the first or the
12th.''
</P>
<P>
   And everybody in London remembers how their homecoming hero was
knocked out by McCall six years ago. Or do they? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
