<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2793 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     07-14 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERGES MAKES BIG CONTRIBUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If someone asked you to name the most valuable
Dodger of 2000, whom would you choose?
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield? Eric Karros? Kevin Brown?
</P>
<P>
   Or, perhaps, Mike Piazza? Pedro Martinez? Eric Young?
</P>
<P>
   Let's throw another name in for consideration, without sarcasm.
Matt Herges.
</P>
<P>
   In a season that is proving to be just minutely better than the
last, Gary Sheffield is having a fabulous year at the plate and
Kevin Brown has been stingy as usual on the mound. But they were
expected to have good years. They're trusted, well-paid veterans
who are among the best at their craft.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Herges, on the other hand, is a 30-year-old rookie with a
modest resume who pitched his way onto the roster in the spring and
has been the most dependable arm in an otherwise undependable
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Herges has won six games without a loss while serving in that
bastard of baseball roles, middle relief. His six straight wins are
the most by any rookie pitcher in the majors this season, and he's
thrown 52 1/3 innings in 35 appearances while averaging almost a
strikeout per inning.
</P>
<P>
   He began the season by not allowing an earned run (and just one
unearned run) in his first 12 appearances over 19 1/3 innings. His
ERA is 3.37 -- 2.13 if you throw out his one bad performance, a
seven-run outing against Arizona in May -- and opponents are
hitting just .233 against him.
</P>
<P>
   During the All-Star break, several baseball publications checked
in with midseason nominations for awards, and Herges' name came up
in the rookie of the year category.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reach to think a middle reliever would get votes ahead of
an everyday player or starter. But the fact others have noticed his
work is more than enough flattery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm honored to death to just be mentioned,'' said Herges.
``I'm just hoping to duplicate or improve on what I've done so far
in the second half of the season. I don't think it's right for me
to talk about personal goals. I just want to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Herges may have been the longest shot of anyone to make a major
league roster in 2000. He made his major league debut last year
after seven years in the minors, and franchises don't provide many
opportunities for rookies over 30.
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressive, he stuck around and fought his way to the
majors after suffering a nightmarish 1997 season that would have
broken the spirit of most ballplayers.
</P>
<P>
   After making 40 appearances in AA and AAA in 1996 and compiling
an earned run average under 3.00, in 1997 he blew up like Mt. St.
Helen's. He was 0-9 with an ERA over 8.00 in 100 innings of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a quality year in 1996, spent a month in AAA, and then
pitched well during winter ball in Venezuela,'' Herges said. ``I
felt I had a future. But everything went bad in 1997. I can truly
say I didn't have one good outing all year. Not one. It was tough
getting up in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I analyzed everything to the point where it was blinding. Once
your confidence gets torn up, it's hard to get it back, especially
in (hitter friendly) Albuquerque. It got to the point where every
time I stepped on the mound I thought something bad was going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 27 and having been removed from the Dodgers'
40-man roster, Herges was staring at a well-known intersection.
More than a few friends and family members suggested it might be
time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends from high school and college would say hey, when will
you give it up?' When is enough enough?' Even one of my brothers
who played college basketball asked how long I was going to stick
it out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said the same thing to everyone: They'll have to rip the
jersey off me, and there's 29 other teams out there. I'll quit when
every door is shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Two people who kept the door open for Herges were Claude Osteen
and Goose Gregson. Osteen, the current Dodger pitching coach, was
Herges' pitching coach at Albuquerque in '97 and got him a ticket
to winter ball in the Dominican after that awful season. ``I'll be
honest, I don't know what (the Dodgers) were thinking when they
said OK, all I know is I was grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregson, the Dodger pitching coach for parts of 1998 and 1999,
was Herges' pitching coach in the Dominican and worked with him
daily, teaching him a changeup and improving his mental approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can ever give up on anybody who has as good
an arm as Matt,'' Osteen said earlier this season. ``Even during
that season (1997), he had the ability to take the ball everyday
and pitch. He could throw back-to-back days and had good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think playing winter ball did wonders for him because he got
the chance to get his innings in. If a guy has the right makeup and
is willing to stick it out, there's a chance he'll find it if he
pitches enough. What he has going for him now is what he learned
from that adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times that season when Claude told me he had
restless nights after I pitched,'' Herges said. ``But he believed
in me and helped me get through it. No one ever said I didn't have
the stuff. If one had, I might have decided to quit. But they were
always encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Herges, who didn't start playing competitive baseball until he
was 15, rebounded well enough in the minors in 1998, then took out
a personal loan to go play winter ball in Australia. He got steady
work, picked up a slider, and then blossomed as a starter in
Albuquerque in 1999 before a mid-season callup.
</P>
<P>
   He made the Dodger roster in 2000 in part because of the team's
unsettled pitching, which included two relievers returning from
injury (Gregg Olson, Antonio Osuna), two starters with baggage
(Carlos Perez, 41-year-old Orel Hershiser) and one non-roster
player, Mike Fetters.
</P>
<P>
   Even after his run-less April, he remained on the bubble. But
he's secured a spot with continued success. He's had 11 scoreless
appearances in 13 outings of two innings or more. His 6-0 record
could be even better if the offense had been as efficient. He
didn't allow a run in six one-run losses this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's shown us things this year we didn't see last year,'' said
Osteen. ``He's learned more about pitching and has more movement on
his fastball, and he has a great attitude towards everything,
because he's not taking anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From day one, I dreamed of having a major league career,''
Herges says. ``I wish I could have figured out a way to get here
sooner, but it's just great to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   HERGES STATS:
</P>
<P>
   G / IP / H / ER / BB / K / ERA
</P>
<P>
   35 / 52.1 / 45 / 23 / 51 / 3.27
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Didn't allow a run in April, 15 innings over 10
appearances ... Extended streak of innings without an earned run to
19 1/3 ... Has most consecutive wins of any rookie pitcher in 2000,
and fourth-longest streak of any pitcher in the National League ...
Hasn't allowed a run in 25 of 35 appearances on the season, and
allowed one run in 11 of 13 appearances lasting two innings or more
... Native of Champaign, Illinois. Attended Illinois State ...
Parents drove from Illinois to L.A. to see his first major league
game in 1999 ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
