u i BC-RUSSIA-CRACKDOWN-NYT &LR;      07-14 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CRACKDOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PUZZLE: WHAT DOES THE WAR ON TYCOONS MEAN? 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ No one outside the Kremlin is quite sure why, or what
it portends, or even whether it will last very long. But after nine
long years of fabulous high living and seeming immunity from the
rules that govern mere mortals, Russia's infamous tycoons have
suddenly found themselves marked men.
</P>
<P>
   At least, some have. Whether they continue to be targets will
say much about whether President Vladimir Putin's much-vaunted
``dictatorship of the law'' is in fact that or is more in the mold
of the last Kremlin, where the rich played by their own laws.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, Russia's government has launched public
campaigns of legal and political pressure against the titans who
run five of the nation's most powerful business combines, including
the largest oil company, automaker, metals processor and power
utility.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, government agencies have lodged tax-evasion
charges against the No. 1 petroleum company, Lukoil, and the
automaker AvtoVAZ.
</P>
<P>
   They demanded in a letter that the tycoon who owns 38 percent of
Norilsk Nickel, a vast Siberian mining company, repay $140 million
supposedly shorted the government when the company was privatized
in the early 1990s. A similar complaint was filed against Tyumen
Oil, another big petroleum company, in late June.
</P>
<P>
   And Friday, the Russian parliament's Audit Chamber took aim at
the electricity monopoly RAO-UES, accusing it of illegally selling
a stake to foreigners when part of the state-owned company was
auctioned to the public in 1992. The chairman of RAO-UES is Anatoly
B. Chubais, who was former prime minister under President Boris
Yeltsin and who oversaw the early privatization of Russian
industry, including UES.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais is reviled by many average Russians as the symbol of
Russia's economic collapse. But he remains the godfather of
right-wing politics here and an icon of the very free-market
policies Putin has demanded that parliament enact this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Chubais called the accusations against RAO-UES unfounded
_ a ``red revanche'' led by parliament's communists, he said _ but
added that he was worried by their political implications.
</P>
<P>
   Whether founded or not, it would be hard to find in the gold
rush that was Russia's early transition to capitalism anyone who
did not play fast and loose with the few rules of the time.
</P>
<P>
   But the political implications of this new campaign have left
almost all scratching their heads. For it is hard to tell, yet,
whether the rash of attacks on the so-called oligarchs is the
payoff on Putin's longstanding pledge to apply the same laws to
both the tycoon and the kiosk operator, or the beginning of some
darker and more subtle bloodletting.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for clarity on this,'' said Thomas Graham,
a former U.S. diplomat who is now a Russia scholar with the
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand, everybody wants to see the thievery stopped,'' he
said Friday, ``and I think most people realize these oligarchs'
empires were built in an illicit fashion. But if it looks like this
is being politicized, it creates problems for investors in Russia
and for the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics has been high on most observers' minds since May, when
the first major attack was sprung against Boris Gusinsky and his
Media-Most empire, a collection of print and broadcast outlets that
are among the Kremlin's most influential critics.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two months, various government offices have staged
armed raids on Gusinsky's offices, seized a gun once awarded him by
Yeltsin, accused him of swindling the government in the sale of a
television station, and briefly jailed him in one of Moscow's most
notorious prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has chided his government for being overly enthusiastic in
its pursuit of Gusinsky, but he has otherwise been silent, leaving
the question of whether he has approved such assaults or is simply
tolerating them because he lacks the political power to call them
off.
</P>
<P>
   To some experts, the challenges are distinguished by two traits:
Many involve owners of powerful media companies, and none touch
those tycoons who are said to be closest to the Kremlin and the
people who made Putin president, the friends and relatives of
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Lukoil has extensive interests in newspapers and local
television. The power behind Norilsk Nickel, Vladimir Potanin, is
an investor in the national daily Izvestia. The man behind AvtoVAZ,
the much-maligned tycoon Boris Berezovsky, took control last year
of Russia most respected and powerful business newspaper,
Kommersant.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to feel the government's sting is Roman Abramovich, a
Yeltsin-family intimate whose Sibneft oil empire was formed from
one of the most notorious privatization schemes in the mid-1990s.
Nor has Putin's government been especially cooperative in
Switzerland's investigation of another Yeltsin family friend, Pavel
Borodin, who oversaw a Kremlin restoration project that has become
the object of a sprawling bribery and money-laundering
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   After Yeltsin resigned, Putin moved Borodin out of the Kremlin
to an honorific job as head of a body overseeing a slow-moving
economic union of Russia and Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other theories as to why the tycoons are suddenly
under assault. One is that the tycoons themselves are jockeying for
advantage in the new Putin government, using their remaining power
to muscle various state agencies into persecuting their rivals. By
that explanation, Putin is at least in part a bystander in a fight
that is not entirely under his control.
</P>
<P>
   Putin himself seems of two minds. In an interview Friday in
Izvestia, he said ``tax evasion and other abuses acquired a mass
scale and became routine'' in Russia's early years, and so it was
natural for those who benefited from the loose rules of the time to
oppose a crackdown now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many businessmen today have found themselves in the `zone of
risk,' in potentially difficult relations with the law,'' Putin
said. ``So, how can't they be but nervous?''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, he said, ``businessmen are now trying to
settle scores with one another by using state structures and law
enforcement bodies.'' He added: ``An end should be put to this.
Otherwise, further damage will be inflicted by such actions.''
</P>
<P>
   One longtime political expert, Vyachaslav Nikonov, a former
member of parliament, said in an interview Friday that an internal
battle among the tycoons was a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But it is equally likely, he suggested, that Putin has simply
given his government free rein to go after the tycoons, both for
political gain and for the immense riches that the tycoons control,
which the government would like to tap.
</P>
<P>
   And if that is not enough, he said, the Kremlin has an obvious
reason to soak the very richest Russians: The very poorest ones,
who vastly outnumber them at the polls, have been salivating at the
prospect for close to a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just popular,'' Nikonov said. ``It's absolutely perfect
politics. People in the streets are absolutely delighted with
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
