<SLUG> BC-PILLSBURY-SALE-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MILLS SAID TO BE READY TO VOTE ON PILLSBURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This article now replaces ECON-REPORT on the first business
page of The New York Times.) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The board of General Mills is meeting Sunday to consider the
company's proposed acquisition of Pillsbury from Diageo PLC for
$10.5 billion in cash and stock, according to executives close to
the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the board, the companies could announce the deal
on Monday, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale would follow a rash of consolidations in the consumer
food industry as food makers battle with grocery retailers for more
leverage in pricing products.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would also immediately make General Mills an attractive
takeover target because it would diversify its product line, which
now includes cereal brands like Cheerios and Cocoa Puffs, to
include Pillsbury's stable of brands like Haagen-Dazs ice cream and
Green Giant frozen food and would give it annual sales of nearly
$1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   According to the executives, General Mills has offered to pay
Diageo about $4.5 billion in cash and about $6 billion in stock for
Pillsbury, giving Diageo a stake in the combined concern of about
33 percent. As part of the agreement, Diageo, which is based in
Britain, would also get two seats on the board of General Mills.
Both General Mills and Pillsbury are based in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo, which has historically acted like a holding company of
sorts for a variety of food and spirits companies, is quickly
abandoning the food business to focus on its much more profitable
spirits business, which includes Smirnoff vodka, Johnnie Walker
whiskey and Guinness stout.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo recently announced that it planned to spin off 20 percent
of Burger King, signaling its intention to eventually sell the
entire fast-food chain.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that with the proceeds from the sale of Pillsbury,
Diageo might go on its own acquisition binge, buying rival spirits
makers like Seagram's liquor business, which is being put up for
sale as part of Vivendi's recent plan to acquire that company.
</P>
<P>
   Though General Mills is expected to acquire Pillsbury's entire
stable of businesses, executives close to the company have
indicated that it may seek to sell brands like Green Giant and
possibly several others that do not strategically fit the company's
brand portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills products include the Betty Crocker line of cake
mixes, Hamburger Helper, Pop Secret microwave popcorn, Gold Medal
flour, and Yoplait and Colombo yogurt. It recently scored a major
hit with Go-Gurt, a yogurt aimed at children that is packaged in a
slender portable tube requiring no spoon. So successful is Go-Gurt,
in fact, that an adult version is being planned.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury's product lineup also includes the Old El Paso line of
Mexican food and Progresso soups.
</P>
<P>
   There are overlaps in several areas, particularly flour and cake
mixes.
</P>
<P>
   Jaine Mehring, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, recently
wrote in a report to investors, ``We believe General Mills would be
most interested in the Pillsbury Doughboy businesses and the
refrigerated-foods technology.'' She added, ``However, it's hard to
imagine Mills taking on Green Giant.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Diageo dropped 2 pence each, to 597 pence, or $8.95,
in London on Friday. Shares of General Mills slumped 68.75 cents
each, to $36.3125, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The sale of Pillsbury follows Unilever's proposed $20.3 billion
acquisition of Bestfoods and Philip Morris' planned $14.9 billion
buyout of Nabisco Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a General Mills-Pillsbury combination would put
even more pressure on companies like Campbell Soup, H.J. Heinz and
Kellogg to consider their own own acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   A merger would probably mean job cuts in Minneapolis. ``As with
any merger there will be some consolidation of jobs and things like
that, and I assume some executive-level jobs will be lost,'' said
Thomas Stinson, the Minnesota state economist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
