<SLUG> BC-TV-BIGBROTHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS RECHECKING BACKGROUND OF `BIG BROTHER' PARTICIPANT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reacting to the news that a participant in its new reality
series ``Big Brother'' is a follower of the former Nation of Islam
official Khalid Abdul Muhammad, CBS said Friday that it was
``looking into'' the report but at the moment saw no reason to
remove the man from the program.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, CBS said that ``we and the producers of `Big
Brother' will not tolerate nor permit any hate speech on the
program.'' But the statement emphasized that ``there has been no
hate speech on Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement came after The New York Daily News reported Friday
that William Collins, one of 10 participants in ``Big Brother,'' is
a follower of Muhammad, who now leads a group called the New Black
Panther Party. Muhammad was ousted from the Nation of Islam for his
denigration of Jews, whom he once called ``bloodsuckers.'' He has
also denounced whites and has called Mayor Rudolph Giuliani a
devil.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad organized the Million Youth March in 1998 in Harlem,
which ended in a violent confrontation with the police. Collins,
who also uses the name Hiram Ashantee, attended that rally. The
News reported that he was at Muhammad's side at a news conference
during the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, under the name Ashantee, was quoted in The Philadelphia
Inquirer after the march, criticizing the police; he made no
anti-Semitic statements. As Hiram Ashantee he is well known in
Philadelphia as an organizer for Khalid and an activist with black
youth groups. In a biography included in CBS promotional material,
Collins is called a ``youth group leader.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Big Brother'' show puts 10 strangers in a specially
constructed house for three months where their every movement is on
camera. Every other week one house member is voted out by viewers
after being nominated for banishment by the other housemates.
Collins was one of two house members nominated for ouster on
Thursday. The members who chose him cited the tension and
dissension he was causing.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two weeks of shows, Collins has been outspoken
about his racial views, but he has not engaged in anything that
would have been described as hate speech.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some executives involved in the production of ``Big
Brother'' expressed concern that Collins had not been entirely
forthcoming about his background. For example, when asked if he
ever went by any other names he reportedly said only that he
sometimes used the nickname ``Hiram.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives involved in the show said that the production
company, Endemol, a Dutch television company, and CBS, which is
part of Viacom Inc., had conducted a background search on William
Collins, not Hiram Ashantee. The search included credit reports,
and a full legal report. Nothing was found to exclude Collins.
</P>
<P>
   CBS began another search Friday and said it still found nothing
that would warrant excluding Collins from the show.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS spokesman said that as of Friday evening the network had
received no calls of protest about Collins from any Jewish
organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
