<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES IDENTIFY LAST OF BODIES FOUND IN BARRELS  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY DIANE CARROLL and TANYANIKA SAMUELS, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As the last of the bodies found in barrels
was identified Friday as that of teen-ager Deborah Lynn Faith, a
family member said relatives had received suspicious-looking
letters about the time Deborah and her mother, Sheila Dale Faith,
disappeared six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The letters, supposedly from Sheila Faith, said she had met a
wonderful man who was taking her and Debbie to Australia, said
Sheila Faith's brother, William Howell of Chandler, Texas. The
letters were sent to his two sisters in the summer of 1994, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The typewritten letters were ``in the form of what a
professional individual would write,'' Howell said. ``It wasn't
just common, everyday language Sheila would use.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said, his sisters do not think that the signature at
the bottom was Sheila Faith's handwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have charged John E. Robinson Sr., 56, of Olathe,
Kan., with capital murder in the deaths of the Faiths and three
other women whose bodies were found in barrels on both sides of the
state line.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also has been linked to three women and a baby who
disappeared in the 1980s. The families of two of those women have
reported receiving similar letters from their loved ones about the
time they dropped out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the letters implied that the women were doing well
and would not be around for a while. One was received by the family
of Paula Godfrey, who disappeared in 1984, and another by the
family of Lisa Stasi, who disappeared in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Raymore Police Chief Kris Turnbow confirmed Friday that the task
force investigating Robinson had received the letters from the
Howell family.
</P>
<P>
   Howell said detectives told him that the letters could be
important evidence in linking the Faiths to Robinson. Howell's
sisters declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Turnbow also said investigators have determined that a van owned
by the Faiths in 1994 turned up in Kansas City sometime in the
mid-1990s. The van was towed by Kansas City police, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have asked the Police Department for a copy of the
tow report, Turnbow said. That report should say where the van had
been towed from and perhaps what kind of shape it was in.
</P>
<P>
   The van has since gone through several owners, Turnbow said, and
been sold for salvage.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, questions about bistate jurisdiction
appeared to be resolved on Friday. Robinson is charged in three
deaths in Missouri and two in Kansas. He is being held in the
Johnson County, Kan., Jail on $5 million bond.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Cass County Prosecutor Chris Koster requested
temporary extradition of Robinson from Kansas to begin Missouri's
case against him.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson County Prosecutor Paul Morrison said that plan could
jeopardize the case.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Koster said Missouri's case would have to wait until
prosecutors in Kansas have tried their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missouri is ready to go,'' he said. ``So when John Robinson
comes for arraignment, we'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are continuing to pursue aspects of the case
including Robinson's source of income, his financial holdings and
the way he went about making contact with the victims. X-rays
crucial
</P>
<P>
   Investigators had to wait for X-ray records from California to
identify Debbie Faith, who was 16 when she disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Young of the Jackson County medical examiner's office
used X-rays taken within one year of her disappearance to make the
identification.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Faith had several ailments and used a wheelchair. She had
undergone surgery that required insertion of staples in her abdomen
area, and she also had a hip deformity, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Turnbow said investigators had been confident all along that the
body was that of the missing teen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investigators made certain assumptions earlier on, and so
detectives proceeded with investigation as if they knew the
identity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities initially suspected that two of the bodies in
Raymore were those of the Faiths, but early tests indicated
otherwise. Those tests included comparing old dental records and
X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   But lingering doubts by members of the task force investigating
the case prompted Jackson County medical examiners to take another
look.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the Faiths said Friday that they still had held some
hope that the last body would not be Debbie Faith's.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Lawrence of Fullerton, Calif., whose daughter had been
best friends with Debbie Faith, said she and her daughter wondered
for weeks what the outcome would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad it has come to such a dreadful conclusion,''
Debbie Lawrence said. ``At least now we know'' what happened to
her, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Koster said the Faiths' relatives likely would be able to claim
the bodies by month's end.
</P>
<P>
   They were the last of the five victims to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Faith's body was identified three weeks ago. The remains
of the mother and daughter were found in a Raymore storage locker
along with those of Beverly J. Bonner, formerly of Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Two bodies found on property Robinson owns in Linn County, Kan.,
were those of Izabela Lewicka, a former Purdue University student,
and Suzette Trouten of Monroe County, Mich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
