<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL SCANDAL REACHES TOP RANKS OF GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ A long-simmering political corruption
scandal has now penetrated the upper echelons of the Brazilian
government and prompted a sudden stock-market downturn, thanks to
the publication on Thursday night of what a Brazilian news magazine
describes as transcripts from 400 hours of wiretapped telephone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   In the transcripts, a fugitive judge who has been accused of
overseeing a fraud and embezzlement scheme, implicates a powerful
former presidential aide, a member of the economic Cabinet, a
senator and several congressional deputies in an illegal patronage
and influence-trafficking network. The magazine, Isto E, did not
disclose how it had obtained tapes of the wiretaps, but government
officials have not challenged their authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal comes at a delicate moment for President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso. With municipal elections set for October, his own
popularity near a record low and opposition parties eager to
exploit the scandal, business interests have expressed concern that
the affair could dampen confidence in Latin America's largest
economy, which has come roaring back from last year's crippling
currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   The focal point of the crisis, which the daily Jornal do Brasil
on Friday called the worst in the six years of Cardoso's
presidency, is a courthouse in Sao Paulo that remains unfinished
nearly a decade after the start of construction.
</P>
<P>
   Recent investigations have determined that normal bidding
procedures were bypassed in awarding contracts to
politically-connected developers and that nearly $150 million in
government funds for the project has vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has already led the Brazilian Senate to expel one of
its members for the first time in its 170-year history. Senator
Luiz Estevao of Sao Paulo, a member of the government coalition,
was impeached on June 20, found guilty of violating parliamentary
decorum, and, once stripped of his parliamentary immunity, arrested
on charges that a construction company he owns pocketed the bulk of
the missing money.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, attention has shifted to Cardoso's former chief of
staff and coordinator of his 1998 re-election campaign, Eduardo
Jorge Caldas Pereira, now a prosperous business consultant in
Brasilia who has been pressed to explain the content of 117 phone
calls he received from the fugitive judge, Nicolau dos Santos Neto,
while the courthouse was being built.
</P>
<P>
   Also under fire is the minister of planning and budget, Martus
Tavares, who authorized additional spending on the project even
after it was being criticized for cost overruns. In the published
transcript of the tapes, dos Santos Neto, the fugitive judge,
boasts of using ``my connection'' to convince the planning minister
to authorize the outlay.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions that Tavares would be fired during an emergency
cabinet meeting on Thursday night proved off base, and he has
denounced the press for what he calls a campaign of sensationalism
and a lack of understanding of the budget process.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the Senate's most influential members said that
``Tavares should leave Cardoso's government as soon as possible,''
and a group of deputies are circulating a petition that would call
Congress back from its winter recess for a special session to
investigate the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000714.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2908 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-GEP-KAN &LR;      07-14 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT ENTREATS GORE TO CONSIDER ANOTHER RUNNING MATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY KEVIN MURPHY and STEVE KRASKE, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As if Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt weren't busy
enough trying to help Democrats take back the U.S. House this year,
he is now being mentioned as a possible savior of Al Gore's bid for
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation ran full tilt Friday that Gore was seriously
considering Gephardt as his running mate, although late in the day
The Associated Press reported that Democratic officials were saying
that Gephardt had urged Gore in a private talk to pick someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said, however, that Gephardt was still a potential
pick. And with Gore's running mate decision just a few weeks away,
political analysts spent the day listing the pros and cons of the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   The pros: Gephardt would help cement support from labor. He
would boost Gore's prospects of carrying Missouri, an important
swing state. And he could help ward off a growing threat from Green
Party nominee Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   But as with any high-stakes move, there are drawbacks. The
biggest: Gephardt would give the Democratic ticket a more liberal
bent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would leave the center of the political spectrum
completely open to Mr. Compassionate Conservative,'' said
University of Virginia political analyst Larry Sabato about likely
GOP nominee George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp has acknowledged that Gephardt, the House minority
leader, is on the vice president's short list. The two reportedly
held a secret meeting last Saturday at Gore's residence to discuss
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt hasn't ruled out sharing the ticket with Gore, but that
is not his priority, his press secretary, Sue Harvey, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you he is committed to running for re-election and
trying to take back the House,'' Harvey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press quoted a Gephardt adviser saying the
Missourian had sought the Saturday meeting with Gore to point the
vice president in another direction. According to the adviser,
Gephardt's message to Gore was, ``If you really think I could make
a difference then we should have a conversation, but (taking a spot
on the ticket) would be a hard thing to do and I really think you
should look at other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has decided not to participate in the customary
candidate background check, according to a Gephardt adviser who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Gore said Gephardt's entreaty doesn't
necessarily mean he won't be asked to take the job, though the vice
president ``is aware of the downside'' to picking him.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has won praise as a tireless fund-raiser for Democrats
running for the House in an effort to erase the Republicans'
222-211 advantage. Running for vice president could seriously
undercut those chances, some observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an awful lot at stake in House races,'' said Charles
O. Jones, senior fellow of governmental studies for the Brookings
Institution in Washington. ``It doesn't totally swing on Gephardt,
but he certainly has dedicated himself to that task.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who know Gephardt well question whether he would
consider trading away his years-long quest of becoming speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that in his heart of hearts he wants to be speaker
of the House,'' said Joe Carmichael, Missouri's Democratic
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The possible choice of Gephardt raises questions on other fronts
as well, Jones said. For one thing, Gephardt has broken with Gore
and President Clinton on some issues, such as NAFTA and trade with
China, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that Republicans may try to exploit those
differences, but that Gephardt could also help bring votes to Gore
from organized labor that backed him on those issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any erosion on the left or in the base of the
party, it shores that up,'' said Vic Kamber, a Democratic
strategist and president of a company that lobbies for labor.
Gephardt, who ran for president in 1988, has been scrutinized for
years and would not spring any surprises on Gore, Kamber said.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato noted that many Democrats are terrified of losing votes
to Nader, the consumer advocate and Green Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nader's moving up in the polls, not down,'' he said.
``Gephardt could help with that.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Gephardt may help draw traditional Democrats into the
Gore fold, he would do nothing to win over conservative Democrats
now leaning toward Bush, said David Israelite, political director
of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of problems Gore is having is with conservative
Democrats, not liberals,'' said Israelite. ``This would be a very
liberal ticket, a very Washington ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Gephardt is under consideration is that he is from
Missouri, a bellwether state that has sided with the winning
presidential candidate every election in the past century except
1956. A recent poll commissioned by The Kansas City Star shows Bush
leading Gore in Missouri by 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Kamber said he did not think Missouri, even though historically
important, is a big enough prize to warrant Gore taking Gephardt as
his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be thrilled if it would happen, but my first choice is
someone who can carry a big state,'' Kamber said.
</P>
<P>
   And given Bush's lead in Missouri, there's no guarantee Gephardt
could deliver the state for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any great affection for Dick Gephardt outside of
St. Louis,'' said Missouri GOP spokesman Daryl Duwe.
</P>
<P>
   Without Gephardt, a slew of Democrats would find themselves
jockeying for position as the next Democratic leader. That could be
divisive at a time when Democrats need to unite to win the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an open race,'' acknowledged U.S. Rep. Karen
McCarthy, a Kansas City Democrat. ``It wouldn't be the smooth
transition that Al Gore is going to need as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the potential losses if Gephardt makes the run for vice
president would be his own House seat in suburban St. Louis, a
district in which Republicans figure to run strongly against a
newcomer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
