<HEADLINE>
FARMLAND INDUSTRIES REPORTS HIGHER QUARTERLY EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY ERIC PALMER, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Farmland Industries Inc. on Friday reported
net earnings of $37.1 million for its third quarter, ending May 31,
on sales of $3 billion. That gain compared with a $7.4 million loss
in the third quarter last year on sales of $2.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The increase, however, was attributable primarily to the $49.6
million Farmland received by selling off part of its marketing
operations to create a joint venture with two other cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
   For the first nine months of fiscal 2000, Farmland reported a
loss of $11.6 million, compared with a loss of $11.7 million in the
same period last year. Sales increased to $8.8 billion for nine
months, up from $7.8 billion in the same period the year before.
</P>
<P>
   While sales were up, the farm economy's depressed prices
continue to pressure Farmland's operations, Harry Cleberg,
president and chief executive of the Kansas City-based cooperative,
said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Higher prices on petroleum products resulted in a 54 percent
increase in sales and a $13.6 million increase in income over the
nine months for Farmland's petroleum business. The cooperative also
saw increases in refrigerated sales of meat, particularly beef,
Cleberg reported in a letter to members of the cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland received nearly $50 million by selling a portion of its
farm marketing operations to create a joint venture with Cenex
Harvest States and Land O'Lakes. Called Agriliance, the venture has
offices in Kansas City and St. Paul, Minn. It markets fertilizer,
herbicides, seed and other products to independent retailers and to
farmers and ranchers who belong to all three cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg said that talks were continuing with Cenex Harvest
States of Minnesota about reconsidering a merger but that there was
no timetable for such a move. Members of Farmland, the nation's
largest farmer-owner cooperative, last year overwhelmingly voted
for a merger, but Cenex members narrowly defeated it.
</P>
<P>
   Cenex is the country's second-largest farm cooperative.
Combined, Cenex and Farmland would have sales in excess of $18
billion. The cooperatives said combining could help them compete
against global food businesses and save them an estimated $500
million over six years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
