<HEADER>
A2910 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-POLICE-TAPE-BEATINGS-     07-14 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-TAPE-BEATINGS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYSTANDER VIDEOTAPES PROLIFERATE, BUT RARELY END IN MAJOR
JUDGMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS: rewrites 3rd graf; inserts new 7th graf; inserts `in March
1991' in 11th graf; changes `the alleged' to `what appeared to be'
in 3rd bulleted item; changes 1998 to 1997 in 4th bulleted item.
Divides into two takes.)  
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the nine years since George Holliday, a Los Angeles plumber
standing on the balcony of his apartment, videotaped the vicious
police beating of Rodney King, tapes made by onlookers have become
a potent legal and political tool.
</P>
<P>
   This week, with two more beatings by police officers videotaped
by news helicopters in Philadelphia and in Lawrenceville, Ga., the
images are as powerful as ever, once again inspiring protesters who
say they are a uniquely vivid display of brutality.
</P>
<P>
   But videotapes of police beatings are actually not so rare,
although few come to national attention. And a review of 18 recent
cases involving such tapes shows that the police officers captured
on film often face no criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   That is no surprise, prosecutors, defense lawyers and other
legal experts say, since bystander videotapes rarely present a
complete picture of an incident, often capturing only the last few
seconds of a violent chase or confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Facing videotapes in police brutality cases, therefore, defense
lawyers generally argue, as they did successfully in the first
prosecution growing out of the Rodney King beatings, that because
the video caught only a piece of the interaction, it missed the
context and the act of defiance that led to the beating.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, hurried amateur tapes of violent attacks that last
seconds rarely provide clear views of precisely who is doing what,
even making it hard to tell which officer struck a particular blow.
For example, in the Philadelphia case, a frame-by-frame analysis of
the video by The Philadelphia Inquirer showed that the victim was
punched and kicked 59 times in 28 seconds before a supervisor
rushed in and backed the officers away.
</P>
<P>
   Tapes may come from a variety of sources. In a 1997 Pittsburgh
case, the beating of a motorist, Evan Gross, was automatically
recorded by a camera mounted on a patrol car. In a 1996 California
case, television news helicopters followed a wild 70-mile chase and
captured the 15-second beating of illegal immigrants piling out of
a rusty pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tapes don't automatically lead to prosecution, because the
legal standard is one of reasonableness,'' said Austin Sarat, a
professor of law and political science at Amherst College. ``So
what appears to us on the outside as absolutely reprehensible,
might look to a prosecutor like bad behavior that, under the
circumstances, would not convince a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sarat said the easy availability of video cameras was a
positive development in helping to make cases against police
officers who were brutal, ``you can't just say, `Oh, gee, these
prosecutors should take these cases.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, almost every one of the incidents spurs local protests,
and if, as is often but not always the case, the police officers
are white and the victims black or Hispanic, the tapes rekindle
deep racial tensions.
</P>
<P>
   In the most famous case growing out of a videotaped police
beating, an all-white jury in Simi Valley, Calif., acquitted the
four officers charged with beating Rodney King in March 1991. The
verdict set off riots that took more than 50 lives.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, two of the officers were convicted in a federal court
of violating King's civil rights. And a year later, a Los Angeles
jury awarded King $3.8 million in damages for his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But many other cases never get to court:
</P>
<P>
   _ In a 1994 case in Compton, Calif., a police officer who was
sent to a trailer park to interview several siblings thought to be
neglected smashed the oldest child in the face with his baton, hit
him repeatedly after he fell to the ground, handcuffed the boy and
used the baton to drag him to a police car, a sequence videotaped
by the boy's godmother, a neighbor. The officer, Michael Jackson,
said that what the tape missed was that he had been threatened and
racially insulted by the boy, 17-year-old Felipe Soltero, and
struck by a younger sister. The district attorney did not charge
Jackson with any crime. A civil jury awarded Soltero, who suffered
a concussion but no broken bones, $1 in damages for the beating.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a 1997 Baltimore case, in which a bystander recorded the
fatal police shooting of James Quarles on a crowded August night at
the Lexington Market, the prosecutor said there was no probable
cause for manslaughter or murder charges. In the video, Quarles has
his back to the camera as four police officers point handguns at
him, so it is impossible to tell precisely what he is doing, but it
is clear that he has a knife in his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a 1998 case in Broward County, Fla., a grand jury would not
indict a Fort Lauderdale police officer of any wrongdoing in what
appeared to be beating of a schizophrenic man, John Clements,
videotaped by two Polish tourists. The grand jury was apparently
unconvinced that it had enough information about what had happened
off-camera. But Clements later settled his civil claims against the
city for $210,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a 1997 Pittsburgh case, state troopers were videotaped
beating Evan Gross after a car chase. In the tape, Gross is seen
getting out of the car with his hands up and being ordered to lie
on the ground, where troopers swarmed over him, punching and
kneeing him. An Allegheny County grand jury, citing testimony from
two police experts in the use of force, decided not to recommend
filing excessive-force charges against any of the troopers, and the
police officers were permitted to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   In those and other cases, lawyers for the beating victims say,
the videotape did not overcome a presumption in favor of the police
_ or the sense that what took place before the tape began rolling
would provide a legitimate explanation for the violence.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecutors and police officers work together all the time,''
said Stewart Greenberg, the lawyer for Clements in Fort Lauderdale.
``No one wants to believe a police officer would ever do anything
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Clements case, Greenberg said, the tape did not stand up
to the officer's lawyer's argument that without knowing what
happened off-camera, it was unfair to charge his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense lawyer's argument is always going to be that the
tape started at X moment, but missed the crucial moment that came
earlier, at X minus 5,'' said Peter Kirchheimer, supervising
attorney at the Federal Defenders Division of the Legal Aid
Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, videotapes are a massive political fact,'' Kirchheimer
added. ``Normally, the criminal justice system is pretty opaque,
and people don't see what happened. Charges don't usually get
brought against the police unless there's egregious injuries like
the perforated rectum in the Louima case _ or a videotape. They're
the thousand-pound elephant, and they change the whole balance.''
</P>
<P>
   As they make their way through the criminal justice system, the
newest cases may face the same problems as their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Philadelphia television stations repeatedly played
the tapes of a group of police officers beating and kicking a man
accused of stealing a police car and shooting at officers in a
mile-long chase. The suspect, Thomas Jones, was treated for five
bullet wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the King case, in which the police were white and the
victim black, the Philadelphia case involved both black and white
officers. While the tapes vividly show a group of police officers
beating Jones, a 6-foot, 240-pound ex-convict, they do not show how
the incident began: The police say that Jones, who was first
stopped for driving a stolen car, and fled on foot, then grabbed an
officer's gun, began shooting and jumped into a nearby patrol car
to flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tapes show that the guy was subdued, and thereafter
assaulted,'' said Chet Mirsky, a professor of criminal law at New
York University. ``You see the guy down on the ground, being
gratuitously kicked, on a continual basis, by more than one police
officer. But in thinking about what's excessive force, you have to
remember that this is a dangerous person, that anyone in their
right mind would have reason to fear. My guess is that it probably
won't get prosecuted, unless there's just enormous public hue and
cry.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, in Lawrenceville, Ga., a news helicopter taped
police officers punching and kicking a drunken driving suspect,
Marshall Dwight Studdard, as he lay on the ground after a 20-minute
chase. But because Studdard is obscured by an officer on the tape,
it is difficult, in that tape, too, to determine what he was doing
during the beating.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is not just in prosecuting police beatings that
videotapes are becoming a factor. Banks and convenience stores have
long taped their transactions to deter crime. And as video cameras
are more widely used, tapes of public events are becoming almost
ubiquitous, whether of the Justice Department's removal of Elian
Gonzalez from his Miami relatives' home, or the recent sexual
violence in New York's Central Park after the National Puerto Rican
Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amateur videotapes are everywhere,'' said Paul Chevigny, a
professor at New York University Law School. ``Look at what
happened in Central Park; they came up with something like 27
videotapes. It's true people are more likely to have cameras at a
parade, but it's also a measure of how much videotaping is out
there now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
