r k BC-HEAS-KAN &LR;      07-14 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEDDLING IN PUMP PRICES BAD FOR BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JERRY HEASTER KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Why did gasoline prices retreat as suddenly
as they surged? Did the recent unexpected relief result from market
forces or industry reaction to political threats?
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to believe politics didn't play some part in the
pump-price plunge, but before anyone celebrates, here's something
to keep in mind: The price mechanism is critical to a steady supply
of any good or service.
</P>
<P>
   If the industry was indeed cowed by saber-rattling politicians,
the short-term pocketbook benefit may come at a much higher
long-term cost in terms of both price and supply.
</P>
<P>
   The petroleum-industry reality is that when motorists were
enjoying historically low prices in the late '90s, those in the
gasoline-selling business were experiencing their hardest times in
a decade. The industry's difficulty generating adequate returns on
its capital explains why refining capacity has been static for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   There were varied reasons for the recent gasoline price spike,
but to the extent it enhanced the industry's profits, it could have
been a good thing as an incentive to expand refining capacity. The
reaction from consumers and their elected representatives, however,
did not send an encouraging message. It said, in essence, any price
development that might improve your return on capital to the point
of encouraging new refinery construction will be met with public
and political disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere down the road, Americans are going to reap a load of
hassle for their shortsightedness when it comes to energy
economics. The fact that government is mandating gasoline
reformulation to fight pollution probably means the day of
reckoning will come sooner than otherwise would be the case.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is not what most Americans want to hear,
because so many of us consider cheap fuel a birthright. This
national attitude translates into more bad public policy. The
president's recent reaction to a predicted heating fuel shortage
this winter is the latest example.
</P>
<P>
   The president has ordered the creation of a home heating-oil
reserve for New England and is seeking legislation allowing
distribution of the heating-oil reserve if prices soar. This sounds
good, but it's the sort of government action that skews the
market's allocative function.
</P>
<P>
   First, the threat of price-depressing intervention in the market
might discourage refiners from increasing supplies if a
colder-than-usual winter is expected. If, on the other hand, the
industry does decide to increase heating-oil supplies, this will
divert some gasoline refining capacity to heating-oil production,
which could force pump prices to soar again this summer.
</P>
<P>
   No outcome can be predicted with certainty, but one thing is
certain: The more government meddles, the more industry makes its
decisions trying to anticipate policy initiatives instead of
marketplace supply-demand developments.
</P>
<P>
   As the price mechanism is short-circuited, resources won't be
put to their most valued use. In the short term, supply patterns
are distorted. In the long run, the capital needed to expand
refining capacity will remain scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Government can do many things, but what it can't do is force
businesses to operate at a loss or commit capital to unpromising
investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
