<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUNWAY-DELAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA REACHES COMPROMISE WITH MOST PILOTS ON SAFETY PROCEDURES TO
EASE DELAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the worst month of delays in air traffic
history, airline pilots and the Federal Aviation Administration
Friday ended a safety dispute that led pilots to sometimes refuse a
specific kind of land instruction.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines said the refusal by pilots to use the procedure
added substantially to delays at airports in Chicago and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute involved a procedure called ``land and hold short
operations,'' under which controllers clear a plane to land using
only part of a runway, because another plane will be landing or
taking off on another runway that crosses the first one. The
procedure had been in use since 1968, but in April the FAA
announced it would broaden use of the procedure, and some pilots
unions said the changes raised the chance that planes would
collide.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Air Transport Association, the trade
association of the big carriers, the refusal by pilots to land
under the procedure was responsible for 25 percent of the delays in
Boston and 10 percent at O'Hare, in Chicago. Miami and Honolulu
were also affected by the action.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots unions often raise safety concerns to the FAA, but in
this case, some unions took the unusual step of recommending to
their members that they use ``discretion'' in deciding whether to
accept clearances to land under the procedure. Many of them began
refusing such clearances, adding to delays at busy airports with
runways that intersect.
</P>
<P>
   At the FAA, Ronald Morgan, the director of Air Traffic, said,
``where demand is high, it's going to decrease delays.''
</P>
<P>
   At United Airlines, which uses O'Hare as a hub and which in June
recorded an on-time performance of less than 57 percent, Peter
McDonald, the vice president of operational services, said, ``not
using it had a significant effect on our operations.''
</P>
<P>
   The procedure is used only when there is little wind, when the
runways are dry and when visibility is good. McDonald said, ``It's
a good-weather procedure, but since we can't use it even on good
days, it is like bad weather all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But the union raised a variety of safety questions. One was
whether the pilots of private planes, or pilots for foreign
airlines, could be trusted to understand instructions to stop in
the middle of the runway, without proof that they had been trained.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm landing full length on the runway, I need some
assurance that another pilot who has been told to land and hold
short of my runway knows how to do that,'' said Capt. Paul
McCarthy, executive air safety chairman of the Air Line Pilots
Union, the largest union. ``How do we verify and document that the
other pilot has the requisite level of training, and how can a
controller tell the difference?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, under a compromise, controllers can order two airliners
to land on intersecting runways, or two private planes; they cannot
order a private plane and an airliner to land on intersecting
runways.
</P>
<P>
   In another compromise, the union and the government have agreed
that controllers will stop using the procedure on a handful of
intersecting runways that the union believes have not yet been
adequately analyzed for the risk of collision if one of the planes,
as sometimes happens, fails to land but circles instead. So far no
incidents have been reported as a result of the procedure's use.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots are always in charge of their aircraft, and whether to
accept a clearance from air traffic control, for landing or
takeoff, is always up to them. McCarthy said his union would be
advising its members that any clearance now offered by controllers
would be in accordance with the union's criteria, and that he, too,
was glad if the result was to allow more landings and takeoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're job-dependent, and capacity means jobs to pilots,'' he
said. But, he added, ``my job is not to increase capacity: My job
is to operate the airplane from Point A to Point B, in the safest
possible manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for some other unions also agreed to the compromise.
Some airlines, however, have never accepted the clearances for the
procedure and will not do so now. For example, Southwest Airlines
flies mostly to smaller airports, and has not trained its pilots to
use the procedure. Controllers are not supposed to offer the
clearances to Southwest planes, and if they do, pilots are supposed
to decline them.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 28 days of June the airlines reported 44,000
delays, up from 38,000 in the same period a year earlier. Weather
was the biggest cause, and McCarthy noted that the FAA does not
keep track of how many landings and takeoffs are performed using
the procedure.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
