<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WOMAN-BISHOP-NYT &LR;      07-14 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMAN-BISHOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER RELUCTANT `YES' TO MINISTRY, CONFIDENT CLIMB TO TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Md., D.C., Ariz.)   By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ She knelt down in her stiff new robe stitched with
purple and gold brocade, surrounded by a tight circle of four
bishops and five elders. One by one, they laid their hands on the
crown of her head in a mighty stack, consecrating her as the first
woman bishop in the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinch me,'' the Rev. Vashti Murphy McKenzie of Baltimore says
she told herself. ``It's really happening, but it seems unreal. All
I was saying was, `Let's not cry now. Let's cry later. Don't cry
here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When she stood, she was dry-eyed, but many of the 5,000 or so
church members watching at the convention center here were not. Men
and women streamed down the aisles to get close enough to snap
pictures of the new bishop, bathing her in a benediction of
flashes.
</P>
<P>
   The laying on of hands happened at 1:02 a.m. Wednesday after
seven days of campaigning at the church's quadrennial convention.
At 3:15 a.m., she was still in the convention center, meeting with
the pastors and lay leaders from the district where she will serve
her first four years: the 18th, which covers Mozambique, Lesotho,
Botswana and Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to move to her district in Africa with her husband,
Stan McKenzie, a former NBA player.
</P>
<P>
   Many said the AME Church could not elect a woman as bishop
because the churches in Africa _ home to about a third of the 2.5
million AME members _ were not ready to accept a woman's
leadership. But McKenzie said that, to the contrary, some African
delegates had asked her to come to their districts if she was
elected. They told her they could use the experience she had gained
in Baltimore developing programs to help the uneducated,
unemployed, or those with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of placing my gender in front of me, I'll place who I
am and what I do, and who I serve in front of me,'' she said in an
interview. ``They know I'm a woman when I walk in the door. So
what? I've been one all my life. Get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie, who says she is in the 50s, is a fitting first. Tall
and regal, her bearing recalls the runway modeling she did as a
teen-ager. Professional and prepared, in her campaign for bishop
she had the glossiest brochure of any of the 42 candidates, the
brightest red T-shirts on her supporters and the slickest video
promoting her accomplishments in 10 years as pastor at Payne
Memorial AME in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is qualified to be bishop, forget the gender,'' said the
Rev. Richard Greene, a pastor from Maryland who joined a huddle of
20 men in the convention center praying passionately for her
victory minutes before the final vote. ``She cares about people,
and finds the best in people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a country boy,'' and quite traditional, Greene said,
``but I believe in her. She has always been there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   As the reality of her purple and gold robe sank in, McKenzie
said she looked back over her life ``and realized that all of it
was the preparation for this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The ministry was not her first career. Initially, she went into
journalism, the family business. Her great-grandfather, John H.
Murphy Sr., had founded The Afro-American newspaper in 1892, when
very few blacks were literate, she said. She honed her writing at
The Arizona Republic and The Afro-American, which still publishes
in Baltimore and Washington. She cultivated her speaking skills as
a broadcaster on gospel radio.
</P>
<P>
   But when the first of her three children was born 25 years ago,
she faced a crisis, she said. She had heard the call to ministry.
She fasted. She prayed. And she said she resisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a very frightening thing when all of a sudden you
realize God is calling you to preach,'' McKenzie said.
</P>
<P>
   There were only one or two women she knew in the ministry then,
she said, and no books on how to do it. Few mentors. She went ahead
and earned her master of divinity degree from Howard University in
Washington and her doctorate of ministry from Union Theological
Seminary in Dayton, Ohio. Her first assignment was to a church with
seven members.
</P>
<P>
   When the pastor of Payne Memorial died in 1989, church insiders
buzzed about who would fill that prestigious pulpit. At a church
gathering, Bishop H.H. Brookins called McKenzie aside and told her
he wanted to assign her to Payne.
</P>
<P>
   She recalls that he asked her, `` `Can you handle the pressure,
because if you are not successful, it will be a long time before a
woman will be given a major pulpit again.' said I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Her church was the first in Maryland to join the welfare reform
effort by winning a $1.5 million state contract to open a job
training center, in 1997. The church's nonprofit affiliate took
over a failing public school. It bought a five-story apartment
building and an office building to house the church's youth and
senior programs, computer classes and a catering service that
employs former welfare recipients. The church grew to 1,700 members
from 300.
</P>
<P>
   She says she follows the ``Ten Commandments for Women Leaders''
that she composed in her book ``Not Without a Struggle'' (United
Church Press, 1996). The first commandment is: ``Thou shalt not
forsake one's femininity for the sake of one's position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You see beautiful women stripping themselves of their
femininity just to be able to hold a position of power,'' McKenzie
said. ``I believe you don't have to give up your femininity. Esther
may have been a good-looking woman and that may have gotten her an
interview with the king, but it was her character that earned her
the crown, and it was her relationship with God that saved her
people.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie's very feminine approach to power was on display at the
convention. She was campaigning when she found herself in a
too-long embrace with a churchgoer who said he had heard her preach
(she has topped Ebony Magazine's ``15 Greatest Female Preachers
List'').
</P>
<P>
   ``You came to see us, and I remember you,'' the man gushed,
``because you're so beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   As he planted a sloppy kiss on her cheek, she never lost her
composure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
