<SLUG> BC-SUBSTITUTE-TEACHER-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBSTITUTE TEACHERS SEEK BETTER PAY AND WORK CONDITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yvonne Christensen approaches her job like a
stand-up comedian. ``You've got about 15 seconds to grab 'em,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Fletcher sees it as similar to being a relief pitcher:
when you walk onto the mound, players are already on base.
</P>
<P>
   And Cindy Manzo sounds as if she's joined the circus: ``I'll
stand on a chair, I'll dance around, I'll pretend my shoe is a
phone,'' Manzo said of her 15 years as a substitute teacher in
three states. ``Anything to keep their attention.''
</P>
<P>
   These three longtime substitutes were among 50 who exchanged
horror stories and survival strategies here at the first national
conference of substitute teachers Friday, part of an effort to
raise pay, benefits and working conditions for what is perhaps
education's least respected teaching job.
</P>
<P>
   The nascent effort, organized by far-flung substitutes who met
over the Internet, comes at a time of severe shortage of substitute
teachers. With student enrollment and teacher absenteeism growing,
class size shrinking and the unemployment rate near record lows,
school districts across the country are scrambling to fill gaps at
the front of the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Many districts have raised wages, but others have lowered
requirements: in half the states, all it takes to be a substitute
teacher is a high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Substitutes have long been disrespected by students, teachers
and administrators, and largely ignored by researchers and
politicians. But students, on average, spend a full year of their
school lives in classes taught by substitutes, a fact that has
fueled a small, but growing, movement to improve training for these
workers and take their role more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like driving a car: it's skill-based,'' said Geoffrey
Smith, executive director of the Substitute Teaching Institute at
Utah State University, which has made a CD-ROM that provides a
self-taught seminar for potential recruits. ``There are skills that
one can learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that fewer than 10 percent of school districts
provided training for substitutes, but those that did found it
decreased the number of complaints and attracted more applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Expert estimates of the number of substitutes range from 500,000
to 1 million, but nearly everyone agrees there are not enough. In a
recent survey by Smith's institute, 86 percent of school districts
reported a substitute teacher shortage, with more than half calling
it a ``serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Pay varies widely, from $30 to $185 a day, with an average of
about $65. Qualifications also vary: Some districts require a
full-fledged teaching credential, others simply do a criminal
background check.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the ranks of substitutes were filled with teachers
unable to find full-time work, retirees and parents helping out in
their children's schools. But now, as the nation faces a teacher
shortage of an estimated 2.5 million in the next decade, substitute
rosters are bare, and districts are turning to flight attendants,
firefighters, college students and others.
</P>
<P>
   The full-employment economy, where potential substitute teachers
might make better money flipping burgers, is not helping. Nor is
the rise in the number of professional development days that pull
full-time teachers out of class. Assistant principals, and even
schools superintendents, are having to fill in during shortages,
and some districts ask cafeteria workers and bus drivers to serve
as subs. Last November, the Kelly Services temporary agency began
providing substitute teachers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In the Atlanta suburbs of DeKalb County, full-time high school
teachers can earn an extra $15 for teaching during their planning
periods. When Georgia passed a law slashing the number of teachers'
aides statewide, the district also decided to turn 600 aides into
substitutes this fall rather than fire them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious thing to do is to pay more money,'' said Franklin
Grant, director of the office of human resources at the
97,000-student DeKalb County school system, and president of the
American Association of School Personnel Administrators. ``How do
you get a commitment out of anybody for $30 or $40 a day?''
</P>
<P>
   The shortage has provided fertile ground for organizing efforts.
The National Education Association and the American Federation of
Teachers each represents substitute teachers in a handful of cities
and towns; substitutes have also affiliated with other labor
groups, including Service Employees International Union and the
United Food and Commercial Workers.
</P>
<P>
   In Oregon, legislators recently passed the eighth in a series of
bills focused on substitute teachers, setting pay scales at 85
percent of a district's average teacher salary. In Michigan, the
state teachers' association has adopted a substitute's ``bill of
rights'' calling for health benefits, a safe environment and ``the
dignity and respect that, as professional educators, they have
earned.''
</P>
<P>
   The keynote speaker at Friday's conference was Shirley Kirsten,
founder of the Fresno Area Substitute Teachers Association in
California. The group began with five people having coffee in her
living room in 1997, and ended up negotiating a contract last year
on behalf of hundreds of substitutes that raised pay for
substitutes to $80 or $90 a day, from $65, depending on the
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been isolated for too long,'' Kirsten told attendees,
who had come from Nebraska, Florida, New York, Oregon, North
Carolina and Virginia. ``We now need to get together under one
umbrella. That umbrella is respect.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most of those attending the conference were longtime substitutes
with teaching credentials, many of them having chosen the
flexibility of daily assignments over the responsibilities of a
full-time classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Manzo, who is 52, said substituting fit with her military
husband's mobility _ they have relocated 18 times _ and enables her
to care more easily for her son and her father, both of whom have
medical conditions requiring her attention.
</P>
<P>
   But substituting can mean teaching French and physics and fourth
grade _ all in one week. Adaptability is essential.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher, who organizes substitutes in Los Angeles, keeps boxes
of teaching material in his car, in case someone forgets to leave a
lesson plan. He does not know sign language, except the sign for
``interpret,'' so he can direct someone to translate if he is
teaching a class of hearing-impaired students.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time he was teaching band, and all the
instruments were locked up. He passed out paper and pencils he had
brought, and taught the students to write musical notes.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Routh, a substitute in San Francisco for 25 years,
revealed a secret for controlling a rowdy classroom of children
she's never met. ``You say, `Kevin, sit down,''' Routh confided.
``There's always a Kevin, so the students think you know
everybody's name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
