<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-TRANSFER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO DEAL SHUFFLES MEMBERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ United Health Group has signed an agreement for
its United HealthCare unit to transfer its California health plan
membership of about 225,000 people to Blue Shield of California,
both companies said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Blue Shield will also provide access to its
network of more than 42,000 physicians and medical facilities to
Uniprise, a separate unit that serves about 700,000 employees and
their dependents in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal means our presence in this state will increase by
about a million members,'' said David Joyner, vice president of
external affairs with San Francisco-based Blue Shield. ``It has
also given their members access to a more extensive health care
network.''
</P>
<P>
   The transfer agreement primarily involves those individuals
covered by United HealthCare in California. Employees and their
dependents will continue to be served by Uniprise, which is
expanding its programs in California through its new alliance with
Blue Shield.
</P>
<P>
   This transfer does not affect AARP members in California who
have Medicare supplement or hospital indemnity coverage through
Minneapolis-based United Health Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made a business decision to partner with Blue Shield
to serve a group of members that are in small- to middle-market
employer groups and shift our focus to our larger multistate and
multisite business,'' said Roger Cruzen, vice president of public
relations for United HealthCare.
</P>
<P>
   The transition is subject to regulatory review. United
HealthCare expects the transfer of its members to Blue Shield to
begin by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates, however, call the agreement outrageous and
want state regulators to block the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health care companies should not be able to trade their
patients like children trading baseball cards on a playground,''
said Jamie Court, director of the Santa Monica-based Consumers for
Quality Care.
</P>
<P>
   ``United HealthCare has made certain promises to their members,
and now they are trying to change those promises,'' Court said.
``If the state won't stop the deal, I know a few class-action
lawyers that will.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Blue Shield and United HealthCare emphasized that all
consumers affected by the transition will receive uninterrupted
coverage and access to care.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner said Blue Shield has done everything to make sure there
would be no disruptions in service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 95 percent of United physicians are already in our
network,'' he said. ``We have additional providers that they don't
even have. We are going to work through any dislocations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Joyner said, ``We are confident we will get a swift
review by the state Department of Managed Health Care.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruzen said United HealthCare's reason for seeking a deal was
simple: The company's health plans were only breaking even in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get beyond that position would have required a lot more
investment,'' he said. ``We could have left the state entirely, so
instead we have found a partner that is aligned with our philosophy
of delivering health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Shield of California, an independent member of the Blue
Shield Association, is California's second largest not-for-profit
health plan. Blue Shield has a membership of 2.1 million and annual
revenue of $3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of United Health Group closed down $1.25, or 1.5 percent,
Friday to $84.50 on heavy volume of 1,437,300 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
