<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: UPGRADING THE MILITARY
</P>
<P>
   The government announced a $3.5 billion, eight-year plan to
modernize the air force by refurbishing 100 combat jets and buying
76 new supersonic fighters. Pressure has been building for a
strengthening of the military's air wing to deal with increased
drug-smuggling flights over the Amazon basin and the growing
strength of left-wing guerrillas in neighboring Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: FORMER PRESIDENT FACES ARREST
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ordered the arrest of former President Jamil
Mahuad and his finance minister on charges they exceeded their
constitutional authority when they declared private bank accounts
frozen early last year. Mahuad took the action to prevent the
banking system from collapsing, but was overthrown in January after
he announced that the U.S. dollar would replace the sucre as
Ecuador's currency. Relatives say he is the United States.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: RALLIES WIND DOWN
</P>
<P>
   A call by the Orange Order in Portadown for continued
provincewide demonstrations against the ban on its march through a
Catholic neighborhood went largely ignored, and the Protestant
group's leader in Belfast said the protests should end. Northern
Ireland has been convulsed by violence for the past two weeks.
``People have had enough,'' said Robert Saulters, grand master of
the Grand Orange Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: LURE FOR FOREIGN EXPERTS
</P>
<P>
   Parliament's upper house passed a U.S.-inspired ``green card''
program entitling up to 20,000 foreign computer experts to work in
Germany to fill a skills gap in computer technology. The experts
must have university qualifications or prove they will be paid a
minimum income of $48,000 per year to qualify for a visa. The plan
was attacked by opposition conservatives as taking jobs from
Germans. The bill becomes law on Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFIC
</P>
<P>
   ASIA VIETNAM: PRAISE FOR TRADE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Trade Minister Vu Khoan praised a Vietnam-United States trade
accord signed Thursday in Washington, calling it ``an important
step in our integration into the world economy.'' In the United
States, the AFL-CIO vowed to fight the pact's approval in Congress,
saying it threatened labor standards and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES: HOSTAGE LET GO
</P>
<P>
   Muslim rebels released a second Malaysian hostage after 83 days
in captivity on the small southern island of Jolo. The rebels still
hold 19 mostly foreign tourists, three French journalists who tried
to interview the hostages and 13 Philippine evangelical Christians
who came to pray over them. A German journalist and three Filipinos
are apparently being held in separate kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKHSTAN: FORMER LEADER FREED
</P>
<P>
   Italian authorities released Akezhan Kazhegeldin, Kazakhstan's
former prime minister, after holding him for two days in Rome at
the request of Kazakhstan's Interpol unit. They said there were no
grounds to detain him further. Kazhegeldin is a political opponent
of Kazakhstan's president, Nursultan Nazarbayev, and has been
accused of money laundering and tax evasion in his homeland, which
he has denied.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: TRIAL NEARING CLOSE
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors completed their closing arguments in the sexual
misconduct trial of former Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim, who
is already serving a six-year term for corruption. Defense lawyers
now have a chance to rebut the arguments before the judge sets a
date for his verdict.
</P>
</TEXT>
