<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SOGO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE BANKRUPTCY STIRS WIDER DOUBTS ON ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The gloom surrounding the bankruptcy of the Sogo Co., a
major retailer that owes more than $17 billion, was dispelled
somewhat Friday after Japan's finance minister said the failure
would not undercut the economic recovery and Standard &AMP; Poor's
called the bankruptcy necessary medicine for the Japanese banking
system.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also signs that another big Japanese corporate
debtor, worried about suffering the same fate as Sogo, might be
bailed out.
</P>
<P>
   And there was speculation that the financial weaknesses exposed
by the Sogo bankruptcy and its aftermath might dissuade the Bank of
Japan from raising interest rates at its policy meeting on Monday.
Up until the Sogo collapse, there had been considerable expectation
that the central bank was prepared to raise rates for the first
time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Sogo, an operator of 25 department stores and an employer of
10,000 people, sought bankruptcy protection Wednesday after a
public outcry over a government-backed plan to use taxpayer money
to keep the company alive and forgive some of its debts amassed
during the speculative boom years in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The bailout plan collapsed after Shinsei Bank, a big Sogo
creditor that was recently bought by foreign investors, balked at
forgiving any Sogo debts.
</P>
<P>
   The Sogo bankruptcy, one of the biggest in Japan, could now
create a domino chain of failures among Sogo suppliers and others
dependent on the 170-year-old retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Kiichi Miyazawa, the Japanese finance minister, offered some
reassurance that the impact of Sogo's collapse would be limited.
``I don't think it would be substantial as the economy is
rebounding,'' he told a news conference in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's also eased some of the anxiety about Sogo,
calling the decision to abandon a bailout a positive step. ``While
Sogo's reversal may lead to an immediate increased incidence of
corporate bankruptcy, the long-term effects may be more beneficial
for the Japanese banking industry,'' the ratings agency said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Japanese news reports said Dai-Ichi
Kangyo Bank, one of the biggest banks, was planning to help the
Hazama Corp., a major construction company, avoid what had befallen
Sogo. The reports said the bank might buy some of the debts that
Hazama owed to Shinsei _ the same bank that helped precipitate
Sogo's bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Should Dai-Ichi take on Sogo's Shinsei loans, that would send a
clear signal that the system of so-called convoy capitalism is
still alive in Japan. That system, in which banks lend to borrowers
to keep them afloat rather than make a profit, was supposed to have
died after the financial crisis that nearly toppled the banking
system here in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, new data on bankruptcies released Friday suggests that
one of the biggest challenges the government will face this year is
how to prevent insolvency from tipping the banking system into
another crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in the law that make it easier for companies to seek
court protection have helped increase bankruptcies to nearly record
highs. Corporate bankruptcies rose 32.2 percent in the first six
months of this year compared with the same period last year, as
9,304 companies went under, according to Teikoku Databank, a credit
research company.
</P>
<P>
   Hazama owes Shinsei 42 billion yen, or about $388 million, and
Japanese newspapers said Dai-Ichi was preparing to buy the 30
billion yen of those loans not covered by Shinsei's reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Dai-Ichi was careful Friday not to deny the stories. ``We are
the main bank of Hazama, and our policy is we would like to support
the company,'' a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said no decision had been made to buy Hazama's Shinsei loans.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a broad request for 105 billion yen in debt relief
from four banks, Hazama has already asked Shinsei to forgive 12
billion yen to 15 billion yen in loans.
</P>
<P>
   Sogo had made a similar request as part of a broad restructuring
plan, but Shinsei refused to go along. Instead, Shinsei asked the
government to take on its loans to Sogo under terms of an agreement
reached last year that put the bank into the hands of a group of
foreign investors headed by Ripplewood Holdings LLC.
</P>
<P>
   The government first agreed to forgive Sogo's Shinsei debts, but
politicians, facing a torrent of public criticism, abandoned the
plan, forcing Sogo into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   There was a possibility that the Hazama's story could play out
the same way. But Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party has
strong reasons to keep construction companies like Hazama afloat.
</P>
<P>
   The ties between the Liberal Democrats and the construction
industry are legendary. Much of the spending on public works that
has contributed to Japan's huge public debt load is a reflection of
those ties, as are the piles of debt accumulated by construction
companies struggling to survive during the economic downturn of the
last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Construction companies keep people employed, and that employment
is translated into votes. And Japan is forever awash in rumors of
kickbacks between politicians and general contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The banks want this debt-forgiveness plan, because if Hazama
goes through a public bankruptcy process, various types of
collusion between the construction industry, politics and the
bureaucracy might surface,'' said Yoshito Sengoku, a member of
Parliament from the opposition Democratic Party, who played a major
role in shaping the bailout of the banking system in late 1997 and
early 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
