<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT DELAYS SOAR THIS SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAM PARK 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ John Mihalik just wanted to fly home to
Pittsburgh, but his United Airlines plane was already 30 minutes
late boarding at Los Angeles International Airport on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of trips out have been very bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a previous trip, it took him 16 hours to get from Pittsburgh
to San Francisco because of airport delays, and he was beginning to
fear that this trip home might not be any better.
</P>
<P>
   He's not the only one playing the waiting game at America's
airports. Because of bad weather in the Midwest on Friday, several
flights were delayed at LAX, leaving passengers sitting stone-faced
and stoic, hoping for the best but expecting the worst.
</P>
<P>
   And airport delays are on the rise, according to new Federal
Aviation Administration figures.
</P>
<P>
   In June, delays in the nation's air traffic control system
jumped 16.5 percent over the previous year. Some 48,448 flights
were delayed 79 percent of them because of weather, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   June was a particularly active month for thunderstorms, the FAA
said. On several days of the month, a solid line of thunderstorms
reaching from Toronto to Dallas disrupted schedules. On June 27,
the Aviation Weather Center of the National Weather Service issued
a record 281 warnings of thunderstorm activity.
</P>
<P>
   While the weather caused havoc, delays caused by the volume of
aircraft actually decreased 5.2 percent, the FAA said. And delays
due to air traffic control equipment outages were down 78.8
percent, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Although FAA officials say there were delays in fewer than 1
percent of the more than 7 million flights in June, travelers
booked on the delayed flights may not have felt consoled.
</P>
<P>
   John Crowder of Washington, D.C., said delayed flights cut his
productivity, but that he has come to expect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awful. You can't plan to get somewhere and do business
that same day. You have to plan to get there the day before.''
</P>
<P>
   The monitor displaying arrival and departure information showed
Crowder's plane was arriving on time Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at it. It's beautiful!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others weren't so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Newman was trying to get home to Honolulu after a
business trip. She was ticketed for a plane that had been delayed
four hours. She was on standby for one delayed two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said she was running late for the second time in a week.
On her previous flight from Boston to Honolulu, she wound up
sitting in San Francisco for an unscheduled eight-hour layover.
</P>
<P>
   And Heide Woolley, a teacher from the Monterey Peninsula, was
trying to get to Ohio for a class reunion. Her plane was running
nearly two hours late, and she feared she would miss her connection
and either get to Ohio very late or have to spend the night in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to my 40th-year class reunion, and I don't want to
get there blurry-eyed,'' Woolley said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
