<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-14 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION: A CLOSER LOOK AT EVANGELICALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER STEINFELS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Count on it: The Religious Right will be back. In about two
weeks, the Republican National Convention will anoint George W.
Bush's choice of a running mate, and depending on that choice,
conservative religious leaders will be featured in the news, either
voicing praise and support or expressing disappointment and
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But how closely do those leaders' views, often partisan and
sometimes downright inflammatory, correspond to the outlook of the
nation's conservative Christians? A considerable body of critical
opinion, no less inflammatory itself, has assumed that the
correspondence is close. As Pat Robertson or James Dobson goes, so
go the evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   Military metaphors abound in commentary on the Religious Right.
Not just the prominent leaders and their organized cadres but the
mass of conservative believers are often portrayed as an angry army
on the march, legions of intolerant zealots eager to use
governmental power to impose their favored moral order on the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Smith, a professor of sociology at the University of
North Carolina, is blunt about such sweeping portraits. ``Most of
those who disparage evangelicals in general terms really don't know
what they are talking about,'' he writes in his latest book,
``Christian America? What Evangelicals Really Want'' (University of
California, 2000).
</P>
<P>
   Few critics, Smith says, ``have significant personal
relationships with enough ordinary evangelicals to inform their
views.'' Typically the critics' views spring from characterizations
in news articles and popular entertainment, from hoary mythology of
the Elmer Gantry sort, from the newsletters and fund-raising
appeals of organizations engaged in today's cultural wars, or from
the impressions of people just like themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In Smith's previous book, ``American Evangelicalism: Embattled
and Thriving'' (University of Chicago, 1998), his extensive polling
and interviews challenged the widespread stereotype that
evangelicalism only flourished in intellectual and economic
backwaters, isolated enclaves guarded from what Walter Lippmann
famously called the ``acids of modernity.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Smith found that by most standards, measuring contact
with this elusive thing called modernity _ years of higher
education, employment patterns, income levels, urban versus rural
residence, age or sex _ people who identify themselves as
evangelical Christians scarcely differed from other Americans.
</P>
<P>
   His new book is based on a three-year national study involving
over 200 extended interviews as well as polling data. He quickly
identifies four fallacies that have distorted many descriptions of
evangelicals: that their views can be equated with those of a
supposedly united evangelical political elite; that their views are
accurately represented by the formulations used in public opinion
polling; that their views are ideologically consistent, and that
they form a monolithic religious bloc rather than a conglomeration
of often bickering subgroups.
</P>
<P>
   In his own interviews, Smith did not shy from the hot-button
questions. Did evangelicals want to restore a ``Christian
America?'' What did they think of moral and cultural diversity? Did
they have a duty to save neighbors of other faiths from hell? What
could and could not _ or should not _be attempted through politics?
What should be the content of public education in a pluralist
society? What about male leadership in the family and equality
between men and women?
</P>
<P>
   On all of these questions he found a range of views, including
extreme ones. That, in fact, was his first important discovery:
that evangelicals were not united or monolithic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Smith found the bulk of evangelicals grouped around
certain convictions.
</P>
<P>
   They were deeply committed to freedom of religion and speech,
not simply as a matter of unavoidable compromise but out of their
religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   They believed strongly in individual change, personal conversion
of the heart, and consequently they remained wary of social
movements, political involvement and institutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Far more than politics, they stressed personal example and
loving gestures, including prayer, as a means to change.
</P>
<P>
   They frequently disagreed with the positions of their most
visible political leaders and often said so quite explicitly.
</P>
<P>
   They were critical of their own failures to live up to the
Gospel.
</P>
<P>
   These views were typically conveyed in rambling statements, not
particularly eloquent, circling around in second thoughts and near
contradictions, statements too long and too loose-jointed to serve
reporters in need of the pebble-hard sound-bite, but statements
with the authentic ring of ordinary people reflecting and not
leaders posturing.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a woman, 54 years old, Midwestern and middle-class, who
thinks that gays, the National Organization of Women and the news
media are all hostile to Christianity, and who once marched outside
an abortion clinic. But she has ``mixed feeling,'' she says, about
the ``back-and-forth yelling thing'' and says ``one-on-one
evangelism'' is ``far better than this group stuff where you're so
militant and radical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really frown on evangelicals that are kind of hostile
themselves,'' she says. ``You don't win people that way. You've got
to love them first. We should just stand firm in our beliefs, of
course, but try to reach them in a loving way, try to talk to them
and befriend them, rather than go and just start yelling things
back and forth. What does that accomplish?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in what you call `hard-sell' Christianity,''
she says, with much elaboration. ``I don't believe in preaching at
people. I invite them to Christian things, and if the conversation
can be such that I can talk to them about Jesus, I do that. I never
hit anyone over the head with the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   American evangelicals ``are neither angels nor demons,'' Smith
concludes. ``They are much too diverse, complex, ambivalent and
inconsistent for that.'' Most are not particularly interested in
waging the culture wars. They are neither apostles of multicultural
diversity nor shock troops of intolerance. They are susceptible to
demagogy but also resistant to it, in much the same ways as other
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The oratory surrounding political conventions sometimes leaves
the impression of a citizenry divided into alien species. Smith's
book argues that it just isn't so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2349EDT &QL; 
