u p BC-GORE-NYT &LR;      07-14 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEMOCRATIC AREA OF MICHIGAN, GORE ENCOUNTERS SKEPTICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAGINAW, Mich. _ Sheila Redman, director of the Saginaw Art
Museum, put it best. ``I feel kind of bad in asking this,'' she
said to the vice president of the United States. ``But where have
you been for the past eight years?''
</P>
<P>
   This is a solidly Democratic, heavily unionized area, the buckle
of Michigan's industrial belt. But as in the rest of this state,
and much of the industrial Midwest, voters here are skeptical about
Al Gore's presidential candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday night, for 3 1/2 hours, Gore stood under the hot
lights in the sweltering gymnasium of Arthur Hill High School here,
patiently answering questions from 200 voters _ many of them
undecided _ on the economy, jobs, trade and the insurgent campaign
of Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Redman's questioning that seemed to strike at the
heart of the issue. Noting that she was only suddenly aware of his
campaign, she told Gore: ``I wasn't sure I would vote for you. I
didn't know if you were strong enough to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the areas where Nader and his anti-corporate
third-party candidacy is siphoning votes from Gore. It may seem odd
that Nader, author of ``Unsafe At Any Speed'' and the longtime
nemesis of the auto industry, could make a dent in the support of
the AFL-CIO-backed Democratic candidate here. But Gore, who as
Republicans like to say, once proposed elimination of the
internal-combustion engine, carries a heavily anti-automobile
reputation, too.
</P>
<P>
   With Nader in the race, according to the latest statewide poll
by The Detroit Free Press, Gore trails Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, his likely Republican rival, by 12 percentage points. The
poll gave Bush 46 percent, Gore 34 and Nader 8.
</P>
<P>
   In the same poll two months ago, before Nader became a factor,
Gore was leading Bush. The Democrats have spent $1.2 million in
television commercials here since then to try to raise Gore's
stock, but to little avail.
</P>
<P>
   But Nader is only part of the problem. Gore backers and analysts
say that as the election heats up after Labor Day and Nader's
bare-bones campaign competes for media attention, he may become
less of a factor.
</P>
<P>
   For voters like Redman, the main concern is that despite Gore's
nearly eight years as vice president and his yearlong presidential
campaign, he is still an unknown quantity.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign is fully aware that the vice president
``hasn't broken through'' with voters, as one Gore adviser put it.
And on Thursday night, he revived one of his favorite campaign
venues, the town hall meeting, an open-ended give-and-take with
voters that allows Gore to display his grasp of issues and, more
important, to try to convey to voters who he his.
</P>
<P>
   While Redman did not mention President Clinton, Gore immediately
interpreted her concern as one about his toiling in the shadow as a
No. 2. He told her that the job of vice president was a ``mixed
blessing.'' The ideal person for the job, he told her, was someone
who would not care about receiving press attention and who would
help ``carry the load when the load gets heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added: ``You may not always notice that man. And if you
do, he may be just standing there stiffly behind the president, not
saying a word.''
</P>
<P>
   He pressed on: ``Well, is it like the woman behind the man?
Well, you know, actually, I've learned a lot about some of those
issues because a vice president who does the job correctly is
somebody who pitches in and does everything that can help out the
country by strengthening the team and moving the ball down the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Sarpolus, a longtime political analyst in Lansing who
conducted The Free Press polls, said that despite Bush's lead
across the state, Gore still leads heavily in this region. But he
added that Redman had given voice to the central obstacle that Gore
had to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's problem in Michigan is not the China issue, it's not
the labor issue,'' he said of some union concerns. ``It's
personality and character because it's tied to Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``When I look at people's angst with Gore, it's not
the policies'' that give them pause, but Clinton's ``moral
turpitude,'' he said. ``They will punish Bill through Al. And until
Gore separates himself from Clinton, it's the sins of the father
being visited on the son.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarpolus said that Gore needed eventually to make a clean break
with Clinton, probably after the convention, even though he was
relying on the Clinton economy as his biggest selling point.
</P>
<P>
   Gore seems more comfortable training the national discussion on
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put your finger on the problem,'' he told a man in a tank
top who implored the vice president to ``get more manufacturing
jobs back into Michigan.'' But even that man, a union worker who
said he earned $23,000 a year, shared a more personal reaction to
the vice president as he addressed him. ``You look a lot like my
older brother,'' he told Gore, approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore strategy at this point is to create the chance for the
vice president to make these personal connections, which he
invariably comes away from successfully, but also to hammer away at
his differences with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, Gore's press secretary, said that Gore would not
be distracted by Nader, whose name Gore never uttered during the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Sarpolus said that Gore's reference to being ``the woman behind
the man'' was probably a useful way to convey his role and his
sensibilities to women, who make up the majority of Democratic
voters _ even if it did not appeal to male voters, who polls show
favor Bush over the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't change the way he communicates that,'' Sarpolus
said. ``He has to reach women, and this helps him do that, by being
a man who is willing to admit that,'' he said. ``And if he doesn't
get the women's vote, it doesn't matter what happens with the
men.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
