<SLUG> BC-CALIF-JOBLESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.'S GROWTH TOPS STATE'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Reflecting a still strong economy, unemployment
dipped slightly during June on an annual basis in Los Angeles
County while remaining flat across California, the state said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, the jobless rate fell to 5.4 percent from 5.8 percent
in June 1999, said the California Employment Development
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Business services and the entertainment industry remained
especially strong, adding 15,800 and 10,000 jobs, respectively,
over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   On a monthly basis, business services added 5,000 jobs, and the
motion picture industry grew by 1,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it still looks real strong. There is no sign of
weakness,'' state labor market analyst Bill Freed said of the
county's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same picture emerged statewide as the jobless late last
month was 5.2 percent, unchanged from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   California businesses added 51,500 jobs from May to June, almost
25 percent of the nation's growth for the period.
</P>
<P>
   It is especially impressive considering that California's labor
force is growing three times faster than the nation's, said Ted
Gibson, chief economist for the state Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, last month the number of people working or looking
for jobs increased by 78,000 from May to June. Of those, 54,000
found jobs last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economy is doing very well,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   During June, business services like software development and
Internet-related jobs, as well as the entertainment industry, drove
the job growth.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-00 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
